<HEADLINE>
KOBE KO'D BY UNKIND BREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Lakers' ugly defeat in their exhibition opener
Wednesday night grew exponentially uglier by Thursday morning: Kobe
Bryant will be out at least six weeks after X-rays revealed he
broke a bone in his right hand in the loss.
</P>
<P>
   Or _ to frame it in terms of coach Phil Jackson's triangle
offense _ the Lakers just lost their hypotenuse, probably for a
minimum of 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal and Glen Rice can mitigate the loss in offense,
but the gaping hole at shooting guard won't be easily filled. Some
combination of Ron Harper, Rick Fox and a host of others will try,
but Jackson admitted there isn't a clear substitute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got no idea, to be honest with you,'' he said. ``That's
one of those spaces that we are short at right now. . . .If we had
to have an NBA game tomorrow, we'd have our problems, I'll tell you
that. Speed-wise and defensively, it's really going to hurt us for
a while. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just happy it's this time of year and not the middle or
the end.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' problems extend to the frontcourt as well. Reserve
power forward Travis Knight severely sprained his right ankle
Wednesday night and is out three to four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Just 21 years old, the dynamic Bryant was emerging as the team's
best defender and established himself last season as a
20-points-per-game scorer and the team's best clutch shooter. He
also was making great strides in the triangle offense, and his
absence will surely hurt the Lakers' progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely a possibility,'' said Derek Fisher. ``I think
because the offense is one that requires all five people to be on
the same page, when a guy's not getting a chance to go through it
and get the repetitions in . . . it will make it a little harder
for him to pick up on some different things and kind of fit back
in. But I think Kobe's bright enough, and he'll be here at practice
every day watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant broke the fourth metacarpal in his shooting hand when it
was struck by someone's elbow in the first quarter of Wednesday's
88-84 loss to Washington in Kansas City, Mo. Amazingly, Bryant
played through the end of the third quarter, scoring most of his 18
points after the injury, which he figured was just a bad bruise
though ``it was hurting like crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knew the extent of the injury until the next morning,
when Bryant was examined at the Kerlan-Jobe Orthopaedic Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours later, Bryant was already dribbling and practicing
with his left hand while his right hand rested in its new cast. And
he vowed to keep up with his triangle training.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is just watching and understanding,'' he said.
``It's imperative for me to be here and acquire a lot of knowledge.
But no, I won't fall behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant was able to forge a smile and joke about shooting
left-handed, but admitted hearing the news ``was tough. When the
doctor first put up the X-rays, he said it was broken, I was down.
I was upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I just pulled myself together. Everything happens for a
reason. I'm a firm believer in that. So it was easy for me to suck
it up and say maybe I'm not in the ultimate shape then. Maybe I
need to get in better shape and come back whenever I come back
ready. Maybe I need to work on my left.''
</P>
<P>
   And Jackson will work on finding a replacement _ probably within
the locker room. Executive vice president Jerry West indicated he
would not immediately try to obtain another shooting guard via
trade or free agency. He'd prefer to let the Lakers play a few more
exhibition games and see if someone emerges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it gives someone else a chance to step forward and get
some confidence and some playing time,'' West said.
</P>
<P>
   Harper and Fox are the obvious choices, but West hopes
first-round picks Sam Jacobson and Devean George will seize the
opportunity as well. Jacobson, drafted in 1998, barely played last
season; George, drafted in June, has made tremendous progress since
a poor summer-league showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be fine,'' assured O'Neal. ``It's going to be real
tough, but we've got a lot of other players that can fill that
void. Whenever you lose a player of that magnitude, someone else
has to step up. . . . If we can get two or three guys who can get
six to seven points (each), that will fill Kobe's 20 points a
game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
