<HEADLINE>
HARPER RELISHES MOVE BACK TO L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ron Harper's last extended stay in Los Angeles was
memorable, if not enjoyable. Remember the five years with the
Clippers, the ones he said felt like jail?
</P>
<P>
   Harper got a one-game suspension for the remark but earned
probation _ and that summer he departed for Chicago, where he won
three championships with Phil Jackson's Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Now the 13-year veteran laughs about his farewell to L.A. and
relishes his return as a Laker. And he isn't about to revisit
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not using that comment no more,'' he said of the ``jail''
reference. ``I'm going to refrain from any comments about my old
team here. I like Donald Sterling and the guys over there, Elgin
(Baylor), they're all friends of mine. . . . I felt that when I
played here was a learning experience, and I had fun playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning to town as a Laker, playing for Jackson, should be
much more fun.
</P>
<P>
   Harper was signed to provide experience in the triangle offense
and backup minutes at both guard positions. Now he's a candidate to
be the opening-night starter at off guard because of an injury to
Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to play a lot, I think, now. I'm going to need to
get in shape fast,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harper practiced for the first time Thursday after signing a
two-year, $4.2 million contract the day before. Personal matters
and the rehabilitation of his right knee prevented Harper from
attending training camp.
</P>
<P>
   But his knee, which underwent arthroscopic surgery in June, is
in good shape, he said, and he's not far behind his teammates
because he played the triangle for five years in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still a good two weeks away from basketball shape, I
think,'' he said. The 35-year-old's health is fine, but ``I'm still
old, though. That ain't never going to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper considered offers from a half-dozen other teams and
retirement before deciding to join the Lakers. They certainly need
his expertise in Jackson's system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched them on TV,'' Harper said of Wednesday's exhibition
loss to Washington. ``I gave them a C. They looked like they were
playing the triangle some. Now we can improve, and we will improve,
but we've got a ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Back to the Rock: The Lakers are trying to reschedule Tuesday's
canceled exhibition game in Little Rock, Ark., and are shooting for
Monday. That would make for a bittersweet road trip for Little Rock
native Derek Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher was disappointed when the exhibition game was canceled,
denying him the chance to play in front of hundreds of family and
friends. But playing Monday would make for a tough back-to-back,
with another game slated Tuesday in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what, I want it real bad, but . . . having to be back
in San Diego for a game on Tuesday, that's a lot,'' he said. ``It
definitely would be fun to get a chance to play that game, but
getting into that back-to-back across the country, this soon,
doesn't sound like a lot of fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
