<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-BOSTON-NY15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yankees add another verse to The Curse
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seven outs shy of escaping New York with a split, the
Boston Red Sox encountered a familiar personality Thursday night:
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees claimed a 2-0 lead in the ALCS, coming from
behind in the seventh on clutch two-out hitting by Chuck Knoblauch
and Paul O'Neill to win 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox threatened in the ninth but were turned away,
Mariano Rivera striking out Damon Buford to end it and strand
runners on the corners.
</P>
<P>
   This was hardly news. The Yankees brought an 11-game postseason
win streak to Yankee Stadium while Boston brought a nine-game
postseason losing streak that dates back to 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees starter David Cone left the game after seven innings as
the pitcher of record, allowing two runs on seven hits while
striking out nine, which tied his career-best in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   New York, needing just one more win to the the major league
record for consecutive postseason wins, entered the seventh
trailing 2-1. But the night changed quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch, staggering through a 1-for-6 series, tied the game
2-2 with a two-out double in the seventh, scoring Ricky Ledee, who
had opened the inning with a walk. That chased Boston starter Ramon
Martinez, who gave up six hits while striking out five.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Tom Gordon next walked Derek Jeter on a full count,
forcing manager Jimy Williams to bring in left-hander Rheal Cormier
to face O'Neill. Playing with a cracked rib that had limited him to
hitting just one ball out of the infield in eight plate
appearances, O'Neill fell behind 1-2 before fisting a soft single
into shallow left, scoring Knoblauch for a 3-2 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Normar Garciaparra's two-run fifth-inning homer off Cone gave
the Red Sox a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   With Jose Offerman on second and a 1-2 count with two outs,
Garciaparra waited on Cone's side-arm breaking ball, which he
golfed into the left field seats for this third homer of the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez, who had just appeared feeble against Ramon
Martinez's breaking ball in the fourth, put the Yankees up 1-0 with
his first home run of the postseason. After getting ahead in the
count 1-2 with his curve, Martinez attempted to throw an inside
fastball, which drifted back over the plate and Martinez laced it
into the right field seats.
</P>
<P>
   Of New York's first five runs of the ALCS, four of them came off
home runs, a surprisingly high rate for a team than ranked just
eighth in AL home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Cone, who struggled through a 3-5 second half, was coming off an
11-day break, which he tried beforehand to play off as a strategic
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I seem to work well on extra rest,'' Cone said. ``The only
other time I can think of that I have had this much rest was during
the All-Star break and then I came out and threw a perfect game.''
</P>
<P>
   Not this night. Cone was not particularly sharp early, walking
two of the first four men he faced, giving up a second-inning
triple to Jason Varitek, yielding two singles in the third and then
a double to Varitek in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sox could not pin him down, due to a clever curve ball
when he needed it. Deep into the fifth, Boston was 0-for-8 with
runners in scoring position with four strikeouts, two of them
called, until Garciaparra's blast.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
