<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7681 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS-HNS &LR;      10-15 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ If Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker listened to a
few reactionary fans, he would be shopping Jeff Bagwell and Craig
Biggio around the major leagues.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Such is the penalty when your bat goes cold in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Hunsicker and New York Mets general manager Steve
Phillips can work a deal. There are a few cold bats in the Mets'
lineup, too. And considering the common denominator, it's really no
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there's nothing wrong with Bagwell and Biggio or Mets
sluggers Mike Piazza, John Olerud and Robin Ventura. The Atlanta
Braves' pitching staff has a way of clamping down on the
opposition's biggest guns during the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the key in every series,'' Braves righthander John
Smoltz said. ``You have to pick out a couple of guys who you're not
going to let beat you.''
</P>
<P>
   That's perhaps the biggest reason the Braves hold a 2-0 lead in
the National League Championship Series as it shifts to New York's
Shea Stadium for Game 3 tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, Olerud and Ventura, who hit a combined .301 with 91
homers and 340 RBIs during the regular season, have one hit in 21
collective at-bats _ with eight men left on base _ in the first two
games of the NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   How do you explain the meltdown? Mets pitcher Kenny Rogers says
it's pretty simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you have to do is look at the other side,'' Rogers said.
``Good pitching shuts down good hitting. The meat of our order is
great, but sometimes you run into a wall.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are few cracks in the wall that is the Braves'
starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   After facing Greg Maddux and Kevin Millwood in the first two
games of the series, things don't figure to get much easier
tonight, when Tom Glavine takes the mound, or Saturday against
Smoltz, who pitched an inning out of the bullpen to earn the save
in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets might actually have the edge in tonight's matchup.
Based entirely on reputation, Glavine would get the check mark. But
Mets starter Al Leiter is on a roll, holding opponents _ the
Braves, Reds and Diamondbacks _ to a 1.90 ERA over his last three
starts and allowing just 10 hits in 24 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``To think it's the end of the world, to me, works totally
against you,'' Leiter said. ``You loosen up a bit, have fun with
it, laugh, joke; you could still have an inner aggressive feeling
inside to want to beat the guy you're facing, but it's still fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're still playing a baseball game.''
</P>
<P>
   While all the focus is on the Nos. 3, 4 and 5 hitters in the New
York lineup, the Mets are hitting just .169 and have scored five
runs in the series. Second baseman Edgardo Alfonzo and right
fielder Roger Cedeno have combined for seven of the Mets' 11 hits.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, they need some help from the Big Three.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to stay positive,'' Cedeno said. ``They're good
hitters, and we're 100 percent sure they're going to start hitting
again soon.''
</P>
<P>
   It had better be very soon.
</P>
<P>
   Time is running out for the Mets, who will be two games from
elimination tonight when they take the field before their home
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the shift of venues will change the Mets' luck, but so
far the series has mirrored the regular season when the Braves won
nine of the 12 meetings, including five of six over the season's
final 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like we're right there (close),'' said Piazza, who
has watched his team lose the first two games by a total of three
runs. ``They (the Braves) always find a way to beat us, and we
never find a way to beat them. It's frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   And frustration no doubt will turn to desperation if the Mets
lose tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team in the National League knows that to get to the
World Series, you have to go through Atlanta,'' Mets center fielder
Darryl Hamilton said. ``Win a game, and you build confidence; but
you have to win a game first.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, is hard to do when your primary run producers
don't produce runs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
