<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS HIRE COOPER AS COACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Sparks have hired a new head
coach. Again.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the Sparks on Thursday named former Lakers guard
Michael Cooper as the team's fourth head coach in as many WNBA
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper signed a guaranteed multi-year contract. Terms were not
released.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper replaces Orlando Woolridge, his former Lakers teammate,
whose one-year contract was not renewed because of philosophical
differences with Sparks president Johnny Buss. Cooper was an
assistant coach on last season's team when the Sparks recorded
their first winning season (20-12) and made their first playoff
appearance, advancing to the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp was the team's first coach but after a a 4-7 start
was replaced by assistant Julie Rousseau. Rousseau was replaced by
Woolridge, one of her assistants, after a 7-13 start in 1998. The
Sparks were 25-17 in regular season games under Woolridge.
</P>
<P>
   Known for his defensive prowess, Cooper was a third-round draft
pick for the Lakers in 1978. He won five World Championships with
the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very excited about this opportunity,'' Cooper said.
``After playing 12 years with the Lakers, knowing that I had some
kind of inkling that I would get into coaching. Little did I know
it would be professional women's basketball, but still it's
coaching and I'm excited and I'm ready to roll with the WNBA and
this franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper was first on a short list of candidates. His name was
mentioned when the franchise was searching for its first coach
three years ago, but the timing wasn't right. He was an assistant
for Lakers vice president Jerry West at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael was the very first person I talked to about coaching
this team,'' Buss said. ``It was just a matter of time before
Michael was going to take the helm. He's someone I always wanted.
The timing was right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper inherits a talented and experienced team that includes
center Lisa Leslie, forwards DeLisha Milton and LaKeisha Frett, and
guards Gordana Grubin and Mabika Mwadi.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks most likely will protect all of the above when next
year's expansion draft takes place for the league's four newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper made no promises for a championship next season, but said
he expects a better performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Lakers first got together in '79 we were a good team,
but it took certain pieces and other pieces were unlimited until we
got what we needed to win a championship,'' Cooper said. ``I think
that's the way our president is handling this. I'm going to not
promise you a championship, but I'm going to promise you that these
young ladies will play hard, they will play aggressive every game,
and we will let the chips fall where they may.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 0053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7685 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-FETERIK-LBPT     10-15 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FETERIK-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FETERIK'S HEISMAN BID UNDER WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kevin Feterik's Heisman Trophy campaign at least the one off the
football field will make its belated debut next week when the BYU
athletic department releases an interactive compact disc titled
``Quarterback Factory, Version 7.0.''
</P>
<P>
   Feterik's Heisman Trophy campaign the on-the-field variety
kicked off on a September evening in Provo, Utah when he was 39 of
59 for 501 yards with three touchdowns in a 35-28 victory over
Washington. His final touchdown throw a 38-yard strike to Chris
Hale after Feterik bought time by scrambling came with 1:16 left in
the contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of like a coming-out party for me,'' said Feterik,
a 1996 Los Alamitos High graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Then why did it take four additional games to launch a Heisman
campaign?
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into the season, Kevin had a couple of years where he
hadn't thrown ball that well or that much,'' BYU coach LaVell
Edwards said. ``Maybe that much wasn't expected of him.''
</P>
<P>
   But here he is, about to be thrown into a Heisman Trophy race
that became considerably more interesting when Florida State's
Peter Warrick, the clear front-runner, was charged with grand theft
recently and suspended from the Seminoles' team.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the Heisman, or for that matter, the Davey O'Brien
Trophy, the Johnny Unitas Golden Arm Award or the Sammy Baugh
Trophy, is not on Feterik's mind right now. He hasn't even
considered the possibility of being the first player from this area
to be invited to New York for the Heisman presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Former Los Angeles Rams, Notre Dame and St. Anthony High
receiver Jack Snow is the only local player to finish in the top
five in the Heisman voting. Snow finished fifth in 1964, the year
Notre Dame quarterback John Huarte won the award.
</P>
<P>
   ``Awards are something to look back on when the season is
over,'' Feterik said. ``It's something you can relish or enjoy at
that time. Right now, all I'm worried about is getting ready for
the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   As the quarterback at BYU, Feterik knows all about post-season
awards and high expectations.
</P>
<P>
   BYU as if you have to be told is the former home of such
quarterback luminaries Gifford Neilsen, Marc Wilson, Jim McMahon,
Steve Young, Robbie Bosco, Ty Detmer, John Walsh and Steve
Sarkisian. In the past three years, whether he wanted it or not,
Feterik grew accustomed to hearing his name mentioned with those
players.
</P>
<P>
   But his mention usually went something like ``Kevin Feterik is
no Neilsen, Wilson, McMahon, Young, Bosco, Detmer, Walsh or
Sarkisian.''
</P>
<P>
   Feterik heard the criticism. He also heard the boos and taunts
directed at he and his teammates. While he knew it was unfair,
Feterik accepted it as part of the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people just like to criticize,'' Feterik said.
</P>
<P>
   His numbers were indeed pedestrian compared to his predecessors.
Feterik was 125 of 208 for 1,767 yards as a sophomore junior
</P>
<P>
   and 202 of 336 for 2,718 last season. He had 27 touchdowns and
11 interceptions in the two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would see the stats and wonder why I didn't throw for
more yards,'' Feterik said.
</P>
<P>
   It was more of a change in philosophy than Feterik's ability.
His 544 attempts in two seasons were 18 less than Detmer had in his
1990 Heisman Trophy winning season alone.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of slinging spirals downfield Feterik spent much of the
time handing off to Brian McKenzie in 1997 and Ronney Jenkins last
year. It was the first time at BYU that there had been back-to-back
seasons with a 1,000-yard rusher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were more of a running attack,'' Feterik said. ``It was a
matter of having good running backs and good linemen.''
</P>
<P>
   The best linemen tackle John Tait was a first-round draft choice
and the top two running backs Jenkins and Junior Mahe left school.
So, with the team moving almost exclusively to the shotgun
formation, Feterik went to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I did was concentrate on putting on weight,'' said
Feterik, who entered the season with 17 more pounds on his 6-foot
frame than last season's 187. ``I think I've worked hard every
summer, but I worked extra hard this year in the weight room. I was
eating and lifting.''
</P>
<P>
   Feterik looked comfortable from the opening snap of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to figure out who was wearing Kevin's uniform
out there,'' BYU linebacker Rob Morris said after the Washington
game. ``We thought we had Jimmy Mac (McMahon) back.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't McMahon, but it was the old get-everybody-involved BYU
offense. Ten different receivers caught at least one pass in a
34-13 win over Colorado State and Feterik found nine separate
teammates in a 34-31 overtime win over Utah State.
</P>
<P>
   He followed the effort against Washington by torching Colorado
State for 310 yards and two touchdowns on 28 of 37 passing. He was
28 of 47 for 303 yards with three touchdowns in a 45-40 loss to
Virginia, 23 of 36 for 289 yards with four touchdowns in a the win
over Utah State and 25 of 41 for 414 yards with four touchdowns in
a 38-28 victory over California.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just taken advantage of our experience,'' Feterik said.
``Most definitely, it's more fun because it's my senior year. I
just feel so confident.''
</P>
<P>
   He also has a perpetual soreness. With a young offensive line in
front of him, Feterik has taken a pounding this season. He missed a
few plays after stretching medial collateral ligament against Utah
State and sat in the Cougars locker room after taking 38 hits
against Cal with ice bags on both elbows and his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is taking a beating like Kevin's taking a beating,''
said Los Alamitos assistant coach Barry Sher, who was the team's
offensive coordinator when Feterik threw for 3,205 yards and 29
touchdowns in his senior year. ``I kept watching him getting hit
and dragging himself up off the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cougars will be in trouble if Feterik doesn't keep getting
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I don't know what's going to happen if he keeps
having to take those hits,'' said wide receiver Ben Horton. ``It's
a real big concern for us. ... It's amazing he can sit back there
and read coverages while he has all those bodies coming at him.''
</P>
<P>
   He also keeps making plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy Stewart, our safeties coach, did a little study,'' Cal
head coach Tom Holmoe said, ``that showed they had 100 yards
passing on broken plays, where we would flush Feterik out of the
pocket and he'd dump the ball to the tight end or a back. That's
not lucky, that's good preparation and execution.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also good reason to insert Feterik's name into a Heisman
race that lost its favorite when Peter Warrick went on his discount
shopping tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin didn't have the advantage of advance publicity,''
Edwards said. ``He jumped onto the scene right now. But if he
continues to do what he's doing, there will be more attention.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
