</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-THRASHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THRASHERS GAIN THEIR FIRST VICTORY WITH WIN OVER ISLANDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ The New York Islanders will forever be linked
to one of hockey's latest trivia questions: who did the expansion
Atlanta Thrashers defeat for their first victory?
</P>
<P>
   For the Islanders' sake, it is good that only a handful of fans
showed up on Thursday night at Nassau Coliseum because it was the
Islanders who looked more like the expansion team in losing, 2-0,
to the Thrashers.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the Islanders who gave the Atlanta Flames their
first victory in 1972 when both teams opened their inaugural
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's game was played in front of the Coliseum's
smallest crowd in recent memory. There were entire sections that
were empty, and other sections had only a handful of fans.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a discount _ the Islanders reduced $27 tickets to $20
for anyone wearing a New York Mets cap or jersey _ there were 3,062
fans spread out in a building that seats 16,297.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't schedule many W's,'' Islanders Coach Butch Goring
said. ``But we certainly felt like this was a game that we could
have won. Atlanta came in and outworked us. That's not going to
happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta (1-2-1) got a goal from Andrew Brunette midway through
the first period, then got some help from a blown call by the
linesman for their second tally _ scored by Kelly Buchberger _
early in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders (1-3), outshot by 28-20, repeatedly fired the puck
into Atlanta goalie Damian Rhodes's pads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't give them much of a reason to come back,'' said
Islanders goalie Felix Potvin, who made 26 saves.
</P>
<P>
   Among the small turnout were the Atlanta Braves pitchers John
Smoltz and Tom Glavine, who watched from a luxury box. Glavine is a
former Los Angeles Kings draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Smoltz and Glavine came into the home team's
locker room and talked briefly about baseball with the Islanders'
Kenny Jonsson.
</P>
<P>
   With little to look forward to this season, both teams can at
least brag about their future. Thursday night showcased two of the
league's top prospects, centers Patrik Stefan of the Thrashers and
Tim Connolly of the Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly, the fifth pick over all in June, made his debut on the
Islanders' top line, playing between Brad Isbister and Mariusz
Czerkawski. Patrik Stefan, the No. 1 overall selection this year,
centered Atlanta's top line, playing between Buchberger and Darryl
Shannon. Stefan set up the Thrashers' second goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders were lethargic and disorganized in the opening
minutes and found themselves trailing, 1-0, after a power play goal
by Brunette at 12 minutes 21 seconds. Buchberger, the Thrashers'
captain, made the score 2-0 at 6:53 of the final period on a play
that was offside. Nelson Emerson attempted to pass the puck across
the blue line, but it slid over the line by nearly a foot before
Stefan picked it up and passed to Buchberger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously he just missed it,'' Goring said of the linesman. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
