<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7688 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      10-15 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN M'S GRAND SCHEME, A-ROD RESOLUTION MUST COME FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Since Alex Rodriguez and his agent indicated this week
virtually no desire to sign a contract extension with any team
until the shortstop becomes a free agent after the 2000 season, the
corner the Mariners find themselves in this off-season just became
excruciatingly tight.
</P>
<P>
   Because of trade-market pressure, the Mariners have to make over
their roster by around Thanksgiving to induce Rodriguez and Ken
Griffey Jr. to sign long-term contract extensions. And that
makeover may have to be accomplished by a general manager new to
the organization's talent.
</P>
<P>
   If the superstars remain unimpressed with the moves toward
fielding a contending team, the Mariners likely will be forced to
unload both players relatively soon in order to get a respectable
return _ agonizing decisions that will nevertheless eliminate a
repeat of the 1998 Randy Johnson debacle.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the club gave Rodriguez a mid-November deadline for a
response to its September contract offer. The first chance to begin
the makeover is baseball's free agency period, which begins 15 days
after the end of the World Series. That could be as soon as Nov.
11, which is also the last day of the annual meetings among
baseball's GMs.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do the Mariners need to move swiftly to satisfy
Rodriguez, they need to move even faster if he spurns them, in
order to take maximum advantage of a thin free-agent crop as well
as ownership's forecasted increase in the player payroll to around
$70 million next season.
</P>
<P>
   Those moves also would be part of the strategy to corral
Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a reason for the deadline,'' said one baseball
executive. ``Not many teams can afford either player, and because
there's no guarantee that either will sign beyond 2000, some of
those teams will fill their roster holes in ways that are cheaper
and less risky.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only are both players great and greatly expensive, they each
hold a kind of leverage that complicates potential transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Any team acquiring Rodriguez for his final contract year of 2000
is faced with the challenge of convincing him to skip his potential
free agency bonanza after the season.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the gamble worked for St. Louis when the
Cardinals were able to sign Mark McGwire to a long-term deal after
his trade from Oakland. Last year for Houston and Randy Johnson,
the gamble didn't work. The Big Unit was rented from Seattle for
two months, then skipped to the Arizona Diamondbacks, while the
Astros lost three top prospects to the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's case is different. As a player with 10 years of major
league experience, including at least five with the same team,
baseball rules allow such a veteran the right to approve the teams
to which he could be traded.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey puts a finer point on it, saying he will demand to
review terms of any trade. If a team he likes guts itself in order
to make the deal with the Mariners, he will refuse the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no rule that says he can do it,'' said a Mariners
official, ``but if we don't tell him the trade terms, he can say no
for whatever reason.''
</P>
<P>
   As such, he can't be limited by any Mariners-imposed deadline,
as with Rodriguez. Griffey can go through the entire offseason and
play into 2000 if he likes, until the Mariners satisfy him.
</P>
<P>
   However, Griffey, 30 next month, also has told Mariners
officials that, unlike Rodriguez, he prefers to do a long-term
extension this winter, be it with the Mariners or another team.
</P>
<P>
   Because Griffey holds such a powerful hammer, and because his
contract length and size will dictate how much money the Mariners
can commit now to many future payrolls, a Rodriguez resolution must
come first.
</P>
<P>
   Since Rodriguez seems to have closed the door on an early
signing, the possibility remains that he could start the season
with the Mariners. If Griffey has re-upped, other improvements are
made and the team is winning big, Rodriguez might be persuaded to
enter into a long-term deal. If not, the club could still get value
for him at the July 31 trade deadline.
</P>
<P>
   That scenario brings up the specter of the Johnson debacle, in
which the uncertainty of his contract future made the Unit an
emotional wreck and compromised his Seattle season.
</P>
<P>
   Though almost no one who knows Rodriguez thinks he will be as
unprofessional as Johnson, the distraction for Rodriguez and the
team will be unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   Another scenario, this one favored by Rodriguez and his agent,
Scott Boras, is that the Mariners let Rodriguez play with the
improved club that includes Griffey for 2000, then pursue him in
the free-agent market with the big dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Boras says if the Mariners truly mean what they say about
building a champion, they shouldn't be afraid. A-Rod has said he's
willing to consider taking less to stay if the Mariners really do
walk the walk. Even if he's traded in July, Boras contends, it
would be with assurances the club will be back after him in the
free agent market.
</P>
<P>
   But a delayed trade is a high-risk maneuver for any club,
particularly one with no history of big-name free-agent success, or
even boldness.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor that be might working against the Mariners is one
the club believed would work only for them _ the new ballpark.
Players were asked this season by management to avoid critical
comments, but it was plain in private conversations that neither
Griffey nor Rodriguez took to the place.
</P>
<P>
   Though the much-discussed fence distances can always be
shortened, there's nothing to be done about two environmental
factors _ cold and glare.
</P>
<P>
   At times, April and May will be almost Candlestick-like. Even in
this season's good weather, the brightness of the
moisture-refracted sunlight caused day-game problems for numerous
players at bat and in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Though such stadium issues may sound petty, remember that these
are pampered ballplayers used to getting everything their way. And
with anyone else, if you don't want to be somewhere, any excuse
will work as a reason not to go.
</P>
<P>
   Bleak as things sound for the Mariners, the situation isn't
without hope, at least as far as trades. The same economic madness
that has helped put the Mariners in this bind can also work a
little for them.
</P>
<P>
   If more than one of the deep-pocket clubs focuses on either
player as a new franchise cornerstone, a testosterone-fueled
bidding war could happen that will outstrip the cautions.
</P>
<P>
   When George Steinbrenner, Rupert Murdoch, Ted Turner and any of
their macho brethren get a chance to not only make a big splash,
but embarrass a rival, they can be goaded into foolishness. The
players who are likeliest to induce that foolishness are Griffey
and Rodriguez, highly talented and attractive athletes who are
almost unbelievably young to be this good and this available.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the possibility of above-market rewards, trades mean
Griffey and Rodriguez would be out from Seattle. No deal will bring
back their dynamism, a void that probably will scream for years.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
