<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-PENGUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENGUINS TOP RANGERS, 5-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Rangers followed their most emotional
performance of the young season with their most lethargic one on
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the announced sellout crowd at Madison Square Garden had
filed out before the third period had begun. No one could pinpoint
the exact reason the Rangers were so bad in a 5-2 loss to the
Pittsburgh Penguins, just three days after a 4-2 victory over the
Islanders on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   But everyone agreed on one thing: it was easily the Rangers'
worst outing of the season. As Coach John Muckler put it: ``We
played very poorly right from the first period. We had nothing
going all night long.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers trailed by three goals just 12 minutes 24 seconds
into the game. And they dropped to a record of 3-3-1, after a
three-game winning streak had put them within reach of two games
over .500 for the first time since Mark Messier left for Vancouver
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the team captain, Brian Leetch _ borrowing a page
from what Messier might have said _ asserted that the Rangers could
learn from Thursday night's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Leetch cautioned, ``we can't look like that out there.
We can't look like we haven't played hockey. We did everything
wrong out there that we possibly could for over a period.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers came out on their heels and pretty much stayed that
way. They played shoddy defense throughout in allowing more than
two goals for the first time this season. The backup goaltender
Kirk McLean, who had had four straight strong outings in relief of
the injured Mike Richter, was yanked midway through the first
period. Richter is due back Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   And again, the Rangers received no help from their power play,
which went 0 for 3 and is now 3 for 36 on the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the goalkeeper's fault,'' Muckler said in defense of
McLean, who came back for the third period and did not allow
another goal. ``It was everybody's fault.''
</P>
<P>
   The tone of the evening was pretty much set 2:08 into the game,
when the former Rangers wing Aleksei Kovalev caught Theo Fleury
flush in the face with a vicious elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury sat out the rest of the period with a sore neck. And as
Muckler scrambled to find the right line combinations, the Penguins
riddled McLean with three goals on nine shots before Muckler
replaced McLean with Milan Hnlicka 12:24 into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Kovalev scored the first goal at 6:25. He made a pretty move
around Mathieu Schneider through the right wing circle, passed the
puck to himself before slapping a shot past McLean for a 1-0
Penguins lead.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was Jaromir Jagr's turn to set up Pittsburgh's second
goal. The last time Jagr played on the Garden ice, he scored the
game-winner to send Wayne Gretzky into retirement, in what many
felt was a passing of the torch. And on Thursday night, Jagr, who
has always given the Rangers fits, again demonstrated why many feel
he is the premier player in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the first period, Jagr carried the puck through
the right wing circle in the Rangers' zone, stopped on a dime,
changed direction, skated back up through the circle to its top and
then passed to Ian Moran at the top of the slot. Moran blasted a
one-timer past McLean.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later, Robert Lang pushed a soft goal past McLean at
12:24 to make the score 3-0. That was it for McLean for a period
and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Petr Nedved scored his first goal of the season at 18:57 of the
first period to cut the deficit to 3-1. But on consecutive
second-period shots, Jagr and Rob Brown each blasted one-timers
past Hnlicka, who was making his first National Hockey League
appearance; Jagr's came at 17:10 of the second, Brown's at 18:57.
And the Rangers _ who received a rare goal from defenseman Sylvain
Lefebrve in the final period _ trailed by 5-1 heading into the
third period.
</P>
<P>
   With a minute left in the game, Pittsburgh's 20-year-old rookie
defenseman, Andrew Ference, rattled Nedved with what the Rangers
thought was a cheap hit. John MacLean and Kevin Stevens went after
Ference with a vengeance. It was one of the few signs of life from
the Rangers all night. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
