<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7691 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-BLACKS-VOTE-KAN &LR;      10-15 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKS-VOTE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Black leaders in Kansas City vowed Thursday to mobilize
African-American voters next year to defeat Sen. John Ashcroft, the
Missouri Republican who led the fight to reject Judge Ronnie White
for a seat on the federal bench. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not get angry. Do not get even,'' intoned former Kansas
City Mayor Emanuel Cleaver. ``Get active.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   White, the first African-American to serve on the Missouri
Supreme Court, was rejected for the federal judgeship last week on
a party-line vote. Ashcroft said White had a weak record on the
death penalty, a charge that Democrats disputed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meeting at Mount Pleasant Baptist Church, about 30 black
officials pledged to mount a vigorous election challenge to
Ashcroft next year. The senator is seeking his second six-year term
in November 2000 against Democratic Gov. Mel Carnahan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The officials plan to fax protest letters to the four Republican
senators from Missouri and Kansas who opposed White. They also plan
to mount voter-registration and get-out-the-vote drives against
Ashcroft, the only one of the four senators up for election next
year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft, meantime, responded that he had an excellent record
when it came to approving women and minorities for federal
judgeships. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the size of Thursday's crowd wasn't especially significant,
the makeup of the group was. For the first time in years, a
coalition that included members of Freedom Inc., the city's premier
black political group; Concerned Clergy, a group of 65 black
ministers; and elected city and county officials were united for a
common purpose. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As recently as last year, African-Americans in Kansas City and
St. Louis were divided over whom to back in the Senate race between
Republican Kit Bond and Democrat Jay Nixon. Bond wound up capturing
33 percent of the state's black vote, a significant accomplishment
for a Republican. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But that will not happen next year in the Carnahan-Ashcroft
race, the black leaders vowed. They said even rank-and-file voters
who don't follow politics closely are angry about the White
rejection. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you Mr. Ashcroft because you just energized a sleeping
giant,'' Kansas City Councilman Kelvin Simmons said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting Thursday, leaders took turns bashing Ashcroft and
Bond for their roles in White's defeat. While Ashcroft spearheaded
the anti-White campaign, Bond announced his opposition the day
before the vote. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Without the support of either home-state senator, White's fate
was sealed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I see little difference between a physical lynching and
political castration,'' said the Rev. L. Henderson Bell, Mount
Pleasant's pastor who led the meeting. ``I see little difference
between a man being drug to death in Texas and a man of Ronnie
White's character being assassinated at this point in his
career.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Mary Groves Bland, president of Freedom, contended
that White's rejection was racially motivated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows he has the qualifications,'' Bland said. ``He
should not have been denied.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft spokesman Steve Hilton defended the senator. Hilton
contended that Ashcroft's record on appointing women and minorities
to important judicial slots was superb. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That record includes the appointment of the first woman to the
Missouri Supreme Court and the first black to the Missouri Court of
Appeals in Kansas City. The black bar association serving St. Louis
commended Ashcroft in 1991 for his appointments. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Senate, he has voted for literally scores of qualified
women and minorities for federal judgeships all over the country,''
Hilton said. ``He cherishes diversity.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hilton repeated Ashcroft's concern that law-enforcement groups
opposed White. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats have countered that Ashcroft orchestrated the
opposition by notifying the groups of potential issues concerning
White's record. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also speaking Thursday was the Rev. Charles Brown of St. Louis,
who contended that Bond lied to clergy members last year because
the senator told them he would back White. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bond, though, has said that he promised to back White only
through the nomination process, not necessarily when it reached the
Senate floor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hard feelings about how African-Americans voted in the 1998
Senate race continue. After the meeting, Bland approached a
reporter to note that in last year's Senate race, Freedom stuck
with Nixon, the Democrat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We researched his record,'' Bland said of Bond. ``We knew who
he was. Freedom made the right decision.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Concerned Clergy, however, backed Bond. Bell defended that move,
saying that ministers could not back Nixon because of his stand on
the Kansas City school desegregation case. Nixon fought to end
state funding of that plan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bond said he turned against White when the law-enforcement
groups spoke out. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 0107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7692 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-SCHOOLS-ACCREDITATION     10-15 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-ACCREDITATION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEARS OF BAD LEADERSHIP PRODUCED KC SCHOOL CRISIS, STATE OFFICIAL
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Missouri Education Commissioner Robert Bartman admits he's a
little fuzzy on what the future would hold for an unaccredited
Kansas City School District. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Bartman is crystal clear on how the district sank to this
point. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He blamed unstable leadership, a bloated bureaucracy, a school
board more interested in patronage than performance and a federal
court presence that kept the district focused on integration rather
than education. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there is a lot of concern about the impact of having an
unaccredited district,'' Bartman said Thursday in Kansas City.
``But I would have hoped the concern would have been just as
heightened knowing that they had young people that weren't doing
well in school...not just this year or last year, but generations
of kids who have gone through the schools without having the kind
of intense focus on student performance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that the position of the state Board of Education is
that the current levels of performance are unacceptable.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bartman is recommending that the Kansas City and St. Louis
districts be stripped of their accreditation for failing to
adequately educate students. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The state board is to discuss Bartman's recommendation Thursday
in Jefferson City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the board follows his recommendation, about 10 percent of
Missouri's elementary and secondary students would be attending
unaccredited schools. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bartman spent parts of two days this week in Kansas City
explaining to civic and business leaders the rationale behind his
recommendation. He met for about two hours Thursday morning with
the editorial board of The Kansas City Star. He then flew to St.
Louis to meet with officials there in the afternoon and evening. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Kansas City school board met in private for the
second time in two nights to discuss the state's actions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Board President John Rios said that district leaders were
``flabbergasted'' and that administrators were reviewing the
district's options. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope this can be worked out and avoid the loss of
accreditation,'' Rios said. ``That's the board's top priority _ to
see what can be done to avoid it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rios said he was angry that the state might act so soon after
the board hired Benjamin Demps Jr. as superintendent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like everybody is telling us what we need to do, but the
assistance is slow in coming,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rios said that if the district loses its accreditation, he would
consider removing his three children from district schools. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``As a parent, I would have to consider moving or fleeing,'' he
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bartman said the possible loss of accreditation should come as
no surprise to the Kansas City district. He said the state had
repeatedly warned the district over the last two years of the need
to raise student performance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bartman said he expected to be lobbied to change his
recommendation. But he said he was confident of the support of the
state Board of Education and Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a discretionary call,'' Bartman said. ``We could say
kids are performing all right and that they're doing the best that
they can. But we don't believe that.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bartman said his high regard for Demps would not sway his
recommendation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been encouraged before, about 18 times over the last 20
years, that this next person is really going to get the job done,''
Bartman said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Bartman said, the parade of superintendents has been a
detriment to the district. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last 20 years, the district has been whipsawed back
and forth by different leadership, different styles of
leadership,'' he said. Those leaders also brought in their own
teams, some of whom remained long after their leaders had
departed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over time, Bartman said, those employees build into layers of
people whose agendas may differ from the current leadership. Too
often, those employees become ``a system of assassins'' who block
progress, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He also criticized the Kansas City school board practice of
electing some board members from subdistricts. He said that had
contributed to superintendent turnover, patronage and retention of
unqualified employees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Board members elected by subdistrict feel some obligation to
take care of their district, and that sometimes means finding
employment for people in their subdistrict,'' Bartman said. ``So
the children of the district became not the first priority of the
district.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bartman said he and the state board considered the accreditation
process its first real chance to positively influence the direction
of the state's two largest districts. In the past, the state
complained that its role in St. Louis and Kansas City was
overshadowed by the federal court, which oversaw desegregation
lawsuits in both districts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The shadow of the federal court did some positive things,''
Bartman said. ``But what they took away from the district over a
long period of time is any notion of what accountability was. The
focus was never on performance. It was all about programs, about
integration, about buildings, about money.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bartman said his department was also concerned about whether the
loss of accreditation might hasten the exodus of district students
to charter schools. Charter schools are publicly funded but free
from many state and district regulations. Fifteen of the schools
began operating in the Kansas City district this year, and two more
have approval to open. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no simple answer I can give to that,'' he said.
``There might be some who would say if the Kansas City School
District is not performing...maybe those kids ought to go somewhere
else.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Bartman also said there was no evidence yet that Missouri
charter schools would perform better than the district. He is
especially concerned by what he considers to be a lack of
accountability for charter schools, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that we need to come to some agreement that we will
hold fast on charter school openings right now until we see what
the impact is of the decision to not accredit the district,''
Bartman said. ``Let's wait and see how the 15 or 17 are doing and
then see how responsive the Kansas City district is to responding,
to healing itself, to getting better.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some believe the district is too large to operate effectively,
Bartman said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But he said large districts can function well if employees have
a common mission, are competent and willing to take some risks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He called for a more streamlined central office that would give
principals more direct access to top leadership. He also said the
district needed to recruit or train existing principals to be top
performers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bartman also said the district must change the culture of the
organization, ``because there are some people who have given up and
said these kids can't be taught and think if we can keep them out
of trouble during the day and go home safely then we've done our
job. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What schooling is all about is how kids perform, what they
know and are able to do and whether they will be successful when
they leave school,'' Bartman said. ``We intend to continue to push
the envelope on performance for all kids across the state. It's
doable in Kansas City, but it's going to take the new leadership we
believe they have now and the focus of the district and the
community.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 0111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
