r a BC-HEALTH-REFORM-KAN &LR;      10-15 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-REFORM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH-CARE REFORM WON'T HAPPEN UNTIL PUBLIC DEMANDS IT, FORMER
SURGEON GENERAL SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED FLETCHER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congress won't pass major health-care reform until the public
demands it, former U.S. Surgeon General Joycelyn Elders told a
group of health-care providers Thursday in Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any problem feeling that every criminal has a
constitutional right to lawyers,'' Elders said. ``Why can't we feel
that every sick person in America has a right to health care? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It really makes no sense.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elders spoke to more than 70 area health-care providers during
the opening day of the Black Health Care Coalition's annual
symposium on issues facing urban populations. The symposium at the
Westin Crown Center hotel concludes Saturday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elders also talked about the need for preventive health care
over the current system of ``sick care'' and the need for health
education for people of all ages. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elders served as President Clinton's first surgeon general. She
was confirmed by Congress in September 1993. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She resigned in December 1994 after making a series of
controversial statements. During her time as surgeon general she
suggested studying the effect that legalizing drugs would have on
crime and said masturbation was part of ``human sexuality'' and
should be taught as part of sex education. She teaches medicine at
the University of Arkansas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She has not stopped giving her opinions, however. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Health-care organizations that allow lawyers and accountants to
make medical decisions are damaging to patients, Elders said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I always tell people they better get better in their time
limit. Back in the old days, if someone needed to stay a month we
didn't think about it,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We as doctors allowed lawyers...to take over medicine.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the medical system excels at curing the sick, it is not
doing what is needed to prevent illnesses, Elders said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we have the best sick-care system, the best
doctors, best nurses and best hospitals, we don't have the best
health care,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Simple things such as prenatal care, immunizations and education
would result in huge savings and better lives for Americans, she
said. More education is needed for the elderly and youth alike.
Elders advocates expanding health education in schools. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We spend $10 million talking about nutrition and Mr. McDonald
spends $40 million on advertising his Big Mac. So it is no wonder
kids want a Big Mac,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patients don't have enough information on caring for themselves,
she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty percent of hospital admissions are there because they
did not take their medicine right. So we know it is very costly. We
as a society have to learn that ignorance is not bliss. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be empowered to take care of your health if you
don't know how.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Education also could end the abortion debate, Elders said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If you prevent unplanned, unwanted pregnancies there would
never be a need for an abortion, because I have never known any
woman who needed an abortion that wasn't already pregnant,'' she
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
