<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7695 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-KIDNAPPING-ARREST-KAN     10-15 1477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDNAPPING-ARREST-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDNAPPING SUSPECT CAPTURED; SEARCH FOR GIRL CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD ESPINOZA, STACY DOWNS and DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two-day hunt for a suspected kidnapper ended Thursday
afternoon when a police employee's hunch helped locate Keith D.
Nelson near the Kansas River. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But after Nelson was handcuffed and flown to a hospital,
investigators said they weren't any closer to reaching their most
important goal: Finding 10-year-old Pamela Butler, the Kansas City,
Kan., girl who was last seen being pulled into Nelson's work truck
Tuesday evening. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Police still hoped to return Pamela to her family alive, but
that hope dwindled as hours passed with little sign of the girl. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's realistic to say that hope fades as time goes on, but we
retain a positive disposition,'' FBI spokesman Jeff Lanza said.
``Most cases where there's a long amount of time after the
abduction, it is not good news.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, 24, was arrested near the 18th Street Expressway Bridge
on the south bank of the river about 1:30 p.m. Limping from a leg
injury, he was wet after taking to the water in an attempt to elude
pursuers who were alerted by the civilian police employee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By 3:30 p.m. he had been charged with kidnapping in U.S.
District Court in Kansas City, Mo. An accompanying seven-page
affidavit describes how authorities think Nelson conceived and
carried out the abduction, including a suggestion that he ``cased''
Pamela's neighborhood. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit says Nelson told a worker at a job site Sept. 29
that he ``would like to kidnap a girl to rape'' and made salacious
comments about a teen-age girl of whom he had caught a glimpse. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit alleges that Nelson was lying in wait in the truck
as Pamela skated unsuspectingly toward it. As she approached the
back of the truck, he jumped out and threw her inside, the
affidavit says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pamela was abducted in front of her home in the 500 block of
South 11th Street. Authorities allege that Nelson, who lived with a
woman in Kansas City, Kan., drove Pamela into Missouri. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, Nelson was at the University of Kansas
Medical Center for treatment of the leg injury, which police think
occurred Wednesday while he was on the run. Bond won't be set until
he appears before a magistrate, which won't happen until doctors
operate on the leg. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 investigators were hunting for Nelson, taking
clothes from Pamela's room to help dogs lock onto her scent, diving
into a pond for clues and searching fields. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But there was no sign of Pamela, whom her mother described as a
happy child. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``She is a funny girl and likes to play jokes,'' her mother,
Cherri West, said. ``She is a tomboy, she's outgoing, she likes to
Rollerblade, she plays basketball, she sings, she dances. During
recess, she plays tether ball and kick ball at Fiske Elementary.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A man who works in Pamela's neighborhood told police that he had
seen a man who resembled Nelson cruising the area Monday as if he
were casing the neighborhood. On Thursday morning, the first
concrete sign that police might catch Nelson and possibly find
Pamela came when someone saw a man who looked like Nelson driving a
white van in the Armourdale area of Kansas City, Kan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Police chased the van through morning traffic from Kansas City,
Kan., along Mission Road into Johnson County as the driver swerved
into oncoming traffic, clipped the rear of a police car and sped
through red lights. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Police thought their manhunt was over when a man bailed out of
the moving van onto the Prairie Village Police Department's front
lawn, but he turned out to be someone with no connection to
Pamela's abduction, police said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Officers told the man to take care of three traffic warrants
from Kansas City, Kan., but the violations were so minor that
Kansas City, Kan., police officers didn't stop him from walking out
of the police department. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The van sped on. The driver continued south along Mission, under
the Interstate 435 viaduct and onto Tomahawk Creek Parkway in
Leawood. Just north of 119th Street, police rammed the van from
behind, spinning it. It stopped and officers arrested a woman, but
she was not charged Thursday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   West said the morning chase led to a rocky day. ``I was really
aggravated when it turned out it wasn't him,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And she didn't feel any better after Nelson was taken into
custody. ``It's not a good feeling,'' she said. ``A court might
find it's not him.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After about 40 minutes of excitement with the morning chase, the
search for Nelson settled back into the routine of the previous
day: Talking to people who might know where to find him, examining
clues from the 1997 Ford pickup he was driving and letting police
dogs sniff for a trace of Pamela. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next suspect who was chased down turned out to be the man
police wanted. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Near the Kansas River the police employee, Laurie Torrez, was
taking lunch to her husband at his job at the Burlington Northern
Santa Fe Railroad tracks. She decided to take a slow drive along a
dike. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was about 1:30 p.m., and she had a hunch Nelson might be
holed up nearby. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He was. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lying near the bridge and realizing he had been discovered,
Nelson hobbled to the river, said Kansas City, Kan., Police Chief
James Swafford. The injury kept him from getting too far into the
current, and he either swam or was pulled back to shore, where
railroad employees held him for police. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Doctors think Nelson had hurt his leg in a long fall the day
before and might have been in too much pain to flee from where he
landed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the helicopter flew Nelson to the hospital, a group of
investigators _ including police divers and dog handlers _ searched
the river and its banks. They left at nightfall without finding
Pamela. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other officers returned to sites that had been searched before.
Some poked through a home-building site on Lee's Summit Road in
Kansas City, where Nelson's boss said he dumped construction waste
to fill ponds. Others returned to the area near a church in Grain
Valley where a church maintenance worker and his wife had seen
Nelson's empty pickup about an hour after Pamela was kidnapped. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Relatives said they helped Thursday when they spent almost three
hours scouring a junkyard that authorities told them Nelson's uncle
owns in Kansas City, Kan. The junkyard, at 1144 S. 14th St., is
about three blocks from Pamela's home. They didn't find anything. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bates County Sheriff Duane Diehl said Nelson had spent time in
the Bates County Jail, mostly for burglary and stealing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a thief and cat burglar and he's pretty good at it,''
Diehl said. ``He's a scrapper and a fighter, too. And he's elusive.
Four or five of us chased him around town here before we found him
hiding on top of a house.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An outstanding Bates County warrant charges Nelson with
tampering with a judicial officer. Diehl said the charge stems from
an incident in which Nelson allegedly threatened his probation
officer with a can of Mace. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nelson's grandmother said Thursday that she was surprised at the
latest allegation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to believe he did it, but if he did, I think
someone put him up to it,'' Wilma Nelson said from her home in
Amsterdam, Mo., in Bates County, about an hour's drive south of
Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always a follower. He did a lot of break-ins and stuff
like that, but he's never hurt a kid. He was always a good person
around me.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She said Nelson was originally from Kansas City, Kan., where he
lived with his mother and four siblings. According to Wilma Nelson,
the mother moved with the children to California. They later moved
to Texas before settling in Amsterdam. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bates County Circuit Clerk Diana Rich said Keith Nelson was
convicted on four counts of burglary and stealing in February 1993
and sentenced to three years on each count, with the terms to run
concurrently. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The judge suspended the sentence and placed Nelson on
probation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, on April 24, 1993, Nelson helped a man
escape from the Bates County Jail. He was charged with aiding and
abetting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His probation was revoked, and Nelson was sent to prison on May
26, 1993. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He was released on Jan. 31, 1996. But he didn't stay free long. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to the Missouri Department of Corrections, Nelson was
returned to prison on April 23, 1996, for second-degree burglary
and served until Feb. 18, 1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; tag1:To reach Richard Espinoza, call {(816) 234-7714} or send
e-mail to {respinoza &LR; kcstar.com} &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; tag1:To reach Stacy Downs, call {(816) 234-7716} or send e-mail
to {sdowns &LR; kcstar.com} &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; tag1:To reach Donald Bradley, call {(816) 234-7810} or send
e-mail to {dbradley &LR; kcstar.com} &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
