<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7696 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-1ST     10-15 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: O'NEIL GRITS TEETH AND BEARS THE PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The glare was direct and distinct, Clint Eastwood in
a pinstriped baseball suit, though it was obviously unrehearsed.
After one question, Paul O'Neill had heard enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to feel it once in a while,'' he said of his
fractured rib. ``But I'm tired of talking about it. The story is
Boston and New York.''
</P>
<P>
   The story, again, on Thursday night at Yankee Stadium was a
nervous home team victory, 3-2, for a 2-0 lead in the American
League Championship Series. The seventh-inning sub-plot starred
O'Neill, wounded warrior with a tender swing, against a left-handed
Boston reliever named Rheal Cormier. The Yankees, having just
pushed across the tying run, had Chuck Knoblauch on third, two men
out.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill, without a hard hit ball in eight series at-bats,
promptly fell into a 1-2 hole. Cormier tried a fastball, running
inside. O'Neill fought it off, breaking his bat. He blooped the
ball, just beyond the sure hands of the shortstop, Nomar
Garciaparra, into left field, for a run-scoring single. The Yankee
bullpen held on, barely. O'Neill had a game-winning hit to talk
about instead of his pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing,'' he insisted, ``has been blown out of
proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   The tentative swings, the foul ball away, say something else, as
did the Game 1 grimace O'Neill wore after making a sliding catch.
When we have seen that look on other faces, we have remembered it
fondly. A wincing Kirk Gibson struck the supreme World Series pose
hitting his mind-bending home run in 1988. Michael Jordan a couple
of years ago, sick to his stomach during the finals in Salt Lake
City, was never more unearthly and human at the same time. Pete
Sampras serving an ace in a U.S. Open match when he appeared more
likely to faint was never more appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Along those lines, O'Neill hurled himself against the
right-field wall in the second inning on Thursday night for a Jason
Varitek drive he mis-timed and did not catch. The run never scored.
The effort did count.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Paul's going to play,'' Derek Jeter said, ``then he's going
to play hard.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a rare subject in sports that doesn't require much talk.
We can see for ourselves that some athletes play when their bodies
tell them not to, and some athletes don't. Some make an attempt
when they're not feeling well and proceed to not run fast enough to
suit the critics. But those who make millions of dollars are never
more publicly hailed than when they drag their aching bodies across
the big game landscape, and when they win.
</P>
<P>
   As a kid, I remember reading in the newspaper that Mickey Mantle
had bled right through his uniform during the 1961 World Series. It
is an image, a young boy's sense of true heroism, that has endured
for 38 years and more than a few less flattering Mantle tales.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill didn't bleed, didn't hit a home run. As he said, ``Two
strikes, a pitcher making good pitches, I'm just trying to put the
ball in play.'' He had already left two runners on in the third.
Had he failed again, had the Yankees lost with the more menacing
Martinez _ Pedro, not Ramon _ looming Saturday in Boston, Joe Torre
would surely have been asked why he let O'Neill convince him he
could play at all.
</P>
<P>
   Torre could have talked himself into a healthier outfield
situation, but he is loyal to the veterans who have helped him win
here and he also seems to sense that vulnerability has been and
remains a most appealing and effective staple of his Yankee teams.
They have a payroll soaring toward $100 million. They won more
overall games than any team in history last year. They are owned by
a man who considers failure to be everything but the ultimate goal.
And yet, the impression is that rooting for these Yankees is not
like rooting for U.S. Steel.
</P>
<P>
   You start with the manager, a cancer patient last spring, and
his 68-year-old bench coach, Don Zimmer, limping through the season
and bouncing up from the recent dugout shot he took to the ear. Go
through the lineup, and there is Scott Brosius dealing with the
trauma of burying his father, while Knoblauch's father battles
Alzheimer's and the second baseman struggles with his own throwing
dysfunction. Yet it was Knoblach who drove in the tying run, then
scored on the aching O'Neill's hit, making a winner of David Cone,
whose future as a Yankee is a survival story in itself.
</P>
<P>
   Chili Davis at the end of a 19-year run. Darryl Strawberry
living day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   This franchise has had a long winning tradition mixed with
turmoil but this Yankee team has carved its own special niche for
professionalism amidst personal pain.
</P>
<P>
   So O'Neill, without another word about his rib, picked up his
glove again on Thursday night and trotted out to right field. He
hung in against Cormier in the seventh. His bloop today looks like
a blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two one-run games,'' he said of the ALCS thus far. ``Pretty
gut-wrenching.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
