<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GRANNY D.' ON HAND AS SENATE BEGINS DEBATE ON CAMPAIGN FINANCE
BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Doris ``Granny D'' Haddock guessed what was inside
the gift from Sen. John McCain even before getting through the red
wrapping paper: a new pair of sneakers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, good,'' said the 89-year-old woman Thursday. ``I've worn
out three of these, and I'm ready for another pair.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Haddock, who has walked from Los Angeles to Nashville, Tenn., so
far on her trek to Washington, slung the new shoes over her neck.
Then she ascended the Capitol steps, flanked by McCain, an Arizona
Republican, and Sen. Russ Feingold, a Wisconsin Democrat, as they
made their way inside to the Senate floor for the start of debate
on a bill to reform campaign finance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Taking a break from her cross-country journey, she had flown to
Washington to present the senators a gift as well: good publicity
about their uphill effort to ban unlimited soft money donations to
political parties. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Feingold saw Haddock as an irresistible means of
putting a face _ tanned, lined, but beaming _ on a subject that
some lawmakers say draws a blank look from constituents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The media and the Senate have said people don't care, but they
do care,'' Haddock said. ``This bill is what we need in this
country to get back our democracy and our republic.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Haddock began walking Jan. 1 after renting her home for a $1,000
a month to supplement her Social Security, which she said is her
only source of income. She has walked about 10 miles a day, six
days a week, across deserts and over mountains, and expects to
reach Washington by her 90th birthday in January. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Haddock said she became disillusioned with politics after the
1996 election campaign, when the amount of money given to political
parties increased dramatically from four years earlier. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fifty donors, for instance, gave $500,000 or more to the parties
that year, up from nine such donors in 1992, Feingold said. Much of
the money was used to support candidates, who were otherwise
restrained by laws that limit what they can take from individual
donors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most politicians start out with starry eyes and ideas,
and then they find it very hard to suddenly have to give their
souls to the corporations and big-interest money,'' Haddock said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Feingold, who joined Haddock for about two miles of her walk in
Tennessee last week, said the Senate has an easy task compared with
Haddock's walk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``All she is asking members of this body to do is lift their
arms to cast one vote _ a vote to ban soft money,'' Feingold told
the Senate. ``Let's join Granny D. on the road to reform.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Feingold and McCain, the road might end as it
did last year in a Senate filibuster. Although drawn more narrowly,
the bill again appears short of the 60 votes needed to break
another filibuster. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the bill won the support of Sen. Sam Brownback of
Kansas, who joined McCain and six other Republicans backing the
bill in some form. But 15 Republicans will be needed to break the
filibuster even if all 45 Democrats support the bill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brownback objected to last year's bill because it would have
prevented independent groups from running ads on political issues
in a way that indirectly promote certain candidates. Many, such as
Sen. Pat Roberts of Kansas, have argued that provision abridges
free speech. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Kit Bond and John Ashcroft of Missouri are still studying
the legislation and had no position Thursday, spokesmen said.
Debate is expected to last several days. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McCain insisted in his opening statement to the Senate on
Thursday that banning contributions to political parties does not
inhibit free speech but protects it by giving a more equal voice to
those who give small amounts, such as $100. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What this fight is all about is taking the $100,000 check out
of American politics for good,'' McCain said. ``It's about putting
the little guy back in charge and freeing our system from the
corrupting power of the special interests' bottomless wallet.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McCain's assertion drew lengthy rebuke from Sen. Mitch
McConnell, a Kentucky Republican and leading opponent of the
campaign reform movement. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say to all my colleagues, do not say `corruption' unless
you have evidence of corruption,'' McConnell said. ``It demeans the
Senate. There is no evidence, none whatsoever, of corruption.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McCain said corruption doesn't have to come in the form of a
specific, provable connection between a large donation and the way
a lawmaker votes. The corruption is the special access and perhaps
special consideration given big donors, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe these large amounts have impaired our dignity,''
McCain said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
