<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7699 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     10-15 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PORTLAND, Ore. _ The conversation finished, he hit the off button
on the cell phone, turned in his chair and smiled up at a familiar
face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, well,'' Scottie Pippen said. ``It doesn't look like
things are going too good in Houston. I mean, a team that's all new
and improved gets beat pretty bad. A team that's going to run and
have a wide-open offense can only score 88 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who knows about basketball knows where the Houston
Rockets are now. They are not a championship contender. Not by a
long, long shot, and they won't be with the personnel they have.
I'll tell you, it doesn't look good from my point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is, of course, way up here in the left corner of the U.S.
map, where the gray skies and the constant drizzle will make a good
match for his frequently gloomy moods and there is no shortage of
trees behind which he can hide.
</P>
<P>
   Less than nine months after arriving in Houston with a police
escort, the fanfare of a marching band and a five-year, $67 million
contract, Pippen does not understand why anyone would get the
impression he bailed out on the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't quit,'' he said. ``I just left. I moved on.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Titanic didn't sink. The staterooms simply filled up
with water.
</P>
<P>
   Different city. New uniform. Same old Scottie.
</P>
<P>
   He talks about providing leadership and showing his team the
way, and yet it all sounds like just a well-rehearsed speech.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere along the way, he learned what a superstar looks and
sounds like, but he evidently never grasped that there is more to
being Michael Jordan than just dressing nicely and doing TV
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   He talks about his former teammates Charles Barkley and Hakeem
Olajuwon lacking the commitment to make the Rockets contenders in
the NBA Western Conference, yet sees nothing wrong with a niggling
little detail like trying to get himself traded to the Los Angeles
Lakers so he could be reunited with his former coach Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked to go to the Lakers,'' he said. ``I don't understand
what all the fuss and the talk about disloyalty was about. I guess
none of them could understand my relationship with Phil and that it
was no reflection on the Rockets.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll look you straight in the eyes and tell you he had no
reason to be remorseful about any of his words or actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel that I owe Charles Barkley an apology,'' Pippen
said. ``Who is he to publicly say I owe anybody an apology?''
</P>
<P>
   One might ask then, Who is Olajuwon to make the same request as
Barkley?
</P>
<P>
   ``Dream said I should apologize?'' Pippen said. ``Where is it in
the law that says I have to apologize to anybody about anything
anyway?
</P>
<P>
   ``But I didn't know anything about Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. It is easier to start a World Wrestling
Federation-style war of words with one of the NBA's so-called bad
boys than to take on one of its icons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just wasn't going to work out in Houston,'' Pippen said.
``Maybe I wouldn't have gone there if it hadn't been for the
lockout and my having to make a decision in a very short time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see, I never paid attention to West Coast basketball
before. The only time I ever saw the Rockets was when we played
them twice a year and they usually kicked our butts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I expected more from Dream, more from Charles. When I
got to Houston, I found that Dream had lost some of his dominance
in the game. Charles makes adjustments, but he's not the player he
was.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing is I didn't think I could go back there and try
to carry that team again. I'm a veteran, and I can only do so much
at this point in my career, and they had me playing 40 minutes a
night. And I was the only one practicing every day. Not Dream and
Charles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought there were veterans on that team who didn't put
forth the effort. I thought they gave up. I mean, you can't beat
the Dallas Mavericks. Are you kidding me?
</P>
<P>
   ``I did what they asked me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Jordan made $30 million a year and scored 30 points a
game. Pippen made $14.5 million with the Rockets and scored 14.5
points a game.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that the superstar yardstick _ a point for every million?
</P>
<P>
   So he pulls on a new jersey and hits the floor running for the
Portland Trail Blazers. In the first quarter alone Thursday night
against Golden State, he scores seven points and dishes five
assists.
</P>
<P>
   He feeds Damon Stoudamire for a layup on a fast break, then
swipes the inbounds pass, kicks the ball out to Steve Smith and
gets a return feed in the left corner, where he nails a 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much athletic ability, so much talent in
Scottie,'' said Trail Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy. ``To me, he's
always looked like a guy that could fit in anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Where have we heard that before?
</P>
<P>
   Still, the biggest question is why Pippen chose to blow up
whatever relationship he still had with the Rockets by blasting
away at his friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd better ask Charles if we're friends,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Weren't you?
</P>
<P>
   ``Were we?''
</P>
<P>
   Didn't he cover your back after bad shooting games?
</P>
<P>
   ``Did he?''
</P>
<P>
   Didn't he defend you after the DWI arrest?
</P>
<P>
   ``Did he?''
</P>
<P>
   What happened, Scottie? What went wrong?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing,'' he said. ``I looked around, checked out my options
and asked to be traded. I'm a professional.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure. Like a pig has wings.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen doesn't understand why we can't understand.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, he just shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here now, and I'm happy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At least until things get tough.
</P>
</TEXT>
