<HEADER>
A7700 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     10-15 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW YORK _ He said it 10 times if he said it once. Eddie Perez kept
insisting he's not a good hitter. No way, he protested, can he
possibly be mistaken for a good hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a good hitter,'' Perez said over and over to the swarm
that had descended upon what used to be his rarely noticed locker
in the Atlanta clubhouse. ``You know I'm not. I'm just hot, I
guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez is hot, all right. Habanero pepper hot. He's so hot, he's
Mr. October.
</P>
<P>
   Senor October.
</P>
<P>
   Perez spent a decade in the Braves organization attempting to
win a major-league roster spot. Once there, he spent four more
seasons trying to win a starting job, which finally came in late
July when All-Star catcher Javy Lopez went down with a
season-ending knee injury. Heretofore, Eddie's lone claim to fame
was his being Greg Maddux's personal backstop.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's a hero. Now he's Ed-dee! Ed-dee! Ed-dee!
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, huh?'' he said, smiling at the minicams, enjoying
the media glow.
</P>
<P>
   Not to the Mets, it isn't. They watched Perez smack a solo home
run on Maddux's behalf in Game 1 of the National League
Championship Series. But that dinger merely gave the Braves a
little breathing room. His two-run shot off Kenny Rogers in a
decisive sixth inning of Game 2 broke a tie at 2 and secured
Atlanta's 4-3 winning margin.
</P>
<P>
   Both homers came at Turner Field, where Perez, a .249 hitter in
his first NL season with more than 200 at-bats, hadn't jacked one
all year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the funny thing,'' he said. ``I had all my home runs
(seven) on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie, trust me, the Mets are not laughing. Perez's blow over
the left-field fence was the third consecutive hit _ following a
walk _ off the worn-out Rogers and came on the first pitch, a
toothless hanging changeup. Mets manager Bobby Valentine was
covered with bruises afterward from kicking himself for not pulling
Rogers before Eddie took his mighty cut.
</P>
<P>
   Perez says he noticed Mets pitching coach Dave Wallace heading
toward the dugout steps as he approached the batter's box. Then he
saw Valentine call Wallace back _ much to Eddie's relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to face him (Rogers),'' Perez said. ``Not a fresh
arm.''
</P>
<P>
   Would Valentine have been so foolhardy had the hitter been
Reggie Jackson, the original Mr. October?
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the ballgame, not changing pitchers,'' Valentine said
glumly. ``It was the wrong decision, that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine's memory must be failing him. Apparently he had
forgotten Atlanta's three-game series against his team in June when
Perez went 6-for-11 with a double, a home run and four RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   As for the postseason, who can explain why Perez consistently
brings his heavy lumber? There's a pattern here, disputing any
notion his recent success is flukish. He was 3-for-4 in limited
duty against the Padres in last fall's NLCS, and his two hits
Wednesday _ he had singled off Rogers in the second _ left him on a
7-for-11 tear in league championship play. This after driving in
three runs with four hits against the Astros in the Division
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, do you remember his grand slam off the Cubs in the Division
Series a year ago? That secured the clinching game and helped
prepare Rod Beck, then Chicago's closer, for what Bernie Williams
did in the ALCS opener Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In 818 career major-league at-bats, Perez has homered only 24
times, a frequency rate of 3 percent. In seven at-bats against the
Mets, he has two, one fewer than the number of outs he has made.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, his infinitely more celebrated Mets counterpart, Mike
Piazza, has yet to manage any manner of hit in his seven trips to
the plate, although he did drive in a run with a groundout in the
first game.
</P>
<P>
   Perez believes pitchers are concentrating so hard on keeping the
Braves' big guns from beating them, they are inclined to take five
against him. He, in turn, is taking them to the cleaners as
Atlanta's adoring fans chant, ``Ed-dee! Ed-dee! Ed-dee!'' The Chop
House crowds have come to love the mustachioed Venezuelan, whose
disarming smile and humility add to his appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like hearing them,'' he said. ``Next year they will forget
about me because Javy will play every day. But it feels good to be
able to step up. They don't want to pitch to Chipper (Jones). They
don't want to pitch to Brian (Jordan). They want to pitch to Eddie,
so I have to take advantage and find a good pitch to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   He's finding lots of them. His bat is a magnet for horsehide;
his nerves repel pressure. He's Walter Mitty in a catcher's mask.
Reporters have begun asking Maddux about him, instead of vice
versa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a backup,'' Perez argues. ``But I have to be ready because
we don't have Javy. My main thing is catching. I try to take the
at-bats as they come. I know I'm not a good hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Enough, Eddie. Enough. You are an excellent hitter. You are
Senor October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
