<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7701 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      10-15 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
After a week of tinkering in the garage, coach Rudy Tomjanovich was
ready to take his new, souped-up model of the Rockets for a spin.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At some point, everything that can be done under the hood has
been covered. The time had come to hit the track for a test drive.
</P>
<P>
   The horsepower was there. But the first test proved more of a
tease. As fast as the Rockets were ready to go, the handling still
needed some work.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets proved Wednesday their determination to run was
designed for more than merely to irritate Scottie Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets insisted they were devoted to learning to play on
the run, literally and figuratively, because the style best fits
the talent on hand, and then went as far as one game could take
them to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Francis was handed the keys to the Rockets' new high-speed
style for the first laps of the massive roster overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   And the Rockets showed their stated intentions to be true,
running from the outset and out in front of the fleet, retooled
SuperSonics.
</P>
<P>
   But in building a 17-point first-half lead and losing it in a
13-point defeat, they also showed how much work remains to be done
heading to tonight's preseason home opener against the Cavaliers.
</P>
<P>
   There are reasons the fast break had moved rapidly toward
extinction in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing to push close to the edge. Step over that line,
and speed kills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to run,'' Tomjanovich said, ``but we want to be under
control, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very encouraged with how we played at first. The mental
part of the game in the second half was not good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Executing at high speed is something that doesn't happen
overnight. We had too many turnovers. But we had too many turnovers
when we weren't running, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets committed 25 turnovers that the Sonics converted
into 24 points despite a week's worth of missed layups in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   When the Sonics threw half-court traps and presses at the
Rockets, the Rockets rushed through the defense but lost control.
</P>
<P>
   Though Hakeem Olajuwon and Charles Barkley had said they were
ready to relinquish much of their offensive load, they were
forgotten in the Rockets' rush far more often than designed.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley and Olajuwon combined for just eight points, making four
of 13 shots, two fewer attempts than Francis put up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get the ball inside to our big guys,'' Francis
said. ``They've got to score. The running game will be there.''
</P>
<P>
   But the big guys understood. Francis might have been lured into
a duel with Gary Payton, but he is far from the first and showed an
ability to stand up to such a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   More important, he also seemed to understand he had been duped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got excited tonight,'' Francis said Wednesday. ``I
didn't even sleep today. I was ready for the game last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first three minutes, I relaxed a lot. That's the
stuff you learn when you play the first game. I'm sure Friday will
be much different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot. Hopefully, Friday I'll put two halves
together. I will put two halves together.''
</P>
<P>
   But the process did nothing to discourage his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our team is going to be fine,'' Barkley said. ``It was
a good start. Everybody is excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good mix of old guys and young guys. We've got a
nice combination. We can run the ball. We can set up in the
half-court. We're going to be pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while Wednesday, they were better than pretty good. It
didn't last, but having replaced the old, reliable sedan, it is
worth remembering sports cars can be temperamental until set up
just right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late in the game, we didn't make any plays, offensively or
defensively,'' Tomjanovich said. ``A lot of things happened that
hopefully we'll learn from.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some turnovers and unfortunate situations. We have some
good tape to show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are game-situation things. They're pressing. We have a
definite pattern on how we break (presses and traps).
</P>
<P>
   ``But the whole team played really well in the first half. It
was a good learning experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
