r f BC-HOECHST-HEADQUARTERS-     10-15 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOECHST-HEADQUARTERS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOECHST MARION MOVING HEADQUARTERS, 900 JOBS OUT OF KC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH, MARK P. COUCH and DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move that will pull 900 white-collar jobs out of Kansas
City, Hoechst Marion Roussel said Thursday that it is moving its
North American headquarters to New Jersey as part of a global
pharmaceuticals merger. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All affected employees will have the opportunity to move with
the headquarters to Bridgewater, N.J., said Gerald P. Belle,
president of Hoechst Marion Roussel North America. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the headquarters move next year, the company will retain
about 820 manufacturing and related employees in Kansas City, where
it makes the Cardizem heart drug and the Allegra allergy
medication. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always disappointing when something like this occurs,''
said Kansas City Mayor Kay Barnes. ``The good news is that the
manufacturing operation is staying here.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's news ended days of rumors about an impending Hoechst
move and followed the recent announcement that MCI WorldCom plans
to buy Sprint Corp., the area's largest private employer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City headquarters employees work in administration,
finance, marketing, human resources and other support functions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hoechst Marion spokesman Charles Rouse declined to give a
payroll figure for the 900 affected employees. Documents from the
city's Tax Increment Financing Commission put a value on some
Hoechst Marion jobs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In its 1999 annual report, the TIF Commission said jobs at
Hoechst Marion comprised an annual payroll of $73.4 million and an
average annual pay of $48,163. Those figures represent a mix of
headquarters and manufacturing jobs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the economic effect, the headquarters loss will
end part of the legacy of the late Ewing Marion Kauffman, who
established Marion Laboratories Inc. in 1950 and was known for his
philanthropy and for bringing the Royals to Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The corporate reshuffling stems from the planned merger of
Hoechst Marion's German parent, Hoechst AG, with Rhone-Poulenc SA
of France. The combination follows a series of mergers in the
pharmaceutical industry, in which companies are joining to gain
market clout and augment research dollars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new company, to be known as Aventis SA, will focus on
pharmaceuticals, crop protection and animal health. Global
headquarters will be in Strasbourg, France. The pharmaceutical arm,
to be known as Aventis Pharma, will have its global headquarters in
Frankfurt, Germany. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Belle, the head of what will be known as Aventis Pharma North
America, said at a news conference Thursday that he had recommended
keeping the North American headquarters at Hoechst Marion's
well-manicured campus in south Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   However, he also defended the move to New Jersey, where Hoechst
has significant operations. Belle said a proliferation of
pharmaceutical firms in the state had turned it into the ``seat of
power'' for the industry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an awful lot to be said about being in Kansas City.
But unfortunately, we were in a position of competing with what
some label the mystique of the pharma corridor in New Jersey,''
Belle said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The merger also is hitting Collegeville, Pa., where
Rhone-Poulenc Rorer pharmaceutical unit has had extensive
operations. All 1,650 jobs at the Collegeville site will be moved
to other cities as a result of the merger. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Belle praised the lobbying efforts of Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan
and former Kansas City mayor Emanuel Cleaver to keep the
headquarters in Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the decision did not go the way they or we would
have liked, there was in my mind absolutely nothing else that they
could have done to turn the tide,'' Belle said. ``They did a superb
job of representing Kansas City.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Area officials expressed disappointment at Thursday's news. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing this company is a far more significant blow than Sprint
combining with WorldCom,'' said Jon Baum, chairman and chief
executive of George K. Baum &AMP; Co. and incoming chairman to the
Kansas City Area Development Council. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom and Sprint executives have outlined an aggressive
growth plan that could expand the company's local presence, Baum
said. Thursday's announcement means Hoechst Marion's executive
class will disappear from Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas City has few Fortune 500 companies, so this hurts as
much psychologically as it does economically,'' said Frank Lenk,
chief economist for the Mid-America Regional Council. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You lose the top end of the jobs and that's where the really
highly paid folks work,'' Lenk said. ``You lose the folks who are
able to start new businesses, the entrepreneurial talent. Companies
tend to be oversize charitable givers in the communities where they
are based, so you lose a good corporate citizen.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   State and local leaders tried three times to sweeten the deal
offered to keep Hoechst Marion headquartered in Kansas City. The
final offer included $63 million worth of incentives _ a package
laced with sales tax exemptions, property tax abatements,
forgivable loans and job-training funds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To emphasize the state's interest, Carnahan made a
middle-of-the-night phone call to catch Hoechst Marion Chief
Executive Richard Markham 15 minutes before a board meeting in
Europe, said Phil Tate, Missouri's director of business expansion
and attraction. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Kansas City couldn't compete with the evolving
research culture based in central New Jersey. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest competitive factor we faced was the synergy of
the work force,'' Tate said. ``That was probably something that we
could never overcome.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pharmaceutical companies with major operations in the
Bridgewater area include Johnson &AMP; Johnson, Merck &AMP; Co. and
Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn. Those companies employ about 24,000 people in
New Jersey. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the company's main North American headquarters is moving
to New Jersey, Kansas City will be the site of a 20-person
industrial operations base that will oversee manufacturing here and
elsewhere in North America. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also, manufacturing in Kansas City, ] Quintiles Transnational
Corp. early this year agreed to purchase Hoechst Marion's research
and development facility, which employs about 500 former Hoechst
Marion workers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rouse said the headquarters move, expected to begin early in
2000 and take most of the year, will free up about 400,000 square
feet of office space owned by the company. The company has not
decided what to do with that space, Rouse said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
