r k BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      10-15 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO PAY TRIBUTE TO PAUL HENSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The late Paul Henson was one of those rare business leaders who
built a corporate empire, but managed to do so in a way that made
him a revered figure among peers, employees and an admiring public
alike. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A strong reminder of the reverence in which Henson is still held
was the reader reaction to a recent column extolling his role in
the ascendancy of the company that became Sprint Corp. After MCI
WorldCom made its record bid for Sprint, my thought was that
Henson's contribution had been overlooked in the excitement. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Henson, as head of United Telecommunications before it evolved
into Sprint, made the key strategic decision that vaulted his
company into the telecom industry's forefront. The nationwide
fiberoptic network initiated by Henson resulted from a courageous
vision. Those who will reap the considerable rewards of Sprint's
purchase by MCI WorldCom owe much to Henson. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps recognition of his legacy helps explain the heartfelt
responses to the Henson tribute. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked for United Telecommunications during the '80s,''
wrote an erstwhile associate now with IBM, ``and you couldn't work
for a finer man than Paul. He was not only a visionary, but also
cared about his employees. He was the only CEO I have ever
encountered who would bother to talk to his people and actually
care about what we had to say. ... (Your column) brought back great
memories of a fun and frantic time in the telecommunications
industry and a true friend and gentle man who deserves much more
credit than the media is giving him.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A particular concern of some who wrote was that Sprint hadn't
done more to honor the memory of the man who had made so much
possible for the company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was his vision that led to today's successful Sprint
Corp.,'' said a longtime employee who now runs a Leawood corporate
communications firm, ``(and) many of us had hoped that the new
Sprint campus (in Overland Park) would have been named in his
honor. It would have been the class thing to do.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it would have been a class thing to do, and it's not too
late to do it. Moreover, since Henson's overall contributions
benefited his community as much as his company, such tributes need
not be limited to whatever Sprint can do. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Naming the new corporate campus in Overland Park after Henson
merely presents the most obvious opportunity to honor the man who
made it happen. It would be just as appropriate for local civic
leaders to consider some way to honor Henson for service and
contributions that transcended his business role. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One possibility is Science City, which is due to open next month
as part of Union Station's restoration. While Science City wasn't
even a gleam in anyone's eye while Henson was building the company
that evolved into Sprint, the company has taken a leading role in
bringing the project to fruition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Henson's successor, Bill Esrey, has been a major force in
the project, it still would be a grand gesture to name Science City
for the man who first put Sprint in position to become a major
community benefactor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is just one possibility, though. Civic leaders who treasure
Henson's memory could no doubt come up with many more. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
