<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7704 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-REDSOX-ART-     10-15 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-REDSOX-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES HOLD ON TO BEAT RED SOX, 3-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Don Zimmer was speaking into his right ear, Mel
Stottlemyre into his left ear, and Yankees Manager Joe Torre said
his mind was spinning through the tense eighth and ninth innings,
his team's one-run lead in constant jeopardy, the game hinging on
his every decision.
</P>
<P>
   And Torre and the Yankees maneuvered successfully, edging the
Red Sox, 3-2, on Thursday night in Game 2 of the American League
Championship Series at Yankee Stadium. The Yankees, who tied their
own record from 1927, 1928 and 1932 with their 12th straight
post-season victory, lead the four-of-seven-game series, 2-0. The
series will resume on Saturday in Boston, where Pedro Martinez will
pitch against Roger Clemens in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   Torre hung his head afterward when asked about the eighth
inning, his posture betraying a satisfied weariness. Neither team
had led by more than a run, the outcome always in doubt. David Cone
and Ramon Martinez, the starters, had pitched brilliantly, Martinez
surrendering a home run to Tino Martinez in the bottom of the
fourth before Cone made a mistake, hanging a slider, and Nomar
Garciaparra slugged a two-run home run in the top of the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   But Martinez, who had not thrown more than 96 pitches in any
game this season, was over 100 as the seventh inning began. He
walked Ricky Ledee leading off, and Ledee moved to second on Scott
Brosius's bunt. Joe Girardi popped out. But Chuck Knoblauch pulled
a double into the left-field corner on Martinez's 120th, and last,
pitch. Ledee ran home, tying the game, and 57,180 fans roared.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gordon relieved Martinez and walked Derek Jeter, with
Knoblauch stealing third, and the Red Sox turned to Rheal Cormier,
their only left-handed reliever, to exploit O'Neill's weakness.
During the regular season, O'Neill's .190 average was the lowest in
the league against left-handers. ``You're just trying to have a
good at-bat in that situation,'' O'Neill said later, ``and put the
bat on the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   His side aching from a broken rib, O'Neill had struggled in his
first eight plate appearances in this series, his swing sickly. He
took a strike from Cormier, barely fouled another pitch. The count
was 1-2 and Cormier rammed a fastball inside; O'Neill's bat broke,
but he hit a looper over shortstop, and Knoblauch scored the
go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   But the Red Sox challenged that lead immediately. The Yankees'
Mike Stanton, who had not pitched in 12 days, entered for the top
of the eighth, and Troy O'Leary smashed a deep drive to
right-center, O'Neill slowing as he ran after the fly; it looked as
if O'Leary had tied the game.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the ball bounced off the very top of the wall _ just as
Jason Varitek's long fly ball against Cone in the second had hit
the top of the wall. O'Leary had a double, and Torre went to the
mound for a reliever, calling on Jeff Nelson. So began the moves
and counter-moves; nine different players would be inserted into
the game in the top of the eighth. ``That's the chess game,'' Torre
said later. ``That's the greatest part of managing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nelson hit Mike Stanley with a pitch on the wrist _ Stanley
left the game in agony, for the pinch-runner Damon Buford _ and
then Varitek bunted the runners to second and third. Two relievers
were warming in the Yankees' bullpen. Zimmer was speaking in
Torre's right ear, Stottlemyre in his left.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hatteberg pinch-hit for Darren Lewis. But when Nelson
threw a first-pitch ball, Torre decided to make another change.
``There was nothing clear-cut,'' he said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   He called for the left-hander Allen Watson. Boston Manager Jimy
Williams inserted Lou Merloni to bat for Hatteberg, who had seen
one pitch. ``It was fun to watch,'' Cone said. ``Two great managers
going at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching from the bench, Luis Sojo figured that at some point
Torre would call for the Yankees' closer, Mariano Rivera. But
Rivera had pitched two innings in Game 1, and Torre wanted to get
through this inning with the rest of his relievers.
</P>
<P>
   Merloni batted .184 against left-handers this year, and yet
there was Joe Girardi, the catcher, signaling for an intentional
walk. The crowd reacted anxiously, confused. The bases were loaded.
Butch Huskey, who had been in the on-deck circle, was called on to
pinch-hit for the left-handed hitting Trot Nixon, and suddenly
Torre's strategy was clear: He called on the right-handed Ramiro
Mendoza to pitch to Huskey.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza is a ground-ball pitcher, Huskey is big and slow. Torre
wanted a double play.
</P>
<P>
   But with his changeup, Mendoza fooled Huskey, striking out the
slugger, the crowd responding with cheers. Jose Offerman was next;
the count ran to 2-2, Offerman swung at a fastball and lifted a fly
to center, where Bernie Williams camped under the ball for the
inning-ending out. Mendoza pumped a fist, the Yankees' fans stood.
The crisis had passed.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox would get two hits in the ninth with two outs,
putting runners at first and third, against Rivera. But Rivera blew
a fastball past Buford to end the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
