<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7707 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-SOWARD-LADN     10-15 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SOWARD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD TO FIGURE OUT SOWARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW BAGGARLY  
 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Examinations by USC team physicians on R.Jay
Soward's head have revealed nothing abnormal.
</P>
<P>
   But then, not everything inside Soward's head can be
sufficiently seen on a CAT scan.
</P>
<P>
   Soward, who suffered a concussion during last week's loss at
Arizona, is expected to play at full speed Saturday when the
Trojans reprise their celebrated rivalry with Notre Dame at South
Bend, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   It's an opportunity for the Trojans to flog themselves into a
winning mode, and flush out the doldrums of a 3-2 start.
</P>
<P>
   For Soward, the flashy receiver from Fontana, it's one of the
few truly big games left in his college career _ and one of the
precious few chances he has to make something of his senior season,
one that is dangerously close to being labeled a bust.
</P>
<P>
   ``R.Jay is one of the most exciting and emotional players in
college football,'' Trojans coach Paul Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, there has been far more emotion than excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Soward blew off summer conditioning in favor of pickup
basketball games, he challenged Hackett's authority, he has been a
nonfactor in four of the five games he has played and he has
declined virtually all interview requests.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, Soward, who appeared on some preseason
All-America and Heisman Trophy lists, has just one receiving
touchdown in five games.
</P>
<P>
   Which begs the question: Was that checkup from the neck up long
overdue?
</P>
<P>
   Just what exactly is going on in that cranium of his?
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't say,'' Soward said, walking briskly off the USC
practice field Thursday. ``I won't tell you anything. I'm not
talking at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, R.Jay's always talking. He's the same motormouth who
starred at Fontana's Steeler Stadium. He talks on the field, the
sideline, the plane, the bus. Just not to anyone with a pen and
notepad.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I'll tell you is I'm real excited to play,'' he said. ``I
can't wait to get over there. It's Notre Dame. Doesn't get much
bigger than that.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it doesn't. Both for him and the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   Soward has seven games left in his college career _ eight if USC
makes a bowl game. That's seven or eight chances to make an impact,
seven or eight chances to show NFL scouts he is capable of
dedicating himself to a cause. Seven or eight chances to restore
his reputation as an electrifying, playmaking receiver.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Soward was supposed to be this season. He was
supposed to be the Trojans' top offensive weapon, their big-game
performer.
</P>
<P>
   In the big-game department, the Trojans are guaranteed just two
more this season. This weekend is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   And the Notre Dame game might be the last time Soward has a
national, made-for-TV spotlight in which to shine.
</P>
<P>
   If Soward is stifled on the Notre Dame Stadium turf, if he
throws his helmet in frustration or prances angrily on the
sideline, he will be one game closer to making it official.
</P>
<P>
   Soward's season will be a colossal failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't had that breakout year we expected,'' running back
Chad Morton said. ``A lot of guys like him and myself haven't had
the year we wanted. We haven't had the season we wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   The low point came last week against Arizona, when Soward was
hit while blocking on a punt return. After a helmet-to-helmet
collision, he was knocked out and lay motionless on the turf for a
few minutes while trainers tended to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked like he was crucified to the field,'' USC
quarterback Mike Van Raaphorst said. ``All sprawled out, like he
was making a snow angel.''
</P>
<P>
   Soward was escorted to the locker room, but fought his way free
at the tunnel, ran back onto the field and crashed into the Trojans
huddle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he knew what was going on,'' Van Raaphorst
said. ``We had to pull him out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought it was the beginning of the game,'' receiver
Windrell Hayes said. ``He thought he was taking the field for his
first snap.''
</P>
<P>
   Soward had to be talked off the field by trainers. His arms
flailed against them the whole way down the stairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not what USC football is about,'' linebacker Markus
Steele said. ``He overreacted a little bit. You can't go out there
and show off like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I guess with a concussion, you might not act the way you
normally do.''
</P>
<P>
   In this season, Soward might settle for a little normalcy. It
began as a spate of quiet and unproductive games, but after the
last two weeks, it has turned downright strange.
</P>
<P>
   He returned a punt for a touchdown against Oregon State two
weeks ago, but failed to catch a pass, battling an undisclosed
illness that left him nauseated and dehydrated.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the concussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what he wanted to have happen in his senior year,''
said Hackett, who insists Soward has maintained a good work ethic
this season after the two settled their differences in camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has time to change things, both for us and for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Soward practiced in a yellow jersey this week, signifying his
precautionary status. But he ran his routes well, and his energy
appeared to pick up as the week progressed.
</P>
<P>
   It's taken a few days, but after his bell was rung, Soward
insists he's cleared out the mental cobwebs.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, it will become clear whether he can clear out the
bad karma of a season gone wrong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
