<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CONE'S INVISIBLE CLIFF
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout)   (sw) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When David Cone strode to the mound at Yankee Stadium
for the first inning of Game 2 on Thursday night, he knew there was
an invisible cliff there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I relish this opportunity; I've been in this position a lot,''
he had said, alluding to having a 5-2 record in nine other
post-season starts since he joined the Yankees in 1995. ``But who
knows what's going to happen on down the line?''
</P>
<P>
   On down the line. For David Cone, that's a euphemism for the
invisible cliff. For what's going to happen when it's time for
George Steinbrenner to decide if an aging right-hander who will be
37 years old next season should be pushed over the cliff of the
Yankee payroll. If the principal owner hasn't already decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year,'' Cone said last weekend in Texas, ``I can honestly
say that this may be my last chance to pitch in the playoffs for
the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone didn't mean just his chance to pitch seven sturdy innings
in the Yankees' 3-2 victory on Thursday night in the American
League Championship Series with the Boston Red Sox, he meant
whenever the Yankees need him to pitch if they get to the World
Series for the third time in four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Pedro Martinez going for the Red Sox on Saturday,'' Cone
said later, ``we felt we needed this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone needed it, too. After a shaky second half of the season, he
surrendered seven hits, but allowed only two runs on Nomar
Garciaparra's two-run homer in the fifth inning. He struck out
nine, matching the most he has fanned in a post-season game. In
chilly, windy weather too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blew on my hand a lot,'' he said, ``but I didn't have as
many problems as I've had in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone, who was credited with the victory, stranded eight Red Sox
base runners over his seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some tough spots,'' he said. ``I had to make some big
pitches. I felt good being able to keep us in the game, keep us
close. I think the rest really helped me. I felt strong, I felt
sharp.''
</P>
<P>
   But had Cone, making his first start in 11 days, made a
statement that might help to keep him from being pushed over that
invisible cliff?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said. ``I've let that issue bother me more
than I should have. This might go a little way to help me come back
next year, but it's a little unpredictable right now.''
</P>
<P>
   If Cone is elsewhere next season, he would be a victim of what
might be called the Curse of the Perfecto.
</P>
<P>
   David Wells pitched a perfect game against the Minnesota Twins
in 1998, then was traded to the Toronto Blue Jays for Roger
Clemens. Cone pitched a perfect game against the Montreal Expos on
July 18 and now he could be in his last days as a Yankee. But he
knows why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let a big year get away from me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of Cone's perfect game, his record was a snappy 10-4
with a 2.65 earned run average. After that, he was 2-5 with a 4.28
era; in his last five starts, he was 1-2 with a 6.00 era. Over all,
he was 12-9 with a 3.44 era that was second best in the A.L. behind
Pedro Martinez, the Red Sox ace.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad, but not what it might have been with a stronger finish.
</P>
<P>
   His arm has been under the Yankee microscope ever since aneurysm
surgery in 1996. The next season tendinitis in his right elbow put
him on the disabled list. In 1998, he had a 20-7 record but needed
extensive medical treatments to get through the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The invisible cliff now in Cone's future, of course, is what
baseball free agency is all about.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Cone has earned in excess of $50 million over the last
decade with the Mets, Blue Jays, Royals, Blue Jays again and the
Yankees, suddenly he might no longer be worth the $8 million he
earned this season on his one-year contract with the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   At least Cone might no longer be worth $8 million to
Steinbrenner, who next season will need to ante up fresh millions
for Derek Jeter, Mariano Rivera, Andy Pettitte and Jorge Posada as
the Yankee payroll soars higher than this season's record $85
million.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean Cone won't be worth $8 million, if not
more, to the Mets or the Orioles next season.
</P>
<P>
   For David Cone, the Mets would be ideal: a return to the other
New York franchise for a year-round New Yorker with an Upper East
Side apartment. And it wouldn't take him any longer to get to Shea
Stadium than it has to get to Yankee Stadium for all those
post-season games he has won.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
