</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE MISTAKES MAKE FOR BIG PAINS 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ These are the Red Sox and Yankees. New history is
written each day. Controversial calls and lucky bloopers that go
against the Red Sox become instant New England folklore. Expect
nothing less between now and next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Game 2 of the Red Sox-Yankees American League Championship
Series provided another painful New York moment for Boston fans.
The Sox stranded 13 runners (an appropriate total), still led, 2-1,
in the seventh, but lost the lead on an RBI double by Chuck
Knoblauch and fell behind when Paul O'Neill scored Knoblauch with a
two-out, bloop single to center off Rheal Cormier. The Yankees won,
3-2, and bring a 2-0 Series lead to Fenway Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   If Wednesday night brought back memories of Ed Armbrister, Larry
Barnett, and the '75 World Series, then Thursday &UR;  &LR; night conjured a
flashback of Joe Morgan's ninth-inning bloop single off Jim Burton
that won the Seventh Game (Morgan and O'Neill both hit 1-and-2
pitches).
</P>
<P>
   Little things went against the Sox in both Yankee Stadium games.
Jason Varitek and Troy O'Leary each hit balls high off the wall in
right field Thursday &UR;  &LR; night. Varitek got a triple, O'Leary a
double. Neither scored. An aggregate of 12 inches on the two hits
would have resulted in a pair of solo homers.
</P>
<P>
   There was excruciating action in the top of the eighth as the
Sox loaded the bases with one out. Jimy Williams and Joe Torre
played chess (three relief pitchers, three pinch hitters and two
pinch runners _ Williams emptied his bench) and wound up with Butch
Huskey hitting against Ramiro Mendoza. Huskey struck out wildly,
then Jose Offerman flied to center.
</P>
<P>
   The ninth was almost as bad. Williams had no bullets left and
had to send overmatched Damon Buford up to face Mariano Rivera, who
hasn't allowed a run since July 21. Looking like Bob ``Beetle''
Bailey, circa '78, Buford went down swinging with two men on to end
the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox stranded eight in scoring position. In Games 1 and 2,
the Sox went 1 for 13 (.077) with runners in scoring position. Both
nights ended with Sinatra's recording of ``New York, New York''
blaring over the loudspeakers as the Sox staggered back to their
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Why do these things happen to the Red Sox? Williams's Warriors
held their ground nicely in New York, led in both games, but
dropped a pair of one-run decisions against the defending world
champs. Now they turn their lonely eyes to Pedro in hopes that he
can keep them from the threshold of a sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Game 2 played out, we could not let go of Game 1, when
umpire Rick Reed blew a call at second base in the 10th inning and
cost the Sox a chance to take the lead. Reed issued a public
apology after the 4-3 Sox loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to make a call that costs a team a ballgame,'' said
the contrite ump. ``It was my job to get it right. I didn't. You
feel bad about it. You feel awful.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the Red Sox got jobbed, just as they did in 1975 when
home plate umpire Barnett failed to call interference on Reds pinch
hitter Armbrister in the third game of the World Series. In that
episode, some of the Sox thought manager Darrell Johnson failed to
argue strongly enough. The inimitable Bill Lee said, ``If it had
been me out there, I'd have bitten Barnett's ear off. I'd have van
Gogh-ed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached at his home in Vermont Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, Lee had a
similar complaint. ``Why didn't Jimy Williams go out and argue?''
asked the Spaceman. ``All you gotta do is have him ask the other
umpires and have them reverse the decision. It drove me nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimy admitted, ``I guess I just had a brain lapse. Whatever, I
don't know. I just didn't ask.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was worse than Armbrister,'' continued the Spaceman. ``It
was flagrant. Yeah, I had flashbacks. I get 'em every time I have
to see Zimmer's face on TV. This was '75 all over with. But I think
they'll come back. This ballclub has a lot of heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Flashbacks. Good word. With the Red Sox, it's always about
flashbacks. They have now lost 10 consecutive American League
Championship Series games. Roger Clemens (Game 7, 1986 vs.
California) was the winning pitcher when the Sox won their last
ALCS game. The Yankees, meanwhile, have won 12 straight postseason
games. Clemens goes for New York Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees rubbed it in a little Thursday when they had their
pitchers take batting practice. The statement seemed to be: ``We're
going to the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's a little premature,'' said Lee. ``Not only is
it arrogant, it's not a good thing to do. That's how I hurt my
elbow in '75.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not 1975. Nor is it 1946, '67, '78, or '86. These are not
your father's Red Sox. But they have not been lucky. And they have
not been good or deep enough to beat the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   A banner hung from the upper-deck facade on the third base side
of Yankee Stadium. It read, ``Babe's Curse is Y2K Compliant.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro against the Rocket at Fenway Saturday. Rick Reed will be
the home plate umpire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
