<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARGAINS ARE STUCK IN BASEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bloomingdale's vs. Almy's.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, but that's the truth.
</P>
<P>
   The third spot in anyone's batting order is supposed to be a
glamour role. He is, in theory, your ``best'' hitter. The Yankees
have a No. 3 hitter who knocked in 110 in an off year. The Red Sox
have a 27-year-old rookie No. 3 hitter who is often completely
overmatched in this exalted level of competition.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have a veteran, battle-hardened and (reasonably)
healthy pitching rotation that features a lefthander with five
career postseason victories. The Red Sox have Pedro Martinez and an
assortment of rehabs and discards. Their starting lefthander was
jettisoned in late August by a National League team going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   You could have made a sufficiently dramatic compare-and-contrast
case to demonstrate that the Red Sox lineup had even less business
being on the field against the Indians, and at last view the
Indians were seen jumping en masse into the Cuyahoga River.
</P>
<P>
   But the hook there was pitching. For all their Central Division
dominance over the past six seasons, the Indians have never
rectified an essentially mediocre pitching situation. The defending
world champion Yankees have not had that problem.
</P>
<P>
   When the climactic moment came in Thursday night's game, Joe
Torre summoned a proven reliever named Ramiro Mendoza, who has
served his team well in a variety of situations the past several
years. With the bases loaded and one out in the eighth and New York
clinging to a precarious 3-2 lead, he bailed his team out by
striking out pinch hitter Butch Huskey and retiring the dangerous
(five hits in the first two games) Jose Offerman on a routine fly
to center.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Jimy Williams's options in a similar situation: Tom
Gordon, barely sprung from rehab; Bryce Florie, considered
expendable by the woeful Tigers; Rheal Cormier, a well-traveled
lefthander of modest skill; and Rod Beck. 'Nuff said.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomie's vs. Almy's.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox try. Oh, how they try. Jimy Williams is correct.
They most certainly do compete. But when you examine just what they
are working with, the fact that they won 94 games and managed to
defeat the Indians is one of the great baseball stories of our
time.
</P>
<P>
   That said, take out the nearest fedora from your closet and wave
it in the general direction of the noble Ramon Martinez, who gave
his team a magnificent effort in a valiant attempt to send his team
back to Fenway Park Saturday with the series tied. He has given
this team the benefit of superior class and baseball breeding since
making his debut back on Sept. 2. We already know that the team
would not have even gone this far without his spectacular
performance in Game 3 last Saturday against Cleveland. And he did
nothing to diminish his considerable reputation Thursday &UR;  &LR; night,
when he pitched 6 2/3 strong innings in the crushing Yankees
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez the Elder is not exactly pitching with the same
equipment and repertoire he had when he was doing such things as
throwing no-hitters and striking out 18 San Francisco Giants. But
the man does know how to pitch, and for six innings he was beating
the Yankees in this vital game, holding a 2-1 lead courtesy of a
two-run Nomar Garciaparra homer. His only mistake was a
fourth-inning 1-and-2 pitch that wandered into Tino Martinez's
wheelhouse and landed in the right-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   But Ramon walked leadoff man Ricky Ledee on a close 3-and-2
pitch to start off the seventh, and in a game like this such a move
was a definite faux pas. Before the inning was over, the Yankees
would push across two runs, the big blows being a two-out Chuck
Knoblauch double that produced the tying run and a two-out Paul
O'Neill soft single off Cormier that brought home the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   It was a great show, but it wasn't enough to beat David Cone,
and the very mention of that name tells you all you need to know
about the essential differences between the Bloomies and the Almys.
For David Cone, a quality, veteran pitcher, hadn't even been needed
in the Division Series against Texas. Were he a member of the
Almys, he would have started Game 2. On the Bloomies, he is now the
fourth starter. Fourth!
</P>
<P>
   Savvy baseball man that he is, Cone is blown away by the
improbability of the Almys. ``They are better than a wild card
right now,'' he maintains. ``This is not a wild-card team. Plus,
they're hot right now. Every guy on that team is putting up quality
at-bats right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the best came at the very end. With two away and nobody
on in the ninth, and with the bitter memory of a pair of would-be
homers by Jason Varitek and Troy O'Leary failing to leave the yard
by 2 and 6 inches, respectively, Garciaparra and O'Leary each got
two-strike, two-out singles in the ninth off gold-plated reliever
Mariano Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   A tease? What do you think? Rivera struck out Damon Buford to
end the game. Bloomies 3, Almys 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are an amazingly resilient team,'' lauds Cone. ``You have
to appreciate that from the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   Resilient? Oh, absolutely. The problem is their shelves are
neither as well-stocked nor as laden with quality goods as the
Bloomies'. But they do have one extraordinarily high-quality item,
and let's see what the Bloomies can do with Pedro Saturday before
we call in the liquidator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 0150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7713 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-YANKEES-HN     10-15 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-YANKEES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ Boston owned the Yankees in head-to-head meetings this
season. Come the playoffs, it has been all New York.
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the second straight night, the Yankees rallied in the
seventh inning to turn a would-be loss into another step toward
defending their World Series title.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch hit a game-tying double and scored the go-ahead
run on a single by Paul O'Neill as the Yankees defeated Boston 3-2
in Game 2 of the American League Championship Series on Thursday
night at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees hold a commanding 2-0 lead in the series, which
shifts to Boston for Game 3 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Boston heads home for the second time this postseason trailing
0-2. The Red Sox lost the first two games against Cleveland in a
Division Series before winning three in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy being 0-2,'' said Boston manager Jimy Williams.
``We understand that. Can we do it again?''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees could. New York, which won the opener Wednesday 4-3
after trailing 3-0, rubbed out Boston's 2-1 lead Thursday with with
two runs in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Ledee drew a leadoff walk off Ramon Martinez and Scott
Brosius sacrificed before Knoblauch drove in the tying run with a
double to left. After Knoblauch stole third and Derek Jeter walked,
O'Neill blooped a single to center off reliever Rheal Cormier.
</P>
<P>
   Boston had five runners on base in the final two innings but
failed to score, leaving the bases loaded in the eighth. The Red
Sox stranded 13 runners in the game and went 1-for-13 with men in
scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 12th straight postseason victory for the Yankees, who
tied their own record set in 1927, '28 and '32.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees swept the last three games of last year's ALCS
against Cleveland and four straight in the World Series against San
Diego. They were 3-0 against Texas in a Division Series last week.
</P>
<P>
   After taking eight of 12 games from the Yankees in the regular
season, the Red Sox have lost two one-run games in the ALCS. Boston
has lost 10 straight games in ALCS play.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are better than a wild card in my mind,'' Yankees starter
David Cone said of the Red Sox, who finished the regular season
four games behind New York in the AL East. ``Plus they are hot
right now. Every batter in their lineup seems to have quality
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are an amazingly resilient team.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone, pitching on 11 days' rest, held Boston to two runs and
seven hits in seven innings as he tied a postseason career high
with nine strikeouts. ``Rest has always worked to my advantage in
the past,'' said Cone, who had not pitched since Oct. 2. ``I felt
strong, felt sharp.''
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez broke a scoreless tie in the fourth with a home
run off Ramon Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   But it was less the home run and two-run seventh that beat
Boston than the Red Sox's own failings.
</P>
<P>
   Boston stranded six runners in the first four innings, and it
got worse in the late going. The Sox were 0-for-8 with runners in
scoring position until Nomar Garciaparra hit a two-out, two-run
homer off Cone in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Offerman opened the fifth with a single and stole second.
Two outs later, the Yankees decided to pitch to Garciaparra instead
of Troy O'Leary, who had struck out in his first two at-bats.
Garciaparra connected with a 1-2 slider, bashing the ball to left
field for a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was the sixth career postseason home run for Garciaparra,
including three this year.
</P>
<P>
   Boston threatened on several occasions but came up empty-handed
against Cone, who twice escaped by striking out O'Leary with two
runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox had a runner at third in the second inning after
Jason Varitek tripled off the right-field wall. But Darren Lewis
popped out and Trot Nixon flied out. In the third, Cone gave up
singles to Offerman and Garciaparra before striking out O'Leary to
end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Martinez, making his first start at Yankee Stadium, gave
up five hits through six innings.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in the seventh, the managers went to the reserves,
shuffling pitchers, batters and runners in and out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the eighth and Red Sox at second and third,
Yankees manager Joe Torre ordered an intentional walk and was able
bring on a tough righthander, Ramiro Mendoza, to pitch to Boston's
most dangerous pinch hitter, righthanded-swinging Butch Huskey.
Mendoza struck out Huskey and got Offerman to fly to center to end
the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to pitch a tougher situation than tonight,''
Torre said of Mendoza.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth, the Red Sox mounted a two-out rally when
Garciaparra and O'Leary singled off closer Mariano Rivera. Rivera
ended the game by fanning Damon Buford.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one-run games, you're in it until the final inning,''
Williams said. ``You want that opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Red Sox haven't been able to answer the knock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
