<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7714 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-MCCLAIN-COLUMN-HN     10-15 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCCLAIN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Irvin incident shows how low Philadelphia fans can go
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
HOUSTON _ It is no secret that Philadelphia has the worst sports
fans in America. They are passionate and knowledgeable, and they
can be extremely loyal, but they also can be unbelievably cruel and
obscene.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Eagles' 13-10 victory over the Cowboys, Philadelphia
fans were most infamous for booing Santa Claus, which happened at
an Eagles game in the 1960s. Now, they will be known for their
reprehensible behavior when Dallas receiver Michael Irvin suffered
a neck injury on the cement-hard surface at Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   As Irvin lay prone on the league's worst artificial surface for
20 minutes, possibly paralyzed, many of the fans cheered. When
Irvin was lifted onto a stretcher, the cheers reached a sickening
crescendo.
</P>
<P>
   When Irvin was actually placed in an ambulance, there was some
polite cheering out of respect for a player who may have suffered a
career-ending injury. But at the same time, many cheered even
louder.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone in the crowd of almost 67,000 was guilty of one of
the most despicable acts in NFL history, but it was guilt by
association.
</P>
<P>
   After Irvin's injury, the Cowboys were never the same
offensively. The Eagles pulled a stunning upset, thanks to a clutch
drive by the offense and a vastly improved defense that often gets
overlooked because the offense is so ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   Can you imagine that some of the Philadelphia fans who cheered
Irvin's injury are actually trying to take credit for helping the
Eagles pull out a victory? That's not surprising, of course.
</P>
<P>
   The Irvin injury and the crowd reaction were played over and
over on the networks. CNN took it worldwide: Philadelphia, where
the Declaration of Independence was signed, where Rocky won the
heavyweight championship of the world, where the Liberty Bell
rests, where they make the best cheesesteak sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   Those television viewers around the world who were unfamiliar
with the ways of Philadelphia fans got to see just how brutal they
can be. Rather like a European soccer crowd, actually.
</P>
<P>
   One caller to a Houston sports talk show tried to make it into a
racial situation. He said the fans reacted that way because Irvin
is black. He must not know too much about Philadelphia sports fans,
who have been known to boo the hometown players so viciously that
they have been compared to animals that eat their young.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter if the player was black or white. It could just
as easily have been quarterback Troy Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter what the fans thought about Irvin as a player
or person _ he played for the elitist Cowboys, America's Team, one
of the Eagles' most bitter rivals that was undefeated and leading
the NFC East. The Cowboys were the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Like fans at a bullfight, they wanted blood. What they could
have gotten was a paraplegic. Fortunately, Irvin is expected to
make a full recovery and might even play again.
</P>
<P>
   If Irvin does return, here's a prediction. When he's introduced
at Veterans Stadium next year, the fans will give him a positive
ovation. Why? Because even the most hard-boiled Philadelphia fan is
embarrassed by what happened.
</P>
<P>
   To their credit, the Eagles players lashed out at their fans, as
did the Cowboys, of course. They admonished the fans. Some of the
younger players were astonished at the crowd. They shouldn't have
been. Welcome to the NFL, Philadelphia style.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia-area media criticized the fans at the game. The
newspapers scolded the fans. No one tried to defend them because
there is no defense for such a disgusting reaction by a stadium
full of degenerates.
</P>
<P>
   If it had happened in almost any city except Philadelphia or New
York, it might not have received so much publicity. Fans in those
cities are easy targets because of their history. They have a
well-founded tradition of reacting in a way that brings
embarrassment to their cities.
</P>
<P>
   Injured players have been cheered and booed in other cities.
Denver, which is supposed to have the best fans in the NFL, was
humiliated two weeks ago. After the two-time defending Super
Bowl-champion Broncos suffered another frustrating loss at Mile
High Stadium, cornerback Dale Carter was leaving the field when a
battery thrown from the stands hit him in the eye and could have
caused serious damage.
</P>
<P>
   But because this was Philadelphia, the incident warranted more
stories in newspapers and more minutes on television. It was as if
the Irvin injury added a notch in Philly's gun and enhanced its
reputation of having the nastiest fans in the country. What a
deplorable reputation to have.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the wretched display at Veterans Stadium,
media around the country attacked Philadelphia. Some outlets tried
to analyze the fans to find out what makes them the meanest and
nastiest in the country. Reporters did stories on the history of
the city's professional sports teams, especially the failures that
left fans angry and devastated.
</P>
<P>
   Even politicians weighed in with their opinions, including
Philadelphia mayor Edward Rendell, who said, ``This, in terms of
bad taste, was as bad as it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia actually seemed embarrassed. It should have been.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia fans have a long tradition of viciousness. Because
of the backlash caused by the Irvin injury, it will be interesting
to see if it affects how the fans respond the next time something
like that happens, whether to an opponent or a home player.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be at an Eagles game. It could be at a Phillies,
76ers or Flyers game. At some point, though, an opposing player
will be injured. He may be knocked unconscious. Blood could be
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   How will the Philadelphia fans react? Will it be with polite
applause for a fallen star? Or will it be with derisive cheering,
as they did with Irvin?
</P>
<P>
   You never know. Philly fans may wear it like a medal of dishonor
and actually go to new heights to prove they earned their title as
the worst in professional sports. If that happens, seldom will you
find a reputation that's more deserved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
