<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMON MARTINEZ VALIANT IN DEFEAT 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-MARTINEZ-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He was the X-factor, the man who just might have
dealt the first body blow to the Yankees. When pennant fantasists
were plotting out the the American League Championship Series, they
circled Game 2 in Yankee Stadium with Ramon Martinez on the hill
against David Cone as the point where things might turn in Boston's
favor.
</P>
<P>
   For the better part of Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, it seemed they had.
Martinez pitched superbly, shrugging off a solo homer by Tino
Martinez in the fourth to take the Sox into the seventh inning with
a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he pitched a tremendous game,'' said Sox manager
Jimy Williams. ``Kept us in that game. The starter sets the tone,
we always say. Certainly, he did more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who had started only four games during the regular
season after rehabbing from shoulder surgery, pitched one out short
of seven innings. He threw 120 pitches, gave up three runs on six
hits, and struck out five. Had his mates done anything with men on
base, that would have been more than enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yankees are one of the greatest teams,'' Martinez said.
``That is the reason why they are here. I know I am going to have a
tough game. I did the best that I could.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the wrenching irony Thursday &UR;  &LR; night. The Sox got
exactly the pitching performance from Pedro's big brother that they
craved. Then they fed him starvation rations. ``We have our
chances,'' shrugged Martinez. ``We got our men in scoring position,
but we can't come up with the base hit we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Inning after inning, Martinez kept Boston in the ballgame. He
kept the world champions scoreless through three. And when Tino
Martinez took him four rows into the right-field seats, he simply
bore down and got tougher, striking out the next three batters.
</P>
<P>
   He kept the Yankees at bay until the seventh, when he lost
leadoff man Ricky Ledee on a full-count walk and watched Scott
Brosius bunt him to second.
</P>
<P>
   Up came Chuck Knoblauch, after Martinez got Joe Girardi to pop
up. Martinez threw Knoblauch a changeup, and he sent it bouncing to
the left-field fence. Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan went to the
phone, and in came Tom Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   The pitch count pretty much ruled out Martinez going any longer.
``If he wasn't coming off surgery, maybe the decision would have
been to leave him in one more inning,'' said Kerrigan. ``But 120
pitches is 20 more than he's thrown in any start this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Martinez was feeling it. ``I can go farther than
that,'' he said. ``I feel fine when I come out. I was just normal.
I didn't feel any kind of pain or tired or anything. I didn't want
to come out, but I had to.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a sixth game in this series, Martinez will be back
here to pitch it. ``I just don't want to hurt the kid,'' said
Williams. ``I thought he had done his job, and it was time to make
a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez stayed in the dugout and watched Paul O'Neill, whom
he'd held hitless, single off reliever Rheal Cormier to put the
Yankees ahead. He stayed there through the ninth, hoping that Damon
Buford could find magic with one swing.
</P>
<P>
   Then he went into the clubhouse, strapped an iceberg to his
shoulder, and picked at a wee-hours plate. ``It was a good game,''
Ramon Martinez concluded, ``an exciting game.'' It was everything
the pennant fantasists wanted _ for 120 pitches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
