<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE'S VICTORY ALL ABOUT HEART AND PERSEVERANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mamma, don't let your babies grow up to be Coneheads.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, why not?
</P>
<P>
   Why not grow a plastic cylinder or a neon orange police pylon
out of the top of your cranium and go absolutely nuts.
</P>
<P>
   That's what they did at Yankee Stadium Thursday night, when
David Cone took the mound and staved off the Red Sox, earning the
3-2 win with a gutsy seven-inning, nine-strikeout performance in
which only one man hurt him _ unless you're counting the Yankee
bullpen, which was gutted in a (finally) successful effort to close
out Cone's win.
</P>
<P>
   His one bad moment came in the fifth inning. Nomar Garciaparra
stood in against Cone and tagged a two-run homer into the
left-field seats to put the Sox ahead, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Cone who struck last. With John Valentin on second,
Cone snuffed Garciaparra in the seventh with a strikeout to end the
inning. The big ``K'' sent Cone to the dugout to watch his
teammates mount a two-run rally in the bottom of the inning, as if
on cue to take care of Coney and secure his first postseason win
this October.
</P>
<P>
   He had his fastball working. His slider and forkball, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just relaxed. I know I had to be poised and under
control because the Red Sox are a hot team. I thought it was going
to be a 1-0 game; that's why I was so mad when I gave up the homer
to Nomar,'' Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   But he did enough to hold the Sox in check, and while he was at
it, maybe Cone staved off those voices all over Gotham that are
whispering about how Cone's days as a Yankee may be growing too few
and too precious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't handled the frustration well at all,'' Cone said
about the second-half slump. ``I let a lot of little things bother
me.''
</P>
<P>
   In the big picture, the 36-year-old right-hander knows this
American League Championship Series is about history, about
rivalry, about the Curse of the Bambino. Cone knows his role is
subordinate, supporting.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there's an ad they play at Yankee Stadium that shows a
bunch of Yankees out at a nightclub. Everyone is dancing this high
leg-kick dance that mimicks the delivery of Yankees starter Orlando
Hernandez, since El Duque is all the rage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called the El Duque,'' a woman tells Cone.
</P>
<P>
   That's when infielder Luis Sojo looks over at Cone. ``Hey,
Coney. Why don't you have a dance named after you?'' Sojo taunts.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, Cone is not the king of the Yankees anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Today in Boston, they'll hold a press conference for Pedro
Martinez and Roger Clemens. The Red Sox ace and the former Red Sox
ace will square off in Game 3 Saturday at Fenway Park. That is the
marquee matchup of this American League Division Series. That is
the heart of this thing, not Cone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's going to be the best matchup in baseball
postseason play in the last 15 years,'' Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday night, Cone proved he is still one of the biggest
gamers in the game. He is still a warrior. He is all about heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a big game because we did not want to go into Boston
and give Pedro the chance to put them ahead in this series,'' Cone
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cone, with the Cy Young and a World Series ring from Toronto and
two more with the Yankees, is not the ace. He is not the same
starter and sometimes stopper whom former Yankee manager Buck
Showalter threw against the Mariners to try and close Game 5 of the
1995 Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   He is not quite the same pitcher whom Joe Torre turned to in
Game 3 of the 1996 World Series. With the Yankees down 0-2 to
Atlanta, Cone turned that series around.
</P>
<P>
   This past July, after throwing a perfect game against the Expos,
Cone finished the second half of the season plagued by
inconsistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to be out there. Everyone wants to be the go-to
guy,'' catcher Joe Girardi said. ``David is no different, but he
knew that at some point, we were going to need him and he had good
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   It's funny how it was Cone who was most shocked the day David
Wells was traded to Toronto for Roger Clemens this past spring.
Cone spent the day at Wells' place in Florida. He was the one who
spoke for Wells, told reporters how upset Wells was about the
trade, about how it hurt for Wells not to be a Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe, just like Wells, Cone could see that being a Yankee,
being on top of the world in the city that thinks it is the center
of the universe, is not a luxury that can last forever.
</P>
<P>
   David Cone took the mound Thursday night, relishing the moment.
He knows this might be his last time around with the world champs,
in a city he has come to claim as his own. He knows this postseason
is not all about him.
</P>
<P>
   But by churning out more important wins for a team and city he
thrives in, he continues to make himself hard to forget.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
