<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7717 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-CONE-BOS &LR;      10-15 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-CONE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE FIGURED OUT ALL THE ANGLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE FAINARU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Cone threw 88 pitches in his perfect game
against the Montreal Expos earlier this season. His 88th pitch came
in the fifth inning Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, and Nomar Garciaparra belted
it 20 rows beyond the left-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   But Garciaparra's two-run homer was the only real blemish of
Cone's postseason debut in 1999. The Red Sox had seven hits against
him in seven innings, and the homer was one of just two hits in 16
at-bats with runners on base. He struck out nine, including
Garciaparra, the last batter he faced, on his 128th pitch of the
night.
</P>
<P>
   Cone left with the Yankees trailing, 2-1, but New York scored
two runs in the seventh, earning him credit for the Bombers' 3-2
victory over the Sox in Game 2 of the American League Championship
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love looking up and seeing him out there,'' said manager Joe
Torre. ``He's such a good influence on this pitching staff and this
clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   At this stage of his career, Cone is something of an
illusionist. At 36, he was the second-oldest pitcher to hurl a
perfect game after Cy Young, who was 37 when he beat Philadelphia
in 1904. Torre said repeatedly that he had no idea what to expect
Thursday &UR;  &LR; night out of the righthander, who had seemed to tire in
the second half, winning just three games after his perfecto July
18.
</P>
<P>
   Cone did not pitch at all in the Yankees' Division Series sweep
of the Rangers, a factor that may have helped Thursday &UR;  &LR; night. He
has been significantly better with additional rest this season.
Torre made him the No. 2 starter for the ALCS, a move that will
ensure that he pitches in Game 6 should the series return to Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good all night, really. The extra rest really helped
me. I could have gone out for the eighth, which is exactly what I
told Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone emptied the pantry against the Sox Thursday &UR;  &LR; night,
throwing from multiple arm angles and changing his rhythm
constantly to keep the Sox off balance as they threatened him
repeatedly in the first four innings. He even used a hesitation
pitch, halting in the middle of his windup before delivering the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox had numerous opportunities against Cone in the first
four innings but squandered all of them:
</P>
<P>
   --In the first, Cone walked John Valentin and Garciaparra, then
struck out Troy O'Leary to get out of the jam.
</P>
<P>
   --In the second, Jason Varitek hit a one-out triple off the very
top of the right-field wall. Cone then retired Darren Lewis and
Trot Nixon on harmless flies.
</P>
<P>
   --In the third, Jose Offerman led off with a single, but Cone
got the next two outs and fanned O'Leary after Garciaparra kept the
rally alive with a ground-ball single.
</P>
<P>
   --In the fourth, Varitek hit a one-out double, but Cone fanned
Lewis and got Nixon on a fly ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like every inning there was a runner on base,'' said
Cone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coney has thrown big game after big game for us,'' said Paul
O'Neill. ``He hasn't pitched in two weeks or something; a lot of
people don't understand how difficult it is to come into a
situation like this and throw the way he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre said Cone is the most difficult pitcher to catch, more
difficult than Orlando Hernandez because he throws the ball from so
many angles. Garciaparra tagged him on one of his hesitation
pitches. Cone had two strikes on the shortstop, but Garciaparra dug
out what appeared to be a low off-speed pitch and buried it deep in
the seats beyond the left-field foul pole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually was trying to waste the pitch,'' Cone said. ``It
was a sidearm slider. I was already thinking what the next pitch
was going to be, and the next thing I knew, it was out of the park.
It was probably the only slider I threw all night that didn't
really break, and he's going to hit that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
