<HEADLINE>
MUSCLE STRAIN SLOWS GARCES 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-GARCES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Rich Garces returned to the dugout at the end of
the sixth inning in Game 1, the reliever had bad news for pitching
coach Joe Kerrigan.
</P>
<P>
   A muscle strain located on his right side had tightened. At
first, Garces confided to fellow pitcher Bret Saberhagen he had
nothing left and his arm hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan walked over to Garces and asked how he felt. The
reliever told his coach, ``It's hurt. It's sore.'' Then Kerrigan
asked the most important question: ``Can you go back out there?''
Garces repeated that he felt sore.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen sensed the reliever would do more harm than good
taking the mound in the seventh and told Kerrigan to get Garces out
of the game. And as a result of the three-way conversation, Derek
Lowe worked the seventh, eighth, and part of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you're hurt in the postseason, you don't want to be
hurt,'' said Garces, who threw two no-hit innings against New York.
``You want to go out there and do the best you can, and that's what
I did.''
</P>
<P>
   In a perfect and predictable pitching world, Lowe would have
filled the role of closer Wednesday night, guiding the Red Sox
through, at most, the last six outs. But nothing about the Boston
bullpen is perfect or predictable. The seven relievers designated
to play in the American League Championship Series are an odd
assemblage. And between past surgeries, long-term injuries,
ill-timed muscle strains, and votes of no confidence, the strength
of the bullpen has been depleted, and it cannot be managed as Jimy
Williams or Kerrigan might like.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a traditional team,'' said Lowe. ``Our games are
probably going to be spread out between three or four pitchers.
That's just the way we've been doing it all year, and I don't think
things will change.''
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1, circumstances dictated when Lowe would play. The
start of the series revealed the coaching staff had no confidence
in righthanded pitchers Bryce Florie, Tom Gordon, or Tim Wakefield.
The knuckleballer was left off the championship series roster,
while both Florie and Gordon warmed up for late-inning action but
were not used. When asked if Flash would be used late, Kerrigan
said, ``only if we're forced to.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was in fact used in the seventh in Thursday &UR;  &LR; night's 3-2
loss in Game 2. He was brought in with two outs in a 2-2 game to
face Derek Jeter with a runner on third (he walked him). That's a
spot in which Williams might have used Garces.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox have become so dependent on Lowe that Kerrigan did
not rule out the young righthander for Game 2. He didn't have to.
</P>
<P>
   Said Kerrigan, ``(Garces) tightened up a little bit after his
second inning Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, to a point where he probably could
pitch if it was a sixth or seventh deciding game. But since it was
the first game of the series, we thought it was smart to take him
out so we'd have him available for the rest of the series.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 0220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
