<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7721 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-EIGHTHINNI     10-15 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EIGHTH INNING LEAVES RED SOX OUT OF PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-EIGHTH INNING-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The utter frustration of that top half of the eighth
inning, so foreign to the American League with four moves by the
Yankees' Joe Torre and five by the Red Sox' Jimy Williams, was
verbalized by the Red Sox' Troy O'Leary.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few moments earlier, the Yankees' Paul O'Neill had broken
his bat ``on a real good pitch by Frenchy (Rheal Cormier)'' and
O'Neill's single had fallen in front of O'Leary in left field,
scoring the lead run.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary was asked to put all this together, how O'Neill's
broken-bat hump-backer would win a game in light of what O'Leary
himself would do only moments later, drive a ball as far as he
could without hitting a home run, and then stand helplessly on
third base for what seemed eons, unable to travel the final 90
feet. The words came. That Paul O'Neill is a good hitter ``who
fought off a good pitch from Frenchy'' and ``it happened to fall
where there was nobody.'' But what of the top of the eighth inning,
when Torre had made the same mistake that American League managers
have made the last few months _ go by the book and bring in a lefty
(Mike Stanton) to pitch to O'Leary? O'Leary has pasted, pulverized,
and pounded lefthanded pitchers this season, book or no book.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary swung, and the ball moved high and far toward right
center. ``I hit it good,'' said O'Leary. ``I thought it might go
out.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary's blast was hit exponentially harder than O'Neill's but
landed _ oh, when will Red Sox fans finally decide exactly whether
it was two inches or three from the top of the wall in right
center? _ in the very small distance above the ``5'' in the ``385''
sign and then dropped to the warning track. O'Leary pulled up at
second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit the wall, just like (Jason) Varitek hit the wall,''
said O'Leary, the life almost gone from his words. ``We just had to
settle for a double.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary was asked how he could reconcile this, that O'Neill and
the Yankees could win with a hump-backer and the Red Sox could lose
despite a blast. No one has ever answered this in baseball, and no
one ever will, and O'Leary's answer, even if it was a cliche,
summed it all up. ``That's the way baseball is sometimes. That's
how it goes sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   The painful inning went on. Mike Stanley was hit by a pitch from
Jeff Nelson, Torre's second pitcher. Varitek laid down a sacrifice
bunt, advancing O'Leary and pinch runner Damon Buford. Williams
sent up Scott Hatteberg, but after one ball from Nelson, Torre went
to lefty Allen Watson to face the lefty Hatteberg. Williams
countered with righthanded-hitting Lou Merloni.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I was looking forward to that; I wanted to hit so badly,''
said Merloni, the Framingham, Mass. youngster who has lived through
so much Red Sox pain. ``And when they (intentionally) put me on, I
was disappointed. I wanted to hit in that situation. It's a
situation you dream of _ one-run game, guys on second and third.''
</P>
<P>
   With Trot Nixon due up, both managers made their moves. Nixon
said he somewhat ``expected to be hit for since I don't face
lefties that much,'' and ``I haven't faced Watson much.'' Williams
sent up Butch Huskey, the power-swinging all-or-nothing hitter.
Torre countered with Ramiro Mendoza.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the opportunity I wanted,'' said Huskey. ``I had the
best opportunity of anybody to do something. I had a great
opportunity to be succssful in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   And Huskey did the least.
</P>
<P>
   He was looking for breaking balls from Mendoza, ``but he didn't
throw me any breaking balls,'' Huskey said. ``He threw me two
changeups and two sinkers. I wasn't looking for any changeups
because he doesn't pitch that way. And the first pitch, I just
pulled it foul.''
</P>
<P>
   And the last pitch? With two strikes on him, ``I was looking for
anything to put in play. He threw me a changeup.'' And Huskey
struck out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll get him next time,'' said Huskey, new to the Red Sox, new
to Boston, where such words come across with such dread.
</P>
<P>
   The last batter was Jose Offerman, who was virtually certain not
to strike out no matter what Mendoza threw at him. Offerman worked
the count to 2-and-2, and ``I had a good swing at his pitch. It was
a pitch a little bit away, and I had a good swing at it and I hit
the ball pretty good'' _ to Bernie Williams in medium-deep center
field. ``It was just bad luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Of which the Red Sox have had more than their share in the two
games in New York. And more than their share this century against
New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
