<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALL TO ARMS ANSWERED 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-NINTH INNING-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Yankee manager Joe Torre's sleight-of-hand tactics
weren't as diverse in the ninth inning Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, but they
were no less compelling than his moves in the eighth, when the
Bombers' skipper opened the bullpen door and kept a steady stream
of pinstriped relievers marching to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the chess game,'' said Torre, who clearly has more good
and reliable options in his bullpen than Sox skipper Jimy Williams
has in his. ``You have to empty your bullpen and go for it. The
greatest part about managing is to be able to go back and forth
with the other manager.''
</P>
<P>
   After going with no fewer than four relievers in the eighth
inning, his one-run lead looking thinner by the pitch, Torre called
for his top closer, Mariano Rivera, to seal it the ninth. Quickly,
effortlessy, Mariano dispatched John Valentin on a roller in front
of the plate and Brian Daubach with a fly to left.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera has been nothing less than phenomenal this season. He
came into the playoffs without allowing a run in his final 28
appearances of the regular season. He escaped the ninth unscathed
again Thursday &UR;  &LR; night and now has made 32 consecutive trips out of
the 'pen without getting touched for a run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any way we can win, we do it,'' said righthander Jeff Nelson,
who was the second arm out of the bullpen, following Mike Stanton
in the eighth. ``That's what you have to do _ you have to go with
the matchups.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera, perhaps the game's most dominant closer, had to work a
little more than usual for his third save of the postseason. After
getting the first two outs, he was touched for back-to-back singles
by Nomar Garciaparra and Troy O'Leary. Garciaparra at third base
soon would become the eighth Boston runner stranded in scoring
position.
</P>
<P>
   But before the inning ended, Torre made an emergency trip to the
mound. Rivera still had to get by Damon Buford to end the game. The
little-used Buford was at the plate, in part, because Mike Stanley
was hit by a pitch in the eighth and had to leave for X-rays.
Rivera reached back and made Buford his fifth strikeout victim in
six innings of postseason relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been automatic for us,'' said an admiring Derek Jeter,
the Yankee second baseman. ``I mean, it's been ridiculous. Hey, you
know, (Ramiro) Mendoza and Rivera _ the Panamanian connection.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, Torre used four relievers in the eighth, including
Mendoza, then pleaded the fifth with Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was about it,'' noted Nelson, who kidded how some of the
relievers hadn't worked in nearly three weeks because he and Rivera
have handled most of the load of late. ``Hideki Irabu was the only
guy left out there.''
</P>
<P>
   While Torre kept his saints marching in, Williams rolled out
only two after starter Ramon Martinez worked into the seventh.
First came Tom Gordon, whose year has been impaired by injury; then
it was Rheal Cormier, the little lefthander who has been a key in
Williams's constant cobbling of the bullpen this season. The
Yankees are much deeper than the Sox _ a large factor in Vegas
making them a 3-to-1 favorite in this series _ and the lopsided
difference may be greatest of all when it comes time to call arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are spinning,'' said Torre, asked what it was like to
be wheeling and dealing with his pitchers, especially in the
eighth-inning chorus-line march. ``I'm in there talking to Zim (Don
Zimmer), and I'm talking to Mel (Stottlemyre) . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``It's do or die. It's right now. There's no thinking, `Oh,
we'll get 'em later on.' It's such an exciting time of the year,
and our players have responded to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
