<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 02:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7723 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-YANKEES-BO     10-15 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSING OPPORTUNITIES SINK RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-YANKEES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the Red Sox lost the first two games of their
Division Series with the Cleveland Indians, Nomar Garciaparra put
on his best poker face and said the Sox had them just where they
wanted 'em.
</P>
<P>
   What, then, to make of the plight of the New York Yankees? The
Bombers will arrive at Fenway Park for Game 3 of their American
League Championship Series Saturday afternoon with the same
advantage the Indians had after coming from behind for the second
straight night to beat the Sox, this time 3-2 on a tie-breaking
single by sore-ribbed Paul O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   History falls heavily in favor of the Yankees, who tied a record
held by three of their illustrious predecessors with their 12th
straight win in postseason play, putting them two wins away from
returning to the World Series for the third time in the last four
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am tired,'' said O'Neill, who hit a flare over Garciaparra's
head off lefthanded reliever Rheal Cormier to score Chuck
Knoblauch, who had doubled home the tying run off Sox starter Ramon
Martinez. ``Everybody is. We are exhausted. One-run games, they are
pretty gut-wrenching, but I feel great. It was a great game. Both
games could have gone either way.''
</P>
<P>
   Little besides blind faith appears to favor the sons of Jimy
Williams. Not after the Sox took a lead into the seventh inning for
the second straight night and lost it. Troy O'Leary and Jason
Varitek missed home runs by mere inches, the Sox are 1 for 13 with
runners in scoring position in two games, and they may have lost
first baseman Mike Stanley, who was hit in the right wrist by a
pitch from Jeff Nelson in the eighth inning (X-rays were negative).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never easy down 0-2,'' Williams said. ``All we can do is
play one game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we did go through it already, in very recent days. Maybe
the way the game ended, the way we had a shot in the eighth and it
didn't work, can we do it again?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you all come to Boston. They have good restaurants
there, it is a nice city, it really is. But we are going, we will
be there to play to say the least.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, who left 13 runners on base, gave it one last shot in
the ninth on two-out singles by Garciaparra and O'Leary. But an
overmatched Damon Buford, who entered the game as a pinch runner
for Stanley in an eighth inning in which Williams emptied his
bench, went down swinging against Mariano Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees closer hasn't allowed a run since July 21, a span of
32 appearances, including four in the postseason. The Sox bullpen,
meanwhile, couldn't protect the 2-1 lead Garciaparra had given the
gallant Ramon Martinez with a two-run home run off Yankees starter
David Cone, who matched a personal postseason best by striking out
nine in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't hope for more than to be in that situation,''
Buford said. ``He (Rivera) just won the battle.''
</P>
<P>
   With a healthier bullpen, Williams probably would have excused
Martinez for the night after he walked leadoff man Ricky Ledee to
open the seventh. Martinez already had thrown 105 pitches entering
the inning, and while he was still hitting 90 miles per hour on the
radar gun, he had not been pushed to such extremes since before his
surgery, 15 months previously.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams elected to stick with the elegant righthander.
Scott Brosius bunted Ledee to second, but Joe Girardi popped out,
leaving Martinez one out away from finishing his night's labors
with a lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Knoblauch rifled a 1-1 pitch into the left-field corner,
scoring Ledee with the tying run. With Derek Jeter the next hitter,
Williams came for Martinez, who delayed his departure until
reliever Tom Gordon was almost to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to come out in that situation,'' Martinez said.
``I had to come out. I could have gone farther.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon had warmed up in Game 1 but was not used. Before the
game, pitching coach Joe Kerrigan, asked if he would use Gordon in
a close game late, said: ``We might be forced to. If the situation
dictates it, yeah, we'll use him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon lasted one batter. Missing high with his fastball, Gordon
walked Jeter, bouncing a 3-and-2 curveball that Varitek did a nice
job of blocking to keep Knoblauch at third, where he'd advanced
with a stolen base without drawing a throw.
</P>
<P>
   Williams then summoned Cormier to face O'Neill in a reprise of
their ninth-inning encounter in Game 1. Cormier won that one,
inducing O'Neill to tap back to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Cormier jumped ahead of O'Neill Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, too, putting
the Yankees' right-fielder in a 1-and-2 hole, but O'Neill, despite
being jammed, flared the next pitch over Garciaparra's head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would throw the same pitch in the same spot,'' Cormier said.
``Unfortunately, the ball went behind the shortstop where nobody
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams emptied his entire bench in the span of four batters in
the eighth inning, using three pinch hitters and two pinch runners.
Yankees manager Joe Torre countered with four pitchers. The outcome
of all the maneuvers? With the bases full of Sox, Yankees reliever
Ramiro Mendoza struck out pinch hitter Butch Huskey and retired
Jose Offerman on a gentle fly to center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Ramiro Mendoza, there is no question,'' Torre said.
``He has done so many good things. He's not going to pitch in a
tougher situation than he did tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Yankees' 12 straight matches the record set by the
'26, '27, and '32 Bombers, the Sox were unable to end their own
streak of 10 straight losses in American League Championship Series
play.
</P>
<P>
   It was of little comfort to the Sox, of course, that umpire Rick
Reed admitted blowing a 10th-inning call that short-circuited a
potential Sox rally in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he accepted the responsibility, then he did,'' manager Jimy
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Sox must return home again, down 2 games to none,
then they will.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's right where we want 'em,'' said reliever
Derek Lowe, who would have been called upon to close if the Sox
could have held serve. ``But we're playing good.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were getting overmatched, it would be different, but
we're not. These games could have gone either way. This series
could be flip-flopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to go back and play the same way. It's very
important we don't change the way we're playing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
