<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILT WAS NO GENTLE GIANT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  Wilt Chamberlain was a test for a sportswriter. If you could
experience his mix of bombast, opinion and over-the-top joie de
vivre and not walk away smiling, it was time to turn in the old
press shield and explore that career in bartending.
<P>
   You didn't interview Wilt, he interviewed you. And did he ever
speak in anything but full-volume thunder? You'd have to ask one of
his 20,000 dates.
</P>
<P>
   ``L-l-let me ask you this, my man,'' he would say with his
authoritative stutter. ``How often do you think B-b-bill Russell
guarded me straight-up, without the help of at least two other
guys?''
</P>
<P>
   I became a Wilt Chamberlain fan at age 8 when I saw him play for
the Harlem Globetrotters, and I remained an unabashed Wilt fan
until the day he died.
</P>
<P>
   The great sports debate was always: Who's better _ Wilt or
Russell?
</P>
<P>
   L-l-let me tell you this: Wilt waxed Russell's butt up one side
and down the other.
</P>
<P>
   And Wilt waxed life's butt. At 60, he told me he was taking up
mountain biking. Great way to meet girls. And to scare mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Wilt would hop in his car on a whim and drive cross-country,
trying to break his own record, stopping only to autograph speeding
tickets. He claimed to be a gourmet cook. He wrote two books with
no ghostwriter. He designed his own cathedral-like mansion. He
traveled the world, lived on a mountaintop in L.A. and on a beach
in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   One day he told me he was designing and producing his own
limited-edition, high-performance car.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wiltmobile!'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No!'' he frowned. ``The Chamberlain.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he mentioned he was considering marriage, what did I think?
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it,'' I said, ``but I don't think it's for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilt settling down would have been like the Titanic settling
down.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the girls. The stories were true. Wilt took care of 20,000
babes, all right. More.
</P>
<P>
   He made it possible for at least that many women to participate
in high-level athletics. Wilt had six sisters, and he hated that
they had no opportunity to play sports. When he traveled to Russia
with the Globetrotters he was amazed at the athletic programs for
females, and he vowed to make that happen here.
</P>
<P>
   And he did. He organized, bankrolled, encouraged and sometimes
coached top amateur track, volleyball and basketball teams, and
promoted road races and marathons. In that sense, he really was
God's gift to women.
</P>
<P>
   And to the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   ASK FOR IT at your newsstand by its new name: ``SUCKcess.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Keating notes that ``Success'' magazine has filed for
Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   Next month's cover story: ``Are we all too hung up on this
material wealth stuff?''
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO can't seem to do anything to slow down the drug
pushers. The shopping-cart pushers, that's another story. We got
'em sweating.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Willie Brown says he never intended to send his cops out
to snatch back the shopping carts used by homeless folks. But that
was  &UR; somebody's  &LR; plan, somebody high-high up in city authority.
</P>
<P>
   Memo to whoever issued that order: Please introduce yourself to
the mayor ASAP.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRALIA'S VERSION of surf 'n' turf? Michael Thurston, a San
Francisco-based salesman, found it on the menu in Sydney _
crocodile and kangaroo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bring me the reptile 'n' rodent,'' Thurston told his waiter.
</P>
<P>
   Thurston's review: ``Wasn't very expensive. Wasn't very good,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Waiter, bring me the suitcase 'n' pouch. Or is it the &LR; 
 &UR; swamp 'n' stomp? Ah, make it a braised bandicoot, and hold the &LR; 
 &UR; young'un.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HONEST, THE ABE LINCOLN knew what it was doing when it steamed
under the Golden Gate Bridge last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The massive aircraft carrier almost skimmed the underside of the
bridge. My inside source said it was pure luck, that nobody had
bothered to calculate the clearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did in fact calculate the air draft clearance,'' says
Captain Bruce Horton, the harbor pilot who guided the Abe into the
Bay, ``and when I got to the bridge of the ship, the captain had
also figured it out. To be exact, we had 27.9 feet of clearance. So
much for pure chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Great, Cap'n Horton, but doesn't all that mathematical
rigamarole take all the spontaneous fun out of boating?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 0314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 03:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7726 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-TESTBAN-CLINTON-SFCHR     10-15 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTBAN-CLINTON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CLINTON ASSAILS GOP FOR KILLING ARMS TREATY  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton delivered a defiant rebuttal
Thursday to the Senate's rejection of the nuclear test ban treaty,
warning that the Republicans' ``reckless partisanship'' poses a
threat to America's national security as well as to its economic
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   During a combative, hourlong news conference, Clinton repeatedly
attacked his Republican opponents in Congress for embracing what he
called a ``new isolationism'' demonstrated by their refusal to
embrace the arms treaty, pay U.N. dues or fully fund his budget for
foreign operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are saying we don't need our friends or allies,'' Clinton
said from the East Room of the White House. ``They are betting our
children's future on the reckless proposition that we can go it
alone _ that at the height of our prosperity, we should bury our
heads in the sand behind a wall.''
</P>
<P>
   The strong words came a day after the Senate voted 51 to 48 to
reject a treaty that the president had called a top priority of his
second term. A two-thirds majority would have been needed for
passage. In his opening statement, and in the course of numerous
questions on the matter, Clinton tried to turn the stinging foreign
policy defeat to his party's political advantage, insisting the
vote will be a potent election issue for Democrats next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``These arms control agreements have created a climate in the
world which has helped to make us far more secure and helped to
reduce the likelihood that nuclear weapons will ever be used
again,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Without the treaty, he declared, ``we will be in a much, much
more dangerous world.''
</P>
<P>
   Adopting an unusually confrontational tone, Clinton also accused
the GOP of jeopardizing the nation's economic prosperity by
``lurching from one unworkable idea to the next'' in spending
proposals and budget cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say to the congressional majority, enough is enough. We've
got a job to do for the American people. It is not that
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss, was quick to rebut
Clinton's assertion that partisanship had triumphed over policy in
Wednesday night's rejection of the arms treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not about politics,'' Lott said. ``It was about the
substance of the treaty, and that's all it was.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some of the most thoughtful senators that have ever
served in this body that said that this treaty was not verifiable,
that it was fundamentally flawed and it should not be ratified,''
Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rejection, Clinton declared that the United States
will abide by the treaty, which has been ratified by 47 nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue the policy we have maintained since 1992 of
not conducting nuclear tests. I call on Russia, China, Britain,
France and all other countries to continue to refrain from
testing.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he assured foreign ambassadors that ``we are not
going to reverse 40 years of commitment on nonproliferation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them ... that we were in a battle with the new
isolationists in the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the political potency of the issue, Vice President
Al Gore released the first ad of his campaign for president, a
60-second television spot in which he says that if elected
president, his first act will be to resubmit the treaty to the
Senate for ratification.
</P>
<P>
   ``This vote goes against the tide of history,'' Gore says in the
ad scheduled to air in Iowa, New Hampshire and nationally on CNN.
``I believe in my heart this vote does not speak for the American
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Among presidential candidates, as in the Senate, support for the
issue is divided along party lines. Like Gore, Democratic Bill
Bradley supports the treaty, while Republican front-runner George
W. Bush and other GOP candidates, as well as independent Bob Smith,
oppose it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton dismissed the Republicans' assertion that personal
politics were not behind the GOP's rejection of the treaty. ``They
had a lot of people committed who didn't know very much about the
treaty,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   Were it not for efforts to contain nuclear weapons over the past
40 years, Clinton said, the spiraling arms race would have
prevented the nation's current economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that without treaties to reduce nuclear arms, the
GOP would be demanding ``another $30 billion, $40 billion or $50
billion a year'' for weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would totally erode the fabric of our domestic climate,''
the president said. Nations like Brazil that have forsaken nuclear
weapons would be wasting valuable resources to protect themselves,
rather than spending money on health care or trade, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be a bleak, poor, less secure world. I don't
want my children and my grandchildren or your children or your
grandchildren to live in it,'' Clinton said. ``I will do everything
I can to stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton demurred when asked whether he agreed with Gore's
criticism of Bradley for having quit the Senate shortly after
Republicans took control. The president offered strong praise for
Gore but refused to reproach Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get into that kind of horse racing,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Al Gore has been by far the best vice president in
history,'' he added. ``I expect to support the nominee of my party,
as I always have.''
</P>
<P>
   The news conference in the East Room of the White House was
Clinton's first since July. He avoided such forums for nearly a
year during the Monica Lewinsky scandal. Thursday, he received one
question on a related matter, and flatly refused to answer.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Judge Susan Webber Wright's decision to fine Clinton
for lying about Lewinsky in the Paula Jones deposition, Clinton
intimated he wanted to respond _ but would not do so as long as he
is president.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I am out of office, I will have a lot to say about this.
Until then, I am going to honor my commitment to all of you to go
back to work ... I am not going to say anything else that doesn't
relate to my responsibilities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
