``But for the pickers, an old way of life is threatened.''
</P>
<P>
   STAR DASH
</P>
<P>
   Paintings of crabs adorn the water tower and every street sign
in this waterfront community. Main Street is lined with businesses
like Eddie Heath's Crab Pots and Supplies and Carvel Hall Cutlery,
where they make knives used in picking. At Gordon's Restaurant,
watermen fuel up on coffee and fried-egg sandwiches before dawn.
Streets dead-end at docks where crabbing boats fill nearly every
slip.
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, lives have depended on the bounty of the bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been crabbing and oystering for 60 years,'' said Homer
Tyler, 73. ``I finished the seventh grade and then I went out on
the water.''
</P>
<P>
   His father was a waterman and so are his sons. Their days are
spent baiting, stringing and checking crab pots in the bay or
tonging for oysters. Tyler spent 35 years on a skipjack, the
working sailboat that has long since been replaced by motorized
craft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Work is what keeps me going,'' Tyler allowed. ``I'm up at 3:30
most mornings in the summer, but I come back in around dinner time.
My fingers don't work too well in winter months. But I love the
water.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Elliott, the son of a sawmill worker, expresses similar
devotion to the crab-picking house at Toddville where he does a bit
of everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I love it,'' he exclaimed. ``I can go fishing off the
pier. It's peaceful. There ain't no place else I want to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott works at Meredith &AMP; Meredith, founded by two cousins
returning from World War I. Their nephew came into the business
when he came home from World War II. His son, J.C. Tolley, joined
the enterprise in 1963 after a couple of years at the U.S. Naval
Academy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The go-go, online '90s'' have bypassed Toddville, Tolley said.
``We don't have high-tech companies, Kmarts or Wal-Marts. We don't
even have a barber.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are blue crabs and oysters nearby in the bay. For
years, shellfish have supported the families of Toddville.
</P>
<P>
   But with the influx of imported crab meat, Tolley said, ``It's
getting harder for all of us to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much we can do to modernize,'' he said. ``It's
hand work. It's not like you could build a new plant with computers
and robots. There's nowhere to squeeze.''
</P>
<P>
   STAR DASH
</P>
<P>
   In 1914, the Phillips family founded a crab-picking plant on
Hoopers Island, just off the Eastern Shore. In 1956, Brice and
Shirley Phillips opened a seafood restaurant in the resort town of
Ocean City, Md. Since then, the family business has exploded _ with
restaurants from Washington, D.C., to West Palm Beach, Fla., and
Phillips ``Maryland-style'' crab soup and frozen crab cakes in
supermarkets across the country.
</P>
<P>
   But the crab meat in the company's restaurants and packaged
products is much more likely to have come from Asia than from the
Chesapeake Bay. Along with its original Hooper's Island picking
house, Phillips now has plants in Indonesia, Thailand and the
Philippines. Those foreign facilities supply most of the crab meat
for Phillips frozen products and restaurants, as well some sold to
outside distributors.
</P>
<P>
   The description of ``Maryland-style'' refers to the Phillips
family recipes, not the origin of the crab meat, said Honey
Konicoff, the marketing director for Phillips Seafood. The quality
of the crabcake is more important than where the crab came from,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips sells pasteurized crab meat to distributors at or above
the domestic market price, said Aden King, the company's sale
manager. Labor costs are cheaper in Asia, he conceded, so Phillips
foreign pickers can take more time to provide ``virtually
shell-free'' crab meat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means a lot to restaurateurs'' who otherwise have to pay
their own kitchen workers to check for shells, said Mark Sneed,
president of Phillips. The company has also expanded by emphasizing
``value-added products'' such as prepared crabcakes rather than
plain crab meat.
</P>
<P>
   Sneed said the seafood market has ``changed dramatically'' in
recent years but domestic crab meat processors ``haven't changed
how they do business.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, domestic crab meat processors have a different view
of the situation. Their pickers are guaranteed the minimum wage,
but most make considerably more because they're paid about $2.25
for every pound they pick. There are spot checks for shells, but
the expense of ``double picking'' would be prohibitive, said Norman
Dorrell, president of Warren Denton Seafood of Broomes Island, Md.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just can't compete on labor costs,'' said Dorrell. Asians
are ``putting us out of business and I don't see any legal way to
stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   For temporary help, U.S. processors are asking the Clinton
administration to impose quotas or duties on imported crab meat to
give the domestic industry time to adjust to the foreign
competition. Similar relief was provided by the U.S. International
Trade Commission when American sheep ranchers were hard hit by lamb
imports from Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tariffs or quotas are only a short-term solution, but (such
measures) might buy time'' for imposing marketing standards and
launching an information. campaign to let consumers know when Asian
crab meat is sold, said Lipton, the marine economist.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers ``may or may not care, but at least they would know
that the crabcakes at a waterfront restaurant didn't come from
local crabs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asian crabs are significantly different from the blue crabs
caught in the Chesapeake Bay and along the Southern coast, said
Jack Brooks, who, along with his brothers, runs J.M. Clayton Co., a
Cambridge, Md., seafood business begun in 1890s by their
great-grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks and other domestic processors maintain that the American
blue crab meat tastes better than the Asian variety. They want
federal requirements so the products will be labeled with the
crab's country of origin. Temporary tariffs or quotas will give the
American crab industry time to differentiate their product, like
Florida has done with oranges or Vidalia, Ga., with onions, Brooks
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Barbara James prays every morning and picks the meat
from a crab every 20 seconds or so. Outside the seafood business,
she said, ``there are no jobs in this town.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
