<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7862 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-GIRLS-SCHOOLS16-COX     10-15 1379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRLS-SCHOOLS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A school of their own
 &HT;    By Doug Cumming
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta is about to get its first girls school in
nearly 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when applications for all-girls' schools are rising in
other big cities, several Atlanta mothers have pulled together
$500,000 and influential friends to open the Atlanta Girls' School
next August at a still undetermined site.
</P>
<P>
   Next Tuesday night, the new day school will market itself
alongside seven exclusive girls' boarding schools at an
informational reception for parents interested in this newest form
of an old tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has not had a girls' school since 1952. But before that,
it had generations of girls learning apart from boys. There was
Girls High, a public school that went coed in 1947 when it became
Roosevelt High, and Washington Seminary, a private girls prep
school that closed in 1952 to become part of the new Westminster
Schools. Westminster had boys and girls on the same campus but
taught them separately until the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not new,'' Emily Ellison, an Atlanta novelist who is
board chairwoman for the Atlanta Girls' School, said of single-sex
education.
</P>
<P>
   However, an intense debate over the return of single-sex
education in the 1990s is new.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the trend cite a spate of research that came out
in the early 1990s claiming schools were not sensitive enough to
the distinct learning styles of girls, who were said to be more
cautious, analytical and perfectionist than boys, in general.
Separate research by Carol Gilligan at Harvard University,David and
Myra Sadker at American University and findings in a 1992 report,
``How Schools Shortchange Girls,'' pointed to evidence that girls
often lose confidence and falter academically as they enter middle
grades, partly because of the way teachers give more attention,
both positive and negative, to the aggressive behavior of boys.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees that this research supports a return to
single-sex classrooms. Some say it instead argues for more group
activities and student-centered learning, elements more likely to
be found in a progressive co-ed classroom than a typical girls
school with its traditional curriculum and pleated-skirt uniforms.
Cliff Adelman, a senior research analyst at the U.S. Department of
Education, has criticized the research that finds bias against
girls, arguing that if teachers pay more attention to boys it's
because they act up and have more academic problems. Now, Adelman
says, females have surpassed males or are rapidly closing the
academic gender gaps at all levels, from high school to medical
school.
</P>
<P>
   The improved outlook for girls and declining achievement for
male students in some areas is acknowledged in an update of the
``Shortchange'' report, called ``Gender Gaps: Where Schools Still
Fail Our Children,'' published last year. The American Association
of University Women, which sponsored both reports, also released a
report in 1998, to the chagrin of girls' school supporters,
challenging the assumption that single-sex education is better than
coeducation.
</P>
<P>
   At least one private school in Atlanta has separated boys and
girls in a few classes for at least six years because of the early
1990s research. At the Walker School in Marietta, math in grades
six through eight and some science in grades five and seven have
been offered to single-sex classes, as schedules allow, said middle
school Principal Nancy Calhoun. One result, she said, is a dramatic
increase in the percentage of girls opting for advanced math
courses in high school, such as calculus. The rate of girls taking
such electives at Walker School has risen from 30 percent to 50
percent, she said. Nationally, it's about 17 percent for boys and
girls.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Orrell, head of Walker's middle school math department,
who initiated the single-sex classes, said a lot of girls who at
the beginning of the year said they wouldn't consider a women's
college, after going through the girls-only math class, became open
to the idea of applying to Agnes Scott or other women's colleges.
Orrell hasn't studied the results of her single-sex classes
scientifically, but cites individual cases. One girl who had been
relatively quiet in class, when Orrell ran into her later in a
higher grade, told her, ``When those boys roll their eyes, I just
keep right on asking the question,'' Orrell said.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the eighth grade, she said, ``many will say,
`Oh, next year we're going to have boys in our math class _
yuck.'''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of the Atlanta Girls School began with several mothers
who were not happy with their educational choices. Ellison, whose
only child, Elli, was at a high-performing public elementary school
in Buckhead, was troubled by the high-pressure environment she saw
children growing up in. She found it ironic that baby boom parents
wanted to get off the fast-track for the sake of their children,
but ``we're putting our children on a fast-track like nothing we
were on.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she read Mary Pipher's popular book, ``Reviving Ophelia:
Saving the Selves of Adolescent Girls,'' about the emotional
difficulties of coming-of-age for American girls. Now, she says,
her home office that was once filled with literary fiction is now
filled with research on education and gender.
</P>
<P>
   The more she read, the more she worried that the pressures on
children _ from media images of style and peer competition _ become
excruciating for girls as they enter adolescence in the company of
too many boy-girl considerations. What she read about girls'
schools seemed to offer an answer.
</P>
<P>
   She and other mothers thinking along the same lines found each
other, through the usual networking of plugged-in parents. Some of
these mothers, unlike Ellison, were themselves products of girls'
schools and were puzzled that Atlanta didn't have one. ``I am
convinced of the value of single-sex education,'' said Brooke
Weinmann, an alumna and trustee of a Virginia girls' boarding
school who worked with Ellison over the last two years on the
Atlanta Girls' School.
</P>
<P>
   The school will open in August with about 100 girls in grades
six to nine, adding grades and students each year until it reaches
12th grade and a maximum of 400 students. Tuition will be
comparable to that of other selective prep schools in Atlanta, with
scholarships anticipated to ensure that students from various
income levels enroll, Weinmann said.
</P>
<P>
   The founders are still looking for a site, but have found and
hired a head of school, Patricia E. Crone.
</P>
<P>
   Crone, the former head of two coeducational private schools in
California, helped found the Coachella Valley Ophelia Project in
southeast California, working with local high school girls using
the ideas in Pipher's book for ``saving the selves of adolescent
girls.'' She has been given free office space from the top-floor
law firm of King &AMP; Spalding, but says she will go anywhere to
interview prospective students.
</P>
<P>
   The first applicant, besides daughters of board members, met her
this week at a coffee shop.
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra Brosius, 13, was nervous and quiet. But instead of
passively answering questions, she asked Crone questions, and not
just about the Atlanta Girls' School. Alexandra asked the woman
four times her age about her own high school experience in Ohio.
And she asked her why girls' schools are better.
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra is being home-schooled now, but at the progressive
Montessori-style private schools she attended before that, she said
she experienced the same problems that Crone mentioned from her own
experience, and from the research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several teachers. . .really seemed to favor the boys,''
Alexandra said. ``The boys would get called on more; they got to
do. More than once, I raised my hand as much as the boys, and still
didn't get called on,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra left the coffee shop telling her mother that she was
very excited about going to the Atlanta Girls' School. Her only
worry, she said, is not having much of a chance to see boys.
</P>
<P>
   What about after school? ``I'm too busy,'' she said, with lesson
in horseback riding, violin and Irish dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7863 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD16-COX     10-15 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New book, new author, familiar old techniques
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's been quite a while since I've seen a woodworking
book so charming as a British reprint called ``David Charlesworth's
Furniture-Making Techniques.''
</P>
<P>
   It is published, of course, by Sterling in the United States.
Given the cumbersome title and the fact that all of the book came
from the pages of a British magazine called Furniture &AMP;
Cabinetmaking, I wasn't expecting much from it. I have never seen
this magazine, but I am familiar with another Guild of Master
Craftsmen Publication called Woodturning, which is more frustrating
than useful.
</P>
<P>
   But this $17.95 paperbound, printed in lovely color, is worth
every penny of its price.
</P>
<P>
   I'd never heard of David Charlesworth, which means nothing, but
I expect I'd like him since he seems to be fascinated by many of
the things that grab me. This is not another treatise on how to
prepare wood and turn it into furniture; it is a series of chapters
on how to prepare and use the kinds of tools he favors, and if you
work your way through it, you'll be able to handle most things.
</P>
<P>
   He starts with a nice discussion of his own shop and of
workbenches. Following that are chapters on how to properly set up
a marking knife, and then a couple of sections on Japanese chisels.
As you would expect, there are half a dozen sections on the
preparation and use of hand planes, including a very good chapter
on dealing with difficult grain.
</P>
<P>
   Then we have chapters on the two basic joints of woodworking,
the mortise and tenon and the dovetail, especially as produced on
the band saw, before going into some truly headache-producing
discussions of compound dovetails, tapered dovetail housings and,
finally, the hidden mitered dovetail.
</P>
<P>
   There are also chapters on making spokeshaves, and three
projects. The only project that is at all commonplace is a
wall-hung display case. It is built in the style of James Krenov,
with dowel joints, although its design is scarcely up to Krenov's.
I certainly admire Krenov's work, but I have no use for dowel
joints.
</P>
<P>
   I would guess that the other two projects are unique to the
literature. One is a little meditation stool made in the Japanese
style. Charlesworth clearly delights in every facet of Japanese
woodworking, and especially the use of extremely complicated joints
to produce extremely simple-looking, understated pieces.
</P>
<P>
   The final production is a Japanese inro box. This is a tiny box
with two compartments and a lid, all fitted together very
accurately and held in place by silk cord.
</P>
<P>
   As Charlesworth points out, something like this might be made
fairly easily on the lathe, but his project is nowhere near round;
it's oblong with curved corners. The project is unbelievably
complicated, but the planning and execution makes for fascinating
reading.
</P>
<P>
   There is a companion book for the turner, called ``Woodturning:
the Best from Woodturning Magazine,'' at $14.95. It's a handsome
production, and features a lot of fascinating work.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
