A7864 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD16-COX     10-15 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New book, new author, familiar old techniques
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's been quite a while since I've seen a woodworking
book so charming as a British reprint called ``David Charlesworth's
Furniture-Making Techniques.''
</P>
<P>
   It is published, of course, by Sterling in the United States.
Given the cumbersome title and the fact that all of the book came
from the pages of a British magazine called Furniture &AMP;
Cabinetmaking, I wasn't expecting much from it. I have never seen
this magazine, but I am familiar with another Guild of Master
Craftsmen Publication called Woodturning, which is more frustrating
than useful.
</P>
<P>
   But this $17.95 paperbound, printed in lovely color, is worth
every penny of its price.
</P>
<P>
   I'd never heard of David Charlesworth, which means nothing, but
I expect I'd like him since he seems to be fascinated by many of
the things that grab me. This is not another treatise on how to
prepare wood and turn it into furniture; it is a series of chapters
on how to prepare and use the kinds of tools he favors, and if you
work your way through it, you'll be able to handle most things.
</P>
<P>
   He starts with a nice discussion of his own shop and of
workbenches. Following that are chapters on how to properly set up
a marking knife, and then a couple of sections on Japanese chisels.
As you would expect, there are half a dozen sections on the
preparation and use of hand planes, including a very good chapter
on dealing with difficult grain.
</P>
<P>
   Then we have chapters on the two basic joints of woodworking,
the mortise and tenon and the dovetail, especially as produced on
the band saw, before going into some truly headache-producing
discussions of compound dovetails, tapered dovetail housings and,
finally, the hidden mitered dovetail.
</P>
<P>
   There are also chapters on making spokeshaves, and three
projects. The only project that is at all commonplace is a
wall-hung display case. It is built in the style of James Krenov,
with dowel joints, although its design is scarcely up to Krenov's.
I certainly admire Krenov's work, but I have no use for dowel
joints.
</P>
<P>
   I would guess that the other two projects are unique to the
literature. One is a little meditation stool made in the Japanese
style. Charlesworth clearly delights in every facet of Japanese
woodworking, and especially the use of extremely complicated joints
to produce extremely simple-looking, understated pieces.
</P>
<P>
   The final production is a Japanese inro box. This is a tiny box
with two compartments and a lid, all fitted together very
accurately and held in place by silk cord.
</P>
<P>
   As Charlesworth points out, something like this might be made
fairly easily on the lathe, but his project is nowhere near round;
it's oblong with curved corners. The project is unbelievably
complicated, but the planning and execution makes for fascinating
reading.
</P>
<P>
   There is a companion book for the turner, called ``Woodturning:
the Best from Woodturning Magazine,'' at $14.95. It's a handsome
production, and features a lot of fascinating work.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
