<P>
   EDITORIAL-IRS _ ATLANTA _ One robin doesn't make a spring, but
I've just been through an exchange with the IRS that has left me
astonished _ at the polite, professional and fair way the matter
was handled, from first contact through final resolution. If my
experience was at all typical, then the worm has turned, the
leopard has changed its spots, however you want to put it: The IRS
treated me like _ a customer! (Matthews, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ Who would have dreamed in
the days of one stoplight and Huie Nipper's vegetable lunches in
the old train station that Fayetteville someday would have three
Waffle Houses? If I lived there, I'd be proud. (Jim Minter is a
former editor of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Last week, when I struggled for
a column topic, a friend tried to give me a hand up. ``Write about
Bruce, how you and Jim chased him around the Midwest,'' she
suggested. ``How we hang onto our youth through the music that we
grew up with.'' It was a good idea, but it isn't nostalgia that
keeps drawing me back to this band. It's not merely music to
reminisce by, but music to grow up with. And to remind us, should
we fall behind, of all the people standing by to lend a hand.
(McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Even as a military coup was raising the risk
Pakistan will restart its nuclear arms race with India, the Senate
was removing the United States as leader of the international
effort to contain nuclear weapons. GOP leadership saw a shot at
paying President Clinton back for besting it on issue after issue,
and took it. (Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox
Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Howard Kleinberg is on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ BERLIN _ In visiting Berlin, an eight-hour train
trip from Warsaw, grandfather would put up at the Hotel Adlon on
Unter den Linden near the Brandenburg Gate. Well before his
arrival, a butler would lay out his personal cache in cherrywood
cabinets that rested on limestone floors covered with oriental
carpets. The last time he stayed there was in 1933, shortly before
the Nazis marched through the Gate to proclaim by torchlight the
start of the 1,000-year Reich. Ten years later, they murdered him
and most of my family as Jews. (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox
News Service in the Washington bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
