<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7867 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-EDITORIAL-IRS16-COX     10-15 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-IRS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A recent run-in with the IRS proves surprisingly painless
 &HT;    (EDs: This is an editorial from Thursday's Atlanta Journal.)
 &HT;    By Richard Matthews
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If there was ever an oxymoron in the realm of the
federal government, one would surely think it must be this: a
``kinder, gentler'' Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what they promised us last year, when Congress got
hopping mad about a string of horror stories from taxpayers abused,
affronted, insulted and wronged by the government's tax collectors.
By near-unanimous votes, both chambers passed the Restructuring and
Reform Act, which required the IRS to be helpful, rather than
heavyhanded, with America's citizens.
</P>
<P>
   We all knew that was going to happen, right? Despite all the
smooth assurances, most of us thought the best we could hope was
that auditors would use softer blackjacks when they worked
taxpayers over in the back room. It's doubtful many people expected
any real changes, least of all a decent regard for people or a
presumption of innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe we were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   One robin doesn't make a spring, but I've just been through an
exchange with the IRS that has left me astonished _ at the polite,
professional and fair way the matter was handled, from first
contact through final resolution. If my experience was at all
typical, then the worm has turned, the leopard has changed its
spots, however you want to put it: The IRS treated me like _ a
customer!
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a big issue. The payroll service firm for my wife's
office had wrongly reported a medical savings account as a
dependent child care account. Since we don't have any children, the
IRS said we owed a few hundred more dollars. We sent in
documentation to correct the error, and everything was fine.
</P>
<P>
   Of course I'm glad the issue was settled easily, but what's
truly interesting is the language used and the apparent
thoughtfulness throughout the process. The first letter didn't
harshly demand money; it said, ``We are proposing changes to your
1997 income tax return ....''
</P>
<P>
   It explained the discrepancy concisely, and described in detail
how we could challenge the ``proposal'' if we thought we were
right. We were given an 800 number and the name of a specific human
being to contact.
</P>
<P>
   After we sent in our explanation, we got another letter
acknowledging receipt, promising a response within 30 days, and
ending, ``We apologize for any inconvenience we may have caused
you, and thank you for your cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks later came the ``closing letter'' giving us
the all-clear: ``We are pleased to tell you that, with your help,
we were able to clear up the differences between your records and
your payer's records.''
</P>
<P>
   That may not be earth-shattering behavior in the private sector,
but it is a dramatic change from earlier IRS ways. As a manager, my
wife has had to deal with inquiries in the past, and she said they
were always abrupt and threatening, treating everyone as if they
were guilty from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Of course there are always going to be differences of opinion
between those who pay taxes and those who collect them, and not
everyone is going to win a challenge to an IRS audit. But if the
agency really has decided to be ``kinder and gentler,'' as my
recent go-round suggests, we may have to go out and find a new
optimum oxymoron for government business. Oh, that's one, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
