</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-ISLAM _ ATLANTA _ The Nation of Islam, best known for
the fiery rhetoric of its leader, Louis Farrakhan, and its
stern-looking ``Fruit of Islam'' security detail, recently
appointed a woman to head its entire Southern region. It's the
first time the group, accused in the past of being sexist, has
appointed a woman to such a position. We profile Sister Ava
Muhammad, the new minister, and examine the growth _ and changes _
in the Nation of Islam. (Blake, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40.
WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGIONSOUTH _ Advance on conference on Religion in the
American South at Emory, featuring among others Jimmy Carter and
Andy Young. (White, Atlanta Journal-Costitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-CONE _ Theologian James Cone speaks at ITC's main
campus. Live report. Will talk about Malcolm X and Martin Luther
King Jr. (Blake, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BIBLE-HOMOSEXUALITY _ Does the Bible say that homosexuality is a
sin? A slew of books _ scholarly and otherwise _ have been written
to support both sides of this issue. But the Rev. Samuel Kader's
book brings something new to the argument: The perspective of a man
who is both gay and a member of the clergy. In ``Openly Gay, Openly
Christian: How the Bible Really is Gay Friendly'' (Leyland
Publications, $15.95), Kader argues that scripture commonly cited
as proof that the Bible condemns homosexuality are misreadings, at
best, used by blatant homophobics or by people who have a sincere
intention to help homosexuals ``get right with God.'' (Dayton Daily
News)
</P>
<P>
   CRUCIFIX _ A diamond-studded crucifix is surely more offensive
to God than a portrait of Mary surrounded by elephant dung. But
cardinals and critics condemn the painting and peddle the crosses.
(Palm Beach Post). 18.
</P>
<P>
   PAPAL-AUDIENCE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The elderly man's face
was a little swollen. From the medication, they said. And he looked
tired, maybe from all of his speaking engagements. But with his
white vestments and his rosy cheeks, he looked regal, too, sitting
there in that big, cream-colored chair surrounded by large men in
black cassocks and suits. Two newlyweds describe their audience
with the pope and the instructions they used to arrange it.
(Belkin, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   LOVESTORY _ Harry Stillwell Edwards, poet, writer and columnist
for the Macon Telegraph and Atlanta Journal, was a
turn-of-the-century celebrity, lauded by the likes of Rudyard
Kipling and Teddy Roosevelt. After losing his wife in 1922, there
was one great romance in Edwards' last years, one that remained a
secret for half a century. During the summer of 1996 a trove of
letters from Edwards to a young poet named Rebecca Griffin turned
up in the attic of an Atlanta house. They detail a relationship
that would never be acknowledged: She was a teenager and he was in
his 70s. Yet the passion of the words fascinated the woman who
discovered them. Yet none of the official keepers of Edwards' flame
knew about the letters. His granddaughter wishes they'd been
burned. The sisters who found them would like to see them preserved
somehow. (Emerson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY
</P>
