<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7870 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN16-COX     10-15 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Concert renews the soul
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The old man and the old woman were in their 90s,
married 70 years. She had Alzheimer's; he was still full of verve.
And devotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I married a beauty,'' he said. ``And she's still the most
beautiful woman in the world.'' As he leaned over to kiss her, you
could see what he meant. You could envision the young woman he
married, and see the beauty still etched in her face.
</P>
<P>
   This scene from a decade ago came back to me, oddly enough, at a
Bruce Springsteen and the E Street Band concert in Chicago last
week. It was one of the closing numbers, when the band took turns
at the mike, a round robin of voices singing the verses to the
ballad ``If I Should Fall Behind.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd always thought of the song as a hymn to enduring love:
</P>
<P>
   ``We said we'd walk together, baby, come what may
</P>
<P>
   That come the twilight should we lose our way
</P>
<P>
   If as we're walking a hand should slip free
</P>
<P>
   I'll wait for you
</P>
<P>
   And if I should fall behind
</P>
<P>
   Wait for me.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd always thought the song was strictly about romantic love.
But it's part of the peculiar magic of a live performance that you
can see a song in a different light. Together again for the first
time in more than 10 years, this band sang the song in a way that
made you think about friendship. About all the times you fall
behind, and all the people who reach out a hand.
</P>
<P>
   They played it as an encore, side by side with a turbocharged
version of ``Born to Run.'' I smiled at the juxtaposition.
</P>
<P>
   When we are young, we sing about being born to run and born to
be wild and bad to the bone and born to be bad. We think about
charging forward, not falling behind.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not only in old age that we need a hand up.
</P>
<P>
   I thought of the friend in grade school who accepted me even
though I was afflicted with braces, nerdy glasses and excessive
piety.
</P>
<P>
   I thought of the high school religion teacher who didn't judge
my rebellion, but encouraged me to question.
</P>
<P>
   I thought of the friend who baked a lasagne and offered to
babysit when I was a new mother at the end of my rope.
</P>
<P>
   I thought of all the times I suffer a morning meltdown, and my
husband takes the punishment, bites his lip and packs the kid's
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   All those faces came before me as the familiar faces of the E
Street Band took turns at the mike. Patti Scialfa sang in her
strangely lyrical Minnie Mouse voice; Steve Van Zandt seemed moved,
even awed, to be back with this band, before these fans. The total
was greater than the sum of its parts _ the suggestion that,
through all the years and distance and difficulties, this band
would stand by each other, old friends:
</P>
<P>
   ``Should we lose each other in the shadow of the evening trees
</P>
<P>
   I'll wait for you
</P>
<P>
   And should I fall behind
</P>
<P>
   Wait for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, when I struggled for a column topic, a friend tried,
for roughly the thousandth time, to give me a hand up. ``Write
about Bruce, how you and Jim chased him around the Midwest,'' she
suggested. ``How we hang onto our youth through the music that we
grew up with.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a good idea, but it isn't nostalgia that keeps drawing me
back to this band. It's not merely music to reminisce by, but music
to grow up with.
</P>
<P>
   And to remind us, should we fall behind, of all the people
standing by to lend a hand.
</P>
<P>
   Old friends.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
