NYT-10-15-99 1116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7871 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MINTER-COLUMN16-COX     10-15 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Where the future meets the past
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ As I've mentioned before, going to town is
a challenge for country folks, even when the town is something less
than Atlanta, or even Peachtree City.
</P>
<P>
   From where we live in south Fayette County, we have to go to
Fayetteville, the county seat, to shop for groceries when we need
more than a loaf of bread. I have to make the trip to mail a
package, to see a doctor, get a prescription filled or put my
Social Security check in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Things certainly have changed in my lifetime, and in lifetimes
much shorter. Not so long ago Fayetteville's first traffic light
was the talk of the town. About the time I was graduating from high
school, the entire county had fewer than 10 miles of paved roads.
Streets around the courthouse were dirt. Farmers came on Saturday
afternoons in wagons and buggies, hitching posts holding their
horses and mules while they shopped for the few necessities they
couldn't grow.
</P>
<P>
   Fayetteville wasn't much bigger than Moreland, which Lewis
Grizzard said needed only one post for the city limits sign. One
sign said ``entering,'' the other said ``leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   Small as it was, Fayetteville made visiting country folks feel
nervous and out-of-place. This was mostly in our heads, but now
it's for real, almost like being in Atlanta or Peachtree City. You
hardly ever see anyone you know.
</P>
<P>
   On Fridays, traffic backs up almost into Clayton County. Time
spent circling a route to the laundry on one-way streets would have
gotten us to Jonesboro in the old days.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping centers hopscotching up Ga. 85 will soon be shaking
hands with Riverdale.
</P>
<P>
   Fayetteville has so many new shopping centers that developers
are running out of names. The newest is going to be called
``Uptown,'' which is appropriate since Custard Mize's grocery, K.W.
McElwaney's general merchandise and Ed Travis' hardware store are
long gone from ``downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   You have to stand in line, sometimes 10 to 15 minutes, at the
post office. That never happened when Stanley Morgan was
postmaster. Nobody ever had to wait on Stanley unless he was out on
the sidewalk tied up in a game of checkers, which come to think
about it, was most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Fayetteville folks had civic pride even when the town's lone
policeman also did the city's garbage collecting. According to
Ferrol Sams, the physician-author who has written more books than
many of his neighbors have read, this changed when a society-type
matron from Atlanta drove down in her Cadillac to call on one of
the town's more prominent families.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta visitor was indignant over being apprehended and
issued a speeding ticket by a gentleman dressed in dirty overalls
and driving a garbage truck. Her prominent hosts were embarrassed
and, according to Dr. Sams, succeeded at the next council meeting
in obtaining funds for a police cruiser and a proper officer's
uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Despite snowballing growth in the last quarter of the 20th
century, give Fayetteville credit for preserving some of its
antiquities. No matter how much else resembles Buckhead and
Peachtree City, you still can't buy a mixed drink. Although you can
buy beer and wine at any number of grocery stores, or on any corner
where they sell gasoline and loaf bread, Fayetteville voters hold
the line on Demon Rum. Order a martini and the best you can hope
for is a baseball player from the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people complain about this, but personally I can't see
why. The ban on mixed drinks keeps the place kind of quaint, like
in the old days when everybody had to drive to the airport liquor
store to buy a bottle, and Mr. Bill Hightower, the garbage
collector, was very popular with the gossips because he counted
empties.
</P>
<P>
   During the last push to get mixed drinks on the ballot, one
fellow got into deep doo-doo when he complained that because city
restaurants can't serve mixed drinks he has to go to Atlanta to get
a decent meal.
</P>
<P>
   Such sentiments slander barbecue and Brunswick stew served on
white bread. I don't live in Fayetteville, but it is our county
seat and I'm ready to stand up for it. Despite tricky one-way
streets and shopping center parking lots designed by Georgia Tech
dropouts, wonderful things have happened since I first went there
from the Woolsey school and got an introduction to indoor plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have dreamed in the days of one stoplight and Huie
Nipper's vegetable lunches in the old train station that
Fayetteville someday would have three Waffle Houses?
</P>
<P>
   If I lived there, I'd be proud.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
