<HEADER>
A7873 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-PAPAL-AUDIENCE16-COX     10-15 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAPAL-AUDIENCE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Papal audience easy to get, hard ever to forget
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The elderly man's face was a little
swollen. From the medication, they said. And he looked tired, maybe
from all of his speaking engagements. But with his white vestments
and his rosy cheeks, he looked regal, too, sitting there in that
big, cream-colored chair surrounded by large men in black cassocks
and suits.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Knobbe felt as if he was outside his body looking down.
Watching himself walk on the red rug toward the man. He saw himself
dressed in the black tuxedo he bought for $10 at a thrift store.
His wife was next to him, elegant in her white wedding gown, a
string of pearls around her neck. The bright light from the hot
Mediterranean sun surrounded them. The word surreal came to mind.
</P>
<P>
   This was the last day of a 2 1/2-week honeymoon for the
newlyweds from Palm Beach Gardens. They had no idea they could
visit the Vatican until a friend told them a few months before they
left for Europe that it was open to the public if they made
reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Knobbe had spent 30 years _ his lifetime _ in devotion to this
man he'd never met and never expected to. His parents and seven
brothers and sisters had built their lives around what he
represented. Now, here the man was, slightly stooped in his chair.
His right hand raised and slightly extended. Dan could see the
ring, it was gold, smudged red with lipstick. He reached forward.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Knobbe watched the back of her husband's head. The man in
the chair said something. His words were hard to understand. Don't
genuflect, she had been told, there wasn't time.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't think about her conversion to Catholicism the year
before. She didn't think about how her husband had asked her to
marry him in a basilica built to honor the divinity the man in
front of her represented. Or how she knew she would remember this
moment for the rest of her life.
</P>
<P>
   She just took the man's right hand and bent over, gracefully she
would say later, and held his fingers. His thumb pressed gently on
the back of her knuckles. His fingers were old, warm, wrinkled. On
the ring was a cross. The hand was part of a lineage that had
touched the son of God. She leaned closer. She placed her lips on
the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just kissed the hand of the pope,'' she thought. Somewhere,
a camera clicked.
</P>
<P>
   Having an experience with the pope like the Knobbes did is
probably easier than you think.
</P>
<P>
   According to Deacon Patrick W. Kennedy of the North American
College in New Jersey, all you have to do is fax or mail a request
at least a month in advance to the visitor's office in Rome. If you
want to have your marriage blessed, note that on the request.
</P>
<P>
   Since the office is run by two people and receives about 50,000
requests a year, you will not receive a confirmation but you can
pick up your invitation the day before the audience at the office.
</P>
<P>
   All public audiences are on Wednesday, usually at 10 a.m.,
depending on the pontiff's schedule and his health. Tickets are
free and available to non-Catholics, too.
</P>
<P>
   Write to the United States Bishop's Office for U.S. Pilgrims,
Via del'Umilta, 30 00187 Rome, or fax your request to 011. 39. 06.
6900. 1823.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
