<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROPICAL CROTONS CAN ADD FALL COLOR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Q: I would like advice on crotons. What should I do to
keep the plant healthy? Can I plant crotons in the ground?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; Crotons (Codiaeum variegatum) are highly ornamental members
of the euphorbia family. These tropical plants have large,
leathery, thick leaves of multiple colors and shapes. Those with
reds and golds in nurseries now are particularly suitable for fall
color.
</P>
<P>
   But crotons are cold-tender and will die when exposed to
prolonged freezing temperatures, so if you grow them in beds,
either protect them or just use them as annuals and replace next
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Many gardeners grow crotons in containers. As winter approaches,
they gradually move the plants indoors and keep them in bright
light. Keep the soil moist, but take caution not to overwater.
</P>
<P>
   Most crotons like sun; some prefer a break from hot rays during
summer. Plant in a sandy, organically enriched soil. These colorful
plants like water, but are drought-tolerant once established.
Fertilize as needed (monthly if they're in containers). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  I have a compost bin that sometimes produces plants I'm not
expecting. One came up in a flower bed when I spread the compost
there. It's about 4 feet tall now, growing somewhat like an
umbrella with the leaves spreading out at the top. Do you know what
it is?
</P>
<P>
   Also, can I expect my avocado to bear fruit? I've had it about
seven years in a large pot. Even after severe pruning this spring,
it's still taller than the house. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; I believe you have a papaya, Carica papaya. Papayas are
tall herbaceous plants with large divided leaves that resemble
those of philodendron. The foliage grows at the top of a
light-green trunk. The flowers are small and greenish; the green,
melon-shaped fruit appear in clusters close to the trunk.
</P>
<P>
   Some papayas have male and female flowers on the same plant;
others bear male or female blooms only. These latter types
generally do not produce tasty fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Papayas can't take freezing weather. But gardeners can enjoy
these fast growers during warm months. They like sun, a
well-draining, organically enriched soil and water.
</P>
<P>
   Local gardeners sometimes report success growing fruit when they
plant seed from store-bought papayas.
</P>
<P>
   Papayas bear within a year after being planted from seed. The
fruit is usually harvested when yellow-orange, but green fruit can
be picked and cooked.
</P>
<P>
   Some gardeners here have harvested avocados, but it's not a
common thing. Even if yours never produces, you can enjoy an
attractive plant. Avocado trees must reach a good height _ some say
35 feet _ before they bear.
</P>
<P>
   Avocados are cold-tender and may be killed to the ground when
grown outdoors here. They then need a few years to regrow before
they bear.
</P>
<P>
   Since we have freezes, you'll want to protect the roots as best
you can. Avocados do best in a sunny, well-draining spot. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  Our daughter has been growing ginger, and it has been
beautiful this summer. Will you identify the variety and tell us
the best time to transplant as well as when and how to prune?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  The ginger in the photo you sent is shell ginger (Alpinia
zerumbet). Gingers in this large genus are easy to grow, preferring
an organically enriched soil that drains well. Morning sun and
filtered afternoon sun are ideal. Alpinias like moisture and thrive
in humidity. The shell ginger produces highly fragrant, large
cascading clusters of flowers in late spring and summer when the
foliage is not frozen back in winter. Each bloom resembles a white
seashell edged in pink with a red and yellow lip.
</P>
<P>
   Shell gingers will die back during freezing weather, but the
broad, tapered foliage on canelike stems reappears each spring and
can easily reach 8 feet or more in height given several warm
months. The rhizomes spread, and each year you have a larger clump.
</P>
<P>
   Although shell gingers won't bloom following a winter with
freezing temperatures, the lush, new foliage that pops up in spring
makes an attractive accent or screen, if the clump is allowed to
expand.
</P>
<P>
   You can transplant in spring, summer or fall. Prune dead foliage
after a freeze. Prune stalks that have already flowered any time
you wish. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to each unpublished letter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
