<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINDOWS 98 FEATURE COULD BE CAUSING PROBLEMS WITH SHUTTING DOWN
COMPUTER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Ever since I upgraded to Windows 98, I've had occasional
problems with shutting down my computer. I'll get to the screen
that says ``Windows is shutting down,'' and that's it. I don't see
``It is now safe to turn off your computer.'' What is causing this?
</P>
<P>
   A: There actually can be many causes for this _ it's one of the
more difficult Windows problems to troubleshoot. But the fact that
it began when you started using Windows 98 offers something of a
clue.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98 has a feature called Fast Shutdown, which in theory
is a great idea. Rather than closing out each active driver and
program first, Windows just shuts down, period. This is supposed to
make the shutdown process less lengthy.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem is that some software rejects this ``brute
force'' approach, and can cause a system to hang. Fortunately, you
can turn off Fast Shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   Go to Start, then Programs, Accessories, System Tools. In that
folder, click on the System Information icon. This brings up the
SysInfo program, which is an excellent diagnostic tool (and by
itself is worth the cost of a Windows 98 upgrade). Click on the
Tools menu, then System Configuration Utility. Click on the
Advanced button, and check the ``Disable Fast Shutdown'' box. Click
OK and exit the utility and the SysInfo tool.
</P>
<P>
   If something else is causing your problem _ or if you still use
Windows 95 _ there are some other things you can try.
</P>
<P>
   First, make sure you have the latest drivers for your video and
sound card, your modem and, if you have one in your PC, your
network card. Next, get down to as lean-and-mean a system as you
can. In February, I did a pair of columns on the wisdom of running
with as few in-the-background programs as possible, particularly
virus checkers and programs that watch for and log software
installations.
</P>
<P>
   These kinds of programs can keep your system from shutting down
cleanly, as well as causing other problems. I advocate not using
them, but religiously and manually scanning any programs or Word
documents that come into your system for viruses. For the details,
see www.chron.com/content/chronicle/tech/99/02/12/compute.html and
www.chron.com/content/chronicle/tech/99/02/19/compute.html.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I had some trouble installing a 133-megahertz processor
upgrade. My computer is a Compaq Presario CDS 526, with a 486DX2/66
MHz processor, bought in April of 1994. I tried to install the new
chip, but when I turned my computer on, the LED lights and monitor
came on, but nothing happened. The screen remained blank. I put the
original processor back in _ still nothing. I called Compaq, and
they said it might be a damaged circuit board. Is it possible there
could be another problem, or will I end up having to spend more to
fix up my computer? I've spent almost $500 trying to upgrade it.
The processor was the first thing I tried to install.
</P>
<P>
   A: Your first mistake was in not calling Compaq before you
bought and installed that chip. Yes, it's very likely that you may
have fried your system board.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Compaq does not recommend installing processor
upgrades. And in many cases chips that are pin-compatible _ meaning
they'll fit in another chip's socket _ aren't compatible with the
motherboard. They may require a different voltage, or work at
speeds faster than the motherboard's capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   I'm surprised that you were willing to spend $500 on upgrade
components, when you could pay that for a new machine and get much
better performance than you would by upgrading an older one. As
inexpensive and as powerful as new systems are now, it's almost not
worth upgrading an older computer _ such as a 486 or a Pentium
system _ once you get past the $400 mark. You're better off getting
a new system.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
