<HEADER>
A7900 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-15 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVATE COMPANIES STILL HAVE OPTIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ These days, when you're negotiating a compensation
package for a new job, a car doesn't cut it. Neither does a country
club membership.
</P>
<P>
   No, executives today want stock options because that's where the
real money is. In good years, when stock prices are strong,
executives can earn much more on their options than on their annual
salary and bonus.
</P>
<P>
   So how does a private company that doesn't have stock options to
offer compete in an environment like that? How can it attract good
managers and executives?
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to attract the best talent when you don't have
the ability to offer long-term wealth accumulation devices such as
stocks and options, said Bob Diers, senior compensation consultant
for William M. Mercer Inc. in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   To try to close at least some of the gap, some private companies
offer ``phantom stock'' to key employees. Phantom stock typically
is based on a variety of variables, such as profitability or
revenue growth.
</P>
<P>
   While that helps, the value of the stock typically doesn't rise
as fast as that of a publicly traded issue. It's insulated from the
gyrations of the tempermental market, which has sent some
profitless dot-com companies soaring in value.
</P>
<P>
   And the phantom stock is also costly to a private company.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't cost a public company anything to issue options,
Diers said. The market essentially picks up the tab. But when a
private company offers phantom stock and options, the money comes
right off the bottom line. Consequently, the amount of stock isn't
as great as it might be if the company were public.
</P>
<P>
   Other private companies use a different kind of lure to attract
high-flying employees: the chance to get in on the ground floor of
a company that's poised to issue an initial public offering. Many
top business school graduates are spurning the traditional
consulting firms and are willing to take less of a salary for the
chance to work for a small start-up, in the hope of holding shares
in the next Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HIGHER PAY, BONUSES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To make up for the lack of options, private companies often pay
a higher base pay and bonus than what employees earn in publicly
held companies.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if a job typically paid $200,000 and the sign-on
bonus is $10,000 to $20,000, a private company could boost the
signing bonus to $300,000 to make up for the lack of options, said
Tom Wilson, managing director with the Stratford Group, an
executive recruiting firm in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But to ensure the employee stays around for a while, the company
would require the employee to sign a note promising to return all
or part of the money if he left before the end of three years.
Under a typical arrangement, one-third or $100,000 would be
forgiven each year.
</P>
<P>
   The asset manager of a privately owned family company in Houston
said he and his colleagues earn above-market salaries and bonuses
to make up for the lack of stock options.
</P>
<P>
   But the lack of options during a time when the market has done
so well weighs on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting older too and I have been thinking about long-term
compensation,'' said the manager, who asked not to be identified.
He said the next time he looks for a job, options will be at the
forefront of his mind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
JOB CANDIDATES PASS BY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Ellisor, president of PolySpec, a private coatings and
sealants manufacturing company in Houston, said there is no
question that he misses some attractive job candidates because he
can't offer stock options like a publicly traded company can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our business is not very sexy, either,'' said Ellisor. ``We're
a manufacturing business and we don't have dot-com behind our
name.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ellisor does have a weapon at his disposal. To the few
employees he has given stock to, there is the chance they can do
well if the company is sold and the buyer pays a premium for the
shares.
</P>
<P>
   And Ellisor said he has been able to hire top executives who
were at a point in their lives that they weren't interested in
money because they've already made money on options.
</P>
<P>
   Discounting those special exceptions, do private companies
overall end up with less-than-stellar employees?
</P>
<P>
   They do if they don't come up with innovative compensation,
Wilson said. An enlightened, creative company would try to attract
the best people possible.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
