<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-VEEP-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        DOES THE BOY FROM INDIANA HAVE A SHOT?
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Tania Anderson  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Oct. 15 -- Vice President Al Gore and Indiana Sen.
Evan Bayh have a lot in common.
</P>
<P>
   Both are sons of the heartland. Both are sons of senators. Both
present clean-cut, All American images. Born eight years apart,
they both spent part of their formative years in the nation's
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Are both destined for higher office? Gore's aspirations are well
known. He wants to be president. But what about Bayh? Does
Indiana's junior senator want to be vice president? Ever since Bayh
was put on a list on potential running mates, Indiana Democrats
have been quietly rooting for the popular former Hoosier governor
as the best man for the second most important job in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   It's not certain how the 43-year-old's name started circulating
as a potential vice president or how much interest there is in Bayh
from the Gore campaign. It started after Bayh delivered the keynote
speech at the Democratic National Convention in August 1996. But
Gore has never pubically talked about Bayh as a running mate and he
probably won't make any announcements until the next party
convention in August 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But was it a coincidence this week when both Gore and Bayh spoke
at the Democratic Leadership Council's annual meeting?
</P>
<P>
   Bayh refuses to talk about the issue. At one point his office
was saying that he was flattered by the possibility, but now his
staffers don't even want to touch the issue. Bayh's press secretary
emphatically refuses the many requests she gets from reporters who
want to discuss the possibility that Bayh has a shot at the
``veep'' seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not participate in an article like that. It's not
something we're thinking about right now,'' said Mary Meagher, as
her boss took the podium at the Democratic Leadership conference
here in Washington last week. ``He's concentrating on being the
senator from Indiana.''
</P>
<P>
   But Indiana democrats say Gore would be smart to choose Bayh for
a running mate. The reasons: he's young and attractive, and he
would bring in midwestern votes to balance out Gore's southern
support and he has gained respect from his colleagues in the U.S.
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a very quiet efficient style. He's not a showboat and
he's able to quietly build bridges,'' said Shaw Friedman, general
counsel for the Indiana Democratic Party. ``Frankly, it's a style
that has served him very well and it's logical that someone of that
stature would be considered.''
</P>
<P>
   Several colleagues have lauded him in particular for
introduction of his ``fathers legislation,'' which would promote
programs that help dads take a bigger role in their children's
life.
</P>
<P>
   Plus he has political roots in Washington. His father, the
former Sen. Birch Bayh ran and lost the presidency in 1976 and lost
his senate seat to former Vice President Dan Quayle in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   At 33, Bayh became the first Democratic governor in Indiana in
20 years. At the time, he was also the country's youngest governor.
He won the top job again in 1993 by the largest margin in the
state's history. Bayh, a lawyer by training, then re-claimed his
father's seat in the U.S. Senate in 1998 by 63 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The father of two appeared in People magazine's 50 Most
Beautiful People earlier this year. He is one of the few
politicians to get on the annual list traditionally shared by
actors, musicians and models.
</P>
<P>
   But some say the Indiana image created by former Vice President
Dan Quayle will hurt Bayh's chances in the race. Quayle dropped out
of the presidential race last month for financial reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``His only downside is the baggage of Dan Quayle,'' said Michael
Aylesworth, chairman of the Republican party in Porter County. ``He
could be associated with that image.''
</P>
<P>
   And some Washington observers say Gore would do better by
choosing a running mate who will add some excitement to his ``stiff
as a board'' personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Gore) wants to do something dramatic he should go after a
woman,'' said Susan Tolchin, a public policy professor at George
Mason University in Fairfax, Va. ``Especially with the gender gap,
it would be very smart for him to go to (California Sens.) Diane
Feinstein or Barbara Boxer.''
</P>
<P>
   But of course Hoosiers want their guy in the veep seat. Even
Indiana Republicans wouldn't mind seeing Bayh make it to the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I'd like to see George Bush but if fate has it, well
it's always nice to have a home guy in there,'' Aylesworth said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
