<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7917 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-1016-     10-15 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-1016-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIAN PRIME MINISTER FACES OPPORTUNITIES, DANGERS WITH LATEST
CHECHEN WAR
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ So far, war has been a healthy thing for the political
life of the man President Boris Yeltsin says should succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   Few Russians had ever heard of Vladimir Putin or bothered to
form an opinion of him when Yeltsin in August named the former spy
and security chief to be prime minister and his presidential
heir-apparent.
</P>
<P>
   But today, as Putin sternly directs the war against the breakway
republic of Chechnya, the no-nonsense, 47-year-old former KGB agent
has seen his popularity soar in public opinion polls. Putin has
been active and visible, waging war in the south and handling
affairs in Moscow as the unpopular Yeltsin, dogged by illness, has
been in the hospital and seclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe the renewed Chechnya war was designed as a
``Wag the Dog''-style effort to raise the poll numbers and
visibility of Putin, and eclipse ongoing scandals alleging
Kremlin-linked corruption and money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   It is a momentous season in Russia; the nation will hold
parliamentary elections in December and the vote to replace Yeltsin
is scheduled for next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in 1994, there was the need for a small victorious war as
elections approached,'' political analyst Nikolai Petrov said,
referring to the first war in Chechnya from 1994-96. That war ended
with a humiliating Russian retreat and a negotiated settlement,
after which Chechnya proclaimed independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it's election time again. This small war may also provide
for establishing a semi-police regime, to prevent the power from
falling into hands that the Kremlin sees as wrong,'' said Petrov of
the Carnegie Center in Moscow, a think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Just two months ago only about 2 percent of Russians recognized
Putin's name, and now his approval rating in one poll stands at 70
percent. Another poll on people's preferences for president put
Putin in a close third place behind two political veterans --
front-runner former Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, and Communist
Party chief Gennady Zyuganov.
</P>
<P>
   That could change as Russian forces move deeper into Chechnya
and confront determined guerrilla fighters in the capital, Grozny,
where most Russian losses came in the last war.
</P>
<P>
   Just as quickly and easily as Putin has ascended, analysts say,
he could fall.
</P>
<P>
   In a commentary Friday headlined: ``Putin on a tightrope,'' the
daily Komsomolskaya Pravda said: ``People seem to love Vladimir
Putin more every day ... In fact, he need only take one step to
become a full-fledged candidate for president. But this is not an
easy step to take. It is called victory in Chechnya.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin projects something Russians haven't seen much of in recent
years _ coherent leadership from the Kremlin. He is Russia's point
man against terrorism, in the wake of a string of
apartment-building bombings that killed nearly 300 in Moscow and
other cities in September.
</P>
<P>
   Those bombings, as yet unsolved but widely blamed on Islamic
militants from Chechnya, prompted Russia to begin an air war
against the southern republic last month. The bombings have also
been responsible for much of the public support for the
re-invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Russia announced Friday that it was moving into a new phase of
its ground war, begun Oct. 1. Russian forces will delve deeper into
the southern territory in their effort to crush militant
separatists.
</P>
<P>
   If the re-invasion of Chechnya was calculated for political
purposes _ akin to the 1998 film ``Wag the Dog,'' in which a
fictitious U.S. president declares war to save his re-election bid
from scandal _ it is an immensely risky strategy in a region where
Moscow has failed before.
</P>
<P>
   Russian newspapers have dubbed Putin the ``military premier''
for his tough talk and conspicuous support of the country's defense
establishment, itself a formidable player in vying for the
Kremlin's influence. Putin supported another $1 billion for the
military budget, even though Russia's government is cash-strapped
and the economy is struggling.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Russia's military has moved cautiously in Chechnya,
directing a largely unchallenged air campaign and moving troops
into Chechnya's northern border region _ a relatively unpopulated
area.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy has resulted in widespread civilian casualties in
Chechnya, but has kept Russian troop losses low.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1994-96 war, at least 30,000 people are believed to have
died, most of them civilians and green Russian conscripts thrown
into the fighting. The war became highly unpopular in Russia and is
widely viewed as the most glaring mistake of Yeltsin's eight-year
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apart from the understandable worry about sparing people's
lives, the premier cannot but consider his political rating, which
will inevitably fall if 'Load 200' arrives from Chechnya,''
commentator Alexander Goltz said in Itogi magazine. Russia's
version of body bags are metal coffins known in military parlance
as ``Cargo Number 200.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the war, analysts also question Putin's staying power
because he is so new to the political scene and without an
established following. In August, Putin was something of a national
joke, coming from virtually nowhere as Yeltsin's fifth prime
minister in just 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Kremlin-backed candidates are not expected to do well in
December's parliamentary elections, leading to widespread
speculation that the ever-capricious Yeltsin could fire Putin early
next year, or be forced to by a new opposition parliament. The
Kremlin inner circle is reportedly already drawing up a list of
several new possibilities for prime minister, including Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, it is the war that will determine Putin's fate.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister has about a month to bring the war in
Chechnya to a successful conclusion, said analyst Vasily Golubev.
Otherwise, he added, ``society's discontent with this fruitless
'struggle against terrorism' will grow. In such a situation it is
useless to expect a continuation of the growth of the prime
minister's rating.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
