<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEFORE `DUTCH,' ANOTHER IMAGINARY REAGAN 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The scene is a fictional re-creation of the
Warner Brothers second-class commissary at lunchtime on March 7,
1938. The author puts some words in the mouth of a young actor
named Dutch Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spaghetti here is the cat's pajamas,'' he says. ``Hey, you
fellows mind if I join you?''
</P>
<P>
   No, the future president is not sitting down with a fictional
character named Morris. Reagan is having lunch with a fictional new
friend named Gabriel Prince, who was invented as a Reagan companion
by the author Peter Delacorte for his time-travel novel, ``Time on
My Hands,'' in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   That was two years before biographer Edmund Morris announced
that he had cast a fabricated version of himself in Reagan's life
for ``Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald Reagan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I were in Toronto when the news broke about
Morris' book,'' Delacorte said. ``She said, `He's stolen your
book.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I feel empathy for Morris. It's so easy to write
fiction about Reagan because he seems like a fictional character.''
</P>
<P>
   In Delacorte's book, the mission of Reagan's imaginary companion
isn't to explain Reagan, as in Morris' book. This companion is sent
back in time to keep Reagan from becoming president, so no one will
have to explain him.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, left-wing physicist Jasper Hudnut finds a time machine
and sends travel writer Gabriel Prince back to prewar Hollywood to
perform an errand. Hudnut is a Reagan-hater who wants to keep the
actor from trickling up to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel doesn't have anything against Reagan or his presidency,
and just thinks of him as ``a daffy old king of America.'' Still,
he agrees to go back and abort the Reagan presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel's plan is deceptively difficult: Turning Reagan into an
A-movie star who'll stay in movies, stay liberal and stay married
to Jane Wyman.
</P>
<P>
   No, he doesn't want to kill Reagan, but Reagan does take an
ill-fated right turn out to sea during a night swim. Time travel
can undo accidents like that. Can it undo a career in B movies?
</P>
<P>
   What a notion _ keep a guy out of the White House by giving him
the career he really wants. If someone went back in time and made
Bill Clinton a rock star, think of how many things would be
different. Well, not much.
</P>
<P>
   As you can see, ``Time on My Hands'' (now out in paperback by
Pocket Books) is a comic novel, one that toys with time, not
credibility, the way Morris' book does.
</P>
<P>
   Morris has said he used the device of an invented character to
get past a bad case of writer's block in writing about Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, it was Reagan who got me out of my writer's
block,'' Delacorte said. He needed some empty object, a
``McGuffin'' like Hitchcock's Maltese Falcon, for his time traveler
to seek.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan is the perfect empty object.
</P>
<P>
   Delacorte's book, like Morris' book, does have its touching
parts, including Gabriel's relationship to young Dutch, his
infatuation with prewar Hollywood and his love for a young Warner's
starlet named Lorna.
</P>
<P>
   When Gabriel finally explains to Lorna that he's from the future
on a mission to keep Reagan out of the White House, she has a line
that shows how far we've come since the days of President Franklin
Delano Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems so ... absurd,'' she says. ``I mean, the idea that a
Hollywood actor could become president. And it's not as if it's
someone like Fredric March, or Spencer Tracy _ someone you could
imagine being president.''
</P>
<P>
   Or Warren Beatty, if you reset the balky ball-bearing settings
on that French-made time machine a bit forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to evaluate Reagan's policies, I'd fall closer to
Hudnut than Gabriel,'' Delacorte said. ``I think he represented a
politics that existed before he came on the scene, but he widened
the gulf between rich and poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Morris, Delacorte didn't collect everything Reagan ever
did in his hometown of Dixon, Ill., or every thought Reagan didn't
have. He talked to a couple of old-timers who knew Reagan in the
'40s and read Garry Wills' book.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't really written a political book anyway. Rather, it's
an entertaining addition to the H.G. Wells time travel tradition,
with intriguing allusions to what life would have been like with
two terms of Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Just for starters, Jerry Brown moved up to Education secretary
and led a worldwide disarmament conference.
</P>
<P>
   Readers will be glad to know that Delacorte's fictional
character takes less than half as many pages to stalk Reagan as
Morris' fictional character.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan is America's great Rohrschach for writers. Think of the
ink spilled by Morris, Delacorte, speech writer Peggy Noonan and
hundreds of columnists. It's amazing how much writing has been
expended on a man with so little to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I haven't read the book,'' said Delacorte, when asked
about Morris' book. He sounded like a man condemned to spending 900
pages with Ronald Reagan and another writer's invented character.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't have to, though. His character was hanging around
with Dutch first and never saw this guy named Morris.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1304EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7950 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-HILLARY-SENATE-HNS &LR;      10-15 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON BLASTS WHITE HOUSE POLICY ON HEALTH CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARA JAKES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOLTON LANDING, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton told New York's
largest health care association what it wanted to hear Thursday,
criticizing her husband's White House administration for enacting a
federal budget-reduction bill that cut millions of dollars in aid
to the state's hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady and prospective U.S. Senate candidate also lashed
out at Congress for approving the cuts, which were stipulated in
the 1997 Balanced Budget Act (BBA). Congress, Mrs. Clinton said,
should not leave Washington this year until some of the $115
billion cut from health programs is restored.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1997 law, New York hospitals will take a $4.7 billion
hit in federal funding over a five-year period, mostly in Medicare
reimbursements.
</P>
<P>
   ``These cuts went too far,'' Mrs. Clinton told about 400 members
of the Healthcare Association of New York State at their annual
meeting in Bolton Landing. ``They have caused far too much pain and
are cutting too much muscle and bone. ... The administration should
take whatever steps the BBA allows it to remedy the situation. And
the Congress must not recess until it has addressed the problem as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout her statewide tour and fledgling Senate campaign,
Mrs. Clinton has repeatedly turned away from policies advocated by
President Clinton that would alienate New Yorkers in next year's
election.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the health association have long been outspoken
critics of the Clinton administration's health care policies. The
group has ripped a White House plan that would restore $7.5 billion
to Medicare cuts over 10 years instead of taking up a proposal
backed by the Republican-led Senate that would restore about $15
billion. Moreover, the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services
is currently seeking paybacks of $1 billion from 130 New York
hospitals claiming that the federal government had previously
overfunded Medicare reimbursements.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton promised to try to ease the Medicare ``squeeze''
but was not specific on how she would do so. That was enough,
however, for Dan Sisto, president of the Healthcare Association of
New York State. ``In order to treat a problem, you have to diagnose
it correctly,'' Sisto said after Mrs. Clinton's half-hour speech.
``And she clearly gave the right diagnosis.''
</P>
<P>
   Others in the audience were unconvinced. ``She didn't really say
anything that was going to happen,'' said Diane Osika, chief
executive officer of the Tri-County Memorial Hospital in Gowanda.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton ``said what needs to be done, and I suppose that's
good, but everybody talks about it _ what are you going to do about
it?'' Osika said.
</P>
<P>
   The event in front of the health association _ and again later
for the state's Nurses Association in Lake Placid _ marked one of
Mrs. Clinton's first major policy speeches on the hustings. She
still has not said for sure if she would run for the seat being
vacated by retiring Democratic Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the first lady is ever edging toward a full-fledged run,
and has scheduled meetings with labor leaders and Democratic
officials around the state throughout the weekend and into next
week. She also avoided a potential pitfall Thursday when the White
House announced the Clintons have refinanced a $1.3 million house
loan through a Pittsburgh bank instead of through Democratic
fund-raiser Terry McAuliffe.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the Clintons chose to refinance the loan for the
Westchester County house through PNC Mortgage of America, campaign
spokesman Howard Wolfson said: ``I gather it was the best deal for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady was criticized for accepting the house loan from
McAuliffe.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's likely Republican opponent, New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, also has not said whether he would run for the Senate.
But while Giuliani has not ``in so many words'' actually confided
his candidacy, ``I have every reason to believe he is and will be
running for the Senate and I would hope he wins,'' Gov. George
Pataki, a Republican, said Thursday. ``If he does, he will be a
great senator for New York.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
