<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTEBOOK BUYERS GET TO DIFFERENTIATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the beginning, most notebook computers looked alike. They all
looked like, well, notebooks. That's changing.
</P>
<P>
   Different users want different things. Some want as little
weight and size as possible, and are willing to sacrifice some
capabilities. Others don't care about heft, preferring something
that can functionally replace a desktop PC. And still others just
want something that looks cool.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at two very different machines that serve the far
ends of the notebook spectrum, showing just how wide a range there
is in portable PC design.
</P>
<P>
   _ iBook, $1,599, Apple Computer: If style and the Macintosh OS
is at the top of your consideration list when shopping for a
portable computer, then this is your obvious choice. Apple has
crafted a slick notebook version of its popular iMac consumer line.
However, iBook is not as good a portable as the iMac is a desktop.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, the iBook has a gotta-have-it design. With its
rounded corners, translucent white-and-blue or white-and-orange
plastic, your choice _ it's an eye-catcher. It also has a nice
feel: The colored portion is rubberized, and the white part has a
slightly textured feel.
</P>
<P>
   It's fairly heavy and bulky
</P>
<P>
   Opening the case, you'll find a wide expanse of plastic
surrounding both the 12.1-inch active matrix screen and the
keyboard. In fact, it almost seems like wasted space that could
have been put to better use.
</P>
<P>
   For example, while the letter and number keys are full-sized,
the function and cursor keys are about a third the size of standard
keys. The cursor keys also are jammed up against the right shift
key, so that it's too easy to hit the up-cursor key when trying to
hit the shift. This is a common design flaw in a lot of notebook
keyboards and Apple, with its design savvy, should know better.
</P>
<P>
   The keyboard has an excellent, springy feel. The pointing device
is a touch pad that's nicely responsive, though as with all Apple
products, it has only one click button. Bummer.
</P>
<P>
   The screen has a gorgeous look to it, though it's limited to
800-by-600 pixels of resolution. This doesn't bother me, but
apparently some Apple loyalists are disturbed that it's not capable
of 1,024-by-768.
</P>
<P>
   The iBook comes with a 300-megahertz PowerPC G3 chip, a
3.2-gigabyte hard drive, a 24X CD-ROM drive, a 56K fax modem and
just 32 megabytes of memory. Unfortunately, the portable is not
available with more memory at retail or from Apple's Web site.
You'll have to buy it from a third party and either have it
installed or do it yourself. And you'll want that extra memory _
the iBook in its standard configuration suffers from sluggishness
if you have more than one application running at a time. If you buy
one, spend the extra bucks to bump it up to at least 64 MB.
</P>
<P>
   The iBook comes with a single Universal Serial Bus port for
connecting peripherals _ owners of older devices will either have
to find adapters or get new printers, scanners, etc. _ and an
Ethernet port capable of connecting to a network at speeds of up to
100 megabits a second.
</P>
<P>
   The iBook also is capable of doing wireless networking at speeds
up to 11 megabits a second using a base station called an AirPort
and a card that installs in a slot in the lid. However, Apple
didn't have one available for me to test.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, I like the iBook, but Apple needs to tweak the design
and make adding memory easier. You may want to wait for iBook 2.0.
</P>
<P>
   _ Armada M300, $1,999, Compaq Computer Corp.: While its
competitors explored, expanded and developed the ``ultra-portable''
notebook category, Compaq has stayed on the sidelines, watching and
waiting. Its designers saw what worked in an ultra-portable, and
more importantly, what didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that Compaq's first entry into this market is
essentially a second-generation model. The business-oriented Armada
M300 (and its consumer twin, the Presario 305) avoids the mistakes
made in designs from other companies. As a result, it's the best
ultraportable I've seen this year.
</P>
<P>
   The M300 I tried came with a 333-MHz Intel Celeron processor; 64
MB of memory; a 4-GB hard drive; an 11.3-inch active-matrix screen;
a single PC card slot; and a 56K fax modem. It comes with an
external floppy drive and a full set of ports on the back, which is
a plus. Many ultraportables require you to have an external port
adapter to connect serial or parallel devices or external monitors.
</P>
<P>
   At just under an inch thick, the case is not as thin as some
other models in this category, but it feels a lot sturdier. It
weighs in at 3.3 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The keyboard, while slightly undersized, is excellent. Compaq
pulls the cursor keys down a bit from the shift key, so you're less
apt to hit them by mistake. There's even room for a wrist-rest. The
touchpad is quite responsive and very customizable.
</P>
<P>
   The 11.3-inch screen is bigger than most ultraportables, which
usually have 10-inch screens, and has a bright, crisp look. It's
capable of resolutions of up to 800-by-600.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq has attached the battery as a cylinder on the back of the
computer, which can be pulled down to angle the keyboard. It's a
small battery, though, and the best I could do with it was just
over two hours of power.
</P>
<P>
   The $1,999 base price does not include a multimedia base that
snaps on the bottom of the M300, giving it CD-ROM ($349) or DVD-ROM
($499) capabilities. The base also adds an additional PC card slot
and a place for another battery.
</P>
<P>
   The main difference between the M300 and the Presario 305 is
that the latter comes with programmable buttons for launching
software or surfing the Web. It also comes with the CD-ROM version
of the multimedia base, and sells for $2,199.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
