<HEADER>
A7957 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-US-HNS &LR;      10-15 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-US-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTWITHSTANDING `DIE HARD,' PROOF THAT BRUCE WILLIS CAN ACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Attention, all ye who loathe Bruce Willis; all ye who mock, nay,
spit upon his career; all ye who curse the wretched earth from
which he rudely sprang; all ye who loathe, condemn, execrate,
spindle, fold and mutilate the celluloid upon which his films are
based; all ye who wince (alas!) at the ``Die Hard'' movies and
shrink (alack!) at the thought of ``Moonlighting.'' Get over it.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to make amends. It's time to give the guy a break.
It's time to look old Bruce in the eye _ which, by the way, has not
been squinting lately _ and smile back at that close-lipped little
half-grin that's annoyed you for the last 14 years, seven months
and 12 days.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to admit to him, yourself and the waiting world that
Bruce Willis Is A Really Good Actor. A Really, Really Good Actor.
In fact, Bruce Willis is such a Really Good Actor that his newest
movie will (are you ready for this?) make you forget
``Armageddon''!
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, Bruce made some progress in this regard earlier
this year, playing the grim, good-hearted shrink to Haley Joel
Osment's haunted kid in ``The Sixth Sense.'' But if that film
showed what Willis can do with understatement, this one _ a
touching, funny charmer called ``The Story of Us'' _ gives us an
actor so blithely gifted that it's hard to imagine anyone else in
the part. Willis has called this the best work he's ever done, and
he may be right. He's superb.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Rob Reiner (``The American President,'' ``Ghosts of
Mississippi''), ``The Story of Us'' concerns the marital woes of
one Ben Jordan (Willis) and his wife, Katie (Michelle Pfeiffer).
Ben and Katie have been hitched for 15 years, a union that produced
two charming children and one SUV, but lately they've been
teetering on the edge of divorce. Katie wishes Ben were more of a
responsible grown-up, while Ben wishes Katie were still that
fun-loving gal who donned a pith helmet with a twirling siren.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am just sick and tired of having to be the designated driver
of this marriage!'' screams she. ``Is it all my fault you turned
into your $&AMP;!! mother?'' howls he.
</P>
<P>
   Ben and Katie yell a lot, but they also flash back to happier
times _ to babies, laughter, tooth fairies, George Bush, sex _ and
go out to dinner with amusing friends. Among them are Paul Reiser
(``the Ten Commandments were probably easier to stick to when you
dropped dead at 35''), Rita Wilson (who helpfully, and hilariously,
explains why women won't have sex while angry) and Reiner himself
(whose dissertation on truth and derrieres yields unexpected
results).
</P>
<P>
   All of them are having way too much fun for woebegone
pessimists, but who cares. ``The Story of Us'' is breezy about
everything; even its hardest, blackest,
this-marriage-is-a-hopeless-pit-of-gloom moments are leavened by
Reiner's unfailingly light touch.
</P>
<P>
   The film's most extraordinary scene _ better than anything he's
done in the last 10 years _ is a bitter bedroom sequence in which
Katie and Ben are joined by their parents. Not their actual
parents, mind you, but the psychic busybodies who crowd the
marriage bed of any bickering couple: in this case, Tom Poston,
Betty White, Red Buttons and Jayne Meadows. The scene is quippy and
painful, bizarre and defiantly honest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Story of Us'' was written (and co-produced, along with
Reiner) by Alan Zweibel and Jessie Nelson, who wrote the
screenplays for ``Dragnet'' and ``Stepmom,'' respectively, and here
prove that redemption is always possible. Despite a pat ending,
it's a smart script _ smart in a breathless, cram-it-in kind of
way, like a vast game of Hollywood speed chess. So many words
tumble so humorously out of so many mouths that sometimes, the
sheer verbal heft of it becomes oppressive; it cries out for the
rewind button.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Reiner's cast rises to the occasion, yielding the sort of
comic-orgasmic crescendos that Meg Ryan made famous in ``When Harry
Met Sally.'' Pfeiffer is brittle and vulnerable and translucent as
usual, and her chemistry with Willis is both believable and tart.
Perhaps it's believable because it's tart _ most marriages, even
the good ones, aren't a perfect fit.
</P>
<P>
   Although it would be simple to attribute Willis' performance to
parallels with his own failed marriage, there's more to it than
that. He seems liberated, sprung free; there's a looseness in his
joints that wasn't there before. ``I've always been big on happy
endings,'' he says, professing optimism. And you know, we believe
him.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
