<HEADER>
A7960 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-MUSIC-LUSCIOUS-HNS &LR;      10-15 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-LUSCIOUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ELECTRIC' LIVE SHOW IS TRIO'S PASSION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOEY GUERRA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world of pop radio can be baffling and unpredictable. Just
ask the New York-based trio Luscious Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the group _ lead singer Jill Cunniff, guitarist Gabby
Glaser and drummer Kate Schellenbach (keyboardist Vivian Trimble
left last year to pursue other musical ventures) _ hovered just
under the mainstream radar. The band won critical praise and a
small circle of devoted fans with its debut EP, 1992's ``In Search
of Manny,'' and its first full-length album, 1994's ``Natural
Ingredients.''
</P>
<P>
   It was all taken up a notch with 1996's ``Fever In Fever Out.''
The trick? ``Naked Eye,'' an impossibly catchy single that was a
groovy break from the more somber tone of the album. The single
went Top 40 and earned ``Fever In Fever Out'' a gold record for
selling 500,000 copies. More fans, relentless touring and a
well-received Gap Christmas commercial soon followed.
</P>
<P>
   The stage seemed set for ``Electric Honey,'' the group's third
and best album, to make an even bigger splash when it was released
during the summer. It boasts good dance beats, energetic charm and
impressive guests, including Emmylou Harris and Debbie Harry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we definitely agreed that we wanted to do something a
little bit more upbeat than `Fever In Fever Out,''' Schellenbach
said from her home in New York. ``Not to say that was a suicide
record, but it definitely had a dark side, and we kinda were
exploring a lighter side on this album.''
</P>
<P>
   Throw in ``Ladyfingers,'' a killer first single, and you have a
flawless pop dessert destined for the upper echelons of Billboard's
charts, right?
</P>
<P>
   Not quite.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Ladyfingers'' is still being pushed to radio
stations, and ``Electric Honey'' has continued to sell modestly
(thanks to the group's constant touring), Luscious Jackson's hip
quotient seems to have cooled a bit, at least on radio.
Schellenbach wonders why.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty funny,'' Schellenbach said of today's music.
``Obviously, it's not allowing a whole lot of room for us on the
radio at this point. There's a lot of pop _ super-duper, kinda
mindless pop. There's a lot of hard rock-rap. We're so perplexed by
radio and MTV and all that stuff. We really do all the work that we
think it takes. We put on a good show; we do a good album; we do
all the interviews. It's kinda out of our hands at this point what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of focusing on what's not being accomplished, however,
Luscious Jackson continues to focus on its original goals and the
residual rewards earned from the success of ``Naked Eye,''
including a spot on last summer's Lilith Fair tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never really had illusions _ or delusions _ of being rich
and famous,'' Schellenbach said. ``That's never been our goal. It's
more like making records, having access to recording and
performing.''
</P>
<P>
   Schellenbach had one of her personal dreams realized when she
was invited to play drums for pop icon Blondie. Members Harry and
Chris Stein were impressed with Schellenbach's playing when they
saw her at a Blondie tribute in New York. A month later,
Schellenbach was called in when Blondie drummer Clem Burke couldn't
make a show.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an absolute dream come true. They were my first band
that I was obsessed with as, like, a 13-year-old. I mean really,''
Schellenbach said. ``They were like, `We know you know the songs.'
The most thrilling part about it was actually the rehearsal.
Playing these songs and having Debbie Harry singing and dancing in
front of me. When we played, it was like a blur.''
</P>
<P>
   Collaboration has always been an integral part of the Luscious
Jackson experience. Schellenbach played drums for the Beastie Boys
in the early '80s, and Luscious Jackson was the first group signed
to the Beasties' Grand Royal label in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Schellenbach and her drums turned up on two
tracks on the Indigo Girls' new album, ``Come On Now Social,'' and
Cunniff co-wrote a song with Harris for her ``Western Wall''
project with Linda Ronstadt.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the things that we have accomplished, actually, have
been connections to other musicians that we've really respected and
been able to collaborate with,'' Schellenbach said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for us, being asked to do Lilith Fair, was like an
affirmation of how far we've come as a band. Being able to chat and
jam with Sheryl Crow _ it's really cool. That means more to us, I
think, than having our faces on the cover of a magazine. It keeps
you on your toes. If you end up playing the same songs every night
with the same band, you're not really challenging yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   The group was faced with a hurdle in April 1998, when Trimble
left to tackle other projects, including a solo album, a
collaboration with Jon Spencer Blues Explosion drummer Russell
Simins and a band (with Breeders member Josephine Wiggs) called the
Dusty Trails.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had been coming for a while,'' Schellenbach said of the
split. ``As friends, you don't wanna force your friends to do
things that make them unhappy. We knew that we could regroup
without her. She just really didn't wanna spend that kind of time
away from home, and she wanted to really work on her music. It's
really cool. We're still close; we're still friends; we still
collaborate.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Luscious Jackson is focusing on its live show, which
the trio aims to improve with each tour. They also give much of the
credit to fans for an always-unpredictable outing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We maintain that we have one of the best audiences around _
the most diverse, the most energetic _ and fun-loving, good-looking
and stylish and good dancers. It really makes a difference,''
Schellenbach said. ``One of our missions is really bringing people
together and proving that people don't just listen to Korn. They
respect us; they respect each other.''
</P>
<P>
   With that confidence, who needs a Backstreet-size radio hit,
anyway? Certainly not these ladies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
