<SLUG> BC-EYE-SURGERY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LASER SURGERY COMPANY CUTS PRICES TO COMPETE WITH CANADIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ LCA Vision Center is cutting the price of its
laser eye surgery in California and Maryland in response to growing
competition from cheaper Canadian providers.
</P>
<P>
   The popular surgery to correct nearsightedness costs about
$5,000 for both eyes. The same operation in Montreal costs $1,600.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Wilson, the president of LCA, acknowledged that stiff
competition by Canadian companies is cutting into business at the
Cincinnati-based company, the third largest provider of laser eye
surgery in North America.
</P>
<P>
   LCA operates 21 clinics in the United States and Canada. LCA
provides LASIK, the most popular type of laser eye surgery.
</P>
<P>
   One reason Americans are going to clinics in Canada is the
exchange rate. For every U.S. dollar, a visitor to Canada gets
$1.48.
</P>
<P>
   Another is a pricing structure in the United States that adds to
the expense, including payments to referring optometrists, higher
surgeon salaries and a $260 premium that physicians must pay to the
laser manufacturer every time they use the machine.
</P>
<P>
   LCA has already taken some steps to lower its price to deal with
its two main North American competitors based in Canada: TLC in
Toronto and Lasik Vision Corp. in Vancouver, British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   In Toronto, where Lasik Vision Corp. charges a total of $1,600
for both eyes, LCA offers a price of about $2,025, less than half
of what it charges in the United States. The company has also given
its Toronto surgeons the flexibility to lower the price further in
individual negotiations with patients.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, however, the company has created a new
discount subsidiary, called LasikPlus. At two new locations in
Maryland and four in California, the company is charging $2,995 in
hopes of attracting more customers, especially from TLC, its
largest competitor in those markets.
</P>
<P>
   LCA has claimed it can perform the surgery at that price because
it is employing its own physicians. In almost all its other
centers, LCA provides only the facilities and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said it was too soon to determine whether those same
prices could be applied at other centers.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Henderson, the president of Lasik Vision Corp., said
such a dual pricing system only reinforces that many American
consumers are being overcharged. ``I do think it's strange that a
company markets its product at two different prices,'' he said from
his Vancouver office.
</P>
<P>
   Lasik Vision also is trying to bring lower prices to the United
States by opening its first U.S. clinic in Bellevue, Wash. The
company has yet to get federal approval to operate its laser there
and has so far used the office to take care of pre- and
post-operative visits for its Vancouver clinic, located just over
the border.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Canadian surgeons have more experience with laser
eye surgery than their U.S. counterparts because they have been
doing it longer. The procedure was approved in Canada several years
earlier than the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
