<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8007 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-CLEARINGCLUTTER-TEX     10-15 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEARINGCLUTTER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEEP AWAY THE MESS TO UNCOVER YOUR TRUE SELF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GAILE ROBINSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you toss all your old magazines, catalogs and newspapers,
pick up your clothes, clean all your closets and attend to all your
stacks of paperwork, Michelle Passoff swears you will find
enlightenment.
</P>
<P>
   Passoff, author of ``Lighten Up, Free Yourself From Clutter''
(Harper Perennial, $13 softcover), is here to bring order,
fulfillment and self realization, if you'll only clean up your
life. She maintains that we hang on to memories and they slowly
suffocate our dreams: ``Clutter cleaning is a way to discover who
you really are.''
</P>
<P>
   Passoff has a theory about cleaning that borders on the
metaphysical.
</P>
<P>
   After almost a decade of helping people organize and eliminate
their stuff, she has witnessed the positive effects of clutter
removal. Productivity, effectiveness, creativity, vitality and
peace of mind come with excising the extraneous.
</P>
<P>
   Say ``Hallelujah.''
</P>
<P>
   Passoff administers to people who are handicapped physically and
mentally by their clutter. Too often, she says, these people are
building monuments to their past that impede their progress. Their
insistence on hanging on to every scrap of paper and every article
of clothing can literally trap them in their physical surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   There is a difference between mess and clutter, Passoff
cautions. A mess is when you try on everything in your closet and
leave it in rejected puddles on the bedroom floor.
</P>
<P>
   Clutter is everything from your closet from the past 10 years
plus all the paperwork needed for your 1997 taxes spread over the
bedroom floor. It is so overwhelming you think nothing of dropping
a layer of 1998 tax receipts on the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``Later,'' that's your mantra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clothes keepers, makeup hoarders, paper stackers are all the
same,'' says Passoff. By the time they come to her, they are
usually at a critical mass. ``One time it was the collapse of a
coat rack. The husband threatened to divorce his wife if she didn't
do something about her collection of stuff.'' Another client came
to Passoff when her bedroom floor became a solid field of laundry
baskets stuffed with cosmetics.
</P>
<P>
   Passoff says the prompting situation could be a threat, the loss
of a job, the coming of a child. The clutterers seek internal
peace, but are burdened with excuses that are the road bumps on the
path to their self-realization.
</P>
<P>
   Passoff says not being organized is the excuse many people use
to keep them from realizing their dreams. They don't entertain
because they are embarrassed by their surroundings. They don't move
because they can't imagine the organizational nightmare it would
take.
</P>
<P>
   Passoff says: ``My focus is not on being neat and tidy. It's
having a life you love, having one that you participate in fully.
And that can happen if your dreams are out there in the world, if
they are tangible and not a figment of the imagination.'' They
cannot be out there if they are buried under a layer of trash.
</P>
<P>
   Her process for change begins with a large vision accomplished
by small organizational steps. Clutter removal requires clipping
and filing, hanging and tossing. For example:
</P>
<P>
   She quickly reallocates the contents of the kitchen junk drawer
_ the fast-food fliers are filed with paperwork in a file cabinet,
under ``food'' with ``recipes.'' Tools and screws are placed in the
tool chest with the other household hardware. Pens, pencils, rubber
bands and the like are relegated to the desk organizer. In almost
an instant, Passoff has freed a kitchen drawer and nothing was
thrown away, it was reorganized.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes time to toss, Passoff suggests that every item be
given at least 20 seconds of consideration. A brief, but expedient
mourning period. Ask yourself, ``Is this something that is of
benefit to me and what I want?'' If it is a nagging guilt brick,
attend to it, now. Answer that letter, write that thank-you note.
File that receipt, pay that bill. Now move on.
</P>
<P>
   The only clothes in your closet should be ones you will wear
this season. Every piece should be in good repair and clean.
Out-of-season clothes, the ones that fit and are in good repair,
should be stored. Anything that is too small, torn, stained or
hasn't been worn in the past two years should be in a trash bag on
its way to the trash, recycling shop or charity bin.
</P>
<P>
   Passoff is cruel. ``Everything that is important must have a
specific place. If it doesn't have a specific place, it's trash.''
She says to make a place to process the incoming paperwork, one
with a wastebasket and file cabinet nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three quarters of the piles of papers on desk and table tops
are things that have yet to be tossed. They are trash,'' she says
with the conviction of someone who lives in a tiny Manhattan
apartment yet still has room in her closets.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   INFO BOX
</P>
<P>
   Clutter removal requires clipping and filing and hanging and
tossing. Passoff has a thorough system. It's in her book, ``Lighten
Up! Free Yourself From Clutter,'' and will be the topic of her
three-hour chalk talk at FunEd Learning Center, 7 p.m. Thursday
night in Dallas, 13608 Midway Road. Tickets are $32, plus a $6
registration fee if you have never been to a Fun/Ed program before.
To make reservations or register, call (972) 960-2666. For more
information visit Passoff's Web site, www.freefromclutter.com.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
