<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8012 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX     10-15 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDY TOOL SWEEPS ICONS OFF DESKTOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: So, here's your chance to show your readers
what an idiot I am. Those kind people at Microsoft were nice enough
to put Network Neighborhood, Inbox and My Briefcase icons on my
desktop. I only use my computer for fun and want to take them off
my desktop but not delete the programs. Can it be done?
</P>
<P>
   _ Desktop Dumbbell
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DD: I'm hurt. Kindly ol' Doc Bombay would never think of
humiliating a reader. Well, not unless you did something really
stupid. This time, it's the doofuses at Microsoft who are to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they thought that everyone would love having all those
mystery icons taking up desktop space. Network Neighborhood shows
up if you use any sort of networking tool, even though you're not
on a network. Inbox is part of Windows Messaging, which handles
network and Internet e-mail. Briefcase is some bright guy's idea
that assumes you're actually organized enough to keep data files on
your laptop synchronized with what's on your other computer. If you
have one, that is. I'd bet most normal users could dump all three.
</P>
<P>
   Well, you could just dump them in the Recycle Bin, but if you
someday have an inexplicable need to use one of them, you'll be out
of luck. There's a tool that lets you ``hide'' them, though, but
you're going to have to do some legwork to find it.
</P>
<P>
   It's called TweakUI, and it's one of the handiest tools you can
have for taming Windows. It hides those icons, fine-tunes the user
interface and clears the browser history so your wife won't find
out you've been visiting the Anna Nicole Smith home page again.
Naturally, Microsoft has stopped making it easily available. Some
people think that's because Microsoft doesn't want to support what
is essentially freeware cobbled together by software engineers
whose ideas got left out of the original Windows interface. I think
Microsoft just wants to show us who's boss.
</P>
<P>
   If you have the second edition of Win98, which is what you find
on almost all new PCs, you'll have to find somebody with an old
Windows 98 CD. Look in the Tools folder, then Reskit, then
Powertoy. Please follow the instructions in the folder. If you
cannot do that, you shouldn't be messing with any settings. You
should probably put the newspaper down, too, before you get a paper
cut.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, you can still find the Win95 version on Microsoft's
Web site (www.microsoft.com/windows95//j downloads). Of course,
Microsoft doesn't officially support that one either. Look,
Microsoft, we don't care if you support the thing or not. Just put
it where we can find it, because it happens to be the handiest
thing to come out of the Pacific Northwest since wood.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: My horror story with America Online: My
31-year-old son passed away unexpectedly. After the funeral, we
moved everything out of his apartment before the end of the month _
turning off the utilities and etc. I called to cancel all credit
cards. When I called to cancel AOL, I was told there was ``no way''
I could cancel the service without sending a death certificate.
Since there was no credit card or phone anymore, I told them where
they could stick their service. I was so very upset that I threw
the phone across the room.
</P>
<P>
   _ Another Dissatisfied Customer
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DISS: And I used to think the people at Microsoft were the
bad guys. A lot of readers have said the only sure way to dump AOL
_ if it won't stop billing you after cancellation _ is to tell your
credit card company to stop paying it. That, or you can wait on
infinity hold for a service rep until you're ready for a death
certificate, and even that's no guarantee AOL will stop.
</P>
<P>
   (Reach Dr. Emilio Bombay at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com, via
snail-mail at Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101, or fax: (817) 390-7257. In real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael
Gerst, editorial systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1430EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
