<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8013 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     10-15 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S ONLY ONE PARENT WHO ALWAYS GETS IT RIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We all like to think we're good at parenting.
</P>
<P>
   I know I do. But there's nothing like disciplining your child to
make you second-guess yourself. It's times like those when I wish I
were Solomon or even God. For example, let me share a talk I had
recently with my youngest daughter, Asha.
</P>
<P>
   Asha is 8, and like most little girls her age doesn't take well
to being told no, as in, ``No, you can't spend the night at
Lindsey's,'' or ``No, I can't afford to buy you a baby grand,'' or
``No, I can't leave work to take you shopping.''
</P>
<P>
   You get the picture?
</P>
<P>
   If saying ``no'' seems to come easily and frequently for me, you
haven't heard Asha's sweet, pitiful plea on my voice mail. ``Mama,
this is your baby, Asha. Call me back, I have to ask you something.
I know you're going to say no, but call me back. I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a moment like this when you understand what your parents
meant when they said, ``This will hurt me more than it will you.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying ``no'' is sometimes like having food go down the wrong
way.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, no amount of explaining will do for Asha.
Inevitably, she folds her arms, pushes her lips out as far as they
can go and storms off. If we're home, she goes to her room and
slams the door. If we're in the car or a store, her lips swell and
her eyelids open and close until the tears flow.
</P>
<P>
   I wish I could cry on cue like that.
</P>
<P>
   I've scolded Asha about her behavior a million times. She
apologizes and responds exactly the same way the next time the word
``no'' forces itself into our conversation.
</P>
<P>
   One day recently, she called me again at work and asked for
Pokemon cards. I told her ``no.'' Determined to nip this little
problem in the bud, I told her that I don't like the way she
responds when she doesn't get what she wants. I told her that maybe
if she can change her behavior by the end of the week, we can buy
Pokemon cards, even though I'm having trouble pronouncing Pokemon.
</P>
<P>
   I feel bittersweet but I think this might work because Asha
hasn't slammed the phone down, hasn't run to her room or acted cold
toward me.
</P>
<P>
   In the most pitiful voice I've ever heard, she said: ``That's
how God made me and I really can't help it. I told (God), I'll try
to be a better girl about my attitude and my temper. But Mama, my
blood pressure gets so built up and I get sooo mad!''
</P>
<P>
   It took everything in me to keep from laughing. I was about to
burst, but there was such sincerity in Asha's voice, I couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing I could say was, ``Well, let's see how you do the
rest of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   After hanging up the phone, I couldn't help but wonder whether I
did the right thing. I reminded myself of all the times I've
excused my behavior with, ``God made me that way,'' but also
reminded myself that God disciplines me anyway. And I remain
punished until I get it right.
</P>
<P>
   I told myself that God is omniscient and perfect in his judgment
and that I'm not, that maybe I didn't handle this the right way. By
week's end, the tally against Asha had mounted. I couldn't buy her
the Pokemon cards.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks have passed, and I notice her struggling to
respond in the right way. We're in the middle of something and she
asks, ``Mama, do you think my attitude is getting better?''
</P>
<P>
   I tell her yes. I notice she's trying.
</P>
<P>
   I hope God's noticing that I am, too.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7791, or e-mail:
gstaples(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
