<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HAPPY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIE BRINGS NO SMILES TO THE REAL HAPPY, TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAPPY, Texas _ Loraine McDonald could barely believe it when she
opened a letter from her daughter and there was a copy of an
article found on the Internet about the new movie ``Happy, Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald left the Happy post office that day and walked up the
red-brick streets of this Texas Panhandle town, past the vacant
buildings on Main Street to the little white building with the
handmade ``City Hall'' sign. The city worker got the copy machine
humming and then set out to distribute the article that the
650-or-so residents of Happy would consider mostly bad news.
</P>
<P>
   She brought copies to the gas station, bank and two grain
elevators, and then she stopped, because there really isn't
anywhere else to go in Happy. There are five churches and two
schools, but McDonald was not going to bring a review of the
slapstick PG-13 rated film to houses of worship and education.
</P>
<P>
   The Miramax film ``Happy, Texas'' opened this week and residents
of the real Happy, Texas, aren't happy about it at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to embarrass us,'' McDonald says.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of folks in Happy say they won't go see the film, not even
when it opens in Amarillo, 35 miles north, on a road so flat and
straight it's like driving across a table top.
</P>
<P>
   ``Happy, Texas'' features two escaped convicts who hide out in a
small Texas town where they are mistaken for gay beauty pageant
directors who have come to revive ``The Little Miss Fresh
Squeezed'' pageant. The plot reveals the small-town sheriff's
sexual identity crisis and plays on a host of Texas stereotypes _
from accents to armadillos.
</P>
<P>
   Happy has no ``town sheriff.'' For that matter, Happy has no
movie theater, doctor, grocery store or police department. Happy
has a convenience store, some feedlots, two grain elevators and The
First State Bank of Happy.
</P>
<P>
   Happy Senior High has a football team _ the Happy Cowboys _ that
is having trouble rustling up enough players to field an 11-man
team.
</P>
<P>
   A long time ago, it had a newspaper, the Happy News, but that
folded decades ago, perhaps because of a lack of happy news.
</P>
<P>
   Happy sits along a 21-mile draw where spring water surfaces, a
fact that so delighted early cowboys they named it Happy Draw, from
which the town derives its name.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's co-writer, Ed Stone, told The Associated Press that
he once worked as a disc jockey in a small West Texas town. He
would hear about Happy's annual Happy Days, held the third weekend
in August every year, and he'd make fun of the Miss Happy, Junior
Miss Happy and Little Miss Happy selected to participate in area
parades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like most every small town in Texas, Happy's citizens were
just mad when it came to beauty pageants,'' Stone told the AP. ``As
a disc jockey from another part of the world, I'd sometimes go on
the air and poke a little fun at this obsession with pageants, and
you wouldn't believe the angry calls that came in.''
</P>
<P>
   Town administrators voted to allow the moviemakers to use the
town's name, said city secretary Patricia Sims, before they knew
the plot line or that the movie would be rated PG-13, which is a
parental warning for films with violence, strong language or
sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to go see movies back when Gary Cooper and Elizabeth
Taylor were around,'' McDonald says. ``I stopped. Now they are just
loud music and violence, and. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Sex.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to get anyone in Happy to talk about the gay
characters. Most of them just roll their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the movie will be just the opposite of what Happy is
about,'' says Judy Shipman, assistant vice president of the First
State Bank. ``Happy is a family place where everyone knows each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Shipman says she'd love to see a revival of the town that was
built on land donated by her great-grandfather, J.F. White. Antique
stores, maybe. A tea shop. Something to attract visitors.
</P>
<P>
   But some years ago, Interstate 27 bypassed Happy, and Shipman
said she thinks that ruined the town's chances for recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost a ghost town,'' McDonald says. Like most folks who
live here, she was born and raised in Happy, the daughter of
immigrants who came from Germany, mostly by way of the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came looking for the American Dream, and when they got
here they didn't really find it, but they stayed,'' McDonald says.
</P>
<P>
   Happy did have its heyday. McDonald recalls stories of cattle
drives that stopped nearby and cowboys who stayed at the now
long-closed hotel, sometimes for months while the cattle fattened.
</P>
<P>
   But fortunes change. Droughts come and cattle and feed prices
don't remain stable. Area farmers lost their ability to irrigate
after the water level dropped in the Ogalalla aquifer, says Michael
Schoenenberger, the city's water superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   And a lot of land fell fallow when the federal government
started paying farmers not to farm, he says.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, more and more buildings became vacant on Main
Street, and the population dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Happy's residents say they don't think it would have helped the
town economy even if William H. Macy and cast had camped on Main
Street to film the movie instead of on location in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where would they (filmmakers) have spent their money?''
McDonald says.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe now, however, a few tourists will come through Happy and
spend a little money. That would make the residents smile again in
a place whose slogan is, ``The Town Without a Frown.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
