<HEADER>
A8022 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-CHICAGO-HOPE-1STLD     10-15 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CHICAGO-HOPE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT BEGINS WITH AN `S' AND ENDS WITH A `T'? ASK CBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Complete writethru; fixes 4thgraf to clarify who produces
show, corrects spelling `Jack' sted `Jake,' makes other edits
thruout.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well, now it's hit the fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicago Hope'' broke new television ground Thursday night, not
with a striking story line or its major cast changes or new gore,
but with four little letters. I'll spot you the ``s'' and the
``h,'' but that's it.
</P>
<P>
   It happens.
</P>
<P>
   Just not on network television. At least until now.
</P>
<P>
   The producers of the show, Michael Pressman and Henry Bromell,
successfully lobbied to have the s-word included in the script. The
historic profanity was said by Dr. Jack McNeil (Mark Harmon) as he
talked to lawyers after a botched operation. ``S--- happens,''
McNeil said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole episode is about that,'' Bromell said Thursday.
``This is a story about a doctor who did everything right and
everything went wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Think for a minute: What do you say when this happens to you?
That's right, ``s--- happens.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to that line and thought, `You know what? I'm going to
fight for this,''' Bromell continued. ``To somewhat my surprise, I
won.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS was making it clear that this was not designed as a frontal
assault on language standards. ``The producers felt strongly the
line was important for artistic truthfulness,'' network spokesman
Chris Ender said Thursday. ``It's not a statement, it's not a sign,
it's not a symbol of things to come.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a word, a word many of us hear if not say every day. It's
only in the bizarre fantasy world of network television where the
majority of people say ``golly,'' ``shoot'' and ``dang-gummit.''
</P>
<P>
   Syndicated radio host Howard Stern Thursday morning vowed to
start using the s-word on the air if ``Chicago Hope'' (9 p.m.
Eastern, Thursdays) can get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   Stern also noted that many rock songs played on the radio are
full of curses. Howard is no longer the most shocking, and he also
has a point: What is the difference?
</P>
<P>
   Another question: If the word is ``artistically truthful'' in
this instance, certainly it is applicable in context in other
instances. So how can the network say this is a one-time-only deal?
</P>
<P>
   Over at ABC, Bromell said, you can bet Steven Bochco of ``NYPD
Blue'' is telling his network he is going the same route. At the
same time, Bromell said he dreads any possibility that profanity
becomes as commonplace on network television as it is in the
movies.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon's curse is not the first time profanity has been uttered
on television: Cable is replete with unbleeped bleeps. And anyone
watching a sports broadcast, especially one employing a sideline or
courtside microphone, does not have to be a world-class lip reader
to make out the curses of athletes.
</P>
<P>
   But never before has a network purposefully ventured this far
into the dirty-word territory in an entertainment show. And if you
had been taking bets which network would have been the first to do
so, you probably would have gotten 500-to-1 odds on CBS (as opposed
to 1-to-5 on Fox and even money on UPN).
</P>
<P>
   ``Needless to say there has been considerable debate about it,''
Ender said. ``We see it as an isolated incident. This doesn't
signal a change in standards at CBS. This won't happen on a weekly
basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, CBS was also the network to break a language
barrier earlier this decade. In 1990, the short-lived ``Uncle
Buck,'' a comedy based on the John Candy movie, made history in the
first of its few moments on the air when a young girl said ``you
suck.'' And there have been numerous other shows, most notably
``NYPD Blue'' on ABC, that have taken the concept of permissible
language and nudity on a network to the extreme. At least to what
was thought was the extreme.
</P>
<P>
   But Ender acknowledges the obvious: There is an acute double
standard between cable and the networks regarding content, one that
allows cable to go further in terms of language, violence and
nudity than over-the-air networks, which are governed by the
Federal Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   And as the networks lose viewers, and more people at home don't
make the distinction between cable and broadcast networks _ they
are all just channels coming through the box _ it's clear it's not
a fair fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a little bit of a double standard,'' Ender said.
``The press showers praise on `The Sopranos,' `Sex and the City'
and `South Park' (all cable shows) for pushing the envelope, but if
the network does this we get burned at the stake.''
</P>
<P>
   So should that double standard be eradicated? Should all walls
be taken down? ``I don't want to go there,'' Ender said.
</P>
<P>
   The networks are losing viewers to cable, the Internet and
elsewhere. And even staid CBS appears willing to test any and all
boundaries to try to get them back.
</P>
<P>
   It happens.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
