<SLUG> BC-POPULATION-WORLD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIGHT SPOT IS CITED ON POPULATION CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES RADIN 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 6 billionth human being on Earth, who by United Nations
estimates was born Tuesday, arrived nearly a year late _ one of an
increasing number of bright spots in the world population picture.
</P>
<P>
   Population control ``was an area of doom and gloom, and everyone
said nothing could be done,'' said Dr. Nafis Sadik, director of the
United Nations Population Fund, in an interview Thursday, ``and it
was not so.''
</P>
<P>
   The late arrival of the 6 billionth, she said, represented a
substantial slowing of the rate of population growth since the 1994
International Conference on Population and Development, in Cairo.
Based on demographic trends at the time, the 6 billion mark should
have been reached in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   At a population conference &UR;  &LR; Simmons College in Boston, where she
was keynote speaker, Sadik also said that, based on current trends,
the next 1 billion jump in global population will take 14 years _
two years longer than the previous rise of a billion, and another
sign of slowing rates of growth.
</P>
<P>
   Sadik, whose agency provides population-program assistance to
more than 140 countries and territories around the world, said
gains are being made mostly because women are gaining the power to
make their own reproductive decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys prior to the Cairo conference showed that people in all
regions of the world desired a family size lower than the usual
family size where they lived, she said, but lack of information,
lack of access to contraceptives, and a feeling among women that
they could not make reproductive decisions had contributed to
keeping family size up.
</P>
<P>
   Since the conference, she said, change has been dramatic:
Family-planning information and services are available in virtually
every country, use of contraceptives is up, and fertility is
generally down.
</P>
<P>
   After the conference, nations turned away from top-down efforts
at population control, such as China's one-child policy, and toward
better education and health care for girls and greater gender
equality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Top-down policies in India and China led to coercion,
poor-quality services, deceptions, draconian measures,'' Sadik
said. Now that such quotas, targets, and regulations have been
dropped, and governments are concentrating on providing information
and services, better results are being achieved, because ``most
women didn't want to have that many children.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort to control population is far from finished, she said,
noting that there are currently 1.04 billion people in the
15-to-24age group, and ``the decisions these young people make will
have a very big effect.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, ``I don't think there are any negative trends in
the developing world,'' Sadik said, adding that developed countries
that have problems with too-low birth rates might also benefit from
improving the situation of women. A case in point is Japan, where
the population is rapidly aging but young women are avoiding
child-bearing.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan ``women are totally responsible for bringing up the
children, and it is onerous,'' Sadik said. ``Not every child is a
success,'' and in Japan the mother is held responsible. Japan is
supplanting the United States as the broker of international
population agreements _ a result of faltering US financial support
for the UN and its programs, and of what she called the
preoccupation of the US Congress with abortion, which blocks
effective US participation in family planning efforts in the
developing world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
