<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 15:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8033 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-RESEARCH-BUDGET-BOS &LR;      10-15 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESEARCH-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTION IN CONGRESS BACKS UNIVERSITIES, HOSPITALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even as President Clinton and the Republican-led
Congress wrestle over proposed spending cuts, lawmakers are poised
to give a major budget boost for the second straight year to a
crucial sector of the New England economy: university and hospital
research.
</P>
<P>
   Little has been signed into law, but House and Senate
negotiators have already agreed to a 7 percent increase for the
National Science Foundation. Senators Thursday joined the House in
approving the Pentagon budget, which includes an 11.5 percent jump
in research spending, the biggest since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The National Institutes of Health, a crucial funding source for
Boston's cluster of medical research facilities, would see a 13
percent budget increase under Senate plans and at least 8.5 percent
under a House proposal. NASA, meanwhile, has sidestepped a stunning
10 percent cut approved by a House panel in July and will receive
slightly more money than the agency requested.
</P>
<P>
   These agencies send hundreds of millions of dollars each year to
local universities and hospital research programs, which are sure
to benefit if the budget increases become law. Moreover, momentum
is building in Congress to restore some of the Medicare payments to
hospitals and nursing homes that lawmakers cut in 1997. In
Massachusetts, hospitals complain that those cuts have made
providing health care a money-losing proposition.
</P>
<P>
   The expected increases stand in sharp contrast to this year's
budget-cutting rhetoric from Republican leaders. Without raising
taxes, they want to keep spending under the tight caps that
Congress and Clinton approved in 1997, and which are partly
responsible for producing this year's budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders have also made a point of saying they will
reject any plan that spends a penny of the Social Security surplus,
which they say should be reserved for the retirement program's
future funding needs.
</P>
<P>
   In the age of the Internet and continual medical breakthroughs,
however, even budget hawks are convinced that funding research is a
proper role for government. Leading Republicans, some of whom are
cancer survivors, have signed on to the general goal of doubling
medical research budgets within five years, which helped give the
NIH a remarkable 15 percent budget hike last year. Newt Gingrich,
the former House speaker, was a top advocate for other scientific
research.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could double the research budgets, and I'd be happy,''
said Kevin Hassett, an economist with the conservative American
Enterprise Institute, a Washington think tank. He compared research
funding to ``borrowing money at 7 percent and investing it at a 50
percent return,'' because it sparks new products, companies, and
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   That opinion is not universal. ``Most of the productive research
is done in private labs with private venture capital dollars,''
said Stephen Moore of the libertarian Cato Institute, another think
tank. ``A lot of Defense and Commerce department-related research
is just another name for corporate welfare, and it should be funded
privately.''
</P>
<P>
   While the funding boosts this year are still not certain,
research advocates are increasingly optimistic about their budget
prospects. Only three weeks ago, university leaders joined science
groups in a ``lobbying day'' in Washington designed to raise alarms
about potential cuts to research funding. The group, which included
Harvard University president Neil Rudenstine and Tufts University
president John DiBiaggio, said that New England stands to lose
about $1.5 billion in research and design money, about a third of
what it now receives, and that thousands of jobs would be
jeopardized.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Senate has approved budget increases in answer
to steep cuts passed by the House. And House leaders have proposed
a variety of accounting devices that could allow them to spend
money without violating the budget caps. Those include designating
some expenditures as ``emergency spending'' and deferring to future
years the cost of today's programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at a much better outcome than many of us would
have predicted,'' said George Leventhal, an analyst at the
Association of American Universities, which represents large
research centers, including Harvard and the Massachusetts Institute
of Technology. ``The final outcome has been quite good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly looks to me that it's not going to be the kind of
disaster that people feared a month or so ago,'' said David
Litster, vice president for research at MIT. ``The people in
Congress have recognized the importance of government support for
basic research and have done things to protect it.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest source of MIT's $400 million annual research budget
comes from private industry, Litster said, but the NIH, the
Pentagon, NASA and the Department of Energy each contribute between
15 percent and 20 percent, with the National Science Foundation
offering a bit less.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, key Republican lawmakers have begun pushing
for some modest relief for hospitals and other health care
providers, who have been complaining about Medicare cuts that
Congress approved two years ago. The cuts were designed to help put
the federal budget in surplus, but hospitals in Boston and
elsewhere said they have turned out to be steeper than the
lawmakers intended.
</P>
<P>
   ``These cuts have a tremendous effect on the research side of
things, because it's in the hospitals that clinical trials go on,
and it's where they train people and do research,'' said Arthur
Ullian of Boston, who leads a task force on biomedical research.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Bill Thomas, a California Republican who leads
the House subcommittee on Medicare, has proposed giving $9.4
billion back to health care providers over five years, and for the
White House to make administrative changes worth another $5.6
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Senator William Roth Jr., the Delaware Republican who leads the
Senate Finance Committee, would spend slightly more money and
devote more of it to hospitals. A bill cosponsored by Senator
Edward Kennedy would give hospitals even more.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Hospital Association Thursday said that the
House plan would restore $160 million of the $1.7 billion in cuts
to Massachusetts hospitals that Congress approved for the years
1998 through 2003. Roth's Senate plan would restore about $200
million.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said the proposals ``show that bipartisan momentum is
building to help hard-pressed teaching hospitals, nursing homes,
home health agencies'' and other providers. ``The issue now is not
whether relief will be enacted, but whether it will be adequate to
undo the damage,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
