A8034 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-15 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSING A CHANCE   FOR A SAFER WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was never this bad.
</P>
<P>
   Not during the first 99 years of the 20th century. Not till the
very last year of the bloodiest, weapons-drenched,
cordite-stenched, violence-saturated century has the Congress of
the United States behaved in such awkward, backward, retrograde
fashion. The Republican majority's rejection of the nuclear test
ban treaty marks the century's low point.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Senate rejected a treaty was 80 years ago,
when Woodrow Wilson was rebuffed on the Versailles Treaty, and we
wound up with World War II after fighting and winning the War to
End All Wars.
</P>
<P>
   Not during the do-nothing years of the first half of the
Depression, or the worst of the isolationist years of the late
'30s, or the craven Red Scare pandering of the '50s, or the '60s
collective cowardice that gave us 55,000 slain GIs in Vietnam, has
a Congress been so far off the path of progress.
</P>
<P>
   The century ends with America's voters bathed in apathy and
cynicism because of the poison-the-well style of politics in vogue
in Washington. This is part of the reason why most people no longer
bother to vote. Petty, vengeful, small-minded and ultimately
inconsequential are all suitable adjectives for this Kollection of
Klucks and Klaghorns currently reigning in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   United only by their bilious hatred of President Clinton, and
their dependence on the corrupt flow of campaign contributions from
well-heeled lobbyists, the minority-of-a-majority that rules the US
Senate and clings precariously to a miniscule edge in the US House
has brought effective national government to a standstill.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-line right-wingers dictate terms to the GOP leadership in
both branches. But not till Wednesday night's rejection of the
nuclear test ban treaty has Congress taken a step that so endangers
the national security of the rest of us. It crystallized the
bloody-mindedness of the Republican majority in this impeachment
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Under the whip hand of Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, an
unctuous right-wing Mississippian whose power rests in the
methodical harvest of tens of millions of dollars of soft money
from corporate influence-buyers, this Senate has repeatedly impeded
the progress of American civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Skewering the nuclear test ban treaty on the heels of the
rambunctuous Pakistani military's seizure of that country's nuclear
arsenal sent the arms control movement back a decade or more. This
may be the most irresponsible of all the Senate's actions under
Lott's small-minded and vindictive leadership.
</P>
<P>
   He has masterminded the refusal of the Senate to vote on
confirmation of more than 60 federal judges, imposing costly delay
as well as ideological blinders on the federal court system. He has
turned the Pentagon budget into a personal trough for his
Mississippi good old boys, ordering ships and planes the Defense
Department neither wants nor needs, to pay off his cronies. The
same week that Lott orchestrated the destruction of the world's
main hope for curbing nuclear proliferation, he yanked around the
congressional furniture to secure funds for a $1.5 billion aircraft
carrier to be built in his hometown shipyard.
</P>
<P>
   His name might as well be Senator Loot, honoring his propensity
for stripping the budget of foreign aid and UN dues in favor of
pork-drenched federal largesse for his homies. Lott has pandered to
the Neanderthal tendencies of Senate Foreign Relations Committee
Chairman Jesse Helms, who orchestrated the vengeful veto of William
Weld's ambassadorial nomination. A vestige of 19th century
isolationist, white supremacist America, Helms wields, by virtue of
the Senate's ridiculous rules and customs, a virtual veto over
American foreign policy on the eve of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   With the kind of graceless dismissal of world opinion for which
he is renowned, Helms mocked the last-minute pleas from the leaders
of Britain, France, and Germany that the Senate not destroy the
test ban framework. Sure, sneered Helms, and Tony Blair probably
told Clinton, ``and give my regards to Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Lott, Republicans have shut down the government, catered
to the rich, beggared federal programs for those without wealth or
power, and frustrated the Clinton administration at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   Playing footsie with the far right, Lott now dares to make the
world less safe from nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Most voters don't grasp the stakes. Prosperity and ennui dull
the voters' appetite for politics. There could be a mushroom-shaped
cloud over Pakistan or India, over the Middle East or the Korean
peninsula, because the US Senate let loose the dogs of nuclear war.
Clinton put it simply:
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, if we ever get a president that's against the test ban
treaty, which we may get _ I mean there are plenty of people out
there who say they are against it _ then I think you might as well
get ready for it. You'll have Russia testing, you'll have China
testing, you'll have India testing, you'll have Pakistan testing,
you'll have countries abandoning the nonproliferation treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to you, Senator Loot.
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
