<HEADLINE>
`YEAR ONE' HOLDS FEW SURPRISES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the nearsighted innocence of ``Freaks and Geeks'' to the
extraterrestrial angst of ``Roswell,'' teen alienation has many,
many faces this season. Friday night, youthful disquiet finds its
way into the Philadelphia police force, where a sensitive
19-year-old cop tries to balance a college girlfriend with some
bloody life-or-death crime situations. Called ``Ryan Caulfield:
Year One,'' the hourlong drama mixes coming-of-age lessons and
romantic distress with gunpoint face-offs and precinct-house
politics. Talk about teen beat.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, despite the inventive way it blends genres,
``Ryan Caulfield'' is familiar and predictable TV. The Fox Network
show never manages to rise above the tired rookie-cop cliches that
have been featured on just about every cop show that ever made it
to prime time. Shock at seeing his first dead body, the numbness of
veteran cops, the worrying mother, they're all here and more. And
of course Ryan can't take his eyes off of a female cop, a
conventional plot twist that will undoubtedly complicate his
romantic life in future episodes. There's little that you haven't
already seen many times in ``Ryan Caulfield,'' formerly titled
``The Badland'' after the dangerous Badlands neighborhood in which
it's set.
</P>
<P>
   What the show does have going for it is an appealing lead actor,
Sean Maher, who looks like a young Ray Liotta. Maher, a newcomer,
veers easily between confidence and fear, and he keeps the
earnestness that's written into his character from becoming
cloying. The show also gets an A for effort for trying to give its
supporting characters some distinction. Ryan's partner, played by
Michael Rispoli (he was Jackie Aprile on ``The Sopranos''), is an
awkward man who likes to sniff his own body odor and ask non
sequitur questions. And Ryan's co-worker, played by Roselyn
Sanchez, is disarming in her quiet honesty. Sanchez and Maher have
the potential to develop a sweet romantic chemistry, if they can
transcend the formulaic script that surrounds them.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's Metabolife
</P>
<P>
   report airs  &UR; tonight &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (FR)  &UR; Tonight &LR;  at 10 on ``20/20,'' ABC will air what it calls
``the report Metabolife is so afraid of.''
</P>
<P>
   The report is the outgrowth of a four-month investigation into
the diet pill's safety claims, and also contains a look at
Metabolife's founder, Michael Ellis. Metabolife recently spent $1.5
million to advertise a Web site on which it posted an unedited
videotape of an interview ABC conducted with Ellis. Last week,
Ellis told the Associated Press that he launched the preemptive
strike because he was afraid ABC wouldn't tell ``the whole story.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis also told the AP that he suspected the ABC report was in
retaliation for the defamation lawsuit Metabolife filed against
WCVB-Ch. 5, an ABC affiliate, for a report the station aired about
potentially harmful side effects caused by the company's products.
An ABC spokeswoman, while acknowledging the Channel 5 report was
one of the stories that prompted the network to take its own look
at the issue, called the claim that the ABC story is retaliatory
``completely and utterly false.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC News president David Westin says the report is ``fair,
accurate, and free from influence others sought to impose.''
</P>
<P>
   DON AUCOIN
</P>
<P>
   THE TALK OF THE DIAL
</P>
<P>
   6 a.m. WBNW-AM (1120) and WPLM-AM (1390) _ ``Business for
Breakfast'' with host Lindsy Parker. Guests: John Curtis, Brian
Koss, and Wendy Northcross.
</P>
<P>
   7 a.m. WRPT-AM (650) _ ``Health &AMP; Fitness  &UR; Today &LR; '' with host
Frankie Boyer. Guests: Carlos Warter, Ted Schaffer, and Nick
Ventola.
</P>
