<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-FIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FIGHT CLUB' PACKS PUNCH BUT LACKS STAMINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Fight Club'' is a midnight-black electrode of a movie that
sizzles with tongue-in-cheek cool and a screenful of marketing
savvy. Even if you choose to experience it as no more than Brad
Pitt's latest body slam, it's still an apocalyptic comedy of rage
that flirts with the muscular allure of fascism. Certainly no movie
in years has had this much subversive fun with militant but shaky
male egos. Even though it can't go the distance, and eventually
turns explosively silly, even though it's only more slick than
genuinely anarchic, it's still not bad for an evening at the
multiplex.
</P>
<P>
   It begins with David Fincher's camera surfing the synapses of
Edward Norton's nerd brain as if in heat-seeking search of the
Eighth Deadly Sin _ or at least Testosterone Central. Yes, there's
fighting, and more, as the film zaps us with its envelope-pushing
aspirations to boldness and originality. It even recapitulates
previous films of Pitt and Norton. If you thought Pitt's Nazi
superman number in ``Seven Years in Tibet'' (fleetingly cited here
as a visual in-joke), or his urban Gothic loose cannon in ``12
Monkeys,'' or the dark moral void he prowled in ``Seven'' were
outrageous, check out his evil twin to Norton's corporate drone
here. And yes, you'll be reminded of Norton's pumped-up neo-Nazi in
``American History X.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't long before we're plunged into illicit slugfests in
ill-lit basements where life's angry losers convene to pound one
another into hamburger as blood rooster tails across dank spaces
heavy with male odors. In those preserves, whose subterranean
aspects are as metaphorical as they are literal, there's as much
masochistic pride in taking a punch as in throwing one. Mostly,
though, ``Fight Club'' is about an over-the-top Brad Pitt bent on
world domination.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a pretty sight, even apart from Pitt's pond-scum chic
look. Norton's numbers-cruncher, whose job involves flying to
accident sites to decide whether it's cheaper for the auto company
employing him to do a recall of a particular model or face the
likely number of lawsuits, chats up Pitt's smug hipster salesman
selling his own homemade soap. But what the soapster's really
selling is anarchy. Before Norton's unhappy corporate camper
realizes it, he has only to think an anarchic thought and Pitt's
wild man makes it happen, although the fighting is Pitt's idea.
</P>
<P>
   One night, for no apparent reason, he starts shoving Norton
around in a parking lot. Norton finally shoves back, punches are
thrown, and the fight club is born as other testosterone-driven
guys are drawn to the slugging duo and want to emulate them on a
weekly basis. As Norton's contempt for his job increases in direct
proportion to his rebellious thoughts, so does Pitt's nihilistic
ingenuity and energy at acting upon them. As the fight club
membership grows, and more or less begins responding in robotic
unison and dressing in black uniformity, Pitt plunges deeper into
his Nietzschean triumph-of-the-will mode and suggests a surfer
version of Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   It's as if he's acting out Norton's angry, destructive,
system-rejecting impulses to the max. As Pitt's private army helps
him escalate his agenda of violence, it extends to the closest
thing Norton has had to a personal relationship. Before he meets
Pitt and his exhilarating just-do-it gang of neo-Nazis, Norton's
character got off on haunting different support groups and playing
emotional vampire, a system that provided catharsis until he
realized that another emotional ghoul played by Helena Bonham
Carter was working the support groups, too.
</P>
<P>
   He confronts the woman named Marla (Bonham Carter, at her
corpselike best, looking like a discarded doll) and makes a deal
with her to split the groups. Tuberculosis and bone cancer for one,
melanoma and testicular cancer for the other. Once immersed in the
punchy delights of the fight club, however, he abandons the
support-group vampirism. Marla tracks him down to the dilapidated
house he and Pitt and their army share, but attaches her punked-out
Pierrette charms to Pitt's character, not Norton's. She, who began
as the weirdest one, becomes the most human.
</P>
<P>
   Pitt and Norton, who bring the Fight Club up out of the cellar,
expand its repertory and rename it Operation Mayhem. They become
more and more outlandishly cartoony until they paint themselves
into a corner from which there is, dramatically speaking, no escape
once Pitt fatefully points out that with enough soap you can blow
up just about anything. Too bad, because ``Fight Club'' begins with
that invigoratingly nervy and imaginative buzz. But its chic
indictment of empty materialist values fizzles, especially when it
replaces them with nothing more than the classical fascist values
of male bonding through physical struggle (and highly defined abs)
and the worship of dynamism and energy for their own sakes.
</P>
<P>
   Given its collapse after that blowout beginning, it's unlikely
that there'll be a sequel to ``Fight Club.'' If there is, Leni
Riefenstahl ought to direct it.
</P>
<P>
   FIGHT CLUB &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by: David Fincher &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by: Jim Uhls (novel: Chuck Palahniuk) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Brad Pitt, Edward Norton, Helena Bonham Carter, Meat
Loaf Aday, Jared Leto &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 139 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R (disturbing and graphic depiction of violent antisocial
behavior, sexuality, and language) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
