<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEAT-BELTS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEAT BELT LAWS DON'T PROMOTE 'RACIAL PROFILING,' STUDY FINDS
 &HT;    BY SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Mandatory seat belt laws do not contribute to the
racial harassment of African American drivers, a new study reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Of 1,100 African American drivers surveyed this year by the
National Black Caucus of State Legislators and the Air Bag &AMP; Seat
Belt Safety Campaign, only four linked the laws to an experience of
police harassment or other race-related problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overwhelming support for strong seat belt laws by African
Americans in primary belt law states tells us that the law is
working fine for them, and that they want the benefits of fewer
injuries and deaths,'' said Georgia state Rep. Bob Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   A primary seat belt law allows a police officer to stop a
vehicle and ticket a driver for a seat belt violation, while a
secondary seat belt law doesn't allow an officer to stop a car with
a driver not wearing a seat belt unless there is another traffic
violation.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, 16 states and the District of Columbia have primary
seat belt laws. The study found that 83 percent of African
Americans wore seat belts in primary enforcement states and 66
percent in states with secondary enforcement laws.
</P>
<P>
   The study also showed that 72 percent of African Americans
favored seat belt laws in primary enforcement states and 62 percent
approved of them in secondary enforcement states.
</P>
<P>
   Favorable attitudes toward seat belt laws among the African
American drivers could not come at a better time.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the African American community, seat belt usage is really a
public health issue,'' said Rep. John Conyers Jr., a Democrat from
Michigan and ranking member of the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study showed that automobile accidents were the leading
cause of death of Americans 15 to 20 years old. Studies have also
shown that minorities are in even greater danger when it comes to
seat belt safety. African American youths are 60 percent more
likely not to buckle up than children of any other racial
background, and black and Hispanic male teenagers are nearly twice
as likely to die in a car crash than white male teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many cases, the fears surrounding the possible impact of a
primary law have been large enough to keep us from taking action to
protect our children and families,'' Florida state Sen. Kendrick
Meek said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Meek said that when Florida legislators began talking about
passing a primary seat belt law, he had apprehensions as a black
driver that it would allow some law enforcement officers to justify
``racial profiling'' practices. Meek added that he is now working
to pass the primary law.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
