<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-STORY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ALTOGETHER UNREMARKABLE `STORY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's appealing warmth in Rob Reiner's ``The Story of Us,''
and some nice work from Michelle Pfeiffer and Bruce Willis as a
couple whose 15-year marriage is unraveling. But its recriminations
and back-and-forth and resurgences of affection are little more
than sitcom-deep. It isn't a bad marriage, exactly, that they're
trying to work their way through, just one that's lost its steam
and is calling for a parting or a renewed commitment by the time
the kids come back from summer camp. The only real question, as
they slosh through anger and anguish, is whether the film is going
to tie everything up neatly in a package, or go somewhere really
surprising. Mostly this potential slugfest in the marital trenches
is undermined by a will to innocuousness.
</P>
<P>
   While such previous Rob Reiner films as ``When Harry Met Sally''
were able to work their way through some protracted stretches of
whininess with wit, this one gets stuck in a rut pretty early on
and has difficulty rising out of it. It suggests a marriage ride in
a theme park, running along a track in tumultuous but predetermined
fashion. The writing is at its best when it has Pfeiffer's
sharp-eyed Kate detail all of the little specifics that she once
may have found charming, like her writer husband Ben's veering off
into spontaneity. But while the film tells us that she's the one
who likes neat little boxes, he's the one who comes off as the
picky one.
</P>
<P>
   Their consultations with their pals have a prefab quality, too.
In fact, the film exerts an inordinate allure when it flashes back
to the days when they got along, if only because it gives us a
break from the spillover of hostility that has sent them to neutral
corners, feeling sorry for themselves. For all the pinpointing of
the little things that become wedges driving couples apart, ``The
Story of Us'' is conspicuously short on the kind of texture that
makes us feel we're watching real people living real lives. In a
film about a writer, it's no help to have so much of what he says
sound so written, and in such routine ways.
</P>
<P>
   They talk about wrestling with the seemingly paradoxical
question of how the things that brought them together now are
driving them apart. But the film never really feels as if they're
grappling with this. The most authentic thing in it is the tension
they project, even though it's grating to sit through. Certainly it
beats the film's glum tendency to fall back on in-law jokes when
the creativity level sags and the fractured time line takes its
toll. The secondary roles add little, although Rita Wilson's salty
confidante freshens up a story that increasingly needs freshening
as it plods to an unremarkable conclusion. Beyond its crescendo of
frazzled nerves obscuring a reservoir of good will each feels
toward the other, the film suggests that what Ben and Kate need is
not a divorce, but a time out. Perhaps that's why, at bottom, ``The
Story of Us'' plays like an intermission. Its promise of marital
fireworks, either comedic or dramatic, is largely unkept.
</P>
<P>
   THE STORY OF US &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by: Rob Reiner &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by: Alan Zweibel &AMP; Jessie Nelson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Bruce Willis, Michelle Pfeiffer, Rita Wilson, Reiner,
Paul Reiser, Tim Matheson, Julie Hagerty, Red Buttons, Betty White,
Jayne Meadows, Tom Poston &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 90 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R (language and brief sexuality) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
