<SLUG> BC-PATAKI-FRESH-AIR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI CALLS FOR NEW POLLUTION LIMITS ON POWER PLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DINA CAPPIELLO  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki said he would require New
York's 32 power plants to reduce emissions that cause acid rain and
smog.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, announced Thursday, raises the bar already placed on
all electric utilities under the 1990 amendments to the federal
Clean Air Act, reducing sulfur emissions at New York plants by an
additional 50 percent and curbing nitrogen oxide emissions
year-round by Jan. 1, 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Current federal law requires only nitrogen oxide reductions
during the summer, the prime season for smog, or ground-level
ozone, which causes asthma and otheratory ailments.
</P>
<P>
   The state just recorded its smoggiest summer in recent history,
with a total of 211 violations of the federal ozone standard.
Sulfur dioxide is the main culprit in the formation of acid rain,
which threatens lakes and streams. Roughly 24 percent of Adirondack
lakes in New York are seriously acidic, according to the National
Acid Precipitation Program.
</P>
<P>
   A 1995 U.S. Environmental Protection Agency study found that
even under the current Clean Air Act, the number of acidic lakes
would double by 2040.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, a Republican, attributed about 80 percent of New York's
air pollutants to out-of-state plants, particularly those located
in the Midwest, but said that well over 20 percent comes from
in-state power sources closer to the Adirondacks. These plants
deposit additional nitrogen and sulfur in the state's lakes and
downwind in New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing for us to stand there and say the Midwest
states do more,'' Pataki told a press conference at the Capitol.
``It's another when you are the state leading the nation in air
emission standards.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, New York's power plants emitted 313,606 tons of sulfur
dioxide while Ohio's, which produce roughly three times the amount
of energy, emitted 1.4 million tons and Indiana's 968,340 tons. New
York plants released 102,000 tons of nitrogen oxide compared to the
515,882 tons in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Yorkers have plenty of reasons to complain about
Midwestern states,'' said Paul J. Elston, chairman of the New York
League of Conservation Voters. ``It is a perfect cover for every
politician to do nothing. That's not what's going on here.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's announcement came a month after Attorney General Eliot
Spitzer said he would take legal action against 17 power plants in
the Midwest and South, which he contends violate the Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's case drew criticism from environmentalists and
industry officials who said that attorney general should look
closer to home. New York has 20 plants that are grandfathered _
exempt from the air quality standards for newer power-generating
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists argue that this exemption provides older
plants with the incentive to remain dirty. By not being required to
install pollution-control devices, companies can produce energy at
a lower cost and sell it more cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Spitzer sent letters requesting documents from eight
older power plants in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In the newly deregulated energy market, Pataki's directive would
narrow the gap in air emissions standards between old and new
plants, making cleaner ones more competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as emissions are concerned, they all would be required
to meet the same standards,'' said Environmental Conservation
Commissioner John P. Cahill.
</P>
<P>
   Cahill's department is responsible for working out regulations
by Jan. 1., 2003, for the 130,000 tons reduction in sulfur dioxide
and 20,000 tons reduction in nitrogen oxide each year that the
governor is seeking. Under deregulation, utilities are getting out
of the power-production business by selling off their plants. For
the companies that are buying them, Pataki's announcement was a
slap in the face.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is certainly unexpected,'' said Frank Rapley, a spokesman
for NRG Energy Inc. of Minneapolis, which recently purchased
Niagara Mohawk Power Corp.'s Dunkirk and Huntley plants and
ConEdison's facility at Astoria in Queens. ``The reductions that he
has proposed are dramatic and they will definitely have a
significant impact on our operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Cahill estimated the cost of updating existing plants to meet
the state's new standards could be as much as $80 million. Pataki
stressed that he expects no rate increase because of the
competition brought about by deregulation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
