<HEADLINE>
PAGE FLIES AGAIN WITH THE BLACK CROWES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a concept: No home video, no pay-per-view, no live album,
no tribute album, no strings attached. The teaming of the Black
Crowes and Led Zeppelin legend Jimmy Page defies all the corporate
machinations that typically accompany such all-star unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing this for the music. The glory is in just
playing,'' Black Crowes singer Chris Robinson says of the band's
short tour with Page this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Crowes/Page express debarked in New York for two shows
earlier this week, and leaves for Los Angeles for two more next
week. But sandwiched in between is Saturday's stop at the Worcester
Centrum Centre. It's a coup for the Centrum and a chance to see
what should be one of the rock events of the year. New York, Los
Angeles, and Worcester. No other US cities are on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole show is us and Jimmy,'' says Robinson, noting that
they'll join forces to play Crowes tunes, Zeppelin tunes, and blues
covers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played with Jimmy in London this summer and did Zeppelin's
`In My Time of Dying,' `Whole Lotta Love,' and `Your Time is Gonna
Come.' And we did the Crowes songs `Remedy,' `Wiser Time,' and `By
Your Side.' Jimmy has his place on those. And this time we want to
do some (Zeppelin) stuff we didn't do there, like `Down by the
Seaside' and ``Ten Years Gone.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As for blues covers, the musicians tackled the B. B.
King-identified ``Woke Up This Morning'' in London, and may do the
Otis Redding-identified ``Old Man Trouble'' this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we don't even rehearse the blues covers,'' says
Robinson, ``except to discuss who's going to play the first solo or
the one after that. We want to keep it pretty spontaneous. Hey, I'm
going to let the guitar players do all the work! Just let them
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Page, who is not doing any interviews, first met the Crowes six
years ago when the Crowes' ``High as the Moon'' tour came to
London's Royal Albert Hall. He and the Crowes hit it off backstage.
A day later, Page went to the Crowes' gig in Paris and sat in. Then
in 1996, the Crowes opened Page and Plant's tour of South America,
further solidifying the bond. Then came the London gig in June when
Page asked the Crowes to be his backup band. It was a benefit for
two children's charities, one of which was Action for Brazil's
Children, chosen because Page's wife is from Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a rehearsal, and it was awesome,'' Robinson recalls of
that show. ``It was so laid-back and easy. Really, no pressure. We
said, `This is so good, let's do it somewhere else.' So here we
are.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Queerstock: The Atlanta-based Queerstock music festival, a
showcase for openly gay musicians, comes to Boston for the first
time next week. The Midway Cafe in Jamaica Plain is the setting for
the kickoff show Thursday with Angela Motter, the Steph Pappas
Experience, and Mehuman Jonson. The Milky Way, another JP club, is
the setting for next Saturday's afternoon show with Rick Berlin,
Tara Lynne, CD Collins and Pincurl, Doria Roberts, Robert Urban,
Cooper Seay, Jessie Zoldak, and Letta Neely.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Woodstock differences: A recent e-mail about the differences
between Woodstock '69 and '99 has been making the rounds. Here are
excerpts: 1969: 3-day ticket for $18; 1999: 3 sodas for $18; 1969:
3 days of peace, love, and understanding; 1999: 3 days of
pay-per-view for $89.95; 1969: Firing up a joint during the show;
1999: Burning down the joint after the show; 1969: Kids didn't want
to fight in Vietnam; 1999: Kids can't spell Vietnam; and, finally,
1969: We are stardust; 1999: We are Starbucks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bits and Pieces: First, the unexpected: The Smashing Pumpkins
have changed managers and have signed with Sharon Osbourne, wife of
Ozzy and coordinator of Ozzfest ... Shania Twain has extended her
tour, but the closest she's coming to Boston is the Hartford Civic
Center Nov. 27 . . . Alanis Morissette has an MTV ``Unplugged'' on
Nov. 1, followed by an acoustic album from the event due Nov. 16. .
. .
</P>
