<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MANAGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS BECOMES HIS BEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Think hard for a moment. How many successful
rock musicians have also been successful rock managers? Not many,
but Paul Geary is living proof that it can be done. He was the
drummer for Extreme _ a million-selling Boston act in the early
'90s _ and he's now managing Godsmack, the hottest-selling
break-out rock act of recent months, whose self-titled album is
approaching 2 million copies sold.
</P>
<P>
   Geary, now 38 and working from a 10th-story office with a
panoramic view of the Boston skyline, knows that he's beaten the
odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many players have come and gone and can't get arrested
now?'' he asks. ``But I've been lucky, because I was able to parlay
one success into another success. And I think I'm uniquely suited
to managing acts. When a band says, `We can't hear our monitors,'
that might go right by some managers, but because I've actually
been onstage, I know exactly what it means. And that goes a long
way for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Geary has become Boston's most prominent rock manager (he also
helps guide the careers of newcomers Reveille and veteran Cyndi
Lauper) since the heyday of Tim Collins, who managed Aerosmith for
12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Collins is an unabashed Geary supporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to make the transition from artist to
manager,'' says Collins. ``It's a different world. It's right brain
versus left brain. But Paul has indefatigable energy. He's
persistent and smart and dedicated. He's got a great ear and is
always hustling. He's been around and has toured internationally.
Plus, he was the guy in Extreme who dealt with the inner politics,
and that set him up to be a good manager.''
</P>
<P>
   Most big-time managers, says Collins, come from a business
background. Cliff Bernstein, who works with Metallica, is a
statistician. Howard Kaufman, who manages Aerosmith and Jimmy
Buffett, is an accountant. Irving Azoff, who manages the Eagles, is
``another numbers guy,'' says Collins, who himself went to business
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even as an artist, I always had my nose in business,'' says
Geary, who grew up in Medford and Malden. ``I co-managed Extreme
from the start, and as the years flew by, I became more and more
comfortable with the business side of things. I'm now as
comfortable jumping on the phone and cutting a deal as I was
getting onstage and playing drums.''
</P>
<P>
   In the band Extreme, which had such Top 10 hits as ``More than
Words'' and ``Hole-Hearted,'' Geary was the only band member who
paid serious attention to the business end. Singer Gary Cherone,
who joined Van Halen after Extreme broke up three years ago, was
mainly focused on writing lyrics, Geary says. Guitarist Nuno
Bettencourt, who has since gone solo, ``wanted to make rock records
where he could bash away on guitar and not worry about singles.''
And bassist Pat Badger, who recently joined Florida band Super
Transatlantic, was also ``content with just playing music.''
</P>
<P>
   Extreme almost signed a management deal with Collins, who had
the band open for Aerosmith in Portland, Maine, as a way to check
it out. Aerosmith's Steven Tyler and Joe Perry were ``cheering us
from the side of the stage and I think we really played well,''
says Geary, who was an Aerosmith fan from childhood (the first
record he ever bought was Aerosmith's ``Get Your Wings''). But
Collins, after much thought, decided to stay exclusively with
Aerosmith.
</P>
<P>
   Extreme was unusual in that it was always much bigger overseas
than in the United States. The group would headline two nights at
London's Wembley Arena and two at Toyko's Budokan, yet struggle to
do more than one show in a US city, despite selling millions of
records. The reason, Geary says, was that overseas audiences
recognized Extreme as a rock band, whereas listeners here became
confused when the first two domestic hits were the acoustic-based
``More than Words'' and ``Hole-Hearted,'' versus the electric,
funk-based rock that was the group's specialty.
</P>
<P>
   Geary left Extreme on ``friendly terms'' a year before the group
officially broke up _ and he quickly started building a management
roster. He signed three bands _ Hunk (from New York), the Hookers
(from Los Angeles), and Flip (from Minneapolis). They all got
record deals, but personnel changes at the labels doomed the
records.
</P>
<P>
   ``I began to get the idea that Extreme wasn't the norm, that it
wasn't easy to take a band to Extreme's heights,'' Geary says.
``You might get a great record deal one day, but in six months it
wasn't worth the paper it was written on.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Godsmack appeared. Geary had known Godsmack singer Sully
Erna for 10 years before the band was formed. Geary then caught
them at the Atlantic Lounge (now called the Tank) in Revere. Geary
went to the show with his New York-based partner Arma Andon, and
they loved what they heard. They also loved the tape Godsmack
recorded at New Alliance Studio in Boston. The band made it for
only ``$2,500 to $3,000, but it was sonically great,'' says Geary.
Universal Records released it as the debut album that has now sold
nearly 2 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   The rest has been a fantasy. Godsmack became the first band
since Metallica to have two singles (``Whatever'' and ``Keep
Away'') chart simultaneously in the Top 10 at most album-rock radio
stations. Locally, WAAF-FM (107.9) was the first station to get
behind the band, but nearly every other rock station has followed
suit. Godsmack also toured on the Ozzfest and performed at
Woodstock '99.
</P>
<P>
   Geary, who has also spent time as a promoter and venue owner
couldn't be happier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long road, but I really feel like I'm home now,''
he says. ``I hope to manage bands for the rest of my career.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
