<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARGAINS ARE STUCK IN BASEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bloomingdale's vs. Almy's.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, but that's the truth.
</P>
<P>
   The third spot in anyone's batting order is supposed to be a
glamour role. He is, in theory, your ``best'' hitter. The Yankees
have a No. 3 hitter who knocked in 110 in an off year. The Red Sox
have a 27-year-old rookie No. 3 hitter who is often completely
overmatched in this exalted level of competition.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have a veteran, battle-hardened and (reasonably)
healthy pitching rotation that features a lefthander with five
career postseason victories. The Red Sox have Pedro Martinez and an
assortment of rehabs and discards. Their starting lefthander was
jettisoned in late August by a National League team going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   You could have made a sufficiently dramatic compare-and-contrast
case to demonstrate that the Red Sox lineup had even less business
being on the field against the Indians, and at last view the
Indians were seen jumping en masse into the Cuyahoga River.
</P>
<P>
   But the hook there was pitching. For all their Central Division
dominance over the past six seasons, the Indians have never
rectified an essentially mediocre pitching situation. The defending
world champion Yankees have not had that problem.
</P>
<P>
   When the climactic moment came in Thursday night's game, Joe
Torre summoned a proven reliever named Ramiro Mendoza, who has
served his team well in a variety of situations the past several
years. With the bases loaded and one out in the eighth and New York
clinging to a precarious 3-2 lead, he bailed his team out by
striking out pinch hitter Butch Huskey and retiring the dangerous
(five hits in the first two games) Jose Offerman on a routine fly
to center.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Jimy Williams's options in a similar situation: Tom
Gordon, barely sprung from rehab; Bryce Florie, considered
expendable by the woeful Tigers; Rheal Cormier, a well-traveled
lefthander of modest skill; and Rod Beck. 'Nuff said.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomie's vs. Almy's.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox try. Oh, how they try. Jimy Williams is correct.
They most certainly do compete. But when you examine just what they
are working with, the fact that they won 94 games and managed to
defeat the Indians is one of the great baseball stories of our
time.
</P>
<P>
   That said, take out the nearest fedora from your closet and wave
it in the general direction of the noble Ramon Martinez, who gave
his team a magnificent effort in a valiant attempt to send his team
back to Fenway Park Saturday with the series tied. He has given
this team the benefit of superior class and baseball breeding since
making his debut back on Sept. 2. We already know that the team
would not have even gone this far without his spectacular
performance in Game 3 last Saturday against Cleveland. And he did
nothing to diminish his considerable reputation Thursday &UR;  &LR; night,
when he pitched 6 2/3 strong innings in the crushing Yankees
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez the Elder is not exactly pitching with the same
equipment and repertoire he had when he was doing such things as
throwing no-hitters and striking out 18 San Francisco Giants. But
the man does know how to pitch, and for six innings he was beating
the Yankees in this vital game, holding a 2-1 lead courtesy of a
two-run Nomar Garciaparra homer. His only mistake was a
fourth-inning 1-and-2 pitch that wandered into Tino Martinez's
wheelhouse and landed in the right-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   But Ramon walked leadoff man Ricky Ledee on a close 3-and-2
pitch to start off the seventh, and in a game like this such a move
was a definite faux pas. Before the inning was over, the Yankees
would push across two runs, the big blows being a two-out Chuck
Knoblauch double that produced the tying run and a two-out Paul
O'Neill soft single off Cormier that brought home the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   It was a great show, but it wasn't enough to beat David Cone,
and the very mention of that name tells you all you need to know
about the essential differences between the Bloomies and the Almys.
For David Cone, a quality, veteran pitcher, hadn't even been needed
in the Division Series against Texas. Were he a member of the
Almys, he would have started Game 2. On the Bloomies, he is now the
fourth starter. Fourth!
</P>
<P>
   Savvy baseball man that he is, Cone is blown away by the
improbability of the Almys. ``They are better than a wild card
right now,'' he maintains. ``This is not a wild-card team. Plus,
they're hot right now. Every guy on that team is putting up quality
at-bats right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the best came at the very end. With two away and nobody
on in the ninth, and with the bitter memory of a pair of would-be
homers by Jason Varitek and Troy O'Leary failing to leave the yard
by 2 and 6 inches, respectively, Garciaparra and O'Leary each got
two-strike, two-out singles in the ninth off gold-plated reliever
Mariano Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   A tease? What do you think? Rivera struck out Damon Buford to
end the game. Bloomies 3, Almys 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are an amazingly resilient team,'' lauds Cone. ``You have
to appreciate that from the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   Resilient? Oh, absolutely. The problem is their shelves are
neither as well-stocked nor as laden with quality goods as the
Bloomies'. But they do have one extraordinarily high-quality item,
and let's see what the Bloomies can do with Pedro Saturday before
we call in the liquidator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
