<HEADLINE>
BC'S CIRINO PLANS TO HOLD THE LINE VS. PITT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Pedro Cirino has already been through two 4-7 seasons
too many. After Boston College suffered its first loss of the
season in last Saturday's 24-14 setback at Temple, the senior free
safety and defensive co-captain emphatically vowed not to finish
his BC career by going through a third.
</P>
<P>
   That's why he intends to draw the line when the Eagles play host
to Pittsburgh Saturday in a huge Big East game at 5 p.m. at Alumni
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were 4-7 last year, and that's something I can't accept,''
said Cirino, a 5-foot-11-inch, 201-pounder from Jersey City, N.J.,
who ranks as the hard-hitting heart and soul of BC's defense.
``It's tough for me because I can't go through another season like
that, and I'm going to do whatever I can to control that.''
</P>
<P>
   What Cirino and Co. weren't able to control, however, was a
Temple offense that gained new life under Devin Scott. The backup
quarterback had suffered a rib-cage injury in a 55-24 loss the week
before at Pittsburgh and wasn't even expected to play against BC.
Scott rallied Temple from a 14-0 deficit to 24 unanswered points,
including 17 in the second half. The Owls amassed a season-high 429
yards total offense against BC's beseiged defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out after taking a 14-0 lead, and I don't know what
happened, but we just relaxed and took the other team for
granted,'' Cirino said. ``We couldn't do much out there after that.
We couldn't move the ball, and we couldn't stop them. They
out-toughed us in the second half, and that's something we're not
happy with. We've got to get back to playing tough football, but we
didn't react well to it.''
</P>
<P>
   What was the most troubling aspect of the Temple loss? ``We
didn't react to the way they came out in the second half,'' said
Cirino, who was credited with six tackles and now ranks second on
the team (42) behind senior linebacker Frank Chamberlin (48).
``They gained the momentum at halftime (when Marcus Godfrey scored
on a 1-yard run to make it 14-7 with two seconds remaining before
halftime), and that was probably the turning point of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We roughed the punter (to help sustain Temple's first scoring
drive of 13 plays, 78 yards), and it was reminiscent of two years
ago when we were down there,'' Cirino said, recalling BC's 28-21
loss to Temple in O'Brien's debut as BC's head coach. ``It was the
exact same situation. We roughed the punter and gave them all the
momentum from there on out. The offense struggled the whole game,
pretty much, and that's something we can't have. We have to have
them help us, and we have to help them out by getting them the ball
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Cirino admitted the Eagles were caught off guard when Temple
``ran some plays we had never seen before and we didn't expect,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   BC's defense failed to react with a physical response. ``The
coaches tried to put us in a position to make some plays, but we
just didn't make them,'' Cirino said. ``The whole thing comes down
to us on the defense. Whether the offense doesn't move the ball or
not, they had 14 points on the board and that's enough to hold
them, but we didn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   BC's defense has become vulnerable on the right side.
</P>
<P>
   ``The past two weeks (against Temple and Northeastern), offenses
have spread us wide apart and then try to pound the ball and have
our linebackers and secondary in a situation where we're spread out
all over the place,'' Cirino said. ``That's what kills you. I mean,
the coaches have gone to a new approach this week, and if they try
to do it to us this week, they're going to pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   But according to O'Brien, the only thing BC's defense needed to
do better was tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're lining up as we were,'' O'Brien said. ``It was just that
we didn't tackle. We had the chance to make plays, and we didn't
tackle. That's the bottom line on defense: too many missed tackles.
There were more missed tackles in that game than in the previous
two or three.''
</P>
<P>
   Cirino concurred. ``If we don't come out and play (against
Pittsburgh), they might beat the hell out of us,'' he said.
``That's something we can't have happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
