<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-LUCY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WOMAN WHO OUTSMARTED `BUTCHER OF LYON' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good causes usually make bad films. Perhaps it's because the
filmmaker subconsciously feels that part of the work is being done
for him by the moral force of the story. ``Lucie Aubrac'' isn't a
bad film. Its high level of craftsmanship keeps it from that. But
it's a curiously inert film, given its dynamite true story. There
not only was but still is a Lucie Aubrac, who was brave and nervy
and clever and lucky enough to snatch her patriotic saboteur
husband from the clutches of Klaus Barbie and the occupying Nazis
in Lyon in 1943.
</P>
<P>
   The statuesque Carole Bouquet, who plays Lucie, is at her best
during the few intimate moments she's able to snatch from her
husband's efforts _ and eventually hers _ on behalf of the
Resistance. What's best about her underground heroics is that
they're done coolly enough to impress us with her sense of
self-possession, although her most magnificent gesture is almost
romantically foolhardy. In a burst of fiery determination, she
decides to get her husband sprung on the anniversary of their
honeymoon and does it by threatening a local prosecutor and Nazi
puppet with assassination.
</P>
<P>
   It works. Her husband, Raymond, is played by Daniel Auteuil,
whose natural acuity is dampened by being required to mostly look
dumbfounded or numb after having been tortured. His first release,
risky as it was for Lucie to have bluffed it into being, was
comparatively easy since he was able to convince his captors that
he was guilty of the relatively minor crime of black marketeering.
But the stakes are raised after a traitor tips the Nazis to a spy
cell meeting and almost all are arrested and sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
   To spring her husband this time, she's got to go through the
infamous ``Butcher of Lyon,'' Klaus Barbie, presented here by Heino
Ferch in the all too familiar sadistic, sneering Nazi serpent mode.
Bouquet convinces as a woman with her own center of gravity, but
while her avoidance of cheap dramatics is admirable, she also comes
across as something of a blank, which the real Lucie assuredly was
not. The film, too, seems more an exercise in iconography than an
urgent dramatization. It would hardly seem possible, given its
real-life heroics and real-life dramatics, but ``Lucie Aubrac''
seems so preoccupied with genuflection that it never achieves its
subject's heart-pounding immediacy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LUCIE AUBRAC &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Written and directed by: Claude Berri (based on Aubrac's
autobiographical novel &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Carole Buquet, Daniel Auteuil, Patrice Chereau,
Jean-Roger Milo, Eric Boucher, Heino Ferch, Pascal Greggory &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 116 minutes. (in French with subtitles) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R (violence) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
