<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BREAKFAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BREAKFAST OF CHAMPIONS' LACKS BITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Breakfast of Champions'' is a well-intended film of Kurt
Vonnegut Jr.'s satiric novel about America's consumer society
consuming itself. But it's largely a misfire, possibly because its
adapter and director, Alan Rudolph, is better suited to mood pieces
than to the madcap energies of Vonnegut's barbed but humanistic
farce. Or maybe Rudolph just waited too long and the vital impulses
that would have fueled the film expired during its long gestation
period, which began with Rudolph writing an adaptation while
working for Robert Altman in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Rudolph and an obviously devoted cast put the material
onscreen with a will, even though the source of the social toxins
in the novel has shifted from the Vietnam War to a mindless runaway
consumerism. As the film opens, its slaves in a manically upbeat
town called Midland City are feeling hollowed out and lost to
themselves while they turn the very land beneath their feet into
festering sewage so that the local factories with their belching
smokestacks can turn out things nobody needs, like
raspberry-flavored air freshener. With an almost too-perfect
symmetry, Bruce Willis's Dwayne Hoover, the richest man in town, is
feeling the most alienated and despairing.
</P>
<P>
   Willis's go-get-'em car dealer, who hard-sells the wares on the
lot at his Exit 11 Motor Village in a manner even more lifeless
than his obvious hairpiece, begins each day by sticking a gun
barrel into his mouth and getting closer and closer to pulling the
trigger. His underutilized wife, played by Barbara Hershey, pines
away in front of the TV between suicide attempts, depressed at his
absence from their life and his refusal to even try to talk to her.
His sales manager, Nick Nolte, lives in fear that his pastime of
dressing in frilly ladies' underwear will be discovered. His
secretary, played with a drolly amusing demure insincerity by
Glenne Headly, dutifully services him with quickies in the motel he
owns, hoping he'll reciprocate by setting her up with a fast-food
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes. Not knowing how to blast out of his rut, he
desperately lunges at enlightenment when his path converges with
that of a crumpled old failure of a writer whose philosophical
ramblings have remained unpublished except as filler in porn
magazines. Kilgore Trout is the name of this pillar of literary
futility (and Vonnegut's alter ego), who appears regularly in
Vonnegut's novels. Failure though he is, he at least maintains a
crumpled integrity, even though, in his own words, he spent his
life looking for art and beauty and ``didn't find doodly-squat.''
Albert Finney dodders good-naturedly through the role of the
old-timer coming to Midland City to be honored by the local art
mavens (an excuse for Vonnegut and Rudolph to tee off on art
poseurs).
</P>
<P>
   But by the time Dwayne and Kilgore collide, the film has pretty
much capsized. Willis and Nolte, trapped in caricature, are
consumed by it as it becomes glumly apparent that there is to be no
escalation to the demented giddiness ``Breakfast of Champions''
needs. For the record, let it be noted that Vonnegut can be seen in
a cameo, as a TV director shooting a commercial at the dealership
littered with self-motivational tools, like the sign over the
full-length mirror that says, ``You look like a winner.'' The
problem faced by ``Breakfast of Champions'' on the eve of the
millennium is that a lot of its satiric targets have been surpassed
by the even more outrageous and relentless iron rule of real-life
marketing. Consumerism is running more amok than ever, but this
satire of it isn't. The Shopping Network is wilder.
</P>
<P>
   BREAKFAST OF CHAMPIONS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed and written by: Alan Rudolph (novel: Kurt Vonnegut
Jr.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Bruce Willis, Albert Finney, Nick Nolte, Barbara
Hershey, Glenne Headly, Lukas Haas, Omar Epps &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 110 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R (sexuality and some language) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
