<HEADLINE>
`ANIMALS' A TELLING LOOK AT HUMAN HEALING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``All the Little Animals'' is a satisfying British film about
damage and redemption, given a benevolent back-to-nature twist. It
begins with a boy, Christian Bale's Bobby, who never has been whole
following a head injury. An even bigger blow befalls him when his
protecting mother dies and he finds himself at the mercy of an evil
stepfather. As played by Daniel Benzali, the greedy arriviste named
De Winter suggests a malevolent iceberg advancing slowly and
determinedly toward the boy, meaning to simultaneously freeze and
crush the life out of him so he can grab the department store the
boy inherited. When The Fat _ as Bobby has nicknamed his sinister
relative _ asphyxiates Bobby's pet mouse, Bobby correctly reads it
as a sign of things to come, and runs away, to Cornwall.
</P>
<P>
   On the road, or, to be more accurate, at the side of it, he
meets a grizzled, eccentric loner contrastingly named Summers. As
played by John Hurt, Summers mumbles to himself, is habituated to a
nip of Scotch but otherwise lives simply in a rough cabin in the
woods, and hides what his eyes tell us is a caring soul beneath a
cranky exterior. Occupying a patch of mythic turf somewhere between
Tolkien and A.A. Milne, Summers _ the perhaps too obvious polar
opposite of De Winter _ keeps busy by burying roadkill, tenderly
laying the small animals in the ground and cursing the cars and
drivers that killed them. His idea of a preemptive strike involves
a nocturnal invasion of a rich butterfly-collector's lawn and
freeing a tentful of moths lured into it by a light.
</P>
<P>
   Under his ministrations, Bobby blooms as he never did back in
so-called civilization. Jeremy Thomas, making his directorial
debut, catches the intimacy with nature so highly prized by the
English, who have preserved at least this patch of the West Country
from encroaching modernization.
</P>
<P>
   As we feel Bobby gather strength and competence, we know
there'll be a clash between Summers and De Winter, that Bobby will
be in the middle of it, and that we will bring to it a rooting
interest. The settings in Cornwall and on the Isle of Man count for
a lot. So do conviction and an offbeat story. They override
predictability in the involvingly acted, surehandedly crafted ``All
the Little Animals.''
</P>
<P>
   ALL THE LITTLE ANIMALS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by: Jeremy Thomas &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by: Eski Thomas (novel: Walker Hamilton) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: John Hurt, Christian Bale, Daniel Benzali &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running Time: 111 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R (some violence) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
