<HEADLINE>
FOLLOWING TRADITION, OCTOBER SPOOKS INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a typical October. The weather is beautiful; the leaves are
changing colors; the New York Yankees are still playing baseball.
And oh yes, the stock market is in a funk.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 54 points Thursday after
losing a total of more than 400 points the previous two days. At
10,286.61, the Dow is off nearly 10 percent from its August high.
</P>
<P>
   This October's damage pales in comparison to Octobers past. The
crashes of 1929 and 1987 both happened in October. But investors
are clearly in an edgy, almost frightened state. When Raytheon
announced a major earnings disappointment this week, its stock fell
44 percent in a single day. Intel and Tyco International, two
blue-chip stocks, have seen their share prices drop sharply in
response to small doses of bad news.
</P>
<P>
   Need more evidence that people are spooked? According to Syl
Marquardt, research director at John Hancock Funds, a popular
survey of investor sentiment he tracks is registering its gloomiest
reading in 20 years. Only 35 percent of stock market investors and
24 percent of bond market investors currently identify themselves
as bullish.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the fact that it is October, what is making investors so
skittish? Economists and money managers we interviewed Thursday
came up with a long list of things worth worrying about.
</P>
<P>
   They include:
</P>
<P>
   --Rising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rates would have to be the number one problem,'' says Wayne
Ayers, chief economist at Fleet Boston Corp. The Federal Reserve
didn't hike rates at its last meeting but the central bank said it
was leaning toward a rate hike in the future.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't hard to see why. The American jobless rate is at a low
4.2 percent; wages are climbing; oil prices are rising; and the
economy shows very few signs of slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   Put it all together and you get the possibility of more
inflation, even if the actual evidence of inflation is hard to
find. Fearful investors Thursday pushed the yield on the 30-year
Treasury bond to a two-year high in anticipation of coming bad news
on the inflation front.
</P>
<P>
   --A falling dollar.
</P>
<P>
   For the past few years, the strong dollar has been a boon to the
stock market. It has kept import prices low and made the United
States a magnet for foreign investment. Lately the dollar has been
weakening, especially against the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The US is not the only game in town anymore,'' says Allen
Sinai, chief economist at Primark Decision Economics. Improving
economies in Asia and Europe are attracting investment money, which
in turn strengthens foreign currencies against the dollar. Because
the US needs foreign capital to finance its trade deficit, the weak
dollar puts upward pressure on interest rates _ bad news for
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   --High stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the recent selloff, the value the market is putting on
stocks is still ``sky high,'' says Mark Zandi, chief economist at
RFA Dismal Sciences, a Pennsylvania forecasting firm.
</P>
<P>
   According to Zandi, the market as a whole is trading at about 30
times earnings, far above historical norms. The high number
reflects an optimism about future earnings that may be difficult to
satisfy, say money managers, especially if higher interest rates
slow the economy next year.
</P>
<P>
   As defense contractor Raytheon found out this week, companies
that fail to meet earnings targets quickly come under attack from
hostile investors.
</P>
<P>
   --The market's dependence on the technology giants.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of big technology stocks, including Cisco Systems,
Microsoft, and IBM, have managed to soar this year while the rest
of the stock market has fallen to earth. Along with a few big
Internet names, such as Yahoo, the tech giants account for much of
the stock market's progress in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   If one of the giants stumbles, says Thomas O'Neill, chief
investment officer at Fleet Boston, ``you could see the whole
market wash out.''
</P>
<P>
   --Everything else.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is entering the presidential campaign season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is always uncertainty around an election,'' says Sinai.
Will a new president radically change economic policy? Health care
policy? No one knows.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign politics could be worrisome too. What if Pakistan's new
government takes a confrontational stance toward India? What if
India gets nasty in response?
</P>
<P>
   And then there is always Y2K. The conventional wisdom is that
the year 2000 problem was overblown all along. But what if the
conventional wisdom has it all wrong?
</P>
<P>
   Syl Marquardt of John Hancock says investors are overly worried
at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be leaning against the wind at this point,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Marquardt may be right. But just in case he isn't, don't walk
under any ladders until October is over.
</P>
<P>
   (Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1525EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
