<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-WILLIAMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TWO WOMEN BEHIND `THE MILLION DOLLAR MERMAID' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE MILLION DOLLAR MERMAID &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Esther Williams, with Digby Diehl &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster, 416 pp., illustrated, $26 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Million Dollar Mermaid'' almost seems the stories of two
different women. There's the public Esther Williams, the
hard-working movie star strong and talented enough to succeed in
the grinding Hollywood studio system. And there's the private
Williams, looking for love in all the wrong places.
</P>
<P>
   In 1941, MGM signed the tall, beautiful 19-year-old swimming
champion to do with water what skater Sonja Henie had done with
ice; i.e., make the studio lots of money. And she did. In the 1940s
and '50s, Williams starred in one water-borne movie musical
extravaganza after another. Her films were kitschy even in their
day. The public loved them. Williams wasn't much of an actor, but
she didn't need to be, as long as she was in or near the water.
</P>
<P>
   Even before publication some of the choicest bits in this
undeniably juicy Hollywood memoir found their way into the gossip
columns, most notably Williams's defrocking, so to speak, of he-man
actor Jeff Chandler. She describes the moment she found her fiance
in ``red wig, a flowered chiffon dress, expensive high-heeled shoes
and lots of makeup.''
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible not to feel a little sorry for Chandler, being
``outed'' as a transvestite at this late date.
</P>
<P>
   But that's show biz. That's show biz memoir, anyway, a genre in
which the departed are fair game.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many before her, Williams understandably prefers to tell
tales about those who are no longer in a position to protest. Joan
Crawford. Ava Gardner. Clark Gable. Bette Davis. Marlene Dietrich.
Gene Kelly. Busby Berkeley. Louis B. Mayer. It's what sells, after
all.
</P>
<P>
   One surprising revelation is that Williams tried LSD. Following
the lead of Cary Grant, an outspoken proponent of LSD-assisted
psychotherapy, Williams took LSD in 1950, under the direction of a
psychiatrist. Back then, the drug was being tested as an aid to
``instant psychoanalysis.'' It worked, for Williams, or so she
writes. It enabled her to understand that at age 8, she had
subconsciously taken on the persona of her older brother, a
promising actor who died at 16. She believes that incorporating her
brother made her driven to succeed, as well as driven to take care
of those around her.
</P>
<P>
   Williams grew up in a poor family. As a teenager, she was
sexually abused by a foster brother, and took refuge in competitive
swimming.
</P>
<P>
   By the time she was 18, she was national champion in five events
and headed for the 1940 Olymics. When World War II broke out, she
instead joined impresario Billy Rose's Aquacade, a swimming show in
which she starred with the first Tarzan, Johnny Weismuller, who
groped her relentlessly underwater and shed his suit at every
opportunity to show off his ``remarkable genitalia.''
</P>
<P>
   The offer of an MGM contract rescued Williams from the Aquacade
and delivered her to Louis B. Mayer. In fairly short order she was
bending down to kiss Mickey Rooney in ``Andy Hardy's Double Life.''
Her career was launched. She went on to make a series of popular,
if seldom critically acclaimed, movies, and piles of money for MGM.
</P>
<P>
   Williams's personal life was less successful than the
MGM-generated image; i.e., a combination of perfect homemaker and
glamorous movie star. At 19, she was married, briefly, to a premed
student. Her second marriage, to band singer Ben Gage, lasted 13
years and produced three children, but it was far from a happy
union. Gage was an alcoholic who squandered her money on gambling
and good times and left her $750,000 in debt to the IRS. Williams
admits that during their marriage she took comfort elsewhere,
ranging from Victor Mature (``a strong and fulfilling lover: Even
better than I had fantasized''), to Clifford Odets (``It had been a
long time since I'd had a conversation with a man who was
intellectually stimulating''), among others.
</P>
<P>
   Williams's third marriage, to Fernando Lamas, in 1961 seems to
have been both the best and the worst of her relationships. The
term ``self-centered'' barely begins to describe Lamas. The
handsome, charming Argentinian actor emerges from these pages
almost as a parody of Billy ``You look maahvelous!'' Crystal's
parody of him. Lamas wanted nothing to do with Williams's three
children. He didn't even allow them in the house he and Williams
shared.
</P>
<P>
   Lamas also demanded that she ``give up being Esther Williams,''
retire from movies, and wait on him full time. It was their
``deal.'' She loved him, and in his way, he loved her, but she paid
an enormous price for that love.
</P>
<P>
   After Lamas died in 1982, Williams rediscovered herself. She
made a popular swimming instruction video for babies and started
designing swimsuits under her own label. She married again, a
former college professor, Edward Bell. And she found that she was
``godmother'' to a new Olympic sport, synchronized swimming, a
perfect role for the movies' one and only mermaid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1526EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
