<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOLLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLE OF LONG SHOTS COULDN'T COME THROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is no famous wall here like there is in Boston.
Or at least there isn't supposed to be one. But as the Red Sox made
their way home early this morning, there were two images flashing
in each player's head. There was a constant, frustrating backdrop
in each image: a light blue wall.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Sox, they have a lot in common with the
two well-hit baseballs that traveled to the edge of the Yankee
Stadium outfield Thursday &UR;  &LR; night. Like the baseballs, the Sox
traveled a fair distance before finding themselves falling just
short, up against the wall.
</P>
<P>
   The facts are that the Sox trail the Yankees in the American
League Championship Series, 2 games to 0. Two more losses, and
their season is over. The cruel underbelly to those facts is that
we could easily be saying the same thing about the Yankees.
Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, the New Yorkers beat the Sox, 3-2. The Sox were
seven or eight inches from winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must work for Home Depot, selling lumber or something,''
Jimy Williams said when someone posed the seven-inches-from-victory
question to him. ``You are about right. I guess I'm being a wise
guy, but you are about right.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning, Jason Varitek hit a towering fly ball to
right field. It appeared to be leaving the park easily. But the
ball landed about five or six inches from the top of the fence. In
the eighth, Troy O'Leary sent a ball toward the 385-foot sign in
right-center. ``I wasn't sure if 'Tek's ball was going to go,''
teammate Butch Huskey said of Varitek, ``but I thought Troy's was
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't. The ball hit just above the ``5'' in 385, two inches
from the top of the wall. Seven or eight inches from a win.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game was won and lost by inches,'' Varitek said.
</P>
<P>
   Down the hall, Yankees second baseman Chuck Knoblauch had no
sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, hang in there,'' he said of the Sox' near misses. ``Our
fences are the right height. What can I say? They always say
baseball is a game of inches, and sometimes it proves to be
right.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes baseball so intriguing and disturbing is games like
Thursday &UR;  &LR; night's. Tino Martinez hit a home run, and it covered 358
feet. Nomar Garciaparra hit a home run and it went 368 feet.
Varitek and O'Leary launched balls that were in the 385-foot range,
and both stayed in the park, becoming a triple and double,
respectively. In both cases, neither man was brought home by a
teammate. The intelligent thing to say, then, was that the Sox did
not take care of their business with runners in scoring position
(they stranded 13). But they were not in the mood to talk about
intelligence. What they felt Thursday &UR;  &LR; night was raw, piercing
depression.
</P>
<P>
   Inside their visiting clubhouse, a few players were able to
smile at the irony of the night. Others cursed nearby reporters.
During this season, the Sox have gained a reputation as a
resilient, gritty team. But no one wanted to talk about that
Thursday &UR;  &LR; night. The Sox are like the guy who has heard, too many
times, the same line from the girl he loves: ``Hey, you're a nice
guy, but you're like a brother to me . . . '' The Sox didn't want
to be the little brother Thursday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Lowe was asked how close the Sox were to homering. He used
a metric-system reference.
</P>
<P>
   ``About a centimeter,'' the reliever said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Sox won't say it, but they need something
extraordinary from Pedro Martinez Saturday. Something very close to
the 17-strikeout performance they got on Sept. 10. They got good
performances in the first two games and have nothing to show for
them. So the truth is that being good is not good enough against
this team. It's akin to taking a championship from an incumbent
heavyweight. If you want to beat him, you cannot match him blow for
blow. You have to knock him out.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the final should have been 4-3, Sox,
Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, Boston still did some things that, if they
continue, will have them sitting at home Monday morning. In the
eighth, with a runner on third base and one man out, Huskey could
not bring O'Leary home with a sacrifice fly. You could make the
argument that Trot Nixon should have never been pinch-hit for _ and
I would buy the argument _ but anyone at the plate in that
situation has to be able to bring the runner home. If Huskey had
done that, it would have been a tie game at 3-all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was put in a situation to be successful,'' Huskey said,
``and I didn't do it. I'll have to go get them tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   True. But the recurring images are of that wall and those fly
balls, rising and then crashing at the top of the wall. That
happened twice. Huskey was asked about the symbolism of being seven
or eight inches short of a win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' the big outfielder said, ``the wall is too big.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
