<SLUG> BC-QUAKES-BABBITT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABBITT PROMOTES EFFORTS TO PREDICT EARTHQUAKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The old dream of earthquake prediction has
faded in recent years, but it lives on in the heart of at least one
top U.S. official: Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt visited a quake conference in Oakland on Thursday to
reassure the geological community of his commitment to an increased
budget for their research.
</P>
<P>
   Just as hurricane forecasters have greatly improved their own
forecasts in recent years, and just as volcano experts can better
foresee volcanic eruptions than ever before, quake predictors might
one day anticipate specific quakes with surprising precision, said
Babbitt, who was trained as a geologist.
</P>
<P>
   ``When will we be able to come to the public and say (a quake
will occur) at 2:01 p.m. on April 21 of a given year? There's a lot
of reason to think we will get there; we're not there yet,''
Babbitt said at the General Assembly of the Association of Bay Area
Governments.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt, 61, cautioned that the breakthrough in quake prediction
would not come soon _ ``not in my lifetime. But in coming
centuries, the answer is yes.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited the U.S. Geological Survey's successful forecast of a
volcanic eruption of Mount Pinatubo in the Philippines as an
example of what scientists can achieve when they put their minds to
it.
</P>
<P>
   At the same meeting, USGS scientist David Schwartz formally
unveiled the agency's long-awaited ``probabilities'' report
estimating the likelihood of another big quake in the San Francisco
Bay area. The report concluded there are 70 percent odds of an
earthquake measuring magnitude 6.7 or worse over the next 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz's quake-casting report is different from the kind of
quake-predicting prophesied by Babbitt. While Schwartz's forecast
involves probability estimates over a few decades, Babbitt hopes
for far more specific forecasts that target fairly specific times,
dates and places for quakes.
</P>
<P>
   Many seismologists have lost hope for such specific predictions,
partly because of the perceived failure of the USGS' highly
publicized ``Parkfield prediction experiment'' in Parkfield, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The Parkfield area has experienced a quake of about magnitude 6
an average of once every 22 years. Hence geologists predicted
another one would strike in the early 1990s. It has not happened _
not yet, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Parkfield experiment _ which maintains an extensive
array of scientific instruments, from lasers to seismographs,
scattered across the cow-and-wildcat-sprinkled hills of Central
California _ must continue, Babbitt told a news conference after
his talk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1528EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
