<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SEASON OF THE HUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, Maine _ Already the October gales have powdered the
high country with snow, already taken the edge off the colors that
swell in the valleys below the hilltops.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, generations of American males have felt a stirring
restlessness in the fall, an anticipation as strong as the promise
of spring. It is the season of the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Through late summer into September, fathers would take sons _
and occasionally daughters (there are whole hunting families) _
into the woods to look for signs.
</P>
<P>
   This is the season when hunters try to figure out the living
patterns of the deer they intend to hunt. Where is the path to
water? Where are the yards? Do they feed on that ridge or the
valley below?
</P>
<P>
   Down on the coast, waterfowlers make repairs to marsh blinds,
camouflage their duck boats, and watch the marsh for activity. Much
can be learned from the first movements of waterfowl in the flyway.
</P>
<P>
   And all is done in the anticipation of a huge season. The hunt
is as deeply ingrained in our psyches as the harvest.
</P>
<P>
   The first boom of shotguns out on the marsh was the very sound
of civility, if not conviviality. Like fishing and gathering of all
kinds, hunting is near some seat of the soul.
</P>
<P>
   And though there have been women hunters and anglers, the
father-son generational bond was the very heart of hunting.
</P>
<P>
   But in closing the century, the figures are clear _ hunting is
on the decline. Where the last, most active hunting generations
were during the war years, the baby boomers they spawned faced the
first problems of the ``modern'' world.
</P>
<P>
   The increase of land postings (as urban folk seek to gentrify
and develop the wilderness) and a rising aversion to violence
rising out of the 1960s created the first generational
disconnection.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Generation Xers,'' said Maine deer biologist Gerry
Lavigne, ``are being recruited into hunting at half the rate of the
boomers.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavigne, whose demographic study of Maine deer hunters echoes
the declining national trend, said that since the early 1980s
through the '90s, as the Generation Xers have grown into adulthood,
the number of hunters has dropped by 16 percent, even as the deer
herd has grown.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, Lavigne said, Maine had more licensed hunters (214,000)
than whitetail deer (160,000). But last year, Maine's deer herd
burgeoned to 292,000 as the number of deer licenses dropped to
180,000.
</P>
<P>
   That number is bound to decrease ever faster. With much fewer
hunters coming north to take the places of their fathers, the math
is simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have two sons, and I always kind of envisioned bringing them
hunting,'' said Cliff, a Portland native who asked that his family
name not be used. ``Until about five years ago, I used to do at
least a few days with my dad, but he can't go out anymore. And my
boys never had any interest. One was into football and the other
was a big skier, but neither one of them wanted to go hunt with Dad
and me. It's wasn't like they hated the idea, they just didn't seem
to have time to get into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the times. (The kids) just seem to have busier
lives, and it's not as if they grew up in the woods like I did.''
</P>
<P>
   But therein is the irony. The fastest growth of Maine's deer
population has not been in the wilderness or forests, but rather in
the state's most populous corridor, from Kittery to Brunswick,
bordered between the coast and the Maine Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   Firearm discharge ordinances make some pockets of southern Maine
so deer-infested that it's impossible to grow crops or even keep a
garden. Forest degradation, traffic hazards, and even disease
become issues in suburbia.
</P>
<P>
   In central Maine, the population density stands at around 25
deer per square mile. Some pockets of southern Maine, such as the
coastal islands and Falmouth Foreside, a seaside suburb of
Portland, the figure rises as high as 100 deer per square mile.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's worse,'' said Lavigne, ``is that Lyme disease (spread
by ticks) is endemic to the deer population.''
</P>
<P>
   Expanding the seasons and liberalizing the bag limits and other
regulations are but a few strategies available to control deer
populations. Maine has changed to smaller management areas and
expanded the archery season, and such tactics could result in more
efficient managing of whitetails.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a larger picture. As urbanites heading for the
wide-open spaces erect the fences that close them down, and as a
new generation never learns what some old sportsmen now simply
refer to as ``the old ways,'' the movement underway in sport
hunting is seemingly irreversible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
