<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STICK WITH THE COMPANY 401(K)
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 37 and earn $110,000 a year. My wife is at home with our
children, aged 4, 3, and 1. I put the maximum 16 percent allowed
into my company's 401(k) plan until I hit the $10,000 annual cap
for pre-tax contributions. I then contribute on an after-tax basis
at the 6 percent level until the end of each year, as the company
will match up to that amount with 80 percent of my contribution
with its own stock. Because of this, I haven't looked into a Roth
IRA. I currently have about $205,000 in the 401(k), which is my
only retirement savings. I would like to retire at age 55. What do
you think of my position? I assume I will be able to withdraw from
the 401(k) with a 10 percent penalty until I reach age 59 1/2.
Would I be better off with some other vehicle after I hit the
$10,000 pretax cap on the 401(k). What do you think of my
allocation, which I attach? J.H., Cape Cod, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I'm not sure how to read this one. If your employer matches
80 percent of all of your contributions, you should be in nice
shape, with $2,231,850 in your retirement savings at age 55. This
assumes average portfolio growth of 10 percent and continued
contributions at current levels. It would be enough to allow you to
continue living at your current lifestyle, even after factoring in
the effects of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But if your employer only matches the after-tax contributions, I
think you've set yourself a pretty ambitious goal, and perhaps an
unrealistic one. Suppose you contribute $1,466 a month to the
401(k) until about the end of July of each year, at which point you
reduce contributions to $550 a month. The annual level of your
contributions is $10,000 on a pre-tax basis, $2,750 after-tax, plus
a $2,200 match in company stock.
</P>
<P>
   Under that scenario, if the plan produced total returns of 10
percent annually for the next 18 years, you would accumulate about
$1,850,000 at age 55.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds like an impressive number, but let's analyze your
needs. After all of your savings, including college savings for
your children, you have a current income of $92,250. If inflation
runs at 3.5 percent for the next 18 years, you will need $171,353
to buy the same goods and services that $92,250 buys today. If you
wanted to make these withdrawals without depleting your nest egg,
you would need a 9.3 percent yield. And that would also leave you
no money at work to protect yourself from the effects of future
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   So if the company match is limited to your after-tax
contributions, it leaves you with a pair of unpleasant options. One
is to consider targeting a later retirement date, and the other is
to step up your savings.
</P>
<P>
   As for whether to set up an Roth IRA instead of the after-tax
contributions to the 401(k), it would be silly to forsake that 80
percent match from your employer, since that money, too, would be
locked up until age 59 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   But if you do decide to save more and to stick with the age-55
retirement target, you should make these savings in taxable
accounts, which will then be available to help you through the 54
months until you can withdraw from your tax-deferred accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Your 401(k) portfolio looks fine to me _ a little less than half
in a US Index fund, a little more than a quarter in your company's
stock, and the rest nicely apportioned among domestic and global
balanced funds, small cap, international stock, and US growth, and
telecommunications sector funds. I also liked your recent portfolio
move, away from large-cap US growth to the small cap and
international positions.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, while I don't have space to go into detail, I suggest
you stop saving for your children's education in UGMA and Education
IRA accounts and put future college savings in your own name.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I will be 42 in December and am in the process of a divorce.
I earn $80,000 per year and expect to get about $1,500 a month in
support for my daughters (ages 11 and 14) until they reach 18. I
currently have $106,000 in my previous employer's cash account
pension plan, and $60,000 in my previous employer's 401(k) plan,
both of which I plan to roll over into my new employer's 401(k)
plan. In addition, I have a $19,000 IRA invested in Fidelity Growth
and Income fund to which I no longer contribute. My priority is to
build my retirement funds and retire as early as possible. Is it
realistic to retire at age 55 or 57, and what type of investment
mix should I pursue when I roll my funds into the new 401(k) plan?
M.M., Hampstead, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   A. The missing element here is how much you plan to save. You
certainly have a nice start, and if you simply left that $185,000
in retirement savings alone and if you achieved 10 percent average
annual investment returns, your accumulation would be $702,000
after 14 years, when you are age 56. Were you to save 15 percent of
your current salary, or $1,000 a month, the total would be
$1,053,619, using the same assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   If you read the discussion of inflation in the answer to J.H.
above, you'll probably see that while you could probably manage a
retirement with such a plan, it would be far from comfortable and
assured. I suggest you save (but not invest) as aggressively as you
can, and consider that a likely retirement age in the range 58 to
60 is more realistic than 55 to 57.
</P>
<P>
   As for investments, you don't supply information about the
available options, but I suggest you put about 50 percent of your
money in a large-cap domestic stock fund, ideally one managed to
duplicate the results of the Standard and Poor's 500 index. I would
then divide the remainder, more or less evenly, among a mid-cap
stock fund, a small-cap stock fund, an international (not global)
stock fund, and, if available, a health care fund.
</P>
<P>
   One strategy which might serve you well would be to adopt a
discipline of adding to your retirement savings each time you get a
raise, maintaining the 15 percent savings level. Thus with decent
raises, you would increase your accumulation and improve the
chances of retiring earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a 65-year-old retiree, recently widowed, and have
recently begun monthly withdrawals of $3,000 from my retirement
savings. My IRA consists of $63,000 in Vanguard Prime Money Market
fund, $123,000 in Vanguards Index 500, $52,000 in its Index Value,
$103,000 in its Balanced Index. I also have an IRA of $95,000 in a
bank CD, which will mature in six months. What can you suggest to
maintain the $3,000 monthly income stream as I move towards an
income-oriented portfolio? R.J., Oceanside, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. To be honest, in addition to quickly moving to a fixed-income
portfolio, I think you should rework your budget. If you achieved
average 6.5 percent portfolio returns, your sequence of $3,000
monthly withdrawals would deplete your savings in a little more
than 23 years. If you were able to manage a 10 percent reduction,
the sequence of withdrawals would stretch over 30 years before the
money is gone.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion would be to reduce the stock side of the portfolio
to no more than 20 percent, and to move the balance to fixed-income
holdings. Since all of the money is in IRA accounts, there will be
no short-term tax effect of changing your holdings, so I would work
out a portfolio where about 50 percent of your fixed-income money
is in Vanguard GNMA, about 20 percent in Vanguard High-Yield
Corporate Bond fund, and the rest in short-and-safe holdings such
as CDs, money markets, or the Vanguard Short-Term Corporate Bond
fund.
</P>
<P>
   If you do maintain 20 percent of your savings on the stock side,
your average portfolio returns should be a little better than the
6.5 percent upon which I based my calculations, thus providing you
with some protection against the inflation which is likely to come
in the later years of your retirement.
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
