<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD TILER, BAD GROUTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, October 17, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. The tiler did a good job of laying ceramic tiles on my
kitchen floor, but a lousy job of grouting. The grout lines are
sloppy, up to 1/4 inch wide, and are bumpy, not at all smooth. How
can I correct this? Can I put new grout over the grout that is
there now?
</P>
<P>
   RAY REICHEL, Quincy, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I am not sure he did such a hot job on the tile laying,
either, because 1/4 inch is a bit wide for space between tiles. You
can't do anything about those wide joints, and you can't put new
grout over the old. However, the joints might look 1/4 inch thick
because excess grout has gotten on the face of the tile; you will
find this out when you scrape out the old grout.
</P>
<P>
   The tiler should scrape out the grout and put new in, but if he
cannot or will not, then you have to do it yourself. My own tiler
asked if I would do the grouting because he knew I'd do it better
than he could. Well, flattery will get you anywhere, and the
handyman took the bait and did it. You can bet it's a good job.
</P>
<P>
   Dig out all the old grout to the full depth and full width of
the joints. You can buy a tool for this purpose, but a cold chisel
or extra-stiff-bladed knife will do. Then put in new grout, and put
it in very, very compactly; if you don't compact it completely, it
will fail in months.
</P>
<P>
   To grout, use a sanded grout, which is best for floors and for
wide joints.
</P>
<P>
   Mix the grout thoroughly so that it is just a shade
free-flowing, not crumbly as mortar should be. You could buy,
instead, a ready-mixed grout of the right consistency. Plop a large
dollop on the floor, and spread it into joints with a rubber
squeegee. And, press more into the joint with the edge of the
squeegee. Press and press and press! That's important. After 15
minutes or so, squeegee off excess grout from the face of the tile,
and a bit off the joints so that the grout fills the joint without
overflowing on the face of the tile. Then wipe the floor with a
damp sponge, well squeezed out. When the floor dries, it will leave
a dry haze of grout; wipe this off with a dry cloth.
</P>
<P>
   What color grout? You asked the wrong _ or right _ person. The
handyman suggests black, or a dark color, which will provide a nice
contrast to the tile and will not show the dirt, mildew and other
crud that gets onto and into light-colored grout.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Some of the joints in my mortared fieldstone foundation leak,
so I repointed them, filling them with hydraulic cement. So far, no
leaks. Can I skimcoat the foundation to help prevent future leaks
and make it look better than it does now?
</P>
<P>
   JIM KEATING, Melrose, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. A skimcoat might be good for looks, but unlikely to prevent
future leaks; the hydraulic cement, which expands as it sets, has
made very tight joints, and basically that is all you want. To
skimcoat, you have to apply a bonding agent to the foundation
first. So, instead, try this: Apply a coat of cement-based paint to
the wall; this is a powder that you mix with water and scrub on the
walls; it will not do much for the stone but will reduce seepage in
the joints. And it will look good.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How can I paint a galvanized steel garage? There is a lot of
peeling, and I'd like to know how to seal the finish and any paint
that remains after I scrape.
</P>
<P>
   CHRSTINE LARSON, Dedham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Paint does not need sealing, and it is not possible to seal
steel, galvanized steel, or other metal. But you can prime it.
Chances are fair to good that the old paint peeled because there
was no primer applied. To prepare, scrape and sand as much paint as
is going to come off. Then apply a primer; for metal the best
primer is a zinc-rich metal primer, usually the godawfulest yellow
color you ever saw. Finish with an oil-based house paint; latex
paint could cause rust spots to show where it hits bare steel. As
always, apply thin coats.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The paint on my house blisters only when it rains; the
blisters are full of water; it dribbles out when I break the
blisters. It happens mostly on the northeast side. What do I need:
New siding? Stain? Or new shingles?
</P>
<P>
   JIM MAHONEY, Foxborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. What you have is a water problem, originating behind the
shingles or clapboards or whatever wood you have on the house. As
for your other questions, no to siding; that only covers the
problem, and is ugly as sin anyway. Yes to stain; you could remove
all the paint and put on a semitransparent stain, which will
accommodate the water and not peel but might not be compatible with
the rest of the house. Yes to new shingles. You could remove all
those old shingles and put up white cedar shingles, let them
weather and never touch them for 40 years. That, too, might not be
compatible with the rest of the house, and it will not exactly
solve the water problem, but the water will go through the shingles
and should not cause any more things like those water-filled
blisters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
