<HEADER>
A8116 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-ROME-HNS &LR;      10-15 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ROME EVERYONE IS STYLISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL VIRTANEN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Rome, the women walk in high shoes and the men wear tight
pants and everyone is stylish.
</P>
<P>
   Almost half the people smoke, too, but they do it stylishly
especially on motor scooters rounding tight turns at 40 mph in a
crowd of fast, small vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The Romans are sleek and slender and smartly turned out and talk
to one another with cheerful animation, sometimes even while riding
on their motorbikes, called motorinas.
</P>
<P>
   The tourists from all over _ and there were a considerable
number considering it was low season in late August _ can be found
on the Spanish steps at any time of the day or evening. They lounge
on the stone stairs in the Roman sunshine and gather around the
fountain to cool off or take photographs of themselves and one
another.
</P>
<P>
   They're not so stylish as the Romans, but for tourists they're
pretty good. Perhaps most understand the standards set by the
Romans, or perhaps a little fashion rubs off after a few days.
</P>
<P>
   In a place of narrow streets, broad piazzas and extraordinary
beauty, in a culture deeply rooted in classical aesthetics, where
antiquities stand in the midst of day-to-day life, where dining out
is a leisurely four-course affair with wine and bottled water,
where cafes are as common as treasures in the 55 galleries of the
Vatican museum or stray cats by the Colosseum, it's difficult not
to be affected.
</P>
<P>
   For travelers, there's a hedonistic Mediterranean undercurrent,
as if the old Roman Empire faded but the toga party never quite
did, that living itself might be fine art _ a Botticelli or Bernini
sentient and in motion. Which is heady if you give yourself over to
it. Buona sera.
</P>
<P>
   Or else it's a conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   They lost my bag on the flight over, somewhere between
Philadelphia and the DaVinci airport. Or else it was held back in
customs, perhaps by the fashion police who examined its contents.
By our second afternoon in Rome, it was still missing, driving me
into the fashionable shops in the old city, near our hotel.
</P>
<P>
   In the shops, the clerks prefer to help you find a garment,
rather than letting you handle all their goods, and I came away
with a shirt and a pair of tight pants. (My wife and daughter had
found the shops much earlier and came away with shoes, sweaters,
I'm still not sure what else.)
</P>
<P>
   Late that evening, after a fine dinner at the rooftop cafe of
our small hotel, the Valadier, the missing bag arrived. The next
morning we left, taking the slow train north into Tuscany, heading
to an artful week at a flat in Florence, driving out one day for a
long, slow, sun-washed day at the beach at Viareggio. By now it was
September, low season at the coast, and many of the beach chairs
and umbrellas were unoccupied.
</P>
<P>
   The last afternoon, on the way back to Rome, we stopped to lunch
and stroll in the medieval hilltop city of Perugia, with its
university students and odd bloody history.
</P>
<P>
   Driving the rental car wasn't too difficult except the evening
we were lost on the winding, one-way streets of Florence, trying to
find the way back to the apartment. The Italian drivers were fast
but not aggressive in the American fashion, especially the stylish
women on the motorinas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
