<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8155 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-NOVELIST-GREEN16-COX     10-15 1377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOVELIST-GREEN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tim Green's latest career: Blockbuster novelist
 &HT;    By Paul Lomartire
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Tim Green, the success machine.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Books plans to make Green the next megamillion selling
author. A brand-name. The franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's exactly right,'' says Rick Wolff, Warner Books
executive editor. ``Tim's primed to become the next David Baldacci
or the next John Grisham ... the next big, blockbuster novelist.''
</P>
<P>
   Bet against Green at your peril. The former first-round NFL
draft pick for the Atlanta Falcons programmed himself from
childhood to be No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   At everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be the best. I was obsessed. In school, I couldn't
waste too much time fooling around with classmates. I had to
listen. One missed fact could mean the difference between an A and
an A-. In sports, if reckless abandon was required, I could do
that, too. If it didn't come naturally, I could learn it.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is Green writing about grade school.
</P>
<P>
   Besides writing books, he is a practicing attorney, National
Public Radio commentator, Fox TV NFL analyst, and USA Today
columnist.
</P>
<P>
   Life as a two-minute warning. Wasted seconds can beat you.
</P>
<P>
   But who is he playing against?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote a 300-page answer to that,'' he says, softly. ``I was
adopted as an infant. People would remark throughout my life that I
was driven, I was an overachiever. I was obsessed with winning and
goals and medals and achievement and honors and awards. A lot of
that, if not all of it, came from this sense of rejection at being
given away at birth.''
</P>
<P>
   Green's 1997 autobiography, ``A Man and His Mother: An Adopted
Son's Search,'' is an uncompromising self-examination. But while
that book came and went, his writing reputation grew with football
fiction. ``Double Reverse,'' in stores now, is his fifth novel, but
Warner Books is basing its battle plan on a book that will be in
stores next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Letter of the Law'' is a legal thriller that has nothing
to do with football. Its female protagonist, attorney Casey Jordan,
caught the attention of Warner's publisher, the head of sales and
the head of marketing. All women.
</P>
<P>
   ``They felt setting my books in a world of football is a huge
handicap,'' recalls Green. ``At first I was confused. It's my
identity. My editor said, `Do you think you can?' I said, `Of
course I can.'''
</P>
<P>
   Key to Green's rise, says Wolff, is an ability to create
powerful, believable, female characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I know women pretty well,'' says Green, ``but I'll
use my wife (Illyssa) as a sounding board for characters.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, 35, better know something about women, considering the
looks he gets at the Jacksonville Hilton bar as the Fox TV team
readies for a 49ers/Jaguars game.
</P>
<P>
   Men glance. Women stare.
</P>
<P>
   At 6 feet, 2 inches, the former linebacker/defensive end is a
bigger, stronger version of Tom Cruise. Retired as a player since
1993, Green is wearing a well-worn, gray New Orleans Saints
T-shirt. His red workout shorts connect six-pack abs to sinewy
legs. Finger-combed dark brown hair matches his high-school hero's
clay-smooth face.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff has seen women react to Green. ``We just may put his
picture on the book,'' Wolff says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Eight seasons with the Atlanta Falcons left Green with a bum
knee, bad elbows and a banged-up shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best analogy is a 1972 Impala,'' he says. ``Things just
loosened up on them and rattled, there's a lot of play in the
steering, but they're still going.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he can no longer run or swing a golf club, Green
finds time to work out _ even while working.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety percent of the time,'' says Kenny Albert, Green's Fox
TV partner the past four seasons, ``when I talk to him on the phone
at his home, he's on the treadmill. He's got one of those headset
phones. Or, he's in the car driving the kids somewhere. He won't
waste any time.''
</P>
<P>
   The weekend Fox TV work allows Green to be home in upstate New
York weekdays with Illyssa and their four kids, ages 2 to 9. A
typical week runs from practicing contract/business law to getting
his son to soccer practice.
</P>
<P>
   Says Albert, ``He's always on the move, nonstop energy, more so
than anyone I've ever worked with. He's one of the nicest, most
genuine people I've ever met, but he is a perfectionist.''
</P>
<P>
   The former ``Good Morning America'' correspondent barely watches
TV, sometimes ``The X-Files'' or a soccer game. Going to the movies
can drive him nuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in a bad mood if I go to a movie that I don't think is
good,'' he says. ``I can't stand to see a mediocre movie. That's
not acceptable because it's two hours of my time.''
</P>
<P>
   There's never enough time to read as much as he wants. James Lee
Burke, Cormac McCarthy, Dickens, Hemingway. Reading was revered
where he grew up.
</P>
<P>
   Green was adopted by a fourth-grade teacher and her computer
program designer husband near Syracuse, N.Y. But while he loves his
parents, sister and brother, not knowing anything about his birth
mother or father haunted him.
</P>
<P>
   Themed nightmares _ trapped with an impossible task that meant
certain failure and rejection _ began in a boy's bedroom and
continued to NFL hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   He was a high school all-everything in academics and athletics.
But his relentless push to perfection made him a big target. While
deciding between free-ride football scholarships from Penn State,
Ohio State, Syracuse and Notre Dame, Green's senior classmates
voted someone else best athlete. They voted him best brown-noser.
</P>
<P>
   ``They booed his valedictorian speech!'' says Greg Allen,
Green's senior producer at National Public Radio. ``Can you believe
that?''
</P>
<P>
   What defines Green these days, says Allen, ``is that he really
wants to give people what they want. He wants to make people happy
whether it's a listener, an editor or a coach. He does his best
work with you, and that's why he's a dream to work with. I wish all
the people I worked with were as easy as Tim.''
</P>
<P>
   Give people what they want and maybe they won't reject you.
</P>
<P>
   Co-valedictorian at Syracuse. Tops in his law class. No. 1 NFL
draft pick. But when it came to women, it got ugly for Green. He
remembers female rejection back to sixth grade when a girl dumped
him with a note passed in a hall.
</P>
<P>
   Fear of female rejection could suffocate relationships and
produce in him a jealous control-freak who could and would use sex
as a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was repulsive,'' he confesses in ``A Man and His Mother.''
</P>
<P>
   To stop the madness, it took a six-year search for his birth
mother that required cash, detectives, lucky breaks and friends
willing to break rules dealing with sealed adoption papers.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 27, playing for the Falcons, he found his birth
parents: She was a Philadelphia teacher and he owned a Seattle
computer software business.
</P>
<P>
   She got pregnant after a one-night indiscretion with a man
looking for fun, not a family. She was in college to earn the
degree that would be a one-way ticket out of her own poor,
fatherless home. She couldn't raise a baby. Her one request of the
adoption agency: he would go to a couple who were college-educated.
</P>
<P>
   When Green's personal mystery ended in 1991, so did his
obsession to excel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still kinda' go about things in the same way,'' he says,
``but I have a lot more equanimity about it. I don't have the same
desperate desire.''
</P>
<P>
   Sensing doubt, he quickly offers an example. His best-selling
book so far is ``The Dark Side of the Game,'' about his NFL years.
Publicity included ``60 Minutes.'' But the book made only a cameo
on the New York Times best-seller list. ``Why?,'' hesays,
``because they didn't have enough books out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Book business bumbling, he says, ``doesn't drive me nuts any
more because it is what it is. My wife gets crazier about it than I
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next book, `The Letter of the Law,' will have a chance
because Warner Books will line up behind it. Sooner or later, if
I'm meant to get there, I'll get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   But couldn't he be happier?
</P>
<P>
   The former obsessed overachiever laughs. ``No, I couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
