<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-FIGHT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FIGHT CLUB' IS A BLEAKLY FUNNY, NO-HOLDS-BARRED FILM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tyler Durden (Brad Pitt) offers to let ``Fight Club's'' unnamed
narrator (Edward Norton) stay at his place after an explosion has
demolished his modernist condo.
</P>
<P>
   He does this on the condition that the Narrator do him a favor:
`Hit me as hard as you can.'' He does, and eventually the two are
going at each other like animals, beating each other senseless
until the ecstasy is undeniable. They're in love, if not with each
other, then with one's recognition that the other is capable a
being a monster.
</P>
<P>
   David Fincher's bleakly funny, pitch-black ``Fight Club''
couldn't be any more on time if Domino's delivered it. Tyler and
the Narrator's live-in relationship runs the gamut from Oscar and
Felix to Ike and Tina to Rocky and Apollo and, ultimately, to John
McClane and (insert ``Die Hard'' demon here).
</P>
<P>
   It's the rawest, most hot-blooded, provocatively audacious,
dangerous movie to come of out Hollywood this year, serving as both
a supercharged spectacle and a scorching, though problematic screed
against materialism, consumption and vanity.
</P>
<P>
   The film has one of the most enthrallingly told first halves
you'll see, brought to you by a band of subversives on both sides
of the camera who are at the vanguard of their crafts, with a
particularly inventive and mind-blowing performance by Norton.
</P>
<P>
   This comes in spite of the film's deadly attempts in its last
act to visualize the supernatural-pyrotechnic lollapalooza that
happens toward the end of Chuck Palahniuk's 1996 novel, on which
``Fight Club'' is based.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler and the Narrator's inaugural parking-lot pummel is both
like a first-date shag and the start of a beautifully malevolent
friendship. The arrival of the crafty, chain-smoking Helena Bonham
Carter as Marla, the pseudo-suicidal sex interest, only ups ``Fight
Club's'' inverted ``Casablanca'' ante, as she hops in and out of
Tyler's bed.
</P>
<P>
   She's a walking Cure tune, made to look like a Wile E. Coyote
Acme bomb has just gone off in her face. Having her mewl the
``Theme from Valley of the Dolls,'' at one point, is a shrewd
touch.
</P>
<P>
   Fincher tweaks this sociopathic odd-coupling for its inherent
laughs. (Their massive, ramshackle house and its squalid insides
make a nice set piece for the mockery.) This material is the ideal
vehicle for the apocalyptic, anti-consumerist idea Fincher's been
working out since his music-video days and ``Seven,'' which was a
grisly rough draft for ``Fight Club's'' mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   Together, Tyler and the Narrator form Fight Club, an underground
support group through which angry males can unload on each other
until one of them has a really tough time getting up.
</P>
<P>
   Anonymous, cathartic and as thrilling as a one-night stand, it's
therapy- playtime-happy hour for blue- and white-collar men who've
had their inner barbarians sucked out of them by 40- to 70-hour
work weeks. (``We are our jobs,'' the film asserts.)
</P>
<P>
   It's a post-modern bathhouse for men who just don't feel
anymore; that pitch-black spot in a man's id where Susan Faludi's
research failed to go for her 800-page tome about disaffected,
emasculated American males.
</P>
<P>
   And Fincher, who's operating on full focus from a handsome Xerox
by Jim Uhls of Palahniuk's brilliant first novel, presents the
bludgeoning as an unsensationalized, if satirical inevitability.
This is simply what three decades of mixed popular-culture messages
will insidiously do to a man.
</P>
<P>
   Women eat or starve themselves or shop or talk. Men go South
Bronx on each other.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting is shot by the ingenious Jeff Cronenweth in mostly
real time under single bulbs in dank, limping color, without the
primal opera Martin Scorsese made of boxing in ``Raging Bull'' and
without any of the chemical-induced techno assaults in a video game
like ``Mortal Kombat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
