<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The steady secularization of
American higher education over the last hundred years has often
been viewed as an irresistible trend. Catholics leaders have
nonetheless declared themselves determined to resist it. Among
colleges with ties to Protestant denominations or other religious
groups, there is also a renewed desire to retain some distinctive
religious character. But opinions clash on how to do it. By Peter
Steinfels.
</P>
