<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8162 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-TEACHERS-REFORMS16-1S     10-15 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS-REFORMS16-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TOP TEACHERS SEEK BIGGER SAY IN EDUCATION REFORMS
 &HT;    Eds: Inserts new graf 12 with official's comment on education
reform panel.
 &HT;    550&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Top teachers from across the country vowed at the
seventh annual National Teachers Forum here to increase their
influence on the reforms that are transforming education in most
states.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are redefining what it means to be a teacher in 1999,''
Mary Beth Blegen, teacher in residence at the U.S. Department of
Education, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could continue to sit back and see ourselves as victims of
teacher-bashing or as worker bees at the bottom of a hierarchy,''
Blegen said. ``But most of us choose to say we understand kids and
teaching and learning, and we want to raise our voice beyond the
classroom and teach others in our schools and districts, and even
at the state level, what's realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   About 120 top-notch teachers _ including all 50 state teachers
of the year, many state finalists and 10 from private schools _
spent three days at the department and in a hotel in nearby
Alexandria, Va., discussing how to reshape details of the school
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all of them said many of their students had been
helped by higher academic standards and tests to assess progress,
but many said the reforms designed by governors, legislators,
businesses and universities need adjustments to work in today's
classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Ivie, who teaches 28 fourth graders in Aurora, Colo.,
said her state's legislators don't realize that today's teachers
can't handle classes as large as those in the days when she and
they were in school.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, she said, their teachers could concentrate on getting
average students through school, while the top one-third excelled
on their own and the lower one-third could still find a job if they
failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, when all children are expected to succeed, it's like
doing an individual learning plan for each child,'' she said.
``I've never had the luxury of teaching less than 25 children, yet
I must assess every single child's understanding and learning and
constantly make adjustments during the day in order to take each
kid up to the highest level.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A real sore spot'' in Texas is that the governor and state
education officials ``desperately need teacher advisers,'' said
Miriam Lancaster, who teaches six English classes at Pine Tree High
School in Longview. ``It could save money and it could save them
from going down the wrong avenues.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, she said, ``conflict resolution'' programs designed
to get children to avoid violence by talking about their
differences face to face ``no longer work with a lot of street
kids, because they see it as weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers are only three of the 64 members of the commission
formed by Gov. Roy Barnes to recommend education reforms in
Georgia, said middle school teacher Ernie Blankenship of
Loganville, Ga. ``It's a voice, but it's a small one, considering
that this is our lifelong profession,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Georgia commission includes six active teachers
and 18 former teachers, said the governor's education assistant,
Ron Newcomb.
</P>
<P>
   But some teachers want to work on local reforms as simple as
exchanging tips with teachers in classrooms across the hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Alaska, when we have a young sled dog, ...we put them in
harness with a calm, experienced, dedicated sled dog,'' said Daniel
Walker, who teaches at a combined middle and high school in
Anchorage. ``We can no longer put new teachers in the classroom,
wish them luck, and close the door.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, ``all our classrooms are wired, but a lot of teachers
aren't sure how to use technology effectively in the classroom,''
said Maureen Judy, an elementary school teacher in Maumee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my technology director to give me a few more computers
than normal, so that anybody could walk into my classroom and see
how we use it in the curriculum.''
</P>
<P>
   Before she can spread her techniques to other schools and
districts, research must be funded to find out whether her approach
is better than others, Judy said. ``Without a research base,
teachers won't even listen to you,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, where standardized tests were used this year to rate
schools on a scale from ``A'' to ``F,'' Ruby Zickafoose, who
teaches at a B-rated elementary school in Manatee County, would
like to find a way to channel more support to nearby schools with
lower ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel this has really caused a lot of bad morale,''
Zickafoose said. ``Teachers who know they are doing everything they
can are walking around with their chins down and this scarlet
letter 'D' on their chest.''
</P>
<P>
   She worries that signs on their school lawns, displaying
messages like ``100 Days Until the Test,'' show that solid courses
are being crowded out by hoopla and constant test-preparation
drills.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, which has had high-stakes tests for three
years, teachers still debate whether to emphasize pre-test drills
or ``authentic assessment and hands-on learning,'' said Marshall
Matson, whose language arts and social studies classes for seventh
graders in Tarboro, N.C., resumed after a two-and-a-half week gap
caused by floods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weird thing is, nobody's systematically collecting the
data to see which method works best,'' Matson said. ``I bet we'd
find it's a combination of the two, but right now nobody knows.''
</P>
<P>
   The teachers at this week's forum carefully avoided endorsing
any nationwide, cookie-cutter approach for all districts and
states.
</P>
<P>
   Montana, ``beautiful and broke,'' lacks the money to
``adequately fund education,'' so teachers at that state's forum
next spring will will skip educational theory and discuss ways in
which ``our economy must be turned around,'' said Dan Adcock, who
teaches at an elementary school in Missoula.
</P>
<P>
   Two South Carolina teachers said they hope to improve academic
performance by pushing for ``access by all children to health
care.''
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, described by high school teacher Joseph Bacewicz
of Tollano as ``one of the nation's wealthiest states, with three
of its poorest cities,'' he and other teachers are starting a
``Read Aloud'' program in a primary school in a poor neighborhood.
They hope that even functionally illiterate parents would come to
school once a week to hear their children take turns reading
stories aloud.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
