<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8164 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-CHAVEZ-BOLIVAR-$ADV-1     10-15 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAVEZ-BOLIVAR-$ADV-17-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAVEZ RESURRECTS A VENEZUELAN HERO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Oct. 17) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ Quiet as a library and featuring a musty
collection of documents, swords and medals, the Simon Bolivar
museum and birthplace isn't exactly Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to encouragement from President Hugo Chavez, throngs
of youngsters crowd the building every day. They come to learn
about the audacious general who freed much of South America from
Spanish rule in the 1800s and dreamed of a unified continent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bolivar liberated five nations. We want our kids to learn that
they, too, can be leaders,'' said Carmen Henriquez, a social worker
who recently brought a group of students from a poor Caracas
neighborhood to the museum on a bus provided by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Bolivar is considered the George Washington of South America for
winning the independence of modern-day Colombia, Venezuela,
Ecuador, Peru and Bolivia from Spanish domination.
</P>
<P>
   But under Chavez, who took office in February, the veneration of
Bolivar has reached new heights. A former army paratrooper and a
fiery populist, Chavez considers Bolivar a military genius, a
visionary and the perfect oracle for a country that, he believes,
lacks national pride and role models.
</P>
<P>
   But critics claim that Chavez is exploiting the image of Bolivar
to stir up nationalist sentiment and build support for his own
political projects.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez peppers his speeches with references to Bolivar. Instead
of the traditional presidential photo, portraits of Bolivar hang in
many government offices. During Independence Day ceremonies July 5,
the president whipped out one of Bolivar's old swords and waved it
to the cheering crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez even suggested renaming the country the Bolivarian
Republic of Venezuela. The idea was scrapped after studies
determined that it would cost $43 million to print new passports,
official documents and currency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of regime that we are promoting must be based on our
culture and our essence. Bolivar is our inspiration,'' said Luis
Miquilena, president of the Constitutional Assembly, which is
writing a new Magna Carta for Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Bolivar can be hard to resist. He even inspired a
novel ``The General In His Labyrinth'' by Gabriel Garcia Marquez.
</P>
<P>
   Born into a wealthy family in Caracas in 1783, Bolivar joined
the rebel army when war against Spain broke out in 1810. After a
series of victories, he entered Caracas in 1813 and was christened
``the Liberator.``
</P>
<P>
   Spain recaptured Caracas, and Bolivar went into exile. But he
returned to launch a series of surprise attacks and eventually
defeated Spanish forces at Boyaca in present-day Colombia. His
triumph is considered one of the great campaigns in military
history.
</P>
<P>
   Bolivar was named president of Greater Colombia, which was made
up of Colombia, Venezuela, Ecuador and Panama. His army later went
on to free Peru and Bolivia from Spanish domination.
</P>
<P>
   But Bolivar's vision of a united Spanish America was thwarted by
separatist movements and resistance to his own authoritarian ways.
Venezuela and Ecuador soon seceded from Greater Colombia, prompting
Bolivar to lament: ``We have plowed the sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Disillusioned and racked with tuberculosis, he died in 1830.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, many Venezuelans today say that Bolivar had the
right idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``When everyone else was thinking of making a separate country
out of every little piece of land, Bolivar wanted to make these
pieces into one country,'' said Frank Payares, a Caracas lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had built one great country, we could compete with the
United States. But now we have the opposite. Everyone is fighting
among themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez intones the glory of Bolivar at almost every public
appearance. Indeed, some analysts believe that Chavez views himself
as a modern-day ``liberator.''
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Leal, dean of the sociology department at the
University of the Andes in Bogota, said that Venezuela was ruled
for much of its history by military strongmen who considered
themselves the heirs of Bolivar and the saviors of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But before jumping into politics, Chavez spent 20 years in the
army. He formed a clandestine group of rebel officers called the
Bolivarian Revolutionary Movement 200 and launched an unsuccessful
coup attempt in 1992 against then-President Carlos Andres Perez.
</P>
<P>
   As president, Chavez has promised to free the nation from
poverty, graft and the stranglehold of traditional political
parties that ran Venezuela for the past four decades until his
election last December. Despite vast oil wealth, the majority of
Venezuelans are poor.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez is also promoting a different kind of South American
unity through regional trade alliances like the Andean Pact and
Mercosur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bolivar dreamed that America would come together, and now this
change is happening through economic integration,'' said Miquilena,
the president of the Constitutional Assembly. ``Bolivar was ahead
of his time.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Venezuelans seem to appreciate the government's
resurrection of Bolivar. Visits to the Bolivar museum are on the
rise. Many people supported renaming the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Venezuelans aren't very religious. If you don't believe in
God, it's no big deal. But if you say that you don't think much of
Bolivar, people will really come down hard on you,'' said Manuel
Caballero, a Venezuelan historian.
</P>
<P>
   Caballero added that, unlike other Latin American nations with
strong Indigenous cultures and a rich heritage, Venezuela lacks
swashbuckling figures and a sense of tradition. Bolivar, he said,
is one of the nation's few authentic heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Critics complain that Chavez is exploiting history for political
gain. They say that by wrapping his government in the aura of
Bolivar, Chavez can paint his political enemies as unpatriotic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has grossly monopolized the father of the country and has
converted him into a miraculous recipe'' for all of Venezuela's
ills, wrote columnist Alberto Barrera Tyszka in the Caracas daily
El Nacional.
</P>
<P>
   Heinz Sonntag, a political analyst at the Caracas research
center Cendes, adds that it makes little sense for Venezuela to
look backward on the cusp of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bolivar was a man of the 18th and 19th centuries,'' Sonntag
said.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Russia's president, he added: ``It would be like
Yeltsin pursuing the politics of Lenin.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
