<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8166 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV17-B     10-15 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV17-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DO YOU SINCERELY WANT TO BE RICH? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, October 17, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After Peter Lynch, the next best-known money man in Boston
probably is John Spooner. There is a world of difference between
the two. But their gospel is essentially the same.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch made jillions as manager of the Magellan Fund, is now best
known now as a pitch-man for Fidelity Investments. Spooner is a
novelist who has made millions for his customers in his day job as
a stockbroker, these days at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch has sold more books _ ``One Up On Wall Street'' and
``Beating The Street'' were huge best-sellers. But Spooner is the
more lively writer.
</P>
<P>
   His novels _ ``Class,'' ``The Foursome,'' ``The King of
Terrors,'' ``Three Cheers for War in General,'' and ``The
Pheasant-Lined Vest of Charlie Freeman'' _ are sly and telling
tales of life among the Boston ethnics that call to mind the
stories of George Higgins and John P. Marquand.
</P>
<P>
   His investment guides _ the classic ``Confessions of a
Stockbroker,'' ``Smart People,'' and ``Sex and Money'' _ convey the
flavor of markets in the 1960s, 1970s, and 1980s, much like those
of John Brooks (``The Go-Go Years'') and Jerry Goodman (who wrote
``The Money Game'' under the pen-name Adam Smith.)
</P>
<P>
   Now Spooner has summed up his distinctive approach to personal
investing in a little book called ``Do You Want To Make Money or
Would You Rather Fool Around?'' It offers very different counsel
from the myriad accounts of fabulous wealth creation in Silicon
Valley that are now tumbling off the presses _ of which Michael
Lewis' ``The New New Thing'' is far and away the best.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it is a deep and cheerful probing of the psychology of
personal investing from the point of view of someone who helps
manage half a billion dollars of other people's money. To be sure,
there is too much schtick for the taste of some; if it is how-to
advice you are after, you'll prefer the Globe's personal finance
columnist, Charles A. Jaffe. (Disclosure: I once went to a dinner
that Spooner attended. When I started to prepare this column, I
went to hear him talk. I manage my own money. But I read everything
that he writes.)
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the new book, Spooner says, ``If you are lucky
in life, you will know, and be friendly with, people who are older
than you.'' To which it might be added, the next best thing would
be to read these 60 short meditations on changes that have taken
place in financial markets over 40 years _ and the things that have
stayed the same.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in ``The Dinosaur Club,'' Spooner describes the
dinner meeting of three old friends from the institutional side of
the investment business. ``That means that they buy and sell stocks
and bonds to and from professional investors like banks, insurance
companies, and mutual funds,'' Spooner explains. These men are in
their late 50s; they drink See-Throughs (martinis); and they are
worried about a business that they fear has passed them by.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had street smarts,'' says one. ``We started at $5,000 a
year and were told to keep our eyes and ears open. Now the trading
desks only hire brilliant kids from the Ivy League at 80 grand. And
they don't want to look at anyone from commuter colleges. We'd
never get jobs in our firms if we were interviewing today.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Oldsters' complaints about the death of loyalty and the
rise of Edge slowly dissolve in a series of stories about the
securities business when it was was fun. The moral capital of their
friendship _ their Dinosaur Club _ becomes more clear. ``Make sure
you stop and think about what you are getting from the way you are
handling your money,'' advises Spooner. ``Do you just want to make
money? Or are you looking for a life?
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, in ``You Need a Net Youngblood in Your
Life,'' he makes the useful observation that, ``In living the smart
life, you always need something to trade.'' People are anxious for
a human touch, advice, personal counsel, he says; a friend once
traded the promise of a few fly-fishing lessons for Super Bowl
tickets. `` &UR; Today &LR; , almost all of us could use help from a
youngblood who is proficient in surfing the Net and can teach us
about the new world of cyberspace.'' Where to find one? Try your
own family first.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Buying on the News,'' Spooner analyzes investors who are
whipped into a frenzy by what they read in the papers. In ``Selling
Short,'' he reflects on his 1,700 clients scattered around the
world. ``No more than one of these people ever sell a stock short
in the space of a year. Why is this? Americans are optimistic
people _ they like betting for things, not against them.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Losing My Virginity,'' he recounts the story of firing a
client who wanted to find something to short the afternoon John F.
Kennedy was shot _ and how he came to regret his reluctance to take
his business. And so on.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Education of a Stockbroker,'' Spooner compresses his
autobiography into four lyrical pages about his family's Irish cook
_ gefilte fish, chopped liver, and cherry cheescake were her
specialties _ who taught him to sing ``Whiskey, You're the Divil''
before he learned ``America the Beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 30 years ago, when ``Confessions of a Stockbroker'' was
published under the pen-name ``Brutus,'' Spooner took advantage of
a good-natured book editor at this newspaper to review the book
under his own name (thus joining the ranks of self-puffing
deceivers whose ranks, my colleague Alex Beam has pointed out,
include Mark Twain and Ambrose Bierce). ``This cynical Brutus, who
can handle my money anytime. . .'' began the review. ``I almost
wish this Brutus were writing for the films or television,'' it
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Other Boston writers are better known. None is more financial.
As editor Nancy Gaines has written, Spooner is a singular figure,
godfather and gadfly, ``telling tales out of school while in a most
discreet profession, painting word-pictures of the city's caste
stystem while sitting atop it's social structure.'' He is, she
says, ``the outsider looking in, the insider looking out. . . He's
Harvard, Beacon Hill, bow ties, Brookline, Jew, wise ass.''
</P>
<P>
   He is also a national treasure.
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
