<SLUG> BC-GAY-MARRIAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLICS PUMP MONEY INTO ANTI-GAY MARRIAGE INITIATIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANASTASIA HENDRIX  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Catholic Church has contributed more than
$311,000 to support a California ballot initiative that seeks to
ban gay marriages.
</P>
<P>
   According to campaign finance reports filed with the secretary
of state, eight of the state's 12 Catholic dioceses have made
donations to support the measure that will appear on the ballot
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an issue we support, and we will be supporting it in
other ways as the campaign actually opens,'' said Carol Hogan,
spokeswoman for the California Catholic Conference, the public
policy arm of the state's 28 Roman Catholic bishops.
</P>
<P>
   Until this week, much of the fund-raising focus has centered on
the Mormon church, whose members have raised $3.6 million to
support the proposal by state Sen. William J. ``Pete'' Knight,
R-Palmdale.
</P>
<P>
   California law already defines marriage as between a man and
woman, and gay marriages would not be legalized if the initiative
fails. But the senator has said he is worried that another state
may eventually approve such unions, which in turn could be
recognized in California.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Knight's gay son, David Knight, spoke out against
his father's initiative for the first time in an opinion piece
published in the Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe, based on my experience, that his is a blind,
uncaring, uninformed, knee-jerk reaction to a subject about which
he knows nothing and wants to know nothing, but which serves his
political career,'' wrote David Knight, a Gulf War fighter pilot
who now works as a cabinetmaker in Baltimore and is estranged from
his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years ago, I told my father I was gay and that I have a
life partner, Joe. From that moment on, my relationship with my
father was over,'' Knight wrote. ``I can't begin to explain the
hurt that has come from this rejection.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator responded to the column by issuing a statement on
Thursday: ``I regret that my son felt he needed to force a private,
family matter into the public forum through an editorial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I don't believe he was fair in describing the true
nature of our relationship, that is a subject which should remain
between the two of us. I care deeply about my son.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing of David Knight's editorial, coming just as the
latest campaign contributions were made public, was applauded by
the opponents of the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is appropriate that it came out today because it really
sends a message to people supporting the initiative that it is an
anti-family measure, and that whether wittingly or not, they are
participating in something solely designed to separate people from
people and families from families,'' said Mike Marshall, campaign
manager for the opposition group Californians for Fairness.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall, who was raised Catholic and who attended Catholic
schools, called the church contributions stunning, hurtful and
disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of Catholics I know support the church
because of its commitment to social justice, not to be part of the
bishops' jihad against gays and lesbians,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Parishioners may not even be aware that the donations were being
made to the Protection of Marriage Committee because bishops
independently decided how much of the church budget to contribute,
said Roberta Ward, spokeswoman for the Diocese of San Jose, which
donated $24,130.
</P>
<P>
   The eight dioceses that made contributions for the July 1 to
Sept. 30 period were:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Roman Catholic Archbishop of Los Angeles, $144,998.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Roman Catholic Bishop of Orange, $36,498.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Roman Catholic Diocese of San Diego, $35,072
</P>
<P>
   _ The Roman Catholic Bishop of San Bernardino, $29,436.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Roman Catholic Church of Sacramento, $25,542.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Diocese of San Jose, $24,130.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Catholic Bishop of Monterey, $10,742.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Roman Catholic Bishop of Fresno, $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   The combined $311,418 is a fraction of the total amount raised
by the Protection of Marriage Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In the 90 days covered by the filing, the anti-gay marriage
group raised $3,119,494.04, bringing the total raised to date to
$3,863,165.04 documented.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the campaign statement filed for the same time
period by the opposition campaign, Californians for Fairness,
raised about $900,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
