 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Saturday, Oct. 16. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-MOOD (Rawalpindi, Pakistan) _ In the bazaars of
Rawalpindi, life goes on as it did before Pakistan was plunged into
a state of emergency by its new military ruler. But if there is
such a thing as a good coup, this one is winning raves in
Rawalpindi. By Tim Weiner and Steve Levine.
</P>
<P>
   NOBEL-PEACE-PRIZE (Paris) _ Medecins Sans Frontieres, which
sends doctors and nurses to some of the most destitute and
dangerous parts of the world and encourages them not only to save
lives but to condemn the injustices they see, was awarded the Nobel
Peace Prize on Friday. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-WESTBANK (Neve Erez, West Bank) _ Prime Minister Ehud
Barak's soldiers are unlikely to face much resistance when they
arrive to dismantle this illegal settlement, one of many
settlements that will be shut down. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL &LR;  (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS&AMP;CLARK-INDIANS (Salmon, Idaho) _ Spurred on by a surge of
interest in the journey of Lewis and Clark and in Sacajawea, the
Lemhi woman who guided them, the Lemhi Indians have asked President
Clinton to carve out a small piece of federal land on the
Idaho-Montana border as a place where the tribe can tell their
story to the hordes of Lewis and Clark history buffs and try to
stitch some of the past to the present. By Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley of New
Jersey, rankled by Vice President Al Gore's new line of attack on
his loyalty, defends his decision to retire from the Senate. A
reconstruction of the 1996 events. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-CORZINE-CAMPAIGN (Trenton, N.J.) _ When Jon S. Corzine first
began talking about running for U.S. Senate from New Jersey in
February, there were at least 300 million reasons for fellow
Democrats to listen. Corzine, 52, was about to retire as the chief
executive of Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co., with a $300 million fortune, and
he has pledged to spend as much as necessary to run a campaign to
replace Sen. Frank Lautenberg, who is retiring. By David
Kocieniewski.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   STARR-SUCCESSOR (Washington) _ A federal judicial panel has
selected Robert Ray, a 39-year-old prosecutor, to succeed Kenneth
Starr as the Whitewater independent counsel. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ A jittery stock market moved sharply lower
Friday after Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan again
expressed concern about the high level of stock prices and an
inflation report showed prices rising at an unexpectedly rapid
rate. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-JITTERS (Washington) _ Prices at the producer level shot up
1.1 percent in September, the biggest monthly increase in nine
years, the government reported Friday. The report stoked fears
among investors that inflation might be accelerating, and helped
set off a wave of selling on Wall Street. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
</TEXT>
