A8171 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TOILET-REPLACEMENT16-     10-15 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOILET-REPLACEMENT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Get a handle on toilet repair
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If you've moved into a new house or replaced a
toilet in the past five years or so, you may look back on your old
toilets with nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   Old-fashioned toilets do a dirty job with a minimum of fuss and
bother. And although some of the moving parts needed to be replaced
occasionally, the sturdy tank and bowl could last forever.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of toilets available for sale now are still as tough
as nails, but they may not function with the effortless grace of
their ancestors. That's because federal water-conservation
regulations dictate that new toilets must do the same work as old
toilets with about one-quarter as much water.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional toilets use about 6 gallons of water per flush;
newer toilets must make do with 1.6 gallons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's having trouble with water-conserving toilets,''
said Tom Long, salesman for A-Atherton Plumbing Co. in Dayton.
``They just can't handle solid wastes and paper without two or
three flushes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting so bad people are going to start going back to
digging a hole in the back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   If you've got an older toilet, there are usually ways to keep it
working effectively and without leaks. Perhaps if you can hold on
to the older model for a few years, federal regulations may ease,
and you'll be able to buy a new toilet with greater water capacity.
</P>
<P>
   But if you really want to replace a toilet now, it's a job most
average do-it-yourselfers can handle.
</P>
<P>
   TOILET MAINTENANCE
</P>
<P>
   Most toilet leaks can be traced to two sources: a bad seal over
the flush valve or a shut-off device that fails to shut off when
the tank is full.
</P>
<P>
   The flush valve is the hole at the bottom of the tank at the
back of the toilet. When you depress the handle to flush the
toilet, you're actually lifting a rubber stopper out of the flush
valve.
</P>
<P>
   Check the stopper first. Cut off the water supply by turning off
the supply valve, which should be under the toilet on the left.
Flush to get the water out of the tank.
</P>
<P>
   The stopper should have the pliable feel of fresh rubber. If it
is stiff or cracked, replace it. A replacement stopper costs no
more than about $5 in any hardware or home-improvement store.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the problem is in the chain or metal rod that lifts
the stopper. Work the mechanism a few times without water in the
tank to be sure the stopper always lifts and drops smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   If the lifting arm moves more than half an inch before starting
to pull the plug open, reduce the slack in the lifting chain or the
metal rod.
</P>
<P>
   The device that shuts off water when the tank is full is called
a ballcock. Adjusting a ballcock that doesn't shut off properly is
usually simple.
</P>
<P>
   Many tanks have a float ball at the end of a metal arm. If the
water does not shut off about an inch from the top of the overflow
tube, grasp the arm and bend it gently to push the float ball
lower.
</P>
<P>
   Some toilets have ``cup floats'' that are positioned around the
body of the ballcock. These are adjusted by squeezing a metal clip
and sliding the cup down to make the water shut off sooner.
</P>
<P>
   A few toilets have pressure valves that don't use floats at all.
They are adjusted by turning a screw counterclockwise, half a turn
at a time, to reduce the water level.
</P>
<P>
   If none of these adjustments work, you can replace the ballcock
for about $10.
</P>
<P>
   This operation involves removing two or three bolts and takes
only about 15 minutes if the bolts holding the old ballcock in
place and the water-supply tube are in good condition. If they're
badly corroded, you may need a plumber to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   REPLACING A TOILET
</P>
<P>
   Modern toilets come in two basic types: gravity-fed and
pressure-assisted. Long said gravity-fed toilets sell for about
$150.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure-assisted toilets use compressed air along with water to
help clear solid waste, and they're typically more effective at
handling solid waste than gravity-fed toilets. But they're noisy
and usually cost about $325 to $350, Long said.
</P>
<P>
   Stores that sell replacement toilets probably will have
brochures or instruction sheets to give you the basics on replacing
a toilet. Two other excellent sources of tips are the books ``The
Complete Photo Guide to Home Repair'' from Black &AMP; Decker and
``Home Improvement 1-2-3'' from Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, though, you'll follow these steps:
</P>
<P>
   _ Shut off the water supply to the toilet and flush to remove
water from the tank. Use sponges to remove remaining water from the
tank and bowl.
</P>
<P>
   _ Disconnect the water-supply line. Remove the bolts holding the
tank to the bowl (unless you have a one-piece toilet) and set the
tank aside. Pry off the protective caps over the bolts holding the
toilet to the floor and remove them. You may have to hacksaw the
bolts if they are badly corroded.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rock the bowl from side to side to break the seal and then tip
it on its side. Have lots of rags standing by in case there is
water left in the bowl. Stuff a rag into the drain pipe to block
sewer smells.
</P>
<P>
   _ Scrape off the wax around the flange that held the old toilet
to the floor. Clean it with a stiff wire brush and disinfect it
with bleach.
</P>
<P>
   _ Place a fresh wax ring and rubber drain sleeve over the bottom
of the new toilet. Take out the rag plugging the drain and press
the toilet down onto the flange to spread the wax ring and create a
tight seal. Bolt the bowl in place.
</P>
<P>
   _ Attach the tank and install any hardware needed inside the
tank. Attach the water supply and test the mechanism. The last step
is adding a toilet seat.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
