<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-NUBIANS-$ADV17-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NIGHT OUT WITH LES NUBIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17) 
(af) 
 By LOLA OGUNNAIKE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Bonjour,'' ``Merci beaucoup'' and ``Je m'appelle''
flew around the balcony of the Bowery Ballroom on Monday night as
fans eager for autographs flexed what little they remembered of
French 101.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere we go people try to speak French to us,'' said
Celia Faussart, the younger half of Les Nubians, the hot Afro-soul
duo that is proving that fine wine isn't the only popular export
from Bordeaux these days. ``Sometimes we don't understand what
they're saying, but it's good that they try.''
</P>
<P>
   At their first major concert in New York, Celia, 21, and Helene
Faussart, 24, played to a sold-out crowd with a five-piece band and
a spoken-word poet in dreadlocks.
</P>
<P>
   They performed songs from their award-winning debut album,
``Princesses Nubiennes,'' Sade-esque lounge grooves laced with
hip-hop and ``Afropean'' rhythms. (They have a French father and a
Cameroonian mother.) Fans who wanted to meet the latest young divas
of the downtown music scene mobbed the sisters before they
retreated backstage.
</P>
<P>
   Preparing for their only night on the town, Celia and Helene
changed from the vintage halter dresses they wore onstage into
Coca-Cola sweatsuits. (Coke is sponsoring their 20-city tour.)
Known as much for their Afro-chic style as for their music, the
sisters dressed up their sweats with matching head wraps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It suits me perfectly,'' Helene said to her sister. ``But it
doesn't suit you at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring the playful dig, Celia wrapped her burgundy pashmina
shawl around herself and looked sullenly at a plate of crudites.
``I'm in New York,'' she announced. ``I'm starving, and I need good
food.''
</P>
<P>
   So the sisters and their entourage of 15 (local friends and a
Frenchwoman who had won a ``Night Out With Les Nubians in New
York'' contest sponsored by a French hip-hop magazine) headed to
First, an American bistro on the Lower East Side.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arriving, Helene looked disappointed. ``Why no Balthazar or
Casimir?'' she asked, standing outside in the cold night air,
smoking a Marlboro Light. After Celia explained that the kitchens
were closed at those places, Helene went inside and nestled into a
leather banquette.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate New York restaurants because they are so
conceptual,'' she said, admiring the silver auto-radiator hose
clamps serving as napkin holders.
</P>
<P>
   The Faussart sisters go for high-concept stage makeup, too:
their arms were still covered in glitter, and white dots lined
their brows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Makeup helps bring magic to the stage,'' Celia said, swabbing
her T-zone with a Ponds facial wipe. ``But I don't really like to
wear it.''
</P>
<P>
   Between bites of beef carpaccio and tuna au poivre, the sisters
surveyed the wine menu. ``You know why I love New York?'' Helene
asked. ``Because I can find wine from every country here. This is
paradise for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, she ordered a bottle of sparkling white from Bordeaux,
and the talk turned to guys. ``I wanted to marry Lenny Kravitz
until someone at the label told me he was too short for me,'' said
Helene, who is 5-foot-8. ``But Method Man is tall, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Around 2 a.m., they were feeling the effects of their 18-hour
day. ``We don't usually have this many people around, because
generally I don't like to talk much after performances,'' Helene
said. Then her exhausted face brightened. ``But it's New York, and
here you have to have fun with everyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
