<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANTING IN DIFFICULT AREAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Oct. 17) 
(jt) 
 By CASS PETERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's possible to have too much of a good thing in a garden. The
danger is not so much in overplanting one thing _ say, German
irises or cottage roses _ and leaving no room for anything else,
but in planting something that decides to take over.
</P>
<P>
   Gardeners who foolishly plant houttuynia, that multicolored
ground cover commonly called chameleon plant, will understand the
problem. A modest patch of houttuynia quickly becomes a juggernaut,
marching inexorably across the soil in defiance of all efforts to
curb its migration.
</P>
<P>
   The same can be said for most varieties of bugleweed,
buttercups, pachysandra and a host of other plants that would be
more useful, and more charitably described by garden writers, if
they were more mannerly.
</P>
<P>
   The silver fleece vine that I planted at the foundation of a
toolshed _ thinking it would drape prettily over the roof, with
cascades of white flowers in the autumn _ has decided instead to
engulf the shed.
</P>
<P>
   Every strand that escaped from the original trellis and touched
the ground promptly rooted, and the vine has moved the full length
of the building, wrapping around it like living luggage straps. It
even grows inside the shed, so that I have to hack my way through
pale, sun-starved vines every time I want to retrieve a tool.
</P>
<P>
   So it is with some trepidation that I recommend lily of the
valley as a fine plant for those difficult areas that are both
shady and dry. Most yards have such places at the base of trees or
under shrubs, where there is too little sunlight for grass and too
little moisture for most ground covers.
</P>
<P>
   Lily of the valley (Convallaria majalis) is perfect for such
places. It stays low, rarely exceeding eight inches in height, and
its foliage stays green all summer. The flowers are tiny waxy bells
on stiff stems, so deliciously fragrant that lily of the valley is
a popular scent for perfumes. Unfortunately, the season of bloom is
short. In my garden in south-central Pennsylvania, lily of the
valley blooms for only a week or so in mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   If the spot is truly dry and shady, lily of the valley will
remain demurely where you plant it, venturing out only as far as
the edge of the nearest lawn, where the mower can keep it in check.
</P>
<P>
   But if there is any sort of natural pathway from the dry spot to
one that is more fertile and moist, the lilies will find it in a
New York minute. They spread by rhizomes that travel horizontally
underground, so you may not notice they're on the move until they
pop up some distance away. The next time you look, they will be
bullying the begonias in the flower beds, crowding out the crowns
in the strawberry patch and harassing the herbs in the kitchen
garden.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Jefferson's garden records suggest that he planted lily
of the valley among his anemones and trolliuses. If the garden had
more than lily of the valley blooming in that spot after a couple
of years, it was only because of regular and thorough human
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Where it can be contained, however, the plant is both delightful
and easy. It's best planted in October, after frost, but before the
ground freezes hard.
</P>
<P>
   What you plant are called pips, the combined roots and crowns,
which are readily available at garden centers or through mail-order
catalogs in the fall. These should be planted three or four inches
apart, and the tips covered with an inch of soil. A light mulch
after the ground freezes is a good idea the first year, to keep the
pips from heaving out of the ground before they are well rooted.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the plants need only a light top dressing of compost
or a sprinkling of fertilizer in October to keep them happy.
</P>
<P>
   If the leaves start to get small and the plants stop blooming
well, they're overcrowded. In that case, dig out large clumps after
frost has killed the foliage in October and refill the empty spaces
with fresh soil. The remaining clumps will quickly recolonize the
bed.
</P>
<P>
   Do not succumb to the temptation to plant those clumps elsewhere
in the garden unless you yearn for a monoculture of lily of the
valley. If you don't have friends who want them and don't want to
waste them, you can force them into bloom indoors.
</P>
<P>
   To do this, choose pips with thick crowns, which indicate that
there are many growing tips clustered together. (The more growing
tips, the more flowers the plant will have.) Avoid lopsided crowns,
which may produce deformed foliage and flowers. Cut the roots back
to about three inches, and plant about a half-dozen pips in a
six-inch-diameter flower pot, just barely covering them with soil.
</P>
<P>
   Water the pot well, and put it in a cool, semidark place until
the pips start to sprout. This will take a couple of weeks; be sure
that the pot doesn't dry out in the interim.
</P>
<P>
   When you see sprouts, put the pot in a warm spot, again being
sure the soil doesn't dry out. You'll have fragrant blooms in a
couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The flowers still last only about a week, but if you prepare
several pots of pips and leave the pots outdoors to freeze, you can
bring new ones in periodically all winter for forcing. Lily of the
valley is never invasive when it's in a pot on a windowsill. It's a
wonderful way to enjoy a good thing you have too much of.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
