<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8183 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-CELEBS-ALTER-EGOS-$AD     10-15 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELEBS-ALTER-EGOS-$ADV17-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY SOME CELEBRITIES CHOOSE ALTER EGOS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(dw) 
 By FRANK DeCARO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the release of his ``In The Life of Chris Gaines'' CD three
weeks ago, Garth Brooks traded in the cuddly, love-handled appeal
that helped him sell almost 100 million albums for the brooding,
eyeliner-wearing visage of a pop rock alter ego no one had ever
heard of.
</P>
<P>
   For the album cover, Brooks, the balding country superstar, put
on a tousled black wig and a clump of hair beneath his lower lip,
and got more grief from critics than the Village People got when
they put on face paint and poet shirts for their 1981 New Wave
album, ``Renaissance.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, who is 37 and a promising actor if his stint as the host
of ``Saturday Night Live'' is any indication, has been accused of
having too much time on his hands by one rock critic; another
called the album the self-indulgent product of a midlife crisis.
</P>
<P>
   His radically altered look resembles ``Trent Reznor crossed with
a guy who eats a lot of cheese steaks,'' wrote Time magazine.
Rolling Stone theorized that Brooks is ``letting his Yankee freak
flag fly'' by assuming the persona of a fictional 32-year-old rock
star who, as his fictional bio goes, has been racking up hits since
1989.
</P>
<P>
   We are in a season of alter egos. Dame Edna Everage, the
creation of the Australian character actor Barry Humphries, opens
Sunday night on Broadway in ``Dame Edna: The Royal Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   In bookstores, Edmund Morris' life of Ronald Reagan, ``Dutch,''
features an alter ego of the biographer, decades older than the
real Morris, who wanders in and out of his subject's life in
fictionalized encounters.
</P>
<P>
   This sort of artistic license makes some critics very nervous.
``Dutch'' has occasioned a firestorm of rebuke. Rolling Stone,
reporting on Brooks, ventured, `` `In The Life of Chris Gaines'
suggests that the singer is confronting some serious identity
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   More likely, Brooks is simply engaging in the human equivalent
of cross marketing, acting a role as a means to reach an audience
he has not yet tapped. ``In The Life of Chris Gaines,'' a mock
greatest hits CD, was No. 2 last week on the Billboard pop chart.
Morris is thought to have become exasperated by the ineffability of
his subject and sought higher truth in a fictional device.
Whatever, he's selling a lot of books.
</P>
<P>
   The intensity of the criticism of all this role-playing is
surprising. Alter egos, after all, are not exactly an unprecedented
career move. Two decades ago, David Bowie unveiled his most famous
alter ego, Ziggy Stardust _ which also was initially derided as too
strange for words.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, in the performance world, barrier breakers like
RuPaul have made drag more acceptable to the mainstream. Strangely,
these days a man dressing as a woman seems to be more acceptable
than him dressing as another man. When a man changes stripes as
convincingly as Brooks does with Chris Gaines, people get
frightened. Costumes, they can handle. Multiple personalities,
perhaps not.
</P>
<P>
   The question is why some performers feel the need to immerse
themselves in a character so deeply? Is it, as drag queens often
say, that they have too much style, talent and personality for one
person? Or is it, to paraphrase the film director Peter Farrelly,
``a very commercial form of mental illness?''
</P>
<P>
   Farrelly was speaking of the actor Jim Carrey, who stars as the
late comedian Andy Kaufman in the upcoming film ``Man On The
Moon.'' Kaufman's alter ego, a piggish lounge singer named Tony
Clifton, was as troublemaking as Kaufman's other famous character,
Latka Gravas on ``Taxi,'' was endearing.
</P>
<P>
   During the making of the film, it was widely reported that
Carrey lived the role of Kaufman on some days and assumed the guise
of Tony Clifton on others. Employing Method acting techniques,
Carrey simply did not exist during the filming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me a little time to get used to it, but it was a
wonderful game to play,'' said the director, Milos Forman, in a
cover story on Carrey in the October issue of Vanity Fair.
</P>
<P>
   Secretly most people have alter egos; they just don't make
albums or appear on stage as them. We employ these alternate
personas to say and do what we in our everyday guise cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Dame Edna verbally shish-kebobs her audience every night in a
way that the more bookishly reserved Humphries would never do.
Brooks can indulge his rock-and-roll fantasies without alienating
his country audience. Whether unleashing an alter ego is cathartic
or schizophrenic is anyone's call.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jeff Roberson, a former advertising art director at Foote, Cone
&AMP; Belding, found his voice not by becoming a latter-day Darren
Stevens of ``Bewitched,'' but by becoming a red-haired diva named
Varla Jean Merman. His alter ego, the supposed daughter of Ethel
Merman and Ernest Borgnine, was created nine years ago as a way for
Roberson to deal with the anxiety of being overweight.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got thinner I had to change my material,'' he said
recently on the phone. These days, he is playing Rhonda Skidmore, a
murderous little girl in blond braids, in ``The Bad Seedling,'' a
parody suggested by ``The Bad Seed,'' on stage at Mother, a
nightclub in the meatpacking district.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that's not true. Varla Jean Merman is playing Rhonda.
Even he has trouble keeping it straight. ``It's strange being in a
play, playing a character, and being billed as someone else,'' he
said. ``When I'm acting, it's not even me, it's Varla. So who am I?
I'm nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   The delicate relationship between a man and his alter ego can be
strained at times. ``When I moved, I had to tell Varla she couldn't
live in this new apartment, it was too small,'' said Roberson,
amused by the notion. ``I had to get a storage space for her. She's
living in Manhattan Mini Storage with the other homeless people.''
But it's not as bad as it sounds, he maintains. ``Her storage unit
is almost as big as my apartment,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
