<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8186 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-LOVESTORY1STTAKE17-CO     10-15 1329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOVESTORY1STTAKE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Uncovering love story between celebrity Georgia author and teen
poet
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 17.
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was a celebrity author, a nationally known newspaper
columnist and 78 years old. &QR;   &QR;  She was a poet, a starry-eyed fan
and only 16. &QR;   &QR;  They exchanged letters for two years in the
mid-1930s. What started as avuncular advice from the literary elder
statesman became something more. He was obviously smitten. Through
the mail, romance bloomed. &QR;   &QR;  Then it was over. She stopped
answering his eloquent typewritten notes. And though he continued
to promote her poetry in his newspaper column, his letters trailed
off as well. &QR;   &QR;  And so the story of Harry Stillwell Edwards,
Macon's second most famous writer, and Rebecca Griffin, ``Tifton's
poet laureate,'' also would have ended. But 60 years later, a
treasure chest of mementos from Griffin's life, stored in a dusty
Austell attic, came into the hands of Sherry Mullinax, and hearts
throbbed all over again.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Tears just rolled when I read,'' says Mullinax, 52,
a Stockbridge (Ga.) mother of four, who became fascinated not just
by the romance but by this glimpse of a forgotten chapter in
Georgia's literary past.
</P>
<P>
   In the blast-furnace summer of 1996, Mullinax was helping Bill
Greene, a retired construction company owner, as he carted boxes of
papers and books out of the attic of his house in Austell. Greene
was once married to Griffin's late daughter-in-law, and the Austell
house was once hers.
</P>
<P>
   The papers were destined for the burning barrel, but a glimpse
of an old book made Mullinax put several boxes aside. Days later
she was still reading Griffin's scrapbooks and journals,
sketchbooks and poetry. And the 50 letters from Edwards were the
icing: articulate, romantic, ornate and thoroughly 19th century.
Mullinax lost herself in an antique world of courtly gentlemen,
beautiful ladies and heartfelt verse. Then she found Harry's
photograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found this picture and I thought, `God, what an elegant,
elegant man!''' Mullinax says. ``The way he wrote, the way they
talked to each other, it was like something you'd see in the
movies, it was like I was back there listening to their
conversations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called (her sister) Barbara and said you need to come over
and check this out. I'm living back in the past with this excellent
gentleman.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax and her sisters Barbara Dumas, 54, and Rose Hammond,
53, were hardly the types to be entranced by a Deep South fairy
tale. None had ever heard of Edwards or Griffin, nor were they fans
of Georgia literature. Atlanta residents since the early 1980s,
they grew up in southern Michigan, part of the sprawling Gale
family, a working-class assemblage of 13 children from two sets of
parents. They spent time in foster care, or with relatives or
grandparents, and life was hard. But their hearts were softened by
this love story, and they decided they needed to find out who Harry
and Becky were, if they could.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;  A rising literary star
</P>
<P>
   The man who drew them into his life was still dashingly handsome
in his late 70s. He was erect and slim, his features distinguished
by calm eyes, a Roman nose and a mustache luxuriant as a gray pushbroom. A one-minute snippet of film in family hands, probably from
1937, shows a poised H.S. Edwards in a wide-brimmed fedora, his
vest and tie immaculate, a cigarette held in his left hand, a cane
hooked over the right.
</P>
<P>
   Though advanced in years, he was at, or near, the peak of his
celebrity. In 1919, Rudyard Kipling had praised his enormously
successful ``Eneas Africanus.'' Franklin D. Roosevelt sent him
birthday greetings in 1935, and two years later Henry Ford made a
special trip to Macon to meet the author, bringing a gift of a
brand-new car. Among the dozens of scrapbooks, photo albums,
letters and journals in Griffin's cache were clippings of news
stories about Ford's visit, during which he pronounced Edwards fit
for the office of U.S. poet laureate. (Edwards, who had been
friends with Macon's most famous writer _ poet Sidney Lanier _
demurred, insisting that he was no poet, but a writer of
``verse.'')
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1855, one of 10 children, Harry Stillwell Edwards came
from a wealthy Macon family. But the Civil War, and the death of
his father and a brother, turned their fortunes upside down, and at
age 8 Harry was delivering The Macon Telegraph to earn money for
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in a house on College Street, he took a special
interest in the young women of nearby Wesleyan College, where he
would frequently stray with his guitar to serenade a crowd of
sweethearts.
</P>
<P>
   He was known to sneak onto the closely guarded campus at night
to ring the college bell, just to let the young women know he was
thinking about them. This practice once prompted the college
president to take a shot at him.
</P>
<P>
   One of those Wesleyan sweethearts, Mary Roxie Lane, would become
Edwards' wife in 1881, the same year he would purchase part
ownership of the newspaper he had once delivered. They had five
children.
</P>
<P>
   In 1886, at the suggestion of his wife, Edwards sent a piece of
short fiction, ``Elder Brown's Backslide,'' to Harper's Monthly
magazine. This inaugurated a successful career in magazine fiction,
and he left the Telegraph (where he was editor and publisher)
shortly thereafter to concentrate on contributing stories to
publications such as The Saturday Evening Post, Atlantic Monthly,
Scribners and Century Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   During a breakneck 23-day burst of productivity in 1895 he wrote
his first novel, ``Sons and Fathers,'' which won the eye-popping
$10,000 first prize in a contest sponsored by the Chicago Record.
Edwards spent some of the prize money buying bicycles for the
neighborhood children.
</P>
<P>
   His greatest success was ``Eneas Africanus,'' a long short story
about the post-Civil War wanderings of a former slave, published
first in The Macon Evening News in 1919. Reprinted as a small book,
it is reported to have sold more than 3 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to fame as a writer, Edwards gained a reputation as
a speaker, touring the Lyceum Circuit on a bill with James Whitcomb
Riley and Edgar ``Bill'' Nye. He dabbled in politics, speaking at
the 1904 Republican National Convention in Chicago to second the
nomination of Theodore Roosevelt. He also made an unsuccessful run
for the U.S. Senate in 1920, campaigning as a Progressive
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;  Writer to writer
</P>
<P>
   After Mary Roxie Edwards died in 1922, Edwards began writing a
column called ``Coming Down My Creek'' for The Atlanta Journal,
which consisted of lighthearted sketches of everyday life in Bibb
County and environs. He often retreated to write at Kingfisher
Cabin, a rustic log house in the woods on Holly Bluff, his
two-square-mile Macon plantation.
</P>
<P>
   It was probably the column that, in 1934, caught the attention
of Becky Griffin of Tifton, a high school journalist and aspiring
poet. A photo from the time shows a dark-eyed girl with a broad
grin.
</P>
<P>
   She sent him letters and poems, and he responded, encouraging
and praising her ability. ``I want to see you develop into a
success dear little Sunshine Lady,'' he wrote her in February, ``to
fling you the torch if I have one.''
</P>
<P>
   In his column of April 26, 1934, Edwards reprinted the
three-stanza poem she had written to him for his 79th birthday
(April 23), ``To You My Friend,'' which includes the lines: ``O
lover of the flow'rs and the birds, / the love I bear for you is
far / Too sweet for idle words. ... O writer of the Cabin and the
Creek, / You are my friend, tho' I, for life's / Ambition, still
must seek.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards didn't identify the poet, except as a ``16-year-old
whose path I cheered a little in this column some months ago. And
of course I am her slave henceforth and forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1713EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8187 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-LOVESTORY2NDTAKE17-CO     10-15 2133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOVESTORY2NDTAKE17-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA: slave henceforth and forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The poem _ and a clipping of the column _ are among the
treasures Mullinax and her sisters rescued. A few days after the
column appeared, Edwards wrote to Griffin privately to say, ``I am
terribly in love with you _ a deep genuine love it must be, since I
have never seen you and know you only in my dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   The next month Edwards traveled to Becky's hometown of Tifton,
where she was a junior at Tifton High School and her father was
manager of the Ritz movie theater. The school had dedicated its May
graduation ceremony to Edwards, with speeches lauding his merits as
a unique man of Southern letters.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards addressed the admiring group and read from his own work,
and also, approvingly, from the work of Miss Griffin.
</P>
<P>
   In his column of May 27, he wrote of the ceremony, and of
meeting ``Tifton's little 16-year-old literary genius, Rebecca
Griffin, whom I herewith name Poetess of the Wiregrass.''
</P>
<P>
   He had already written a letter to her suggesting that they
might have a future together, a future impossible while she was yet
16, but conceivable if she was willing to wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``My compromise is for us to be engaged until you are 18,'' he
had written on May 23, ``to give you a chance to secure an
education, without which you would be lost if anything disastrous
happened to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Such an arrangement was not to be. Edwards' letters became more
wistful over the next few months, until he lamented, on April 18,
1935, ``Have you entirely ceased to love me?''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;  Destroy my letters, he said
</P>
<P>
   We may never know. No letters from Griffin have turned up _
either in the Edwards archives at Macon's Washington Memorial
Library, in the small Edwards collection at the Macon Museum of
Arts and Sciences or in any of the boxes from that Austell attic.
</P>
<P>
   And none may ever surface. Edwards knew that the vast difference
in their ages was unacceptable, and advised Griffin to destroy his
letters. ``A lost letter can wreck a life,'' he wrote to her on
April 23, 1934. The odds are good that he destroyed hers.
</P>
<P>
   But Griffin couldn't follow suit. She carefully saved at least
50 of his dispatches, which he had typed on plain manuscript paper
and mailed to her in care of her father's theater. She also clipped
out his columns, and any news stories that made reference to his
writings, and pasted them into scrapbook after scrapbook _ the
sisters have at least a half-dozen. But the only place to hear
Griffin's voice is in her poetry, and the few quotes attributed to
her by Edwards in his columns and letters.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, she also produced an impressive file of her own
newspaper clips. After graduating from Tifton High in 1935, she
moved to Manchester with her family and wrote reviews of the movies
that showed at her father's movie theater there, the President. Her
poems were also published in The Tifton Gazette, The Carroll County
Times, The Dublin Courier Herald, The Warm Springs Mirror, The
Manchester Mercury, The LaGrange Herald and The Atlanta Journal.
Some of the newspapers called her ``Tifton's poet laureate.''
</P>
<P>
   Her poems were collected in a slim booklet published by the
Mirror, and several were included in an anthology published by
Crown. Her poem ``The Little Chapel,'' about the Old Church on the
Emory campus at Oxford, was highly praised, and the Rev. A.I.
Branham, who was connected with the school, told her in a letter
that the poem should be inscribed on a plaque on the wall there.
</P>
<P>
   But it never was, says John Forney, president of the Oxford
Historical Shrine Society, which has raised $400,000 to rebuild the
Old Church _ and probably never will be.
</P>
<P>
   By 1937 Griffin was carrying on a lively correspondence with a
Warm Springs newspaperman named Sid Williams, who was much closer
to her own age, and they were married at the end of that year.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, ever gallant, continued to promote the ``Poetess of the
Wiregrass'' in his column, and remained cordial. When he learned of
her nuptial plans, he advised her that he would make sure The
Atlanta Journal printed an announcement. He died of bronchial
pneumonia in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;  Time takes its toll
</P>
<P>
   Today if you want to find Harry Edwards, you must step through
the automatic glass doors of the very modern Washington Memorial
Library in downtown Macon. There, in the genealogical research
room, is a handsome bronze bust of the writer as an older man, with
a plaque that reads ``Distinguished Southern Author.'' Adjacent to
Edwards is a similar statue of Sidney Lanier. The two seem to stand
as bookends, holding up Macon's literary history.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards was also postmaster in Macon for 14 years, and his
figure is part of a mural adorning the walls of the post office, up
the hill from the library.
</P>
<P>
   But the most tangible part of his legacy is the original
Kingfisher Cabin, the 12-by-24-foot writing shack where he could
pen his column away from the noisy brood of grandchildren who
shared his house at Holly Bluff. After his death the cabin was
disassembled and placed on the Wesleyan campus; then, in the late
1960s, it was moved to the grounds of the Macon Museum of Arts and
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Charmed by his words, entranced by his photograph, Mullinax and
her sisters recently made a pilgrimage to the cabin, to see the
place where their hero spent his quiet time. They left a bouquet of
roses on the mantelpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Are Edwards' letters evidence of an unseemly May-December
courtship? Mullinax doubts it. She says that, despite appearances,
this was a relationship of the mind. ``She wanted to learn how to
write,'' Mullinax says, ``and he was the elite of writers.'' The
trip to the cabin was a high point, she adds. ``I could feel Harry
there, I could picture him sitting there. Going to his cabin, after
reading all those letters, that was pie a la mode. There couldn't
be anything better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but to the casual visitor, wandering down a cinder path
in the woods, not 50 yards from the museum's back door, the little
one-room structure seems forlorn and alone. Once the site of
birthday parties, nature classes and dramatic re-enactments of
scenes from the author's stories, the cabin has not fared well in
the lapse of years.
</P>
<P>
   All the furnishings _ the stuffed deer head, the woven grass
rugs, the framed lock of hair from young Becky Griffin _ are gone.
Some of the timbers have been attacked by post beetles, and others
replaced with anachronistic pressure-treated lumber. Birds have
found their way into the bare interior, and a finch has constructed
a nest in one of the built-in shelves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're beyond Band-Aids,'' says Bonnie Hopkins, the
museum's director of development, who confesses regret at the
cabin's condition and a dedication to finding the money to restore
it, even though that could cost up to $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   If you ask Mary Lane Hartshorn, it would be money well spent. An
Edwards granddaughter, she was one of those rambunctious children
riding her tricycle inside the big house at Holly Bluff. She
remembers the cabin as Edwards' special retreat.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather wrote about the noise, how my mother would try
to keep us quiet, and he would say, `No, I'm getting inspiration
from the children,''' says Hartshorn, 72, who lives in
Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   The Holly Bluff house burned in 1964, taking most of Edwards'
manuscripts, first editions, letters and personal papers with it.
Reprints of some of his short works are still sold by the Middle
Georgia Historical Society, and the Wesleyan library carries a
complete collection. For many years his daughter, Nelle Edwards
Smith, continued to print several of his works, including his paean
to education, ``The Tenth Generation,'' through her own Eneas
Africanus Press.
</P>
<P>
   But Edwards' literary reputation seems almost as neglected as
Kingfisher Cabin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone recognizes his name,'' says Doris Lanier,
a retired professor of English at Georgia Southern University who
wrote her master's thesis on Edwards in 1970. Edwards' genius was
in capturing the post-Civil War world of Middle Georgia, which made
him an important member of the regionalist movement, but less
relevant to other places and times.
</P>
<P>
   His most famous character, the peripatetic Eneas, is today a
politically incorrect embarrassment: a faithful former slave who
pledges gratitude and fealty to his master. Yet Edwards documented
black church services, and other aspects of rural Georgia life,
both white and black, that might otherwise have gone unreported. In
fact, Booker T. Washington, one of the most influential black
leaders of his day, praised Edwards' essay ``The Negro and the
South,'' saying, in a letter, ``it is strong, courageous, and will
prove helpful, I am sure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He wrote about the Old South,'' says Hartshorn, whose garage
shelters the 1938 Ford given to Edwards by Mr. Ford himself. ``That
era is gone now, and a lot of people don't appreciate knowing about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Also out of fashion is Edwards' 19th-century style of courtly
banter, which he seemed to carry on with all women at all times.
For this reason, Hartshorn suggests that the romance between
Edwards and Griffin was strictly literary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aunt Roxie kept house for him, and she would always put a big
bouquet of daffodils on the piano,'' recalls Hartshorn. ``When he
was going downtown he would swoop them up and give one to the girl
at Woolworth's, and one to the girl at the S &AMP; S (cafeteria). ...
Pretty girls were his chief delight.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;  `I do not want fame'
</P>
<P>
   If Edwards' writing is hard to find today, even more obscure is
the poetry of Rebecca Griffin. She grew up in a time when
newspapers routinely printed poetry from writers both famous and
amateur, sometimes on the front page. Her scrapbooks show that
dozens of her poems appeared in print, and her slim 1937
collection, ``Stars and Flowers,'' was reviewed favorably by the
local press.
</P>
<P>
   In his ``Coming Down My Creek'' column for July 3, 1936, Edwards
reprinted Griffin's sonnet to the Old Church, plus part of a letter
she had written him. Pasted into one of the scrapbooks rescued from
the Austell attic, it is one of her few surviving missives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose I shall always go on writing, even though the world
doesn't know,'' the young woman said. ``I do not want fame, for I
wouldn't know what to do with it. I live to share my heart with my
mother, my sweetheart and my friends. As long as they love me, I
shall feel famous enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax spent two years trying to find Griffin's descendants,
before giving up. ``I wanted to return these things,'' she says.
She learned only that the poet, who would marry three times, died
sometime in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax's sisters then began trying to market the collection.
They approached a used bookstore in Decatur, Sotheby's auction
house in New York City and the Macon museum. They tried to get a
message to Ted Turner because, says Barbara Dumas, ``Ted is the man
with the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of inexperience, the sisters have yet to talk with any
archivists, in Macon or elsewhere. Whether they seek to sell or
donate, however, they will find the crowd of takers small, says
Tena Roberts, archivist at Wesleyan's Willet Memorial Library,
which houses some of Edwards' surviving papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world knows Ernest Hemingway, but not Harry Stillwell
Edwards,'' says Roberts, who has seen some of the Edwards-Griffin
letters. ``He's known by a limited circle of scholars, so these
letters have limited appeal.'' Nevertheless, she said, Wesleyan
considers them significant and is interested.
</P>
<P>
   Dumas and Hammond would like to sell the collection; Mullinax
would be happy if it found a home in a proper archive. And all
three seem delighted to dive into those cardboard boxes again and
again, and spend time with Harry. This Southern gentleman, who had
such a way with women, has, across the ages, cast his spell on the
sisters.
</P>
<P>
   One afternoon at Rose Hammond's knickknack-choked Norcross
apartment, Hammond and Dumas sift through photographs, yellowed
clippings and old composition books strewn across Hammond's carpet.
``Everything we've got is worth a fortune to us,'' Dumas points
out, ``but probably isn't worth a dang to anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the story, she says, should be told. ``I think this story is
a great romance, about true love, deep-down emotional love, about
honesty, faithfulness, devotion.''
</P>
<P>
   And, casting her eye across the photograph of that elegant man,
she betrays another motivation.
</P>
<P>
   Says Dumas, ``I think this was the greatest human male of all
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bo Emerson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
