u l BC-CUSTOM-SUITS-$ADV17-A     10-15 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUSTOM-SUITS-$ADV17-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RETURN OF THE SUIT THAT SPEAKS FOR ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Tenn.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17) 
(af) 
 By RUTH LA FERLA    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last summer, Dr. Andre Churchwell bought himself a
new blue suit. Not just any blue suit, but a single-breasted,
two-button model with peak lapels and a dapper ticket pocket _ a
ringer, he was quick to note, for ``the suit Pierce Brosnan was
wearing when he first met Renee Russo in `The Thomas Crown
Affair.'''
</P>
<P>
   Churchwell, 45, a cardiologist in Nashville, Tenn., makes it a
point to know about such things. Speaking by phone from his office,
he all but crowed describing another recent acquisition, a
dove-gray coat and trousers made in New York by his tailor, Leonard
Logsdail, and cut, he said, from the poshest ``Super 100'' wool
flannel.
</P>
<P>
   Terms like Super 100 and Scabel (a luxury fabric from a British
textile mill) have also leeched into Dennis Saul's conversation.
The head of his own stock brokerage firm, Saul, 56, has his suits
made in Brooklyn by a tailor whose name he won't disclose _ for
fear of driving up his prices.
</P>
<P>
   Each new ensemble sets Saul back about $2,000; a bargain, he
maintained, since ``I'm getting the difference between a Chevy and
a Porche.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Last Saturday, I looked at 20 different fabrics,'' he
recalled. ``I like to feel that in the course of examining this
stuff, I'm building a body of knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Churchwell and Saul are devout members of an exclusive but
growing fraternity of affluent clothing buffs, who have turned
their backs on off-the-rack apparel in favor of a garment uniquely
tailored to their whims.
</P>
<P>
   Men like these contend that they are wild about a custom suit's
superior fit and quality. But they are just as taken with its
unspoken function as a badge of rank, an expression of their
rarefied tastes and connoisseurship _ as though it were a rare wine
or a vintage car they had studied up on before acquiring.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly brand-conscious, a prosperous minority of men with
a passion for finery has given rise to dynamic sales of hand-made
apparel for the first time since the boom years of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In this decade, suit sales overall have taken a beating as
consumers lean toward casual wear. But when men do buy suits,
retailers and tailors say, they are more likely to splurge these
days, investing in top-of-the-line goods.
</P>
<P>
   Just as in the '80s, men's wear's last gilded age, when a
peacock display of red suspenders or an Hermes tie were thought to
be status symbols, consumers with well-lined pockets are not
blinking at the $2,000 to $7,000 price tag for a custom suit. It's
the sartorial equivalent of a platinum card.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the custom club like to subtly signal one another by
flaunting their ticket pockets _ slim pockets on the jacket
originally used to fit a pair of theater tickets _ and functioning
buttonholes on jacket sleeves, which Wall Street's young turks
leave undone in a quiet show of status.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last few years, the custom business has picked up
dramatically,'' said Clifford Grodd, the president of Paul Stuart,
a high-end men's-wear emporium in midtown Manhattan, where the
custom business has doubled since the mid-'90s.
</P>
<P>
   Other merchants cite a similarly robust growth _ about 15
percent to 25 percent annually _ in hand-tailored suits, though no
industry-wide figures exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the hallmarks of affluence, beside buying your Range
Rover, is having a suit made,'' Grodd said. ``It's the sartorial
equivalent of name dropping.''
</P>
<P>
   The lineup of clothiers offering men's custom services in the
New York area, including suits, shirts and sometimes ties, includes
tailors like Leonard Logsdail; specialty stores like Saks Fifth
Avenue, Neiman Marcus and Bergdorf Goodman, and such lofty labels
as Oxxford, Kiton, Zegna, Brioni, Attolini and, most recently,
Giorgio Armani, who began selling made-to-measure suits just this
fall under the Le Collezioni label.
</P>
<P>
   Even Moe Ginzburg, the venerable rack-and-pipe operation on
lower Fifth Avenue that is home to $250 budget suits, is trading
up. Next spring, the store will feature made-to-measure men's
apparel in its newly renovated and gentrified store.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Ginzburg, the third-generation owner of Moe Ginzburg,
expects made-to-measure customers to come from the ranks of those
who are ``bestowing fine wine on themselves, along with good
caviar, expensive girlfriends and even more expensive wives,'' he
said, adding, ``A custom suit is one more luxury that makes them
feel they have arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers, and some retailers _ are often confused about the
terminology of tailored clothing. Essentially, there are three
levels of quality and expense:
</P>
<P>
   _ A custom suit, the cordon bleu of tailored apparel, is cut and
stitched from scratch, using a pattern made of muslim cloth
designed for each client. Known as a bespoke suit in England.
Prices range from $2,000 to well over $7,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ A made-to-measure suit is a Betty Crocker variation on custom
tailoring. Customers are measured, and choose from a wide range of
fabrics, but their suits are cut using standard patterns, not made
from scratch. This is what men's-wear designers offer when they do
``trunk shows'' at stores. Priced from $700 to $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   _ Off-the-rack suits, those hanging in stores when customers
walk in, are made in standard sizes and can be altered in simple
ways by a tailor. Priced from $100 to $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
