<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8188 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MTVERNON-SHOW16-COX     10-15 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MTVERNON-SHOW16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wahsington exhibit reveals America's renaissance man
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ George Washington did not cut down the cherry tree.
</P>
<P>
   A historian quashes that bit of American mythology in one of the
video clips in ``Treasures of Mount Vernon: George Washington
Revealed,'' opening today at the Atlanta History Center.
</P>
<P>
   But don't worry: You won't end up admiring him any less.
Washington may have worn false teeth _ a spring-operated
contraption has fascinated visitors at prior stops of the show tour
_ but his conduct was true. And remarkable in many ways.
</P>
<P>
   Marshaling letters, clothing, furnishings, military gear,
artwork from the collection of his Virginia estate, the Mount
Vernon staff reveals Washington to be a man of diverse talents. The
able statesman and military hero was also a successful farmer, a
gallant dancer, a tasteful decorator, a prescient environmentalist
and a reluctant international celebrity. All that, and a
Southerner, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Treasures'' tells its story chronologically and thematically.
It begins with a plaster cast of the ``life mask'' made by French
artist Jean-Antoine Houdon in 1785, immortalizing the famous
features, as chiseled as, well, Mount Rushmore. The teeth are in
the same case, behind the mask. The pairing makes a statement about
the show's intentions to get beyond the public persona. It must be
said, however, that the teeth are about as intimate as it gets. If
you were looking for a warts-and-all expose, you will be
disappointed. This is a show about achievement, not peccadilloes.
</P>
<P>
   The curators wisely alternate small-scale objects and
life-size-displays , both of which are augmented by wall texts and
labels. (There is also an audio tour, free with admission, which
was unavailable for review.) For instance, the first gallery
includes the surveyor's tools representing Washington's first
career and a walk-in replica of the tent from which he directed
battles as Commander in Chief of the Continental forces.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was ``charmed'' by the sound of whizzing bullets, our
leader loved the farmer's life on his Virginia plantation. The
gallery devoted to Mt. Vernon tells us much about his various
talents. Ledgers and letters chronicle his prosperous and diverse
agricultural pursuits, from fish to liquor. We learn that
Washington was ahead of his time in rotating crops.
</P>
<P>
   Chairs, silver and porcelain speak to his elegant taste. He also
knew a thing or two about time management: He took advantage of
time spent in Philadelphia during the Constitutional Convention to
buy household goods from the great craftsmen there.
</P>
<P>
   The plethora of portraits of this famous man as well as displays
of his clothing give you sense of his imposing physical presence.
They also bespeak his life-long fame, a fate to which he responded
with good-natured resignation. As suggested by the number of French
portraits, he was revered across the Atlantic as well. The Marquise
de Lafayette even gave him the key to the Bastille to honor his
role in fostering the French Revolution. Such was his popularity
that his likeness became a cottage industry, copied, often badly,
in engravings and stamped on mugs and medallions. The phenomenon
can be compared to the rage for souvenirs of John F. Kennedy and
Lady Di.
</P>
<P>
   A venerated hero while alive, he quickly became a near-deity
when he died in 1799. In the engraving, ``The Apotheosis of
Washington,'' he ascends to heaven like a saint. Through this show,
we know him as saint with two feet firmly planted in American soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Treasures From Mount Vernon: George
</P>
<P>
   Washington
</P>
<P>
   Revealed''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta History Center. 130 W. Paces Ferry Road N.W. Through
Jan. 6. $10; $8 students and seniors; $4 youths 6-17; free for
members and children 5 and under. 404-814-4186.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A Renaissance man made in America and brought to
life in this exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fox writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
