u l BC-CUSTOM-SUITS-$ADV17-A     10-15 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUSTOM-SUITS-$ADV17-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: to $3,000.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hand-made suits appeal to the kind of man who wants a walnut
dashboard in his car and a cherrywood floor in his dining room.
``The more prosperous the man, the more difficult it is to satisfy
his needs,'' said Lawrence Kudlow, a chief economist with Schroeder
bank and a commentator for CNBC and Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   Kudlow, who buys his hand-made pinstripe suits from Logsdail,
views the craving for hand-made apparel as the indicator of a
larger trend: ``Customization is a theme in all consumer goods,''
he noted. ``The suit business is part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Kurt Salmon Associates, a New York consumer research
group, which conducted a survey of middle- to high-income shoppers
earlier this year, forecasts increases of 20 percent to 30 percent
in sales of custom-made apparel over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Younger consumers, men now in their 30s and 40s, whose notions
of style were honed on aggressively voguish labels like Prada,
Helmut Lang and Dolce &AMP; Gabbana, are among those giving
made-to-order suits a push. Disenchanted by the indifferent
construction and evanescent life span of designer brands, some have
discovered custom apparel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men's clothes are becoming so fashion forward that I can't
wear them,'' complained Giovanni Russo, one such recent custom
convert. Russo, 33, an art director and the head of his own New
York design firm, called No. 11, has mostly abandoned designer
suits, which he deems too flashy, for the subtlety of a
trim-fitting gray wool coat and pair of trousers, like those he
ordered last summer from Seize Sur Vingt, a downtown clothier to
the young and hip.
</P>
<P>
   Learning about the arcana of style _ the names of fabrics, the
types of stitching _ is part of the allure of a custom suit, said
Dan McCampbell, a Saks Fifth Avenue vice president and fashion
director, who based his observations on findings from a survey by
the store of 300 consumers aged 25 to 64 and earning $75,000 a year
or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men are turning increasingly to a tailor or a knowledgeable
sales associate to inform them about how clothes are made,'' he
said. ``Why? They see clothes as an investment.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he might have added, an instant passport to James Bondian
self-assurance. Some tailors trade on their clients' eagerness to
become connoisseurs _ a trait hard-wired into many men, the same
instinct that leads them to become audio buffs _ while preying
slyly on their insecurities.
</P>
<P>
   One television executive, who declined to be named, told of
visiting the New York hotel suite of Gianni Campagna, a Milanese
tailor, who says he makes suits for the billionaire Ronald O.
Perleman and Henry Kravis, the financier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had on my best Zegna suit,'' the client recalled, laughing
ruefully, ``but they looked me over, and told me my cuffs were too
short, my shoulders too low and my buttons too high. All I could
think was, Oh my God, do I look that bad?''
</P>
<P>
   He succumbed just the same, buying one suit in solid gray wool
and another in a navy Prince of Wales plaid. Cost: $3,800 each. He
also bought a cashmere sportscoat for $2,600.
</P>
<P>
   Some men take the passion for personalization to extremes.
Logsdail, a Midtown tailor with a Savile Row pedigree, tells of one
client who asked to have his suit coat lined with a patchwork of
silk Hermes scarves.
</P>
<P>
   But Americans more often shun such display, opting for
refinements as faint and elusive as the scent of English lavender.
They include Jeffry Schneider, 31, an investment banker and
long-time patron of Paul Stuart.
</P>
<P>
   His latest purchase is a tasmanian wool suit decorated with
plaid so fine it is all but invisible. ``A hand-made suit is a
subtle thing,'' he said during a fitting the other day, pointing
out the hand-stitching along the edge of the lapel. ``But this is
my favorite detail,'' Schneider said, turning his jacket inside out
to show off his pen pocket _ a one-inch slash just beneath his left
breast pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers acknowledge that the advantage of such features may
well be in the wearer's eye. ``So much of this business is
psychological,'' said Grodd of Paul Stuart. ``A hand-sewn
buttonhole is a sign of status, sure, but one that is much
overrated. With all the technology available now, ``handwork
doesn't necessarily make something better.''
</P>
<P>
   True custom fans brush such reservations off like lint. Eager to
stand out from the herd and, at the same time, blend in with their
peers, some take a line from their tailors, contending, a bit
solemnly, that their suits are an addiction _ not to say the
plushest of security blankets.
</P>
<P>
   They certainly serve that purpose for Russo. ``I hate being
self-conscious,'' he said. ``I like to feel that my clothes aren't
wearing me. And when I find a suit I really can relax in, well, I
just go with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
