<HEADLINE>
JONBENET CASE FRUSTRATING _ BUT THAT'S LAW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It wasn't the headline most people were hoping for: ``JonBenet
grand jury returns no indictment.''
</P>
<P>
   No indictment? No charges of any kind against anyone? What in
the world is going on here?
</P>
<P>
   The media legal eagles are saying that it's not so uncommon,
really, this mind-boggling lack of anything remotely resembling a
prosecution in the nearly three years since 6-year-old JonBenet
Ramsey was found slthe basement of her family's home in
Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Homicides often go unsolved, say the experts _ including
homicides of children. Sometimes there's just not enough evidence.
</P>
<P>
   And lack of evidence is the problem in the Ramsey case,
according to Boulder County District Attorney Alex Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not have sufficient evidence to warrant the filing of
charges against anyone who has been investigated at this time,''
Hunter said Wednesday after a grand jury concluded its 13-month
review of the case.
</P>
<P>
   For JonBenet's parents, Hunter's announcement was both good news
and bad news. Having lived under an ``umbrella of suspicion'' since
their daughter's death in December 1996, John and Patsy Ramsey were
relieved that neither of them was indicted.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Ramseys said in a statement released
after Hunter's announcement, ``We take no satisfaction in this
result because a child killer remains free and undetected.''
</P>
<P>
   Free? Definitely. Undetected? Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   If the slaying was committed by an unidentified perpetrator who
invaded the Ramsey home and left JonBenet's battered body to be
found the day after Christmas _ well, that individual is as yet
undetected.
</P>
<P>
   But if the murder was committed by John and/or Patsy Ramsey _ as
so many experts and nonexperts alike have speculated _ then why are
the police, the prosecutors, a battalion of well-paid crime
consultants and a grand jury of Colorado residents unable to bring
the culprit(s) to justice?
</P>
<P>
   In a word: ``proof.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy enough for glib panelists on the Geraldo Rivera and
Larry King talk shows to declare a suspect guilty of murder, to
lambaste law enforcement officials for failing to file charges
against some individual who's been convicted in the media. But cops
and prosecutors aren't entertainers; they must operate under
certain legal constraints.
</P>
<P>
   It's an inconvenience to the police and the occasional lynch
mob, to be sure, but the Constitution of the United States
guarantees due process of law to criminal suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, neither John nor Patsy Ramsey has formally
been identified as a ``suspect'' in the death of JonBenet, although
Hunter has been holding the ``umbrella of suspicion'' over them and
the media have pretty much obliterated the Ramseys' presumption of
innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Just about everybody has a theory about the murder _ I have one,
but I'm taking the high road and keeping it to myself _ and all the
theories share a common flaw: They are based entirely on
speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of Hunter's no-indictment announcement, a woman
identified as an advocate for crime victims was on ``Rivera Live''
expressing her outrage at the lack of prosecution when ``we know
that one of two people'' killed JonBenet.
</P>
<P>
   We ``know?'' Excuse me, folks, but if we ``knew'' that one or
both of the Ramseys committed this horrifying crime, then that
Boulder grand jury surely would have indicted one or both of them.
If the people who've been investigating this crime for three years
don't ``know'' who did it _ and they don't _ rest assured that some
talking head on ``Rivera Live'' doesn't know.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the bottom line. Nobody who's in a position to file
charges, make an arrest or pursue a prosecution ``knows'' who
killed JonBenet Ramsey. In the absence of knowing, the authorities
need evidence to support their suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   It's frustrating _ maddening, even _ to see this case go
unresolved. But the Boulder authorities deserve praise, not
criticism, for declining to stage a murder trial simply to quell
the impatience of the media and the public.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
