<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
19TH-CENTURY GUN ENTREPRENEUR TRIPPED UP BY 20TH-CENTURY PRESSURES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can't be first, I won't be second at anything.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Samuel Colt, 1844
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   When he spoke those words 155 years ago, there was no way that
the man who revolutionized manufacturing in this country in the
mid-19th century could know that one day his corporate namesake
would be the first to crater to legal threats caused by a
hysterical response to the misuse of his product.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Colt's story of industrial genius and self-promotion,
gleaned from books, biographical narratives and historical papers,
is enough to make Donald Trump swoon with envy. Even the tale of
how he came up with the idea of the revolving breech pistol borders
on the fanciful.
</P>
<P>
   Sent off to see the world by his textile-agent father after the
death of his mother, young Sam Colt was aboard a Calcutta-bound
sailing ship when he conceived the idea for the rotating cylinder
that would make him famous. He reportedly got the notion from
studying the movement of the ship's wheel.
</P>
<P>
   After Colt returned to the United States in 1832, he spent the
next few years traveling the country under the name of Dr. Coult.
He would use any gathering of people he could find to demonstrate
and sell the latest medical discovery, nitrous oxide _ laughing
gas.
</P>
<P>
   In 1834, Colt signed a two-year contract with Baltimore gunsmith
John Pearson to work on various models of firearms. This would lead
to his eventual U.S. patent for the revolver. At the end of his
contract, the 23-year-old took his patent and, with seed money from
wealthy East Coast relatives, opened the Patent Arms Manufacturing
Co. in Paterson, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Success did not come quickly. Despite much wining and dining of
government officials _ on his relatives' nickel _ lucrative offers
never materialized, Colt was forced to declare bankruptcy six years
and 5,000 pistols and rifles later.
</P>
<P>
   From 1841 to 1846, Colt lived in New York City. While still
trying to find buyers for his guns, he shifted his attention to
other munitions and developed an underwater mine that could be
detonated by a telegraph signal. Although his demonstration of
blowing up a 500-ton schooner on the Potomac River wowed
spectators, it did nothing to garner a government contract.
</P>
<P>
   Enter 1846 and the Mexican War. Colt received a letter from
Capt. Samuel Walker saying that the guns he had made years before
in Paterson had changed the way that the Texas Rangers fought
Indians in 1839.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Jack Hays and 15 Texas Rangers had been ambushed by 80
Comanche warriors, reputedly the best light cavalry in this nation
at the time. Walker wrote that the soldiers finally had a weapon
that matched the Comanches' rapid-fire abilities with bows and
arrows _ and exceeded their accuracy. Walker needed that advantage
against the Mexicans and wanted to outfit his 500 men with two
revolvers each.
</P>
<P>
   By 1847, Colt was back in business. He set up shop in his
hometown of Hartford, Conn., which had developed as the industrial
capital of the country through the widespread introduction of
machine tools and precision measurements. Such technology could
produce assembly guns with interchangeable machined parts.
</P>
<P>
   Colt's system for mass-producing firearms helped spark a
revolution for other complex metal products, such as typewriters,
sewing machines, cameras and bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   From 1836 to 1870, the world was a volatile place. The Texas
Revolution had ignited the imagination of the public, with the
scrappy heroes rebelling against a foreign power. Wars for
independence dotted the globe _ Italy, Russia, Mexico. The Crimean
War. The Franco-Prussian War. The Civil War. Colt's firearms were
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good people in this world are very far from being
satisfied with each other and my arms are the best peacemaker,''
Colt said in 1852.
</P>
<P>
   The Peacemaker. Colt's products are considered anything but by
too many people in today's hyper-reactive society. Their use for
self-defense has been obliterated in the minds of people who focus
their rage on the guns and not on the purveyors of evil who misuse
them. Because of the precarious financial situation that liability
lawsuits have placed the company in, Colt officials said this week
they are dramatically curtailing the number of models that will be
available for sale to the public.
</P>
<P>
   A sad irony can be found in tomorrow's announcement that Samuel
Colt will be among the 21 larger-than-life personalities to be
added to the Texas Trail of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   His invention played a key role in shaping this nation's western
heritage and this state's unique character. It remains to be seen
whether Texans will continue to value the kind of self-reliance and
self-determination that are the hallmarks of the Lone Star State's
history.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7599. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1716EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
