<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8197 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-BLONDE-BOMBSHELLS-$AD     10-15 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLONDE-BOMBSHELLS-$ADV17-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSINGS ON THE MAKING OF A BOMBSHELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Oct. 17)  
(js) 
 By LAREN STOVER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The see-through ``Happy Birthday, Mr. President'' gown (Lot No.
55) may go for $1 million at Christie's auction of the personal
property of Marilyn Monroe, on Oct. 27 and 28. But for me, the far
more revealing relics are her colander and cheese grater (No. 401),
her dogeared books, many first-editions (Nos. 500 to 566) and all
the intimate, mundane remains from the life and legacy of a
bombshell.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, I have become entranced by bombshells _
those women present and past, famous and not, who instantly make a
devastating impression on men. Are they invariably blond and dim?
Are they born or made? Most crucially, could I be one?
</P>
<P>
   I read bombshell biographies, rented bombshell videos and talked
nonstop about what makes a bombshell. Some friends and I even
started holding bombshell roundtables earlier this year at our
apartments in an attempt to decode the secrets of this iconic
creature. We quickly concluded that every woman has an inner
bombshell waiting to be detonated. We made lists, jotted down
maxims. We outlined what makes her tick, from her shoes (any
peekaboo sandal, even in the coldest of weather), to the two types
of temper tantrums she is prone to (blondes pout; brunettes throw
breakable objects) to the bombshell's philosophy (optimism gives
her good posture). We decided her favorite film would be ``Bambi.''
</P>
<P>
   In the voluptuous 415-page catalog, there is evidence that a
bombshell's allure is not that she is, as doctrine dictates,
devastatingly dumb, but rather devastatingly complex. In this book,
which weighs almost as much as my unabridged Webster's, are objects
and biographical bits that reveal outrageous vanity, extreme
frailty and a restless intellect.
</P>
<P>
   For the famous dress in which Marilyn crooned ``Happy Birthday''
to President John F. Kennedy in 1962, she implored the couturier
Jean Louis to ``design a truly historical dress,'' the catalog
says, ``a dazzling dress that's one of a kind'' and that was
``sculpted'' on her body while she drank Champagne _ all for a
performance that would last less than half a minute. Yet amid the
furs and long gloves are things humble and sentimental, too: a worn
stuffed toy poodle (No. 469); Marilyn's certificate of conversion
to Judaism, for her third husband, Arthur Miller (No. 355); an
unglamorous Plexiglas tissue-box cover (No. 418), from which I can
imagine her pulling pink Kleenex to blot up heartbreak.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who want to own these seemingly everyday objects
hope her shimmering, effervescent and breathless appeal might rub
off, as if owning something _ anything _ ``Marilyn'' (No. 147: a
battered picnic hamper) would give us a little va-va-va-voom.
Because a bombshell, as this tome clearly proves, is not made
entirely of slit-to-there dresses, wicked stilettos and false
eyelashes. No, being a bombshell is a state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   I first glimpsed this in the fourth grade, when my grandmother,
a Southern belle, gave me a bottle of Christian Dior's My Sin and
my first stockings and high-heels, in aqua blue brocade. I
practiced sashaying over the uneven brick path in her backyard,
repeating my bombshell mantra, ``Why don't you come up and see me
sometime?'' I was awed by the throaty power Mae West seemed to have
over men, but I adored Marilyn for her friendly femininity.
</P>
<P>
   Bombshells, however, were not highly regarded in my house. My
mother was a serious thespian. To her, Marilyn (and actresses of
her ilk, from Jean Harlow to Sophia Loren) was simply a body void
of talent _ and worse, she seemed to enjoy being ogled. My own
bombshell aspirations were squashed under my mother's prim pump.
</P>
<P>
   So, I grew up to lead a sensible life, a writer of fiction who
keeps an office job, too, and whose style signature was vintage
orthopedic shoes. My turnaround came after a breathy, voluptuous,
blonde began swishing into our morning advertising meetings. With
Veronica Lake hair, tight sweaters and 4-inch heels, she was the
kind of woman who could cross the street without looking. She was a
lush landscape, and her smile was an invitation to enjoy the view.
I had dismissed her as a vapid blonde, until I threw out a grammar
question to the room, and she was the only one who responded.
``Don't you have `The Chicago Manual of Style'?'' she asked in her
sultry tone. ``Here, borrow mine.''
</P>
<P>
   It was then that I realized a bombshell could be brainy. Later I
would discover it may even be a requisite.
</P>
<P>
   No longer inhibited by the conventional wisdom that intelligence
ruled out glamour, I traded in my black geek glasses for
tortoise-shell Gucci cat's-eyes not unlike Marilyn's (No. 121) and
started growing out my bangs. I picked up a few snug sweaters, and
had my A-line skirts taken in. I even bought a pair of marabou
mules (like No. 305: Plexiglas mules trimmed with white fox fur) to
parade in around the apartment, unable to dress like a slob under
any circumstances. I'd ask myself, would a bombshell be seen in
sweats?
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   What is and isn't a bombshell is, of course, up for grabs.
Harlow started it all with her 1933 film, ``Bombshell,'' in which
she portrays Hollywood's creation of the ultimate ``it'' girl, a
peroxide blonde with ``a pinwheel personality.'' But Marilyn
perfected the ideal, and the Christie's catalog reads like a
virtual bombshell bible.
</P>
<P>
   A bombshell, it reveals, is the kind of woman who turns heads
and yet is flawed, physically (a candid photograph, on page 54,
shows Marilyn's legs to be plump and curveless) and emotionally
(No. 499: a handwritten poem with the lyrics ``I've got a tear
hanging over my beer/that can't let go/it(s) too bad I feel
sad/When I got all my life behind me ... They say I'm lucky to be
alive it's hard to figure out _ when everything I feel _ hurts!'').
</P>
<P>
   She has dignity, often transcending a tragic childhood. Dorothy
Dandridge was beaten routinely with a hairbrush; Marilyn grew up in
orphanages and foster homes (No. 355: a white baby grand piano that
once belonged to her mother _ and that Marilyn spent years
searching for after her mother was institutionalized).
</P>
<P>
   ``The bombshell's library,'' my friend Nicole asserted, doesn't
always merit a room of its own. In fact, a bombshell's collection
may consist entirely of books on the floor surrounding her bed or
stacked so that she can, say, climb up on them to open a window.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole and the other members of our bombshell roundtable had our
own ideas about the books and authors a bombshell would or would
not read. Yes to Shakespeare's ``Anthony and Cleopatra,'' George
Bernard Shaw's ``Caesar and Cleopatra.'' No to T.S. Eliot, Carl
Jung and John Updike. We speculated that she would think Sylvia
Plath was pretty and would glance at ``The Bell Jar'' in a
bookstore, but after reading about her suicide would put the book
down. As for Anne Sexton, another beautiful poet, Nicole was
certain that no bombshell would ever read her after hearing that
she'd hugged an air-conditioner in her analyst's office. We figured
Marilyn had read F. Scott Fitzgerald's ``The Great Gatsby'' (No.
506) but were surprised by James Joyce's ``Dubliners,'' Faulkner's
``The Sound and the Fury'' (No. 549) and ``The Little Engine That
Could'' (No. 522).
</P>
<P>
   I was equally startled by Marilyn's domestic aspirations. I'd
always fantasized that a bombshell refrigerator was essentially a
vanity on ice used to store nail polish, perfume, hosiery (in the
freezer) and a bright blue eye mask. Marilyn may have only mastered
``toast, pasta and scrambled eggs,'' but her tattered ``New Joy of
Cooking'' (No. 523) looks like a happy wreck.
</P>
<P>
   A bombshell is resilient. A film that bombs, a marriage on the
rocks (No. 8: a photograph of Joe DiMaggio) are setbacks, but she
always bounces back, or at least puts up a good front. A bombshell
puts glamour before comfort. A nude leg on a cold day. The
constraints of boned underpinnings (No. 306: a group of corsets). A
bombshell lives, really lives, in her heels. She walks in them,
runs in them _ to arrive flushed and breathless was one of
Marilyn's secrets _ and dances in them in ballrooms and bedrooms
and onstage (No. 1: ravaged gold-leather high-heels worn to
entertain the troops in Korea).
</P>
<P>
   While she might have a temper, a bombshell is compassionate. She
likes to be photographed cuddling small fluffy dogs (No. 443: a
group of pictures featuring her pet Maltese). A bombshell is
obsessed with fuzzy things. Kim Basinger and Brigitte Bardot rescue
animals, but Marilyn at her height of fame in the 1950s wore white
ermine (No. 24), beige beaver (No. 175) and lynx (No. 181).
</P>
<P>
   After all, a bombshell has complexities to hide and an image to
project.
</P>
<P>
   Our roundtables led to a reading from our own ``Bombshell Manual
of Style'' at the Algonquin Hotel earlier this year. Too shy to
read, I introduced the evening, wearing my first pair of skinny
heels for the occasion. I had clipped on ``dress-up'' earrings, a
pair of dangly fakes I've probably had since I was 16 (like No. 3:
rhinestone earrings). By then I knew: a bombshell doesn't need real
diamonds to feel like a million dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1723EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
