<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8202 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CONSERVATIVE-NAG-ART-     10-15 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSERVATIVE-NAG-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GADFLY AT HARVARD IS INSPIRATIONAL MENTOR FOR CONSERVATIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Spelling of Ceaser in 8th graf is CQ.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By LYNDA RICHARDSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ It is the first day of the semester, and
Harvey C. Mansfield has once again drawn a standing-room-only crowd
of Harvard students to his course on the history of ancient and
medieval political philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Courtly and serious in a dark gray suit, Mansfield paced in
front of the blackboard, gazing sternly into the faces of the more
than five dozen students who showed up, most of them white and
male.
</P>
<P>
   ``This course is trans-millennial,'' he began, gently ridiculing
the faddishness of millennium-related discussions. ``We're
interested in the permanent significance. We're interested in what
belongs to every millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   The statements are as much of an introduction to his course as
they are to his world. At 67, Mansfield is probably best known
around the Harvard campus as a popular government teacher and a
famously conservative nag. He strongly opposes affirmative action.
He has warned against the dangers of not respecting manliness and
declared that homosexuality would undermine civilization if it were
made respectable.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the current issue of Harvard Magazine dubs him ``Prince
of the Conservatives''; on the cover, Mansfield adopts a Tom
Wolfe-like pose, wearing a panama hat, a cream-colored blazer and a
slight smirk.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Mansfield is more than a university gadfly. A kind of Father
Confessor to students of politics for nearly four decades,
Mansfield has quietly shaped the thinking of a generation of
conservative writers, academics and public figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intellectuals often have their greatest political influence
indirectly,'' said E.J. Dionne, a senior fellow at the Brookings
Institution and a Washington Post columnist who has written several
books on government. ``Somebody like Harvey Mansfield might not be
quoted by George W. Bush, but a lot of the advisers sitting in the
room with Bush would be influenced by Harvey Mansfield.''
</P>
<P>
   They include people like William Kristol, editor of the
conservative Weekly Standard and a former adviser to Vice President
Dan Quayle; Alan Keyes, a Republican presidential contender and
former Reagan administration diplomat; Gary Rosen, associate editor
at the conservative monthly Commentary; James Ceaser, a government
professor at the University of Virginia, and Nathan Tarcov, a
political science professor at the University of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself very lucky to have run into him when I was
18 years old,'' said Kristol, who was a student of Mansfield's in
the early 1970s. ``He really helped me understand how the questions
of political philosophy relate to practical political issues
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Sean Wilentz, a liberal Princeton University historian who
drew harsh criticism from Mansfield for his defense of President
Clinton during the impeachment proceedings, admitted, ``Some of us
would give essential body parts for that kind of influence.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent day, Mansfield sat serenely in his book-lined
office, surrounded by portraits of Dead White Males like John
Locke, Thomas More and the subject of decades of his scrutiny,
Machiavelli. Mansfield has produced translations of three works by
the Renaissance figure, including ``The Prince,'' in addition to
three books on the man himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is even more evil than he appears to be and he had
a plan to change our way of thinking, to make us realistic, more
willing to do dirty and nasty things for the sake of some good,''
he said of Machiavelli. ``It's with reason that he is considered
the first modern thinker, even the founder of modern thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Mansfield, who is trimly built and looks 20 years younger than
his age, is soft-spoken, even a bit shy in person. Machiavelli is
his speciality, but it is his exposition of the ideas of the
American philosopher Leo Strauss that has resonated in current
policy debates.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss, an unabashed elitist, was harshly critical of modern
political thinkers, arguing that they were unable to make value
judgments. He fervently celebrated the ancient Greek philosophers,
believing they should be treated not as historical figures but as
sources of wisdom today. ``He runs one of the intellectual
factories that has kept Leo Strauss' work alive,'' said Dionne.
</P>
<P>
   Mansfield says his provocative style is part of his appeal.
``People come to me because there are very few academic
conservatives and also because I answer,'' he said, confessing to
enjoying the center stage. ``If you're going to go out on the limb,
you might as well say, `Everybody look at me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Rosen, who once served as Mansfield's teaching assistant,
says that he is purposely ``naughty'': ``He wants to kind of shake
the humorless orthodoxy of the other side and encourage
discussion.'' Keyes, a staunchly conservative radio talk show host,
agrees: ``He does not compromise so that it will sound better to
your ear. He will present it in such a way so that your mind is
forced to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But for some, that is precisely the problem. His critics insist
that Mansfield's inflammatory remarks and reliance on stereotypes
often do more to polarize debate on campus than to encourage it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of Harvey Mansfield's problem is that he likes hyperbole;
he likes to state extremes,'' said Everett Mendelsohn, who is
chairman of the university's history of science department and
protested the Vietnam War as a Harvard graduate student. ``He takes
issues which might well need discussion and by overstating the
problem makes them undiscussable.''
</P>
<P>
   Mansfield, for instance, speculated that an increase in the
number of black students at Harvard had led to grade inflation,
even though he admitted he had no hard data to prove it. In his
office, he characterized affirmative action as ``a bad idea wrapped
up in one great mistake, self-esteem.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He attacked the feminist movement, saying it was based on the
flawed notion that there are no essential differences between the
sexes. ``Men today are out of control because manliness is not
being respected,'' he declared. The only Harvard faculty member to
vote against a women's studies major in 1986, Mansfield is now
working on a book titled ``Manliness.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been quoted as saying that gay sex is ``shameful'' and
that homosexuality ``rightly causes most regular people to feel
repulsed.'' Mansfield said he became more outspoken after he
stepped down as chairman of Harvard's government department in
1977. He describes the late 1960s as a catastrophe for Harvard and
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Everything became ``directed toward the goal of social justice
rather than truth and learning,'' he said. ``Harvard is very trendy
these days. It does not want to be isolated, aloof in an ivory
tower. That's a big mistake we're making. We should be much further
from political and social questions. The purpose of the university
is not to produce solutions for these questions but to think and
raise questions and to challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Mansfield said he found it paradoxical that the counterculture
of the late 1960s had become the establishment culture of Harvard,
``even though many of them are very liberal or very far to the left
and oppose the idea of establishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Mansfield was reared in a New Deal liberal household. His mother
was a homemaker, his father a political science professor at Ohio
State University who ended up at Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   He has spent most of his own adult life at Harvard, however. He
graduated summa cum laude in 1953 and received his doctorate in
1961. ``I love it, but I'm angry at it,'' he snaps. He said he
became disaffected with liberals when he attended Harvard because
he was strongly anti-communist.
</P>
<P>
   Mansfield who has two grown sons, met his current wife, Delba
Winthrop, at Harvard when she was a graduate student in his
political philosophy class. She teaches political theory in
Harvard's adult education program. Together they run the
Harvard-based Program on Constitutional Government, which sponsors
public forums. (His former wife, his 28-year-old daughter and his
son-in-law were killed in a car accident a decade ago.)
</P>
<P>
   Amid the ivy and Georgian red brick at Harvard these days, there
is little of the political ferment of the late '60s, when students
held sit-ins, called strikes and took over campus buildings to
protest the Vietnam War, the ROTC presence and the lack of a black
studies department, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, in a referendum over a boycott of grapes
in support of migrant farm workers, Harvard students voted to
reintroduce the grapes to university dining halls. The campuswide
turnout was larger than in most student elections.
</P>
<P>
   Walking across Harvard Yard recently, Mansfield acknowledged
that there were more conservative students on campus. But he
complained that students now chose courses on the basis of the
professor's politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the students that I get are conservative students and
the ones that I don't aren't,'' he said, adding that he misses the
days when students were quick to challenge him. ``When I was
younger, they listened to me more. Now they respect me more.''
</P>
<P>
   Mansfield said he taught students not so much what to think as
how to think: ``That means going back to the origin of our thoughts
in the early liberals, people like Hobbes and Locke, but it also
means going back to the classical thinkers that they opposed, like
Plato and Aristotle. So I guess that says, `Don't be smug and don't
think that the dominant thoughts today are the only thoughts.'''
</P>
<P>
   John Couriel, a 21-year-old senior who was assistant policy
director to Florida Gov. Jeb Bush during his political campaign,
was among the many conservative students who packed Mansfield's
lecture hall the other day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of temerity at Harvard about thinking seriously
about hard questions, but professor Mansfield is not affected by
that,'' said Couriel, a social studies major. ``It makes him
controversial but also makes him the great scholar he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Another student, Jacqueline Newmyer, a 20-year-old history and
literature major who describes herself as a moderate Republican,
said she was drawn to his traditional approach. ``He's kind of a
breath of fresh air,'' she said. ``A lot of professors here are
kind of immersed in this politically correct, more stylish kind of
teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   But Melvin Priester, a social studies major who received an
A-minus in a contemporary government course with Mansfield last
fall, is less adulatory: ``Mansfield genuinely does believe he is
fighting to save Harvard and the sanctity of American academics.
The question is what really is he saving? I'd argue that he's
saving a tradition of patriarchy and white male dominance.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mansfield's outspokenness has gained him admirers from
the other end of the spectrum. Michael Sandel, a government
professor who has offered the liberal counterpoint in courses that
he has jointly taught with Mansfield, describes him as ``a one-man
antidote to liberal complacency'' at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He saves the Harvard faculty from sliding into smugness and
self-satisfaction,'' Sandel said. ``He forces those of us who
disagree to defend our views and to never stop thinking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
