<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8204 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOBYDICK-METAPHYSICS-     10-15 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOBYDICK-METAPHYSICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERN HUNTS FOR THE GREAT WHITE WHALE LEAVE AHAB ADRIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Skedded earlier as CONNECTIONS.)  
 (bl)  
 By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``What is it,'' Ahab cries in his last moments of reasoned
thought before the chase of the White Whale, ``what is it, what
nameless, inscrutable, unearthly thing is it; what cozening, hidden
lord and master, and cruel, remorseless emperor commands me; that
against all natural lovings and longings, I so keep pushing, and
crowding and jamming myself on all the time?'' Ahab has his
Moby-Dick. But we have our ``Moby-Dick.''
</P>
<P>
   Melville's novel stands whalelike, imperious, encyclopedic,
containing multitudes. Ahab claims that one of the reasons he so
hates the White Whale _ aside from its having devoured his leg _ is
its stupendous mystery. In ordinary life, he tells his first mate,
Starbuck, each event, each deed is a ``pasteboard mask'' hiding
behind its stale form a ``reasoning thing,'' a sensible being. So
too with the whale. And, in his pursuit, Ahab intends to thrust
through this most gargantuan pasteboard mask of all, shove against
its inscrutable barriers and reveal that ``reasoning thing.'' Or
its devilish absence.
</P>
<P>
   And doesn't the novel mount such a challenge as well? While not
inscrutable, it does defy simple scrutiny, hiding its secrets while
proclaiming their immensity. Egyptian pyramids and Greek gods,
Macbeth and Lear, Khan and Jonah, all erupt through waves of
allusive prose. ``Moby-Dick'' can appear, at times, like the
tattoos on the cannibal Queequeg's body, ``a mystical treatise on
the art of attaining truth'' _ on the art, but also on the dangers.
</P>
<P>
   So is it any wonder that the novel also inspires obsessions,
inviting us to tame it, unmask it, strip it of its skin and see
what lies behind this account of a mad quest by a crippled man to
kill a demonic brute? Even in our own decade, so suspicious of
Ahabian imperialism, the challenge is being answered.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, for example, will be the last performance of
Laurie Anderson's ``Songs and Stories From Moby-Dick'' at the
Brooklyn Academy of Music. And a new novel, ``Ahab's Wife''
(William Morrow)'' by Sena Jeter Naslund is a main selection of the
Book-of-the-Month Club and has been hailed for its ``brilliance''
in early reviews. It imagines the life of the obsessed captain's
stay-at-home spouse.
</P>
<P>
   Melville's whaling ships were equipped with the most advanced
equipment of the early 19th century _ whaling was a $120 million
industry, its products ranking third in American exports _ but
contemporary artists come just as heavily laden in their ventures
into Melvillian seas, steering the frigates of 20th-century
invention.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Anderson, these are multimedia tools that turn the
book's cascading prose into showers of video images and replace its
musical cadences with somber, portentous sounds created by
instruments saturated with electronic circuitry. She does not
encircle ``Moby-Dick''; instead she stabs at it with her sardonic
declamations.
</P>
<P>
   And while Ms. Naslund ostensibly preserves Melville's literary
tools _ the exclamations, the alliteration, the sharply contrasting
chapters, the occasional archaic phrase _ she also chases her
subject in ardent 20th-century fashion, with self-conscious
proclamations of political virtue.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Naslund has said that in focusing on Ahab's wife _ a figure
barely mentioned by Melville _ she was attempting to ``redeem the
territory'' of the novel by providing a place in it for women. And
while Melville is in her words ``an advocate of cultural and
religious tolerance,'' she also wanted to suggest tolerance ``for
other people's realities.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Naslund's and Ms. Anderson's ventures both seek to turn the
resources of the novelistic whale to contemporary use, but their
hunts are flawed in different ways. Ms. Anderson is clearly humbled
by the brilliance and peculiarity of ``Moby-Dick,'' and one can see
why Ahab's quest resonates: In her best performance art she has
stripped away society's pasteboard masks, elegantly revealing the
oddities and delusions of modern culture. But her style of wry
commentary is best not at building myths, but at dismantling them.
For example, she turns Melville's astonishing tale of a harpooner
trapped in the sinking skull of a dead whale into a slight
anecdote, finishing with a playful suggestion that the novel is
``really about head size.''
</P>
<P>
   Melville was much more suggestive on his own, both tearing down
and building up, swerving between comic invocations of midwifery in
the rescue of the trapped seaman and solemn descriptions of the
skull's ``sanctum sanctorum'' within which the harpoonist
struggled.
</P>
<P>
   So Ms. Anderson, often despite herself, undercuts the mythic
novel she honors. But Ms. Naslund is intentional in her
dismantling. She rejects the very premises of Melville's universe.
Biblical beliefs are replaced by a good-natured agnosticism.
Metaphysical broodings are supplanted by sentimental musings. Grim
eroticism is turned into maudlin romance (``And here I let out a
little shriek followed unexpectedly by a flotilla of boohoos. `I'm
so happy,' I sobbed, `with Captain Ahab'''). Ahab's wife is an
abolitionist, a perky pacifist, a protofeminist and a sprightly
iconoclast who proudly sings praises of her own ``goat-nimble
mind.'' There is evil in her world _ cannibalism, suicide,
childhood deaths _ but it hardly registers against the sunny
determination to celebrate tolerance and healing.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, in contrast, Melville's tragic universe. No event or
word or action is arbitrary. Everything refers to something else.
Every decision carries with it the burden of consequence. Behind
every mask are hidden truths. His is a dark and precariously
balanced world; there is no escaping its burdens.
</P>
<P>
   And now, it is no more. We have overturned it, magnifying
Melville's sense of irony and diminishing his sense of myth. The
piquant high-tech skepticism of Ms. Anderson often promises that if
only we could see how much we are being manipulated or how much we
distort what we see, we would be able to lighten the world's
burdens.
</P>
<P>
   And the pop-politics of Ms. Naslund promise that if attitudes
were remade or masks changed, this whole Ahab thing might just go
away. Then, perhaps, we could stop all this pushing and crowding
and jamming. Call me Ishmael, but I doubt it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
