<SLUG> BC-CAROLE-KING-TRIBUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAROLE KING, HIGH PRIESTESS OF MELODY, IS HONORED BY HER PEERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANN POWERS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``There's only one universal currency in this
business, and that is melody,'' writes Lewis Shiner in ``Say
Goodbye,'' his new novel about the rock 'n' roll game. ``It's the
great unsolved mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   Carole King, honored Thursday night at the Theater at Madison
Square Garden at a concert that also served as the 25th-anniversary
celebration for People magazine, is that mystery's high priestess.
The hits she wrote with her ex-husband, Gerry Goffin, and others
have fed the legends of soul singers, girl groups, rock stars and,
most impressively, herself.
</P>
<P>
   When her old friend Reba McEntire took the stage, she recalled
how strange it had been to meet someone whose album cover was so
familiar. She was referring to the pensive portrait adorning
``Tapestry,'' the 1971 solo album that made Ms. King one of the
best-selling artists of all time.
</P>
<P>
   At 57, Ms. King still resembles that earthy hippie queen, albeit
in a blessedly wealthy incarnation. She claimed the stage with
friendly enthusiasm for the night's second half. Her voice revealed
raw spots, but remained warm and welcoming, ideal for songs with
which generations have grown up singing along.
</P>
<P>
   Representing those myriad fans was a firmly mainstream celebrity
cast. Mavis Staples offered a playful version of ``One Fine Day.''
Luther Vandross flirted expertly through ``Hey Girl.'' Chrissie
Hynde reminded the audience that this was rock 'n' roll with a
rousing ``Don't Bring Me Down.''
</P>
<P>
   Trisha Yearwood, Rickie Lee Jones, the groups 98 Degrees and
Boyz II Men and Brian McKnight, whose gospel croon on ``Way Over
Yonder'' was enhanced by a small choir, all performed loving takes
on King songs.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. King's daughter Sherry Goffin Kondor also performed, and her
son-in-law, the pianist Robbie Kondor, played in the band. The
ensemble, replete with strings and horns, was conducted by Ms.
King's old friend Paul Shaffer. The jazz musicians Ronnie Laws, Don
Byron, Wallace Roney and John Pizzarelli joined Ms. King for a
rollicking version of ``Jazzman.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. King took time to thank the lyricists who gave her melodies
context and the musicians who lent them human dimension. More of
those original stylists would have enhanced the evening. One did
make a surprise appearance.
</P>
<P>
   James Taylor rushed on stage as Ms. King sang ``You've Got a
Friend'' with Babyface, a reigning superstar of pop songwriting.
Taylor and Babyface traded cool vocal lines as the song ended.
Their mellow intergenerational exchange proved that melodies like
Ms. King's are indeed beyond fashion, lodged in some proverbial
corner of the soul.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
