<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8206 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-RELIGION-ISLAM     10-15 1804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-ISLAM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ava Muhammad ushers in a new day for controversial muslim group
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since Malcolm X thrust the Nation of Islam into the
national spotlight in the 1960s, many people have viewed the group
as a collection of scowling men in bow ties who condemn whites as
``blue-eyed devils.''
</P>
<P>
   Few people know, though, that the Nation is undergoing a
profound transformation _ centered in Atlanta _ that promises to
drastically change its image.
</P>
<P>
   Minister Louis Farrakhan, the Nation of Islam's leader, recently
appointed Sister Minister Ava Muhammad to lead the group's Southern
region. Farrakhan's appointment not only defied 1,400 years of
Muslim custom _ traditional Muslims do not allow women to lead men
in a mosque _ but it offered graphic evidence that the Nation is
moving away from its pit bull approach to race and religion.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad, a regal woman and an attorney, smiles more than she
scowls. She's formed alliances with black clergy. She insists that
she's still a Christian. And she declares that God welcomes people
of all colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all one,'' Muhammad, 48, says. ``It is the ego in us
that assigns labels and names and creates divisions. We can never
say that because you're Jewish, because you're Christian, because
you're Muslim, you're not going to heaven and you're not right.''
</P>
<P>
   At 7 tonight, the public can hear Muhammad when she delivers a
keynote address at the Berean Seventh-day Adventist Church on
Hamilton Holmes Drive. The address will commemorate the fourth
anniversary of the Nation-sponsored Million Man March on
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad is expected to discuss the Nation's ambitious plans:
The group will hold a Million Family March on the nation's capital
next October that's open to all races. And it is organizing a mass
pilgrimage to Mecca for the following year.
</P>
<P>
   The Nation's recent moves _ appointing a woman leader, calling
for a massive interracial march_ are all part of the group's
attempt to redefine itself, observers say.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Lee, author of ``The Nation of Islam'' (Syracuse
University Press, $17.95, 144 pages), says the Nation is modifying
its rhetoric because it no longer wants to be viewed as a fringe
religious movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems only natural that when a group wants to have a more
general political influence, the more extremist part of their
doctrine gets reinterpreted or discarded,'' Lee says. ``If you are
part of the mainstream, you get more people.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of that change was obvious when Muhammad spoke at an
Atlanta church one recent Sunday. She preached at the Imani Temple
on the Atlanta University campus. Ringed by impassive Fruit of
Islam bodyguards, she delivered a sermon that mixed apocalyptic
biblical passages with urges for community service.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two kinds of people _ it's not racial,'' Muhammad
told the group of about 200. ``There are those who do God's will
and those who don't. That's all he cares about.''
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad says her appointment has inspired both Muslim and
Christian women. Women battle sexism in the pulpit and the mosque,
she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (sexism) is so deep-seated in religion, not only in Islam
but in Christianity,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   In the Nation of Islam, Ava Muhammad's appointment was greeted
as a pleasant surprise, says Wendell Muhammad, a Nation member.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minister Farrakhan has always taught us not to follow biology
but to follow wisdom, no matter what vessel it comes through,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   The Nation also accepted Ava Muhammad so readily because she was
already well-known for her legal work with Farrakhan, Wendell
Muhammad said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Ava Muhammad went to federal court and successfully
prevented the federal government from arresting Farrakhan for
traveling to Libya after President Reagan had issued an executive
order banning American travel to the country. And in 1994, Muhammad
successfully sued the New York Post for defamation of Farrakhan's
character.
</P>
<P>
   Ava Muhammad exudes a sharp intelligence combined with a
maternal warmth. Friends say she loves Motown music, books, and
trivia about the Negro baseball leagues. She is also a compulsive
moviegoer (her two recent favorites are ``The Matrix'' and
``Runaway Bride'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Each time I talk to her, I learn something new,'' Wendell
Muhammad says.
</P>
<P>
   Farrakhan handpicked Ava Muhammad at a Chicago meeting of Nation
leaders last July. Muhammad said she was shocked when he turned to
her during a dinner meeting and asked her if she would accept the
position. The room fell silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He actually had someone else in mind,'' Muhammad says, but he
changed his mind on the spot. ``He said he knew in an instant that
I was the one. He stated that it was an act of inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrakhan's inspiration is viewed with skepticism by some
observers. Imam Plemon El-Amin of the Atlanta Masjid of Al-Islam
says Islam does not allow a woman to be an imam, a position
reserved for mosque prayer leaders. ``In Islam, women can be
leaders, but the position of imam is established for men,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   In defiance of that tradition, as part of her new position,
Muhammad has authority over all of the Nation's mosques in the
Southern region.
</P>
<P>
   The Islamic world has not traditionally accepted the Nation of
Islam, says Lee, whose book examined the Nation's mysterious
beginnings. Much of the Islamic community's opposition centers on
the Nation's doctrines.
</P>
<P>
   Lee traced the beginning of the Nation to Detroit in the 1930s,
when Wallace Fard _ a man who the Nation acknowledges was part
white _ first appeared. Fard, who sold silk door-to-door in the
black community, declared that he had come from Mecca to tell
blacks that they were actually lost members of an ancient tribe
called Shabazz.
</P>
<P>
   Fard's message attracted Elijah Poole, the poor son of a country
preacher. Poole, who saw Fard as God incarnate, joined Fard's
movement and adopted the name Elijah Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
   After Fard mysteriously disappeared, Muhammad became the group's
leader. He refined Fard's message and, blending the Bible and the
Koran, preached a doctrine that mixes Islam, Christianity and, some
say, racial hatred.
</P>
<P>
   Under Elijah Muhammad, the Nation disdained getting involved in
American political life. He was imprisoned during World War II for
telling Nation members that they should not join the military. The
Nation also refused to get involved in the traditional civil rights
movement, often scoffing at leaders such as the Rev. Martin Luther
King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad also claimed that he was a prophet and that Fard was a
divine embodiment of Allah. But traditional Islam says that only
God is divine and the 7th century prophet Mohammed _ not Elijah
Muhammad _ was his last messenger, Lee says.
</P>
<P>
   The Nation split over questions of doctrine in 1975 when W. Deen
Mohammed, Elijah Muhammad's son, changed the group's name to the
American Muslim Society and asked members to follow traditional
Islam. Farrakhan, ignoring Mohammed, revived the Nation of Islam
name and preserved the teachings of Elijah Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin, who was once a member of the Nation, said more Nation
members are leaving the group because its doctrine does not conform
to traditional Islam. Late in his life, Malcolm X _perhaps the
Nation's most well-known symbol _ disavowed the group, partially
over questions of doctrine, and embraced traditional Islam.
</P>
<P>
   People who leave the Nation, El-Amin says, ``begin to study a
littler deeper and they realize that Islam is much bigger than the
small idea that God is black.''
</P>
<P>
   A symbollic message?
</P>
<P>
   Ava Muhammad, however, defends the Nation's Islamic credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a presumption, which is 100 percent wrong, that the
teachings of Elijah Muhammad are not in accord with mainstream
Islam,'' she said. ``Nothing can be further from the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Nation members insist that some of Elijah Muhammad's
teachings are simply symbolic, not to be taken literally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in many respects more in harmony with the requirements
of the holy Koran than many Muslim societies where people drink
alcohol, smoke cigarettes and women dress immodestly,'' Ava
Muhammad says.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad's background may help her handle the criticisms
directed at the Nation. She was raised to be a leader, she says. A
native of Columbus, Ohio, she grew up in a middle-class home where
her parents were teachers. Her early heroes were people like King
and Stokely Carmichael (later known as Kwame Ture).
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Georgetown University law school in 1975,
Muhammad eventually became a criminal defense attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Her turning point came at age 28, when she was diagnosed with
cancer. For comfort, Muhammad says, she returned to the Methodist
church where she was raised, but it didn't help her overcome her
fear of death. On a lark, she decided to go hear Farrakhan speak in
New York City. She had long admired the Nation's insistence on
black self-reliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard him talk about Allah, it penetrated my very
being,'' recalls Muhammad, who says her cancer disappeared after
hearing Farrakhan speak. ``I knew that this was what I was born to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad envisions her current role as a bridge-builder among
women and people of different faiths. She is close friends with
Essence magazine editor Susan Taylor and with Iyanla Vanzant, the
best-selling self-help author. Muhammad's husband, Brother Darius,
is usually at her side during her public lectures.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad says she wants to refute the idea that the Nation is
filled with the ``lunatic fringe'' of society.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't like being viewed as haters of people,'' Muhammad
says. ``It hurts. We're like everybody else. We like to go and see
films. We like to listen to music. We like to go on vacation. It's
difficult when you walk through places and some people look at you
_ sometimes your own people _ with hostility because of what
someone said to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Haney, a professor of religion at the Interdenominational
Theological Center, an Atlanta seminary, says that while the public
is fascinated by the Nation's stormy past, Muhammad represents its
best hope for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a very smart woman and she plays her role very well,''
Haney says. ``She's articulate on any spiritual issue. The Nation
realizes that, in order for it to survive, it has to change its
theology.''
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad says, however, that the Nation's theology is simply
evolving.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been an evolution in the message,'' she says. ``But
it is not changing and going into a different direction. It is
moving toward that which the Creator intended it to be.''
</P>
<P>
   John Blake writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
