<SLUG> BC-PAVAROTTI-OPERA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOULD PAVAROTTI SING CAVARADOSSI? YES. 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The popular Franco Zeffirelli production of Puccini's
``Tosca'' returned to the Metropolitan Opera on Thursday night, but
the buzz in the house centered on one question only: could Luciano
Pavarotti, just two days after his 64th birthday, still sing the
role of Cavaradossi?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is a qualified yes, though his performance has to be
taken in context.
</P>
<P>
   First is the matter of Pavarotti's health. Last year he
underwent major knee and hip surgery correcting long-standing
problems that had severely limited his mobility and stamina.
</P>
<P>
   He recovered sufficiently to sing the gala performance in late
November commemorating his 30th season with the Met, but just
barely. His voice still had its distinctive color and beauty, but
lacked power. Then he returned in the spring for some quite
satisfying performances as Cavaradossi.
</P>
<P>
   By now this would appear to be one of the few roles he can still
handle. Though he had to husband his vocal resources strategically
to get through it, Pavarotti did some impressive singing. There was
not much in the way of character depiction, however.
</P>
<P>
   When Cavaradossi, after being brutally tortured by Scarpia's
henchmen, overhears the news of Napoleon's victory at the Battle of
Marengo, he is supposed to leap to his feet and sing triumphant
cries of ``Vittoria! Vittoria!''
</P>
<P>
   Pavarotti, hardly spontaneous, walked slowly to the rim of the
stage, planted his feet firmly in place, faced the audience,
composed himself, wet his lips and started to sing. But his
full-voiced, ringing high notes _ first F-sharp, then A-sharp _
were thrillingly unleashed.
</P>
<P>
   Having delivered, he had scant voice left for the rest of
Cavaradossi's outburst. In general, Pavarotti sounded patchy and
weak in his lower range. Still, there was that Pavarotti sound and
we are going to miss it when he is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Even with his shortcomings, Pavarotti gave the most complete
performance of the evening. Dramatically, the soprano Elizabeth
Holleque was an alluring and ardent Tosca. But her voice was sadly
tested by this role. Her high notes were short-breathed, harsh and
shouted. There was little legato in her phrasing.
</P>
<P>
   As Scarpia, the baritone Juan Pons had ample power, but it came
at a price: constant huffing and puffing behind nearly every note.
Daniel Oren conducted a fleetly paced and vigorous performance,
though sometimes the ensemble was inexact and the orchestral sound
overly thick.
</P>
<P>
   So will Pavarotti return next season for yet another try at
Cavaradossi? If so, there will surely be loyal fans eager to cheer
him on.
</P>
<P>
   He sings four more performances this month through Oct. 30. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
