<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-YOUNG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NINERS QB'S FUTURE FUZZY AFTER CONCUSSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATTHEW YI AND DWIGHT CHAPIN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ While Steve Young's future with the San
Francisco 49ers is uncertain, the likelihood that he will suffer
another concussion if he returns to the game is not. And the
cumulative effect of multiple concussions can be deadly.
</P>
<P>
   Although much about concussions remains a mystery and people
recover differently, neurosurgeons agree that it is not a good idea
for a person who has suffered one to be in a situation where
physical trauma is part of the routine. Young has had four
concussions in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Repetitive concussions cause cumulative brain injury, and
cumulative brain injury causes problems in the future for you and
your family,'' said Dr. Jay Rosenberg, neurosurgeon at Kaiser
Permanente in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg, co-author of the guidelines on concussions for the
American Academy of Neurology, said he could not determine Young's
condition without examining him, but it is no secret that multiple
concussions take a toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have repetitive concussions ... basically you're
losing your brain cells,'' he said. ``The issue is, how many brain
cells do you have to lose before you decide to quit?''
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old 49ers quarterback has been sitting on the bench
since he was knocked out in a game against Arizona on Sept. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Young's doctor said Thursday that although tests show no
bruising of Young's brain, it still needs time to recover and he
will not play Sunday against the Carolina Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gary Steinberg, chairman of the Department of Neurosurgery
at Stanford University Medical Center, said he made a medical
recommendation to Young regarding the concussion, but did not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to figure out how many concussions a person may have
before suffering permanent damage is difficult, said Dr. Martin
Holland, a neurosurgeon at the University of California at San
Francisco who practices at San Francisco General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a million-dollar question,'' he said. ``Does one
concussion lead to permanent injury? Some do, and some don't. What
about multiple concussions? We don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult for doctors to advise injured athletes on
whether they should retire or continue playing, especially when the
concussions seem mild, Holland said. The final judgment usually
lies with the athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve Young is a very intelligent man. He's a big boy. He's
responsible for his health and safety,'' Holland said. ``The only
thing that his physician can do is to let him know what the risks
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Holland said that, based on several studies, one thing that Is
clear is that people who have suffered concussions in the past are
more likely to have them again in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is no answer why that may be true, one theory is
that aggressive players are likely to have concussions and will
suffer more in the future, unless they change their ways, Holland
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another reason may be that the first concussion has slightly
impaired the athlete and he's prone to get hurt again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a normally functioning brain, the cells constantly fire
neurotransmitters in a coordinated manner. A big enough blow to the
head could cause a massive release of neurotransmitters at one
time, causing the person to lose consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have loss of brain cells, which may lead to other
things like loss of memory, problems concentrating or handling
complex problems,'' Holland said.
</P>
<P>
   A severe blow can bruise the brain, leading to internal bleeding
and possible blood clots, which can be fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Although full recovery is possible from mild concussions,
Holland and Rosenberg said they think there are residual effects
each time an athlete gets knocked out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Concussions aren't a new problem for athletes. National Football
League players Merril Hoge, Al Toon and Chris Miller all were
forced to retire because of head injuries, although Miller returned
this season as a backup quarterback with the Denver Broncos, after
being away from the game for three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Hoge, who is now an ESPN radio sportscaster, left the Chicago
Bears in 1994 after suffering two concussions within six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Often players are almost fatalistic about the risks they face
when _ to use a long-popular football phrase _ they ``get their
bells rung.''
</P>
<P>
   Before returning to the NFL, Miller, who has yet to play in a
regular-season game this season, consulted a series of doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `Sure, you have a risk,''' he said. `You might have
a 4 to 6 percent chance of sustaining another concussion compared
to the normal player who hasn't had problems.' But I could get hit
by a golf ball walking down the fairway or get in a car wreck or
whatever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
