<HEADER>
A8216 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DENMARK-THEATER-REVIE     10-15 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENMARK-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MYTHOS': A DANISH THEATER COMPANY ESCAPES NARRATIVE THROUGH
RHYTHM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Denmark, Poland, Italy)  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By D.J.R. BRUCKNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rhythm is the soul of Odin Teatret's sumptuous
``Mythos''; music is a frayed thread barely holding the limbs of
the actors together as the rhythm threatens to shake them to
pieces, and language is a murmur of anger and wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ``All dies, all is born again'' are among the few intelligible
words in this stunning performance, and they suffice. Eugenio
Barba, the Italian founder and director of Odin Teatret, Denmark's
most celebrated theater company, has sought for 30 years to escape
from narrative and its nagging companions, calendars and clocks. In
this work _ the centerpiece of a program of seven Danish plays at
La Mama through the end of the month _ the escape is complete.
</P>
<P>
   So perfect, in fact, that the performance can hardly be said to
have an audience, only individual viewers or participants. Some
look puzzled, restless; occasionally one will laugh, startling
others. A young woman sitting next to me on opening night got it
right: after a while one of her feet was unconsciously tapping;
rhythm is understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Barba carries the group theater idea further than his teacher,
Jerzy Grotowski, did in Poland or the Living Theater did here. He
presents a notion for a play and lets each actor develop a role,
drawing on song, verse, dance, chants, acrobatics, whatever; only
at the end does he try to draw a common progress (nothing so
definite as a plot) from the cast's sounds and movements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mythos'' rests on an image of Guilhermino Barbosa, one of
thousands of Brazilian soldiers who from 1925 to 1927 marched
15,500 miles through their country protesting government
corruption. Barbosa later barricaded himself in a jungle shack,
remaining until his death faithful to his revolution. Myths that
control civilizations also die, Barba says, and in ``Mythos'' Greek
mythical figures, who might themselves have just emerged from
graves, struggle with the question of whether Barbosa and his ideal
or we and our myths can be reborn.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers sit on two sides of an oblong stage paved with loose
black stones that are raked into labyrinths, oceans, graveyards or
gardens by the tireless stone-pusher Sisyphus and some others.
Orpheus, the great seeker, little more than an animal skull above
an empty cloak, drives fellow heroes into action. Cassandra, all
fire and seduction, finds giddy freedom in her incredibility, and
Medea's murdered children become countless legions in their
mother's laments. Fear alone impels Daedalus to fly lest he fall;
Oedipus survives, indeed thrives, on scorn for anyone with hope;
and that primal shape-shifter, Odysseus, is so enthralled with
human folly he never notices his own.
</P>
<P>
   Amid these gods Barbosa's endless march gives tragedy itself a
distinct gait until, in a surprisingly poignant moment, Orpheus
stabs the soldier right through his accordion and he is reborn in
an unforgettable vision of the accordion playing itself somewhere
above the earth.
</P>
<P>
   Some vocal effects produced in songs and chants are wildly
beautiful or terrifying, and one cannot quite imagine how they are
made. The words are by the Danish poet Henrik Nordbrandt. La Mama
announces that all plays but one in Odin Teatret's presentations
here are in English. Not quite. Most of the lines in ``Mythos'' are
not translated, but they don't really have to be; in ways it is
hard to put a finger on, the actors make the meaning transparent.
</P>
<P>
   One bit of translation not available might have helped: in
several talks Barba has mentioned the ancient practice of military
victors' cutting one hand off each prisoner no matter how many they
captured. People seeing ``Mythos'' should know that, since hundreds
of carved wooden hands have lives of their own in the play.
</P>
<P>
   Odin Teatret, which has a large following in Europe and Latin
America, has been seen here only once before, also at La Mama, 15
years ago. Since the very idea of group theater seems to have died
out in this country, experiencing the almost religious intensity of
``Mythos'' leaves one feeling that this surprisingly effective
meditation on death and resurrection is a fitting emblem for the
company.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MYTHOS'
</P>
<P>
   Based on poems by Henrik Nordbrandt and texts by the Odin
Theater. Directed by Eugenio Barba. Sets and costumes by Odin
Theater; lighting by Jesper Kongshaug; music by Odin Theater, with
political and popular songs; musical director, Frans Winther. Odin
Theater presented by La Mama ETC in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   With: Kai Bredholt (Guilhermino Barbosa), Roberta Carreri
(Cassandra), Jan Ferslev (Orpheus), Tage Larsen (Oedipus), Iben
Nagel Rasmussen (Medea), Julia Varley (Daedalus), Torgeir Wethal
(Odysseus) and Frans Winther (Sisyphus).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1747EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8217 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-VICK'S-THEATER-REVIEW     10-15 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VICK'S-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`VICK'S BOY': SHALLOW BUT FUNNY MAYHEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes appear at the end of the review.) 
(mk) 
 By D.J.R. BRUCKNER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Facts about Ben Bettenbender's play ``Vick's Boy'':
Its premise is as silly as its lines, many of them cliches of
television sitcoms; it is plotless, and if its jokes and occasional
slapstick are not as old as Aristophanes, any ancient Roman would
know them.
</P>
<P>
   Yet thanks to a smart, energetic cast and direction, by Bob
Balaban, that could make most video combat games look slower than
shuffleboard, the Rattlestick Productions version of ``Vick's Boy''
at Theater Off Park keeps an audience laughing for two hours.
</P>
<P>
   A Manhattan law firm is dominated by a real termagant called
Molly (Johanna Day), whose name has become a verb meaning to get
axed. An office manager, Vick (Rob Sedgwick), plots to get her into
bed and have their sex videotaped so he can blackmail her into
guaranteeing him a cushy lifetime job with no duties. He traps a
nervous clerk, Lester (Andrew Polk), into handling the camera.
Invading their scheme and vastly complicating it is Keith (Jim
Bracchitta), the office's cowardly sponge.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out Molly is a bit of a prude, and Lester, manning the
camera while hiding in a closet and under a bed, is, of course,
wildly claustrophobic. So the tape is a hilarious piece of
confusion. But Molly doesn't know that. She quits the firm and
retreats to a sleepy South Jersey town where a repentant Lester
finds her and gives her a totally improbable kind of consolation.
</P>
<P>
   The cast approaches all this nonsense like cutups at a party and
the atmosphere seems to take hold of the audience immediately.
Bracchitta and Polk, who run the Cape Cod Theater Project in
Massachusetts, are a fine pair of old-fashioned comics; when they
are together you know anyone who is rational will fall victim to
them _ as Sedgwick's and Ms. Day's characters do with exasperated
astonishment.
</P>
<P>
   It's shallow, but there are enough moments that are like Laurel
and Hardy without the mayhem to keep the laughter rolling.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `VICK'S BOY'
</P>
<P>
   By Ben Bettenbender; directed by Bob Balaban; sets by Van
Santvoord; lighting by Ed McCarthy; costumes by David Woolard;
sound by Laura Grace Brown. Presented by Rattlestick Productions,
in association with Daryl Roth Productions and Connie Simmons. At
Theater Off Park, 224 Waverly Place, Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   With: Rob Sedgwick (Vick), Johanna Day (Molly), Andrew Polk
(Lester), Justin Hagan (Patrick) and Jim Bracchitta (Keith).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1748EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8221 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-ART-CENTURY16-COX     10-15 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-CENTURY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    America's art story, Part II, a little hazy
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 17.
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``The American Century'' at the Whitney Museum of Art
is a 100-year retrospective of art and its relationship to culture.
Part one, which examined the first half of the century, was an
absorbing interplay of the fine, decorative and popular arts that
told America's story. Ironically, as American art comes into its
own in the second half of the century, the exhibition itself loses
steam.
</P>
<P>
   One problem is inherent in modern and contemporary art. For one
thing, it's more difficult to make connections between the
historical narrative and abstract or even contemporary figurative
art, especially in the visual language of an exhibit. For another,
there may be little connection to make: Most of the art of the
second half of the century evolves in response to the art that
precedes it, not the Cold War or the hippie movement. In other
words, Andy Warhol influenced the course of art history more than
John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of being woven together, the strands of culture and
history seem to barely intersect. If part one of this exhibit was a
tapestry, part two is more like a map of Atlanta's highway system.
Even the visual art and other arts in the ``cultural sites'' _
displays of books, video and television clips, music, etc. _ no
longer seem like partners.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, part two becomes an art survey rather than a
cross-cultural exploration _ and a superficial, predictable one at
that. It even takes the traditional art historical approach of
excluding art forms considered minor, such as ceramics, industrial
design and outsider art.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there are many occasions when art links up with life. You
could point to pop art and its relationship to consumer culture.
The broadening of the mainstream art world to include feminist and
ethnic artists in the '70s and '80s reflected (or in some cases,
preceded) stronger voices of women and minorities in society.
Artists who came to prominence during the '80s, like Cindy Sherman
and Barbara Kruger, took aim at our media culture. And photography,
which is put to many uses during the last few decades, never
abandons its documentary role, as affirmed by the series of images
that convey the events and emotions of the civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   But, in large measure, art establishes its own context and its
own concerns. One sub-theme is art's ever-expanding formal
boundaries. Eva Hesse and Lucas Samaras are among those who use
everyday materials in unusual ways. For Robert Smithson _
represented by photos and a video of his great earthwork, ``Spiral
Jetty''_ Earth and sky, tides and erosion become his palette and
vocabulary. Video in many forms becomes a popular medium.
</P>
<P>
   Another sub-theme is the artist's position as outsider. This
stance _ or is it a natural inclination? _ liberates the artist to
criticize the center as well as to explore, and occupy, territory
at the edges. Nan Goldin's ``Ballad of Sexual Dependency,'' an
unflinching audiovisual presentation of dysfunctional lives of her
East Village friends, is one of the show's most moving pieces.
</P>
<P>
   But this path has led artists outside conventional morality, and
the chasm this creates between the art world and the rest of the
world is not without consequences. Indeed, as a time line on the
culture wars adjacent to Andres Serrano's ``Piss Christ'' reminds
us, the differing world views can be explosive and deleterious. It
can even divide the art community: The sexual antics and violence
in former Atlantan Kara Walker's ``Gone With the Wind''-era
silhouettes, one of which is included here, outraged fellow
African-American artists as well as members of the lay audience.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the achievements of so many artists and incendiary
quality of the most current art, the ``American Century'' is
missing a spark. Maybe it's because the first half of the century,
during which America experienced the Depression and two world wars,
was more eventful. Possibly it's because the seismic social shifts
of the second half are more difficult to convey. And certainly, the
aesthetic revolutions of the art world pale in comparison to both.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as the current controversy about the dung-adorned image of
the Madonna at the Brooklyn Museum of Art confirms, visual art is
still very potent as a set of symbols. Maybe the act of squeezing
the chaos of modern and contemporary art into a linear narrative
squeezed out the excitement.
</P>
<P>
   VISUAL ARTS REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``The American Century: Art &AMP; Culture 1900-2000, Part II''
</P>
<P>
   Whitney Museum of American Art. 945 Madison Ave., New York.
Through Feb. 13. 11 a.m.-6 p.m. Tuesdays, Wednesdays,
Fridays-Sundays; 1-8 p.m. Thursdays. $12.50; $10.50 senior citizens
and students, plus $2 for timed tickets. To order advance tickets
or for information: 1-877-944-8639 or www.whitney.org.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: The art heats up, but the show loses steam.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fox writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
