<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8225 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CLINTON-DATA17-COX     10-15 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DATA17-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   SIDEBAR TO COX-CLINTON-AGENDA17
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday, October 17
</P>
<P>
   Moving in Washington (w) and Politics (p) categories
</P>
<P>
   c. Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Campaign politics and increasingly sour relations between the
White House and the Republican-controlled Congress have dimmed the
prospects for a host of initiatives President Clinton had once
hoped to enact. Fifteen months before he leaves office, the
following Clinton proposals are at risk:
</P>
<P>
   - Social Security reform. The centerpiece of his 1998 State of
the Union address, Clinton called for a year-long bipartisan
conversation on how to adjust premiums, benefits or both to put the
giant federal retirement insurance program on sound financial
footing. The conversation took place, but Clinton and the
Republicans have not joined to hash out a plan for shoring up the
system, which is set to begin hemorhaging red ink sometime around
the year 2013.
</P>
<P>
   - Medicare reform. Another State of the Union promise was to
overhaul the massive federal health insurance program and to add a
prescription drug benefits package to it. Neither is moving
forward.
</P>
<P>
   - Tobacco tax increases. Clinton has proposed raising federal
cigarette taxes by 55 cents a pack _ a measure that would raise an
estimated $8 billion a year in revenues _ and use the money to
finance spending increases in areas such as education and law
enforcement. He's also proposed forcing polluting companies to pay
a larger share of the cost of environmental cleanup. Republicans
oppose measures, but the White House remains hopeful for some
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   - Hiring new teachers. Clinton pressed through a plan last year
to hire an additional 29,000 new teachers in an effort to reduce
class size in elementary schools. He wants to triple that number,
but even the current hires are under threat amid the ongoing 2000
budget battle. Republicans want to give the money to local school
boards and let them decide what to do with it. Clinton has
threatened a veto when the spending bill arrives on his desk as
early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   - World Trade Organization. Clinton will lead a summit in
Seattle at the end of November to kick off the ninth round of
global trade talks since 1947. His hand in the talks is weakened,
though, by his inability to win so-called ``fast track''
negotiating authority from Congress and by the global perception of
his standing as a result of the failure last week of the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty. Clinton's biggest problem on trade,
though, comes from within his own party. It's Democrats, in the
main, who oppose ``fast track,'' and, as Vice President Al Gore
continues to woo the support of organized labor, even Clinton's
plans for negotiating China's admission into the World Trade
Organization face uphill sledding on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
