<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Saturday, Oct. 16. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ A jittery stock market moved sharply lower
Friday after Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan again
expressed concern about the high level of stock prices and an
inflation report showed prices rising at an unexpectedly rapid
rate. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   STARR-SUCCESSOR (Washington) _ A federal judicial panel has
selected Robert Ray, a 39-year-old prosecutor, to succeed Kenneth
Starr as the Whitewater independent counsel. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-MOOD (Rawalpindi, Pakistan) _ In the bazaars of
Rawalpindi, life goes on as it did before Pakistan was plunged into
a state of emergency by its new military ruler. But if there is
such a thing as a good coup, this one is winning raves in
Rawalpindi. By Tim Weiner and Steve Levine.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-WESTBANK (Neve Erez, West Bank) _ Prime Minister Ehud
Barak's soldiers are unlikely to face much resistance when they
arrive to dismantle this illegal settlement, one of many
settlements that will be shut down. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   NOBEL-PEACE-PRIZE (Paris) _ Medecins Sans Frontieres(Doctors
Without Borders), which sends doctors and nurses to some of the
most destitute and dangerous parts of the world and encourages them
not only to save lives but to condemn the injustices they see, was
awarded the Nobel Peace Prize on Friday. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
