<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8229 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v BC-SPOT-BJT16-COXUPDATE     10-15 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 UPDATE &HT;    UPDATE
 &HT;    Eds: Adds: ATL-OLY, GERONIMO-HEADRESS, YOUNG-CANCER
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Saturday, October 16,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-MONEY _ Gov. George W. Bush has spent more than $20
million, more than most of his opponents have raised. We look at
what he's spending his money on. Friday is the day candidates must
file campaign finance reports with the FEC. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   IRENE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Though barely a hurricane with
75 mph winds around its center, Irene's torrential rains threatened
to flood the lower third of the Florida peninsula today as the
storm crawled across the straits separating Cuba from the United
States. (Palm Beach Post). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   GERONIMO-HEADRESS _ ATLANTA _ The attorney who was charged after
trying to sell Geronimo's headdress over the Internet now hopes to
resolve his legal mess by donating the headdress to a national
museum. But the FBI has no plans to drop the charges. (Shelton,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-CANCER _ ATLANTA _ Former Mayor Andrew Young has been
diagnosed with early-stage prostate cancer. Surgery skedded for
December. (Kurylo, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HOMECOMING-DESEGREGATION _ COWETA COUNTY, Ga. _ Decades after
lunch counters, city buses and schools were integratged, one of the
last vestiges of segregation is going by the wayside this weekend:
East Coweta's homecoming queen. For 30 years, ever since the black
and white school systems merged, East Coweta has been electing two
queens _ one white and one black. Students lobbied for the change,
so this year only one queen will be named. (Donsky, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GIRLS-SCHOOLS _ ATLANTA _ Research suggesting that boys and
girls learn in different ways is sparking a national trend toward
single-sex classrooms. The private Walker School, in Marietta, Ga.,
has been separating boys and girls for middle grade math. While a
few public school single-sex experiments are under attack in
California and Michigan, 27 private girls schools have sprung up in
3 years. Now some Atlanta parents have hired a school head to open
the Atlanta Girls School next year, the first single-sex
pre-college school around Atlanta in 50 years. (Cumming, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ATL-OLY _ Rep. Fred Upton plans to seek more answers from
Atlanta's Olympic officials about their lobbying tactics. They'll
be given questions and writing and must provide quick responses. At
the same time, lawmakers will continue to threaten legislative
action to keep the heat on the IOC to ensure they enact reforms.
(Turner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Also moving in the general news (a) category
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA-WINES _ TELAVI, Republic of Georgia _ The last man in
this former Soviet republic who knows how to handcraft a wooden
barrel is suddenly in demand. This green vale in the shadow of the
Caucasus Mountains was the Napa Valley of the Tsars. Georgian wines
were prized for their flavor and clarity. And then came the Soviet
industrial revolution. The Soviet's built mass-production plants in
the '50s with gigantic steel vats that reduced Georgian wines to
the mediocre. Now, hoping to revive their winemaking skills and
appeal to lucrative Western markets, Georgian winemakers are going
back to the future. They want to store their wines once again in
oak barrels. That's where Rubiko Batiashivili comes in. He learned
the craft as a teenager half a century ago, and now he's finally
putting the skill to work. (Holmes, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Wed., Oct. 13 in (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   PANDAS-WILD _ WOLONG, China _ One thousand pandas _ it sounds
like a lot of the cuddly-bear mammals still lumber through China's
bamboo-forested mountains. But despite glowing reports of
conservation and scientific successes, wildlife experts are not at
all convinced the enchanting animals will survive to amble through
many new chapters in their 3,000-year history. Efforts are being
made to stop the encroachment of mankind that has cut up panda
territory and divided the panda population, making genetic
in-breeding a potentially deadly problem. And now the Chinese are
laying the groundwork for the precarious possibility of
reintroducing to the wild pandas born in captivity.
(Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service). 30. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Wed., Oct. 13 in (i) International and (L) Lifestyle
categories.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA _ MOSCOW _ When President Boris Yeltsin in
August named a relatively unknown former spy chief to be his prime
minister and designated presidential successor, few Russians had
ever heard of Vladimir Putin, much less formed an opinion of him.
But today, as he sternly directs the war against the breakaway
republic of Chechnya and is seen as a no-nonsense administrator in
Moscow, his popularity has soared. (Holmes, Cox News Service). 20.
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SEAT-BELTS _ WASHINGTON _ Seat belt safety laws do not
contribute to the racial harassment of African American drivers, a
new study reported on Friday. (Schultz, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   TEACHERS-REFORMS _ WASHINGTON _ How top teachers say they plan
to cope with the big changes they see lying ahead for the public
schools. Based on interviews at the end of a three-day federal
strategy session for top teachers, including each state's current
teacher of the year. (Mollison, Cox News Service). 22.
</P>
