<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8230 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-5-QUESTIONS-$ADV1     10-15 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-5-QUESTIONS-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIVE QUESTIONS FOR BERNARD ARNAULT  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After months of behind-the-scenes wrangling, a victor emerged
last week in the battle for Fendi SpA, the Italian luxury design
house best known for its Baguette bag, a wide Tootsie Roll-shaped
purse that fits snugly under the arm.
</P>
<P>
   The winning bid came from an unusual partnership of two bigger
luxury-goods companies, LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton and Prada,
that have each been on an acquisition binge.
</P>
<P>
   This year alone, LVMH, which owns designer houses like Givenchy
and Celine, has gobbled up majority interests in Hard Candy and
Bliss SpA, while Prada has bought stakes in Jil Sanders and Helmut
Lang.
</P>
<P>
   LVMH and Prada did not disclose how much they were paying for 51
percent of Fendi, a privately held company, but people close to the
deal put it at about $520 million. That implies a value for Fendi
in excess of $1 billion, a stunning amount for a company whose net
income last year was estimated at $10 million to $17 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Arnault, chairman of LVMH and a leader in the
consolidation of luxury-goods brands, spoke about the deal last
week. Here are excerpts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Leslie Kaufman
</P>
<P>
   Q. Did you pay too much for Fendi?
</P>
<P>
   A. When I was offered Gucci five years ago, it was almost
bankrupt, and I was offered it for around the same amount, $1
billion. I made an offer at a lower price, because at the time it
was not making any money.
</P>
<P>
   So the question is, are we convinced we can do in the next five
years what has been done in the last five years with companies such
as Gucci and Prada? If we are convinced, which we are, the question
of price versus earnings does not mean anything, because five years
from now it will be a fantastique investment. If you are not
convinced of that, you should not touch it.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is the game plan to make Fendi grow rapidly?
</P>
<P>
   A. The problem is that they have not enough shops. They are
extremely successful, but people have to wait for the bags, because
they have not enough shops and not enough production capacity. With
our friends at Prada we will give them production in Italy, and
with Vuitton we will give them shops. This business should explode
in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Vuitton, Prada and Fendi all do a big leather accessory
business. You could be considered rivals. Won't there be conflicts
of interest?
</P>
<P>
   A. Fendi will be run by a team already in place. There is
already a very good managing director, but he was not given the
investment capacity to grow the business. We have spent a lot of
money, so we will do everything possible to make it a success.
</P>
<P>
   When you say we are rivals, I am not so sure. When we are
together, Prada, Vuitton or Dior in the mall, we do more business
than when we are isolated all over the city. It is in our common
interest to do something together.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are there ways the new owners can help cut Fendi's costs?
</P>
<P>
   A. We will help them purchase raw materials or give them to them
at our price. With our ad-buying power, immediately they will save
20 percent. There are numbers of their products they can make in
Prada's factories in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   We will give them, across the world, some of the best locations
at the best price. Little Fendi alone trying to rent space in
Manhattan, it is difficult. When you arrive with Prada, Vuitton,
Dior and Givenchy asking for space, you get larger space at a lower
price.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are there names of Fendi's caliber still out there to be
bought?
</P>
<P>
   A. There are not many. That is why we were so interested in
doing this deal. It is not a frequent phenomenon to have a brand
that is so hot and is still small.
</P>
<P>
   If you take Vuitton, it is hot, but big. Prada, it is hot, but
big. So from an investment standpoint it is better to get them hot
and small.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0178 </DOCNO>
