<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8236 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-SYMPHONY-BOS &LR;      10-15 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SYMPHONY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BSO MAKES AN ASTONISHING DREAM JOURNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The story goes that Dr. Samuel Johnson, standing by the
fireplace as he began to turn the pages of Henry Fielding's novel
``Amelia,'' was so enthralled that he didn't even move to a chair
until he had finished it. Afterward he said, ``This has enlarged my
experience of life.''
</P>
<P>
   This is pretty much how this listener felt after hearing the
world premiere of Peter Lieberson's ``Red Garuda'' with the Boston
Symphony Thursday night. Lieberson's association with the BSO has
been career-long: He composed his first orchestral work for pianist
Peter Serkin and the BSO in 1983, and the BSO also commissioned
``Drala''; other pieces of his have been performed during the
Tanglewood Festival of Contemporary Music. He is a known quantity,
but always a surprising one: Before this season opened, Seiji Ozawa
remarked that ``Red Garuda'' is the work of a composer utterly
changed.
</P>
<P>
   It is certainly an astonishing and masterly work by a composer
who has learned both to look inward and to turn outward; his music
describes inner experience in a public way that does not violate or
betray its integrity and intensely personal nature. The piece is a
response to a dream or vision about being lifted by a giant
red-orange bird above daily concerns so that Lieberson could see
whole, elemental landscapes _ literally so, for the landscapes are
of fire, water, and earth/wind. Technically, the piece unfolds as a
series of variations. The piano, played by Serkin again, is not a
concerto soloist but a prominent part of a continuously shifting
texture, as in Scriabin's ``Prometheus: A Poem of Fire''; the
emphasis is on the upper reaches of the keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   The writing is vivid, kaleidoscopic both in color and in
texture; the piece sounds full throughout, but the full orchestra
is in fact never simultaneously heard. Water, first glimpsed in
clarinet tremolos, shimmers; earth, usually the bad guy in elements
pieces, sounds like a delightfully capricious place to be (or to be
soaring above) _ among other things, ``Red Garuda'' is almost
completely nonjudgmental. The piece as a whole traces an emotional
journey no less complete and compelling than the visual one; it
begins in one place and ends in another _ a final flap of wing
above the gleam of the crotales (bell-like tuned cymbals). Under
Ozawa's vigilant leadership the performance was wonderfully
persuasive, and Serkin has both the attack it takes to be heard and
the imagination and coloristic variety to be worth hearing; the
page turner was assistant conductor Federico Cortese, no less. The
audience greeted the appearance of the composer
</P>
<P>
   on stage with warmth, enthusiasm, and gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   The second half of the program was Tchaikovsky's Fifth Symphony,
a familiar choice when there is a challenging new work at hand. It
did not sound over-rehearsed _ there was even an early brass
entrance, the kind of anticipation you never hear at BSO concerts.
But the performance had intensity, fire, and inspiration, some
luscious playing, a delicious lilt in the waltz, and haunting
colors and dynamics in the eloquently phrased horn solo in the
second movement (James Sommerville). Ozawa has cleaned up his
interpretation, omitting many traditional taffy-pull rubatos in
which he used to indulge. The only problem was that too much was
too loud; one feels certain that Tchaikovsky, living before
airplanes, CDs, and amplified music, never heard anything this
loud; 20th-century man has chosen his ears for mutilation. Too
often Ozawa left himself nowhere further to go, and Tchaikovsky
always did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
