<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8238 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-SPOOKY-WORLD-BOS &LR;      10-15 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOOKY-WORLD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORROR THEME PARK SCARES UP SOME NEW HAUNTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ ``I'm alive!'' exclaims the round-faced man
in the rented trailer. Dave Bertolino, 45, the co-owner of Spooky
World, is ebullient, holding court in the modest hospitality area
at his theme park on this crisp autumn night. ``I am thrilled to be
alive again.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Spooky World _ which bills itself as ``America's Horror
Theme Park'' _ has risen from the dead. Unlike zombies in George
Romero movies, this was not exactly a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   Spooky World, the October-only, Halloween-themed attraction, has
relocated from its home of eight years, land owned or leased by
Bertolino in Berlin, Mass., and set up shop on 60 wooded acres near
Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It has hauled its interactive attractions, including the Haunted
Hayride and its haunted houses _ a 3D disco, a phantom mine shaft,
Tom Savini's House of Horror and a killer-clown riddled Cirque
Macabre _ down the pike, spent $4 million on construction, and is
beckoning New Englanders by promising to once again scare the wits
out of them with things that go bump in the night, at a rather more
advanced level than your local neighborhood Halloween spook house.
</P>
<P>
   And this much is true: Every time a ghoul barks at you in the
dark, you jump. Maybe not as much the 100th time as the first time,
but you do jump.
</P>
<P>
   Spooky World's second life has been immensely aided by Foxboro
Associates, which is helmed by the New England Patriots-owning
Kraft family. Bertolino, a self-proclaimed ``hauntrepreneur,''
calls Spooky World a ``joint venture with the Kraft family ... with
a partnership likely down the road.'' Adds Foxboro Stadium general
manager Dan Murphy: ``It's much more than landlord/tenant. We both
have a vested interest, and we're involved in marketing with
David.''
</P>
<P>
   Spooky World has about 140 actors on its premises, ranging from
maniacal clowns to deranged miners to premises-wandering spooks.
There are carny sideshows with huge snakes and deformed frogs.
There is an outdoor magic show. One of the more prominent
attractions is Ruth Phelps, a.k.a. Mouse Girl, who lies behind
glass in the Cirque Macabre, looking desperate and helpless as
scads of mice crawl over her.
</P>
<P>
   Spooky World's pull is timeless. Humans are fascinated by
horror. Almost everyone knows who Ted Bundy was and Charles Manson
is. Are we not riveted by the sad case of JonBenet Ramsey? Why did
the masses flock to ``The Blair Witch Project?''
</P>
<P>
   We pity the victims and thank God it's not us. We get vicarious
thrills from depictions of pain or suggestions of violence. Spooky
World organizes its horror. It controls it and confines it,
throwing a cloak of safety over our terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very skeptical,'' says actress Linda Blair, recalling
how she felt when Bertolino first approached her six years ago to
appear at Spooky World. The child star of ``The Exorcist,'' now 40,
was at the park two weeks ago as part of a promotion. She says she
is not a fan of horror anddoesn't get why people like to be jolted.
``But I came and found people of all ages having a good time,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Spooky World had a large chunk of its operations shut
down when a new building inspector for the town of Berlin decided
some of the attractions were fire hazards. Three of the exhibitions
were shut down by order of a Worcester Superior Court judge. Spooky
World handed out 40,000 refunds, attendance dwindled, and the
company was forced into Chapter 11, from which it has since
emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Bertolino got a call from the Don Law Co., owned by
entertainment giant SFX Entertainment. SFX was interested in buying
Spooky World. Then, the Kraft family entered negotiations, and
Bertolino struck a deal to locate the park next to the stadium. Not
only that, Bertolino plans to host three more annual events on the
site, including a Christmas theme park later this year (no killer
Santas, Bertolino promises), a Renaissance Faire and a Comedy
Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Bertolino is clearly happy Spooky World has moved on. He says in
this first year at the new spot, ``We're paying our bills, but not
getting rich quickly.'' The park is drawing 5,000-plus people per
night, although it is open Friday-Sunday _ 15 dates total _ and not
all week. Also, Spooky World lost parts of last weekend because of
a freak power outage.
</P>
<P>
   Bertolino has a $12-million suit pending against the town of
Berlin. As to any concerns about safety in Foxborough, fire
department captain Gerry McNamara says he has none. ``I think
they've done an awesome job. We're happy to have them in
Foxborough.''
</P>
<P>
   Bertolino has gotten rid of the hay (a fire hazard?!) on the
17-minute Haunted Hayride, a Spooky World highlight _ the 50 or so
people hauled on one of the nine tractors now sit on artificial
turf as they trip through the horrors of time. They see a torso on
a crucifix and bodies on stakes, and a guillotine where the
condemned man's head doesn't fall off. (``He's a little attached to
himself,'' explains the executioner, when asked). They are
good-naturedly ``assaulted'' by an assortment of crazies and
zombies, staggering toward the tractors, wielding chainsaws,
clamoring for ``brains.''
</P>
<P>
   Spooky World has temporarily retired one particularly gruesome
exhibit _ wax figures in the throes of medieval tortures. There is
a gallery of wax figures drawn from real life _ Manson, Richard
Ramirez, Aleister Crowley, the Rev. Jim Jones. There's a ``black
hole'' catwalk that is only 24 feet but looks endless and will give
you vertigo. There is a gift shop for all your blood 'n' gore
needs, including a lovely inflatable coffin. There are Patriots
cheerleaders there to pose for pictures and sign autographs. No
one, cheerleaders included, could exactly explain how they fit into
the horror theme _ especially with the team doing well.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions are rated on a 1 to 5 skull basis, judging for how
extreme the exhibit is. We'd say the park operates between PG and
PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, Lou Ferrigno (the Incredible Hulk) and R.A.
Mahaillof (Leatherface in the third ``Texas Chainsaw Massacre''
movie) will sign autographs.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of horror? ``In wrestling,'' the burly Mahaillof
says, ``they call it the `ritual re-enactment.' You have these
prototypes or archetypes, and in wrestling and in horror, they are
very similar. It is always good against evil and hopefully good
triumphs.''
</P>
<P>
   Spooky World is open Fridays to Sundays through the end of the
month, 6 p.m.-midnight. Admission is $23.50, with parking $5. Call
978-838-0200.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
