<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSICAL-REVIEW-SATURDAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SATURDAY NIGHT FEVER,' A NEW MUSICAL WITH A BRIGHT NEW ACTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 17)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KRIS WORRELL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is difficult to believe that James Carpinello
hasn't closely studied John Travolta's performance in the 1977
movie ``Saturday Night Fever.''
</P>
<P>
   Carpinello has the Brooklyn accent down cold. He has the
sculpted hair. He has the strut.
</P>
<P>
   And the attitude, certainly the attitude.
</P>
<P>
   But Carpinello, the newest sensation to swivel across a Broadway
stage, swears he didn't spend weeks copying Travolta's movie moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I've seen the movie a couple of times. But this is a
play, it's not a movie,'' he said of the new Broadway mega-musical
version of ``Saturday Night Fever.''
</P>
<P>
   In the production, which opens Thursday after three weeks of
previews, Carpinello plays Tony Manero, the role that made Travolta
a star two decades ago and lodged white polyester suits and disco
music forever in the national psyche.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to re-create what they did. We're doing our
own thing,'' Carpinello said.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, but that accent! Those pelvic thrusts! That swagger!
</P>
<P>
   Carpinello even delivered a little Brooklyn street talk when
asked about a recent New York Post article that called the play
``trash theater.''``(Bleep) 'em,'' he said, leaning his muscular
frame forward. ``As far as I'm concerned, they haven't seen it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his candlelit dressing room in the Minskoff Theatre
an hour before one recent preview performance, the 24-year-old
actor sank back into the plush couch and considered his words.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad said, `Don't swear as much in this interview,' said
Carpinello.
</P>
<P>
   His mouth and mannerisms might be like those of Manero, the
blue-collar dancer from Brooklyn, but his East Greenbush background
couldn't be more different.
</P>
<P>
   The son of New York State Appellate Court Judge Anthony J.
Carpinello and Sharon Carpinello, the executive deputy commissioner
of the state Office of Mental Health, James Carpinello began taking
dancing lessons at the age of 6, but dropped them after a few years
in favor of sports. Peer pressure, explained his mother.
</P>
<P>
   The only photograph in the actor's dressing room that isn't of
his girlfriend, Lacey Kohl, an actress in Los Angeles, is one of
Carpinello, about age 8, dressed in a neat suit, dancing and
smiling.
</P>
<P>
   In high school at Albany Academy, from which he graduated in
1993, Carpinello began studying voice and acting. In his junior
year, he attended the prestigious summer acting program at Carnegie
Mellon University in Pittsburgh and was hooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just fell in love with theater and found my home there,''
said the actor, whose 20-year-old sister, Amy, studies dance at
Skidmore College in Saratoga Springs, N.Y. ``Everything was
pointing in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   His parents, however, were slightly less in love with the idea
of a life on stage. They had watched their son perform in countless
plays in the basement as a child, then later at school and Park
Playhouse's ``Brigadoon,'' but they never considered theater a
serious career path.
</P>
<P>
   ``As conservative parents, we were a little reluctant to see him
enter such a competitive business,'' said Anthony Carpinello. ``But
we decided if the professionals at a highly thought-of collegiate
program thought he had talent and could make it, that we ought to
let him pursue his dream.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Carnegie Mellon's theater program _ which
has produced such actors as Jack Klugman, Ted Danson and Holly
Hunter _ Carpinello went on to perform in ``Romeo and Juliet'' in
Atlanta, ``The Tempest'' in Cleveland and a provocative
off-Broadway play called ``Stupid Kids,'' which was a cult hit last
year in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Polland, general manager of ``Stupid Kids,'' called
Carpinello ``a born star. ... He has it. Plus, he's a very
intelligent and wonderful man.''
</P>
<P>
   While doing ``Stupid Kids,'' Carpinello went to a New York
audition for a stage version of ``The Rocky Horror Picture Show''
to play piano for a friend who was trying out. After his friend
finished, the director who was casting the show asked Carpinello if
he could sing. Carpinello said yes and performed ``Gethsemane,'' a
difficult song from the musical ``Jesus Christ Superstar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I pretty much cast him for (the role of) Rocky on the spot,''
said director Dennis Erdman. ``Visually, he's very magnetic in a
room, and he looked the part.''
</P>
<P>
   When ``Stupid Kids'' closed, Carpinello went to Los Angeles to
perform in what turned out to be a short-lived ``Rocky Horror.''
But Carpinello was getting noticed. In a review of ``Rocky
Horror,'' The Los Angeles Times said: ``James Carpinello, who
recently had New York panting over his appearance in the play
`Stupid Kids,' will soon have Los Angeles doing the same over his
comically vacant and oh, so beautifully sculpted gym god of a
monster.''
</P>
<P>
   Carpinello was chosen for the highly coveted role of Tony Manero
over hundreds of hopefuls nationwide (including Joey Lawrence of
``Blossom'' fame).
</P>
<P>
   The buzz on this darkly handsome actor is louder than a theater
bar during intermission. Already he's been featured in a fashion
layout in Harper's Bazaar and in ads for Bloomingdale's. He taught
Katie Couric how to do the Hustle on the ``Today Show,'' and he has
been interviewed in dozens of newspapers and magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just look at it like everything else ... except now there's
a lot of people around, asking questions and wanting me to do
things,'' said Carpinello. ``I just feel really lucky. But I don't
feel like something was handed to me. I feel like it's the right
role, at the right time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1815EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
