<P>
   SHOOTING-MONTH LATER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The hallway is draped in e-mail printouts,
posters, banners and poetry from all over the world, each
expressing a singular thought: You are loved. Peace has returned to
this place. One month ago, Larry Gene Ashbrook walked down the hall
at Wedgwood Baptist Church, shooting at church members before
entering the sanctuary and firing at hundreds of young people
gathered for a rally. He left seven dead, seven injured, and a
building scarred by blood and bullets. Now the scars have been
replaced with sympathy. By REBECA RODRIGUEZ. Story will move in
``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   L I F E S T Y L E &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STAPLES-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ All of us parents like to think we're good at
parenting. I know I do. But there's nothing like disciplining your
child to make you second-guess yourself. It's times like those when
I wish I were Solomon or even God. For example, let me share a talk
I had recently with my youngest daughter, Asha. By GRACIE BONDS
STAPLES. Story has moved in ``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS-BOMBAY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ A reader asks Dr. Bombay: ``So, here's your chance to
show your readers what an idiot I am. Those kind people at
Microsoft were nice enough to put Network Neighborhood, Inbox and
My Briefcase icons on my desktop. I only use my computer for fun
and want to take them off my desktop but not delete the programs.
Can it be done?'' By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY. Story has moved in ``l''
lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CLEARING CLUTTER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ If you toss all your old magazines, catalogs and
newspapers, pick up your clothes, clean all your closets and attend
to all your stacks of paperwork, Michelle Passoff swears you will
find enlightenment. Passoff, author of ``Lighten Up, Free Yourself
From Clutter'' (Harper Perennial, $13 softcover), is here to bring
order, fulfillment and self realization, if you'll only clean up
your life. She maintains that we hang on to memories and they
slowly suffocate our dreams: ``Clutter cleaning is a way to
discover who you really are.'' By GAILE ROBINSON. Story has moved
in ``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E N T E R T A I N M E N T &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-HAPPY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HAPPY, Texas _ This small, economically depressed Texas
Panhandle town is unhappy about the movie ``Happy, Texas,'' which
is about two escaped convicts mistaken as gay beauty pageant
directors who have come to Happy to revive the ``Little Miss Fresh
Squeezed'' contest. City fathers gave moviemakers permission to use
the town's name before they knew the plot line. By JESSIE MILLIGAN.
Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-PERKINS-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ With ABC's ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' set to
return for November sweeps, the other major networks are
frantically piecing together original game-show concepts or putting
contemporary spins on vintage ones. What's in store? By KEN PARISH
PERKINS. Story will move in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C O M M E N T A R Y &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ It's easy enough for glib panelists on the Geraldo
Rivera and Larry King talk shows to declare a suspect guilty of
murder, to lambaste law enforcement officials for failing to file
charges against some individual who's been convicted in the media.
But cops and prosecutors aren't entertainers; they must operate
under certain legal constraints. It's an inconvenience to the
police and the occasional lynch mob, to be sure, but the
Constitution of the United States guarantees due process of law to
criminal suspects. By BILL THOMPSON. Story has moved in ``k''
commentary category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LABBE-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ In the mid-19th century, when Samuel Colt was
revolutionizing manufacturing in this country, there was no way
that he could know that one day his corporate namesake would be the
first to crater to legal threats caused by a hysterical response to
the misuse of his product. By J.R. LABBE. Story has moved in ``k''
commentary category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
