A8262 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      10-15 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Oct. 16, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Hurricane Irene bore down on southern Florida on Friday,
winds gusted to 77 mph at Homestead Air Reserve Base near Miami
while heavy rain, estimated at rates of 2 inches per hour, doused
much of the region.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, though likely downgraded to a tropical storm, Irene
will remain very dangerous as it produces prolific rains across
northern Florida, southeastern Georgia and, perhaps, southeastern
South Carolina. Isolated tornadoes may spin up, but the greatest
threat from this storm will be flooding rains.
</P>
<P>
   A cold Canadian air mass will tighten its grip on the northern
Rockies and northern Plains on Saturday. Snow will develop along
the Front Range from northeast Colorado to eastern Wyoming as moist
winds from the east circulating around a high-pressure system over
Idaho are forced to ascend the sloping terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Cold air will spill west over the Rockies and into the Great
Basin, with temperatures falling toward 10 degrees Saturday night
over parts of Nevada. The expansive high over Idaho will also
produce offshore winds over parts of the California coast. Blowing
from the east, these winds will warm on descent from the Sierra,
paving the way for very warm weather along parts of California
coast, including San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, temperatures in the Northeast will rise above
seasonal levels after a chilly start as winds from the southwest
develop ahead of a slow-moving cold front across the Middle West.
The sluggishness of the cold front may invite Irene to move up the
East Coast on Sunday into Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Seeing an Eye &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friday, as the eye of Hurricane Irene passed over Key West,
Fla., winds subsided and clouds briefly broke. But Irene's eye was
not visible from satellite. In general, eyes of hurricanes are
visible from space roughly 50 percent of the time. The eye often
becomes visible on satellite images when the hurricane intensifies,
particularly when intensification is rapid. Under these conditions,
air sinking in the eye becomes more pronounced, helping to
evaporate clouds and exposing the eye to space. When a hurricane
reaches extreme strength, its eye is almost always seen from
satellite. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
