<HEADLINE>
INVESTING DIGEST  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Piano Man Sings For Baron Shareholders &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to having a party, mutual fund types have never
been able to hold a candle to Hollywood _ or even to high-spirited
accountants who want to celebrate a revision in the tax code.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Baron of Baron Capital, a money manager, wants to change
that. A case in point is the annual investment conference he held
on Friday in Manhattan for current and prospective shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try and make the business younger all the time,'' Baron
said.
</P>
<P>
   The unannounced lunchtime guest performer was Billy Joel, who
surprised the 2,000 or so attendees with a rendition of ``New York
State of Mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Other stars were from companies in which the Baron funds hold
major positions. They included Sol Kerzner, chief executive of Sun
International Hotels, and David S. Pottruck, co-chief executive of
Charles Schwab. Baron said the purpose was to raise shareholder
confidence in the stocks Baron holds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a costly event,'' he said, hastening to add that Baron
Capital, not the funds themselves, picked up the bill.
</P>
<P>
   How will he handle the gate crashers likely to arrive at next
year's conference? ``I haven't figured that out yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _Richard Teitelbaum
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
