<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE FOOTBALL MATCHUPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; SATURDAY'S KEY GAMES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ratings by The New York Times computer. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State (4-2)
</P>
<P>
   at No. 3 Penn State (6-0)
</P>
<P>
   After Penn State piled up 500 yards (341 rushing) against Iowa,
Coach Joe Paterno said, ``I think overall we've improved, but we're
certainly not good enough yet.'' Penn State is certainly better
than Ohio State, whose coach, John Cooper, admits, ``This is not
the best team we've had around here.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 11 Syracuse (5-1)
</P>
<P>
   at No. 10 Virginia Tech (5-0)
</P>
<P>
   Tech's defense, ranked second in the nation (allowing 206.8
yards a game), has an offense to go with it. Playing only the first
half against Rutgers last Saturday, Michael Vick, Tech's
quarterback, accounted for 311 yards. Syracuse could make it close
in this game between Big East leaders.
</P>
<P>
   No. 5 Michigan State (6-0)
</P>
<P>
   at Purdue (4-2)
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State, 6-0 for the first time since 1966, faces a
three-game stretch against Purdue, Wisconsin and Ohio State. The
Spartans, fresh from an upset of Michigan, have the nation's best
rushing defense (36.7 yards a game) and must stop Drew Brees'
passing.
</P>
