<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHWAB COUNTERS A PINCERS MOVEMENT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17) 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The (star) word should be replaced with the symbol. Also,
questions may be italicized). 
(af) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Charles Schwab Corp., a pioneer of discount stock brokerage
and even cheaper on-line brokerage, is getting it from all sides
these days.
</P>
<P>
   After staking out a position between low-cost electronic trading
shops and traditional brokerage firms, Schwab finds that both ends
are moving toward the middle: Deep discounters like E(star)Trade
Group are adding services for investors, while full-service firms
like Merrill Lynch are offering on-line trades at a discount.
</P>
<P>
   The brewing storm of competition has frightened investors out of
Schwab's stock, which has fallen more than 60 percent from its high
in April, to $28.50 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Richard K. Strauss, an analyst at
Goldman Sachs Group, talked about Schwab's predicament, its
prospects and why he thinks it will hit $50 within a year. Here are
excerpts from the conversation: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why did Schwab go from being a darling to getting dumped so
quickly? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Schwab's stock tends to go through a bad period once every
couple of years. Typically, the cause is that Schwab is
transforming itself, facing a new competitor or there's a slowdown
that is either seasonal or cyclical. Those tend to be the things
that change the fortunes of Schwab's stock. However, the company
has an incredible track record of making those downdrafts into
buying opportunities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Which of those usual suspects is the culprit holding down
Schwab's stock this time around?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. This right now is more of a seasonal slowdown. But it's also
a smoke screen of sorts from other E-brokers who are talking about
adding accounts but not talking about growing assets profitably. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Those competitors certainly are talking _ and advertising _
plenty. Isn't Schwab going to have to match the huge ad budgets of
these upstart firms? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If you look at E(star)Trade and Ameritrade combined, their
marketing budget next year is going to be well over $500 million.
That's more than double what Schwab will be spending. Schwab has
over $600 billion in customer assets. E(star)Trade and Ameritrade
combined have no more than $50 billion. The economics speak for
themselves. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. But by doing all that advertising and price-cutting, aren't
they putting pressure on Schwab's profit margins? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Not necessarily. Look at what Schwab has done in 1999. They
have brought in $75 billion of net new money and their profit
margin during that period has averaged close to 15 percent of
revenue, which is the highest their margin has ever been. Of the
$75 billion they've brought in, $25 billion came in this summer
during a slowdown that really was a stealth bear market. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How long can they keep up that pace of gathering assets in
the face of increasing competition late in a long bull market? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Schwab's customer-asset base has gone from $7 billion to $600
billion in 12 years. There have been some pretty hairy markets
during that time but Schwab has continued to take in assets during
those periods of turmoil. The company's profits have been growing
35 to 40 percent a year. My growth projection for them now is 25 to
30 percent. Even with the seasonal slowdown this summer, their
earnings should be up close to 60 percent this year. My forecast
for their long-term growth is higher than it's ever been. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is the new money rolling into Schwab in bigger or smaller
chunks? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The average new account they're bringing in starts out with
$44,000 and that's 42 percent bigger than their new accounts were
last year. The company's average account size now is about
$100,000. That's the kind of account that a full-service broker
like Merrill Lynch would be going after. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Speaking of Merrill Lynch, that firm is about to offer
on-line trades for $29.95 each, the same price Schwab charges. How
much of a threat is that to Schwab? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Financial services is an incredibly fragmented industry.
Merrill has $1.5 trillion of customer assets but that's only about
3 percent of the total investable assets in the U.S. The moves that
Merrill is making have been painful for Merrill in the short term.
But if anyone has the capital and the staying power to compete with
Schwab, it's not the E-brokers, it's the full-service brokers. It
will depend on how quickly they can get their cost structure down
so they can continue to offer great service but at a better price. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. So Schwab is being smart in positioning itself as an
alternative to the traditional brokers rather than competing
against the little guys on price? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Schwab is competing with anyone who is trying to gather
assets. In the asset-gathering world, it's getting more and more
difficult to accumulate assets, in part because there are so many
competitors and partly because more people are choosing to do it
themselves. To a large degree, Schwab has enabled and empowered
that trend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1841EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8274 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-QUAKE-INSURANCE-HNS &LR;      10-15 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAKE-INSURANCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY IN CALIFORNIA FOREGO QUAKE INSURANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The number of Californians with earthquake
coverage is falling as homeowners choose less costly alternatives:
retrofitting their houses or going without insurance at all.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance industry says the percentage of policy holders
taking earthquake insurance has dropped to 17 percent from the
state historic average of 20 to 25 percent. And the number of
policies since the state took control of coverage nearly three
years ago has dropped from 1.3 million in December 1996 to about
920,000 today.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Lepoutre-Baldocci took a look at earthquake insurance
premiums when she moved from Knoxville, Tenn., to Oakland in May
and decided to put that money and her faith in retrofitting her
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insurance made no sense. I find it prohibitively expensive and
it doesn't cover much at all,'' said Lepoutre-Baldocci, who feels
reasonably safe after completing a $5,000 retrofit in July.
``First, we want to be able to get out alive. And secondly, we
would like the house to stay intact _ especially since we have no
insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a game of chance many homeowners are playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have this dual mentality,'' said Mark Leonard,
spokesman for the California Earthquake Authority, created by the
state in December 1996 to provide a pool of money, now up to $7.2
billion, for losses from quakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing they think is if they've survived Loma Prieta
or Northridge, they don't need to do anything. At the same time,
they think if the Big One hits, there's nothing they can do about
it so they don't retrofit and they don't buy insurance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the drop may be due to the general apathy that
comes from a long time without a major quake, it's clear homeowners
are frustrated with the earthquake insurance options they have.
They complain the deductibles are too high, the coverage is too
limited and they doubt they will ever see a dime _ especially under
the state-run program.
</P>
<P>
   Private insurers say they're writing more and more policies, but
they are selective of their customers. All together, they cover
about a third of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Both insurers and seismic specialists recommend that homeowners
retrofit their homes and insure them for content and other damage.
But with the high cost of housing compounded by the price of
insurance premiums, many people say they cannot afford to do both.
</P>
<P>
   Retrofitting a home can cost anywhere from about $1,500 to
$15,000, depending on the size of the house and the amount of work
that needs to be done. Standard retrofitting involves bolting the
house to the foundation and installing plywood cripple walls to
brace the foundation to the floor framing.
</P>
<P>
   Rodeo resident Elda Fox, who works in San Francisco as a
paralegal, has not had earthquake insurance since 1994 when the
rates skyrocketed in the aftermath of the Northridge quake in
Southern California. The quake killed 57 people and caused $20
billion in damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided at that point it wasn't worth it, given the
deductible,'' said Fox, who has just decided to invest in a $6,000
retrofit on her 57-year-old home. She said she recently received an
offer in the mail for earthquake insurance but tossed it out:
``Now, getting the retrofit done, I don't think I'll even consider
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Mezey, who has lived in San Francisco for the past 40
years, bought another home in Berkeley about four months ago and
decided to spend $3,000 retrofitting the house instead of insuring
it. ``I've been told by our engineer that, short of some terrible
thing, this is probably going to protect it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance industry may be frustrated by such opinions, but
this public reaction grew out the industry's inability to deal with
the damage created by the Northridge quake, which is still
considered the nation's costliest natural disaster.
</P>
<P>
   After that quake, some insurers refused to sell fire or
earthquake policies as required by state law because of the
potential loss. So the state created the earthquake authority.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen insurance companies have joined the authority,
including State Farm Fire &AMP; Casualty, Prudential Insurance, Liberty
Mutual Insurance Co., Farmers Insurance Group, Allstate Insurance
Co. and the California State Automobile Association. The authority
covers 70 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the criticism of the state authority centered on the
so-called mini- policy, which offered residents a 15 percent
deductible along with a bare-bones $5,000 in content coverage and
$1,500 in living expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to clamors for a lower deductible and increased
coverage, the authority has made available another policy that
lowers the deductible to 10 percent and boosts content coverage to
$100,000 and living expenses up to $15,000. However, Leonard said
only two of the companies _ State Farm and Liberty Mutual _ offer
the supplemental coverage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1842EDT &QL; 
