<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Oct. 17, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN-REVIEW (United Nations) _ India and Pakistan seem
to be taking starkly divergent paths into the next political era.
India anointed another democratically elected government and
Pakistan applauded yet another military coup. But beneath the
surface, are these events as diametrically different as they seem?
These two countries may be demonstrating a common trend. In their
search for identity, a new generation of Pakistanis and Indians are
unveiling the face of home-grown, grassroots politics _ pure Indian
and pure Pakistani, more inward-looking, less cosmopolitan. And,
perhaps, more likely to misunderstand each other. By Barbara
Crossette. (`i' category)
</P>
<P>
   LEWINSKY-LINGO-REVIEW (Undated) _ Although the epilogue to the
sordid impeachment scandal is still being written, there are
constant reminders of our long national nightmare in Americans'
every day speech. Every era has its popular terms, but the
impeachment scandal _ with its overheated mixture of sex, lies,
power and audiotapes _ provided a bounty of material for Americans
searching for phrases that fit the cynical weariness that permeates
so much of the nation's popular culture. By Don Van Natta. (`a'
category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   TRIANGULATION-POLITICS-REVIEW (Austin, Texas) _ There is no
higher praise from Bill Clinton's devotees than when they applaud
George W. Bush for proving himself a deft triangulator. Bush says
he does not know what the word means. The definition, according to
Dick Morris, the former Clinton adviser who invented the idea, is:
`A process of taking the best ideas from each party and combining
them into a coherent policy and program. It is not just splitting
the difference, but molding a creative synthesis which rises above
the doctrine of either party.' By Richard Berke.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERWARFARE-REVIEW (Undated) _ The addition of an
information-war fighting capability to the U.S. military arsenal is
a watershed event, both adding cyberwar to the quiver of the
Pentagon and at the same time taking a set of military activities
which have for the last two decades largely been confined to the
