<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8276 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-YOUNG-NYT &LR;      10-15 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-YOUNG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG DELAYS RETIREMENT DECISION AS HE SEEKS SECOND OPINIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Minn., Calif., Ariz.)  (dw) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steve Young was hit in the head. Knocked woozy. More than that,
it injured his brain, causing major consternation and concern among
his doctors, family, friends, teammates, coaches and fans. Many
warned of permanent danger if he returned to football. Many tried
persuading him to quit.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, it is a familiar story. Young has had four concussions in
three years. The latest came Sept. 27 in a Monday night game at
Arizona on a play in which Young was blitzed, pummeled in the head
by another player's helmet and then by another's knee. He has
missed the last two 49ers games. He will miss at least two more.
</P>
<P>
   This week his neurosurgeon, Dr. Gary Steinberg, told Young that
he could not immediately resume his role at quarterback. No serious
brain damage has been revealed, but Young still has dizziness and
headaches. Steinberg told him more, but neither Young nor his
doctor will publicly discuss it.
</P>
<P>
   This is a case of no news not likely being good news.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason he hasn't been cleared to play up until now is that
it's my opinion and the opinion of the 49ers that it's in the best
interest of Steve Young to allow his brain to recover,'' Steinberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers play at home against Carolina Sunday and at Minnesota
next weekend before a bye. That gives Young three weeks to seek
more medical opinions and, he hopes, time for his condition to
improve so that he could be free to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``My point to Steve is that five to 10 years from now when he's
feeling fit, he's going to say: `Why didn't I play football? I took
the advice of one physician, the consultation of one neurologist _
I should have really checked it out,''' said Bill Walsh, the 49ers'
president. ``So, I want to make sure he checks everything.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a telling statement. It certainly sounds as if Steinberg
told Young to retire, that the risks were too great.
</P>
<P>
   Young, 38, is a two-time league most valuable player and a Super
Bowl XXIX mvp and champion. He is the quarterback who replaced the
49ers legend Joe Montana, and his left-handed spirals, spinning
scrambles and spirited leadership became signatures of his game. He
already holds virtually every meaningful 49ers passing record. He
is a player of tremendous work ethic and desire.
</P>
<P>
   Quitting now? In the middle of the season? Quitting while still
a prime player and passer?
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve would want to retire on his own terms and even then it
would be difficult for him,'' 49ers receiver Jerry Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   But really, retire he must.
</P>
<P>
   After 169 games and 4,149 passes and 358 sacks and countless
other hits, it is time. Four concussions is a lot. Not only that,
but this season he also has been battered. In one game, Sept. 19
against New Orleans, Young was hit 21 times.
</P>
<P>
   Young should continue playing if he is medically cleared and if,
in his mind, he decides that the rewards are greater than the
risks. For most of us, they are not.
</P>
<P>
   But for a football player, for a man like Young who loves the
game and gives so much to it, maybe his happiness is tied so much
to the field that quitting now would slowly drain him. Defeat him.
Some people love what they do so much that they are willing to pay
a high price. That is Young's decision. It is his right.
</P>
<P>
   His parents and friends tried persuading him to quit after a
concussion two years ago, so imagine their fears. Imagine what they
are saying now.
</P>
<P>
   For Young, the next three weeks will be filled with pull and
tug. Doctors may solve the issue by saying he cannot play again. If
they allow him to play, then Young must measure his own fears
against his desire to play, mixed all the while with the constant
coaxing from those who want him to quit. It is not an easy road.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Steve's mind, there is some hope,'' said Steve Mariucci,
the 49ers' head coach. ``Somehow he's reaching for some hope that,
hey, I'll be back. That's what he's thinking about. That's all he
thinks about.''
</P>
<P>
   His heart is telling him yes.
</P>
<P>
   His brain should tell him no.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
