<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8279 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CRUCIFIX16-COX     10-15 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUCIFIX16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Soiled Mary art more Christian than a cross with diamond setting
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A diamond-studded crucifix is surely
more offensive to God than a portrait of Mary surrounded by
elephant dung. But cardinals and critics condemn the painting and
peddle the crosses.
</P>
<P>
   Christians often confuse their symbols. Unwittingly, they
trivialize their faith. Mary surrounded by dung is biblically
accurate. Crosses made of gold and worn as jewelry are at least in
bad taste if not blasphemous.
</P>
<P>
   They become decorative items replicating a hideous instrument of
death, and they are used to enhance one's appearance _ the crucifix
as fashion accessory. Hard to believe God had that in mind at
Calvary.
</P>
<P>
   He did, however, seem to want Mary linked with prostitutes and
manure. But politicians and religious leaders have long thought God
mistaken about that and have tried to clean up the faith.
</P>
<P>
   The current flap is over an exhibition at the Brooklyn Museum of
Art in New York. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Roman Catholic John
Cardinal O'Connor vehemently condemned a painting of the Virgin
Mary. The picture includes a scene filled with the body parts of
prostitutes and clumps of elephant feces.
</P>
<P>
   The painting may be bad art and the artist may even have a
malevolent intent, but he cannot make Christianity more offensive
than it already is or intends to be.
</P>
<P>
   Those who would sanitize Christianity, make it pretty,
culturally acceptable and dull miss the point. Christianity claims
that prostitutes, reprobates and everyone else who wallows among
the human debris of the world are precisely the congregation God is
looking for.
</P>
<P>
   The promise of the faith is that God embraces those poor souls
whom religious and political leaders find offensive. Jesus preached
_ and lived _ that message. He was crucified for it.
</P>
<P>
   The Bible makes the point graphically and poignantly in what
many consider the greatest story ever told. The Gospel of Luke
tells us that Mary gave birth to the Son of God in a cave filled
with sheep and cattle. The Christ child might well have been put
down on a bed of straw mingled with animal feces and dirt.
</P>
<P>
   The story paints a marvelous image of one who was intimately
associated with the dregs of society. The church claims Jesus was
murdered on their behalf. Yet critics find prostitutes in a
portrait of Mary offensive.
</P>
<P>
   The real offense is to deny God's association with the likes of
those whom proper society condemns.
</P>
<P>
   But many of us want the one we worship to be more
discriminating, more sensible, more like us. We want to transform a
blood-drenched cross into a thing of beauty.
</P>
<P>
   We don't like our gods to appear weak or poor or hang out with
those who are. But Jesus does just that. And the portrait of Mary
among prostitutes and feces is an accurate symbol of his ministry.
</P>
<P>
   That's the wonderful scandal of Christianity, the offensive
truth the faithful call good news.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1850EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8280 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-DYSTROPHY-SURVIVORS16     10-15 1903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DYSTROPHY-SURVIVORS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brothers outlive predictions, forcing family to pay for care
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Everyone said Dwight and Debbie Eldred's
boys would be dead by now.
</P>
<P>
   But they've lived longer than the doctors predicted. Longer than
the actuaries and legislators and insurance companies and Medicaid
experts thought was possible. Long enough, the way Dwight Eldred
sees it, to commit an unpardonable bureaucratic sin:
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Jr. and Christopher have survived to ages 24 and 21 with
DuChene's Syndrome, a form of muscular dystrophy that weakens the
spine, curls the limbs and usually kills its victims by age 16.
Medical advances extended their lives, but insurance laws have not
kept up. As a result, the money needed to keep them alive is about
to run out. Medicaid coverage for Christopher's at-home care
expired last month. It ends for Dwight in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the unintended penalty for survival,'' said Kathi
Deakyne, director of Just For Kids, a private agency that provides
home nursing care to the Eldreds and other families. ``Unless
someone like Bill Gates reads this and decides he wants to pay for
care for the rest of their lives, they're basically out of luck. ``
</P>
<P>
   For years, the Eldreds _ with help from local agencies _ have
wrangled with the system to get the hundreds of thousands of
dollars needed to care for their boys. There is no more wrangling
to be done. To qualify for Medicaid coverage now, Dwight and
Christopher must move into a nursing home. There's no guarantee
they'd be placed locally, since Medicaid can choose whatever
facility has an open bed. But location isn't the problem, Debbie
says.
</P>
<P>
   Even the best nursing home can be a breeding ground for
respiratory infections that could kill her sons, she says. At home,
where the air is purified, their lungs and skin remain clear and
clean. Their nurses take pride in keeping infections at bay. Along
with exposing their weakening bodies to new germs, there are
questions about whether they could live in a communal facility
after spending all their lives at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would kill them,'' she says. ``Here, they have a reason to
wake every day.''
</P>
<P>
   For Dwight Jr., who attends classes at Palm Beach Community
College twice a week, waking is an ordeal in itself.
</P>
<P>
   He sleeps in a hospital bed in his family's living room. His
brother is in an identical bed nearby. Two hours before Dwight must
leave for school, his nurse, who sleeps on a sofa next to the
kitchen, rouses him and gives him an array of medicines meant to
compensate for his muscular atrophy. Heart medications.
Antibiotics. Diuretics. Drugs with sterile, menacing names such as
Minoxine and Lasix.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes breakfast. Dwight usually doesn't get enough vitamins
because he's too weak to chew, so a can of Ensure vitamin
supplement is part of the morning routine.
</P>
<P>
   Then the hole in his windpipe must be unhooked from the
ventilator next to his bed. The ventilator forces air into his
lungs, which are too weak to breathe round-the-clock without
assistance. He can be disconnected from the device no longer than
eight hours at a time. Without it, he would slowly suffocate.
</P>
<P>
   He is then carried to the bathroom to be bathed and dressed and
eventually placed in a motorized wheelchair. Dwight has lost the
ability to raise his hands, so he navigates the chair with deft
clicks of small, clothespin-like fingertip controls that rest next
to his legs on the seat.
</P>
<P>
   Then it's time for either the nurse or his mother or his father
to suction excess fluids that gathered in his throat during the
night. The suction machine, a small box with a clear tube that is
snaked into his windpipe, makes an awful sound, something you'd
expect to hear in a dentist's office. But it's a lifesaving sound.
Without the machine, he'd literally drown.
</P>
<P>
   Then he must wait for another nurse to meet him at the house so
she can tend to him while at school. If fluid collects and blocks
his breathing, she will suction it in the hallway outside a
classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Then a van equipped to take him in his bulky wheelchair arrives.
The Eldreds live on a dirt road near the South Florida Fairgrounds.
The van drivers, from a medical transport service, sometimes
mistake the address for one downtown. No van, no school.
</P>
<P>
   Once at the campus, Dwight and his nurse meet a note-taker hired
by the college. Dwight's hands, curled by the disease, are useless
for writing, so he relies on the note-taker and whatever he
remembers from lectures.
</P>
<P>
   His mind is sharp, but his body betrays him. During one
economics class, the teacher asks if anyone knows the answer to a
difficult formula. Dwight knows and tries to say it loud enough to
be heard. But when he's disconnected from his ventilator, sounds
are difficult to make because the air doesn't reach his voice box.
Not even his note-taker can hear the whispers coming from the hole
in his throat.
</P>
<P>
   With so many indignities in his life, this is little more than a
glancing blow, and Dwight's stubborn nature lets him deflect most
emotional wounds with grace and humor. He's even strong enough to
joke about his wheelchair: a ``South Park'' ``I Killed Kenny''
sticker adorns the left side.
</P>
<P>
   It's a love of laughter shared by his brother Christopher, who
is housebound because he needs the ventilator full time to keep him
breathing.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher is ``harder to get to know,'' Deakyne says, ``but
once you've made that contact, you find out that he has a wicked
sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   He also has a natural gift for music, and he uses his computer
to write songs _ ``techno crap,'' according to Dwight Sr., who is
in awe of his son's talent even if he doesn't share his tastes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got an amazing ear for music,'' his dad says. ``As a kid,
he'd hear music in the car and come home and be able to play it. At
five or six he could play Jimi Hendrix. I was, like, 'Whoa.'''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher also has many friends online, where he spends many
late-night hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a night owl,'' Deakyne says, ``so he's quiet during the
day. He saves his antics for 1 or 2 a.m.''
</P>
<P>
   But lately Christopher has needed to use voice recognition
software to help him use the computer. He no longer has the
strength to type on a keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see the frustration in his eyes,'' Debbie says.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their circumstances, those who know the Eldreds are
impressed by the job they have done raising their boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parents could have treated them with kid gloves and the
kids could have become demanding and difficult, but they're exactly
the opposite,'' Deakyne said. ``They're all gracious. It's
something you wouldn't expect given their circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dwight has patience,'' Debbie says. ``I get frustrated by
small things, but he's so calm.''
</P>
<P>
   But the inevitable _ death _ is not discussed in front of
outsiders. It's too much to think about when it's such a large
struggle to get through each day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any parent is truly prepared,'' Deakyne said.
``Even in situations when they know from birth what will happen,
they intellectualize it right up until the moment it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Doubling the pain is the realization that one son will die
before the other. Whichever survives, he'll likely find it
extremely difficult to come face to face with his own mortality.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll witness their parents' grief and get a glimpse of what
their parents will endure once he goes too,'' Deakyne said.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight and Debbie were high school sweethearts in Canton, Ohio.
The week after they graduated Canton High School, they were
married.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Jr. was born about a year later. While she was pregnant
with Christopher, Dwight Jr. was diagnosed at age 3 with muscular
dystrophy after his parents noticed an odd rhythm to his gait and
his difficulty climbing stairs. The diagnosis was repeated after
Christopher was born. She was devastated but not surprised because
the disease ran in her family. Doctors said the boys would live to
age 16, tops. A third boy, Nicholas, was not stricken. He now
attends the University of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early years, hospitals and doctors and bills have
dominated the Eldreds' lives.
</P>
<P>
   Together 25 years, the couple has endured crises that would have
torn some marriages to shreds.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Dwight was driving a medical van when he crashed
through the wall of a restaurant, killing 85-year-old Jack Dean, a
nursing home patient Eldred was transporting to a kidney dialysis
session. Eldred had a blood-alcohol level of 0.24, three times the
legal limit.
</P>
<P>
   Convicted of DUI manslaughter and sentenced to eight years in
prison, Gov. Lawton Chiles and the Cabinet granted Eldred clemency
in 1996 so he could serve his term on house arrest and support his
family. Along with destroying Dean's family, Eldred's recklessness
devastated his own. Without his income, Debbie and the boys had no
option but to go on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight is now home and helps care for his sons, but his
regimented lifestyle, which includes random drug tests, family
counseling, weekly Alcoholics Anonymous meetings and public
speaking about the dangers of driving drunk, is a constant reminder
of his crime. If he is seen outside even helping his wife unload
groceries, he could be returned to prison. Work and home, that's
it. Any deviation _ even a stop at a convenience store for gas _
could violate his parole.
</P>
<P>
   With Dwight's license revoked for life, Debbie must drive him to
and from his job as an alcohol counselor. Each parent takes an
eight-hour shift caring for their boys. At night, a state-provided
nurse allows them time to sleep. On weekends, Debbie works as a
secretary at the Hanley Hazeldon drug and alcohol treatment center.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we're afraid of is that Debbie will wind up
in the grave before the boys do,'' Deakyne said. ``She's just so
tiny and yet she lifts the boys into their wheelchairs, in and out
of the tub, on and off the toilet. But they're both extremely
dedicated parents.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 11, Christopher turned 21. On that day, Medicaid
stopped paying for his home care because he qualified as an adult
and because his IQ is greater than 70. Now the Eldreds rely on an
emergency $50,000 granted by the state Children's Medical Services
agency the morning before benefits were due to expire. How long
that will last is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight's coverage had been due to expire when he turned 21. A
loophole in Medicaid rules allowed his money to continue until he
turned 25. Some of that assistance also was used to care for
Christopher. That source of money expires in June.
</P>
<P>
   After June, barring some unlikely legislative change, it will be
up to the Eldreds to provide total care. Dwight and Debbie say they
each will take a 12-hour shift. They haven't figured out yet how
Dwight will get to work or whether Debbie will work weekends or
where the thousands of dollars for medicine will come from.
</P>
<P>
   They are the first family to deal with such a deadline in the
area but they will not be the last, Deakyne said. She said
legislators have been slow to act and haven't anticipated what she
expects will be a huge surge in money needed to care for disabled
children who outlive expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately,'' she said, ``children don't vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
