<SLUG> BC-HALLOWEEN-COSTUMES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Austin Powers costumes a Halloween hit
 &HT;    By Stephanie Allmon
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Along with ``Trick or Treat'' this Halloween, expect
to hear plenty of, ``Groovy, Baby! Yeah!''
</P>
<P>
   According to Halloween costume retailers, ``shagadelic''
shoppers are snagging Austin Powers costumes faster than they can
say, ``Oh, Behaaaaaave.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything having to do with Austin Powers is selling really
good,'' said Ashley Charles, manager of Halloween Bootique.
Although it's most popular with 20- to 30-year-olds, even children
are dressing up as the International Man of Mystery, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Halloween costume trends are often driven by popular movies, and
this year, ``Austin Powers is what people are asking for,'' said
Doris Fugate, owner of Custom Costumes.
</P>
<P>
   The whole costume _ the velvet leisure suit, lace ascot, shaggy
brown wig, crooked teeth and black wire-rimmed glasses _ can cost
$80-$85, Charles said.
</P>
<P>
   Other characters from the movie _ Dr. Evil, Mini-me and Felicity
Shagwell _ are also going to be popular, costume shop owners said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of movie trends, retailers had expected sales of ``Star
Wars'' costumes to be astronomical, but so far, they haven't taken
off, Charles said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Logan, manager of The Card and Party Factory, said the
store's home office began buying costumes at the beginning of the
year, before the release of ``Star Wars: Episode One.'' So far, he
said, Darth Maul, Queen Amidala, Anakin Skywalker and Jar Jar Binks
have been more popular with children than with adults.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road at Toys R Us, ``the Pokeman craze has hit,''
manager Carol Archie said. ``(Pokeman costumes) don't stay on
shelves that long.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pokeman costume consists of a foam rubber head and a
jumpsuit for the body, Charles said.
</P>
<P>
   But kids still love to be action figures for Halloween, with
Superman and Batman flying ahead of the pack each year.
</P>
<P>
   Action figure has a new meaning in 1999 now that WWF wrestling
and NASCAR racing are more popular than ever, Archie said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps to the dismay of some parents, costumes of pro-wrestler
Stone Cold Steve Austin are seeing a lot of sales action this
Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   And they may not have cars or even drivers licenses, but many
kids also want to dress up as NASCAR drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The world of music usually creates a trend or two in Halloween
costumes, with Madonna as the traditional fall-back '80s rocker
costume. Last year, little girls and teen-age girls were content to
be Spice Girls. This year, Kiss masks are flying off the racks,
Logan said.
</P>
<P>
   As far as masks go, ``the more gory, the better they sell,''
Charles said. She said masks and costumes from the ``Scream''
movies have also been good sellers. And back for a second year are
the Monica Lewinsky mask and cigar-smoking Bill Clinton mask.
Although parents can dress their children head-to-toe in
pre-packaged costumes that can often cost $20-$40, Halloween is the
one time of year when many busy mothers dust off their sewing
machines, said Judith Lusk, professor of home economics at Baylor
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I've been in fabric stores, I have seen mothers and
children choosing what they'd like to become,'' Lusk said. ``It
allows a mother and child to embrace the creative in both of them
and come up with costumes. The mothers are making sure the children
have that kind of experience with creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Internet may help busier people choose and buy costumes
this year.
</P>
<P>
   On such sites as www.every
</P>
<P>
   thinghalloween.com and www.coachhousegifts.com, shoppers can buy
costumes and props, get creative costume ideas and even post
questions about costumes.
</P>
<P>
   Fugate said no matter the costume craze, some people always take
more time in assembling Halloween costumes, while others know
exactly what they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's choice is different from the next person's,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
