u e BC-MOVIES-OMEGA16-COX     10-15 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-OMEGA16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thriller baits secular hook to fish for souls
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When the Christian film industry makes
an evangelical film, it usually does pretty well _ with evangelical
Christians.
</P>
<P>
   But the
hit-them-over-the-head-with-Jesus-until-they-see-the-light-genre
hasn't worked as well with the vast swath of Americans who go to
the movies purely to be entertained.
</P>
<P>
   So when Stephan Blinn set out to write the screenplay for the
evangelical Christian thriller ``The Omega Code,'' which opened
Friday, he knew he had to walk a fine line between secular
storytelling and proselytizing. His hope is that the
action-adventure will hold together on its secular merits _ and if
it provokes some conversation about what's in the Bible, so much
the better.
</P>
<P>
   That attitude is gaining in the world of evangelical film
production, where function has often preceded form and doomed films
such as ``The Joyriders'' to early box-office graves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal was to make a film that would appeal to a secular
audience with the thought that we are planting a seed,'' Blinn
said. ``We want people to leave the film and say, 'Hey I didn't
know that was in the Bible. I need to pick that up and read it for
myself.'''
</P>
<P>
   Televangelist, Trinity Broadcasting Network founder and
president and executive producer of ``The Omega Code,'' Paul Crouch
is less circumspect. In a publicity package sent to clergy and
media, Crouch urges pastors to use the film as a teaching tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went generations letting the devil have the silver screen,
letting our enemy use it for the wrong purpose,'' Crouch said.
``Only lately have a few of us gotten ahold of this milieu and
said, `Let's make it work for the gospel. Let's make it win souls
instead of sending people to perdition.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Omega Code'' is a good vs. evil morality tale that roughly
follows the books of Daniel and Revelations, with some extra
special effects thrown in for good measure. The characters are all
essentially misguided, Blinn says, driven either by career
ambition, New Age philosophy, or a desire for power.
</P>
<P>
   The main character, Dr. Gillem Lane (played by Casper Van Dien
of ``The Legend of Sleepy Hollow'' and ``Starship Troopers''), is a
sort of square-jawed Everyman who works as a motivational speaker
and is eventually hired by Stone Alexander, the European Union
chairman (played by Michael York, of ``Austin Powers'' and ``The
Three Musketeers''). The story turns when Lane realizes his boss is
a megalomaniac who is trying to take control of a code that can
uncover the prophecies in the Bible and use them to dominate the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts say even though the millennium is a good time
to offer an evangelical message to a mainstream audience, losses
within the genre in the past have made producers wary.
</P>
<P>
   Take ``The Joyriders,'' for instance. The Evangelical film,
released this spring, starred Kris Kristofferson and Academy Award
winner Martin Landau. Bankrolled by born-again millionaire Norm
Miller, the movie reportedly cost more than $5 million to produce
but grossed only $250,000 in its first month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Omega Code'' reportedly cost $8.5 million _ about
three-quarters of which was covered by TBN. The network also kicked
in another $3 million in free advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Said Todd McCarthy, chief film critic for Variety magazine:
``It's easy to blow millions and never catch the public's interest.
But the audience doesn't want to have someone's message stuffed
down their throat, so (an evangelical movie) has to be really slick
if it's going to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   To reach both secular and Christian audiences, producers hired
two marketing companies. The movie is opening in 350 cinemas
(compared with about 2,000 for the ``Star Wars'' prequel) in places
where the demographics favor an evangelical message. Those markets
were determined by taking the film into areas that have the most
donors to the TBN. Florida, Texas and California came out on top.
</P>
<P>
   The movie does not contain swearing or nudity, but received a
PG-13 rating for violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violent things happened in the Book of Revelations,'' Blinn
said. ``There's no way to get around that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
