</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CAULFIELD16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Innocent-as-cop story has poignant moments
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Combine the frat boy craziness of
``Beverly Hills, 90210'' with the gritty realism of ``NYPD Blue''
and what do you get?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan Caulfield: Year One,'' a surprisingly tender, though
totally predictable cop drama. Ryan Caulfield (Sean Maher) is a
19-year-old rookie cop patrolling Philadelphia's toughest streets.
That means instead of getting hammered with college buddies at dorm
parties, Ryan's in the middle of deadly shootouts. No wonder his
friends thinks he's crazy for turning down a college scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   At 19, the boyish-looking Ryan doesn't look much like a cop.
When he's not chasing bad guys, he likes playing video games and
rolling in the mud with his friends. Hey, didn't you roll in the
mud when you were 19? Ryan even lives at home with his mom and has
G.I. Joes in his room. But that's the point. We're supposed to see
what it's like being a cop through a rookie's eyes. (But G.I.
Joes?) And most of the time those eyes are... scared. Ryan
nervously swallows hard before entering an apartment. He asks his
veteran partner Susser (``The Sopranos''' Michael Rispoli), ``What
should we do?'' And when a low-life gets popped in front of him, a
stunned Ryan says, ``It's not like you see in the movies. It's not
like what they tell you in the academy. It's not real unless you
smell it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan Caulfield: Year One'' certainly won't win any awards for
being the most original cop drama. All of the cop cliches we've
seen countless times are played out here. The seasoned partner
schooling the new cop, drug busts gone bad, gut-wrenching
slow-motion shots _ that sort of thing.
</P>
<P>
   But as the scared rookie, Maher is totally believable and
achingly earnest. He looks like Ray Liotta's younger brother. He
also has the same honey-dripped voice during his many voiceovers.
Maher is helped by a strong supporting cast, including Rispoli as
the world-weary cop and Clifton Powell as a hard-nosed lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   While Ryan has a girlfriend, he's already making goo-goo eyes at
a fellow rookie cop (Roselyn Sanchez) who's a Sandra Bullock
lookalike. If ``Ryan Caulfield: Year One,'' makes it to ``Ryan
Caulfield: Week Five,'' you can bet Ryan and that Sandra
Bullock-looking chick will be ripping off each other's bulletproof
vests.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1851EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8286 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-REDSOX-FANS-NYT &LR;      10-15 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REDSOX-FANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON CURSES THE CURSE, HOPES AGAINST HOPE AND BEGS FOR TICKETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Consider it the ultimate pompom waving of the cultural
elite: Seiji Ozawa, who has conducted the city's acclaimed symphony
orchestra for 27 years, plans to bring his black-clad virtuosos to
Fenway Park on Saturday to play the anthem among the crimson hose
and pinstripes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting 40 years for them to go all the way,''
Ozawa, an unreconstructed Red Sox fanatic since he came here from
Japan in 1960, said Friday. ``They've made it this far. They have
to go all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds like a plaintive note of hope-against-hope in
Ozawa's voice, he was in harmony with much of this Sox-mad city.
</P>
<P>
   Boston is well practiced in sports fever, particularly in this
year of the Ryder Cup and the All-Star Game, and all the customary
ticket-finagling, hotel-room-begging and minor mass hysteria of
major sports events have been at work in these frenetic moments
before the third Yankees-Red Sox play-off game opens on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But there was also a special bittersweet tinge to the obsession
sweeping the city, as hapless Bostonians struggled with the baggage
of past disappointments dating back to 1918, the last time the Red
Sox won the World Series. It did not help that the Sox had lost the
first two play-off games against the Yankees, either.
</P>
<P>
   James Stevens, a born-and-bred Bostonian of 48, said Friday that
he believed in all seriousness that the Red Sox had been cursed
ever since they sold Babe Ruth to New York some 70 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something,'' he said, looking skyward. ``God, I don't
know what we did, but please lift it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think,'' he added, ``we should go and dig up Babe Ruth and
put him in Fenway.''
</P>
<P>
   Beth Teitell, a humor columnist for The Boston Herald, lectured
Bostonians as would a therapist working on a woman who loves too
much: ``You say you can stop caring at any time,'' she wrote.
``Please. Look at yourself. Up late for the last three game days.
Wearing the same `lucky' underpants for an entire week.''
</P>
<P>
   It is time, she mock-chided, ``to stop enabling them.'' She
continued: ``Stop rewarding them with unquestioning love and
support for disappointing you.''
</P>
<P>
   But passion for the Red Sox runs so deep and wide here that
baseball seems to penetrate every corner of the city's life lately,
from screaming fights overheard in restaurant kitchens over whether
the Sox could win, to speculation by state political analysts that
the public was too Sox-mad to give a hoot about the budget, to
television weather reports focused mainly on predictions for
game-time, to women in health-club locker rooms discussing their
husbands' emotional distress.
</P>
<P>
   Among local media, it is probably the tabloid Boston Herald that
has most abandoned all restraint, emblazoning ``We Hate N.Y.''
across its front page and calling New York in one column: ``The
city that never sleeps. Or bathes.'' But local television was only
too happy to chime in with elementary schoolers chanting ``We are
number one'' and a little boy who declared he'd like to throw out
his baseball signed by Roger Clemens but, with a grimace, ``My Mom
says it's valuable.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the purely concrete effects of the convergence
of unscheduled cap-wearing masses on the city. Many hoteliers, are
already fully booked for the foliage season, yet are suddenly
facing waves of calls from longtime customers seeking rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball, y'know!'' said the unapologetic clerk at the
undistinguished Howard Johnson's hotel right near Fenway Park, when
asked why rooms there, which usually cost between $145 and $210 a
night, were suddenly going for $325.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm overwhelmed,'' lamented Robin Brown, general manager of
the Four Seasons Hotel. ``I haven't eaten in two days and I cannot
get up out of my chair without taking calls from people who want
rooms. Calls from all over the country and a lot from New York.''
</P>
<P>
   The hotel was fully booked, he said, ``and when you're that sold
out, and all of your best friends in the world call, and all the
relationships the hotel has spent years building are dependent on
finding a room, what you do is magical, mystical.''
</P>
<P>
   Others have been depending on magic as well; on Tuesday, about
200 people gathered outside Fenway Park hoping that some tickets
might go on sale, until the police insisted they leave.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's game ``is definitely the most difficult ticket Boston
has seen,'' said Patrick B. Moscaritolo, president of the Greater
Boston Convention and Visitors Bureau. ``I'm afraid even some of
the people on the A list aren't going to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the city as a whole could reap a bonanza from the games,
Moscaritolo said. If Boston hosts three games _ the two this
weekend for sure, and a third on Monday if the Sox are not shut out
_ it could see as much as $10 million in extra spending.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Boston is so riveted to the games that John Spence,
who sings in the band ``Common Street Trash,'' said the group could
not perform on Thursday night until the last out; there would have
been no audience. Radio hosts joke about the difficult choice faced
by expectant fathers whose wives may deliver during game time.
</P>
<P>
   That is not so funny to Sheldon Cohen, general manager of the
Sports Depot bar and restaurant in the Allston section of town. He
has tickets to the game Monday night. Monday is also his second
wedding anniversary, and his wife, who is seven months pregnant, is
not a big baseball fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting the old, `Oh, you can go, I don't mind,''' he
said. ``So what am I going to do? I'm going to give my tickets to
somebody else, do the right thing and not be miserable the rest of
my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
