<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8287 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     10-15 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GREED' IS GOOD: AT LEAST THAT'S WHAT THE NETWORKS THINK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's aptly titled, at least.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greed'' is the newest prime-time TV game show, unless another
has popped up in the past hour or so.
</P>
<P>
   Greed is also the reason the hit-desperate networks are
scrambling to invent big-money quiz shows for an audience always
game for something new and on the odd side.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that and fear.
</P>
<P>
   Before ABC's ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' sent the industry
into shock by luring millions of viewers every night for two weeks
in August, prime-time network viewers hadn't seen them outside
syndicated programming in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Millionaire'' and its host, Regis Philbin, set to return
Nov. 7 for the all-important sweeps, when networks and local
stations dress up programming to influence advertising rates, the
other major networks are frantically piecing together game-show
concepts or putting contemporary spins on vintage ones. How far
will they go? CBS is betting on ``Survivor!,'' a program that
strands contestants on a remote island, promising $1 million to the
last one standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get out there as fast as possible,'' said Mike
Darnell, head producer of Fox's reality programming. ``Once five or
six of these are on the air, they won't be as special. In being
second in the market, we could still make an impact.''
</P>
<P>
   What Fox and every other network have planned is as spectacular
as you'd expect in a business where bigger really is considered
better.
</P>
<P>
   Fox is doubling the winnings of ``Millionaire'' to $2 million
for a show that shrewdly and shamelessly exploits our current state
of Jerry Springer abrasiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greed,'' slated for consecutive Thursdays beginning Nov. 7, if
the network can meet that fast-approaching deadline, will send a
much-hyped Fox show based on that very principle to the bench for
the month. The poor-performing comedy ``Action,'' about a heartless
film producer, is being shelved, as is the animated ``Family Guy.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Greed'' is the type of show that the fictional Peter
Dragon would watch on his time off. It will feature teams in a
``Family Feud''-type question-and-answer setting. But as stakes
rise, teammates are encouraged to turn on one another, freezing out
the people who helped them in order to take most, or all, of the
really big money. If no one wins one night, $100,000 is added to
the next week's pot, which could conceivably grow into millions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor!,'' a reworking of a show that's an international
sensation, is matching ``Millionaire's'' payoff but upping the ante
in drama. The concept involves 16 ``castaways'' on Pulau Tiga, an
island off Malaysia's Borneo coast. The group is whittled down by
secret ballot, with members voting every three days to expel a
fellow contestant. When the final two contestants are left, those
most recently voted out of the game will decide who wins.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, they are being asked to survive physically and thrive
socially on an island populated only by wildlife and a TV camera
crew hoping that something bizarre occurs.
</P>
<P>
   Not that something hasn't already. In a 1997 Swedish version of
the show, the first contestant who was asked to leave the island
committed suicide by jumping in front of a train a month after
returning home.
</P>
<P>
   The widow of Sinisa Savija told a Swedish newspaper that her
husband felt humiliated and became depressed after being the first
one kicked out by his team. Producers of the show, called
``Expedition Robinson,'' have denied any link between Savija's show
experiences and the suicide. CBS has said that contestants will
have criminal, medical and psychological background evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor!,'' scheduled to air in the summer, has been
teasingly referred to as ``The Real World's'' dramatic friction
crossed with ``Gilligan's Island's'' stranded-in-nowhere appeal,
and it's an accurate description.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the people selected, ``Survivor!'' is the kind of
strange-but-true undertaking that could lure the curious in droves.
At least initially.
</P>
<P>
   But with CBS ordering six episodes of a souped-up version of the
vintage ``What's My Line?'' and the classic ``The $64,000
Question,'' and NBC working on a remake of ``Twenty-One,'' the
genre may be oversaturated by the time ``Survivor!'' arrives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imitation is the sincerest form of television,'' says John R.
Rash, senior vice president and director of broadcast negotiations
for Campbell Mithun Esty, an advertising agency. He warns that the
newcomers risk diluting the audience not only for the other new
shows but perhaps even for syndicated shows already airing.
</P>
<P>
   A similar barrage helped halt the game-show run 30 years ago,
after the genre peaked in the late '50s and early '60s.
Well-publicized scandals merely contributed to pushing the shows
off a cliff.
</P>
<P>
   First a staple on radio, game shows like ``The $64,000
Question'' spawned a number of imitators in the mid-'50s, including
its own spinoff. ``The $64,000 Challenge'' offered ``Question''
alumni the chance to win even more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Tell the Truth,'' ``The Price Is Right,'' ``Keep Talking''
and ``Twenty-One'' triggered viewers' money-hungry glands with a
variety of lavish prizes (even losers sometimes won; runners-up on
``The $64,000 Question'' are said to have received Cadillacs).
</P>
<P>
   In the late '50s, though, a former contestant on the game show
``Dotto'' confessed to receiving answers beforehand; then Herbert
Stempel outlined his elaborate coaching on ``Twenty-One,'' igniting
a wide-ranging scandal involving intellectual golden boy Charles
Van Doren. The scandal, in which 10 people were convicted of
perjury, was introduced to a new generation with the 1994 film
``Quiz Show.''
</P>
<P>
   During the '60s and '70s, game shows such as ``The Joker's
Wild'' and ``Tic Tac Dough'' were relegated to daytime hours and
designed to be either cerebral or inane, to keep them above
suspicion. The joke was that contestants would have needed special
coaching to answer questions incorrectly. Currently, game shows can
be found in syndication and on The Game Show cable network.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the first of this new batch of game shows
experienced not a scandal but at least an embarrassment when it
goofed over a question worth, coincidentally, $64,000. David Honea
of Raleigh, N.C., correctly answered that Lake Huron is the second
largest Great Lake after Lake Superior but was told he was wrong
and sent home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millionaire,'' which heightens the drama by having host
Philbin and a contestant sit facing each other while a live studio
audience gasps at every answer, later admitted its mistake. The
show apologized and invited Honea back to add to his $32,000
winnings
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, this renewed interest in prime-time game shows has
everything to do with the success of ``Millionaire,'' which was the
top-rated program during the last three nights of its run,
delivering a peak of 21 million viewers. (That's how many viewers a
new episode of ``Friends'' attracted two weeks ago.)
</P>
<P>
   But the $64,000 question now is whether ``Millionaire,'' or any
of the newcomers, will attract large audiences at a time when the
networks are airing glitzy miniseries, movies and ``special''
episodes of series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millionaire'' received its huge ratings against summer reruns.
``Is that a concern?'' Fox's Darnell said. ``I don't know. We've
been really busy. We haven't gotten to that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kperkins(at)star-telegram.com (Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
