<HEADER>
A8290 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BIBLE-HOMOSEXUALITY16     10-15 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIBLE-HOMOSEXUALITY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Minister: Bible has place for gays
 &HT;    By Kathy Whyde Jesse
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Does the Bible say that homosexuality is a sin?
</P>
<P>
   A slew of books _ scholarly and otherwise _ have been written to
support both sides of this issue. But the Rev. Samuel Kader's book
brings something new to the argument: The perspective of a man who
is both gay and a member of the clergy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted this book to have the focus of ministry,'' says
Kader, pastor of Community Gospel Church in Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Openly Gay, Openly Christian: How the Bible Really is Gay
Friendly'' (Leyland Publications, $15.95), Kader argues that
scripture commonly cited as proof that the Bible condemns
homosexuality are misreadings, at best, used by blatant homophobics
or by people who have a sincere intention to help homosexuals ``get
right with God.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, the story of the city of Sodom is viewed by many
Christians as God's condemnation of homosexuality. A group of gay
men threatens to rape two visitors who have come to Lot's home in
Sodom. God saves Lot and his family, but rains burning sulfur on
the city, killing all its ungodly inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   In Genesis 19:4, the men of Sodom circle Lot's house and say to
him, ``Where are the men which came in to thee this night? Bring
them out unto us, that we may know them.''
</P>
<P>
   Kader argues that the verb ``to know,'' can mean ``to know
carnally,'' but it can also mean ``to be acquainted with.'' Later,
Lot offers the crowd his daughters instead, saying ``you can do
what you like with them.'' Why would Lot offer his daughters to a
crowd of gay men, Kader asks.
</P>
<P>
   His book sets out to deconstruct anti-gay interpretations of
other biblical passages, such as Leviticus 18:22: ``Do not lie with
a man as one lies with a woman; that is detestable.''
</P>
<P>
   He makes his points in a readable manner, using ``Strong's
Concordance,'' a book that alphabetically lists and defines words
in the Bible based on their original Greek and Hebrew meanings.
It's a reference that anybody can use and that's the point. Kader
doesn't want his argument obscured by layers of scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Farmer, an Old Testament professor at United
Theological Seminary, has not read Kader's book, and she warns that
``the whole area of Biblical interpretation depends upon the
assumptions you come with.''
</P>
<P>
   But she is familiar with the Biblical passages commonly used to
support the argument that homosexuality is wrong. Of the story of
Sodom, she supports Kader's view that the use of the verb ``to
know'' is ambiguous. ``There is no way of knowing from the text''
which meaning the author intended. But a clue is offered in Ezekiel
16:49, in which the word of God is being delivered to Israel. Sodom
is described as having done ``abominable things,'' the worst of
which appears to be ``injustice to the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Kader, 48, founded the Community Gospel Church in 1986. It has
20 members, not all of whom are gay. But it is what he calls a
``reconciling church,'' a term that describes a ministry that
reaches out to those who have been hurt by churches in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Raised a Roman Catholic, he was swept up in the charismatic
Christian movement, ``But I was unable to accept Christian doctrine
from heterosexuals. I knew they had a hidden agenda. If they knew I
was gay, they wouldn't accept me.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many other gay Christians, he tried to change his sexual
orientation through prayer, fasting and the laying on of hands.
Finally, a friend told him, ``Any God who made you won't condemn
you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what started me on my journey with God,'' Kader says.
``I knew I was OK.''
</P>
<P>
   He received his call to ministry in 1976. Ministering to gays,
and to heterosexuals who have misconceptions about gays is his
ministry, he says. ``Many people say they're ex-gay to get the
affirmation of a traditional Christian church. But I'm the one who
gets the phone call in the middle of the night from people saying,
'I can't live this way anymore.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
