<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-CONE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID CONE: `STABLE INFLUENCE' ON THE YANKEE MOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The closer he gets to the December of his career, the
more he savors his Octobers. David Cone tells himself every
postseason to take none of it for granted, that it isn't going to
last forever, that he and the New York Yankees never made any
until-death-does-them-part arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   He just never understood the wisdom of his admonitions.
</P>
<P>
   And how little he meant the part about one day giving up
Octobers in pinstripes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year I think I can honestly say, `This may be my last
chance to pitch in the playoffs for the Yankees,''' Cone said.
``Now, more than ever, I realize that.''
</P>
<P>
   The realization has been hounding Cone for weeks, casting a pall
over a season that could have been so gratifying. At 36, Cone
became the second-oldest pitcher to throw a perfect game. He
pitched in his fifth All-Star game. He finished with the lowest
earned-run average (3.44) of any American League pitcher not named
Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night at Yankee Stadium, Cone had to leave his worries
and insecurities behind him. Cone took the mound for Game 2 of the
AL Championship Series against the Boston Red Sox feeling strong,
feeling rested. He hadn't pitched in 12 days, giving him plenty of
time to contemplate the sort of things that pitchers do when
they're his age and are overdue on their 2,500-inning checkup.
</P>
<P>
   How much does someone with 180 career victories and arm
operations have left? How could somebody with so much pitching
know-how struggle so mightily during the stretch run? Would the
Yankees decide that Cone hasn't done enough for them lately to make
him a part of their plans after this season?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sort of at a crossroads,'' Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   Cone just made it a lot harder for the Yankees to move on
without him. Lest anybody have forgotten what a big-game hunter
Cone is, he provided an emphatic reminder in a 3-2 victory against
the Red Sox. Cone out-dueled Red Sox right-hander Ramon Martinez,
sparing the Yankees of the daunting prospect of a tied series and
the best pitcher in the Martinez family lurking.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 57,180 cheered Cone through seven innings of
seven-hit, two-run, nine-strikeout craftsmanship. Yankees manager
Joe Torre had to Rolodex his way through four relievers to get the
next three outs before turning over the ninth inning to Mariano
Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   Cone and the Yankees have been constants in the past five
postseasons. When Cone joined the Yankees in July of 1995, he had
the reputation as a hired gun who couldn't tie himself down with
allegiances. Have arm, will travel to highest bidder or neediest
contender. Cone has re-upped with the Yankees twice since then.
</P>
<P>
   Given the leverage of a 20-7 record last season, Cone settled
for a one-year contract just so he could stay and help the Yankees
defend their World Series title. The Yankees anted up $8 million
plus incentives, but Cone could have gotten a multiyear deal
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't done a good job of controlling my emotions down the
stretch,'' Cone said. ``I've let a lot of little things bother me.
I've just got to come to the point where I put all those issues to
the side for now. How do you do it? I don't know. I haven't been
very good at it to this point. I've got to find a way to just
forget about all the issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let a big year get away from me. I really thought I should
have pitched better in the second half. I took the one-year deal
with the Yankees in order to stay here, and now I find myself in a
position of uncertainty. It's nobody's fault. It is what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   What it was on July 18 was absolutely perfect. Twenty-seven
Montreal Expos came up, 27 went down, on only 88 pitches. Cone's
record at that point was 10-4. His ERA was 2.65. He went 2-5 with a
4.82 ERA in his final 13 regular-season starts. At one point, Cone
went eight consecutive starts without a victory _ the longest
drought of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confidence is a fleeting thing even among veterans and guys
who have had success,'' Cone said. ``There were times in the second
half where I did have some self-doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   If any of those doubts accompanied Cone to the mound, he hid
them well. Cone got a big break when Jason Varitek lashed a drive
off the top of the right-field wall _ missing a home run by inches
_ with one out in the second. Triple. That piece of luck wouldn't
have done Cone any good if he hadn't skillfully maneuvered out of
the jam. With the infield drawn in, Cone got Darren Lewis to lunge
at an off-speed pitch and pop weakly to short. Trot Nixon flied to
right, ending that threat.
</P>
<P>
   The only blemish was Nomar Garciaparra's two-out, two-run homer
in the fifth. Cone bought the Yankees time to come back from a 2-1
deficit by hanging tough through the sixth, through the seventh,
all the way to his 128th and final pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``David was sensational,'' Torre said. ``I always love looking
up and seeing him. He has been such a stable influence on the
pitching staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cone has been around enough not to be naive about the
business of baseball. Traded four times. Former Cy Young winner and
high-ticket free agent. Active member of the Players Association.
Whether or not he spends any more Octobers in a Yankees uniform
isn't entirely in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't hurt,'' Cone said. ``It's just harsh reality
setting in. I think I've proven I've got some life left. There's no
guarantee where it's going to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
