<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREMONA-STRADIVARI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SOUNDS OF MUSIC LIVE ON IN STRADIVARI'S HOMETOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL NUCKOLS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CREMONA, Italy _ If you don't hear music in Cremona, you're not
listening.
</P>
<P>
   Opera, chamber music, movie music, even Celtic music _ you can
hear all of them in this small city 75 miles southeast of Milan.
</P>
<P>
   But the violin reigns. For Cremona was the home of Antonio
Stradivari, maker of the most renowned violins the world has known.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1666, when he finished his apprenticeship to Niccolo
Amati, until his death in 1737, Stradivari made more than 1,000
violins and other stringed instruments. But it is the violin for
which the great master is most famed. His innovations, including
decreasing the arch of the top of the violin and altering the sound
holes, might sound like overly technical and perhaps irrelevant
details to the average listener, but the changes improved the tone
and projection of the instrument. Stradivari's instruments are
still revered as the ultimate.
</P>
<P>
   Stradivari's hometown, a 1 1/4-hour train ride from Milan, is an
easily reached destination for aficionados of the stringed
instrument that many believe sounds most like the human voice.
</P>
<P>
   Instruments by Stradivari and his predecessors in the Cremonese
violin-making tradition _ members of the Amati and Guarneri
families _ are on view in the Sala dei Violini in the Palazzo
Comunale (Municipal Palace).
</P>
<P>
   The Museo Stradivariano (Stradivari Museum) contains none of the
1,000-plus instruments made by the great master. But on display are
other instruments, including such oddities as a 19th-century violin
constructed in the shape of an eighth note, and tools and patterns
for the violins, violas, cellos and other stringed instruments
Stradivari made.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there are paper patterns for cutting out bridges,
scrolls and f-holes (sound holes); calipers for measuring the
thickness of the top or back of an instrument; and scrapers for
shaping the wood.
</P>
<P>
   Violin making hasn't changed much since the golden era of the
mid-16th through the mid-18th centuries, says Bruce Carlson, an
American who makes and restores instruments in the Cremonese studio
of Carlson Cacciatori Neumann.
</P>
<P>
   ``The violin was perfected in the 1500s, and it is still
essentially the same instrument,'' he says. A computer might be
able to measure the thickness of the wood, but ``in the final
analysis, it's a question of experience. Your sensitivity, your own
feeling about what you're doing are very important.''
</P>
<P>
   When Carlson is planing the wood for the top of a violin, for
instance, ``the sensation of how the wood is _ hard, soft, mushy _
tells me what I have to do to this piece of wood.'' The violin's
curved top and back are carved, not pressed, into shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very complex instrument. There are so many variables,''
Carlson says. ``Until you've strung up the instrument, you never
really know how it sounds.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes approximately 200 hours to make a violin or viola,
twice that for a cello, says Carlson, who came to Cremona to study
at the Scuola di Luteria (violin-making school) and stayed. He and
his colleagues sell mostly to violin dealers, but also to
violinists who visit Cremona in search of a fine modern instrument.
Prices run from around $10,000 for a violin to $20,000 for a cello.
Most world-famous soloists prefer older instruments, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Carlson considers Cremona an ideal place for a violin maker to
work. ``It's very inspiring knowing that these makers were here,''
he says. And it's not just the musical tradition. Dating more than
2,200 years, when it was a Roman colony, Cremona is permeated with
history and art.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the duomo (cathedral), construction of which began in
1107. Though not as big as Milan's famous duomo, it confers just as
much of a sense of height and grandeur. It contains bright
16th-century frescoes; elaborate altars; an enormous 15th-century
silver cross; a 13th-century rose window; and a floor laid in pink,
black and white marble squares. Looming over the cathedral is the
campanile (bell tower), built between 1267 and 1305.
</P>
<P>
   The entire town glows with charm and sophistication, a contrast
between old and new. Red brick buildings are interspersed with
others of umber or a peachy terra-cotta stucco, adorned with iron
grillwork and brown shutters and topped with red tile roofs.
</P>
<P>
   Some townspeople ride bicycles, but the late 20th century also
intrudes: A bus from the train station takes travelers past
sophisticated shops displaying Italian fashions and avant-garde
home furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, the church where Stradivari was buried no longer stands
(his body and those of others interred there were moved); in its
place is a city park. And on the site of his home, across the
street from the church, a McDonald's stands.
</P>
<P>
   But Stradivari's statue holds court in the piazza in front of
the duomo, and his spirit lives on in the instruments crafted by
his hand.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
