<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   General Electric's Tribute To the Master Inventor &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As he nears the end of his career, Jack Welch is returning to
General Electric's roots. He has agreed to raise $80 million to
preserve historic sites associated with Thomas Alva Edison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, GE should be heavily involved in this campaign,''
Welch said last week, ``because several of GE's modern businesses,
including lighting, power generation and industrial systems,
essentially were invented by Edison.'' The Edison General Electric
Co. merged with the Thomas-Houston Co. to form GE in 1892.
</P>
<P>
   As if all his inventions weren't enough, Edison has come to be
revered as the founder of modern technological enterprise _ the
first techie-turned-business-baron.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Welch gave $5 million on behalf of GE to preserve
Edison's laboratories in West Orange, N.J., and his home nearby. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Golden Leash? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ebit Wachner, the Yorkshire terrier belonging to Linda J.
Wachner, the boss of both Warnaco and Authentic Fitness, would be
the first to benefit if Ms. Wachner's plans for merging the two
companies went through. Ms. Wachner said last week that she would
use her $47.9 million proceeds from the deal to further cancer
research and to buy Ebit a new collar.
</P>
<P>
   In an apparently paw-written note to a reporter on Ebit
Wachner's personalized stationery, signed with a paw print, Ebit
herself expressed appreciation last week for the publicity given
these plans, adding, ``Now I'm certain to get my new collar on
time.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Other Executive's Philanthropy &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven A. Ballmer, the president of Microsoft, may not be quite
as wealthy as Bill Gates, his boss and college classmate, nor have
his philanthropic endeavors been followed in anywhere near as much
detail. But he recently gained all the attention anyone could want
when his comments about a ``gold rush'' mentality in
high-technology stocks drove down the market, trimming his personal
stake in the company by $1.2 billion in a single day.
</P>
<P>
   As for his donations, one of the chief beneficiaries so far has
been Harvard University. (He graduated in 1977, while Gates
famously dropped out.)
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Ballmer returned to Harvard for the dedication of the
Maxwell Dworkin building, a center for computer science and
electrical engineering. He and Gates together donated $25 million
in 1996 for the building _ bearing the maiden names of Gates's and
Ballmer's mothers, respectively _ and a new professorship.
</P>
<P>
   At the dedication, Ballmer put in a backhanded plug for his
school: ``I hope the building and the new faculty help make Harvard
as much a center of computer science as MIT is a center of computer
science,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to The Harvard Crimson, Ballmer questioned students
about Microsoft's image and how it could be improved among young
people. Showing off a computer program that, with the click of a
mouse on a Microsoft media player, could easily edit a video of a
two-hour Seattle Mariners game to about five minutes of action, he
said the real innovations of the computer age were still to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really just at the beginning of the Internet
revolution,'' he said. _Sam Howe Verhovek &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Saving, Through a Child's Eyes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At age 7, most of us were doing well enough if we could add and
subtract. Richard K. Anderson Jr. has already rung the opening bell
at the New York Stock Exchange (while still in kindergarten), and
testified before Congress, the youngest person to do either.
</P>
<P>
   At a Manhattan conference next Saturday, H. Carl McCall, the New
York State Comptroller, plans to give him and his father, Richard
K. Anderson Sr., what McCall calls the ``Empower Your Future
Award'' to honor their role in promoting savings and investments.
</P>
<P>
   The father has a financial planning and money management firm,
Anderson Financial Services, in Crown Heights, Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Young Richard, a second grader, has learned from his father
about stocks, bonds and mutual funds, and how, in interviews, to
say things like, ``If you don't save, you're going to have to work
for a long time, and nobody likes that.'' Anderson says his son
began taking to finance as a 3-year-old, when he was made to watch
CNBC as a punishment instead of cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson says they are intent on promoting investment and
financial security, particularly among black people.
</P>
