<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA SAYS ITS TROOPS HAVE MOVED FARTHER INTO CHECHNYA 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Markedly expanding their operations in the rebellious
republic of Chechnya, Russian troops have crossed a strategic river
and apparently control a ridge from which they could bombard the
airport and suburbs of the capital, Grozny, Chechen officials said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the Russian Defense Ministry confirmed that their
troops had crossed the Terek River, which roughly divides
Chechnya's ethnically Russian north from the predominantly Islamic
south.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Chechen president, Aslan Maskhadov, said
Russian artillery and other vehicles are trying to occupy the
highlands south of the Terek, 15 to 20 miles north of Grozny, so
that ``long-range artillery can control Grozny's northern and
northwestern outskirts and the airport.''
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman said Chechen troops were seeking to repulse the
Russians, but no details were available.
</P>
<P>
   The Interfax news service quoted Russian military officials as
saying that the offensive would continue until they were confident
that Chechen fighters could not break into a so-called security
zone that the Russians have established in the north.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Russian ambitions extend further was not clear. Other
reports have suggested that the Russians plan an assault on Grozny
itself. Russian artillery and jets virtually leveled the city in
1996 in a secessionist war that ended in a debacle for Moscow, and
it is not known whether Russian troops, emboldened by their success
this time, have the appetite for a rematch.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials have said they are fighting a smarter war
than in 1996, having learned that they must coordinate troop
movements more closely and use their resources more efficiently.
And in fact Russian troops generally seemed to have performed
better than in the last conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Chechnya is so dangerous that few journalists have been
able to report personally on the war, and officials of both sides
often give distorted views of their forces' successes and failures.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian offensive began last month with a plan to cordon off
the Chechen border with Dagestan, the republic to the east where
fighting originally broke out in August when Islamic militants from
Chechnya tried to extend their influence to the Caspian Sea. But
Moscow's ambitions have expanded as Russian troops have moved
successfully onto Chechnya.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Russian military aides quoted by Interfax said troops would
try to solidify their command of occupied areas by scouring towns
for terrorists and mercenaries.
</P>
<P>
   The aides said counterterrorist operations would be mounted
against ``several hundred mercenaries who have arrived in Chechnya
from Moslem countries, CIS states, and Russia itself.'' CIS, the
Commonwealth of Independent States, is made up of nations that were
part of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians estimate publicly that they face some 25,000
Chechen troops, adding that 8,000 of them come from the armed gangs
that rule much of Chechnya outside the capital.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the Russians are so deeply involved in the
Chechen operation that they have told European military officials
that Russian troop strength now exceeds the regional limits set by
the Treaty on Conventional Forces in Europe, a crucial 1980s
agreement that limits the number of weapons in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   From the West's standpoint, the accord was aimed at minimizing
prospects that Soviet troops could mass for an invasion of Europe
or Turkey. Russian officials have told European military attaches
that they are exceeding limits on armored equipment in southwestern
Russia _ perhaps by hundreds of units _ but that the breach will
last only until the Chechen situation is under control.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Ministry said Friday that 179 Russian servicemen
have died in action in Dagestan and Chechnya since fighting broke
out this summer, including 47 in Chechnya. Antiterrorist officials
in Moscow say they have also seized 515 tons of explosives, 4,000
explosive devices and 7,000 guns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
