<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8328 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ECON-JITTERS-ART-NYT &LR;      10-15 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-JITTERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT OF RISE IN PRODUCER PRICES PROMPTS SELLING ON WALL STREET 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MARKET-NYT) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Prices at the producer level shot up 1.1 percent in
September, the biggest monthly increase in nine years, the
government reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The report stoked fears among investors that inflation might be
accelerating, and helped to set off a wave of selling on Wall
Street, which was already jittery following comments on Thursday
night by Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, about the
difficulty of determining whether stock prices are too high.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the increase in the producer price index, while
nearly three times larger than anticipated, overstated the
inflation threat. The rise in the index, they said, was largely
driven by increases in a few categories, including oil, tobacco and
automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   But the jump in the price index was substantial enough that it
increased the odds of the Federal Reserve raising interest rates at
its next meeting on Nov. 16. Fed officials are leaning toward
increasing rates for the third time this year, said Mark Vitner, an
economist at First Union Securities, and Friday's figures ``give
them the cover they need to do so at their mid-November meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   The so-called ``core'' price index, which excludes food and
energy, rose eight-tenths of a percent in September, after being
roughly flat for most of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding food, energy, tobacco and cars, the index rose just
one-tenth of a percent in September, suggesting that there is no
broad-based increase in prices paid by producers for finished
goods. There did not appear to be much inflation pressure in the
pipeline, with the core index on intermediate goods _ a stage of
production between raw materials and finished goods _ rising
three-tenths of a percent in September after jumping eight-tenths
of a percent in August and six-tenths of a percent in July.
</P>
<P>
   Oil prices have been rising for months as global demand has
grown. Tobacco companies have been raising prices to pass along the
costs of their settlement with the states over the health effects
of smoking. Car prices often jump in September, reflecting the
start of a new model year. The jump in all three categories is
likely to flatten out this month, analysts said, but will show up
in the consumer price index for September, scheduled to be released
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed said in a separate report Friday that industrial
production fell three-tenths of a percent in September, largely
because of the disruption created on the East Coast by Hurricane
Floyd. Excluding the effects of the storm, the Fed said, production
would have increased slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Although the chances of another rate increase from the Fed are
growing, the decision is by no means a foregone conclusion,
analysts said. Among the factors that might persuade the central
bank to hold off is the decline in stock prices and the rise over
much of the year in the long-term interest rates set in the bond
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that to a large degree, the markets are
doing the Fed's job,'' said Stephen D. Slifer, an economist at
Lehman Brothers. ``Eventually the cooling off in financial markets
should result in a cooling off in economic activity. The Fed must
be asking, why tighten when jawboning works so well?''
</P>
<P>
   With Wall Street waiting anxiously for any further sign from
him, Greenspan spoke publicly again Friday, but confined his
remarks mostly to preparations for the Year 2000 computer problem.
Investors, however, continued to chew over the remarks he made
Thursday night, in which he discussed the complexities of measuring
financial risk.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan has been trying for the last several years to assess
how swings in the price of stocks and other assets affect consumer
confidence, the long-term health of the financial system and
economic growth _ and how and when the Fed should respond to them.
</P>
<P>
   He has generally concluded that the central bank should not try
to second guess investors about whether stocks are overvalued,
especially at a time when technology is reshaping the economy.
Rather, Greenspan has said, the Fed should be prepared to act
quickly if financial markets run into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Greenspan and other Fed officials have been
increasingly vocal in telling banks and other financial
institutions not to assume that the good times will continue
forever.
</P>
<P>
   It was against that backdrop that Greenspan spoke to a
conference on Thursday night sponsored by the Office of the
Comptroller of the Currency in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan noted a decline in recent years in the ``equity
premium,'' or the additional return demanded by investors to buy
stocks rather than relatively less risky securities like government
bonds. The decline in the equity premium, Greenspan told the bank
regulators, ``should prompt careful consideration'' of assumptions
about how well financial institutions could cope if asset prices
should plunge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key question is whether the recent decline in equity
premiums is permanent or temporary,'' Greenspan said, touching on a
debate over whether the economy has been fundamentally strengthened
by technology or is simply in the midst of an unsustainable bubble.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is at issue is how much of the decline reflects new,
irreversible technologies, and what part is a consequence of a
prolonged business expansion without a significant period of
adjustment,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan has considerable experience with financial crises,
having taken office just before the October 1987 stock market crash
and having weathered the problems of last fall, when global markets
all but seized up as financial problems in Asia spread to Russia
and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I have indicated on previous occasions, history tells us
that sharp reversals in confidence occur abruptly, most often with
little advance notice,'' Greenspan said. The bursting of a bubble,
he said, is ``incontrovertibly evident only in retrospect.''
</P>
<P>
   The lesson, he said, is that regulators should insist that
financial institutions set aside enough money to weather ``the
losses that will inevitably emerge from time to time when investors
suffer a loss of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These reserves will appear almost all the time to be a
suboptimal use of capital,'' Greenspan said. ``So do fire insurance
premiums.''
</P>
</TEXT>
