<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGED-SUSPECT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOOTING SUSPECT, 103, REFLECTS ON JAIL, HIS LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By MELODY McDONALD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ He lived through World War I, the Depression
and the days of Jim Crow. He married five times and outlived two of
his three children.
</P>
<P>
   For 103-year-old Ben Collier, jail wasn't so bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got a nice jail,'' Collier said, flashing a grin. ``They
fed good. I tell you, they run me off.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a white shirt, blue pants held up by suspenders, and red
house shoes, Collier sat in his lawyer's office on Thursday and
reflected on his long life, including three days behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   Collier is accused of shooting his grandson, Tyrone Collins,
four times after the younger man awakened him, complaining about
conditions at the duplex Collins rented from him. Collier, who has
been charged with attempted murder, was released Wednesday from the
Tarrant County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   At times Thursday, his thoughts got away from him, bouncing from
his release from jail to the time during the war when black
soldiers couldn't eat in mess halls with their white counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   As Collier recalled events in his lengthy life, his 45-year-old
grandson was recovering from surgery at a hospital. He remained in
serious condition.
</P>
<P>
   Collier's attorney, Jim Lane of Fort Worth, told him not to talk
about the shooting, saying a grand jury will probably hear the
evidence next week.
</P>
<P>
   But Collier couldn't help himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry this happened,'' he blurted out, his voice cracking.
``I wouldn't shoot that boy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, Benny,'' Lane said, interrupting his client. ``We can't
talk about that. We're not going to go into all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Collier did speak candidly about his life, his family _ 11
grandchildren, 14 great-grandchildren and eight
great-great-grandchildren _ and his stay in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've all been good to me all the way through,'' he said,
referring to the people he has met since his arrest. ``I don't know
what all this fuss is about. All I want is for my grandson to get
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Relatives said Collins arrived at the house about 1 a.m., angry
and drunk, cursing at his sleeping grandfather and calling him a
slumlord.
</P>
<P>
   Collier grabbed a gun, fired four bullets into his grandson and
then went back into his room to load another weapon, relatives
said. His daughter Viola Collins, 75, snatched the bullets away.
</P>
<P>
   ``One minute he was just standing there, and the next minute he
comes back with a gun and bang, bang, bang,'' Viola Collins said
Wednesday. ``After Tyrone fell, he stood over him and pumped
another bullet into his chest.''
</P>
<P>
   Collier was released from Tarrant County Jail after Lane posted
$20,000 bail. State District Judge Scott Wisch released Collier on
the condition that he not possess firearms or have contact with his
grandson. He must also remain at the home of his nephew David
Swanson, except to go to church, court, doctors' appointments or
his attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   Thelma Byrd, who lives across Galvez Avenue from the house
Collier shared with his daughter, granddaughter and Tyrone's twin
brother, Jerone, said she doesn't blame Collier for his actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``These old people are just scared,'' she said. ``Someone comes
and knocks on your door at 1 o'clock in the morning drunk, and you
don't know what is going on. This old man rides up and down this
street all day long on his scooter, not bothering no one.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1896 in Granger, Texas, to parents who made their living
picking cotton and cooking, Collier said he moved to Fort Worth
when he was 4. He said he went to boarding school in Oklahoma and
joined the Army in 1918. As World War I raged in Europe, Collier
was in the 18th Company of the 165th Depot Brigade at Camp Travis
in San Antonio, waiting to be transported overseas.
</P>
<P>
   He never went, but he made it back to Fort Worth, where he held
a variety of jobs throughout his life, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he mainly lives off the money and rental property he
inherited from his fifth wife, Early, whom he described as a
``businesswoman in real estate.''
</P>
<P>
   Collier said his biggest regret in life is selling some of those
properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me to keep them until I died,'' he said. ``And I
didn't do it. My wife left all that stuff to me and I messed it
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Collier said he doesn't know how much longer he will live. And
right now, he said, he doesn't know how much he has to live for. He
refuses to return home.
</P>
<P>
   He is thinking about getting an apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have no job,'' he said. ``I done lived my life. I've
walked in these shoes for 100 years. I've been there.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
