<HEADER>
A8335 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r w BC-CRIME-DROP-$ADV18-HNS     10-15 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRIME-DROP-$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
17)  
 &HT;     MURDER RATE FALLS TO LOWEST LEVEL IN MORE THAN 30 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For Monday a.m. papers; release time is 6:00 p.m. Sunday, Oct. &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's murder rate plummeted to its lowest
level in more than 30 years as serious crimes reported to police in
1998 declined for a seventh consecutive year, the FBI said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's news is great for citizens across the nation,''
Attorney General Janet Reno said. ``For seven years now, we have
seen serious crime go down in each region of the country, and in
cities and towns, large and small.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of murders in the United States fell to 17,000 in
1998, a 7 percent drop from the year before and 28 percent lower
than in 1994. The murder rate of 6 offenses per 100,000 inhabitants
was the lowest since 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Final FBI figures for 1998 released by the Justice Department on
Sunday showed a 6 percent drop from 1997 in the number of violent
crimes and serious property crimes reported to more than 17,000
police agencies around the nation. The total number of serious
crimes in 1998 was 12.5 million, 12 percent below the number a
decade earlier and 5 percent below the 1997 figure.
</P>
<P>
   The crime rate, adjusted for population growth, dropped even
more. Last year's rate was 4,616 crimes per 100,000 residents, down
6 percent from 1997, 14 percent below 1994 and 20 percent lower
than 1989.
</P>
<P>
   All violent crimes _ murder, rape, robbery and aggravated
assault _ and all the far more numerous property crimes _ burglary,
auto theft and larceny-theft _ dropped in both number and rate.
</P>
<P>
   The violent crime rate was down 10 percent from 1997 to its
lowest level since 1987, led by a 10 percent decline in robberies
and the 7 percent drop in murders. The aggravated assault rate was
down 5 percent, and the rape rate declined 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The property crime rate dipped 7 percent _ down 8 percent for
auto theft, 5 percent for larceny-theft, 5 percent for burglary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend is good news,'' said James Alan Fox, dean of
Northeastern University's College of Criminal Justice. But he
cautioned, ``People should remember that these numbers are only
part of the story. The country needs to watch out because these
drops in crime could turn quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox said two dominant trends are influencing the nation's crime
rate.
</P>
<P>
   First, the aging of the baby boom generation _ those born
between 1946 and 1964 who make up 25 percent of the population _
has pushed down the number of crimes because adults tend to be less
violent than juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the number of crimes committed by teen-agers
has risen sharply since the mid-1980s. The number of murders
committed by teen-agers increased 145 percent from 1985 to 1995.
And although the number of violent crimes committed by juveniles
has fallen slightly in the past two years, the number of teen-agers
will grow quickly over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   There are 40 million children under the age of 10 nationwide.
Fox said future crime rates will be determined by how society deals
with the rising tide of teen-agers over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, crime rates peak in the couple of hours between the
end of school and when most parents get home for dinner,'' he said.
``That tells you that our children are not getting enough
supervision from their parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno agreed, saying that the nation should not become
``complacent.''
</P>
<P>
   All regions saw crime rates fall in 1998, with the Northeast and
West experiencing the largest drop, 7 percent, the FBI report said.
The crime rate in the South declined 5 percent, while the Midwest
saw a drop of 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The South remained the nation's most dangerous region with 5,223
offenses per 100,000 people in 1998. The West had 4,879 offenses
per 100,000 inhabitants, with the Midwest and Northeast reporting
4,379 and 3,474 respectively.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
