<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8336 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-PAKISTAN-MOOD-ART-NYT     10-15 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-MOOD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAKISTAN, IN SEARCH OF A STRONGMAN
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By TIM WEINER and STEVE LeVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAWALPINDI, Pakistan _ If there is such a thing as a good coup,
this one is winning raves in the bazaars of Rawalpindi.
</P>
<P>
   A decade of crooked and incompetent civilian rule before the
takeover this week, a decade of competently brutal dictatorship
before that, and life keeps getting harder for Pakistan's 138
million souls. A Pakistani poet, Faiz Ahmed Faiz, once was asked
what would become of his nation. ``My great fear,'' he said, ``is
that nothing will happen. Things will go on the way they are.''
</P>
<P>
   There is not much passion for politicians or for going to the
polls again. There is a thirst for leadership, or even something
stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there should be any elections,'' said Kalsoon
Syed, an elementary school principal. ``There should be a strong
dictator.''
</P>
<P>
   The American ambassador, William Milam, met Friday for 90
minutes with the coup leader, Gen. Pervez Musharraf, at the army's
general headquarters here just hours after the general declared
himself the country's chief executive, suspended the Constitution
and dismissed Parliament. The general's government also froze the
assets of more than 500 political figures, among them Nawaz Sharif,
the ousted prime minister, and his predecessor, Benazir Bhutto.
Western diplomats said the ambassador had given the general a
message from President Clinton calling on him to return the nation
to civilian rule as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton may be calling for a return to democratic principles in
Pakistan, but politicians here have rarely practiced them. For 11
years, since the end of the last military dictatorship, most of
them have behaved like medieval barons, plundering most of what
remained of the nation's wealth.
</P>
<P>
   What was left was not enough to run a civil society. The
principal export of Pakistan today is Pakistanis. The most
talented, the best educated, the potential leaders are gone. So
nostalgia for a strongman fills the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   That feeling may support the military government of Musharraf,
who seized power this week, becoming the latest in a series of
rulers who have led and misled the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan was created in 1947 out of the violent partition of
India. While it often has been ruled by military dictatorships, it
has also had the trappings of democracy: a Parliament, a lively
press, political debate.
</P>
<P>
   But to many Pakistanis, democracy is a facade. Waheed Zaman, 30,
the well-spoken owner of a trophy shop in Rawalpindi, said his
middle-class family was ``like other people; we are fed up with
politicians; we have love for our armed forces despite their
checkered history.''
</P>
<P>
   Zaman and others in the teeming bazaar in this city, 25 miles
southwest of the national capital, Islamabad, spoke in heroic terms
of a man who was once a national demon: Gen. Mohammad Zia ul-Haq.
He ruled Pakistan for 11 years until he died in a plane crash in
1988, a still unexplained midair explosion that also took the life
of Arnold Raphel, then the American ambassador to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   ``General Zia was an angel,'' said a grizzled rickshaw driver
named Amir Khan, 59. ``Then there was no inflation. Crime was under
control. When I heard he was killed, I thought Pakistan was an
orphan.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment is sometimes tinged with blood; many Pakistanis
want their political miscreants punished. ``These smugglers, these
bribe-taking people should be behind bars or hanged,'' said Mrs.
Syed, the school principal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pervez Musharraf, my prayers and my best wishes are with
him,'' she said ``This man is a general. He knows law and order and
how to get things done. We expect him to do things for the common
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Much needs to be done. Pakistan is a basket case, and the coup
may make things worse.
</P>
<P>
   Today two-thirds of the country's wealth goes to the military
and to paying its debts. Three-quarters of the aid Pakistan
receives from the International Monetary Fund goes to pay off IOUs
to the I.M.F. That aid was immediately suspended after the coup, as
was a trade agreement with the European Union that Pakistan
desperately needed. Pakistan has only $1.4 billion in foreign
reserves _ just enough to buy three weeks of imports.
</P>
<P>
   In the troubled 2{-year tenure of Sharif, Pakistan's currency,
the rupee, lost half its value against the dollar. Everything in
the bazaar seems to cost far more than it did in 1997. And the $600
million in annual military and economic aid Pakistan received from
the United States in Zia's day, during the 1980s, ended after he
died and when the Cold War was over, blocked by law after the
United States acknowledged that Pakistan was building a nuclear
bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is now uneasily contemplating the prospect of dealing
with a dictator in Pakistan once more. Western diplomats said the
general had given Milam a preview of the speech he is to give on
Saturday, which those diplomats expect will set forth his plans for
dealing with Pakistan's crushing problems.
</P>
<P>
   Those plans may include a slow return to what the West would
like to call democracy. It may come, but for now the bazaar has
spoken, and in much the same voice as that of Talat Massoud, a
retired lieutenant general who served as defense secretary from
1988 to 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coup was a good thing,'' he said, in a voice devoid of
happiness or anticipation. ``It gave us a sigh of relief. There was
no choice left for the military. Our politicians put us on the
brink of disaster. They were making a mockery of democracy. The
prime minister had corrupted every institution. The judiciary was
bought off; there was no justice. The police were run as a fiefdom.
What kind of democracy was that?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1920EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8338 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-RUSSIA-RESIGN-365&AMP;ADD     10-15 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-RESIGN-365&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP RUSSIAN SECURITIES REGULATOR RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's top securities regulator resigned in
frustration Friday, the latest in a series of troubling signs that
the country is ill equipped to defend the interests of shareholders
and foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   Dmitri Vasiliev, chairman of the Federal Securities Commission,
said that Russia was failing to protect investors from abuse and
expropriation, and that other government agencies had obstructed
his efforts to uphold shareholder rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's perfectly clear that we haven't gotten the support of
other government agencies we need in connection with some recent
shareholder disputes,'' Vasiliev said.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of the commission since it was formed in late 1994,
Vasiliev has been among the few proponents of foreign investment
and U.S.-style securities markets to have survived the frequent
purges of President Boris N. Yeltsin's government. Investors said
he tried to help establish the rule of law in a realm where
powerful local business interests use friends in the government to
solve their problems, and where courts are notoriously corrupt. A
successor has not been named.
</P>
<P>
   Many foreign shareholders see Vasiliev's departure as a sign
that their tenuous rights have eroded further. ``People felt that
Vasiliev was the only one in the government paying attention to an
agenda to protect shareholder rights,'' said Andrea Rutherford, a
director of Brunswick Warburg, a Moscow brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   Other ambitious Russian bureaucracies, including the Central
Bank, had sought to oust Vasiliev or wrest oversight of the market
from him over the years. He defeated such campaigns and even built
a securities commission that, despite its shortage of staff,
resources and political influence, succeeded periodically in
protecting shareholder rights.
</P>
<P>
   The commission this year suspended dozens of Russian companies
from over-the-counter trading because they had failed to report
financial information on time. The suspensions prodded many
companies to disclose results quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But after surviving many attacks, Vasiliev said he had begun to
consider resigning several months ago, when some ugly fights over
shareholder rights erupted.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One of those cases involves the Russian oil company Yukos,
accused of authorizing shares to company insiders that would
unfairly dilute minority shareholdings. Although Vasiliev objected,
a court on Monday approved the share issue for a Yukos subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision, Vasiliev said, ``is just another argument
that shows that the system here doesn't protect investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Many foreign investors believe Vasiliev's resignation is tied to
the commission's inability to rein Yukos in. ``There's a great deal
of concern that the share issue was approved, because it is such
blatant abuse of shareholders' rights,'' said Chris Weafer, who is
in charge of research at Troika Dialog, a Moscow brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a small meeting with Western journalists Friday,
Vasiliev told of the indifference and obstruction he had
encountered at other government agencies. In the Yukos case, for
example, the dilutive shares are to be sold in a closed offering to
four offshore companies that many analysts and minority
shareholders believe are owned by Yukos management. Vasiliev said
he had appealed in vain to tax authorities and the Interior
Ministry to help him get information about a possible link between
Yukos and the offshore companies.
</P>
<P>
   Vasiliev's decision to leave was eventually clinched by a St.
Petersburg court's decision on Monday to re-nationalize the
Lomonosov porcelain factory, a move that annulled a 51 percent
stake held in the company by executives of Kohlberg Kravis Roberts
&AMP; Co. and the U.S.-Russia Investment Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, which the fund plans to appeal, marks the first
major re-nationalization in Russia since economic reforms began.
Vasiliev called it ``an extraordinarily dangerous precedent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1921EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
