<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8340 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-WESTBANK-ART-1     10-15 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-WESTBANK-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST BANK SETTLERS INDICATE THEY WILL NOT PROTEST EVACUATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 has been sent to NYT photo clients. Locator
map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEVE EREZ, West Bank _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak's soldiers are
unlikely to face much resistance when they arrive to dismantle this
illegal settlement, a funky hilltop community of beat-up caravans,
young back-to-nature types and goats.
</P>
<P>
   The community leader, Erez Maman, 27, who wanders around the
rocky site playing a recorder, is an unusually mellow Israeli. Five
months ago, five days after Barak was elected, he and some friends
grabbed this land because it seemed to be in the middle of nowhere,
the views were fabulous and the rent was free.
</P>
<P>
   They were assisted by the nearest established settlement, Maale
Michmash, which wanted the hilltop seized to further the right-wing
dream of solidifying Israel's hold on the West Bank. But Maman and
friends have no hard-core political motives themselves, and they
made it clear that although they do not want to leave, they will.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be moved to violence, that's for sure,''
Maman said. ``Maybe we'll stand on the roofs, maybe we'll puncture
a tire? You have to stand up for what you believe in, but that
doesn't mean fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak defused a politically explosive situation late Wednesday
night when he reached a compromise with settler leaders, who are
growing increasingly pragmatic and moderate as the peace effort
marches forward.
</P>
<P>
   Testing a new approach to a destabilizing issue, Barak charted a
middle ground between settlers and peace advocates, both of whom
emerged proclaiming victories. Out of 42 outposts established in
the West Bank in the last year, he agreed to evict residents from
only 12, including Neve Erez, rather than the 15 he had initially
proposed.
</P>
<P>
   To the Palestinians, some of whom privately expressed
satisfaction that any action was being taken, it still seemed a
very small first step in the dismantling of an enterprise that they
consider entirely illegal. It left intact 30 of the outposts
created in the last year, not to mention the 145 previously
existing settlements.
</P>
<P>
   ``This way of deceit _ saying that there are 15 that are legal,
or illegal _ this is not the way to build trust for
permanent-status negotiations,'' said Ahmed Qurei, known as Abu
Ala, who is speaker of the Palestinian Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   But, from the perspective of many Israelis, Barak not only made
an extraordinary move against illegal settlements but also managed
to secure the settler leaders' unusual cooperation. The leaders
promised to help make the evacuations ``voluntary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time that settlements will be removed by
agreement with the settlers, not in a confrontation with them,''
Yossi Beilin, the justice minister and a leftist, said Thursday on
Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
   For all parties, it served as a kind of social preparatory class
for the year ahead, when the ultimate fate of the settlements will
be decided in final-status negotiations. Even if the Palestinians
accede to Barak's desire to preserve large settlements in blocs,
many small or isolated ones are likely to end up similarly slated
for evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   In his compromise with the settlers, Barak agreed to save three
hilltop communities from eviction, to preserve a school in a fourth
and to allow livestock to remain in a fifth. He also left them with
the impression that they could seek to legalize and repopulate
several outposts after the evacuation and move the mobile homes
from others into existing settlements, according to Yehoshua
Mor-Yosef, a spokesman for the settlers.
</P>
<P>
   In so doing, he gave the settler leaders a way to proclaim
victory and to calm down some of their more radical followers.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this means that the evacuation, scheduled to start next
week, will take place smoothly remains to be seen, since at least
one makeshift settlement contains a quite militant population.
</P>
<P>
   But, following their representatives' lead, most settlers said
Thursday that they would protest peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there will be no physical resistance in terms of
violence against Israeli soldiers,'' said Yiftach Sapir, 24, a
second-generation settler who lives in Mitzpe Danny, an outpost
removed from the evacuation list. ``There will be passive
resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying his evacuation plan was not directed at ``the settlement
enterprise'' as such, Barak presented it instead as an effort to
put decision-making in such a sensitive arena back under government
control.
</P>
<P>
   He said: ``I am convinced that it contributes to the
fortification of the rule of law and strengthens the understanding
that a government cannot allow itself to be led by groups of
private citizens _ as dear as they may be and as much pain as they
are experiencing.''
</P>
<P>
   While Yitzhak Rabin, the late prime minister, cracked down on
rogue outposts in confrontations that shook up the country, they
tended to be overnight installations and not sites like these with
deeper roots.
</P>
<P>
   The 42 newest West Bank outposts were all established since the
Wye River peace agreement was signed in Washington last November.
Mitzpe Danny, for instance, was created two days after the signing
at the White House. Maman established Neve Erez just after Barak
won the May 17 elections.
</P>
<P>
   All 42 are tiny settlements, most with fewer than 20 residents _
and four of the ones to be closed are by now uninhabited. Because
the living conditions are primitive, the sites have been
intermittently occupied at capacity, mostly by people in their 20s,
including many devoted second-generation settlers, some militants,
some nature lovers and some loners.
</P>
<P>
   Using criteria that some in Israel found incomprehensible,
Defense officials recently decided that seven of the 42 were
actually legal extensions of existing settlements. They found seven
to be overtly illegal.
</P>
<P>
   And the remaining 28 were in the process of being legalized.
</P>
<P>
   They recommended that 15 be shut down: the seven overtly illegal
ones and eight that were either sparsely populated or isolated and
hard to protect.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who serves as his own defense minister, accepted the
recommendations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At first, this provoked a fierce reaction from all sides.
</P>
<P>
   An editorial in Ma'ariv, a leading tabloid, excoriated the prime
minister for ``laundering'' the 27 outposts that would be allowed
to remain open.
</P>
<P>
   From the right, Ariel Sharon, former foreign minister and head
of the opposition Likud Party, asserted that Barak must have made a
secret deal with Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the settlers, calling Barak's plan
``anti-Zionist,'' warned that they would fight every single
evacuation, while leftist leaders promised to respond with large
counterprotests.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday morning, however, after the compromise on evacuating
just 12 had been reached, plans to revive the old internal Israeli
battle over the West Bank had been suspended. After saying on
Wednesday that he wanted a ``civil rebellion, nonviolent for the
moment,'' Elyakim Haeztni, an outspoken longtime settler, said
Thursday, ``We won't get into a conflict over it.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sharon, after touring the West Bank, conceded that Barak had
accomplished much by avoiding a confrontation with the settlers.
</P>
<P>
   Neve Erez sits on a barren hilltop about 1,800 feet above sea
level, overlooking rippling hills, dun-colored now before the
winter rains start.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer, the heat got so intense that the residents cooled
one another down with water pistols.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's about our level of violence,'' said Amy Abels, 30, a
new immigrant from the Upper West Side of New York, who fingered a
visitor's shirt and asked, ``Is that Banana Republic?''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven free spirits, including several new immigrants who met in
Hebrew language school, the Neve Erez residents form a tightknit
collective. Some write, some paint, some make music, some study
scholarly Jewish texts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love each other very much, and we are very much in love
with this place,'' Maman said. ``It has a special rhythm and I
still hope we will not be removed. We're not bothering anyone. It's
not like there are Arabs around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Maman seemed oblivious to the Bedouin Druse tents just down the
hill, and said, ``Oh, true,'' when it was pointed out that an Arab
village could be clearly seen from his back porch.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fantasy is that all the governments butt out and we'd just
invite the Druse over for tea,'' Ms. Abels said.
</P>
<P>
   The land that Neve Erez occupies was slated to be a cemetery for
a nearby settlement, and, like ruins, tracks for the graves are
growing weeds.
</P>
<P>
   Even to the residents, it seemed a bit glaringly metaphorical
Thursday, as if it represented a burial place for the settlers'
dreams of expansion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
