<SLUG> BC-SPACEPORT-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS FRONT-RUNNER IN RACE FOR SPACEPORT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Calif.) 
 
By ANDREW BROMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Texas congressional delegation sent a letter
Thursday urging a space launch company to choose a Texas site for a
spaceport.
</P>
<P>
   An executive from the California-based Space Access Co. said
Friday that Texas is the front-runner, although obstacles remain
before a spaceport for reusable launch vehicles can move forward.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, Florida and California are vying to attract the fledgling
spaceport industry. At least three companies _ Lockheed Martin,
Kistler Aerospace and Space Access _ are making plans for possible
spaceports. Texas has presented two possible sites, one in Brazoria
County and another near Corpus Christi.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Texas congressional delegation wishes to express to you
our desire that the site for the spaceport be Texas,'' said the
letter to Steve Wurst, president of Space Access.
</P>
<P>
   Before Space Access can build, it must pass environmental
inspections and receive approval from the Federal Aviation
Administration to launch. But so far, Space Access likes the idea
of locating in Texas because the state offers takeoff routes over
the Gulf of Mexico and large amounts of sparsely populated land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas entered the game late as far as spaceports go, and
they've made up a lot of ground,'' said Michael Wade, a vice
president at Space Access. ``They are very energetic in making this
happen. If I had to say who was in the lead right now, I would have
to say Texas has a clear lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Gene Green, D-Houston, one of 23 lawmakers who signed the
letter to Space Access, said local tax breaks as well as federal
assistance will be key to luring space launch companies to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you look at the competition in other countries,
China, France and Russia, we have to be able to match that,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A bill introduced in the Senate would offer government-backed
loans to the space launch industry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
