<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8347 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BRAZILIAN-JAPANESE-78     10-15 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZILIAN-JAPANESE-785-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY BRAZILIANS OF JAPANESE DESCENT MIGRATING TO JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By SIMON ROMERO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ What urges someone like Nobotoshi Uski, a
41-year-old dentist whose grandparents emigrated to Brazil in an
exodus that formed the largest community of Japanese descendants
outside Japan, to reverse that trajectory and move to the homeland
of his ancestors?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of yen,'' said Uski as he waited in a winding line in
front of the Japan Airlines counter at Sao Paulo's international
airport, where he planned to board a midnight flight to Tokyo. Uski
said he hoped to earn the equivalent of $2,500 a month at a job
awaiting him at a Japanese auto parts factory, or about double what
he earned as a dentist in his home town about 200 miles west of Sao
Paulo.
</P>
<P>
   Uski will join an estimated 220,000 Brazilians who have moved,
at least temporarily, to Japan in the last decade. Coming almost
entirely from a Japanese-Brazilian community numbering 1.3 million,
many of these immigrants do work that is snubbed by the Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese-Brazilians began arriving in Japan in 1990 after Tokyo
eased its immigration laws to allow people of Japanese descent to
work in the country. They now form the third-largest immigrant
group in Japan, after Koreans and Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, in a trend that underscores the nascent recovery of
Japan, the world's second-largest economy, and the strengthening
yen, as well as the stagnating economy in Brazil, the rate at which
Brazilians are moving to Japan appears to be rising. While some of
these immigrants are merely replacing countrymen returning home to
celebrate the New Year with their families, there are abundant
signs of a stronger Japanese job market for Brazilians.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the pages of the Sao Paulo weekly newspaper Jornal
Nipo-Brasil are now full of help-wanted ads from the 100 or so
companies that serve as intermediaries for corporations in Japan
wanting to hire Brazilians. ``Minolta, Toyota, you name it,'' said
Ricardo Sumida, the owner of one go-between company with offices in
Liberdade, this city's Japanese district. ``They want more
Brazilians and were working overtime to find enough people.''
</P>
<P>
   Longer lines in front of the Japanese consulate's work-visa
section and in the waiting rooms for flights from Sao Paulo to
Tokyo also indicate an increase in the number of Brazilians moving
to Japan, said Sumida. Aid agencies that follow such immigration
have perceived a pick-up in interest as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be surprised if 40,000 Brazilians move to Japan in
the second half of this year, compared with 20,000 in the same
period of 1998,'' said Masato Ninomiya, president of the
Information and Aid Center for the Worker Abroad, a group based in
Sao Paulo and supported by the Japanese government.
</P>
<P>
   A Brazilian who moves to Japan is called a ``dekasegi,'' a word
that originally referred to sojourners from remote regions in Japan
who left their homes to work in urban factories, according to Raul
Takaki, the publisher of Nikkei Shimbun, one of Sao Paulo's two
Japanese-language daily newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the word `dekasegi' is used to describe a wide variety of
Brazilians, from the guy mopping the floor to the well-off kid
working for a few months at a ski resort,'' Takaki said.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the role dekasegis play in supplementing the
incomes of relatives back home has become as significant as that of
Mexicans laboring in the United States. Dekasegis sent home an
estimated $1.09 billion in the first half of this year, helping to
ease concern over the current account deficit, a wide measure of
foreign transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Some dekasegis also eventually return to Brazil to invest
savings in the purchase of their first home or in business
ventures. Ademir Kimura, for example, worked for seven years in
Japan before returning to his home city of Maringa in southern
Brazil to establish an Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   ``To become an entrepreneur I needed my own capital,'' Kimura,
31, said.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration to Japan is an escape valve for unemployment
pressure, with Brazilian joblessness near an all-time high and
inflation-adjusted wages in decline. ``I want my boys to have a
taste of what Brazil can't give them, which is opportunity,'' said
Keite Nakamura, 52, the owner of a small Brazilian construction
company. Nakamura accompanied his two sons, 18 and 21, to the
airport for their flight to a new life in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The planeloads of Brazilians heading to Japan reflect a somber
twist to a 91-year saga that has resulted in one of Brazil's most
successful immigrant groups. While the Japanese came to Brazil in
search of opportunity, many of their descendants, who are often
well-educated yet members of a struggling middle class, choose to
leave Brazil for economic reasons.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The first group came to Brazil in 1908 _ nearly 800 immigrants
who arrived on a boat named Kasato-Maru to work on the coffee
plantations, which were also attracting laborers from Italy, Spain
and elsewhere. Their arrival was partly a result of informal
policies in the United States that sought to limit the entry of
non-European immigrants. (These policies became law in the 1920s).
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan needed to alleviate population pressure, and with access
to the United States closed, the agricultural opportunities in
Brazil were the best alternative,'' said Karen Tei Yamashita, a
Japanese-American writer from California whose 1992 novel,
``Brazil-Maru,'' describes a group of Japanese who moved to Brazil
in the first decades of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the Japanese community grew larger than similar
communities in the United States and Peru, the other big South
American outpost. Although most Japanese immigrants to Brazil
started out as field hands or small farmers, many moved to cities
as the country was transformed from a rural to an urban society.
Most Japanese-Brazilians live in Sao Paulo and in the southern
state of Parana.
</P>
<P>
   In Sao Paulo's Japanese district, a neighborhood near the city's
crumbling city center, the streets are lined with sushi
restaurants, karaoke bars, Japanese grocery stores, newsstands with
Japanese publications and even a McDonald's, with menu items
written in Japanese as well as in Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the indelible mark the Japanese have made on Sao
Paulo's cityscape, they have influenced contemporary Brazilian
society as a whole. Japanese-Brazilians have been successful in
politics and business and in the arts. Modern Brazilian painting,
for instance, is largely defined by names like Manabu Mabe, Tomie
Ohtake and Flavio Shiro. Filmmaking, ceramics and architecture have
also been heavily influenced by Japanese-Brazilians.
</P>
<P>
   Still, though they have, as a group, integrated so much into
Brazilian society, their entry into Japanese culture is often not
smooth. Lili Kawamura, a Brazilian sociologist and visiting
researcher at Tsukuba University who has written a book on the
dekasegis, said the culture clash could be immense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although our appearances are so similar, there is little
contact between the groups,'' said Ms. Kawamura. ``Brazilians end
up creating their own peripheral economy within Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Many dekasegis who have gone to Japan and returned to Brazil
said their relations with the Japanese were strained. Some
dekasegis said the resentment in part reflects the insularity and
homogeneity of Japanese society, which historically has viewed
outsiders _ including descendants of Japanese emigrants _ with some
suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I had `dekasegi' written on my forehead, but
when I opened my mouth and the Japanese noticed my accent, I was
treated as second-rate,'' said Clarice Onaka, 40, a professor of
Brazilian literature who returned to Sao Paulo last year after
eight years of factory work in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you expect when the jobs we do there are described by
the three k's?,'' said Ms. Onaka _ ``kitsui,'' ``kitanai'' and
``kiken,'' the Japanese words for ``hard,'' ``dirty'' and
``dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Jeffrey Lesser, a professor at Connecticut College
who has studied Brazilian immigration to Japan, these feelings of
alienation are exacerbated by Japanese policies that make it
extremely hard for descendants of Japanese born abroad to attain
citizenship. Though many dekasegis who move to Japan remain there,
he added, they do so first on work visas and then on permanent
visas.
</P>
<P>
   Still, while many Brazilians complain of discrimination in
Japan, others, like Joe Hirata, chalk up their success to their
experiences on the archipelago.
</P>
<P>
   Hirata, 31, worked for several years in factories in Okinawa and
Nagoya while also pursuing a career as a country music singer. In
1994, he won the televised NHK Nodogiman contest, singing romantic
ballads in the Japanese he had polished.
</P>
<P>
   Hirata went on to record a CD back in Brazil, ``Sonho de um
Brasileiro,'' or ``Dream of a Brazilian,'' and now divides his time
between Japan and Brazil, singing tunes that evoke rural life and
lost loves, the mainstay of Brazilian ``sertaneja'' music, itself
heavily influence by American country music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan took me in and treated me well,'' said Hirata, whose
everyday attire includes a suede cowboy hat, striped leather pants
and snakeskin boots. ``I learned there that success comes from
being true to who you are and that I'm far more Brazilian than
Japanese.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1931EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8349 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY16-COX     10-15 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    House panel to keep pressure on IOC
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One day after a heated Congressional hearing on the
Olympic bribery scandal, the panel's chairman said he and other
lawmakers would keep up the pressure on the International Olympic
Committee to reform its process for selecting host cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message I think was certainly received that if they back
away from these reforms, we are going to act pretty swiftly,'' said
Rep. Fred Upton (R-Mich.), chairman of the House Commerce
subcommittee on oversight and investigations. ``We are going to be
staying on top of them. Our effort is not to trash the Olympics. We
want to clean it up.''
</P>
<P>
   As Thursday's hearing on Capitol Hill indicated, there is
widespread bipartisan concern about the culture of greed and
corruption that has consumed the Olympic movement. Despite
assurances from IOC officials, few on Upton's panel think the IOC
will clean up its act without a vigilant Congress overseeing the
process.
</P>
<P>
   Upton's subcommittee has been examining the extensive gifts and
favors provided IOC members during Atlanta's winning bid for the
1996 Summer Games. Panel members submitted Atlanta Olympic
officials Billy Payne and Andy Young to pointed questions about
lavish travel, medical care, scholarship offers and potentially
illegal accommodations they provided IOC members and their
families.
</P>
<P>
   After the daylong hearing, the members had more questions for
Payne and Young. They plan to submit them in writing and they
expect quick responses, Upton said.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Congress intends to put the Atlanta bid
activities behind it and is concentrating on the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The period of discovery is over,'' said Upton, who believes a
report documenting Atlanta's bid activities and comments by Payne
and Young at the hearing provided the necessary evidence of
widespread corruption of the host city selection process.
</P>
<P>
   If the IOC has not enacted sweeping reforms of the process and
its organization by the end of the year, Congress will not hesitate
to act, Upton said.
</P>
<P>
   While it has no jurisdiction over the IOC, Congress could
cripple the organization by putting its cash cow _ U.S.
corporations and television networks _ out to pasture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the cutoff of American corporate money will get the IOC's
attention,'' said Rep. Henry Waxman (D-Calif.), who has proposed
legislation, co-sponsored by Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), prohibiting
U.S. corporations from financially supporting the Olympics if the
IOC rejects reforms proposed by an independent ethics commission
headed by former Sen. George Mitchell (D-Maine).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced if the IOC does not adopt those Mitchell reforms
in December, the Congress is not going to have any patience any
longer to leave the IOC to reform itself,'' Waxman said at the
hearing
</P>
<P>
   The two IOC members from the United States, Jim Easton and Anita
DeFrantz, did not endorse congressional action. In fact, Easton was
flippant when asked by Waxman if he thought Congress should
intervene.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we wish to pass a bill that no Americans can participate in
the Olympic Games, that would solve the problems also,'' he said,
``But I don't think that's what we want to do. What we want to do
is try to reform what we have. I think we are headed in that
direction and I don't think we need any other incentives to do
so.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a really insulting answer,'' Waxman shot back, an
indication of the antagonistic atmosphere during the hearing. ``We
don't do anything that would affect the athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would simply eliminate the revenue from U.S.
corporations ``that is subsidizing the lifestyle of Mr. (Juan
Antonio) Samaranch and some of the others at the IOC in addition to
the booty that they collect every time a city wants to attract the
Olympics,'' Waxman snapped.
</P>
<P>
   Although IOC President Samaranch was spared what would surely
have been a hostile attack had he attended the hearing, he plans to
attend a second hearing Dec. 15, two days after a special IOC
session at which reforms will be put to a vote. Former Sen. Howard
Baker (R-Tenn.), who serves on the IOC's new ethics commission,
also will be called, Upton said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the IOC adopts reforms at its meeting in Lausanne,
Switzerland, Upton still wants to summon Samaranch to Washington
for assurances that the IOC will enforce the policies. ``You can
have the standards, but if you don't have the enforcement
mechanism, it doesn't work,'' Upton said.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, U.S. Olympic Committee President Bill Hybl, a
member of the IOC's reform commission, said there is a ``little
better than a 50 percent chance'' of all recommendations passing.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch told The Associated Press on Friday that he thought
the odds were better. ``I am very confident that the most important
recommendations will pass,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that pressure from Congress will have no impact on the
fate of reforms. ``I don't like to enter into what the Congress is
thinking,'' Samaranch said. ``I have to take care only of the
IOC.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
