<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8353 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BASEBALL-FINANCE-BOS &LR;      10-15 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-FINANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG GAMES, LITTLE IMMEDIATE FINANCIAL PAYOFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is a major event in Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Red Sox versus the New York Yankees, arguably the
greatest rivalry in the long history of the game, is being played
out in a best-of-seven-game series for the American League pennant.
And yet the Red Sox face the possibility of making only a couple of
million dollars from the postseason appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, the revenues are not likely to be significant,'' said
Robert C. Furbush, chief financial officer of the Red Sox. ``I
would hestitate to say that it would make the difference between
making a profit and not making a profit this year.''
</P>
<P>
   In an odd twist, determined by the economics of Major League
Baseball, franchises that play in postseason stand to make
comparatively small amounts of money directly from the highly
anticipated, much-watched games. The postseason instead presents a
remarkable marketing opportunity in their pursuit of future
season-ticket customers, corporate sponsors and advertisers. It
also enhances their bargaining positions for the next round of
broadcast negotiations, a singularly important piece of the revenue
pie for sports franchises.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps most importantly to the Red Sox, success in the
postseason in the major sports has often proven to help franchises
in their efforts to building new stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   The major reasons for the revenue that will trickle into the Red
Sox front office is that most of the money from gate receipts goes
directly to the players, Major League Baseball and the American and
National Leagues.
</P>
<P>
   By agreement with the Major League Baseball Players Association,
60 percent of gate receipts from the first three games of the
best-of-five divisional series and the first four games of the
league series and the World Series benefits the players alone. In
1998, that pool of money was at an all-time high of $39.3 million,
up from $23.4 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The money is then divided among the teams with specific portions
going to participants in the World Series, the League Championship
Series and the Divisional Series, based on whether they win or
lose. The players on the individual teams then vote on each
player's share of the purse.
</P>
<P>
   Of the remaining gate receipts _ the 40 percent for the first
three or four games, depending on the series; and all of the
receipts from any additional games that are played _ most is
distributed to the offices of Major League Baseball, in the case of
the World Series, or the American League and the National League
offices, in the League Championship and Divisional Series.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there also is no extra money from the national
broadcasting contracts for teams that play in postseason, officials
of Major League Baseball said. And the Red Sox, like most teams in
the major leagues, charge no extra fees in the postseason for
corporate sponsorships, stadium advertising or the rental fees on
premium seating, Furbush said.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves teams like the Red Sox to make most of its revenue
in postseason from the residual gate receipts and concessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much a team makes depends almost entirely on whether you
go deep in to postseason, and then continue to play after Game 4 of
the World Series,'' said Andrew Zimbalist, a sports economist and
professor at Smith College.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that the Red Sox, if they go deep in the league
championship series with the Yankees, win, and then go deep again
in the World Series _ and given that they play in Fenway Park _ are
in the $6 million to $8 million range,'' Zimbalist said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Sox are eliminated by the Yankees, and in fairly quick
order, chances are the club will have trouble clearing $2 million,
observers said.
</P>
<P>
   Furbush and other Red Sox officials refused to discuss details
of the teams financial status, in postseason or otherwise. But CEO
John Harrigton recently told the Globe that the Red Sox lost money
this year and, without commenting directly, Furbush indicated that
even in if the Red Sox play deeply into the postseason the
franchise may still not turn a profit.
</P>
<P>
   But for a team that many observers thought would not play in
postseason at all, the Red Sox surprising success may well pay
dividends of a different sort, observers said.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the impact on the Red Sox' big ticket item _
the proposed new Fenway Park. The Red Sox, success in the
postseason in the major sports has proven to be a magical elixir
for teams proposing to build new stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it makes a huge difference to a team talking about
building a ballpark, because there is such a positive environment
when a team does well in the playoffs _ especially when it is
exceeding expectations, like the Red Sox clearly are doing this
year,'' said Marc Ganis, a consultant with SportsCorp Ltd. in
Chicago. ``Those things are not lost on either the fans, the press
or the politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres and the Seattle Mariners recently received
approval for stadium plans and public financing after successful
appearances in the postseason, said Mark Rosentraub, a professor at
Indiana University and author of a book on the business of
baseball. It works in other sports, too, Rosentraub said, with the
Denver Broncos building a new stadium after their win in the Super
Bowl and the San Antonio Spurs dramatically increasing their
chances for a new stadium after winning the NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   But Red Sox officials and their spokesmen were reticent to claim
any greater support for the stadium proposal, based on the success
of the team, and some of the notable government officials involved
asserted that success on the field will not play a substantive
role.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great, all of the excitement that it's producing and
it's a lot of enjoyment,'' said Mayor Thomas Menino. ``But the
stadium is going to come down to their financial plan and how they
treat the community. That's what's going to decide this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1938EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
