<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8354 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-LOWES16-COX     10-15 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOWES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lowe's issues Internet challenge
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lowe's Cos. is beefing up the troops to go
head-to-head with Home Depot in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkesboro, N.C.-based Lowe's said Friday it will hire nearly 40
people for a separate Internet business group. That will quadruple
the staff dedicated to www.lowes.com and match the size of the
Internet team at Atlanta-based Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's already sells a limited number of products through links
to other Web sites. Both Lowe's and Home Depot have company sites
that provide do-it-yourself home improvement tips.
</P>
<P>
   Retail sales on those primary company sites won't come until
next year. Both companies have delayed original plans as they
grapple with the challenges of electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Home Depot said it was pushing back its debut by
several months because of a major shift in strategy. Instead of
testing limited sales, which would have begun this fall, the
retailer plans to offer its entire inventory of more than 50,000
products on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's seems to be taking the opposite tact. It plans to offer
6,000 to 8,000 products on its site next year, then gradually add
more items.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have been selling over the Web site next month with a
catalog-based offering,'' said Greg Bridgeford, senior vice
president of business development at Lowe's. But as the company
prepared to offer its inventory over the Internet, executives
decided a ``solution-based'' approach made more sense, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, some product sales on lowes.com will match the
retailer's existing ``how-to'' information on 1,000 current Web
pages. Shoppers could opt to buy a project kit or pay to have
Lowe's install it, Bridgeford said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Lowe's products on the Web will be targeted to specific
customer groups, such as contractors or ``serious
do-it-yourselfers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's expects to start selling products during the first half
of next year. The company started selling certain tools, ceiling
fans and steel doors through manufacturer Web sites last year.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot has let its rivals get the jump on it when it comes
to online sales. Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. and regional retailers such
as 84 Lumber and Scotty's have launched online sales. A slew of
pure Internet companies dealing in hardware and building products
have popped up as well.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry observers are wondering whether Home Depot is
taking too long to execute its game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every delay in getting a ... product-selling site up and
running gives all the many new retailers a better chance of
building customer lists and gaining name recognition,'' said a
recent editorial in National Home Center News.
</P>
<P>
   ``What should have been a slam dunk for Home Depot is beginning
to look like a wild and competitive game now,'' the editorial said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, at least one recent report suggests that the
do-it-yourself market is not as frenzied for Web sales as other
sectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most DIYers consider themselves novices, not pros, and
therefore need the comfort of seeing the product before taking it
home,'' said analyst Dan Wewer of Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown.
Customers mainly want to use the Home Depot and Lowe's Web sites
for advice, not to shop, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot declined to elaborate on its strategy Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The company's Internet plans have gotten a lot of attention,
particularly after it warned suppliers not to sell directly to
customers through their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeford of Lowe's said none of its suppliers plans to sell
products over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
