</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AGENDA17-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   PRESIDENT'S AGENDA THREATENED BY TENUOUS RELATIONS WITH CONGRESS
</P>
<P>
   With Sidebar: Clinton-Data
</P>
<P>
   Moving on Washington (w) and Political (P) categories
</P>
<P>
   By Bob Deans
</P>
<P>
   Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After accusing his Republican foes on Capitol Hill
of turning their backs on the rest of the world, undermining the
national economy and attacking the nation's teachers, police,
environment and the poor, President Clinton suddenly shifted gears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to work with Congress,'' Clinton said Thursday,
standing beneath the crystal East Room chandeliers during an
hourlong White House press conference. ``We can put an end to
reckless partisanship, to gimmicks and gamesmanship.''
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes Clinton's political nemesis, Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., called his own press conference on
Capitol Hill. Not only are he and Clinton not working together,
Lott stressed, they're not even speaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I talked to the president about the budget and
the appropriations bills was the middle of July,'' Lott fumed.
``Hadn't had a single call from him, not any contact, no
suggestions, other than a few missiles fired over from the White
House.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the state of relations these days between the respective
banner carriers of the Democratic and Republican parties and, of
more immediate import, between the president and the Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's acrimonious,'' said presidential scholar Wayne Steger.
</P>
<P>
   ``My big question is, 'Are they ever going to, as long as
Clinton is in the White House, be able to work together and
compromise,''' wonders Steger, a political science professor at
Chicago's DePaul University in Chicago. ``I'm not sure that's going
to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It's increasingly unlikely to happen in the week ahead. Next
Thursday is the latest deadline set for Clinton and the Congress to
complete work on the discretionary spending bills guiding the $1.8
trillion federal budget for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   That work should have been finished by the start of the fiscal
year, Oct. 1. After extending the deadline for three weeks, Clinton
is expected to sign another temporary spending measure, called a
continuing resolution, to keep the government hobbling along for
another week or so in the hope that the White House and the
Congress might finally come to terms.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing particularly new about partisan confrontation.
The annual budget wrangling makes fights between the White House
and the Capitol something of a rite of autumn. And politicians from
both parties are busy hardening their positions as part of the
posturing that precedes every presidential election year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, to watch Clinton and the GOP-controlled Congress face off
and fall out utterly over issues ranging from tax cuts to health
care, from judicial nominations to the fate of the world's nuclear
non-proliferation efforts in the short space of several weeks is to
wonder what chance there is for the sort of comity and compromise
generally thought to form the heart and soul of politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just no give and take, there's no willingness to sort
of bend the other guy's way at all,'' said political science
professor Cary Covington of the University of Iowa in Iowa City.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly two terms of idealogical bickering hardened by the
polarizing impact of the Monica Lewinsky scandal, said Covington,
``The president's just worn out his welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the executive and legislative branches aren't
completed paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly half of the 13 spending bills for 2000 have made their
way to the White House, and been signed, even as Clinton vetoed the
centerpiece of the Republican budget agenda: a $792-billion tax
cut.
</P>
<P>
   The core of Clinton's so-called ''patients' bill of rights,''
strengthening consumers' hand in dealing with health maintainence
organizations, has passed the House. Though the White House remains
unsatisfied with a similar Senate version, there's room for
possible compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Lott promised Friday to move expeditiously toward a vote on a
pair of low-bore trade bills aimed at boosting U.S. commerce with
impoverished African and Caribbean states.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton insists his door is open to Republicans willing to
sit down and negotiate tax and budget priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president wants to get things done,'' said White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart. ``He is not someone who relishes
confrontation. He relishes cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, seven years of bitter fighting over policies,
priorities and personalities have left Clinton and the Congress all
but immobilized on a host of bigger picture issues ranging from
Social Security and Medicare reform to tobacco tax hikes and
teacher hires.
</P>
<P>
   The situation threatens to leave Clinton, with 15 months left in
the White House, as a classic lame duck: unable to work with
Congress enough to advance his centrist agenda in the twilight of
his term.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts cite several reasons for the malaise.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and Republicans alike appear in recent years to have
migrated away from the sort of centerline policies and attitudes
that foster compromise. That trend has been accentuated by the
onset of presidential politicking, Steger said, as leaders in both
parties begin to perceive greater gains from sticking to their guns
than from the sort of split-the-difference horse trading required
to get things done in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   And so, when Clinton said last month he was willing to go along
with up to $300 billion in tax cuts _ a good reason to believe he
might be persuaded to accept slightly more _ Republicans decided it
would be better to stiff the president and force him to veto their
larger package, a move that's certain to feature prominently in
next year's Republican campaign ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can't get what they want,'' Steger said, ``at least
they can score points with their Republican constituencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two years, though, there's been something more to
the equation than politics.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton looks down Pennsylvania Avenue toward Capitol Hill,
he's facing 223 Republicans in the House and another 50 in the
Senate who voted to remove him from office. The House prevailed,
forcing him to go down in history as only the second president in
the history of the republic to be impeached, while the Senate
narrowly acquited on a distinctly party-line vote.
</P>
<P>
   Despite public appeals from both sides to move on, Clinton
remains mindful of those who threw a spear at the king, just as his
opponents can't forget how narrowly he slipped the noose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their ability to speak and be civil and polite and sympathetic
and listen to each other, thahas to have been compromised by
this experience,'' said Covington, an expert on
presidential-congressional relations. ``Their willingess to give
this president any benefit of the doubt appears unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
