<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Saturday,
Oct. 16. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   ACCRED: Missouri joins a growing number of states to intervene
in struggling urban school districts. So far, such efforts have
produced mixed results. While the intervention helps ensure that
the districts clean up their finances, fix their buildings and
eliminate favoritism in hiring, there's not a lot of evidence that
yanking accreditation does anything to improve what's going on in
the classroom, according to various studies and education experts.
We share the experience of cities that have been through this, such
as Cleveland, Jersey City and Newark. We also touch on whether the
loss of accreditation by Missouri's two largest districts will harm
economic development and the state's efforts to rank among the top
public school systems in the nation by 2010. Photos, graphic. Phil
O'Connor, Kevin Hoffmann, Will Sentell. 35.
</P>
<P>
   AMBER: On Tuesday, the day Pamela Butler was abducted from her
Kansas City, Kan., neighborhood, a stack of paperwork sat on a
Kansas City police official's desk. The papers are for a new
program designed to get the word out immediately when a child has
been abducted. The program, started in Texas, should begin here
soon. But experience shows the program isn't perfect. Mary Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   ABDUCT (with AMBER). The search for Pamela Butler continues in
the Kansas City area. Ann Lamoy, Richard Espinoza, Stacy Downs.
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   Other sidebars pending.
</P>
<P>
   DANCE: Homecoming at William Jewell College has never included a
dance on campus before, a taboo left over from the Baptist heritage
that condemned dancing as a sin, right along with drinking,
swearing and gambling. Until now. ``The time has come that the
prohibition, whether official or unofficial, ends,'' one alumnus
said. There will be a dance this Saturday night. Lynn Franey. 15.
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   GIRL: Tipper Gore and Lesley Stahl once wore green and on Friday
they tell the national Girl Scouts convention what they got from
the experience. Photo. Donna McGuire.
</P>
<P>
   MAT. Governor's press secretary moves to the Kansas Board of
Regents, where he will be paid $26,000 a year more than the woman
he is replacing; he will take on extra responsibilities, but this
comes the same week a woman sued the regents, alleging that she was
paid less than her male counterparts and was demoted in a
reorganization. Diane Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
