<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPS-RESULTS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPS earnings up 28% in third quarter
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ United Parcel Service reported a 28.5 percent increase
in third-quarter earnings, helped by a strong U.S. economy and
improving conditions overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's earnings announcement would be the last as a private
company for UPS, assuming shareholders approve a plan to go public.
Shareholders, most of whom are employees, will vote on the issue
Oct. 25 in Wilmington, Del.
</P>
<P>
   UPS expects to complete its planned public stock offering in
November if shareholders give it the green light, said spokesman
Norman Black.
</P>
<P>
   The Sandy Springs-based package delivery company earned $577
million, or $1.03 a share, in the three months that ended Sept. 30.
A year ago, UPS earned $449 million, or 81 cents a share. Revenue
rose 9 percent to $6.72 billion in the latest quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The company's domestic package delivery had operating profit of
$879 million in the third quarter, up 16.1 percent. The company
defines operating profit as revenue less operating costs, and
excluding interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization.
</P>
<P>
   International operations produced an operating profit of $38
million, against a loss of $15 million a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europe and Asia had a very strong quarter,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   Like competitor Federal Express, which reported its results last
month, UPS noted increasing fuel costs. Those costs rose $32
million, or 22.5 percent, in the latest third quarter, UPS said.
For the first nine months, fuel costs are up a lesser amount, by
$24 million, or 5.4 percent, the company added.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
