<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX HOPES TO NET TICKET SCALPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Red Sox were busy surfing the Internet on Friday. By the
time they were finished looking for what they wanted, a whole lot
of season tickets-holders figure to be caught in a ``net.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who has resold even a single ticket to these playoffs,
will have their season tickets taken away permanently,'' said Sox
public relations director Kevin Shea, passing on the direct word of
Sox CEO John Harrington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our staff is going through the Internet right now,'' said
Shea, adding, ``and Major League Baseball is conducting its own
investigation. We are well aware of what has been going on, and we
are going to take the appropriate action.''
</P>
<P>
   Ticket scalping, in the guise of an auction, is what is going
on.
</P>
<P>
   The search by the Red Sox and MLB center on eBay, an Internet
auction site, which first started to gain attention Thursday when
four tickets to Saturday's classic matchup between Pedro Martinez
and Roger Clemens in Game 3 of the American League Championship
Series sold for $12,100.
</P>
<P>
   The tickets are in Field Box 34, Row K, Seats 1-4. If you own
those tickets. . . you don't anymore. These are prime seats,
located 10 rows back from the field between home plate and the Red
Sox dugout. The person that owns those seats as season
ticket-holders will lose them. The person that sold the seats will
also come under the scrutiny of the Internal Revenue Service, who
will be looking to collect taxes on the profit made by the seller.
The face value of the four tickets is $260, which means the seller
has realized a profit of $11,840.
</P>
<P>
   This is not just a random sale. As of Friday afternoon, there
were 86 people trying to ``scalp,'' sell for a profit, tickets to
this Red Sox-Yankee series in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Someone going under the name of ``boston-baseball-bob'' sold the
tickets to a doctor named ``Neil Pearson.'' The doctor should have
his head examined because no one else is bidding anywhere near what
he did, and there are tickets available all over eBay. Also, on the
street in Boston Friday, good seats were going for $1,500 each.
</P>
<P>
   One seller, looking for $4,400 for two tickets to Saturday's
game, couldn't get a single bid on eBay. While the top bid for
another set of two tickets was up to just $630, or $315 each. The
good doctor, paid at the rate of $3,025 per ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these tickets for sale, of the 86 listed, had no
bidders. The highest number of bidders on any set of tickets was
28. The price for four tickets to Sunday's game at Fenway, was up
to $1,025 dollars, with 15 people in the bidding.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox' policy under Harrington has been that anyone
selling tickets for profit would lose those seats. It was the same
notice sent to all season ticket-holders during the All-Star Game
in Boston in July.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox do not have control over all of the postseason
tickets. The American League office distributes tickets to each
team in the league, league officials, television and radio
advertisers, etc. This is why MLB security is also involved, to see
if anyone involved with the league, or teams in the league, has
been scalping tickets through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox late Friday afternoon were also considering removing
anyone from the ballpark who had purchased a scalped ticket. They
were garnering this information from the Internet, where you could
punch into the seller's account and get the exact location of the
ticket. The Red Sox were recording all of the seats by section, row
and seat number, and then researching their records to see who
those seats belonged to. If it turns out that they belonged to a
season ticket-holder, they will not be a season ticket-holder any
longer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, who have the same policy, said Friday they would
investigate their tickets being sold on the Internet. There were 34
Patriot sales available on eBay, and almost all of them for home
games. Dallas, Denver, and the Jets were the hot games remaining on
the Patriots' schedule. A top Patriots official said Friday night
that the team was investigating, and will pull the tickets from any
season ticket-holder found to be selling the tickets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This little story should tell you what kind of a guy Wilt
Chamberlain was. The Globe's Bob Duffy was doing a story with Wilt
about coming to the Bill Russell tribute in May, where the people
putting on the show wanted to fly Wilt in via a private jet that
would have cost $25,000. Wilt turned it down, saying he would pay
his own way because the event was for charity. And he did.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bates, who was the Patriots' trainer for years, starting in
1961, was close to Wilt when they were young. Bates was a Philly
guy, who knew Wilt through high school, college, and later as a
trainer with the Warriors, who changed their name to the 76ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilt was a nice guy,'' said Bates, who like everyone else that
knew him, was stunned with the news of Wilt's sudden death Tuesday.
``His death is surprising because he always kept himself in good
shape. When he was younger, he was a shy guy, but once he was in
the dressing room, he was very much one of the guys kidding around
with the other players. One year he won the MVP trophy in the
league (NBA) and he got a Volkswagen. Imagine that, 7-2, 300
pounds, a Volkswagen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was working the game he scored 100 points in Hershey (Pa.).
When there was games in Hershey, I worked with the visiting team,
the Knicks that night. The arena had a lot to do with it. We played
in the Hershey Park Arena, and I remember the rims being loose. A
lot of guys on both sides scored big numbers in that game. Wilt got
59 in the second half. They couldn't stop him. When he made up his
mind to go to the basket, that was it. But he loved that fadeway
jump shot, and the teams we played loved him to take it. He could
do anything but shoot fouls. One day after practice I bet him $5
dollars I could beat him shooting fouls. He got 5 of 10. I got 8 of
10. When it was all over, Dolph Schayes, who was the coach at the
time, came over to me and says, `Bill, would you mind not beating
our star player shooting fouls? It doesn't do any good for his
confidence.' I remember one year, Guy Rodgers, who used to lead the
league in assists, telling Wilt he didn't pass the ball enough. So
Wilt led the league in assits the next year (1967-68).
</P>
<P>
   ``He never got the credit he deserved. Someone told me that
Michael Jordan holds three NBA records, and Wilt holds 58. If he
had the players around him, that Russell had in Boston, Wilt would
have won all those championships.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Russell, he left Boston and working with the Celtics
to attend Wilt's funeral. It is nice that they patched up the
friendship before Wilt died. Wilt was mad at Russell after Bill
knocked him for not finishing the seventh game of the championship
series vs. Boston in 1969. The Celtics beat the Lakers, and Wilt,
injuring his knee, couldn't play the closing minutes of the game.
Russell critized Wilt for that and Chamberlain wouldn't talk to him
for years.
</P>
<P>
   Russell went to lunch with Antoine Walker while he was here,
talking about a commitment to winning and how to make the team, and
his teammates, better. Russell said he asked Walker to lunch
because he wanted to go with a millionaire, in a millionaire's car.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the town fathers of Foxborough think they have the Patriots
trapped, they are making one huge mistake. The Patriots/NFL weren't
just talking the other day when they said if the access road they
are looking for is voted down, there will not be a new stadum in
Foxborough. That's the deal. It won't happen. Some in Foxborough
feel they can vote in a stadium without the access road, and that's
good enough, but they are wrong. The league is already mad because
it thought this entire deal would be finished by now, and a new
stadium would be under construction and ready for the 2001 season.
That won't happen now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago, 90 percent of the players in the NFL were
Canadian-born. In 1990, the number was 72 percent. Now it is down
to 56 percent. Oh Canada.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Plain Dealer came up with these numbers on
football coach John Cooper's new contract at Ohio State: $300,000
base pay; $450,000 TV show; $310,000 from Nike; $40,000 extra for a
bowl bid; $25,000 for radio show; $10,000 for a speaking
appearance; $5,000 for a summer football camp.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have run the ball 127 times this season. Of those,
only 13 have gone to the right. And Drew Bledsoe throws more to his
right than he does over the middle or to the left combined.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With remnants of Hurricane Irene hitting parts of Florida, the
Dolphins practiced in a torrential downpour Friday, and considered
leaving a day early for Sunday's game for fear local airports might
be shut down Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In just one week after being awarded an expansion franchise,
Houston has orders for 41,000 season tickets and 240 corporate
suits. In that period of time, the team had 2 million hits on their
Web site about buying tickets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox are trying to reverse they curse. They're bringing
back David Wells as the modern Bambino. Wells, former Yankee and
present Blue Jay and idolizer of Babe Ruth, will be a special guest
of the Red Sox at Saturday's game. The Yankees want to honor him
for his perfect game last year.
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
