<HEADLINE>
NOTHING MINOR ABOUT MOUNT UNION'S SHOT AT SUPPLANTING SOONERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
Nothing minor about Mount Union's shot at supplanting Sooners
<TEXT>
<P>
   Either way, Otterbein College will be part of history today. The
Cardinals will either be the team that ends Mount Union's winning
streak. Or they will be the Purple Raiders' 48th consecutive
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Union's 47-game streak equals Oklahoma's in the 1950s for
the longest streak in college football history.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Otterbein plays at Mount Union. For the home team, it's a
chance to make history. For the visitors, it's a chance to simply
assert themselves as a team to be reckoned with in the Ohio
Athletic Conference. The Cardinals (4-1, 3-1 overall) haven't had a
winning season since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``We happen to be playing Mount Union by the luck of the draw,''
Otterbein coach Wally Hood said. ``We just happened to be the team
sitting here, playing this team at this time when they're trying to
set a record. For us, the record doesn't mean a thing. Fifty years
from today, kids will be able to say they played in that game, win
or lose. But for us, it's a game that could put us in first place
in the Ohio Athletic Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we beat Mount Union, we're tied for first with destiny in
our hands. Our goal for 1999 was to have the best record at the
school in the last 16 years. We're not trying to win a game to stop
a streak. We're trying to win to be No. 1 in our conference.''
</P>
<P>
   The Purple Raiders have won the past three NCAA Division III
national championships. They have become a small-school power. And
with that comes the Bull's Eye Syndrome. Everybody is gunning to
end the streak. Two weeks ago, John Carroll, also an Ohio Athletic
Conference school, nearly did the deed. Mount Union needed three
overtimes to survive and continue the winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never feared losing a game,'' Mount Union coach Larry
Kehres said. ``We have feared losing ground in the conference race,
because winning the title leads to so many other good things, such
as getting into the national playoffs. But we overcome fear
associated with losing by teaching our players to be consistent and
poised.''
</P>
<P>
   Otterbein will be no pushover. Mount Union is leading Division
III in total offense (587 yards per game) and scoring (55 points
per game), but the Cardinals are 13th in total offense and are
averaging 36 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otterbein's an up-and-coming team in our league,'' Kehres
said. ``They've had a couple of big victories and a close loss
\R27-24 to John Carroll\S, and are a team that is confident they
can beat us. We've talked to our players about how difficult
Otterbein will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this isn't that big a deal. There are those who say this
is a major-league/minor-league comparison. That it is unfair to
compare Oklahoma's 47-game winning streak against major-college
competition to Mount Union's 47-game winning streak against
small-college teams.
</P>
<P>
   Hood doesn't buy that argument. A winning streak of that length,
in any sport, against any competition, is an outstanding
accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you understand how good they've been it's amazing,'' he
said. ``But if you understand Mount Union's program, it's not that
amazing. Success breeds success at this level. This league is as
good as any in the country at Division III.''
</P>
<P>
   If Mount Union wins today and closes out the season with its
fourth consecutive Division III title, its winning streak will be
at 56, the same as Joe DiMaggio's hitting streak _ another record
that might never be broken. If the Purple Raiders lose, they will
have equaled a record most thought was unreachable.
</P>
<P>
   After Oklahoma's 47-game streak ended with a 7-0 loss to Notre
Dame in 1957, Sooners coach Bud Wilkinson told his team: ``This is
a record that will never be broken by a major-college team. The
only ones who never lose are the ones who never play.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the level of competition.
</P>
<P>
   LOTS OF VICK'S OFFENSE IS HOKIES' PRESCRIPTION
</P>
<P>
   When No. 16 Syracuse plays at No. 4 Virginia Tech today in a
crucial Big East Conference game, the Orangemen will be facing
redshirt freshman quarterback Michael Vick for the first time. But
Vick should look familiar. He's being compared to former Syracuse
quarterback Donovan McNabb, who was a four-year starter and a
dangerous run-pass, pass-run threat.
</P>
<P>
   Vick had been the missing piece in the Hokies' offense. With
running back Shyrone Stith (116 yards rushing per game) and a
receiving duo of Andre Davis and Ricky Hall, Virginia Tech needed a
trigger man. Last season, the team used three quarterbacks _
including a converted safety _ and relied on defense and special
teams play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's good enough right now to be in the Heisman Trophy race,''
Virginia Tech defensive end Corey Moore said. ``In my opinion he'll
be a Heisman Trophy winner in the next year or two.''
</P>
<P>
   Vick, a 6-foot-1, 211-pounder, has made the difference with his
ability to run and throw. He is completing 67 percent of his
passes, has thrown for five touchdowns and has rushed for 203
yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so doggone happy to see McNabb graduate,'' West
Virginia's Don Nehlen said. ``But this guy Vick looks even better;
throws like a rocket.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech is 4-0 and is in position to have a shot at the
national championship. Syracuse's only loss came at home to
Michigan. This will be the Hokies' first big test. Last season, the
Hokies lost at Syracuse on a last-minute touchdown pass by ...
McNabb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defensively, they're so good,'' Virginia Tech coach Frank
Beamer said of Syracuse. ``We had a hard time moving the ball last
year, and it's going to be tough this year. Michael Vick is coming
along quickly; he's making better decisions and consistently doing
it, but I think he's going to have to make them faster this week.`'
</P>
<P>
   Vick's mother, Brenda Boddie, wanted her son to attend Syracuse
and become the next Donovan McNabb. Vick, instead, chose Virginia
Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to be the next anyone,'' Vick said.
SIZE MATTERS
</P>
<P>
   When Wake Forest plays Florida State today, it will match one of
the nation's smallest schools against a perennial football
powerhouse. Wake Forest's enrollment is listed at 3,600; Florida
State's is 30,200. This week, one of the Demon Deacons' players
voiced his displeasure at playing the top-ranked Seminoles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything about them irritates me,'' Wake Forest linebacker
Dustin Lyman said. ``They could never possibly understand what it's
like to be like most other teams in the country, having to scratch
and claw for everything they get.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way they play their games, they have little respect for
their opponents. They'll be doing halfback passes on their own
5-yard line. That kind of arrogance is, obviously, fun for them.''
TWO-WAY STREET
</P>
<P>
   Two coaches, two approaches, one game.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State coach Joe Paterno decided to limit to three the
number of Nittany Lions who could meet with the media this week.
No. 2 Penn State (6-0, 2-0) will be playing host to Ohio State in a
key Big Ten Conference game. Paterno, perhaps is beginning to tire
of his team's status and the media attention that draws.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ohio State coach John Cooper doesn't seem to have
much faith in his Buckeyes, who are 4-2, 1-1 and nearly
two-touchdown underdogs to the Nittany Lions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can win the football game, but I think we have to
play far and away the best ballgame we've played so far this year
and probably have to have a little bit of help from Penn State
along the way,'' Cooper said. ``It's pretty obvious if we play our
best game and they play their best game and neither team makes any
mistakes, they'll probably win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper often has riled Buckeyes fans with his honest assessments
of his team. And this week, his players didn't particularly
appreciate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's a fair assessment,'' wide receiver Reggie
Germany said. ``If that's the case, we don't need to play the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go over there with a winning attitude,'' defensive
tackle Mike Collins said. ``If we don't expect to win, we might as
well not go at all. Wow. That fires me up. It gets me a little
upset to hear that.''
AROUND THE NATION
</P>
<P>
   --Scott McInnis, a state representative from Colorado, plans to
sponsor legislation that will prevent athletes at the service
academies from dodging their five-year commitment to the military
in order to play pro sports. ``The bottom line is that this is
special treatment for athletes and not just any athlete, but the
top athletes,'' McInnis said. Former Air Force players Beau Morgan,
Steve Russ and Chris Gizzi all served less than five years in order
to play in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   --When No. 21 Brigham Young plays at New Mexico today, it will
match quarterbacks from the same high school. New Mexico's Sean
Stein was a year behind and served as the backup to BYU's Kevin
Feterik at Los Alamitos (Calif.) High School. Stein played a year
at Long Beach City College, where he threw passes to Jonathan
Pittman, who is now one of BYU's top receivers.
</P>
<P>
   --There's not much buzz to the Southern California-Notre Dame
game today. While this is regarded as one of the nation's best
intersectional rivalries, neither team is ranked. That's only the
seventh time in 71 meetings that has been the case, but it's the
second time in the past three seasons that neither team has been
ranked when they played each other.
</P>
<P>
   --Max DeLuca, a punter for NCAA Division III Baldwin-Wallace,
was involved in a statistical oddity in Saturday's game with Ohio
Northern. He punted 10 times and his net average (46.3 yards)
exceeded his gross average (45.7). Three of his punts were returned
for a negative 6 yards, and two were fumbled.
</P>
<P>
   --According to research by The Associated Press, the last time
that the Pacific-10 Conference didn't have a team ranked was Oct.
6, 1985 (when the AP ranked 20 teams). Southern California dropped
out of the top 25 this week. The last time the Pac-10 didn't finish
with a team in the final AP rankings was 1963, when only 10 teams
were ranked.
</P>
<P>
   --Now you know, Part One: Illinois claims to have staged the
first homecoming on the weekend of Oct. 14-16, 1910. In the first
homecoming game, the Illini beat the University of Chicago, 3-0.
Illinois has celebrated homecoming for all but one of the past 89
years (the 1918 event was canceled because of a flu outbreak).
Today, Minnesota plays at Illinois in this year's homecoming game.
</P>
<P>
   --Now you know, Part Two: In Temple's 24-14 victory over Boston
College, Owls freshman defensive end Dan Klecko had six tackles,
including two sacks. He's the son of former New York Jets defensive
lineman Joe Klecko, who also attended Temple. OVERHEARD
</P>
<P>
   John Cappelletti, who won the Heisman Trophy for Penn State in
1973, on the arrest and suspension of Florida State's Peter
Warrick:
</P>
<P>
   ``Has the Heisman become, `If I win it, fine, if I don't, I'm
still going to be the fourth pick and make $50 million?' I think
it's getting that way. I think money starts to overshadow the fact
you were chosen the best player in the country.`
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina quarterback Ronald Curry, who will be out six
months after surgery to repair a torn Achilles' tendon, putting his
availability to the Tar Heels' basketball team this season in
doubt:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all right emotionally. I'm a strong believer that
everything happens for a reason. Maybe I need this rest. I haven't
had a long rest in a long time. Maybe that's what my body was
telling me. Unfortunately, this is the way I have to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota coach Glen Mason on a holding call on a second-down
running play that pushed the Gophers out of field-goal range in
overtime of a game they lost to Wisconsin, 20-17:
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around here almost three years, and you don't hear
me whine very much, but I tell you one thing, fellas. It's amazing
to me that you watch 60 minutes of football without a holding call,
not one, and you go into overtime and one flies. It's truly
amazing. I hope it really was a holding penalty. I really do.''
</P>
<P>
   LSU quarterback Josh Booty, who played the past five seasons in
the Florida Marlins' system, on the downpour during last Saturday's
Florida game in Baton Rouge:
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I played in anything like that, we just put a
tarp over the field and called a rain delay.'' nn
</P>
