PATIENCE PAYS OFF FOR TEXAS A&AMP;M'S BERNARD (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Sometimes, the best counsel for a
friend in need is the unspoken word. Show support in your actions,
but suggest no solutions unless asked.
</P>
<P>
   That worked wonders for Texas A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum in dealing
with tailback Eric Bernard. The fifth-year senior averages more
yards per carry (5.3) than any tailback on the Aggies' depth chart
and figures to be a central figure in the gameplan for today's
11:30 a.m. contest against Kansas in Kyle Field.
</P>
<P>
   But that hardly seemed a likely scenario at this point last
year, when Bernard considered ending his football career and Slocum
stood ready to second the motion. Slocum said he is glad Bernard
never asked his opinion on what to do after suffering a
season-ending knee injury for the second time in 14 months on Oct.
4, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard, A&AMP;M's third-team tailback at the time, tore the
anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee while preparing for a
game against Nebraska. During two-a-days before the 1997 season, he
tore the ACL in his right knee. Both injuries required
reconstructive surgery and a minimum of 10 months in
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I had the second one, I started thinking, `Why am I even
trying to play football?,''' said Bernard, who contemplated telling
Slocum that he planned to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he'd asked for my advice, I'd probably have advised him to
do that,'' Slocum said, reflecting on the prospect of a downcast
Bernard rehabilitating a different knee in hopes of playing in a
crowded backfield. ``I really was at a loss for words. He was so
dejected. The year before, I'd given him my best pep talk about
coming back. ... Now, he's facing more surgery. He's got one more
season to play football and the rest of his life to do something
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great example of a guy who had every reason to throw in
the towel and wouldn't do it. I'm so proud of Eric.''
</P>
<P>
   When No. 13 A&AMP;M (4-1, 1-1) meets Kansas (2-4, 0-2), Bernard is
expected to handle the brunt of the carries because of injuries to
starting tailback Dante Hall (back) and fullback D'Andre Hardeman
(groin). Bernard rushed for 81 yards on 15 carries and scored his
first touchdowns since the 1996 season in last week's 45-13 rout of
Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into the Baylor game, Bernard had 127 rushing yards in
A&AMP;M's previous 31 games. Now, he leads A&AMP;M tailbacks in rushing
yards (168) and rushing average (5.3) at the midpoint of his final
season. Although the master plan calls for Hall (156 yards, 3.1
average) to return to his starting spot when healthy, Bernard has
given A&AMP;M coaches some food for thought when distributing playing
time in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum said Bernard, even after two rounds of knee surgery,
``looks like the player we always thought he could be. That's quite
an accomplishment for someone who's hardly played for three
years.''
</P>
<P>
   To teammates, he stands as an inspiration. Offensive guard Chris
Valletta said the guys in the trenches tend to play harder when
they know Bernard will be carrying the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do our best job for him. He deserves it,'' Valletta
said. ``What Eric did shows so much character and so much heart. He
knows what it means to not play football. He had it taken away
twice. He runs every play like it's the last time he'll ever touch
the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernard said he developed that determination during his second
stint of rehabilitation. It began while contemplating his departure
from football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prayed a lot and got my answer. All that hard work and the
negative things I've gone through made me grow up,'' said the
5-foot-9, 190-pounder from Tulsa, Okla. ``It's been worth it. I
didn't know how much I'd play this year, but I knew I wanted to get
back in position to where I could help, if \Rcoaches\S needed me.
This is my last year to play football. So I wanted to put every
ounce into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, that's proved to be enough to inspire teammates and
keep an A&AMP;M ground game headed in the right direction during a
difficult stretch with injuries. Quarterback Randy McCown said
there's a deeper lesson here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric's a great example of good things happening to good
people,'' McCown said. ``He's been back in the shadows and could
have griped about a lot of things that went against him. But he
never did. He kept his nose to the grindstone, and it's paying off.
He deserves every bit of credit he gets about making us a better
football team.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
