<HEADLINE>
COMMERCE DEPT. PAYS A CALL ON WEST BANK PALESTINIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (dw) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In one long day of their regional tour, American
executives were whisked into an unscheduled meeting with Prime
Minister Ehud Barak of Israel and chauffeured by armored vans into
a walled Ramallah compound to break bread with Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinian market will be a free market,'' Arafat,
attired in his traditional keffiyah and olive-drab military garb,
promised the potential investors as they sat for a sumptuous Middle
Eastern feast.
</P>
<P>
   The visit marked the first U.S. Department of Commerce business
mission to the Middle East to include the West Bank, part of an
American effort to reward regional peacemakers with investment and
trade.
</P>
<P>
   So far this effort has met with only limited success, American
officials concede. But they assert that one major obstacle has been
removed: the previous Israeli government of Benjamin Netanyahu, who
resisted pressure to ease the movement of Palestinian and Jordanian
goods through Israeli security checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difficulty in the last government kind of blocked
everything,'' said Commerce Secretary William Daley, who led the
delegation. In the first three months of the Barak government,
Daley said, Israeli trade officials have demonstrated a new
willingness to work with Palestinian and Jordanian counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings this week, the American visitors, who included
executives from Merck &AMP; Co., Lucent Technologies and Enron, heard
Israeli officials promising to do more to help the Jordanian and
Palestinian economies, and implicitly recognizing that they have
obstructed trade in the past.
</P>
<P>
   In response, they also heard Jordanians and Palestinians
acknowledging that they cannot entice investment and trade without
addressing their own problems, including a rigid bureaucracy and
the flaunting of intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most encouraging, Israeli and Palestinian trade
officials politely suggested they no longer need such active
American mediation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tone was so different,'' said Daley, who was paying his
third extended visit here in less than a year. ``They said we
appreciate your doing this, but we have our relationships. Our
ministries are talking back and forth every day on specific
problems and issues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference comes from the top,'' Daley said.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in Amman, Jordan, last weekend, the Commerce delegation
moved on to Israel and the Palestinian territories, and then Cairo,
for the first joint gathering of the Jordanian, Israeli,
Palestinian and Egyptian chambers of commerce. Officials hope the
regional meeting will help set the agenda for a Middle Eastern
economic summit meeting tentatively scheduled for Egypt next
spring. Past plans for annual regional business conferences were
suspended after Arab complaints about Netanyahu's stance on peace
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Daley and other American officials have sought to
coax Israel, Jordan and the Palestinian Authority to eliminate
barriers to cross-border trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, for its part, gave the Palestinians duty-free
access to the U.S. market, a status previously enjoyed only by
Israel, Mexico and Canada. But intraregional trade remains
marginal, and cross-border business ventures are rare. Despite
three years of free trade privileges, Palestinian exports to the
United States are still so paltry that they do not even show up in
Commerce Department statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Though much has to do with the quantity and quality of export
goods, American officials agree with Palestinian merchants who say
their problems have been compounded by stringent and sometimes
seemingly arbitrary security measures at Israeli ports and customs
posts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have a duty-free, quota-free relationship with the
United States, but if you can't get your goods to a port, it's
pretty tough,'' Daley said. ``If you don't have a free flow of
people and goods, you don't have an economy.''
</P>
<P>
   For Jordan, the immediate concerns are Israel's quotas on its
exports to the West Bank _ once Jordanian territory _ and its
requirement that these goods be meticulously inspected and reloaded
onto Palestinian or Israeli trucks. Despite repeated Israeli
pledges to ease these restrictions, Jordan's exports to the West
Bank remain stalled at an insignificant $20 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Daley says some Israeli rules have more to do with protectionism
than security. ``There is a $2.5 billion market in the West Bank
and Gaza that a lot of people would like to keep a stranglehold
on,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
