<HEADER>
A8373 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-UMASS-LAWSUIT-BOS &LR;      10-15 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UMASS-LAWSUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE FORMER PLAYERS ALLEGE PHYSICAL, VERBAL ABUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three former women basketball players at the University of
Massachusetts, all of whom left the team due to problems with coach
Joanie O'Brien, sued the university in federal court Friday,
charging they were subjected to physical and verbal abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Kara Trent, Nicole Vallieres and Tori Grant, and the parents of
the three players, are seeking $15 million in damages. The civil
rights suit filed in U.S. District Court in Boston charges O'Brien
constantly harassed, intimidated and degraded them during their
brief stint at the university and that school officials did nothing
to stop it. Those are violations of Title IX as well as the NCAA
Constitution, the suit charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a hostile environment and the university didn't do a
thing about it,'' said attorney Brian J. Woolf, who represents the
women and their families. ``There was unwanted and excessive
touching, yelling and screaming, and the result was that all three
suffered severe emotional hardship.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate response from the university. A call
placed to the office of associate counsel, Deirdre Heatwole, who
had a brief communication with Woolf last June, was not returned.
In addition to the university, 12 individuals are named as
defendants including O'Brien, Chancellor David Scott, UMass
President William Bulger and Athletic Director Robert Marcum.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no verbal communication of any substance,''
Woolf said. ``My opinion is that the university is putting its head
in the sand and hoping it goes away. Well, it's not going away.''
</P>
<P>
   Trent, Vallieres and Grant were teammates on the 1997-98 UMass
team. Trent and Vallieres, both freshmen at the time, were on the
active roster while Grant, a transfer from Seton Hall, practiced
with the team while sitting out the season due to NCAA transfer
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Trent, who emerged as a starter during that season, subsequently
left the team at the start of her sophomore year over differences
with O'Brien. Grant was kicked off the team for violating team
rules. Vallieres transferred to Division II American International
College, where she played last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe reported on the problems the women had with O'Brien in
a Dec. 13, 1998 story. At the time, O'Brien dismissed the women's
charges and said it was simply a matter of her coaching style,
which she admitted was intense.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs think it goes further than that. All three
players have needed counseling because of their basketball
experiences at UMass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be done,'' said Robert Cernik, Vallieres' mother.
``For what Nicky went through. For what we, as parents, went
through. I lost my daughter for a year. One whole year.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Kara Trent, ``I grew up playing basketball and it was
something I loved. Once I got to the UMass campus, all that changed
severely. This is what goes on behind closed doors at a lot of
colleges and it has to stop because it takes a lot away from the
game and it takes a lot away from us as people.''
</P>
<P>
   While the three women each cite O'Brien's behavior as abusive,
ranging from streams of profanity to pushing, grabbing and shoving
the players, they also have independent claims in the 37-page
complaint. Trent also is alleging medical malpractice, charging the
university ignored a knee injury during her freshman season and
gave her inadequate medical care and advice. She subsequently
needed surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Grant said O'Brien accused her of being gay in a lengthy meeting
in the spring of 1998, six months before the coach dismissed her
from the team. In the fall of 1998, the complaint states that
O'Brien confronted Grant about rumors that the player had smoked
marijuana. Grant admitted to O'Brien she had done so on one
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien then dismissed Grant from the team although, the
complaint said, there was no such action taken against other
teammates who also admitted smoking marijuana. Grant also said she
was not offered any counseling following O'Brien's decision and
that her parents were rebuffed by Marcum when they asked to discuss
the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Trent is the only one of the three still at the university.
Grant is living at home in New Jersey, but plans to re-enroll at
UMass in January. Vallieres remains at American International.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
