<SLUG> BC-BLIND-WORKERS-$ADV-17-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLIND, DISABLED WORKERS GET TEMPORARY REPRIEVE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Fore release Sunday, Oct. 17) 
 
By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The jobs of 1,400 blind and severely disabled &UR;  &LR; workers were
temporarily spared last week when the head of the General Services
Administration in Washington scuttled plans to phase out eight
government supply depots.
</P>
<P>
   The decision prolongs at least 150 manufacturing jobs at Texas
affiliates of the National Industries for the Blind, including
Lighthouses for the Blind in Houston and San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The Lighthouses have been reliant on government contracts for
decades, employing blind and severely disabled people who make
products ranging from pencils to floor polish, all used in federal
offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very, very pleasantly surprised,'' said San Antonio
Lighthouse president Bob Plunkett.``It gives us time to find other
options and be better prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Technological changes, the Internet and greater privatization of
supply systems were cited by GSA administrator David J. Barram in
July when he ordered the closing of eight regional depots that
funnel supplies to federal agencies. One of the depots is in Fort
Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Almost overnight, the decision caused a drop in orders and lower
income at dozens of NIB affiliates, including those in Texas. At
the San Antonio Lighthouse, where office supplies are made, about
25 blind part-time workers were dismissed last month. Supply
officials said they were so well stocked with some items, they
couldn't justify placing new orders.
</P>
<P>
   About 120 full-time workers at the San Antonio Lighthouse have
been on a voluntary four-day work week since August, and officials
there were bracing for more manufacturing layoffs in coming months
due to the downturn in orders. Houston has about 30 blind workers
whose jobs were endangered.
</P>
<P>
   Barram announced Wednesday that he had reached a pact with the
federal employees union ``to examine the problems and directions in
our distribution system.'' A final decision should come by the end
of this month, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Union president Bobby L. Harnage said the depot shutdown was
opposed by federal workers because ``it did not appear economically
justified and because it failed to respect the interests of the
blind, the handicapped, victims of disasters and U.S. military
forces overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   The reprieve may be postponing the inevitable, though, according
to a blind man in Houston who advocates placement of blind workers
in service jobs over low-paying assembly tasks.
</P>
<P>
   James O. ``Jim'' Skelton, Jr., president of the Houston Chapter
of the National Federation of the Blind of Texas, said the
Lighthouse approach is sometimes outmoded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked there 11 years and I got laid off and I'm glad I
did,'' said Skelton, who is now a computer instructor at Houston
Community College. ``A lot of blind people are not getting out and
reaching their potential.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The workers _ they're not sharing in the profits,'' he said.
``You get in there and you say, `I can't do any better than this,'
and so they're stuck and all of a sudden they're put out to
pasture.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1949EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
