<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8375 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-FUNDRAISING1     10-15 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FUNDRAISING16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush outspends all foes, still has $38 million left
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The five most expensive presidential campaigns
already have spent $68 million, more than three months before the
first votes are cast and before heavy television advertising has
begun.
</P>
<P>
   At the same point four years ago, the top five campaigns had
spent $42 million.
</P>
<P>
   The latest campaign finance reports, filed Friday with the
Federal Election Commission, show Texas Gov. George W. Bush
continuing to obliterate records in his pursuit of the Republican
nomination. Bush has spent $19 million out of $57 million raised
through the end of September, leaving him with $38 million.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Steve Forbes also has spent nearly $19 million, but
most of that came from his own fortune.
</P>
<P>
   To get an idea of the scale of Bush's totals, Bush spent $7
million just to raise money. Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.), second to
Bush in polls in New Hampshire, has spent $7.3 million on his
entire campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was second among Republicans in contributions, raising $3
million in the past three months and bringing his total for the
year to $9.3 million. That includes $2 million he transferred from
his Senate campaign committee.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's numbers obscure the robust finance operations on the
Democratic side, where Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill
Bradley have spent $14.5 million and $8.5 million, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Gore continues to spend money at a faster rate than Bradley,
reporting expenses for the third quarter of $6.4 million, compared
to $4.2 million for Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also has spread his money over many more states, including
Georgia, an indication of organizational strength that extends
beyond early primary states like New Hampshire, California and New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has spent more than $10,000 this year in only 10 states,
spending the most in New Jersey, site of his campaign headquarters,
Illinois, California and Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, by contrast, has spent more than $10,000 in 34 states.
Gore has spent nearly $500,000 in California, a key primary and
general election state, and more than $330,000 in New York. Both
states hold primaries on March 7, as does Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has moved slightly ahead of Gore in terms of available
cash, $10.7 million to $10.3 million
</P>
<P>
   Despite the massive numbers posted by the campaigns and their
appeals to $1,000 donors, the candidates continue to paint
themselves as the choice of average, working Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Gore boasted an average contribution of $187. Bradley's figure
was $334, while Bush's was $386.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Republicans, Gary Bauer, Patrick Buchanan, Elizabeth
Dole and Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah each raised more than $1million
from July to September, according to the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1950EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8376 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-SHOOTING-MONTHLATER-T     10-15 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-MONTHLATER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOOD OF SYMPATHY UPLIFTING, PASTOR SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (Wash. State ATTN.) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REBECA RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The hallway is draped in e-mail printouts,
posters, banners and poetry from all over the world, each
expressing a singular thought: You are loved.
</P>
<P>
   Peace has returned to this place.
</P>
<P>
   One month ago on Friday, Larry Gene Ashbrook walked down the
hall at Wedgwood Baptist Church in Fort Worth, shooting at church
members before entering the sanctuary and firing at hundreds of
young people gathered for a rally. He left seven dead, seven
injured, and a building scarred by blood and bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Now the scars have been replaced with sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I walk into church and I see the new banners and
letters hanging on the walls, I'm encouraged,'' said Wedgwood's
pastor, Al Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   The families of the victims are equally touched.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only word we can come up with is `overwhelmed,''' said
David Griffin, whose 14-year-old daughter, Cassandra, was killed in
the shooting. ``We're at a loss as to how to show our gratitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffin said he and his wife, Tralissa, learned this week that a
circle of trees was planted in Israel in memory of the slain. And
shortly after the shooting, grocery stores donated trays of
prepared food and paper goods and the Tandy Corp. donated cellular
phones to the victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   In the quiet hallways of Wedgwood, one senses the jarring
juxtaposition of pain and compassion born of the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 feet from where Kevin Galey, a 38-year-old church
counselor, was wounded hangs a brightly colored mosaic of messages
from students at Oakmont Elementary School, a few miles from the
church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this won't bring back (those) who died, but I'm
sorry,'' read the words, scrawled on a bright yellow sheet of
construction paper. ``I hope they go to heaven. From: Bridgette.''
</P>
<P>
   A letter from the Mount Baker Baptist Association in Sedro
Woolley, Wash., north of Seattle, is posted steps from where Sydney
Browning was killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted them to know that someone outside the state of Texas
cares about them,'' said Mary Davis, who works at the association.
``I thought if, heaven forbid, this should happen to us, how much
we would appreciate the rest of the world praying for and thinking
about us.''
</P>
<P>
   And in front of the church, an unknown donor has arranged eight
metal crosses bearing the names of the dead, including Ashbrook,
who fatally shot himself after he ended his rampage.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the overwhelming number of messages displayed at
the church, more than $100,000 has been raised through memorial
funds, and proceeds from several planned concerts and benefits are
going directly to the victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   Near the entrance to the sanctuary, a bold orange poster
proclaims, ``We've Been There 2 _ Littleton, Colo.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been nearly six months since a tragic shooting at
Columbine High School near Littleton snuffed out the lives of 12
students and a teacher. The two student shooters also wounded 22
people and then turned the guns on themselves.
</P>
<P>
   And the love keeps pouring in, said Rick Kaufman, director of
communications for the Jefferson County Public School District,
which includes Columbine High.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still get letters, cards, e-mails, flowers, teddy bears,''
Kaufman said. ``And millions of dollars have been distributed''
through individual and corporate funds set up after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman said the spontaneous outpouring of affection filled a
large section of Clement Park, which adjoins the school. The
district eventually rented an empty store in a shopping center to
store the items and has moved everything to a federal warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   The compassion has helped the community feel loved, Kaufman
said, but there are times when the media revisit the nightmare at
Columbine, forcing people to relive a day that changed many lives.
</P>
<P>
   Several days ago, CBS TV aired a grainy clip of video taken by a
surveillance camera in the Columbine High cafeteria. It shows a
gunman kneeling in a rifleman's pose and firing across tables and
chairs. No bodies are shown and no deaths occurred in the
cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine what it's doing to some of the families,''
Kaufman said. ``Enough has been written about this that it does not
add any benefit, and the negative impact is far greater.''
</P>
<P>
   At Wedgwood, flowers still grace the front lobby, church
services are still attracting hundreds, and members feel loved,
Meredith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to know people from all over the world are praying
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
