<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS INDONESIA INCHING TOWARD DEMOCRACY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ The president's head snapped up in
surprise. In the middle of his speech late Thursday night, someone
was pointing a finger and shouting.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers were roughing up demonstrators on the streets outside,
shouted the man, a member of the electoral assembly listening to
the speech that could determine the political future of the
president, B.J. Habibie.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later another delegate interrupted with a shout
about the student demonstrators, and then another.
</P>
<P>
   As never before, the outside world was intruding into what for
decades was an insulated and oblivious political process. And the
process was responding, not only with shouts from the floor but
with the stirrings of innovative lawmaking that reflected public
demands for change.
</P>
<P>
   Both the violent demonstrations and the parliamentary session
continued Friday as delegates began presenting formal responses to
Habibie's speech, in which he sought their votes next Wednesday
when they select the next president. Most were harshly critical.
</P>
<P>
   Many people portray next week's vote as a choice between
candidates representing the past and the future, with Habibie's
main challenger, Megawati Sukarnoputri, seen as offering a fresh
start. But already the past is being left behind as Indonesia
experiments with representative democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Like two wary strangers, the country's government and its people
are inching tentatively closer together.
</P>
<P>
   In a gesture of respect that signaled the possibility of a new
relationship, the assembly's speaker, Amien Rais, walked into the
streets Thursday night and escorted four of the student
demonstrators inside to observe the session. A parliamentary
official said more students would be invited to attend in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is going on inside the assembly now is really very
important,'' said Daniel Lev, an expert on Indonesia who is a
professor at the University of Washington in Seattle. ``Whether you
want to call it a process of democracy or whatever, the point is
they are responding to some pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   These pressures, from the press, from newly formed civic groups
and most insistently from the students, are keeping alive an agenda
of reform that could have sunk, in Parliament, under the weight of
inertia and self-interest.
</P>
<P>
   The reform agenda is affecting not only the presidential
selection but a newly vigorous legislative process. Overshadowed by
the clamor of the presidential race, legislative committees are
drafting laws and constitutional amendments that would limit
presidential power and institute a degree of democratic checks and
balances.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the green-roofed parliament building, there is a sense of
excitement and empowerment as legislators work to craft the future
outlines of their government.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking a taboo, they are preparing to amend the constitution,
created when the nation was founded in 1945. Proposed changes would
limit a president to two five-year terms and hand over to the
legislature the power to pass laws.
</P>
<P>
   Among other issues, nine draft decrees address the reform of the
judiciary and law enforcement systems, which are now riddled with
corruption and are subservient to the president.
</P>
<P>
   The legislature has faced particular difficulty in formulating a
constitutional change that would relinquish Indonesia's claim on
East Timor, which it invaded in 1975 and which voted Aug. 30 to
become independent. After the vote, the people of East Timor were
terrorized by violent militias who drove them from their homes.
Because of the emotional heat of this issue, analysts say a
parliamentary vote could be delayed.
</P>
<P>
   The vigor of the current criticisms of Habibie may also partly
reflect this mood of liberation from the decades-long grip of the
autocrat, Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   The newspapers, the airwaves and the assembly hall were filled
with criticisms of Habibie's speech, in which he sought to win
support by outlining what he said were the accomplishments of his
17-month term in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deceitful grandstanding,'' the English language daily Jakarta
Post called it, in what seemed a giddy break with the
obsequiousness that had been required during Suharto's 32-year
rule. The newspaper further characterized the address as
``pathetic;'' ``a shameless bid to stay in power,'' a display of
``arrogance and contempt towards our long-suffering people'' and
``nothing short of disgusting.''
</P>
<P>
   When Suharto was forced to resign in May 1998, Habibie, as his
vice president, took over as an interim president. He did in fact
make a number of immediate democratic reforms, freeing the press
and labor unions, opening up the political process and setting in
motion the transition to a new elected leader that is now taking
place.
</P>
<P>
   The main criticisms of Habibie are that he failed to pursue a
corruption investigation against Suharto, that he allowed
corruption to continue and flourish, that abuses by the military
continued during his administration and that he created the debacle
of East Timor's independence vote.
</P>
<P>
   The distant shouts of students on the streets and the passions
of the newly empowered legislators seemed to drown out Habibie's
plea on Thursday: ``We have tried our best. I fully realize that we
cannot resolve the crisis _ which was an accumulation of damage and
problems over so long a time _ within 512 days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
