</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-KENNEWICK-MAN-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO WERE THE FIRST AMERICANS? BONES OF `KENNEWICK MAN'
INCONCLUSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)  (bl) 
 By TIMOTHY EGAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The prehistoric bones of Kennewick Man, found in the
banks of the Columbia River in Washington state three years ago and
hailed as one of the most significant archaeological finds of the
decade, cannot be linked to any modern American Indian tribes or to
Europeans, a scientific panel has concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The remains, estimated to be about 9,300 years old according to
earlier radiocarbon dating, most closely resemble Asian people,
particularly the Ainu of northern Japan, and to Polynesians from
the South Pacific, the scientists said. Both groups are descendants
of people from southern Asia, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are likely to hurt the case of American Indians
seeking to control the bones under a federal law that requires
native skeletal remains to be returned to people who can show
affiliation with them. But the conclusions also put a damper on
claims of some scientists and pagan religious groups that Kennewick
Man came from Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Because Kennewick Man had features that seemed to be neither
modern American Indian nor contemporary Asian, the find has held
the possibility that it could lead a broader theory about how the
Americas were peopled.
</P>
<P>
   The new research, which was made public by the Interior
Department on Friday in response to a lawsuit by scientists who
want to study the bones, does little to resolve the ongoing
anthropological question of who were the first Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But some scientists said the new analysis bolsters the case that
some of the first Americans may have come to the continent by boat,
crossing the Pacific or following islands and the coast from north
of Japan to the Bering Sea and then south along West Coast of North
America. The Ainu, indigenous to the Sakhalin Islands of northern
Japan, were known as a maritime people.
</P>
<P>
   The long-held view has been that migration came from northern
Asia over a Siberian land bridge and then down the interior of the
continent by foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kennewick Man fits into an emerging pattern that these earlier
American people are not like the modern people of today,'' said Dr.
Joseph Powell, a physical anthropologist at the University of New
Mexico, and a member of the panel.
</P>
<P>
   If, as the studies indicate, Kennewick Man is not a distant
relative of modern Europeans or American Indians, then it points to
two interpretive conclusions, Powell said. One is that people from
Kennewick Man's age in the late Pleistocene era left no descendants
_ that they were wiped out at some point. The other is that they
had features from all over the Pacific Rim that have diversified
over time.
</P>
<P>
   The studies were done by comparing the skull size of Kennewick
Man with that of all the known ethnic groups. The closest match was
to Ainu and Polynesians. The most distant matches were to Africans
and Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Kennewick Man was found, with his skull and bones
more than 85 percent intact, a number of anthropologists speculated
that he was Caucasoid _ referring to people from Europe or
modern-day India. In a reconstruction of the skull by Dr. James
Chatters, the anthropologist who first analyzed the find, Kennewick
Man was made to look like Patrick Stewart, the British actor best
known from ``Star Trek: The Next Generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's report debunks most of the ties to Cacaucasoid
background, when the term is meant to define people who live in
what is now Europe, the Middle East and India. ``When defined this
way, Kennewick is clearly not a Caucasoid,'' the panel concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Asatru Folk Assembly, a pagan religious group from
California which had claimed that Kennewick Man may have been a
descendant of ancient Norse people, will press forward with its
legal attempt to gain control of the bones, according to the
group's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still think there is a distinct possibility that it could
be a proto-European,'' said Michael Clinton, the attorney for the
pagan group. ``Next step is a DNA analysis. That's the bottom line
that will determine everything.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear if the judge hearing the case over Kennewick Man,
U.S. Magistrate John Jelderks will order DNA testing. But he has
given the government until March to decide whether the bones will
be open to a group of leading anthropologists for study.
</P>
<P>
   Indian tribes in the Columbia Basin area say Kennewick Man is an
Indian ancestor, and that his remains should be properly buried.
But in order to make such a determination, the government must find
``a shared group identity'' or a ``cultural affiliation'' with a
modern Indian tribe. The panel assembled by the government will do
a radiocarbon dating to check against the initial reports of
Kennewick Man's age, and may do DNA testing if ordered by the
court.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the bones are at the Burke Museum in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was made public today makes it very difficult for the
government to claim that Kennewick man belongs to modern Native
Americans,'' said Alan Schneider, a Portland, Ore., attorney who
represents eight scientists who are suing for access to the bones.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``This is an extremely important discovery,'' said Dr. Douglas
Owsley, who heads the physical anthropology section of the
Smithsonian Institute, and is a plaintiff in the lawsuit. ``We have
never said Kennewick Man was this or that. But we do feel that it
was far too important a discovery not to learn something from it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Umatilla Indian Nation, which claims Kennewick Man as a
descendant, did not respond to telephone requests for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Included in Friday's report was a compelling description of
Kennewick Man's age and health. He was described as a robust man of
45 to 50 years old, about 5 feet-9 inches tall, with no
deterioration of his joints. His bones are so well preserved that
he may have been deliberately buried, suggesting a funeral ritual
among the oldest in America.
</P>
<P>
   Although he had a 3-inch spear point imbedded deep in his
pelvis, the scientists say it was probably in him for a long time,
and never caused serious infection. ``He was one tough guy,'' said
Powell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
