<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-100COUNTDOWN-TEX </SLUG>
 
Cal touchdown stopped the music (For use by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
By CARLOS MENDEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The headline in the ``Berkley Gazette'' the next day was a
confession, and it best summed up the events of Nov. 20, 1982 on a
football field in Berkley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no words.''
</P>
<P>
   California's five-lateral kickoff return for a touchdown on the
last play of the game would be a stirring memory. But the
freakishness of the play _ the near tackle at the 44-yard line, the
leg cramp Mariet Ford suffered on the way to the end zone, the
Stanford trombone player crushed in the end zone _ lifted the
sequence from amazing to surreal.
</P>
<P>
   Cal-Stanford 1982 produced one of the most unbelievable plays in
college football.
</P>
<P>
   The 89th meeting of the Pac-10 schools looked like it would be
simply another entry in Stanford quarterback John Elway's Heisman
Trophy campaign. He had rallied Stanford from a 10-0 first-half
deficit to a 20-19 lead with four seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Play,'' as it's known around Cal, came next.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford had been penalized 15 yards for excessive celebration
after its go-ahead field goal, so Cal had at least a small
advantage for its kickoff return.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Stanford band had started making its way to the
south end of the field.
</P>
<P>
   Cal kickoff return captain Richard Rodgers told his teammates:
``Just keep lateraling the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Moen picked up the squib kick at the Cal 43-yard line and
took it into Stanford territory. He heard Rodgers yelling for a
lateral and fired a pass behind him that freshman Dwight Garner
caught at the Stanford 48.
</P>
<P>
   Garner was surrounded, and replays show his knee was close to
the ground as he lateraled to Rodgers at the Stanford 48. Without a
whistle, play continued.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the band had streamed on to the field.
</P>
<P>
   Upfield, Rodgers lateraled to Mariet Ford, who was about to
throw a block. Ford raced toward the end zone but suffered a leg
cramp on the way and pitched the ball behind him at the 25, where
Moen grabbed the final lateral.
</P>
<P>
   Moen weaved through the band and found the end zone, landing on
a trombone player, and waited for a ruling as 70,000 in the
stadium, both teams and the band stood around wondering, ``What
happened?''
</P>
<P>
   Touchdown, the officials said. Cal won, 25-20.
</P>
<P>
   Cal linebacker Ron Rivera had the final word: ``I still can't
believe it. It was an act of God.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
