<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON STUDIES, SURVEYS AND PRODUCTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From I.M.F. to IMF: A Trademark Battle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's a trademark dispute with a difference: A small California
mortgage bank and brokerage is being sued by, of all things, the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is the brokerage's name: IMF Loans Inc. ``My maiden
name is Eisenberg, which is German for `iron mountain,''' said Jan
Pasternak, the company's owner. ``So we started as Iron Mountain
Financial. But that is too long to be an Internet domain name, so
when we went on line, we shortened it.'' Ms. Pasternak didn't think
there would be any confusion. ``Nobody in the United States knows
what the IMF is, or cares,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There certainly is no overlap in customer base. The fund
supplies multibillion-dollar loans to member national governments
to help them stabilize currencies and capital flows; it cannot
legally lend to individuals. As for IMF Loans, ``Poland has never
applied,'' Ms. Pasternak said, adding that her company ``is just a
blip,'' with just $135,000 a month in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   So why sue? Kathleen White, a spokeswoman for the fund, said:
``There are an increasing number of fraudulent financial schemes
around the world where people use the fund's name or imply some
sort of connection, to mislead investors or add credence to some
product. We're not saying that is what is going on in this case.
But if we failed to take adequate measures, it could weaken the
protection of the trademark in general. We have to be consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   _Patrick J. Lyons
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
