<SLUG> BC-CANCER-RULING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY ORDERS DAMAGES FOR EXPERIMENTAL NUCLEAR TREATMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal jury Friday ordered Massachusetts General Hospital and
a retired neurosurgeon to pay $8 million in damages to the families
of two brain tumor patients who died 38 years ago from experimental
nuclear treatments.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict could bolster efforts by lawyers for the families to
bring a class-action suit against the hospital and doctor on behalf
of another 60 patients who received the deadly treatments in the
1950s and 1960s as part of a government-funded cancer research
project.
</P>
<P>
   Wiping away tears after the jury awarded her $2.5 million,
Evelyn Heinrich of Westwood, whose husband George, 35, died from
the treatments in 1961, said, ``I have absolutely felt that the
passage of time has not diminished these crimes, not for one
minute. Human experimentation, what could be worse?''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Sienkewicz, whose family was awarded $5.5 million for the
1961 death of his mother, Eileen, said, ``We're grateful to the
jury for listening to us and believing in us.''
</P>
<P>
   After hearing three weeks of testimony and deliberating for five
days in US District Court in Boston, the four-man, five-woman jury
found that MGH and its former chief of neurosurgery, Dr. William
Sweet, now 89, were negligent and caused the deaths of George
Heinrich and Eileen Sienkewicz. The jury rejected claims that the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, which had also been named in
the suit, was also liable for the deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Joseph L. Doherty Jr., who represents MGH and Sweet and
argued that they made a good-faith effort to save terminally ill
patients, said he will urge US District Chief Judge William G.
Young, who presided over the trial, to set aside the jury's
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a surprise based upon the evidence,'' Doherty
said. ``I think the amounts are excessive. It will be appealed.''
</P>
<P>
   But a team of lawyers from Washington, Vermont, Colorado, and
Massachusetts who represented the families, said the jury sent a
powerful message to the medical community that patients always come
first.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont Attorney Anthony Z. Roisman, who represents the
families, said ``good intentions are not enough,'' and medical
ethicists and review boards should prohibit experiments ``unless
it's clear that the benefits you are going to deliver are greater
than the risk you are going to cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you don't know, then go back to the drawing board.
Don't make the decision to experiment on patients.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit accused MGH, Sweet, and MIT of using Heinrich and
Sienkewicz as ``human guinea pigs without their consent'' in
painful, unproven medical experiments that were of no therapeutic
value to them.
</P>
<P>
   Heinrich, the father of a 3-year-old daughter, and Sienkewicz, a
40-year-old mother of three, were afflicted with fast-growing brain
tumors when Sweet and MGH decided to administer boron neutron
capture therapy, an experimental treatment that was partially
funded by a grant from the US Atomic Energy Commission.
</P>
<P>
   They were injected with boron, a chemical that concentrates on
brain tumors, then placed in a nuclear reactor at MIT where they
were zapped by a neutron beam. The treatment destroyed their
tumors, but also scorched healthy brain tissue, hastening their
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a wonderful mother and a wonderful sister, and she
didn't deserve to die the way she died,'' said Sienkewicz's sister,
Marie Denning. ``She deserved to die with dignity and peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Jurors rejected the claim that MGH and Sweet failed to inform
Sienkewicz and Heinrich about the procedure and get their consents,
but found they were negligent and wrongfully caused the deaths. The
jury rejected all claims against MIT.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Attorney Owen Gallagher, who represents MIT, said, ``I'm
glad the jury recognized from the evidence that MIT entered into
this with the best intentions and were able to differentiate
between the two parties (MIT and MGH).''
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher said MIT provided technical assistance to MGH for what
it believed was promising therapy and its involvement was as
``experts in nuclear energy, not in medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for MGH, Sweet and MIT had argued unsuccessfully prior
to trial that the case should be dismissed because the claims were
so old. Massachusetts law in 1961 required malpractice claims to be
filed within two years. But the families said they didn't learn
details of the experiments until 1995 when the President's Advisory
Committee on Human Radiation Experiments released previously secret
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Roisman said they've learned that up to 200 patients
were injected with boron without their knowledge during the 1950s
and 1960s, while some 60 patients received the same treatment that
killed Heinrich and Sienkewicz.
</P>
<P>
   Roisman said he'll urge Young to allow him to file a
class-action suit on behalf of other victims. If the judge grants
that request, MGH and Sweet would be forced to identify other
victims who underwent the treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Roisman is also ready to move forward with a negligence suit
against the federal government, on behalf of the families of
Heinrich and Sienkewicz, for funding the deadly treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was all government funded with taxpayers' dollars,'' said
Evelyn Heinrich. ``The public should know this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
