<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIXES TIME REFERENCE IN THIRD PARAGRAPH!
TEXAS AIMS TO IMPROVE OUTSIDE SHOOTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas basketball coach Rick Barnes said he hopes there is one
constant from last season, and he's not just talking about the
Longhorns winning another Big 12 title.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I hope is that teams defend us like they did a year
ago,'' Barnes said as the defending conference champions prepared
to open practice tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Division I schools could begin basketball practice Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' inference is that such a strategy could _ and should _
backfire for teams that expect to reprise the sagging, inside
double-team strategy to stop the Longhorns' top player, center
Chris Mihm.
</P>
<P>
   Texas couldn't counter that strategy last season because of a
lack of consistent outside shooting. Barnes vowed to correct that
flaw and believes that he has by signing guards Lawrence Williams,
Darren Kelly and Roosevelt Brown and guard/forward Chris Ogden. He
has also worked with Mihm and senior forward Gabe Muoneke in the
open court and added some wrinkles to his offense to take advantage
of their outside shooting ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be a better shooting team than we were a year ago,''
Barnes said. ``I am excited about our new guys. And to be honest,
some of them were underrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Blending the new _ which includes sophomore forward Chris Owens
_ with returning starters Mihm, Muoneke and point guard Ivan Wagner
will be the main focus of the Longhorns' preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner reportedly looks like a new player after having
arthroscopic surgery on his left knee. Brown is expected to be his
backup, although Barnes said all three of his new guards are good
ball handlers. Williams _ who is described as a slasher with
3-point range _ will probably open as the shooting guard. He, Kelly
and Ogden can double as shooting guards and small forwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches have high expectations for all \Rthe new players\S
right off the bat,'' Mihm said. ``And I've been really, really
impressed with everyone they've brought in. The new players have
brought an aspect to our team we really needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens, 6-foot-8, sat out last season after transferring from
Tulane. He will combine with the 7-foot Mihm and 6-7 Muoneke to
give the Longhorns a formidable rebounding and scoring trio.
</P>
<P>
   Texas fans again can expect a contender _ as can those of
Kansas, Oklahoma, Oklahoma State and maybe Missouri. All made the
NCAA Tournament field last season and have received preseason Top
25 mention. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
