<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MONEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush preparing for media assault
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In a sure sign that the airwave war is about to
begin, Gov. George W. Bush reported Friday that he has already
spent more than $1 million on his TV ad campaign that will begin in
coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has sent $600,000 to WMUR, New Hampshire's dominant TV
station, for airtime. Bush, the frontrunner for the GOP
presidential nomination, also has paid more than $420,000 to
Maverick Media, the Austin-based company producing his ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sends a signal that we intend to spend money to be
communicating our message on their station,'' Mark McKinnon,
Maverick Media's president, said of the payment to WMUR. ``By doing
so early we are trying to get the premium time slots.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's Friday report to the Federal Election Commission shows he
has raised more than $57 million since beginning his campaign in
March. He has spent $19 million, more than double the amount any of
his GOP opponents have raised. So far, the heaviest spending _ 37
percent of the $19 million _ has gone for fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   The production of TV ads and buying time to air them has eaten
up just 5 percent of the expenditures. By the time the campaign
ends, TV ads will become the largest single expense.
</P>
<P>
   The ad spending will be driven in party by his GOP foe Steve
Forbes. Forbes has collected only $4.5 million in contributions but
has dipped into his pocket for $16.3 million. Forbes has spent $19
million, including more than $4 million on TV ads. So far, the ads
have been self-promoting and on issues. The Bush campaign expects
that to change in coming weeks with Forbes airing ads challenging
Bush's record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to shy away from engaging in a robust
discussion,'' Forbes adviser Greg Mueller said Friday when asked if
anti-Bush ads will begin running soon. ``We are confident this has
boiled down to a Bush-Forbes race.''
</P>
<P>
   But new poll numbers indicate Arizona Sen. John McCain, who has
raised $9.3 million, could be the biggest beneficiary of a
Bush-Forbes crossfire, at least in the crucial New Hampshire
primary.
</P>
<P>
   A Zogby International poll, commissioned for Reuters and Boston
television station WHDH and conducted Oct. 8-10, showed Bush
maintaining a stout, but shrinking, lead over McCain in New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor topped the GOP field with support from 40
percent of the 608 likely voters in the state's Feb. 1 GOP primary.
McCain was second with 21 percent. Forbes was third with 12 percent
and Elizabeth Dole trailed at 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll has a margin of error of four percentage points,
meaning results could vary that much in either direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``What will happen when Forbes' negative ads on Bush hit full
swing?'' asked John Zogby, director of the polling company.
``Bush's support is leveling off while McCain's has increased. Bush
could be aided by a victory in Iowa (where McCain is not competing)
while McCain could be the beneficiary if Bush stumbles there. The
book is not closed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Zogby poll includes other numbers that could cause concern
in the Bush campaign. Fifty-six percent of the respondents to this
month's poll said they did not know enough about him to nominate
him for president. Thirty-nine percent said they did.
</P>
<P>
   A Zogby poll in New Hampshire in late April showed Bush at 38
percent, Dole at 15 percent and McCain in third place with only 9
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Former New Hampshire Sen. Warren Rudman, a national co-chairman
for the McCain campaign, said the new numbers show his man is in
``a solid second-place position.''
</P>
<P>
   The Zogby numbers align with a recent Franklin Pierce College
poll, conducted Oct. 3-6 , that showed Bush at 43 percent and
McCain at 23 percent, and all others in single digits. A September
poll by the college showed Bush at 48 percent, and McCain, Dole and
Forbes all at 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``While support for Governor Bush has fallen off slightly,
McCain's surprising strength seems to have come at the expense of
the other GOP contenders,'' said Robin Marra, director of the
Franklin Pierce College Polling Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
