u a BC-HOMECOMING-DESEGREGAT     10-15 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMECOMING-DESEGREGATION16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High school ends segregated election of homecoming queen
 &HT;    By Paul Donsky
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Thirty years after East Coweta High School's
classrooms and school buses were integrated, one last segregated
tradition went by the wayside Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   One student was crowned homecoming queen, ending a three-decade
practice of naming two winners each year _ one black and one white.
</P>
<P>
   Experts on Southern culture and history say racially segregated
social functions like homecoming and prom are not common but still
occur, mainly in small towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``People involved in it found it as a way of being inclusive,''
said Dan Carter, an Emory University professor who specializes in
Southern history. ``They were concerned that minority students who
came to majority institutions would become invisible.''
</P>
<P>
   East Coweta students say they think it is about time the school
crowned only one queen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's how it should have been all the time,'' said
senior Krista Kneuer, a member of the homecoming court, who is
white. ``If everybody is supposed to be equal, then there shouldn't
be two queens.''
</P>
<P>
   For many students, the racially divided homecoming court was an
embarrassing, backward tradition that reflected badly on their
school, located 40 miles south of Atlanta in Sharpsburg. It was a
true-life brush with segregation, something most students
experience only second-hand, through grainy pictures of ``colored''
water fountains in their history books.
</P>
<P>
   The change ``is for the better,'' said senior Emily Thompson, a
member of the homecoming court, who is black. ``Everything else is
present day. Homecoming court should be also.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-queen system began after the merging of the Coweta
County, Newnan city and black school systems. School officials at
the time felt it was a fair way to ensure that black female
students would be recognized during homecoming festivities, East
Coweta Principal Eddie Lovett said.
</P>
<P>
   Students lobbied for the change last fall. Student government
leaders began talking up the issue, and stories appeared in the
school newspaper, Smoke Signals. In a poll conducted by the paper,
64 percent of students who responded said the two-queen system
should be abolished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our school is so culturally diverse ... that that way just
wouldn't work anymore,'' said editor Jillian Brogan. ``To put
people in a category because of their race is just awful.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue came to a head in part because a Laotian student was
nominated last year for the homecoming court. She asked to be
placed in an ``other'' category rather than be classified as black
or white, which forced students to confront the issue, Brogan said.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time, students at nearby Newnan High School
voted to end their practice of naming black and white homecoming
queens. Next weekend the school celebrates its first homecoming
since that change.
</P>
<P>
   Students at Claxton High School in southeast Georgia voted to
end its two-queen system several years ago, said Assistant
Principal Joy Collins. Since then, students have elected both black
girls and white girls as homecoming queen.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone at East Coweta High is in favor of the change. Some
black students say a black queen won't be named at the school as
long as it remains a mostly white school. About one-third of the
school's 1,570 students are black.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of black students feel we should leave it the way it
was, because that's the only way there will be a black queen,''
said Melvenette Lowe, a black member of this year's homecoming
court.
</P>
<P>
   The current homecoming court has six members _ three white and
three black. It wasn't planned that way; that's just who the top
six vote-getters were, said Lovett.
</P>
<P>
   Some students sounded an optimistic tone, saying they believe
personality, not skin color, determines who becomes queen. As
proof, they note that half of this year's homecoming court is
black.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all comes down to how your classmates feel about you,''
said senior Shawn Reaves, a member of the homecoming court. ``I
don't think that (the queen) is going to always be a white person.
Hopefully, there will be a fair chance for both.'' East Coweta and
Newnan students are to be commended for requesting the change, said
Ted Ownby, a professor at the University of Mississippi's Center
for the Study of Southern Culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly a hopeful sign,'' he said. ``They're making the
precise decision that racial segregation belongs to another
generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Parent Laurie Voss, who has daughters in the 10th and 12th
grades at East Coweta, said the old segregated homecoming was
simply out of step with modern times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy with the decision not to have the separation
anymore,'' Voss said as she manned a refreshment stand at a
pre-homecoming carnival on Thursday. ``It brings us into the
'90s.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
