<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN TROOPS DRIVE TOWARD CHECHEN CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Federal troops and tanks drove to the outskirts of
Chechnya's capital Grozny on Friday as Russian commanders said they
were stepping up their effort to wipe out Islamic rebels in the
breakaway Caucasus region.
</P>
<P>
   But Moscow's campaign to win the hearts and minds of civilians
in Chechnya suffered a setback when it was reported that Russian
troops were forcing refugees from the fighting back into the
province.
</P>
<P>
   Conflicting reports about Russian losses also undermined the
generals' upbeat descriptions of the campaign, which Moscow has
insisted would avoid the costly mistakes of its 1994-96 war in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Federal commanders announced that Russia's campaign was entering
a second stage after troops occupied the strategically situated
town of Goragorsk after a heavy four-day bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   ``What started as an antiterrorist operation has grown into a
military one, with the appropriate tactics and weapons,'' General
Vyacheslav Ovchinnikov, commander of Russia's Interior Ministry
troops, said at a Moscow briefing Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Taking Goragorsk removed a major obstacle on a main route into
Grozny. News agencies said a large Russian column had moved to
within 10 miles of the capital, where Chechen militia were
reportedly putting up heavy resistance.
</P>
<P>
   The commander of Russian forces in the North Caucasus, General
Viktor Kazantsev, said his troops had completed setting up a
``security zone'' covering the northern third of Chechnya. With the
rebels trapped in the south, he said, federal forces would attack
and destroy them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to expect us anywhere, any time, and they must
constantly suffer losses,'' Kazantsev said.
</P>
<P>
   Chechen commanders acknowledge that they are losing ground to
the larger, better equipped Russian forces in the steppes of
northern Chechnya. But, mindful of the huge casualties they
inflicted in the last war after federal troops stormed Grozny and
entered the hilly southern regions, they seem to be waiting for the
Russians to try it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let the Russians shoot at us some more, we are a patient
people,'' rebel commander Shamil Basayev said in an interview
published on the rebels' Web site. Basayev is wanted by Russian
authorities for leading attacks on Russian regions outside
Chechnya, and Moscow blames him for a wave of deadly apartment
bombs that killed 300 last month.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, evidence emerged that the Russians are once again
wildly underreporting their losses. Friday, Russian generals said
they had lost 47 regular army troops and seven Interior Ministry
troops in Chechnya since fighting began last month. But another
officer, speaking on condition of anonymity, put the toll of
Interior Ministry troops alone at 116.
</P>
<P>
   ``I counted the death certificates myself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kazantsev also acknowledged that Russian forces had lost a third
jet in the conflict, a Su-25 attack plane, after the air force
initially denied it had been shot down.
</P>
<P>
   While Kazantsev threatened the rebel fighters, the Kremlin named
its new envoy to federal-controlled Chechnya, Nikolai Koshman.
</P>
<P>
   Koshman, who was prime minister of the pro-Moscow government
that was chased out when the rebels won back Grozny in 1996,
already faces a humanitarian crisis. Some 170,000 civilians have
fled Russian airstrikes and artillery bombardments. Friday, the New
York-based Human Rights Watch said Moscow was turning back Chechens
who tried to leave for other parts of Russia.
</P>
</TEXT>
