<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8406 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-SENSATIONS17-COX     10-15 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENSATIONS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Once you get past controversy, Brooklyn museum's `Sensation' an
interesting experience
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 17.
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's aim was off when he attacked
``Sensation,'' the notorious exhibition of contemporary British art
showing at the Brooklyn Museum. There's plenty here that is much
more offensive than the unobtrusive dung affixed to the painting of
the Virgin Mary.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition has more range than the controversy would have
you think, but it is dominated by a confrontational group of
artists. They practice what you might call either gross-out
hyper-realism or ``Duane Hanson does the British tabloids.'' In my
book, Jake and Dinos Chapman's mutant mannequins _ lifelike
sculptures of little girls with penis noses _ take the prize in the
disgusting category. Damien Hirst's piece with live maggots is a
close second.
</P>
<P>
   It is, however, important to make the distinction between works
that shock with no redeeming value, which the Chapman pieces
exemplify, and the ones that are interesting once you get past your
nausea, such like the Hirst. Among the biggest names of the group,
Hirst is definitely a showman, best known for pickling fish and
farm animals in large, white, framed tanks of formaldehyde. All his
sculptures here, including ``A Thousand Years,'' in which maggots
turn into flies that hover around a fake cow's head, are
meditations in one way or another on death. Indeed, life, death,
sex and religion _ art's fundamental topics _ are the main subjects
in the show.
</P>
<P>
   After such a recitation, you may wonder whether all of these
British artists consider nausea a necessary prerequisite to
understanding. No. The best work evokes other feelings:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Richard Billingham's sad, unflinching but loving photographs
of his blowsy mother, pathetic alcoholic father and their unkempt
home are hard to take because they are so powerfully truthful.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rachel Whiteread's elegiac room-size installation, 100
translucent resin casts of the space beneath chairs, makes absence
present, caught in time like a bug in amber.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jenny Saville, taking a page from Lucian Freud's paintings of
corpulent nudes, blows up the scale and focuses on the headless
fleshy torso or arranges bodies in abstract patterns, creating an
engaging tension by painting unlovely rippling skin with sensuous
abandon.
</P>
<P>
   Too often the shrillest work is the worst _ derivative or banal,
goosed up with electric shocks. Mona Hatoum has set a table and
replaced a plate with a video of the inside of her throat making
swallowing motions. This is in keeping with her exploration of
innards but is neither moving nor insightful. Perhaps that's why
she added the salacious title, ``Deep Throat.'' Like willful
children, these artists push the buttons of propriety. Giuliani,
the gullible parent, fell for it.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Ofili's Madonna was destined for oblivion until the mayor
stepped in. Now, it is installed behind glass as if it were
``Guernica'' or the Mona Lisa. Basically, it's a colorful image of
a black Madonna surrounded with shimmering striations like a
latter-day mosaic. The dung, presented in varnished balls, would
have been difficult to identify before the brouhaha. The clippings
from porn magazines, more offensive than the dung, also are
difficult to discern.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the artist's explanations about his African heritage and
the hip-hop updating of the image, both gestures seem gratuitous.
Judging from the patterns and colors of his other pieces in the
show, Ofili is a very good decorative painter. But you don't get
any respect for that in the art world. Is it possible that Ofili
added transgressive materials and imagery in order to be taken
seriously? Or to be noticed in a world bombarded with images?
</P>
<P>
   Because it makes us think about such things, visiting
``Sensation'' is ultimately an interesting experience. The museum's
labels and audio tour, narrated by David Bowie, create a context
for looking at the art. In a departure from the norm, both
regularly pose questions, emphasizing that it is up to the viewer
to make a decision about the work.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming you don't consider it the height of moral turpitude,
``Sensation'' is also naughty fun, on the level of, say, a whoopee
cushion.
</P>
<P>
   During my visit, ``Sensation'' was quite crowded, and the gift
shop was doing a brisk business selling ``Art-Danger'' pins,
body-part soaps, ``Health Warning'' T-shirts and Zoo Doo. Whatever
people thought of the art, the fact that they came seemed a rebuke
to Giuliani for trying to shut down the show.
</P>
<P>
   Said Damien Leebold, as he refilled the shelves with catalogs,
``People like to decide for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sensation:
</P>
<P>
   Young British Artists From the Saatchi Collection''
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn Museum of Art,
</P>
<P>
   200 Eastern Parkway, Brooklyn, N.Y. Through Jan. 9. 10 a.m.-
</P>
<P>
   5 p.m. Wednesdays-Saturdays; 11 a.m.-6 p.m. weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Children 16 and under not admitted unless accompanied by an
adult. $6.75-$9.75.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: 1-877-427-5248.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Provocative, but not necessarily in the way the
artists intended.
</P>
<P>
   See ``Sensation'': Nexus Contemporary Art Center has organized a
weekend trip to New York, Nov. 12-14, for an exhibition outing. For
information, call director Sam Gappmayer at 404-688-1970.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fox writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
