<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL BUSINESS NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL: OIL GIANT REVISES ACCOUNTING
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's big oil company, Petroleo Brasileiro SA, reduced
shareholders' equity by about 4.8 billion reais, or $2.4 billion,
as it shifted its accounting practices to U.S. standards in
preparation for listing its shares in New York. Petrobras, as the
company is called, changed the way it accounts for drilling
operations, pensions and health plans. The government, which owns a
controlling stake in Petrobras, is opening the country's
oil-exploration industry to competition from outside companies.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL: LEGAL THREATS
</P>
<P>
   The chief justice of Brazil's Supreme Court, Carlos Velloso,
threatened to sue The Economist in British courts over its coverage
criticizing the court's annulment of government measures to tax the
pensions of retired civil servants. Justice Velloso called the
criticism unfounded. The magazine is published by the London-based
Pearson PlC. In another legal skirmish over a sensitive financial
issue, Minas Gerais, the Brazilian state governed by a former
president, Itamar Franco, has sued Arminio Fraga, president of the
central bank. Fraga has cautioned foreign investors against placing
money in Minas Gerais.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: INFLATION PRESSURE
</P>
<P>
   Canada's consumer price index rose by three-tenths of a percent
in September, a 2.6 percent annual inflation rate, which is the
highest since June 1995, Statistics Canada reported. Economists
noted that the core inflation rate, excluding energy and food
prices, also was 2.6 percent. The Toronto-based investment dealer
Nesbitt Burns Inc. said the core inflation rate, which was less
than 1 percent at the beginning of the year, ``appears poised to
move higher as rising energy costs spill into other prices.''
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: UNION CLAIMS VICTORY AT PARTS MAKER
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian Auto Workers union said it had won a certification
vote at a seating plant owned by Magna International Inc., a
leading automotive parts maker. A ruling on the outcome of the vote
at the plant in Windsor, Ontario, which makes seats for Chrysler
minivans, is in the hands of the Ontario Labor Relations Board. But
if the union is certified, it will be the first successful union
penetration of Magna, which has 55 plants in Canada and 40 in the
United States and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   NORTH KOREA: HYUNDAI TOUR DELAYED
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean conglomerate Hyundai put on hold its plans to
send a survey team to North Korea in preparation for construction
of an industrial complex. A 16-member Hyundai team had been
scheduled to arrive in North Korea this weekend for a 10-day survey
of possible sites. In a visit earlier this month, Chung Ju-yung,
the honorary chairman of Hyundai, met the country's top leader, Kim
Jong Il, who gave his approval for a complex.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH KOREA: CAR MAKER SEEKS FOREIGN LINK
</P>
<P>
   South Korea's largest car maker, Hyundai Motor Co., is seeking
to form a strategic alliance with a foreign partner, the Hyundai
president, Lee Kye-ahn, said. ``We are considering strategic
alliance with a foreign company to contribute to our technological,
financial and marketing capabilities,'' Lee said. ``We have had
offers and we are also making offers.''
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH KOREA: STOCK INQUIRY BY SEOUL
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean Financial Supervisory Service said it would
investigate possible illegal stock purchases in a domestic
telecommunications giant, Dacom Corp., by LG Group and four other
major conglomerates. LG and the Tongyang business groups are
suspected of failing to report major purchases of Dacom stocks to
the authorities. By law, companies' failure to report huge
purchases of stocks can result in fines of more than 5 million and
one year in prison for the individuals responsible.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BANK ALLIANCE
</P>
<P>
   Two European banks _ Rabobank Nederland and DG Bank AG _
announced a strategic alliance that will merge their corporate and
investment banking businesses. The new bank, to be called DG-Rabo
International, hopes to enlist other partners in Europe. The banks
said they had discussed bringing Caisse Nationale de Credit
Agricole of France into the fold.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD TRADE
</P>
<P>
   LAMB COMPLAINT FILED
</P>
<P>
   Australia and New Zealand have formalized their dispute over
lamb trade with the United States after informal talks failed. The
two countries are challenging the imposition by the United States
of a three-year quota on lamb imports and have asked the World
Trade Organization to establish a panel to resolve the dispute. In
1998, the imports were worth about $140 million, an amount U.S.
commercial lamb farmers called a threat to their business.
</P>
</TEXT>
