<SLUG> BC-INVEST-MGM-FILM-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE 3 FOR KERKORIAN: THE REBUILDING OF MGM  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOANNE LEGOMSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This time, it looks as if Kirk Kerkorian wants to build his film
studio into a player.
</P>
<P>
   When Kerkorian, the billionaire investor bought
Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer in 1996, it was the third time he had done so.
After the previous purchases, he unloaded assets before reselling
the company. Many analysts assumed that MGM was in for a repeat
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some of them believe that Kerkorian, 82, wants to return
the studio that was once home to the likes of Clark Gable and Judy
Garland, _ and which counts last quarter's ``Stigmata'' and ``The
Thomas Crown Affair'' among its hits _ to its former glory.
</P>
<P>
   After two and a half years of mediocre performance, the company
installed new management in April: Alex Yemenidjian, former
president of MGM Grand, a casino-hotel company that is controlled
by Kerkorian's Tracinda Corp., was named chief executive. MGM has
also bought the Polygram and Orion film libraries, tripling its
holdings to 5,200 titles.
</P>
<P>
   And it recently began talks with cable operators and satellite
broadcasters _ it will not identify them _ aimed at creating new
MGM-brand cable networks.
</P>
<P>
   If these moves generate sufficient cash flow and stanch MGM's
losses, which come largely from its film and television production
and which totaled $157.6 million last year, the rewards could be
considerable.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for entertainment is growing, said Frederick W. Moran, an
analyst at Jefferies &AMP; Co. ``MGM is one of few pure plays in filmed
entertainment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a public offering in 1997, Tracinda sold 10.9 percent of MGM
for $20 a share, and although the stock rose as high as $27 in
early 1998, it finished last month at just $17.50.
</P>
<P>
   A key factor weighing on the stock price was a secondary
offering planned for this month that would have raised $750
million, most of it to pay down debt. On Oct. 5, MGM canceled the
offering, instead announcing a $720 million rights offering that
allows shareholders to buy additional shares for just $14.50
apiece. That sent the stock higher; it closed at $22.5625 on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Since Kerkorian has pledged to exercise his rights, he will kick
in the largest part of the money being raised _ something that
Jeffrey Logsdon, an analyst at the Seidler Companies, calls
encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   The stock, trading at 18 times analysts' estimate of 2000 cash
flow, is not cheap. But Logsdon said his 12-month price target of
$26 did not include potential cable alliances. Analysts say these
could add up to $17 to the current price.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to securing wider distribution for MGM titles,
Yemenidjian, 43, said the company would release MGM movies on
digital video disks and the Internet. ``We inherited a company with
the best content and the weakest distribution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Putting the studio's production business on a profitable footing
will be tougher than improving distribution, analysts said. But
they regard two recent co-production deals as steps in the right
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from those deals, the newest James Bond film, ``The World
is Not Enough,'' is expected to generate $100 million to $125
million for MGM in domestic theaters. It is to be released on Nov.
17.
</P>
<P>
   But there are risks. Unlike its rivals, MGM has no theme parks
or television stations to fall back on.
</P>
<P>
   Others are encouraged by the positive cash flow MGM reported
last Tuesday. Mary Chris Gay, a fund manager at Legg Mason, said
that could be attributed in part to Yemenidjian's success in
cutting marketing costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
