<HEADER>
A8418 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-DIARRHEA-VACCINE-     10-15 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DIARRHEA-VACCINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY WITHDRAWS DIARRHEA VACCINE FOR INFANTS AND CHILDREN
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ American Home Products, the manufacturer of the only
licensed vaccine to prevent the most common cause of severe
diarrhea among infants and children, announced Friday that it was
withdrawing the vaccine from the market because of concerns that it
could cause a painful, potentially fatal bowel obstruction.
</P>
<P>
   The diarrhea is caused by the rotavirus, and last year the
government recommended that every infant in the United States get
the protective vaccine. One million children swallowed three doses
of the vaccine, RotaShield, at 2, 4 and 6 months of age, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   But in July the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said
no one should get the vaccine because a program monitoring side
effects suggested a link between the vaccine and the bowel
condition, called intussusception.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, prompted by more than 100 reports of intussusception to
the agency _ more than half of them within a week of vaccination _
American Home Products has asked doctors and health workers to
return all unused vaccine immediately. It said it would wait for
completed studies to determine whether withdrawal of the vaccine
would be permanent.
</P>
<P>
   The drug company's action leaves the United States without a
rotavirus vaccine just at the time when the virus tends to occur
most often, from November to May. Rotavirus infects more than half
a million American children, usually from 3 to 35 months of age,
and leads to 500,000 doctors' visits, 50,000 hospitalizations and
about 40 deaths, officials at the disease control centers said.
</P>
<P>
   Rotavirus is also said to be the biggest diarrheal killer of
children around the world, accounting for 600,000 deaths a year,
chiefly from dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   RotaShield has been approved for use in Europe but has not been
marketed there, said Doug Petkus, a spokesman for American Home
Products. Researchers are working on half a dozen other rotavirus
vaccines, but they are still in experimental stages.
</P>
<P>
   The developments are highly embarrassing to federal health
officials. The vaccine was developed at the National Institutes of
Health. Even before the Food and Drug Administration licensed the
vaccine to Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories, a subsidiary of American Home
Products, the centers for disease control promoted it as the new
weapon against rotavirus.
</P>
<P>
   The situation with RotaShield is the latest in a series of
problems for American Home Products, of Madison, N.J. Last week the
company agreed to pay at least $3.75 billion to settle claims that
its half of the diet drug combination fen-phen caused heart
problems. And over the last year, it withdrew the painkiller Duract
because it caused fatal liver problems; agreed to a
multimillion-dollar settlement of lawsuits claiming that the
contraceptive Norplant caused side effects, and recalled more than
half a million kits used to treat deadly allergic reactions because
they were apparently not potent enough.
</P>
<P>
   The company's action comes one week before an advisory committee
to the CDC on vaccines is scheduled to meet in Atlanta to review
studies to determine whether the vaccine led to bowel obstruction.
Full data will not be complete by the time of the meeting on Oct.
22, CDC and drug company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   As of Sept. 24, the CDC had received reports of intussusception
among 108 infants, and nearly 100 were confirmed or strongly
suspected cases. Among them, 56 had onset of symptoms within one
week of receiving the vaccine and an additional 9 had onset within
the second week.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeffrey Koplan, the CDC director, said the findings would
still be discussed at the meeting because the scientific review was
continuing and would not be affected by the product's withdrawal.
``As planned, CDC will seek a recommendation from the Advisory
Committee on Immunization Practices regarding the use of this
vaccine among children in the U.S.,'' Dr. Koplan said.
</P>
<P>
   Available information shows no on-going risk to children given
RotaShield in the past, Dr. Koplan and the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the CDC and American Home Products have shared data on
the vaccine's side effects, the company did not consult the disease
centers before withdrawing RotaShield, according to Barbara
Reynolds, a CDC spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA called the voluntary withdrawal ``an appropriate
action,'' said Larry Bachorik, a spokesman for the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Intussusception results when a section of bowel slides inward,
like a telescope, into another part of the bowel. In severe cases,
a previously healthy infant suddenly screams in pain.
</P>
<P>
   Other symptoms include persistent vomiting and a bowel movement
that appears black. A doctor can often feel a knot from the
telescoped bowel and make a tentative diagnosis. Confirmation comes
from giving a child a barium enema and then X-rays. In some cases
the enema itself can straighten out the telescoped bowel. But in
others surgery is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of a vaccine, the CDC urged parents to teach
children the importance of hand washing with soap to reduce the
spread of rotavirus.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating that the rotavirus vaccine problem might renew
criticisms of vaccines in general, Dr. Koplan said that ``continued
immunization of children with licensed vaccines is critical to
their well-being.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
