<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8441 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-2TAK     10-15 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY REBUTS CHARGE THAT HE ABANDONED DEMOCRATS BY LEAVING
SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In 1995, Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey gave one
of the most bittersweet speeches of his 17-year political career,
announcing to a roomful of stunned and tearful supporters that he
would retire at the end of 1996. Wearily, he declared that
``politics is broken.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Bradley is back in politics, running for the Democratic
presidential nomination. And with the former basketball star now
locked in a tightening race with Vice President Al Gore, those
words and that action are suddenly being used by his rival as
ammunition against him.
</P>
<P>
   With escalating harshness, Gore and his allies have recently
accused Bradley of abandoning, even disavowing, his party in the
months that followed the Republican takeover of Congress after the
1994 elections. They say he considered running for president in
1996 as an independent, an unpardonable act of disloyalty in their
eyes. And they suggest that his retirement in his party's hour of
need demonstrates that he would not stand up well under the
adversity of a long campaign or a problem-fraught presidency.
</P>
<P>
   In his quiet, methodical way, Bradley has tried to dismiss those
attacks as ``the politics of the dart board.'' But having clearly
felt their sting, he has begun defending his record as a loyal
Democrat who campaigned for Democratic candidates after he retired
and who left Congress to search for ways to revive his party, not
undermine it.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview this week, Bradley described his life since 1996
as a time of rejuvenation, of reconnecting with voters and of
learning about life beyond the cloistered world of Washington _ a
world, he asserts, that Gore remains trapped inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had I not left the Senate, I don't think I would be doing a
presidential campaign now,'' he said. ``The fact that I had
returned to private life, working in the private sector, that I was
teaching and once again writing and speaking all over the country
were all things that I wanted to do and each of them refreshed me
in a new way.''
</P>
<P>
   But he insisted that he had not thought seriously about leaving
the party, or of running on a third-line for president. ``I knew I
was Democrat,'' he said. ``I figured if you were going to make a
difference, you had to work within the Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many democrats feel a lingering bitterness toward Bradley
because of both the timing of his retirement and the way he
announced it. The Republicans had won control of Congress in
November 1994 and were just 8 months into a campaign of rolling
back Democratic programs when Bradley announced his plans to
retire.
</P>
<P>
   And then, as if losing one of the party's best known senators at
that low moment was not enough, Bradley gave a speech attacking not
just the Republicans, but the beleaguered Democrats as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans are infatuated with the `magic' of the private
sector and reflexively criticize government as the enemy of
freedom,'' Bradley said in that speech. ``And the Democrats
distrust the market, preach government as the answer to our
problems and prefer the bureaucrat they know to the consumer they
can't control. Neither party speaks to people where they live their
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats, including some of Bradley's friends, felt
betrayed by those words. But in the interview, Bradley said he had
been surprised by their responses, since he had expressed similar
thoughts before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt many politicians were not leading from core
convictions, but from polls,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In questioning Bradley's party loyalty, the Gore campaign has
focused on more than just the retirement speech. On the day after
his announcement, Bradley told reporters who asked about it that,
``I have not ruled out an independent route'' to the White House.
He also acknowledged making phone calls to retired Gen. Colin
Powell and Ross Perot to discuss his plans.
</P>
<P>
   Later that year, Bradley participated in two conference calls
with six other prominent politicians, four of them Democrats and
two of them independents. Two had run for president, former Sens.
Gary Hart and Paul Tsongas, both Democrats, and at least one other,
former Connecticut Gov. Lowell Weicker, an independent, had been
mentioned as a possible third-party presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley now contends that media coverage of those conversations
was overblown. The discussions were part of an effort by the group
to define the major issues facing the nation, he says. But he
claims they did not discuss mounting an independent campaign for
president.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he refused to rule out a third-party candidacy in
1995, he chalked it up partly to frustration with the two-party
system, which he has likened to a broken thermostat: ``You turn the
dial and nothing happens.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said vanity may have also played a role. ``I think I was
having a little difficulty moving off stage,'' he said. ``From my
standpoint, it was never really a serious possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said his decision to step down was not prompted by any
particular event, but was more the result of a gradual realization
that Congress had become overly partisan and that money had become
too important in politics.
</P>
<P>
   The seeds of his dismay were actually sown in 1990, when he
nearly lost his Senate seat to an upstart Republican, Christine
Todd Whitman, despite outspending her 12-to-1 and lavishing more
than $1 million on polling over several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can have too much money, and I had too much money
in 1990,'' he said in the interview.
</P>
<P>
   What helped crystallize his disenchantment with politics, as
well as his desire to move onto other things, was writing his
memoirs, ``Time Present, Time Past,'' which he completed in 1996,
he said. Drawing an analogy to his 10-season basketball career, he
noted that he decided to retire from the New York Knicks in 1977
shortly after finishing a book about playing professional
basketball, ``Life on the Run.'' He won his Senate seat the next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as in basketball, where my interest in political life
began to go up as the interest in basketball began to go down, my
interest in politics began to go down as my interest in the other
things went up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his friends and aides say they think that Bradley
retired from the Senate largely to prepare for a Presidential
campaign. ``It's not easy to be in the Senate and campaign,'' said
Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., who has endorsed Bradley. ``I
know he left meaning to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley asserted that he was not seriously thinking about
running for president in 1995. ``I was thinking about going out and
doing what I ended up doing,'' he said, which included writing a
book, lecturing at Stanford, Notre Dame and the University of
Maryland, and giving speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I do things, I kind of live in the moment and then the
moment evolves into something else,'' he said. Though he is known
as a meticulous planner who carefully deliberates every decision no
matter how small, he added, ``I don't try to set some kind of
target and then shape life toward that achievement. Because that
kills spontaneity and creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought the Gore campaign's attacks on his loyalty
and his toughness were unfair, Bradley demurred. But an aide called
the assertions ``laughable,'' contending that Bradley was
considered a fearsome competitor as a basketball player.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democratic members of Congress whom Bradley helped in
those campaigns said in recent interviews that they thought the
Gore camp's attacks on Bradley's loyalty were unfair and
potentially divisive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same old political industrial complex,'' said Rep.
Rod Blagojevich, D-Ill., who has not endorsed anyone in the race.
``Gore ought to tell us what he's for and where he'd like to take
America. He has to make a case for why he should be president. Many
of us are waiting for him to do that. It is not helpful that he
attacks Bill Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mark Udall, D-Colo., , said, ``I think part of Senator
Bradley's appeal, frankly, is that he is extremely comfortable with
himself. He seems to have a vision that he is going to share with
Democrats and the nation. And that comes, in part, from taking a
bit of time out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
