<HEADLINE>
THE RAMS BECOME HOT COMMODITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - After five weeks of the NFL season, the hottest
fantasy players around play for the (drumroll optional):
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis Rams?
</P>
<P>
   Stunning as it might seem, the Rams have built an almost
unstoppable offense. In fantasy leagues across the land, St. Louis
players are being snapped up quicker than refunds on Diamondbacks
playoff tickets.
</P>
<P>
   In my league, they're even asking about owner Georgia Frontiere,
though she's clearly lost a step.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the credit has gone to St. Louis quarterback Kurt
Warner, the former Iowa Barnstormers (of the Arena Football League)
star who leads the league with 14 touchdown passes in four games.
</P>
<P>
   It took an injury to big-money free agent Trent Green to get
Warner in the lineup, and he may never come out. He's taking full
advantage of his chance to start, which is especially sweet after
he was cut by the Packers and played in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's wide receiver Isaac Bruce, the oft-injured enigma
who has stayed healthy this year and caught four touchdowns Sunday
against the hated 49ers (hated by me anyway, I don't know about the
Rams).
</P>
<P>
   Bolstering the receiver corps are first-round pick Torry Holt
and Az-zahir Hakim, who scored four touchdowns two weeks ago and
forced a legion of grumpy sportswriters to learn how to spell his
name.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget running back Marshall Faulk, another fan of
adhesive tape who has given the Rams a threat at running back. The
St. Louis passing attack is so potent, Faulk at times has been
reduced to a decoy.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dick Vermeil, who is undoubtedly weeping somewhere at this
moment, has also drawn his share of kudos for leading this group
into contention in the NFC.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, none of those guys deserves the real credit.
</P>
<P>
   That goes to the Rams offensive line, which has given Warner
enough time to balance his checkbook and have high tea while he
peruses the field for an open receiver.
</P>
<P>
   The line is led by left tackle and man-mountain Orlando Pace,
the former Ohio State star and the first overall pick in the 1997
draft. The Rams also added guard Adam Timmerman, a former Packer,
to solidify the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in a tough defense that keeps getting the ball back, and
you have a pretty decent team.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you could argue that the Rams are a house of cards,
waiting to topple at the first sign of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Warner is unproven and could end up being a one-year wonder, a
la Jeff Blake, Scott Mitchell and scores of others now toting clip
boards around the NFL. NFL teams are great at adjusting to
overnight sensations (Jake Plummer comes to mind), and the real
test will come when Warner must overcome defenses designed to stop
him.
</P>
<P>
   On the wide receiver front, Bruce is injury-prone, and if he
goes down, the Rams' ability to stretch defenses will be seriously
hampered. The other receivers are either inexperienced or Ricky
Proehl.
</P>
<P>
   At running back, Faulk is always a question mark. He can
dominate one week and disappear the next, depending on his mood.
</P>
<P>
   If you like to roll the dice, you might want to trade away a top
St. Louis player, say Faulk or Bruce, with the idea that it's all
downhill from here.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, the Rams already have exceeded everyone's expectations,
so there. All these guys who are always hurt may stay healthy. And
Warner may lead the league in passing. And the Rams may go to the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Naaah. &QL; 
(at)j  &QL; 
Tip of the week
</P>
<P>
   (at)j  &QL; 
Dinged-up San Diego running back Natrone Means was held out of the
Detroit game because it was played at the Silverdome on artificial
turf. I expect him to return to action on his home grass this week
and put up decent numbers against Seattle. &QL; 
(at)j  &QL; 
Waiver wire
</P>
<P>
   (at)j  &QL; 
With Green Bay receiver Bill Schroeder nursing an ankle sprain,
backup Corey Bradford could have a nice game against the Broncos.
Look for Arizona running back Michael Pittman to get more work than
Adrian Murrell against the Redskins this week. &QL; 
(at)j  &QL; 
One-hit wonder
</P>
<P>
   (at)j  &QL; 
This week it's Miami receiver Oronde Gadsden, who helped Dan Marino
chase away Father Time for just one more week. &QL; 
 &QL; 
