<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-EURO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORIES THINK THAT THEY HAVE FOUND A CAMPAIGN ISSUE: THE EURO 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Sensing that his beleaguered party has found an issue
to cut into the governing Labor Party's domination of Britain's
public life, the Conservative leader, William Hague, said Friday
that he would tour the country to rally Britons against the
European common currency.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would appear in cities, towns and villages
broadcasting the message ``vote Conservative to save the pound''
from the back of a flatbed truck emblazoned with the slogan,
``Battle for the Pound, Battle for Britain.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea recalled the soapbox that former Prime Minister John
Major, also a Conservative, successfully used to win support when
he was lagging in the polls before the 1992 election.
</P>
<P>
   With little else going their way since their overwhelming defeat
in 1997, the Tories have found favor with the public by demonizing
the European Union as ``the federal superstate'' and characterizing
the Labor Party policy of keeping open the option of adopting the
euro as one of ``scrapping the pound,'' a resonant symbol of
tradition and nationhood.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair, in starting up his own campaign on
Thursday to emphasize the benefits to Britain of membership in the
European Union, acknowledged that the Conservative attack on the
single currency had proven ``often effective.'' Reacting to the
Conservative appeal to nationalistic instincts, he insisted that
the real patriotic cause was embracing Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Though Blair was joined by Michael Heseltine and Kenneth Clarke,
both heavyweight members of the last Conservative government, and
Charles Kennedy, leader of the Liberal Democrats, in a rare
cross-party start-up for his Britain in Europe campaign, he played
down the thorny issue of monetary union and focused instead on the
merits of closer association with other European nations.
</P>
<P>
   He said nothing that changed the government's so-called plan and
decide policy, whereby the British are encouraged to prepare for
the possibility of the country's adopting the euro some years from
now while an actual decision is postponed until there is more
economic justification and the British public is more accepting.
</P>
<P>
   Hague was quick on Friday to depth-charge that effort, saying
the new campaign was clearly one promoting the euro itself, not
just Europe. `` Blair has finally, if halfheartedly, joined the
debate on the single currency,'' the Tory leader said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether to join the 11 other nations that agreed Jan. 1 on the
euro as legal tender is the biggest political decision facing
Britain, and in the last week the Conservatives have turned it into
the one on which they hope to work their way back into power.
</P>
<P>
   Under Hague, the Conservative position has been to discourage
thoughts of ever entering monetary union and to rule it out
absolutely through the next elected Parliament, or until 2008. But
at the Conservative conference last week in Blackpool, he moved the
party into an even more hostile stance, placing it not just in
opposition to the common currency but also at greater distance from
the European Union itself. He suggested that the founding treaty of
1957 be renegotiated in Britain's favor and that the country refuse
to participate in any new arrangements that do not allow the
country the right to escape rules it does not like.
</P>
<P>
   Blair saw in this an opportunity to portray the Conservatives as
intent on disengaging entirely from the Continent, an extremist
position that would command little support in Britain, instead of
one of shunning the common currency, now the wish of most Britons.
``We believe that by being part of Europe, we advance our own
self-interest as the British nation,'' he said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The campaigns, though, have little to do with economics and
everything to do with public opinion. The Conservatives oppose
swapping the pound for the euro, even if it becomes economically
justifiable. Labor favors the idea and will find it economically
justifiable once it becomes clear that the British public supports
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
