A8447 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-YOUNG-CANCER16-COX     10-15 0464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-CANCER16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-Atlanta Mayor Young diagnosed with cancer
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Kurylo
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Former Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young has prostate cancer
and is scheduled for surgery in early December.
</P>
<P>
   Young's cancer was diagnosed in late September, when a routine
blood test prompted doctors to do an ultrasound and biopsy. His
prognosis is good because the cancer was caught early, said Lee
Echols, a spokesman for Young.
</P>
<P>
   The 67-year-old former U.N. ambassador was traveling Friday to
the Virgin Islands, where he was scheduled to speak and spend the
weekend, Echols said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andy is very optimistic about his prognosis,'' Echols said.
``He is a man of very strong faith. Fortunately, this is a curable
disease. It will force him to slow down his pace and his schedule
for several months so that he can take care of himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The surgery will be at Emory University Hospital, and afterward
Young's doctors will determine what other treatment might be
necessary, Echols said.
</P>
<P>
   Young is chairman of Atlanta-based GoodWorks International, a
consulting company that brings together investors and
entrepreneurs, particularly in Third World countries. He helped
bring the Summer Olympic Games to Atlanta in 1996 and testified
about that effort before Congress on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued Friday, Young said he wanted to go public
with his diagnosis partly to encourage middle-aged and older men to
have regular prostate screenings.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many of my friends and colleagues have had this operation _
and at a much younger age _ that I consider it a blessing that I've
made it almost to age 68 with no difficulties,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Prostate cancer is the most common cancer, excluding skin
cancer, of American men. The American Cancer Society estimates
179,300cases of prostate cancer will be diagnosed in the United
States and 37,000 men will die of the disease this year.
</P>
<P>
   African-Americans have a prostate cancer rate nearly twice that
of whites, and black men are twice as likely to die of the disease.
Treatments include surgery, radiation, hormone therapy and
chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Young has had regular blood tests _ PSA tests _ to
screen for prostate cancer. ``Andy's commitment to prostate
screening has enabled him to detect this early,'' Echols said.
</P>
<P>
   Young will curtail his activities in the first couple months of
next year, Echols said. ``This is major surgery and will require
some additional recuperation time.''
</P>
<P>
   Young's first wife, Jean, died of cancer in 1994. They had been
married 40 years. In 1996, he married Atlanta schoolteacher Carolyn
Watson in a ceremony in Cape Town, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
