<SLUG> BC-N.H.-TAXES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT REJECTS N.H. PLAN FOR STATE PROPERTY TAX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N. H. _ New Hampshire's Supreme Court dropped a bomb on
the State House on Friday, rejecting the statewide property tax
that underlies the public school funding plan agonizingly crafted
last spring by the legislature and Gov. Jeanne Shaheen.
</P>
<P>
   The news ignited emergency meetings around the capitol building
Friday as lawmakers faced the prospect of finding a way to raise
some $440 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   The court declared unconstitutional a part of the funding plan
that phased in the property tax for some towns. Without that
provision, though, it is not clear whether political leaders, who
took months of bitter debate to agree on the formula rejected
Friday, could easily find a new compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``By striking down the statewide property tax, the court has
endangered our ability to keep schools operating,'' Shaheen said in
a terse statement after the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The fight over how to pay for public schools has been the most
divisive political issue in modern state history. In 1997, the
state Supreme Court ruled that the state's traditional financing
system, which relied heavily on local property taxes, unfairly
discriminated against less affluent communities.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers then scrambled to find a new way to raise money, with
some even suggesting that New Hampshire impose its first ever
income tax. To the shock of many and horror of some both houses of
the legislature passed versions of an income tax, but the effort
then failed in the face of threatened Shaheen veto.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the fight looked to be settled, though the solution was
under legal attack from rich and poor towns alike. Yet after
Friday's court ruling many, including the governor, were dismayed
that the battle will now escalate instead of abate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unfortunate that the supreme court was unwilling to give
the education-funding plan time to work. Taxpayers across the state
were seeing property tax relief and communities were making major
new investments in their schools,'' Shaheen said.
</P>
<P>
   Property tax bills under the new system have already been mailed
in many towns. School districts are counting on the money and most
residents in the state are looking forward to Christmas season tax
bills hundreds and in some cases thousands of dollars less than
last year's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought it would go this way,'' the state's revenue
commissioner, Stanley Arnold, said after reading the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of an income tax hope that the court decision will
give them added ammunition. The state senate was already scheduled
to take up the income tax issue again on Tuesday. It will now do so
on Thursday, said Senate President Beverly Hollingworth with the
House planning to convene as soon as the Senate takes action.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen would not say whether the ruling had changed her
opposition to the income tax. ``The question was asked,'' said
Hollingworth who met with Shaheen, House Speaker Donna Sytek and
other state officials. ``She said that she did not want to see the
schools closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Shaheen's support, an income tax would probably not
become law, because, said lawmakeres, it would be extremely
difficult to convince two-thirds of the Republican-controlled
400-member House to override a Shaheen veto of an income tax.
</P>
<P>
   If the legislature is not able to come to a quick agreement the
state's bond ratings could be threatened. Last spring, after the
state missed a court-imposed April 1 deadline to find a solution,
bond rating agencies put the state on their ``watch lists'' - a
warming to investors that ratings could drop.
</P>
<P>
   Political leaders were quick to stress that they would not,
under any circumstances, permit a shutdown of the state's public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will the schools close. No the schools will not close,''
Hollingworth said. ``What will happen is that the money will come
from the general fund.'' All other state services save the running
of prisons ``will have to wait in line,'' for their money, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the state's poor school districts, meanwhile, said
that they were frustrated that the issue has taken years to settle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This chaos is really unfounded,'' said Andru Volinsky, lead
lawyer for the coaltion named for the mill town of Claremont that
first sued the state in 1991. ``This is inexcusable and it's
happened to them every time. When will they finally learn to plan
for alternatives?''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Sytek, an income tax opponent, predicted that
lawmakers will impose a new statewide property tax, restructured to
make sure that it passes constitutional muster.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever lawmakers do, they should do it quickly, said the man
in charge of collecting the Live Free or Die state's taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legislature is going to have to take action rapidly if
they want to have any sense of normalcy,'' Arnold said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
