<HEADLINE>
SWISS FREEZE BANK ACCOUNT THAT MAY BE LINKED TO KAZAKHSTAN
PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By STEVE LeVINE with JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALMATY, Kazakhstan _ After the government of Kazakhstan asked
the Swiss to look into foreign bank accounts held by one of the
opponents of the Kazakh president, the Swiss wound up freezing an
account kept for the benefit of the president himself.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Devaud, the investigating magistrate in Geneva, froze an
account in August at Credit Agricole Indosuez, the Swiss affiliate
of a French bank, that Devaud believes is available for the benefit
of President Nursultan Nazarbayev, people with knowledge of the
inquiry said. However, it could not be determined if the
president's name is actually on the account.
</P>
<P>
   The exact source of the Kazakh money held in Switzerland could
not be determined. Kazakhstan, a Caspian Sea nation of 15 million
people about five times the size of France, has received more than
$2 billion in signing bonuses from foreign companies for rights to
explore and develop its vast oil fields in recent years. At least
some of the money was deposited in government accounts in Swiss
banks, people with knowledge of the bonuses said.
</P>
<P>
   The freeze on the bank accounts followed a request by Kazakh
government prosecutors who asked Devaud to examine the assets of a
vocal opponent of Nazarbayev, the self-exiled former prime
minister, Akezhan Kazhegeldin, who served from 1994 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Devaud widened the money laundering inquiry that had
focused on high officials of the Russian government, and ended up
freezing several Kazakh accounts in at least two Swiss banks,
people with knowledge of the order said.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss lawyers for the Kazakh government have appealed to a
Geneva court to lift the freeze order, and the case is pending. A
spokesman for the Kazakh government declined comment, as did
Devaud.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has been the main focus of Swiss investigators, but
because of suspicions about money laundering in other former parts
of the Soviet Union, the Swiss have begun looking at bank accounts
held by the governments of Ukraine and Kazakhstan and some of their
leading politicians.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The examination of Kazakh assets is separate from a Swiss
investigation of a construction company, Mabetex Project
Engineering Group of Lugano, that performed major construction work
in both Russia and Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
   Mabetex won large contracts to renovate the Kremlin and,
according to investigators, paid kickbacks to Russian officials. It
is also accused of providing credit card accounts for President
Boris N. Yeltsin and his two daughters, which Yeltsin has denied.
</P>
<P>
   Mabetex also did construction work in the past few years in the
new capital city that Nazarbayev has built in Astana, located on
the country's vast steppe. Among Mabetex's work was the
construction of a new Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss authorities are looking into whether Mabetex may have paid
kickbacks or provided other benefits like credit cards to Kazakh
officials in return for construction contracts, according to people
with knowledge of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Nazarbayev, 59, Kazakhstan's former Communist Party leader
during the Soviet period, rules his republic autocratically. He has
formed strong friendships with power figures in both the Democratic
and Republican parties in the United States, Kazakhstan's main
guarantor of independence from Russia, and most recently visited
the White House in April.
</P>
<P>
   Since August, the State Department has been considering
sanctions against Kazakhstan because it sold some 40 MiG fighter
aircraft to North Korea, a rogue nation that the United States
views as a supporter of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Washington has criticized Kazakhstan for its
treatment of Kazhegeldin, the former prime Minister and opponent of
the president. Kazhegeldin, 47, was barred from running for
president in January, failed to qualify for last Sunday's
parliamentary elections, and last month was briefly arrested in
Moscow on a Kazakh accusation of corruption and abuse of power. He
was later released without being charged.
</P>
<P>
   Kazakhstan has accused Kazhegeldin of enriching himself as prime
Minister, and as part of its campaign against him the government
asked Switzerland to disclose any bank assets held by him or his
family. Kazhegeldin has denied the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Kazhegeldin also held $4.5 million in deposits at Pictet &AMP; Cie,
a Geneva bank, at least until 1997. But he withdrew most or all of
the funds from Switzerland and moved them to an undisclosed
destination, according to documents of the accounts.
</P>
<P>
   When the Swiss investigators responded to the request for
assistance from the Kazakh government they turned up several Kazakh
accounts in Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
   One set of transactions particularly caught their attention: the
movement in the summer of between $80 million and $85 million from
a Kazakh government account at Credit Agricole Indosuez to what
appeared to be a personal account at the same bank held for the
benefit of the president.
</P>
<P>
   In August, after Devaud initiated his inquiry, the money was
suddenly transferred from the personal account to a Kazakh
government account at Pictet &AMP; Cie, according to people with
knowledge of the accounts who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at both banks said they were barred by Swiss bank
secrecy laws from commenting. Swiss law strictly prohibits
officials, lawyers and bankers from discussing such criminal
investigations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
