<HEADLINE>
IGNORING THE SKIPS IN A LATIN AMERICAN BEAT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since May, the Brazilian real has been declining. At the end of
last week, it was at 1.98 to the dollar, not far from its low for
the year of 2.15, in March.
</P>
<P>
   But the decline has caused much less concern among investors
than one might think. After all, the 1999 low came after Brazil
made headlines by suddenly devaluing its currency in January.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, four other worrisome events this month have passed
without a major outcry in emerging markets, which just a year ago
were teetering on the brink of disaster.
</P>
<P>
   First is the default, by Ecuador, on Brady bonds, something that
has never happened before. It was those bonds that helped pull
Latin America out of its debt crisis in the 1980s. Second is the
threat of another interest rate increase by the Federal Reserve _ a
move that would steepen borrowing costs of already heavily indebted
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Third is the downgrade by Moody's Investors Service of
Argentina's long-term-debt credit rating to B1, four notches below
investment grade. And fourth is the rejection by Brazil's Supreme
Court of new taxes on retired and active government workers that
would have cut the deficit in the country's social security
program.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one barometer of sentiment is improving. The spread, or
difference, between the yield on emerging-market bonds and the
yield on comparable United States Treasury bonds has narrowed since
August, to 10.87 percentage points from 12.34, according to J.P.
Morgan Securities. The spread has also narrowed for Latin American
bonds alone.
</P>
<P>
   Most Latin American stock markets have also fared reasonably
well. In Brazil, the Bovespa index has rallied 9.3 percent since
August, while in Argentina, the Merval index is up 9.0 percent,
despite recent selloffs in both markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market has been strong, given how negative the fundamental
developments have been recently,'' Joyce Chang, global head of
international fixed-income research at Chase Securities, said of
Latin American bond markets. ``If this happened in July, there
would have been a selloff.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason for this performance, she said, is that ``the
increase of cash inflows into emerging markets is outweighing
negative fundamental developments.''
</P>
<P>
   For investors, this should be a yellow flag. The new cash inflow
is not a result of the improvement in the long-term outlook.
Instead, it is an asset-allocation call. Because expected returns
elsewhere are not looking so good, especially in bonds, global cash
that can go anywhere is finding its way back to Brazil and other
Latin American markets.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman Brothers is recommending a position in Brazil just
because the spread over United States Treasuries there is about 2
percentage points wider than the spread over Treasuries in
Argentina. The belief is that the Brazilian spread should move back
toward the level of Argentina's, which would push Brazilian bond
prices higher.
</P>
<P>
   But as more new money comes in, it may set up another sharp
decline if, as some analysts expect, the news gets worse on Brazil
and Argentina next year. It was the flight of this kind of global
cash that added to the big selloff in emerging markets in the fall
of 1998, when the world financial crisis reached its worst point.
</P>
<P>
   A quick look at Brazil shows that the view into the new year is
not so rosy.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the government is moving to close the deficit gap opened by
the supreme court decision. But the country still has an enormous
debt burden, faces budget deficits in the years ahead that will be
just as difficult to bridge and has a government that could lose
the political will to continue with very painful economic reforms,
especially with important municipal elections next October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil remains vulnerable to swings in confidence and, more
importantly, to political and fiscal shocks,'' said Jose M.
Barrionuevo, director of global market strategy at Lehman Brothers.
``As we move into next year, if there is economic growth higher
than 3 percent in the first quarter, Brazil has a shot at easing
the political pressures.'' That is because the spending cuts and
tax increases needed to balance the budget would be less severe.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if growth is weaker,'' he said, ``the social pressure will
build going into the municipal elections.''
</P>
<P>
   So why recommend Brazilian bonds? ``We are likely to see some
improvement in the short term,'' he said, referring to the interest
rate spread between Brazil and Argentina. But that is not an
enticing invitation for the average investor.
</P>
</TEXT>
