<SLUG> BC-U.S.-CANADA-FRENCH-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECLINE IN CANADIAN DOLLAR HELPS LURE U.S. STUDENTS OF FRENCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., N.Y., Wis., Ill., Canada)  (dw) 
 By JAMES BROOKE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ When Thomas Stasko, a University of Maryland graduate
student, signed up for a French language immersion program in a
foreign university, he decided to go to there by car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was convenient getting up to Quebec,'' he said of his
semester at the Universite du Quebec at Chicoutimi. ``They all
spoke French and were very friendly people.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Canadian dollar trading a near historic low, American
teachers of French are promoting language studies in Quebec
universities and summer camps. By looking north to Canada, French
language teachers are borrowing a tactic from Spanish language
teachers who have long looked south to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   This discovery of Quebec is one of several new tactics aimed at
making French more appealing to an increasingly diverse American
study body. Hoping especially to interest African-Americans,
colleges offer courses in the literature of the French-speaking
countries of West Africa and the Caribbean, as well as study trips
to these regions.
</P>
<P>
   French teachers in Louisiana and the Mississippi River Valley
teach language students about local French history. Study of Quebec
and the Acadian diaspora appeals to many of the 17 million
Americans who are descended from French Canadians.
</P>
<P>
   At stake in this battle for relevancy is the future of language
training in American universities. Over the last 30 years, the
portion of American college students studying a foreign language
has dropped by half, to 7.9 percent in 1998, according to a survey
released on Thursday by the Modern Language Association in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   But the survey indicates a slowing in the sharp erosion of
French, which ranks behind Spanish as the nation's second most
widely taught language. During the first half of the 1990s, French
language enrollments in American colleges dropped by one quarter.
But since then, enrollments have dropped only 3.1 percent, to
199,064 college students last year.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, foreign language enrollments were up 4.8 percent. But
this was largely due to Americans' growing interest in Spanish. An
additional 60,000 students took Spanish in 1998, for a total of
656,690. About 30 years ago, Spanish began to surpass French in
popularity among students, and today it attracts more than three
times as many students as French does. The survey showed minor
gains for Italian, Chinese and Portuguese. Losses were recorded for
German, Japanese and Russian.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest news appeared to be the stabilization in French
enrollments, which had dropped by almost half since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of American schools we work with that 10 years
ago had four French teachers and two Spanish teachers, and now it
is the reverse,'' said Woodruff Halsey, executive director of
School Year Abroad, a program that sends about 60 high school
juniors a year to France and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, the number of American college students
studying overseas nearly doubled, hitting 113,954 last year. But
France as a study destination has slipped from second to fourth
place, attracting fewer than 10,000 Americans today. Now, fewer
American college students study French in France than study Spanish
in Mexico and Costa Rica combined.
</P>
<P>
   Quebec was long overlooked as an American study option because
of the province's distinctive accent and because of the heavy
English influence. The twangy regional accent has not softened, and
some students said they did not want it to replace the Parisian
accents they had learned in college. But the nationalist government
in Quebec has worked to purge English from signs and from public
places.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Quebec connection has become quite marked now,'' said
Elaine Marks, a French professor at the University of Wisconsin.
``There are students who are interested in going to Quebec over the
summer, who are unable to go to do the summer in Europe because of
the expense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian dollar trades at 68 American cents, an exchange
rate that makes Quebec a bargain, helping to attract almost 15
million American tourists to Canada last year. The linguistic
bastion of French in North America, Canada has seven million native
French speakers.
</P>
<P>
   With the strengthening of French in Canada, the American
Association of Teachers of French has started to alternate its
annual meetings between France and Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quebec is affordable,'' said Jayne Abrate, the association's
executive director, who teaches French at Southern Illinois
University in Carbondale. She said that elementary school teachers
``who are intimidated about taking a group to France will start out
by taking them to Quebec.'' Every year, more than 100 American
college students study French at the university at Chicoutimi, a
French-speaking city about 225 miles northeast of Montreal. For
programs under 12 weeks, Americans do not need student visas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids come back happy and speaking French,'' said Tom Carr,
a lecturer at the University of Maryland. ``It's so much more
economic, and they can get there by car, which gives them a certain
amount of mobility.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Summer language camps in Quebec are also attracting more and
more Americans. On the American side of the border, a high school
French language camp now takes students on regular trips to
Montreal and Quebec City from the Potsdam campus at the State
University of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the old tourism slogan of Canada as ``friendly,
familiar, foreign and near,'' Americans can go through a bit of
culture shock in Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cuisine is definitely different,'' said Alanna Prisby, a
22-year-old French major from Central Michigan University, who is
spending the fall semester in Chicoutoumi with a family that has
some distinctive favorite dishes. ``For one meal we had cabbage
rolls with potatoes, but with vanilla ice cream on top,'' Ms.
Prisby said. ``We've also had fried bologna with creamed corn on
top.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
