<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET DROPS LOWER, ENDING WORST WEEK IN A DECADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also ECON-JITTERS) 
(ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A jittery stock market moved sharply lower Friday
after an inflation report showed prices rising at an unexpectedly
rapid rate and Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve,
alarmed investors by warning that the stock market might be riskier
than many people believe. The market suffered its worst week in a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average traded below 10,000 for the
first time since April, but rallied a bit to close at 10,019.71.
Still, it was down 266.90 points, or 2.59 percent, on Friday. The
weekly decline of 5.9 percent was the worst since a fall of 7.8
percent in the week ended Oct. 13, 1989. That problems are
happening again in October _ a month that has seen crashes before
_added to the market's nervousness.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks fared even worse,
dropping 2.8 percent on Friday to close at 1,247.41, and falling
6.6 percent during the week. That index is now up just 1.48 percent
since the end of 1998, while the Dow, which has a larger
representation of energy issues that have benefited from rising oil
prices, is still up 9.13 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   The market has been unusually volatile in the last few weeks,
reflecting concerns that the Fed might raise short-term interest
rates again when it meets next month. At the same time, the market
has been pushing up long-term interest rates, although they fell a
bit Friday. The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond, which set a
two-year high of 6.32 percent on Thursday, slipped to 6.26 percent
Friday as investors sought safety.
</P>
<P>
   All this has come against the backdrop of a booming economy,
which has produced strong corporate profits. ``Earnings have been
good, but interest rates have surprised people by rising,'' said
Byron Wien, an equity strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
``Inflation is not dead, and that has been the undoing of the
market.''
</P>
<P>
   The government reported Friday that the producer price index
rose 1.1 percent in September, the largest monthly climb in nine
years. Most of that could be explained by rising prices of tobacco,
cars, food and energy, but the so-called core rate, which excludes
food and energy, was up only eight-tenths of a percent. Still, the
rise was larger than expected, and that contributed to the
weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan, addressing a banking conference Thursday night in
Washington, was careful to express no opinion on whether stock
prices were justified by the current economic outlook. But he
cautioned that stock prices had increased in recent years in
significant part because investors think equities are far less
risky than they were historically thought to be, making prices
vulnerable if such confidence were to fade.
</P>
<P>
   ``History tells us that sharp reversals in confidence occur
abruptly, most often with little advance notice,'' he said. ``Panic
reactions in the market are characterized by dramatic shifts in
behavior that are intended to minimize short-term losses.'' He
warned that banks should carry high levels of reserves to protect
themselves against such an occurrence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's telling bankers to be prudent,'' said Hugh Johnson, an
economist at First Albany Corp. ``That is extremely benign. Does it
signal a change in policy? I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed is widely expected to raise short-term interest rates by
a quarter-percentage point when it meets Nov. 16. If it does, that
would be the third increase since June, completely erasing the
three cuts it made last year, when the Fed feared world recession
in the wake of the Asian and Russian financial crises. Asian
economies have since recovered much of their losses, and many
European countries are also doing better.
</P>
<P>
   ``When global growth recovers from a significant period of
weakness, inflation and interest rates tend to go up,'' said Doug
Cliggott, an equity strategist at J.P. Morgan Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Barbera, the chief economist of Hoenig &AMP; Co., said he
believed the producer price figure ``ended the debate'' about
whether the Fed would raise rates again. ``They recognize the
economy is growing too fast, and they are going to raise rates
until they slow it down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Greenspan said little in his speech about what he was
going to do, markets around the world weakened as soon as reports
of it were distributed Thursday night. Major stock markets in both
Europe and Asia fell by at least 1 percent Friday, although none
performed as badly as the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the NASDAQ composite index has been a beacon of
strength in the market, reflecting its heavy concentration of
technology issues that have been market leaders. In fact, that
index hit a record high on Monday. But it fell 2.67 percent, or 75
points, on Friday, to 2,731.83, and is now down 6.7 percent since
the Monday high, as leading technology stocks have slipped. On
Friday, Microsoft, Cisco and Intel all lost at least $2 per share.
Still, the NASDAQ composite is up 24.6 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The market has been unusually volatile this year, and that
volatility seems to have intensified in recent weeks. Fane Lozman,
chairman of Scanshift, a Chicago research firm, noted that the Dow
had lost more than 200 points on seven days this year _ four of
them since Sept. 21. ``This shows there is a change in mentality
here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That nervousness stems in part from the memories of past
Octobers. The 12th anniversary of the 1987 crash arrives on
Tuesday, 10 days before the 70th anniversary of the worst day of
the 1929 crash. The last week this bad, exactly 10 years ago, came
as the market was shocked by the collapse of a proposed buyout of
United Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Since World War II, only 16 weeks have been worse than this one,
in terms of percentage decline for the Dow, according to Birinyi
Associates, a research firm.
</P>
<P>
   While it is misleading to pay attention to Dow points, given
that the index has gone up so much in recent years, this week's
decline was the largest ever by that measure. The 630.85-point
decrease surpassed the drop of 524.30 points set in the week ended
Sept. 24.
</P>
<P>
   The market's jitteriness has so far not stopped the booming new
issues market. An Internet stock called Women.com went public
Friday at $10 a share and closed at $18.50, although that was down
from a high of $23.375 reached in midafternoon. Companies scheduled
to go public next week include Martha Stewart Omnimedia and World
Wrestling Federation Entertainment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
