<HEADLINE>
BUSH FINDS A FEW CRITICS DURING SCHOOL VISIT IN WASHINGTON STATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Presidential candidate George W. Bush was a hit with
the children at Kimball Elementary School on Friday, but some of
their parents flunked the Texas governor on his visit.
</P>
<P>
   Some grown-ups, who acknowledged they were Democrats, said they
believed the governor was using their children and their school for
his political advantage without trying to understand the school's
funding problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we were being used as his whore,'' Mary Austin, a
self-described ``raging Democrat'' and mother of two Kimball
students, told reporters after Bush had left the school
</P>
<P>
   Other parents said they believed the governor added insult to
injury by turning a student walk-a-thon _ a major fund-raising
event for school supplies _ into a photo opportunity and then
contributing only $20.
</P>
<P>
   During his campaign for the Republican presidential nomination,
Bush has stopped at schools throughout the country. They are
carefully staged photo opportunities in which the governor usually
answers questions from students and reads to them.
</P>
<P>
   Kimball was Bush's second school Friday. He began a two-day
campaign trip to Washington state with a visit earlier in the day
to an elementary school in Yakima. Later Friday, he addressed the
National Federation of Republican Women convention in Seattle and
planned to attend a Republican fund-raiser Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   At the mostly Hispanic school in Yakima, Bush said ``it's muy
importante'' for him to capture the Hispanic vote. He also read
aloud to the class the children's book ``The Very Hungry
Caterpillar.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush followed his normal script at Kimball, a well-respected
school with a large minority, mainly Asian-American, enrollment.
When one fourth-grader asked what Bush would do for education if
elected president, he replied that he would first ``pass power back
from Washington, D.C., to the states'' because he believed in
``local control.``
</P>
<P>
   But the governor's parent-critics said his answer did not offer
them any assurance that he cared about the funding problems that
plague many public schools in their state. Student-teacher ratios
in classes at Kimball range from 28-to-1 to as high as 32-to-1,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   And the parents were at the school Friday to help teachers with
their classroom-related chores.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Kovar, a physician and a Democrat, said he did not even
know that Bush was going to visit Kimball and was surprised when
the Republican presidential front-runner showed up as Kovar was
stapling homework assignments for his son's first-grade class.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, 'Hiya, fella,' like a frat guy,'' Kovar told
reporters later. Bush belonged to a fraternity at Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   He said he told Bush that Kimball needed more federal help but
that Bush dismissed his plea. The federal government now
contributes about 7 percent of a school district's budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me to call my state legislator. He said the real
problem is federal meddling,'' Kovar added. ``That tells me more
about that man than anything else I can imagine.``
</P>
<P>
   Not all the parents were critical of their visitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was thrilling to see the man who might be the next
president of the United States,'' said Mary Wikel-Chauncey,
co-president of the school's Parent, Teacher and Student
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Foreman, the school principal, said she did not know
why Seattle school officials chose Kimball for Bush's visit, but
she said she welcomed the governor's arrival as a ``wonderful
learning experience'' for the students.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't matter which candidate came. Some parents would be
thrilled and some wouldn't,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan said the governor ``knows when we
have high expectations, high standards and real accountability, our
schools will rise to the challenges and no child will be left
behind.``
</P>
<P>
   Among other education changes, Bush has proposed that schools
that are rated low-performing for three years in a row lose part of
their federal funds. Parents would be allowed to use the funds to
send their children to other schools, including private facilities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
