<HEADLINE>
MURDOCH SAYS HE'S IN TALKS TO BUY A STAKE IN KIRCH GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany, France, Britain, Australia)  (dw) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Rupert Murdoch confirmed Friday that his News Corp. was
in talks to buy a minority stake in the Kirch Group media company
of Germany and might purchase part of Deutsche Telekom AG's cable
business.
</P>
<P>
   But he denied speculation that British Sky Broadcasting Group
PLC, which is 40 percent owned by his company, might purchase or
merge with Canal Plus, the French pay-per-view company that the
French utility giant Vivendi SA owns a large stake in.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch, whose vast media holdings have given him a dominant
presence in Britain's print and broadcast businesses, made the
disclosures to reporters after B Sky B's annual meeting in London.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear from his remarks that he was frustrated over News
Corp.'s unsuccessful efforts so far to gain a prominent foothold
elsewhere in Europe, and he appeared to place part of the blame on
official French obstinance.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling out a B Sky B merger with Canal Plus, Murdoch said: ``It
is nothing to do with Vivendi or Canal Plus. It's purely French
politics. We learned from the behavior of the French politicians
that it wasn't a suitable climate for a British company to be
operating in.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It is the very insistent, bipartisan position of the
French political establishment that television must remain strictly
controlled and regulated in every sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Vivendi, which owns 49 percent of Canal Plus, acquired 24.5
percent of B Sky B over the summer, contributing to speculation
that an outright merger might come next. Friday was the first time
Murdoch had publicly discussed the possibility of the tie-up of the
two largest pay television companies in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Concerning speculation that B Sky B was negotiating to buy a
minority stake in Kirch, Germany's second-largest media company and
was eyeing Deutsche Telekom's cable unit, Murdoch said: ``There
have been talks going on, on both fronts. There's absolutely
nothing concrete to announce at this stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom has been actively soliciting bids to sell its
cable unit in an effort to placate European Union regulators.
Murdoch declined to offer much detail, but he said B Sky B would
not try to acquire Deutsche Telekom's entire cable unit, which
consists of nine regional cable businesses valued somewhere between
$11 billion and $17 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't plan any total bid like that,'' he said. ``We may
join with partners, but we don't know yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The B Sky B annual meeting coincided with the release of its
first-quarter results, which showed the company lost 12.1 million
pounds, or $20 million, in the three months ended Sept. 30. A year
earlier it earned 38 million pounds.
</P>
<P>
   B Sky B has been aggressively trying to attract new customers to
use its new digital satellite service by subsidizing much of the
cost of the set-top boxes. Shares of B Sky B fell 3 percent to
592.5 pence, or $9.78.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
