<HEADER>
A8484 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HURRICANE-IRENE-ART-N     10-15 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-IRENE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORM CAUSES POWER LAPSES AND FLOODING IN FLORIDA
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds note: no byline) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Hurricane Irene brought heavy rains and strong wind
gusts to southern Florida Friday, causing flooding in some areas as
well as traffic tie-ups and power failures.
</P>
<P>
   Friday evening, a 150-foot freighter was washed onto the beach
in Broward County, and a tornado sent several people to hospitals
and did minor damage in Fort Lauderdale. By midafternoon, Florida
Power and Light officials had reported 400,000 households without
power in Miami-Dade, Broward and Palm Beach counties. Most of Key
West, in Monroe County, lost power late on Thursday or early
Friday, but by Friday evening, service had been restored. Major
flooding was reported in Miami-Dade and Broward counties and in Key
West.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane, classified as category 1, hit Havana and western
Cuba on Thursday night, destroying more than 10 buildings, causing
scattered power failures and leaving at least four people missing
and feared dead, Cuban officials said. Government offices and
stores were closed, and about 130,000 people from western and
central Cuba were evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane also hit the Bahamas, where four people drowned
when their truck slid into the ocean off a slippery pier in a heavy
downpour, emergency officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The storm reached Florida Friday near Cape Sable, on the
southwest tip of the state, 75 miles from Miami. On Thursday night,
Gov. Jeb Bush of Florida declared a state of emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters are predicting that rainfall from the storm could
top 20 inches in the Miami area. They expect the hurricane to move
northeast across the Everglades before leaving the state overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Mayor Alex Penelas of Miami-Dade County and other
tri-county officials urged people to go home early from work.
Officials also urged thousands of tourists in Key West to leave.
</P>
<P>
   In the Florida Keys, officials issued mandatory evacuation
orders for residents of mobile homes and recreational vehicles.
Public schools and Key West's small airport were closed.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, Broward and Palm Beach counties, schools were closed
for a teacher workday. The major airports in the state, including
Miami and Fort Lauderdale International Airports, remained open,
but many flights were canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Still, compared with other storms, like Hurricane Andrew in
1992, Hurricane Irene was relatively weak, and many South
Floridians were nonchalant about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a wet storm,'' said Mary Kay Reich, a Monroe
County commissioner. ``We're flooding pretty badly down here in the
Keys, but we're used to riding out these storms.''
</P>
<P>
   Floods in many South Florida neighborhoods and on roads caused
lines of cars to stall. The rain, which at times blinded drivers,
and slick roads caused more than a dozen accidents on interstate
highways.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 2038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
