u f BC-PONZI-SCAM16-COX     10-15 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PONZI-SCAM16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta day trader charged by SEC in Ponzi scheme
 &HT;    By Robert Luke
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Securities regulators Friday alleged that a
32-year-old Atlanta day trader, Mark Drucker, engaged in a Ponzi
scheme that raised $6.2 million from about 80 investors. The
investors thought they could get profits of 50 percent or more, in
two months or less.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission said it obtained a
temporary restraining order in federal court in Atlanta prohibiting
Drucker from violating the anti-fraud provisions of securities laws
and from destroying documents. It also got an order freezing
Drucker's assets.
</P>
<P>
   In its complaint, the SEC alleged that Drucker _ known in
Atlanta social circles for throwing lavish parties _ took money
from new investors to pay purported profits to earlier investors
and to pay his own personal expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC alleged that instead of generating fat profits from day
trading, Drucker ``consistently'' lost money _ including $634,453
this year _ trading stocks such as Yahoo, Amazon.com,
priceline.com, Qualcomm and Chase Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Drucker couldn't be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the lawsuit as a ``relief defendant'' was Atlanta
attorney Michael Weinstock, an original investor in the scheme,
according to Richard P. Murphy, the SEC's assistant district
administrator in charge of enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not alleging in the complaint that Mr. Weinstock
actively engaged in the fraud,'' Murphy said. ``We are alleging
that the monies he received _ beyond what he put in _ he is not
entitled to. We are seeking the return of that money for ultimate
distribution to defrauded investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstock invested about $1,035,916 and received about
$1,575,514, according to the SEC. He couldn't be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said regulators also may seek to recoup money and other
assets _ including a $153,000 Ferrari _ from other early investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will be determined by evidence received in litigation,''
Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC alleged that from July 1998 through Sept. 30, 1999,
Drucker offered and sold interests in a ``momentum'' stock trading
program that was based on a ``complex mathematical formula.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said most of the investors live in metro Atlanta. Some
live in Michigan and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme spread ``primarily by word of mouth,'' according to
Murphy. ``He (Drucker) relied on some of the earlier investors of
the scheme, who did pretty well, to talk to their friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Some investors signed a management agreement giving Drucker
``full and complete discretion to invest, trade and make
transactions associated with the account,'' according to the SEC's
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said the agency has not been able to find Drucker. And it
doesn't know what assets he has.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did have cash withdrawals that he took from the account in
August,'' Murphy said. ``There were some wire transfers made out of
the account. We have not yet tracked down where all the money was
sent.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said the long bull market may have had a role to play in
the alleged scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get to the later stages of a bull market, people tend
to have more money,'' Murphy explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because they are accustomed to whatever the market's been
generating _ returns have been averaging 20 to 25 percent a year _
they become receptive to someone offering considerably more, as Mr.
Drucker was,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bottom line: People should be skeptical before they make
investments,'' Murphy continued. ``There really is no such thing as
a free lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
