<SLUG> BC-NASA-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS PASSES $13.7 BILLION SPENDING PLAN FOR NASA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A $13.7 billion spending plan for NASA cleared
Congress on Friday, providing the space agency with about $75
million more than requested by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the legislation puts a hold on a controversial
satellite project pushed by Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The NASA budget, which passed the Senate 93-5, was part of a $99
billion measure financing environmental, housing, veterans and
space programs for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, with less than a week left before expiration of a
temporary funding resolution that has kept the government running
since Oct. 1, Congress and the White House have not reached
agreement on five annual spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   Officials signaled Friday that an agreement was likely to pass
another stopgap bill to keep federal agencies operating beyond
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no intent to shut the government down, not on our
part, not on the president's part,'' said House Speaker Dennis
Hastert, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Congress will have to
make ``a credible case'' for another extension. Republicans must
``come clean, be honest on the numbers, make the tough choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Faced with Clinton opposition to Republican spending priorities,
Congress has yet to approved three bills covering funding for the
departments of Labor, Health and Human Services, Education,
Interior, Commerce, Justice, State and several smaller agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The president earlier vetoed a bill financing the District of
Columbia _ saying it included misguided social policy and did not
respect the district's right to govern itself _ and Congress
returned to work on the legislation hoping to secure his approval
before Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Also, aides say Clinton plans to veto a second measure covering
foreign aid because it is $2 billion less than he requested and
does not allow for payment of the United States' current, or
delinquent, dues in the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who in August threatened to veto the NASA budget after
House Republicans cut it by almost $1 billion, was expected to sign
the measure early next week.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which was approved Thursday by the House
406-18, sets aside $13.65 billion for space agency programs, about
$12 million less than the current budget. In January, the
administration requested $13.59 billion for the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, House Republican leaders yielded to Senate
demands to restore the Republican cuts and add even more for NASA,
the Environmental Protection Agency and veterans' health care.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the House agreed to back off demands for less
spending on low-income housing programs.
</P>
<P>
   At the insistence of House negotiators, the bill puts a hold on
funds for the Triana project, a camera-equipped satellite proposed
by Gore to provide round-the-clock video images of Earth for
Internet users. Lawmakers want a National Academy of Sciences study
of the project's scientific merit before NASA can spend any more
money on the satellite project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disturbing to see NASA wholeheartedly support a project
just because it's proposed by the vice president (while) other
worthwhile projects are scrutinized more closely for their
scientific merit,'' said House Science Committee Chairman James
Sensenbrenner, R-Wisc.
</P>
<P>
   Named for Rodrigo Triana, the sailor who first sighted the New
World on Christopher Columbus' voyage in 1492, the satellite was
scheduled for launch in December 2000. It was to be stationed about
halfway between Earth and the sun.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to beaming back images of the sun-splashed Earth for
viewing on the Internet, the telescope and high-definition camera
aboard the satellite were to provide scientists with information
about weather patterns, cloud formations, oceans and the planet's
vegetation canopy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
