<SLUG> BC-DOW16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dow dives amid inflation fears, Greenspan signal
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Dow Jones industrial average dipped briefly below
10,000 Friday for the first time in more than six months. The sharp
drop was sparked by renewed inflation fears and some blunt talk by
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   In what Prudential Securities strategist Larry Wachtel called a
``double whammy,'' the government reported a worse than expected
1.1 percent September rise in the Producer Price Index, which
measures wholesale price changes. The core rate _ minus the cost of
food and energy _ rose 0.8 percent, considerably bigger than
forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that would have been bad enough for stocks, but it
came on the heels of a Thursday night speech by Greenspan to a
bankers' group. He cautioned them about stock market valuations _
reminiscent of his December 1996 warning against ``irrational
exuberance'' in the market.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's economic reports and Greenspan's remarks renewed
investor concern that the Fed might raise interest rates in
November for the third time this year. The Fed raised rates to
fight inflation after its meetings in June and July. The board left
rates unchanged in October, but signaled it was more likely to
boost them again later than cut them.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, there was considerable uncertainty about what
next week may bring. The government will release the Consumer Price
Index on Tuesday and the balance of trade report on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The market's response to Friday's events was immediate, starting
overnight in the Far East and Europe after Greenspan's speech.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, stocks plunged at the opening bell. When
investors regained their composure, they started shopping for
bargains.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark Dow dipped just below 10,000 shortly after 3 p.m.
_ the first time since April 7 _ and later tested that level before
bouncing back. The index finished at 10,019.71, down 266.90 points,
or 2.6 percent. It was the Dow's worst point loss in more than a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
