<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AGREES WITH TEST BAN VOTE, BUT WOULD KEEP MORATORIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush said Friday he agrees with
Senate Republicans who rejected the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban
Treaty, but said he would not resume underground nuclear weapons
testing if elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters at a Seattle elementary school, Bush
described the treaty, which bans underground testing, as
non-verifiable and argued that ratification would have ``made it
very difficult to make sure our arsenal is safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The position puts the Republican presidential frontrunner
directly at odds with Vice President Al Gore. Gore pledged here
Wednesday night that he would to rebsubmit the treaty for Senate
ratification as his first act if elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was terse in his answers about the test ban, and did not
elaborate on his thinking. But he did seek to refute an assertion
made Thursday by President Clinton as he lambasted the Senate's GOP
majority for turning down the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   At a White House news conference, Clinton said: ``Now, if we
ever get a president that's against the test ban treaty, which we
may get _ I mean there are plenty of people out there who say they
are against it _ then I think you might as well get ready for it.
You'll have Russia testing. You'll have China testing. You'll have
India testing. You'll have Pakistan testing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, while opposing treaty ratification, said he would keep in
place the current moratorium on underground nuclear testing _ and
thereby set an example to the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the United States can send a strong message, that we
aren't going to test and they shouldn't either,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate refused to ratify the test ban on a 48-51 vote
earlier this week. Only four Senate Republicans broke ranks to
support the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has made news in recent weeks by seeming to put distance
between himself and Republican leaders in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   During his two-day visit here, however, the Texas governor is
working to reaffirm his credentials as a GOP loyalist. ``He's a
team player who is working to maintain Republican majorities in
both the House and Senate,'' said Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash.,
state chairwoman of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spent Friday doing what has become a hallmark of his
presidential campaign _ conducting photo opportunities at schools
with heavy enrollments of minority students.
</P>
<P>
   He stopped at Garfield Elementary School in Yakima, which is 76
percent Hispanic. He read to a group of first graders from a book
called ``The Very Hungry Caterpillar.''
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, Bush visited Kimball Elementary School on
Seattle's Beacon Hill, where one-third of the students are learning
English as a second language, and again read from ``The Very Hungry
Caterpillar.''
</P>
<P>
   Kimball Elementary School uses U.S. Department of Education
dollars, under a program called Title I, to support three of its
teachers. The program allows the school to lower class size and
give better instruction in reading and mathematics.
</P>
<P>
   If elected, said Bush, he would give ``a bonus'' to schools that
use Title I money to boost achievement scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``If students aren't learning, I have a plan to give your
parents more options,'' he told a fourth grade class, apparently
referring to vouchers that would allow parents to send their
children to private or parochial schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would you do about the homeless?'' asked fourth grader
Anthony Bissiri.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would work with local jurisdictions to get homes for them,''
Bush replied.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to name his heroes, Bush started off with ``my dad'' _
former President George Bush _ and listed Great Britain's World War
II Prime Minister Winston Churchill.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has raised more than $57 million for his presidential bid,
$20.1 million of it in the third quarter of this year. He ended the
quarter with $37.7 million in cash on hand.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has spent the last two days debating proposed
campaign spending limits, and has scheduled a series of key test
votes next week. The drive for spending reform is led by GOP Sen.
John McCain of Arizona, one of Bush's rivals for the Republican
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Friday that he would increase the current limit of
$1,000 per election on individual donations to congressional and
presidential campaigns. He also defended political action
committees whose giving would be curbed under a reform proposal
sponsored by McCain and Sen. Russ Feingold, D-Wis. PACs can give up
to $10,000 in an election cycle to federal candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush noted that PACs are an outgrown of Congress' last effort to
control campaign costs, in the wake of the Watergate scandal.
``PACs are a reform that came into existence to give people a
chance to participate in the system,'' he argued.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
