u f BC-COPPER-BID-NYT &LR;      10-15 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPPER-BID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASARCO ACCEPTS GRUPO MEXICO'S $1.18 BILLION TAKEOVER BID 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Asarco Inc. said Friday that its board had voted to accept a
sweetened $1.18 billion all-cash takeover bid from Grupo Mexico AG
and that it planned to break its $1.17 billion cash and stock
merger agreement with Phelps Dodge Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Phelps Dodge decides to increases its bid _ a move
analysts said was unlikely _ its seven-week effort to acquire
Asarco, the nation's third-largest copper producer, will come to an
end.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, the story is virtually complete,'' said
Clarence Morrison, an analyst at Prudential Securities. ``I don't
see Phelps Dodge increasing its offer, for the simple reason that
they have come to the realization that it is no longer economic to
purchase the company at this point for more than they are currently
offering.''
</P>
<P>
   Asarco shareholders could, however, opt for the Phelps Dodge
offer, particularly if the suitor's stock price rises.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal struck on Oct. 5, Phelps Dodge agreed to pay
$14.75 in cash plus 0.2513 Phelps Dodge share for each of Asarco's
39.8 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Grupo Mexico, a rail and mining conglomerate and Asarco's
largest shareholder, lobbed a $26-a-share, $1.03 billion cash bid
for Asarco in September, topping an earlier hostile offer from
Phelps Dodge. Grupo Mexico sweetened the offer on Oct. 7 to $29.50
a share, or $1.18 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Phelps Dodge said on Oct. 8 that it would not raise its bid.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Suber, a spokeswoman for Phelps Dodge, said Friday that
the company had no comment on the Asarco decision.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, Asarco said it intended to end its
agreement with Phelps Dodge ``at or after'' 9 a.m. on Oct. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Asarco will pay Phelps Dodge a $30 million breakup fee when it
ends the deal, Jerry Cooper, an Asarco spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Phelps Dodge exchange offer is still open, but it looks
likely Asarco shareholders will go with the cash bid,'' said Tom
Burnett, founder of Merger Insight, which is based in New York.
``However, if Phelps Dodge sees its stock price go up to $62 or
higher, all things could change.''
</P>
<P>
   Phelps Dodge and Asarco shares withstood Friday's stock market
dive. Phelps Dodge closed at $57.875, up 62.5 cents a share, while
Asarco rose 6.25 cents, to $29.375.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase of Asarco would make Grupo Mexico one of the
world's largest copper companies, with annual production of about
800,000 metric tons.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Asarco's decision to accept the Grupo Mexico bid has
apparently stifled Phelps Dodge's sweeping effort to become the
world's largest copper company. As copper prices slumped earlier
this year, Phelps Dodge began an offensive in August to acquire
both Asarco and Cyprus Amax Minerals Co., in an effort to cut costs
through consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   Until Friday, it looked as if its efforts had succeeded: Earlier
this month, in addition to striking a deal with Asarco, it agreed
to acquire Cyprus for $1.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   John Tumazos, an analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co., said
that even if Phelps Dodge abandons its effort to acquire Asarco
now, it may choose to revive its interest later on, particularly if
copper prices slide from their current levels of around 78 cents a
pound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phelps Dodge may have the idea to try and buy part of Asarco
at a lower valuation than $29.75 a share if the outlook for copper
turns out to be unfavorable six, twelve or eighteen months from
now,'' he said. ``Grupo's all-cash offer reinforces my thought that
their expectation about copper prices is very aggressive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
