<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES, RED SOX BRACE FOR HEAVYWEIGHT PITCHING MATCHUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ On the eve of the most striking postseason pitching
matchup in a generation, the principals didn't exactly play to
their reputations of single-minded combatants.
</P>
<P>
   In this corner, Roger Clemens was talking about the beautiful
fall foliage of New England. In the other corner, Pedro Martinez
was wearing a soft, off-white jacket and black-framed glasses and
saying how much he respected Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured when Martinez and Clemens face each other Saturday
afternoon, in Game 3 of the American League Championship Series,
they will compete like Ali and Frazier, Russell and Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond their individual greatness _ Clemens has won five Cy
Young Awards, Martinez will win his second next month, both seem
destined for the Hall of Fame _ there are fascinating layers to
this game. The Red Sox trail the best -of-7 series 2-0, and history
says they must win Game 3. No baseball team has ever returned from
a 3-0 deficit to win a postseason series.
</P>
<P>
   There are leftover feelings from Clemens' nasty divorce with the
Red Sox: He established his stardom in Boston and departed
unhappily _ he feels he was ushered out by the general manager Dan
Duquette, who essentially replaced Clemens a year later with
Martinez. Cast out as the city's favorite son, Clemens is returning
in pursuit of the championship he never won with Boston, to face
the pitcher who has replaced him in the hearts of Bostonians.
</P>
<P>
   Fenway Park will be an epicenter of emotion. ``I think the
circuit breaker for that electric company, for the great pad in the
sky, might be challenged,'' said Jimy Williams, the Boston manager.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette told ESPN: ``This could be the defining moment in the
careers of those pitchers, and it could be a defining moment for me
personally.''
</P>
<P>
   The conditions may be perfectly suited for power pitchers. The
game is scheduled to start just after 4 p.m. and the sky is
expected to be clear, meaning that the autumn shadows will darken
the infield in the early innings and make it extremely difficult
for hitters to see. The awesome talents of two pitchers headed for
the Hall of Fame will be exacerbated. ``Everybody but two people
are hoping for a cloudy day,'' David Cone said, smiling a pitcher's
smile.
</P>
<P>
   As in most Super Bowls, there is always the chance one or the
other, or both, will struggle. Clemens has had great stuff most of
the season, his fastball 94-96 mph, but his seven shutout innings
against Texas in the division series belied a year in which he was
mostly inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez struck out 28 in 16 innings in successful starts
against the Yankees this season, but he is coming back from a
strained back muscle and even while pitching six no-hit innings
Monday in Cleveland, he was not fully armed with his best stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens mostly has affected a detached air when speaking
publicly about facing Martinez, but others in the Yankees'
organization say Clemens was thrilled to have gotten the
assignment; he badly wanted the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great challenge for Roger,'' said another Yankee.
``Pitching in Boston, against the guy who replaced him, in a
playoff game _ it can't get any bigger for him, personally, unless
it was the seventh game of the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   When Torre told him earlier this week of his opponent _
Martinez, in Game 3 - Clemens responded, ``Beautiful,'' got up and
walked out of Torre's office. It was as if Clemens didn't want to
give Torre a chance to reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have a good time with it,'' said Clemens, referring to
himself and family members who have come to Boston to see the game.
``I know the environment, and you know, it brings back memories.
Today we were going down the Mass Pike seeing the color of the
trees. It is awesome, this time of year. This is what you play
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens won three of his five Cy Young Awards and 178 of his 247
career victories while in a Red Sox uniform, but he will be booed
heavily Saturday, in the place that used to be his home ballpark.
``I will be as excited as everyone else tomorrow,'' Clemens said.
``But I think I will have to channel all that and hopefully get off
to a good start and hold up my end of the deal to make it exciting
for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he respects Clemens for what he has accomplished.
``All the players have to have respect for a man like that, a man
that puts up the numbers,'' said Martinez, who, along with his
brother Ramon, will become only the second pair of brothers in
postseason history to pitch for the same team; Dizzy and Daffy Dean
pitched for St. Louis in the 1934 World Series, against Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been through everything,'' Martinez said of Clemens.
``He has been through war and he is a great competitor and I'm sure
he knows how to handle the situation.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Red Sox have shrugged off questions about the Curse of the
Bambino, rightly noting the obvious: None of them were around in
1920, when the Red Sox sold Ruth to the Yankees, or in 1949 or 1967
or 1972 or 1978 or 1986, when Boston failed to win the championship
that was within its grasp.
</P>
<P>
   But the Red Sox could have wondered about their bad luck in the
first two games of this series. An umpire, Rick Reed, admittedly
blew a call that sabotaged Boston's 10th inning rally in Game 1,
and in Game 2, Jason Varitek and Troy O'Leary each came within an
inch or two of hitting home runs, their drives denting the very top
of the right field wall at Yankee Stadium. Then, in the seventh
inning of Game 2, Paul O'Neill drove in the go-ahead run with a
broken-bat, bloop single over shortstop, a fluke hit.
</P>
<P>
   Boston could have created better fortune for itself, too: They
went scoreless in the last seven innings of Game 1, before going 1
for 13 with runners in scoring position in Game 2. The Yankees,
conversely, have capitalized on most of their opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody feels sorry for us, you know,'' said Williams. ``We are
going to be prepared tomorrow. We know we need a win tomorrow. We
are going to do our darnedest to win tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox will have the best pitcher in the American League
going for them. But he will have to beat the best pitcher in modern
Red Sox history to do it. Martinez against Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Said Torre: ``It is electric. It would be a special time if it
happened during the season, but to happen in Game 3 of the American
League Championship Series in Fenway, where both pitchers have won
Cy Youngs _ it is pretty incredible. I just hope it lives up to
that hype, and I have a sense it will.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 2057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
