<HEADER>
A8550 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BAUER-CAMPAIGN-SFCHRO     10-15 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAUER-CAMPAIGN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAUER SAYS BUSH WILL LOSE ELECTION IF HE STRAYS TO LEFT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Firing an ominous warning from the right, dark
horse Republican presidential candidate Gary Bauer said Thursday
that George W. Bush cannot win the presidency unless he sharpens
his conservative message.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, the darling of many in the religious right, said
Republicans are setting themselves up for a great disappointment by
placing electoral pragmatism above their ideological beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Republicans, the surest way to lose is to enter the
primaries looking for a winner,'' Bauer said when asked about
Bush's tremendous lead among Republicans. ``It means that we're
looking at polls instead of having a campaign that is driven by
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited Bush's support for trade with China, his tepid support
for school vouchers and his unwillingness to emphasize social
issues as weaknesses in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe that the current vague message coming out of
Austin, Texas ... can prevail against either Al Gore or Bill
Bradley, regardless of what the polls say now,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer offered his blunt assessment over lunch with California
reporters, during which he discussed matters ranging from his
belief that he can win the presidency to his doubts that gays would
serve in his administration.
</P>
<P>
   The former Reagan aide, who left his post as president of the
conservative Family Research Council to seek the presidency, has
stressed social issues such as abortion, school prayer and family
values in his uphill quest for the GOP nomination. Bauer blamed his
lack of money _ not his message _ for his current low standings in
the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it looks like (Republicans) think we can buy an election,
or that the only way to win is to nominate the guy with the biggest
inheritence or the biggest fund-raising effort _ I think almost
inevitably we end up losing,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, who compared his quest to win the nomination to Ronald
Reagan's battle in 1980, said many voters have grown sick &LR; tired of
Bush's apparent invincibility.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer quoted a bartender in Louisiana he spoke with a few days
ago who said, ``I'm so tired of having George Bush being shoved
down my throat.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer criticized Bush for his comments last week in which
he &LR; Bush attacked the GOP Congress for trying to ``balance the
budget on the backs of the poor.'' Though Bauer said he actually
agrees with the substance of Bush's complaint, he blamed him for
using ``the rhetoric of Ted Kennedy and Barney Frank and Hillary
Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer said Bush is headed for defeat ``unless he defines his
message to be more of a Reagan-type message. I do not believe a
message of trying to be everything to everybody can win.''
</P>
<P>
   On other matters, Bauer said he cannot fathom asking someone who
is openly gay to serve in his administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot, in my wildest imagination, imagine someone who is
openly homosexual would want to work in an administration that is
going to emphasize that marriage is between a man and a women ...
and that homosexuality has a moral aspect to it that makes it
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such an individual, in my view, would be so deeply conflicted
that I would worry about their stability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer also warned that there is no room for a pro-choice
candidate on the GOP ticket, and suggested that there would be
widespread defections if the ultimate nominee attempts to name a
pro-choice running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do not have a ticket that at both top and bottom is
pro-life, we may as well cancel reservations for the inaugural now,
because that ticket will not win,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer said he supports efforts to crack down on illegal
immigration, and would have supported Proposition 187, which sought
to deny services to those who crossed the border illegally.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to come to America,'' Bauer said, ``apply like
everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   He rejected the suggestion that he was on a quixotic quest in
the hopes of inserting conservative issues into the debate. ``Yes,
I think I can be the next president of the United States,'' he
asserted. Citing the strain of the campaign on his family life, he
added, ``I would never do this just to make a point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
