   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Saturday, October 16, on the New York
Times wire. For questions, please call Georgie Dennison at
415-777-6055 or the business desk at 415-536-5172. For business
stories running in main news, call the news desk at 415-777-7074.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; KAUFER  &LR; _ Kaufer's Religious Supplies, now in its 96th year of
operation, is San Francisco's oldest provider of paraphernalia to
Christian faithful. After nearly a century in the holy hardware
business, a fifth generation of Kaufer is now being groomed to
eventually take over the shop. Store employees say sales have been
booming as the Millennial moment approaches, and they are
witnessing a surge in interest in all manner of religious goods. By
David Lazarus
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KAUFERSIDE _  &LR;  Cavanagh Co. of Rhode Island, the world's
largest manufacturer of communion wafers, is perhaps uniquely
positioned to cut out the middleman and deal directly with Catholic
churches via the Internet. The company dominates its market, and
its products are constantly in demand. By David Lazarus
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; PIRACY  &LR;  _ Microsoft Corp. attorney Anne Murphy earnestly expected
people who were using pirated software to just drop on by Justin
Herman Plaza to turn in their illegal booty. But to perhaps
nobody's surprise but her own, yesterday's mildly publicized ``Ask
If It is Licensed`` event did not draw one single repentant soul.
By Benny Evangelista
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SILICON  &LR;  _ Santa Clara's Silicon Valley Bank, which specialized in
loans to young technology companies, said regulators are requiring
to increase its capital in response to a surge in credit problems.
By Sam Zuckerman
</P>
