<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEDRO VS. ROGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Understand this about great postseason pitching
matchups: They are almost entirely circumstantial. That's why there
have been so very few of them.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro vs. Roger is even more special than most people realize.
You might think that during the 96-year history of 20th century
postseason baseball there would be a score of ballyhooed pairings
to stir the diamond soul, but you would be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The very first World Series game featured one, however. Cy Young
(28-9) was matched up on Oct. 1, 1903, against Pittsburgh's Deacon
Phillippe (25-9). There would be no suspense. Pittsburgh won it,
7-3, as an anonymous Globe scribe analyzed as follows: ``Cy Young
was hit hard. He fell considerably short of his best work, lacking
speed, his winning ingredient.''
</P>
<P>
   Christy Mathewson, always a Main Attraction, found himself in a
marquee matchup two years later when his Game 1 foe was
Philadelphia's ``Gettysburg Eddie'' Plank, a fellow future Hall of
Famer. In what would turn out to be merely the first of five
consecutive shutouts for one team or the other, Big Six (31-8, 1.27
ERA) and the Giants beat Plank (25-12, 2.26) and the A's with a
four-hitter, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Said the Globe man, ``Each team had its best pitcher, Mathewson
putting it all over Plank, who was wild and continually getting
himself in a hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathewson could have been matched up with Smoky Joe Wood seven
years later, but it never materialized. Matty faced Ray Collins
once and Hugh Bedient twice. Smoky Joe faced Jeff Tesreau three
times, beating him in Games 1 and 4 and losing to the Giants rookie
in Game 7. Wood did, however, pick up the relief win in the
deciding Game 8 (Game 2 was a tie).
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, two full decades passed before there was
anything close to a stop-the-presses, you-just-gotta-be-there
matchup in the World Series. You can make a case for the 1934 Game
5 pairing of Detroit's Tommy Bridges (22-11, 3.67) and St. Louis's
Dizzy Dean (30-7, 2.66). Bridges and the Tigers prevailed, 3-1, and
the Globe's Victor O. Jones was suitably impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's battle was by all odds the best of the series _ a
tightly played, fiercely fought engagement in which Bridges,
superbly supported, outpitched incredible Dizzy Dean,'' declared
Mr. Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later the Game 1 confrontation between the Giants'
``King Carl'' Hubbell and the Yankees' Lefty Gomez had a major
appeal. The Globe headline: FIRST GAME OF WORLD SERIES WILL BE A
``BATTLE OF LEFT HOOKS'' _ GOMEZ AND HUBBELL PERFORM.
</P>
<P>
   John Lardner, meanwhile, soared to lofty rhetorical heights.
``This will make the first game an orgy of sinistralism, an orgy of
saturnalism, a pantheon of portside prowess,'' he gushed.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way there were certainly great pitching battles. You
had Johnny Sain beating Bob Feller's two-hitter in a 1-0 Braves
triumph in Game 1 of the '48 Series. You had back-to-back 1-0 games
to start the 1949 Series (the Yankees' Allie Reynolds over Don
Newcombe and the Dodgers' Preacher Roe over Vic Rashi,
respectively). But it wasn't until 1963 that baseball again had a
primo pulse-racing matchup in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   You want numbers? OK, then, try these. In Game 1 of the 1963
World Series it was the Dodgers' Sandy Koufax (25-5, 1.88, and 11
shutouts) against Yankee ace Whitey Ford (24-7, 2.74). Now that's a
matchup.
</P>
<P>
   The day belonged to Koufax, who established a Series record with
15 strikeouts as he fashioned a 5-2 victory. This was the game in
which Frank Howard hit that famous 450-foot double to the deepest
portion of the old Death Valley in left field at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Jim Lonborg vs. Bob Gibson in Game 7 would
have been a bigger deal if the playing field had been leveled. But
Lonnie was working on two days' rest, while Gibson was working on
three for the Cardinals. Does anybody remember that in addition to
winning the game with a route-going performance, Gibson also hit a
fifth-inning solo homer?
</P>
<P>
   A year later Gibson was part of the next great media hype.
Coming off a memorable 22-9, 1.12, 13-shutout campaign, he found
himself matched up against Detroit's Denny McLain, he of the 31-6
record. Each man did his best to avoid the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not facing Gibson,'' said McLain. ``I am facing the whole
Cardinal team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't pay too much attention to those things,'' echoed
Gibson. ``I will pitch my own game, the same as always.''
</P>
<P>
   (From what we can tell, copies of these statements have already
been faxed to Messrs. Martinez and Clemens.)
</P>
<P>
   The game? Strictly a Gibson show. He fanned 17, prompting at
least one Tiger (second baseman Dick McAuliffe) to say he was ``the
best I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was the Last of the Great Matchups. Oh, sure, former Cy
Young winners Vida Blue (A's) and Jim Palmer (Orioles) hooked up in
Game 3 of the 1974 American League Championship Series and it was a
splendid game (Blue won it, 1-0, on a two-hitter), but this was a
battle between a 17-15 guy (Blue) and a 7-12 guy (Palmer).
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, the single most publicized pitching showdown did
not take place in the postseason. But it did take place right here
on Sept. 6, 1912. Ladies and gentlemen, we give you the legendary
Walter Johnson (28-10) vs. Smoky Joe Wood (29-4, a winner of 13
straight who had not lost since July 4).
</P>
<P>
   Or shall we say, as the Globe did, ``The Terrible Swede''
against the ``Kansas Cyclone''?
</P>
<P>
   This was a Very Big Deal that had been carefully arranged by
managers Jake Stahl and Clark Griffith, a couple of guys with
obvious baseball soul. Check this Globe headline: WOOD AND JOHNSON
IN PITCHING DUEL TODAY. ONE OF GREATEST BATTLES OF BOXMEN IN YEARS
TO BE FOUGHT AT FENWAY PARK.
</P>
<P>
   A great weekday crowd of 29,000 stormed Fenway. ``The playing
field was surrounded by a triple, even quadruple, rack of
humanity,'' reported The Globe.
</P>
<P>
   And what did they get? Merely a 1-0 Wood triumph on sixth-
inning back-to-back doubles by Tris Speaker and Duffy Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Wrote the Globe's venerable Melville E. Webb, ``A pitcher's
battle was predicted between the gladiators of the mound, and a
pitcher's battle it surely was.''
</P>
<P>
   Concluded Mr. Webb, ``It was as sterling a game as possibly
could be played.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, Pedro and Roger. There is your performance bar. Think you
guys can reach it?
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
