<SLUG> BC-SILICON-SILICON </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Examiners Get Tough on Santa Clara Bank  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
In what could be a sign of a tougher regulatory stance on risky
loans, bank examiners have instructed Silicon Valley Bancshares to
boost its capital.
<P>
   The Santa Clara bank _ known for financing hot young technology
and health care companies _ said yesterday that it had signed a
memorandum of understanding with the Federal Reserve Bank of San
Francisco and state bank regulators to raise its capital by an
estimated $25 million by year's end. Capital is retained earnings
and money contributed by investors that serves as a cushion against
loan losses.
</P>
<P>
   Examiners ``had concerns about loan quality,'' said John Dean,
Silicon Valley's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The memorandum, the mildest form of regulatory sanction, doesn't
mean Silicon Valley is in financial straits. In fact, on Thursday,
the bank reported a record profit of $10.5 million for the three
months ended September 30.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, analysts said, the action may signal that regulators are
putting their money where their mouths have been _ following up
recent public warnings about risky lending with sterner supervision
of banks.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators from Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan on down
have been sounding the alarm that banks are getting too lax in
commercial lending standards just when the economy may be slowing.
Some of those borrowers may not be able to pay the loans back,
which could produce big losses and a credit crunch down the road.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, said Sutro &AMP; Co. analyst Campbell Chaney, ``Banks
are getting more scrutiny on loan quality now than they have in the
past. This is just the first example. You will see more.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaney was a Federal Reserve bank examiner before he switched
careers.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Richard Spillenkothen, the Fed's top bank
supervisor, sent a seven-page memo to examiners urging them to step
up their vigilance against ``overly aggressive lending practices.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Federal Reserve spokeswoman Carol Eckert declined
to comment on Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, regulators have reason to focus on Silicon Valley
apart from any national trends. The bank has an unusual business
model, somewhere between a conservative bank lender and a venture
capital investor, financing risky young companies most traditional
banks avoid.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year and a half, Silicon Valley's delinquent loans
and loan losses have spiked. In response, the bank has set aside
more money to cover bad loans and reviewed its credit policies.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley officials said the bank's loan problems have been
concentrated in industries outside its technology and health care
specialty areas, and that they are cutting back such loans.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that after a regularly scheduled examination,
regulators pressed the bank to sign a memorandum of understanding
``is something not to be taken lightly,'' said Chaney. ``It tells
me they have a lot of potentially risky credits on the books.``
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the memorandum requires Silicon Valley to boost
its Tier 1 leverage ratio, a key capital measure, to 7.25 percent
by year's end from 6.7 percent at the end of September. The bank,
which has $3.7 billion in assets, needs roughly $25 million in new
capital to reach that threshold, Chaney calculated.
</P>
<P>
   The bank said it is considering a public equity offering to
raise the additional capital. ``We want some cushion (above 7.25
percent) and we want the ability to grow the bank,'' Dean said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
