<HEADER>
A8562 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-KAUFER-KAUFER_SFCHRON     10-15 1628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAUFER-KAUFER </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Religious-Supply Firms Aren't Realizing Visions of Big Sales  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
For many people, the millennium's end is nothing more than an
excuse for one heck of a good New Year's Eve party. For others,
though, this brief moment is seen as nothing less than the
beginning of the end of life as we know it.
<P>
   From the second coming of Jesus to the arrival of the Antichrist
to all-out Armageddon, Y2K is viewed by many in religious circles
as a pivotal event in the history of mankind _ one that is best
prepared for with a renewed commitment to spiritual matters.
</P>
<P>
   This surge in faith-related activity should be making itself
felt in companies that specialize in religious goods. But those in
the religious-supplies trade are finding that sales are up only
modestly as the 1990s stagger to a close.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufer's Religious Supplies, San Francisco's oldest and largest
purveyor of church goods, is a good case in point. Although owner
David Kaufer said it is clear that church attendance is up because
he is selling more candles to parishes, he has yet to see a run on
religious supplies by people believing that the apocalypse is just
around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you going to stockpile?'' he asked. ``Are you going
to buy 100 a hundred  &LR; crucifixes?''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Kaufer doesn't recognize Y2K as a unique business
opportunity. He has high hopes that banners, pins and coffee cups
bearing the Catholic church's official ``holy year'' logo will be a
hot item going into the all-important Christmas season.
</P>
<P>
   And he is keeping his fingers crossed that the increase in
church attendance may prompt more clerics to spruce up their
appearance with new black shirts ($30), white collars ($3.20) or
even a snappy Jesus wristwatch ($37.50).
</P>
<P>
   The religious-supplies field is dominated by companies like
Kaufer's _ small, family run concerns that cater mainly to the
needs of local churches. Only about a quarter of sales are to
walk-in retail customers.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufer's was established in Tacoma, Wash., in 1904, and
subsequently expanded to Seattle and then to San Francisco. The
company grew when it bought out Stadler Co. on Market Street in
1968 and moved to its present location near San Francisco State
University in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufer's serves about 2,200 Catholic churches and 800 other
Christian facilities throughout the Bay Area and Pacific Rim,
including Hawaii, Guam and Japan. It sees approximately $2 million
in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by metal chalices, colorful vestments and crosses of
all stripes, David Kaufer, 49, makes a striking impression with his
long hair, dark eyes, mustache and goatee. He represents the fourth
generation of his family in the religious-supplies industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people in the business, they grow up in it,'' Kaufer
said. ``I've been working in it since I was a teenager.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar story was told by Michael Norton, whose father
purchased 90-year-old McCoy Church Goods in Burlingame about three
decades ago. ``The family structure in this business works well
with churches,'' he said. ``No one's trying to ace anyone out.''
</P>
<P>
   Norton said the millennium has had a small but noticeable effect
on his shop's sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are gathering nuts for the winter,'' he said.
``I've seen people buy multiple candles out of anticipation of
three days of darkness. People are feeling a need to prepare.''
</P>
<P>
   Three days of darkness are one of the prophesies concerning the
return of Jesus and a cataclysmic battle with the forces of
darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Other faiths, meanwhile, are finding adherents a good deal less
preoccupied with millennial matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not our millennium,'' noted Millie Goltz, a saleswoman at
Palo Alto's Bob and Bob, the Bay Area's largest purveyor of Jewish
goods. ``For us, the year is 5760.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jerry Derblich, owner of Afikomen Jewish Books, Gifts and
Arts in Berkeley, said he has seen about two dozen Christian
customers stop by his store during the past year to purchase prayer
shawls. He speculated that the buyers may have millennial motives
related to Old Testament prophesies.
</P>
<P>
   By the Islamic calendar, the year is now 1420. Khaled Hamid,
manager of Casbah Halal Market in South San Francisco, said he
hasn't seen much of an improvement in sales of prayer rugs, incense
or other such items as a result of looming Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Muslims consider the year 2000 to be just like any
other,'' he noted. ``They believe God has provided and will
continue to provide.''
</P>
<P>
   While the millennium may be having only a modest effect on
religious-supplies companies, there is another development out
there that many in the business believe could have a potentially
devastating impact: the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, such worries remain largely hypothetical because
there are as yet relatively few religious-supplies firms online.
But it was only a few years ago that online purveyors of books, CDs
and all manner of technology were themselves a rare commodity, and
today, they are turning their respective industries upside down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, manufacturers sell to dealers, who then sell to the
churches,'' said David Malhame, executive secretary of the National
Church Goods Association in Pennsylvania. ``But if a manufacturer
puts up a Web site, they can sell to anyone they please. Who knows
how this will affect our business?''
</P>
<P>
   David Kaufer isn't sure about that, either. But he does know
that things gradually are changing in an industry that has always
prided itself on being close-knit and cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, for example, an Arizona company began direct marketing
to churches nationwide, seeking to snatch business away from local
suppliers by undercutting their prices. Such brazen aggressiveness
previously was unheard of in the religious-supplies trade, in which
established companies honor long-standing ``gentlemen's
agreements'' not to encroach on each other's territories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to compete with them,'' Kaufer said. ``They have their
game plan and are good at what they do.''
</P>
<P>
   His consternation is clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could put an 800 number out there, but I don't,'' he said.
``It's just a personal decision about how we want to do business.''
</P>
<P>
   At McCoy, Norton expressed similar distaste for more
confrontational business practices. But he admitted that his
company is vulnerable to any competitor with the resources to mount
a significant e-commerce operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``No family business has the time or money to maintain a
400-page catalog on the Internet,'' Norton said.
</P>
<P>
   The 800-pound gorilla that many in the religious-supplies
industry are keeping an eye on is an Illinois outfit called Roman
Inc., formerly Roman Religious Goods. With an already substantial
Web site, Roman is well-positioned to capture a hefty online share
of church-goods sales.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for the mom-and-pop shops, though, Roman is more
concerned these days with gifts and collectibles than it is with
traditional religious supplies.
</P>
<P>
   If there is an area where such shops do have legitimate
concerns, it's books. A sizable portion of business for nearly all
religious-supplies companies involves supplying Bibles and other
religious publications to churches and schools.
</P>
<P>
   At Kaufer's, a large part of the company's showroom is devoted
to shelves containing titles like ``10 More Good Reasons to Be a
Catholic'' and ``Sacred Sex: Chastity _ Because You're Worth It!''
More than 60 pages of the company's 550-page catalog are devoted to
books.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufer admitted that his business would take a serious hit if
the major religious publishers offered their products online at
discount prices.
</P>
<P>
   To date, none has rocked the boat. For example, Catholic Book
Publishing Co. of New Jersey offers its ``family edition'' Bible
through dealers and online at the same price: $51.95. The
Liturgical Press of Minnesota offers a book of hymnals both online
and through dealers for $11.95 for orders of 25 or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   However, both companies allow buyers to purchase books online,
thus allowing ``wired'' pastors to bypass local retailers if they
so choose.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for religious-supplies outlets, Kaufer said precious
few members of the clergy are computer savvy. (His company carries
only a handful of religious-software titles.) The threat of direct
business-to-consumer e-commerce will remain limited until a new
generation of tech-oriented pastors arrives on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufer, like virtually all others in his business, insisted that
brick-and-mortar dealers will survive the onslaught of the Net by
emphasizing the personal service they provide to customers _ a
sense of loyalty that he says his customers reciprocate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Churches like the people contact,'' he said. ``They wouldn't
just go on the Internet and buy things directly.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not now, but give them a few years. Whatever else, it
seems clear that the religious-supplies industry will be making
some adjustments by the time a fifth generation of Kaufer takes
over the family business.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if the next generation is keen to carry on the legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufer has three daughters and a son. His oldest child, Lisa,
15, has been helping out around the store for the past couple of
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it's my job,'' she said with a shy smile. ``In the
next 20 years, I probably won't be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa went on to explain that she wants to open her own bookstore
_ selling mainstream titles, not just religious publications _ and
almost certainly will sell books on the Web, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, sitting beside her, listened quietly, his hands
clasped together as if in prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry, Dad,'' Lisa said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
