<SLUG> BC-KAUFERSIDE-KAUFERSIDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMUNION WAFER FIRM WON'T BREAK BREAD PACT  &HT;     BY DAVID LAZARUS
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Cavanagh Co. of Rhode Island, the world's largest manufacturer of
communion wafers, is perhaps uniquely positioned to cut out the
middleman and deal directly with Catholic churches via the
Internet. The company dominates its market, and its products are
constantly in demand.
<P>
   ``We'd never do it,'' insists George Farrelly, Cavanagh's
general manager. ``We have a conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a decision to pursue e-commerce would have profound
moral implications. That's because Cavanagh now sells its entire
output at wholesale prices to convents around the world, and the
nuns in turn sell the wafers to parishes with a retail markup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The convents rely on altar bread almost solely for their
income,'' Farrelly said. ``To cut them out would be
unconscionable.''
</P>
<P>
   Cavanagh has been in the communion wafer business since 1946,
when brothers John and Paul Cavanagh began building and selling
machines devised by their father to automate the production
process.
</P>
<P>
   They received special permission from the church in the 1950s to
begin producing wafers themselves as nuns became increasingly
unable to keep pace with demand.
</P>
<P>
   Then, about a decade later, the brothers came up with patented
new machines after the Second Vatican Council ruled that communion
wafers should look and taste more like food. They stopped selling
their machines to would-be competitors and focused exclusively on
altar-bread production.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the privately held company operates out of a
60,000-square-foot facility in the town of Greenville, R.I. The
wafers are cut from sheets of flour and water that have passed
through a gas-fired oven and special humidifier.
</P>
<P>
   Cavanagh sells 1,000 white or whole wheat communion wafers to
convents for approximately $9. The nuns then pass them along to
parishes for roughly 50 percent more per shipment.
</P>
<P>
   Cavanagh's wafers account for about 70 percent of the U.S.
market and half of the wafers consumed in Canada, Britain and
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Do nuns drive a tough bargain in business negotiations?
</P>
<P>
   Farrelly laughs. ``You'd be surprised,'' he replies.
</P>
<P>
