<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANLEY'S INJURY ADDS TO QUESTIONS ABOUT RED SOX LINEUP
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The trainer walked up to Mike Stanley and, without
interrupting the conversation, peeled away the big bandage that
held the ice bag in place on Stanley's left wrist. As he continued
talking, Stanley shifted the soda cup from his left hand to his
right hand. The outside of the wrist was red, but little damage
showed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't as much swelling as I thought there would be,''
said Stanley, the Red Sox first baseman. ``It's not that bad. I've
been hit quite a few times this year, but never in the wrist.
Little worried about it, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Had there been a game Friday, could Stanley have played?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he replied. ``I'm not testing it out. Just let
it relax. Sit here with this ice on it. Let it mend, heal. Wait
until tomorrow before I start testing it out. As far as gripping
the bat, I can squeeze pretty good. See how much mobility and
flexibility I have when I start getting into the swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley was hit in the wrist Thursday night by Yankees pitcher
Jeff Nelson in the eighth inning of Game 2 of the American League
Championship Series. He left the game for X-rays, which showed no
break, the Red Sox said. The Yankees went on to win by 3-2 and take
a 2-0 lead in the best-of-7 series.
</P>
<P>
   With Game 3 here on Saturday, most of the conversations
concerned the pitching matchup of New York's Roger Clemens and
Boston's Pedro Martinez. But the Stanley injury also could prove
significant for a gritty Red Sox team that seems to be suffering
physically as the postseason wears on. Martinez missed part of the
previous series against Cleveland with a sore back. Rich Garces, a
relief pitcher, could not pitch in Game 2 against the Yankees
because of a sore arm.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra, the star shortstop, missed one game against
Cleveland with a sore right wrist and has played with bandages on
it. He, like Stanley, was hit by a pitched ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `It hurts, doesn't it?''' Garciaparra said when asked
about his conversation with Stanley about their injuries. ``He's a
little bigger than I am. Bigger bones.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Stanley has only one hit in seven at-bats against the
Yankees, he was 10 for 20 against Cleveland. If he cannot play
first base, manager Jimy Williams would have to make at least one
change in his lineup. Scott Hatteberg, with no at-bats yet in this
series, already was a candidate to replace Brian Daubach as
designated hitter because Daubach is 1 for 10. But Daubach could
stay in the lineup to play first base. Another possibility, at
designated hitter or first base, is Butch Huskey, who struck out as
a pinch-hitter with the bases loaded in the eighth on Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Huskey acknowledged that Stanley's absence might increase his
participation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably would,'' Huskey said. ``Hopefully, Stano will be in.
If he's not, we'll keep up from where he is. It's not one guy on
this team that makes this team win every day; guys come off the
bench and do great jobs. Stano has been one of our best hitters in
the postseason. If he can't go, we'll have to figure something out,
get someone in there who's going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked specifically about Stanley's condition, Williams
replied: ``He got whacked good. He got whacked pretty good. I just
talked to him and he says he is better. I said, `Better than what?'
He got hit not too many hours ago, but I really believe he will be
ready to play. He is a tough kid, you know, he is, he doesn't say a
lot. But that ball got him flush.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
