<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8583 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CANADA-AIR-TRAVEL-ART     10-15 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-AIR-TRAVEL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGREEMENT LEADS TO BOOM IN U.S.-CANADA AIR TRAFFIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., N.C., Ohio, La., R.I., Ariz., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA _ The last time President Clinton came to Canada's
capital, in 1995, he visited the neo-Gothic Parliament building to
witness the signing of an abstract piece of economic diplomacy: an
open-skies agreement with Canada.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton returned here last week, the benefits were as
concrete as the direct flight between here and Washington's Reagan
National Airport that began two months ago, just in time for the
president's advance team.
</P>
<P>
   The new flight is part of a two-thirds increase in the number of
flights between Canada and the United States over the last five
years. Across the United States, 24 cities have begun direct
flights to Canada. Freed to choose routes and equipped with smaller
commuter jets, Air Canada, the nation's largest airline, has
tripled its American destinations to 45.
</P>
<P>
   By bringing the regional jet revolution to north-south air
travel, Canada now paces Britain as the favored destination for
Americans. Last year, about 8.4 million Americans boarded planes
for each country.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, according to analysis by BACK Associates Inc., a
research firm, there are 193,427 commercial flights from the United
States to Canada _ more than the total for Asia and Europe
combined.
</P>
<P>
   Deregulation led Air Canada to inaugurate direct flights from
its Toronto hub to a series of unlikely American destinations:
Allentown and Harrisburg, Pa.; Charlotte, N.C.; Columbus, Ohio; New
Orleans; Providence, R.I.; Phoenix, and San Jose, Calif. As a
result, Ontario now receives more American air travelers than
France or Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``Air Canada built up a nice model for adding direct city
pairs,'' said Don Ogden, an industry analyst in Vancouver. ``Over
the first couple of years they were able to add route after route
after route.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Canadian side, American and Canadian airlines have
channeled most of the growth into the nation's two busiest airport
hubs, Toronto and Vancouver. But new pairings have also evolved:
Winnipeg-Denver, Edmonton-Chicago, Whitehorse-Anchorage,
Ottawa-Philadelphia and Montreal-Portland, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Moving aggressively into western Canada, Alaska Airlines has
inaugurated service from Seattle to Calgary, Edmonton and Kelowna,
British Columbia. Connecting the prairies, Northwest Airlines has
started flights linking Minneapolis and Regina, Saskatoon and
Kenora.
</P>
<P>
   On Canada's Atlantic side, Air Canada has service between Prince
Edward Island and Boston and has just inaugurated a daily flight
from Halifax, Nova Scotia, to Dulles International Airport in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Since the open-skies agreement was signed in February 1995,
Northwest and Continental Airlines have each inaugurated 10 flights
to Canada. American Airlines has inaugurated eight, United Airlines
six, US Airways four and Delta three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I find out there are new routes being established
between our two countries,'' said Canada's prime minister, Raymond
Chretien, who came here for the Clinton visit. ``Open skies is
great because it has changed the way we do business. It has brought
far more Americans to Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   It has not always been this way. Before the accord was signed,
passenger traffic was stagnating. Since the accord, it has jumped
about one-third.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was enormous frustration on the part of business
travelers, tourists and family members how to get to Canada,''
recalled Federico Pena, who was U.S. transportation secretary when
the 1995 agreement was signed. Speaking from Denver, where he
advises an investment firm, he added: ``There were very, very few
flights, very few locations. If you wanted to fly to Canada, you
had to go through a number of airports.''
</P>
<P>
   Deregulation negotiations had dragged on for years, stalled
largely because Air Canada and its smaller rival, Canadian
Airlines, feared they would lose market share to American
competitors. In the end, a fresh team was brought in and the
Canadians were given a two-year head start to open new routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at the signing on Parliament Hill in 1995,'' recalled
Paul Frazer, spokesman for the Canadian Embassy in Washington.
``There were all these other people, some with gray hair. I was
trying to figure out who they all were. It turned out the room was
full of negotiating teams going back 25 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Air Canada is currently fighting a hostile takeover: a proposal
to merge with Canadian Airlines, on which shareholders are to vote
Nov. 8.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how a merger might affect the new American air
links, and there is some fear that fledgling American routes might
be cut to increase the combined airlines' profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Partly to head off criticism that he wants to create a monopoly,
Gerald Schwartz, a Canadian financier who is leading the takeover
bid, announced last week that if his merger plan was approved, he
would largely freeze domestic fares and route networks for five
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
