<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8585 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-ABDUCTION-KANSAS-KAN &LR;      10-15 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABDUCTION-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCHERS FIND BODY OF 10-YEAR-OLD KIDNAP VICTIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD ESPINOZA and TANYANIKA SAMUELS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Investigators Friday found the body of
10-year-old Pamela Butler in a field a few hundred yards from a
church in Grain Valley. She was covered with sticks, and her
clothes were strewn nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the story didn't have a happy ending, like we
had hoped,'' said George Sims, a spokesman for the Kansas City,
Kan., police. ``But we did find her.''
</P>
<P>
   Pamela was kidnapped Tuesday evening, snatched from the street
while she skated in front of her family's home in Kansas City, Kan.
As one of her sisters watched, a stranger threw Pamela into a
pickup and sped away.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities Thursday charged Keith D. Nelson, 24, with
kidnapping. Nelson was arrested earlier that day on the banks of
the Kansas River near the 18th Street Expressway bridge. He was in
custody Friday night at the University of Kansas Medical Center,
where he was being treated for a severe leg injury.
</P>
<P>
   At 2 p.m. Friday, Pamela's father, Paul Butler, tearfully told
friends and news reporters, ``They found her; that's all I can
say.''
</P>
<P>
   About an hour later, Cherri West, Pamela's mother, talked about
how she'd been bracing herself for the possibility of Pamela's
death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was worried about her not eating and being cold,'' West
said, crying. ``Now I don't have to worry about that; but this
isn't the way it should have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities searched four sites during the morning before
turning almost full attention to the partly wooded Grain Valley
area. It was the third time detectives looked there, but they
wanted to go in further Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt there was still evidence out there, so we wanted to do
a large-scale, thorough search,'' said Monte Strait, assistant
special agent in charge of the FBI's Kansas City office.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 FBI, Jackson County and Wyandotte County, Kan.,
officials fanned out across the field, which borders the woods and
encircles the Grain Valley Christian Church. Slowly, methodically,
they walked shoulder to shoulder through the knee-high grass and
overgrown brush, finally disappearing into the thicket.
</P>
<P>
   About 12:30 p.m. searchers found Pamela's body lying several
hundred yards northwest of the church. They had searched a little
more than a square mile.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, members of the search team found items of clothing that
matched what Pamela was wearing when she disappeared Tuesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the body was found, about 60 FBI agents and other
investigators kept scouring the land behind the church, looking for
additional evidence, such as blood and more clothing, FBI spokesman
Jeff Lanza said.
</P>
<P>
   For several hours Pamela's body remained where investigators had
come across it, while the lawmen finished examining the area for
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   They said they couldn't tell how Pamela died and were waiting
for the results of an autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation in Grain Valley was to continue into Friday
night and resume at first light Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela's body was carried away in a coroner's van at 4:25 p.m.
to the medical examiner's office. An autopsy was expected to be
performed Friday night, and but U.S. Attorney Steve Hill said he
would not release the cause of death because it was an ongoing
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson has been charged in federal court with kidnapping Pamela
and carrying her into Missouri. Hill said Nelson may appear before
a magistrate early next week. Officials are waiting until he is
physically and mentally fit.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said investigators will continue to evaluate the evidence
and decide whether to bring additional charges. Hill said
investigators will continue to look into the possibility of a
second suspect, but refused to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the U.S. attorney's office said they planned to
meet with Jackson County and Wyandotte County officials and
Pamela's family before deciding on whether to seek the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities had been searching for Pamela since Tuesday, when
she was dragged into a pickup near her home. Another driver gave
chase and although he lost track of the pickup, he wrote down its
license plate number and reported it to police.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that the abductor literally lay in wait in the
truck as Pamela skated unsuspectingly toward it. As she approached
the back of the truck, he jumped out and threw her inside, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   An hour or so after the abduction, a church custodian and his
wife saw a pickup parked behind Grain Valley Christian Church, near
where Pamela's body was found Friday. They told authorities they
didn't see much inside other than a brown plaid afghan with a
fringe, spread over the front seat. The truck didn't belong at the
church, so the man wrote down its license plate number for police.
</P>
<P>
   Grain Valley Police Chief Gary Scherer praised the custodian,
saying his tip was critical in this case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had that not happened, we might never have gotten here,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The pickup was next seen about midnight, parked in the 3000
block of East 14th Street, about four blocks from Nelson's mother's
home. It had been emptied, vacuumed and scrubbed inside and out,
according to an affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   But when investigators removed the seat, the affidavit said,
they found longish, light-colored hair strands that matched
Pamela's hair.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle was identified by its owner, who told authorities he
had lent it to Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at Nelson's mother's home, detectives saw an afghan
similar to that the custodian described as being in the truck. A
tracking dog that had sniffed clothes from Pamela's room walked
around the house and stopped at the afghan.
</P>
<P>
   But where were Nelson and the girl?
</P>
<P>
   Nelson was found about 1:30 p.m. Thursday after a civilian
employee of the Kansas City, Kan., Police Department took lunch to
her husband on the job at the Burlington Northern Santa Fe railroad
tracks near 18th Street and the Kansas River. She decided to take a
slow drive along the dike on a hunch that Nelson might be there.
</P>
<P>
   She spotted him near the expressway bridge and he hobbled on his
injured leg into the river. Railroad workers took Nelson to shore
and held him for investigators, who turned him over to a helicopter
ambulance crew.
</P>
<P>
   Cherri West said her family needs help for the burial. Donations
may be sent to the Pamela Butler and Family Fund, First State Bank,
650 Kansas Ave., Kansas City, KS 66105. Checks should be made out
to the Pamela Butler and Family Fund.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
