<SLUG> BC-MARKET-RATTLED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW DIPS 267 POINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The stock market dropped 267 points Friday _ an 11.5
percent slide from its all-time high in August _ as investors
panicked about an ominous inflation report and a warning by the
Federal Reserve chairman that stocks are becoming risky.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's close of 10,019.71 marked an official ``correction''
in the market, or a drop of 10 percent or more from the index's
all-time high of 11,326.04, reached on Aug. 25.
</P>
<P>
   The rout was triggered by a carefully worded speech delivered by
Fed chief Alan Greenspan on Thursday night that warned investors
and lenders to prepare for a ``reversal'' in the business cycle and
``inevitable'' losses as stock or other asset prices fall.
Investors then were hit by a government report that wholesale
prices in September had their biggest jump in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was a perfect illustration that inflation and stock
prices tend to go in opposite directions,'' said Doug Cliggott,
managing director of J.P. Morgan in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried about the next few months. We've got more bad news
on inflation and interest rates ahead of us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's slide Friday, to 10,019.71, was the outcome of a
nerve-wracking day in which the index plunged by more than 200
points during the first hour of trading and later slumped to a low
of 9998.18, before recovering slightly. It was the first time since
April 7 that the market has dropped below the psychologically
important 10,000 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Other major stock indexes dropped even more. The
technology-heavy Nasdaq plunged 75.01 points, or 2.67 percent, and
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index gave up 36.01 points, or 2.81
percent.
</P>
<P>
   With Greenspan's speech still fresh in investors' minds, the US
Department of Labor reported that inflation may be gaining
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Investors fear that if the CPI begins to creep up, the Federal
Reserve will raise interest rates for a third time this year to
cool a sizzling economy and attempt to relieve inflationary
pressures. If the Fed, at its Nov. 16 meeting, increases rates, the
cost of borrowing for businesses and consumers would rise,
dampening demand for goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   Wholesale prices paid to producers rose 1.1 percent in
September, the government said. That translates to a 3.39 increase
in the producer price index during the past year, according to
Oscar Gonzalez, an economist for John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance
Co..
</P>
<P>
   Subtracting out fuel prices, prices, which have been rising, and
food prices, the so-called ``core'' producer price index was up a
hearty 0.8 percent last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very large number,'' said Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Said Greg Smith, chief investment strategist in New York, ``If
you were worried about Greenspan before, that (PPI report) just
cranked it up another notch.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a clear trend of higher wholesale prices, however, there
is virtually no evidence that they are being passed through to
consumers, analysts said. But economists will be closing watching
the consumer price report for September, which will be released
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's market, nearly every industry _ from financial
services to automobiles _ was pummeled. Some small technology
stocks listed on the Nasdaq declined 20 to 30 percent or more.
Motorola Inc., General Motors Corp. and Biogen Inc. fell by more
than 5 percent. And financial stocks, which are particularly
sensitive to moves in interest rates, fell sharply. A large
credit-card issuer, Capital One Financial, gave up more than 8
percent of its value.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market seemed to be non-discriminating in taking stocks
down,'' said Steve Esielonis, head of global equity strategy for
State Street Global Advisors, division of State Street Boston Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's fallout capped a week in a nervous market marched
steadily downward in reaction to each whif of bad news. Market
analysts said Friday's reaction to bad news was the most dramatic
example of how jittery investors have become.
</P>
<P>
   On a calmer note, Wayne Ayers, chief economist for Fleet Boston
Corp., said the forces driving wholesale prices in September ``are
probably going to be one-time events.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Clough, chief investment strategist for Merrill Lynch &AMP;
Co., sees the early signs of weakness in the economy, including a
softer bond market than a year ago, a softer dollar, and
indications that some companies relied on ``accounting'' to boost
profits.
</P>
<P>
   A slowdown in the economy would be welcome by the Fed, which
would see less reason to put on the brakes by raising interest
rates. Clough said a slowdown that brings softer profits and lower
sales is another scenario for weak stocks in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually we're going to see demand slow down,'' Clough said.
``It's taken longer than we thought because money has been so
available, but once it starts to slow we'll see more profit
problems. That's why the market is so weak. I don't think it's an
inflation problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps reacting to signs of weakness, yields on the benchmark
30-year US Treasury bond dipped to 6.26 percent. That is down from
a two-year high of 6.33 percent on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
