<HEADLINE>
PATERNO PREPARES FOR OHIO STATE BY ASKING FOR PEACE AND QUIET  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Pa.)   By JOE DRAPE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATE COLLEGE, Pa. _ He believes his team is being treated like
rock stars and, frankly, Joe Paterno does not like it. So the Penn
State football coach pulled the plug on the show _ the publicity
one _ this week and asked the team's fans to ease up and let the
Nittany Lions prepare for Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   No autographs. No crowd scenes. For reporters, he offered up
three players for a total of 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get away from it,'' Paterno said of his Nittany
Lions, 6-0 and No. 3 in The New York Times computer ranking. ``It
got to the point where we've got to get some control over it. You
guys keep forgetting they're still college students.
</P>
<P>
   ``LaVar Arrington walks down the street and he's besieged by
people. You're the first people that would crucify them if they
don't go to class or they flunk out of school or something happens
to them. I've got to protect them. This is just a week I felt I had
to get a grip on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outmaneuvered, Ohio State Coach John Cooper reminded
his players that no one is clamoring for them. They are a modest
4-2 and have hardly resembled the Big Ten power that has finished
No. 2 in the final national rankings in two of the last three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper caught his players' attention when he suggested the
Buckeyes needed a poor game from Penn State to win Saturday at
Beaver Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's pretty obvious that if we play our best game and
they play their best game and neither team makes any mistakes,
they'll probably win the game,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Each coach is doing what it takes to gain an edge in one of
college football's newest and fiercest rivalries. Since Penn State
started playing in the Big Ten in 1993, the two have met six times.
The Buckeyes have won four of them _ including a 28-9 thumping of
the Nittany Lions last year.
</P>
<P>
   In asking for peace and quiet this week, Paterno acknowledged
that Ohio State, despite its two losses, could be the most
formidable threat to his team's national title aspirations and
indicated he wasn't entirely pleased with his team's performance
this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions needed a blocked field goal to down
Pittsburgh, a late bomb to outlast Miami and have sputtered the
last two weeks in victories over outclassed opponents, Indiana and
Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have been a tired football team,'' Paterno said.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State is trying to play down the rivalry. Safety Derek Fox
said the Nittany Lions do not want to put the Buckeyes ``up on a
pedestal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a big week,'' Fox said. ``But this year, myself and this
whole team, we're taking a different approach. Sometimes, we put
too much emphasis on this game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes, meanwhile, are befuddled about their coach's lack
of faith. Some bristled. Others tried to get inside Cooper's head,
and still bristled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a fair assessment because if that's the
case, then we don't need to play the game,'' Ohio State wide
receiver Reggie Germany said.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Ahmed Plummer tersely said that he would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Mike Collins acted stunned. ``Wow, that fires
me up,'' he said. ``That gets me upset to hear that.''
</P>
<P>
   The All-Big Ten linebacker Na'il Diggs tried to play it off as a
motivational technique _ to insure that his Buckeyes are more like
the team that defeated Purdue, 25-22, last week rather than the one
that gave up 42 points and lost to Wisconsin the previous week.
</P>
<P>
   Diggs has reminded his teammates that they were the nation's No.
1 team last year when Michigan State came to Columbus and upset
them, and that an upset of undefeated Penn State would move them
back up the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he is irritated at Cooper's comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is, it's a weird way of doing it,'' Diggs said of
Cooper's needle. ``If it is, it sounds like it should work. It's
going to tick a few guys off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
