<HEADLINE>
FAMILY, FRIENDS REMEMBER PAMELA BUTLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STACY DOWNS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ As her relatives wept, Amanda West recalled
the little things she did with her stepsisters, Penny and Pamela
Butler _ things that now have become important memories.
</P>
<P>
   She and the two girls had fun when they shopped for school
supplies or when they recently attended a church retreat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a blast,'' Amanda West said. ``I don't know what it's
going to be like without both of them together.''
</P>
<P>
   The body of 10-year-old Pamela was found Friday in a partly
wooded area in Grain Valley in Jackson County. Pamela had been
missing since Tuesday evening when she was abducted while skating
on the street in front of her home in Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   As the news spread, friends and relatives gathered to hug and
cry on the front lawn of the family's home in Kansas City, Kan.
They shared memories of Pamela, who loved to play outdoors. They
said she was a sweet girl, who often smiled and laughed.
</P>
<P>
   They brought flowers and mementos that were placed with the
candles, stuffed animals and large cards on the front porch of the
modest two-story frame house. Others handed Cherri West small
amounts of cash they had collected. West said it would help pay for
her daughter's burial.
</P>
<P>
   Penny, Pamela's 11-year-old sister, stood with family and
friends on the front porch after learning that her sister's body
had been found. Her eyes were red from crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure it's hit Penny yet,'' said her mother, Cherri
West. ``In a couple of days, she'll want to play and ask `Where's
Pammy?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Penny saw a stranger grab Pamela and drive away.
</P>
<P>
   Before the death of Pamela, whom many called ``Pammy,'' the
sisters always played together.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't pry them apart,'' said Amanda West, 18.
</P>
<P>
   Cherri West talked about how people wouldn't get to see Pamela,
a fifth-grader at Fiske Elementary, grow up to realize her dreams.
She was a straight-A student who wanted to go to Sumner Academy,
where students who have excellent academic records can attend
starting in the seventh grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her wish didn't come true,'' Cherri West said between sobs.
</P>
<P>
   She thanked the community for its outpouring of support and for
working hard to find Pamela and the person who abducted her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope no one else in this community has to go through this,''
she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
