<SLUG> BC-FBC-BC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON COLLEGE IN A MUST-WIN SITUATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ At the beginning of the season, almost everyone on
Boston College's football team recognized the sixth game of the
season against Pittsburgh was important. If everything fell into
place, the Pittsburgh game could provide an opportunity for the
Eagles to start 6-0 and become bowl eligible.
</P>
<P>
   But the Eagles' 24-14 loss at Temple last week changed all that,
transforming Saturday's game against the Panthers (3-2, 1-1 Big
East) at Alumni Stadium into a must-win situation for the Eagles
(4-1, 1-1).
</P>
<P>
   Junior quarterback Tim Hasselbeck suffered a mild separation of
his right (throwing) shoulder against Temple. Although Hasselbeck
had been medically cleared to play, coach Tom O'Brien will start
redshirt freshman Brian St. Pierre against the Panthers. O'Brien
said he did not want to put at Hasselbeck at risk, and will have
him back up St. Pierre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim has so much more experience, and we've tried to get Brian
in the games and have him play,'' O'Brien said. ``You just don't
know what he's going to do in a full game. That's the biggest
apprehension I have on my part about Brian right now, but I feel
confident in his ability.''
</P>
<P>
   There are hardly any easy games left on BC's schedule, which
will get exponentially tougher next week against Miami and at
Syracuse Oct. 30. The Eagles wrap up the season with games against
West Virginia (Nov. 13), at Notre Dame (Nov. 20), and at Virginia
Tech (Nov. 26).
</P>
<P>
   That explained why, as far back as last week, senior center and
offensive captain Butch Palaza was prompted to remark that the Pitt
game ``was going to be humongous for us.''
</P>
<P>
   With BC's season hinging on Saturday's outcome, it could be even
bigger than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be huge,'' said Pedro Cirino, BC's senior free
safety and defensive co-captain. ``There's a lot of implications in
the Big East standings. We can't afford to go 1-2 in conference. We
have to do whatever we can to get this game. They're going to come
up with the same mindset and the same attitude. It's going to be
tough, but we're going to be at home.''
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers enter the game on the heels of a 24-17 loss to
Syracuse Oct. 7. Quarterback David Priestley entered the game in
the second half in relief of starter John Turman. Although
Priestley rallied Pittsburgh from a 24-0 halftime deficit to within
a Hail Mary heave at the end of the game, Pitt coach Walt Harris
indicated earlier this week that Turman will remain as his starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the decision to go with David because I thought we
needed a spark (against Syracuse),'' Harris said. ``But that
doesn't mean that John is finished as a starter.''
</P>
<P>
   During their first open date of the season Sept. 11, the Eagles
saw what Pittsburgh capable of in the Panthers' 20-17 loss at Penn
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone came back to the locker room the next day and said,
`Pitt's for real,' '' said Hasselbeck. ``You look at that game and
they probably should've won that game. Then you look at the
Syracuse game and the ball doesn't bounce their way the whole first
half. I mean with a couple of breaks, they're 5-0. They've had some
tough losses, but they're a good football team.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien was most impressed by Pitt's improved running game, led
by junior tailback Kevan Barlow (90.0 yards per game), who ranks
third in the conference behind Virginia Tech's Shyrone Stith (116)
and BC's Cedric Washington (114.4).
</P>
<P>
   ``Barlow's a great back and has really helped them a lot as far
as their running game goes,'' O'Brien said. ``They're sound on
defense and come at you from all angles and play solid defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite losing its first game of the season and being outgained
by Temple, 492-328, O'Brien realizes his team cannot afford to
dwell on the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's move on,'' he said. ``Let's just worry about and take
care of the things we have control over and let the other things go
away. That's the only way we're going to get another victory this
year, and that's to focus and concentrate on the opponent at hand
and that's what we have to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 2120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
