r a BC-ABDUCT-SAFETY-KAN &LR;      10-15 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABDUCT-SAFETY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS CAN TEACH CHILDREN MEASURES TO REDUCE RISK OF ABDUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN UHLENHUTH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The kidnapping Tuesday evening of 10-year-old
Pamela Butler from the street near her Kansas City, Kan. home
serves as a chilling reminder, says Sgt. Joe Reed of the Overland
Park, Kan., Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't any guarantees, and we're vulnerable as a
society.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, he and other law enforcement and mental-health
professionals point out that such tragedies need not cause
excessive worry among other children and their parents, and that
there are actions people can take to minimize the odds of such a
tragedy striking again, closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of random acts of violence, parents should
reassure their children and reinforce the importance of exercising
certain reasonable safety measures, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   The extent to which children become anxious over random violence
aimed at other children varies widely, said Sharon Cain, a clinical
assistant professor of psychiatry at the University of Kansas
Medical Center in Kansas City, Kan. She suspects that only a small
proportion of children are seriously troubled by news of such
tragedies.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, she said, parents ``need to be reassuring, that
they're doing everything they can to keep (their children) safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Calvert, a clinical social worker at Crittenton, said:
``If your child is particularly anxious, I think you would want to
validate their concerns and fears, allow them to express their
feelings about it, and then open it up to talking about, `What kind
of things can we do to keep ourselves safe?' ''
</P>
<P>
   She suggests that parents address, ``Why is it important that we
know where you are, and if you go someplace else? Why is it
important that you be with friends, and not out by yourself? Why is
it important not to talk to someone who approaches you in a car?
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time,'' she cautioned, ``you don't want to cause
them anxiety and fear. You want to emphasize your confidence in the
child's ability to make safe decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed, of the Overland Park Police Department, points out that
there are ``no recipes'' for preventing such a tragedy, but he
encourages parents to take certain steps.
</P>
<P>
   It is best that children be supervised by an adult when they are
not at home, he said. And those who are supervising should ``look
with a suspicious eye to what's going on around them. Is there a
strange person here with their kid, or (someone) paying undue
attention to kids?''
</P>
<P>
   Next best to adult supervision is the company of other children.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, ``we need to keep hammering home the point
about when a stranger approaches, when you get that uncomfortable
feeling, go with that feeling, run, seek the nearest adult.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people stop and ask directions or offer rides, if you don't
know the person in the car and they're approaching, get away from
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve McBride, executive director of the Kansas City branch of
the National Center for Missing and Exploited Children, noted that
Pamela Butler ``did one thing that she absolutely needed to do. She
brought attention to herself and to what was being done to her.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, people obtained a description of the abductor's
vehicle and the license number. Those clues helped police in their
hunt for the abductor and led to the arrest Thursday afternoon of
Keith D. Nelson, 24, on the banks of the Kansas River near the 18th
Street Expressway.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a key, key thing, to bring attention to yourself,'' he
said. ``She did great.''
</P>
<P>
   Some perpetrators have been known to release children because of
the ruckus they were causing, McBride said.
</P>
<P>
   Caryln Saunders, a counseling psychologist in Kansas City,
concurred with the need for parents to reassure and instruct their
children about safety precautions. But she added one other note _
don't overreact.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is such an unusual event. I'm not trying to minimize
what's going on, but how long has it been since we had an event
like this in Kansas City? People are more upset about this than
being in a car accident, and yet the probabilities are so far
apart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
