<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY RIVALRY A ONE-WAY AFFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rudy Giuliani had just ended his daily news
conference and was walking briskly toward the door when I shot out
the question I had traveled so far to ask: ``Do you regard Boston
as the major cultural rival to New York?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No more questions,'' an aide barked in a typically New York
way. Giuliani paused in the doorway and stared back bemused, his
coterie of advisers pausing silently around him.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the eruption that was no doubt to come at the very mention
of his archrival city, his patience breaking like a pane of glass,
the seething quotes that would tumble forth. Boston? You think that
glorified little cowtown peopled by puritanical nerds could even
hold a church candle to my teeming metropolis?
</P>
<P>
   He opened his mouth. I squinted in delighted dread.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Boston very much,'' he said, smiling. ``It's a very
nice city. But my attitude is that you can't rival New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Like it very much? Very nice? That scum. How dare he!
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the mayor has gone soft, so I quickly punched out the
number to a real New Yorker, Ed Koch, a guy who would just as soon
disembowel Bambi as tell you how to find the 4-train up to the
Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Boston,'' he says. ``But there are no rivals to New
York. We're the capital of the world in commerce, culture,
capitalism, everything. But if it spurs you on, that's great.''
</P>
<P>
   Love? Spurs you on? The temerity. The ruthless brass!
</P>
<P>
   OK, next up: Donald Trump. His assistant announced that he was
unavailable. Aha. The man is so obviously outraged and threatened
at the mere mention of his metropolitan nemesis that he can't find
his way to speak a few civil words. Finally, we're getting to the
moody core of this dark rivalry. So I approach someone of equal
importance: Trump Tower doorman John McDwyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big Brahmin hello to you,'' I said, knowing that would get
him _ the history he doesn't have, the refinement we do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston's a beautiful city,'' he offered.
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful? I am incensed, almost irrational. In a last-ditch
effort, I take myself up to Game 1, where I find a man named Carl
Marino from Tinton Falls, N.J., walking around the outfield stands
in a T-shirt that, politely paraphrased, says, ``Boston is not a
nice place.'' Here we go (wink, wink). The rivalry lives on. You
just have to know where to look.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never been,'' he shrugs when asked what he so despises about
Boston. ``My wife wants me to take her there. I just haven't gotten
around to it.''
</P>
<P>
   As I walk away despondent, he calls out sympathetically,
``Boston's all right.'' No, you don't understand.You don't
understand that because we hate you, you must hate us. We draw
life, fullness, validation from your hatred.
</P>
<P>
   We want to hear all the cliches. We want to hear you call us
dorks, geeks, simpletons who marry our own cousins (for the money)
and look at fish and chips as a gastronomical triumph. The men
among us, such as we are, wear brown shoes with blue suits, right?
The women look at Talbot's as the height of fashion. We are Timex
to your Rolex. We want to hear this because it makes us matter.
</P>
<P>
   And we'll strike back. Will we ever. You are predatory and
unsavory and uncouth, not to mention unfriendly. So there. Your car
breaks down on I-95, give it 20 minutes before it's stripped of its
stereo, tires, for God sakes, its dignity. So many of you wear
black that the entirety of Manhattan Island looks like a seminary
school for wayward priests with cell phone addictions. You are
personified by this mananimal Joey Buttafuoco.
</P>
<P>
   All else aside, you do hate our baseball team, don't you? We're
your worst nightmare, right? True enough, you got our goat back in
1920, all for the benefit of ``No, No Nanette.'' You killed us in
September of 1949. You stole our hearts on Oct. 2, 1978. And, OK,
your Yankees have 24 world championships in a span of time in which
the Red Sox have none. But now we have arrived on the doorstep of
history.
</P>
<P>
   We are, as novelist Alexander Theroux writes about this fierce
rivalry, ``natural enemies, threatening entities.'' I call Theroux
for encouragement. Just kidding, he says. ``The rivalry is all in
the minds of Bostonians. It's an amazing hubris on your part.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're like our little brother,'' said Sal Cozzupoli, another
Yankees fan in a ``Boston is not a nice place'' shirt.
</P>
<P>
   All of which makes me hate them even more. Is it really too much
to ask that they hate us in return?
</P>
<P>
   Brian McGrory's e-mail address is mcgrory(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 2126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8608 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-DELAY-REPUBLICANS-ART     10-15 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELAY-REPUBLICANS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
WASHINGTON: he said.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Building DeLay Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Delay was never expected to become whip. When Republicans won
the majority in 1994, Gingrich had endorsed his friend, Rep. Bob
Walker, R-Pa. Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., also made a spirited and
well-financed run. But DeLay defeated them both, benefiting from
nine months of helping Republican congressional candidates around
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   He formed a leadership political action committee, known as
Americans for a Republican Majority, that poured $2 million into
the campaigns of incumbents and challengers. The group has received
large donations from an array of corporations, including tobacco
and telecommunications companies. He has traveled to 25 states to
help get Republicans elected, offering campaign advice,
fund-raising help, anything that a candidate asked for. His toiling
translated into votes.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, now a lobbyist, still seems somewhat jarred that DeLay
defeated him. ``Tom is someone who enjoys raising money,'' Walker
said. ``It is one of his strengths. Even though I didn't want to
campaign that way, I admired in the end that it was successful for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mildred Webber, a DeLay loyalist who managed his campaign
for whip says that it was more than contributions that led to
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom knew that it wasn't just going to be money that got us the
majority _or that won him the whip race,'' she said. ``It was going
to be a full-service operation and that's what we became.''
</P>
<P>
   He even sent out tapes to candidates providing such practical
tutoring as how to use lawn signs.
</P>
<P>
   After securing the whip's job, DeLay continued using money to
enhance his power, much like other aspiring House leaders. Because
he rarely faces a serious challenger for re-election he
traditionally gives away as much as 90 percent of his campaign
funds. And, with Gingrich gone, DeLay has become the linchpin
between Republicans in the House and their conservative donors. His
popularity with these donors was enhanced by his role in the
impeachment of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't waste Tom on small donors,'' said one of DeLay's
advisers. ``We don't ask him to make $1,000 calls. He makes
six-figure calls.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay has expanded his organization from a vote-counting
operation into a kind of political machine.
</P>
<P>
   This year, through a program called Romp, or Retain Our Majority
Program, DeLay nudged his deputy and assistant whips to contribute
to the campaigns of 10 Republican incumbents who were in dange of
losing their re-election races. The money was supplemented by
lobbyists, political action committees and other House leaders,
altogether netting more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay's edge was apparent in an early draft of the program's
organization plan, written by an aide. It opened with a quote from
Winston Churchill that seemed to capture the spirit of the office:
``Victory at all costs, victory in spite of all terror, victory
however long and hard the road may be. For without victory there is
no survival.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay also opened an offshoot of ARMPAC in Virginia, where he
gave donations to candidates for the state legislature. He called
the focus on state politics essential to ``grow the majority
party,'' saying it was designed to help create a farm team for
Congress and wrest control of state legislatures before crucial
decisions on redistricting that could affect control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Operating in Virginia allowed him to take advantage _ as other
lawmakers have done _ of that state's lack of contribution limits
for PACS. In 1996, the Virginia operation directed $12,000 back
into DeLay's federal PAC, drawing a warning letter from the Federal
Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Although DeLay eventually closed his Virginia group, his federal
PAC has continued to maintain a state fund that accepts corporate
donations and keeps its records to itself. The organization is in
the process of registering again in Virginia and Mississippi,
associates said, and plans to focus on the 22 states that allow
corporate contributions to candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Another organization that benefits from DeLay's fund raising is
the Republican Majority Issues Committee, which Democrats have
challenged before the Federal Election Commission because of its
decision not to report donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the worst thing in politics is anonymous, under the
bedclothes money,'' said Rep. David Obey, D-Wis.
</P>
<P>
   The group is led by Karl Gallant, who previously ran the federal
PAC for DeLay. For years, Gallant fought organized labor as vice
president of the National Right to Work Committee. He described the
group as a ``mirror image of the AFL-CIO'' because it would devote
its efforts to identifying and turning out conservative voters in
key Congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the organization unusual is that it is registering
under the IRS code as a nonprofit corporation involved in politics.
That designation means that it does not have to make its tax
returns public or report its contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal election law, such a group is banned from
coordination with candidates and Gallant carefully says that
although DeLay is a major fund-raiser, the organization is
independent from him. ``We are separate from the DeLay operation,''
he said. ``I have had to leave the nest to get this started.''
</P>
<P>
   But many Republican-leaning lobbyists say they consider the
group another surrogate DeLay organization, and DeLay has been
unabashedly helping it raise money. He says he does not run the
group, but he does not distance himself from it either. And he
staunchly defends the lack of disclosure because ``the law doesn't
require it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be glad to disclose it if I can get disclosure of Ralph
Nader's groups, disclosure of the ACLU, disclosure of the leftist
organizations,'' DeLay said. ``If they'll disclose, I'll
disclose.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee made its initial pitch for funds earlier this year
on the private yacht of Amway president Richard DeVos and his wife,
Betsy, the chairwoman of the Michigan Republican Party, both of
whom are among the Republican Party's biggest donors.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay and the other Republican leaders in the Hose were all on
hand. The first to step forward with a pledge was lobbyist and
fund-raiser Jack Abramoff, who is close to DeLay. He says he will
raise ``plenty'' for the effort.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 2126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8609 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-DELAY-REPUBLICANS-ART     10-15 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELAY-REPUBLICANS-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: the effort.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Protecting a Majority
</P>
<P>
   A larger majority in the House would help DeLay with his job as
whip _ to pass the Republican legislative agenda.
</P>
<P>
   To carry out that role, he has assembled 64 colleagues into what
has been called the largest whip organizations in decades, and also
one of the most effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people think I'm handed a bill and I go to the floor and
try to pass it,'' DeLay said. ``It takes much more work. It takes a
lot of work one on one with members.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay's clout was most visible in last year's Republican
leadership elections. DeLay, who has earned the moniker ``The
Hammer,'' was the only one of the Republican leaders to go
unchallenged and in most of the other races he mobilized on behalf
of chosen candidates.
</P>
<P>
   He virtually installed his chief deputy whip, Hastert, R-Ill.,
as speaker after DeLay's first choice, Rep. Bob Livingston, R-La.,
unexpectedly stepped down because of reports of sexual
infidelities.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Thomas Davis, R-Va., who was elected chairman of the
National Republican Congressional Committee, was DeLay's candidate.
The ascension of Rep. J.C. Watts, R-Okla., as Republican Conference
chairman in place of Rep. John Boehner, R-Ohio, led to another
increase in DeLay's power: the uncontested role as his party's
chief liaison with lobbyists, trade associations and business.
</P>
<P>
   Since becoming the majority, House Republicans have aggressively
sought to make sure the corporate interests who benefit from their
agenda hire more Republicans and give them financial support and
lobbying help.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay has long had a kitchen cabinet of lobbyists who meet with
him regularly. Among those hashing out strategy are Paxon, who has
joined the Washington law firm of Akin Gump Strauss Hauer &AMP; Feld,
Abramoff of the Preston, Gates &AMP; Ellis law firm, David Rehr of the
National Beer Wholesalers Association, and Dan Mattoon of Bell
South Corp.
</P>
<P>
   This year DeLay has used his role as liaison to the corporate
world to organize business groups into loose-standing coalitions
around particular issues. His office has relied on high-tech
companies, for example, to build support for legislation shielding
business from lawsuits resulting from Year 2000 computer problems.
When he was fearful that a bill alloting funds for the U.S.
military operation in Yugoslavia would not pass, he enlisted the
lobbying might of defense contractors.
</P>
<P>
   The lobbyists report back with details of whom they contacted.
Aides to DeLay say that the lobbyists get nothing specific in
return though one DeLay loyalist acknowledged, ``We do know who
produces votes. Guys who do well see more favor in our eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay has sought to convince lobbying firms and trade
associations to install more Republicans in their executive
positions. He was warned by the House Ethics Committee after he
tried to persuade a lobbying group not to hire a Democrat as its
president.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay does not insist that every Republican back the
leadership's legislative goals on every vote. And he loses some,
such as the recent defeat of a managed health care bill favored by
the Republican leadership over a more stringent version. Instead,
he demands a signal of how each member will vote _ yes, leaning
yes, no, leaning no _ and he expects no surprises.
</P>
<P>
   In the closing moments of a recent vote on the spending bill for
foreign operations, DeLay signaled to two lawmakers sitting behind
him. Aides said the motion had a meaning: He was letting his
colleagues know he had enough votes to pass the bill without their
votes, and that they could vote no.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are members who on any given issue, because of their
districts or their own particular circumstances, can't vote for a
particular thing,'' said Doolittle. ``He knows who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   FROM HUNTS IN THE SHIRES TO THE HALLS OF CONGRESS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The term ``whip'' was first used in the British Parliament and
was derived from the fox hunt, where a person called the whipper-in
kept hounds in a pack.
</P>
<P>
   The majority whip is the third-ranking member of the House
leadership, responsible for knowing the whereabouts of party
members, knowing how they will vote on specific issues and lobbying
them to support the party position. Through weekly floor notices,
the whip keeps party members up to date on the floor schedule and
when to expect important votes.
</P>
<P>
   The party in a minority in the House also elects a whip.
</P>
</TEXT>
