<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nemechek back on pole
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLADEGA, Ala. _ Joe Nemechek is called ``Front Row Joe'' by
his fellow drivers for his propensity to win pole positions.
</P>
<P>
   Nemechek lived up to his billing during first-round qualifying
at Talladega Superspeedway on Friday, motoring along at 198.331 mph
to capture the No. 1 start for Sunday's Winston 500.
</P>
<P>
   The Chevy No. 42 driver has won the pole this season at the
circuit's shortest track (Martinsville) and longest (Talladega).
Nemechek, who posted his first career victory at New Hampshire last
month, won his third pole this year Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've worked really hard on our speedway program the last two
years,'' Nemechek said. ``Qualifying is really, really tough.
You've got to have a good diving race car, lots of power, and then
the driver has got to do his job.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Rudd is also on the front row thanks to his future
employer, Robert Yates Racing. Andy Petree teammates fill the next
row with Kenny Wallace third and Ken Schrader fourth.
</P>
<P>
   By starting second, Rudd put himself in prime position to extend
his streak of winning at least one race per year for the past 16
seasons. The Ford No. 10 driver had assistance for qualifying when
he was offered the use of a trademark Yates motor.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd is leaving his team after this season to operate the No. 28
car owned by Yates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to say but `Thank you,''' Rudd said. ``Not
only did (the engine) qualify good, but I think I can talk (Yates)
into letting me use this thing in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got something to race with. This thing is bad
fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Engines were a major problem Friday for Richard Childress
Racing. Both of the team's drivers, Dale Earnhardt and Mike
Skinner, had engine malfunctions during the qualifying lap.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner's motor stopped before he could take the green flag and
he posted no speed. Earnhardt shut down his car after the first
lap, which was 39th.
</P>
<P>
   ``We blew up,'' Skinner said. ``We haven't had a lot of problems
with qualifying motors all year. The guys back at the shop have
done a great job. I hate that it happened, but that's OK. We've got
another one and we'll try it again (today).'' Other drivers failing
to make the field in the first round were Darrell Waltrip, Bill
Elliott, Kyle Petty and John Andretti.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
