u s BC-FBN-WARNER16-COX     10-15 1400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-WARNER16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rams' Warner springs from anonymity
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kurt Warner's college coach didn't see it. Neither did
Mike Holmgren, who cut Warner a few weeks into his first NFL
training camp with the Green Bay Packers.
</P>
<P>
   It took awhile for St. Louis coach Dick Vermeil to realize
Warner's potential, too. Not until Rams starter Trent Green
suffered a season-ending knee injury in the preseason did Warner
get the opportunity to prove he could play quarterback in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Sunday's game against the Falcons, the Rams are
undefeated, and Warner is the league's hottest quarterback. Warner,
28, has thrown for 14 touchdowns and only three interceptions,
completing 72.6 percent of his pass attempts. His current passer
rating of 136.0 would shatter the NFL record of 112.8, set by San
Francisco's Steve Young in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``His performance is probably not going to continue at (its
current pace),'' Vermeil said. ``That is darn tough. ... (But)
gentlemen, this kid is for real.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner's improbable success is attracting a lot of attention.
He's on the cover of Sports Illustrated this week, with the
headline ``Who Is This Guy?'' David Letterman wanted him to fly to
New York on Monday or Tuesday for a taping; Warner turned it down
because his second wedding anniversary was Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, who is open about his religious beliefs, was invited to
a crusade by the Rev. Billy Graham. Representatives of evangelist
Pat Robertson called seeking a five-minute interview. Warner Bros.
Studio in Hollywood is developing a promotional cartoon of the
quarterback and the Warner Bros. _ the nickname of St. Louis'
talented receiving corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get to know the young man, you see that he is a very
humble, sincere human being,'' Vermeil said. ``He is not awed by
all this. He is excited, but he hasn't changed a bit in his
demeanor.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner's career has been a humbling odyssey. From Regis High
School in Cedar Rapids, Iowa, to Division I-AA Northern Iowa to the
Arena Football League and NFL Europe, he has demonstrated a knack
for drama. And he carries undaunted confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had that swagger all his life,'' said Kansas coach Terry
Allen, who coached Warner for five seasons at Northern Iowa. ``When
he steps out there, he knows he can do it. He's confident.''
</P>
<P>
   That confidence could be mistaken for arrogance, if not for the
obstacles and tragedies Warner and his family have overcome. Seven
years ago, Warner met his future wife at a country and western
dance in Cedar Falls, Iowa. Brenda Warner told Kurt that she was a
divorced mother of two children, living with her parents, and that
if he didn't want to see her again, she would understand. The
college quarterback showed up at her front door with a rose the
next morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been through a lot of hings,'' Warner says. ``We've had
some good times and some bad times. We realize what's important in
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, his wife's parents were killed when a tornado
demolished their home in Mountain View, Ark. Her parents had moved
there a year earlier when her father retired.
</P>
<P>
   Warner adopted his wife's children, including 10-year-old
Zachary, who is legally blind and has brain damage from an accident
he suffered at 4 months old. Brenda's first husband was taking him
out of a bath when the baby slipped out of his hands and hit the
back of his head on the tub. Doctors told Brenda her son would die,
but he lived.
</P>
<P>
   Zachary can see things when they are close to his face. He
attends his father's football games but watches the action on a
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to struggle with everything he does,'' Warner said.
``Nothing comes easy for him. In the position I'm in now, (I'm not
going to) allow things to give me a big head and I'm not going to
get too upset when things don't go well. It seems pretty minute to
me that I would get upset about things that happen on the football
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize that there are more important things. (Zachary) just
keeps my head level. I'm going to do everything I can to be
successful in football, but I'm not going to let it dictate the
kind of person that I am.''
</P>
<P>
   If Warner did, he might have given up on his dream of playing in
the NFL. He didn't start at Northern Iowa until he was a fifth-year
senior, spending four years behind Jay Johnson, who's now the
quarterbacks coach under Allen at Kansas. Warner lost his first two
games as a starter, separated his shoulder in the second, but led
Northern Iowa to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played behind a quarterback that we were having an awful
lot of success with,'' Allen said. ``It's not that Kurt didn't have
the talent. Kurt always had the arm strength, there's no question
about that. He's always had a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner was not drafted out of college, but landed a tryout with
the Packers in 1994. He spent only a short time with Green Bay,
however. Brett Favre, Mark Brunell and Ty Detmer were already on
the roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't get a whole lot of snaps and probably didn't get
much of a chance with us,'' said Holmgren, who left Green Bay for
Seattle before this season. ``We looked at him more like our fourth
camp quarterback. I really hadn't heard much about him since then,
except I saw an Arena League game. I can't take credit for Kurt
Warner.''
</P>
<P>
   After he was cut by the Packers, Warner tried to catch on with a
team in NFL Europe but nobody would sign him. He went back to Iowa
and worked nights at a grocery store. He played for the Arena
League's Iowa Barnstormers and became a smashing success, throwing
for 183 touchdowns in three years, including 79 in his final
season. Twice, he took the Barnstormers to the Arena Bowl, the
league's equivalent of the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Dick McDonald, director of media relations for the Barnstormers,
said the team has received dozens of requests for replicas of
Warner's No. 13 jersey. HBO's ``Inside the NFL'' and other national
media have flocked to Des Moines, Iowa, to trace Warner's roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't pay for this,'' McDonald said. ``This publicity is too
expensive for us to buy. Our team and our league can't pay Kurt
enough for doing this well.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the '98 NFL Europe season, Amsterdam Admirals coach Al
Lugenbill contacted the Rams, asking them to give Warner a tryout.
Warner didn't think the audition went well, so he and his wife went
to Jamaica for their honeymoon. During the trip, Warner was bit by
a scorpion or centipede on his elbow. He couldn't throw for nearly
a month and missed a scheduled tryout with the Chicago Bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times when I didn't know what the Lord's plan for
me was,'' Warner said. ``I didn't know if it was going to take the
step back through the NFL, or if He just wanted me to be in Arena
Football and doing things for him there. I continued to believe
that I could play, and it was the Lord's will that I would be back
in (the NFL).''
</P>
<P>
   To Warner's surprise, the Rams had been impressed by his
workout. After playing a summer in Amsterdam, where he led the
league in yards, touchdowns, completions and attempts, he made St.
Louis' roster as the third-string quarterback in 1998. Quarterbacks
Tony Banks and Steve Bono left after a disappointing 4-12 record,
and Warner moved into the backup role behind Green, who signed a
$16.5 million contract in February.
</P>
<P>
   Warner makes the league minimum of $254,000 and is signed only
through this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven years ago, I was on food stamps,'' Brenda Warner says.
``We didn't have enough money to go get Happy Meals. So we're
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner became the starter when Green was injured on a
controversial hit by San Diego Chargers safety Rodney Harrison.
Through the first four games of his NFL career, he still feels like
he's throwing in the Arena League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have that same mentality, that we can go out and be
successful against anyone we play,'' he said. ``You develop that in
the Arena League because you score all the time. I'm not going to
change my mindset just because I'm in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the guys that we've got and the way we're playing on
offense, I don't think anyone can stop us. If we play like we're
capable of playing and I make good decisions, I feel like we can
score every time I touch the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 2128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
