u s BC-HKN-THRASHERS16-COX     10-15 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lambert providing spark
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ On his fourth NHL team in five years, Denny
Lambert hopes he's finally found a home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've bought a house (in Duluth), and my wife is expecting
twins, our first kids,'' the Atlanta Thrashers left wing said. ``I
hope we don't have to move again.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is permanent in the NHL, but Lambert is supplying just
what the Thrashers hoped when general manager Don Waddell obtained
him from Nashville, Tenn., for Randy Robitaille a couple of weeks
before training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denny's an agitator, one of those guys who is miserable to
play against,'' coach Curt Fraser said. ``He's tough and also
capable of scoring home goals. Denny's playing just like we knew he
could.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambert will be hitting anything that moves and hustling again
tonight, as the Thrashers face Tampa Bay in the second of a
three-game trip. Atlanta, which beat the Islanders 2-0 Thursday for
its first victory, plays at the New York Rangers on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Never a top scoring threat, the 5-foot-10 Lambert's NHL high is
nine goals for Ottawa two seasons ago. But he got the Thrashers'
offense on track with an early goal against Dominik Hasek in a 5-5
tie with Buffalo last Saturday and has played well on a line with
Swedes Per Svartvadet and Johan Garpenlov.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always hard to come to a new team and have to learn
another system,'' Lambert said. ``With a first-year team, everybody
is new. It takes a while for everyone to get comfortable in their
roles.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has come easy for Lambert, who is half Ojibway Indian
and grew up near the reserve in Wawa, Ontario. After going
undrafted, he was signed by Buffalo in 1991 and sent on loan to San
Diego of the IHL, where Waddell was general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Lambert played nearly four full seasons with the Gulls, and
Waddell knew exactly what kind of hard-nosed player he was getting
when he traded the potentially high-scoring Robitaille _ the most
valuable player in the AHL last season.
</P>
<P>
   The deal drew some surprised looks around the NHL, but Waddell
thought his team was overstocked with smallish centers and needed
another feisty player like Lambert, who had just lost his
arbitration case with Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't that surprised to be traded, and I was happy it was
to Atlanta,'' said Lambert, who was awarded $465,000 instead of the
$700,000 he was asking.
</P>
<P>
   Lambert had five goals and 11 assists with the expansion
Predators. The statistic that sticks out is penalty minutes;
Lambert had 218. In his two seasons at Ottawa, he had 217 and 250.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy in Atlanta, but I still want to show Nashville they
made a mistake,'' said Lambert, who broke into the NHL with Anaheim
in 1994. ``Every player wants to beat his old team. I wish we
played them more than twice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Denny has made himself into a NHL player,'' Fraser said.
``He's a great guy to have on a team.''
</P>
<P>
   DENNY LAMBERT FILE
</P>
<P>
   Position: Left wing.
</P>
<P>
   Age: 29.
</P>
<P>
   Birthplace: Wawa, Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   Heritage: Mother is Ojibway and father French Canadian.
</P>
<P>
   Family: Wife, Rhonda, is expecting twins, their first children.
</P>
<P>
   Career: In his sixth NHL season. Played with Anaheim, Ottawa and
Nashville. Went into the season with 19 goals, 48 assists and 744
penalty minutes in 274 games. Had five goals, 11 assists and 218
penalty minutes last season with Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
