<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8616 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-HAIRCARE-FRAUD-2NDTAK     10-15 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAIRCARE-FRAUD-2NDTAKE-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: Paul Mitchell.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Goodman suggested that Paul Mitchell was simply seeking to
improve its sales and didn't care where the products went. He noted
that none of the products in question are in his clients'
possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps this was another way of augmenting the distribution of
the company,'' he said, ``to send these products to other parts of
the world.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DeJoria led a delegation of Paul Mitchell executives and hair
stylists to China in late 1997. They held news conferences, gave
interviews to newspapers and organized training sessions for salon
owners in Shanghai and Beijing. ``Our trip was delayed three
times'' at the Axelrods' request, DeJoria said. ``I had to talk
them into letting us go over and give them support.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior Paul Mitchell stylist, Bill Peplow, went to Shanghai
late last year, also to see how things were going. ``His trip was
delayed several times, too,'' DeJoria said. According to the
lawsuit, ``Mr. Peplow's visit posed tremendous risk to the
defendants that their fraud would be discovered.''
</P>
<P>
   Memos attached to the complaint and attributed to China
Distribution include one that ordered the defendants' China
employees to ``stay with him at all times _ we do not want him to
go off on his own even if it is for sightseeing.'' The lawsuit said
Seibel, the China Distribution lawyer, sent that memo on Aug. 28,
1998, to Randy Zhou, an employee in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman said he had not seen all the memos and had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Both DeJoria's group and Peplow were stalled not only in getting
to China, but also once they arrived, the lawsuit said. It contends
that the employees of China Distribution had to scramble from salon
to salon to conceal the dearth of Paul Mitchell products in actual
use in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to a couple of salons that had Paul Mitchell products
there,'' DeJoria recalled. ``But there were many delays. They kept
saying our schedule is too tight. They showed us some salons in
Shanghai. But when I asked to see more, they said our schedule is
too tight, or the other salons are outside the city and in the
provinces.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit says that as Paul Mitchell executives left one
salon, the same products they had seen in that salon were being
hastily forwarded to the next destination, to make it appear as if
Paul Mitchell shampoos were readily available all over Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Zhou arranged to take Peplow on a slow route from salon to
salon while the Paul Mitchell products in the salon just inspected
would be rushed to the next salon to be inspected,'' the lawsuit
says. ``The ruse was successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman scoffed at the story. ``It's all hearsay,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when a Paul Mitchell employee was shopping at a
drugstore in the Midwest, he spotted some of the company's products
and bought them, DeJoria said. The numbered codes on the bottles
indicated that they had been part of a shipment to China.
</P>
<P>
   DeJoria said he confronted Axelrod with the discovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Maybe someone went into China, bought two bottles
and brought them back to sell here,''' DeJoria recalled. ``He said,
`There's nothing that left China.'''
</P>
<P>
   DeJoria said China Distribution's lawyer, Seibel, also assured
him that everything was fine. ``Don't worry about it,'' DeJoria
said Seibel told him. ``It's all in China.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DeJoria said there were many such sightings of Paul Mitchell
products across the country.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not so unusual, Goodman countered, adding that he did
not think the brand in general was as closely protected as the
company liked to depict it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can find them in any drug chain,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The China operation began to unravel this year in Shanghai's
sticky summer heat. Randy Zhou, who led Peplow on the salon tour
and was China Distribution's chief liaison in Shanghai, had become
bored on the job, DeJoria said. After all, the lawsuit contends, he
had very little to distribute.
</P>
<P>
   And he saved many of the memos he received from his bosses,
including a final one, written by Seibel on June 16, 1999, the
lawsuit says, that instructed him to cover his tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lastly, please destroy this memo along with all the others
after you have read,'' it said, according to the lawsuit. ``No
paper trails!!''
</P>
<P>
   Zhou appears to have ignored the request. He described the
situation to Ms. Wang, the Paul Mitchell executive, in July,
according to an affidavit filed by Ms. Wang.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman, however, said he thought Zhou might have had some other
motivation. ``He was bored?'' Goodman asked, sarcastically. ``He
had nothing to do but turn over his employer's documents? If that's
what boredom is, I would watch everybody who doesn't have anything
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   As for whether the documents would be key evidence in the case,
Goodman said he had not yet had the time to assess their relevance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quantity,'' he said, ``is not necessarily evidence of
quality.''
</P>
<P>
   The case will be taken up in a jury trial in United States
District Court in New York City early next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
