<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON POINTS TO DIFFERENCES WITH GIULIANI ON TEST BAN
TREATY 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY     
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton condemned Senate Republicans on Friday
for rejecting a treaty that would have barred all underground
nuclear testing, saying Republicans had ``played partisan politics
at the expense of our national security'' and drawing a clear
distinction on the issue with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, her likely
opponent in next year's race for U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This vote sent a dangerous message to people around the world,
to our allies, and to Americans at home,'' Mrs. Clinton said, using
language that closely tracked what President Clinton said in
denouncing the Senate's 51-49 vote not to approve the Comprehensive
Test Ban Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York has a long and proud tradition of senators from both
parties realizing that our fight against nuclear proliferation,
nuclear testing, nuclear weaponry and an attempt to have a
comprehensive test ban treaty is not a partisan issue,'' Mrs.
Clinton declared. She added, ``New York's next senator must not
turn away from the world by saying no to a treaty that is so
critical to our future.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton detailed her position first in a statement issued
by her Exploratory Committee, and later in a speech to about 100
people, including a number of clergy leaders, in the basement of
the Antioch Baptist Church in Hempstead, N.Y. With her remarks, the
first lady becomes the latest prospective Democratic candidate to
seized on the vote as a potential issue in the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he would have voted to defeat the treaty,
although, in an interview on CNN last Saturday, before the vote,
the mayor said he would prefer to see the vote delayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I would vote no if it were brought to a vote, but
what I prefer to see is that it be put off and the administration
have to answer for the fact that we now have nuclear weapons in
Pakistan, in India,'' Giuliani said. ``Nuclear weapons under
Clinton have expanded dramatically in China and nothing's been done
about it. And this treaty would not address any of that.''
</P>
<P>
   At City Hall on Thursday, Giuliani described the results as
``one of the big defeats of the Clinton administration.'' He blamed
the outcome on Senate Democrats who pressed Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott for a vote on the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``In essence, the Clinton administration and the Senate
Democrats required a vote and they required a vote now,'' Giuliani
said. ``I think, as all the newspapers said, they made a very big
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said she had discussed the issue repeatedly with
her husband over the past few days, and that both viewed the
outcome of the vote with alarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had many conversations with my husband in the last days
because, as he said yesterday in his press conference, the world
will not be safer because the Republicans in the Senate voted
against that treaty,'' Mrs. Clinton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
