</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sore wrist could keep Stanley out of Red Sox lineup
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Mike Stanley, Boston's best hitter against New York
this season, will be held from the lineup today if his right wrist
does not show significant improvement by game time.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley was hit by a Jeff Nelson fastball in the eighth inning
of Game 2 Thursday night and while precautionary X-rays were
negative, the wrist was placed in a protective splint. The Red Sox
didn't work out Friday, meaning Stanley won't get a reading on his
status until batting practice today.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got whacked pretty good,'' Boston manager Jimy Williams
said. ``I just talked to him and he says he is better. I said,
`Better than what?'... He's a tough kid. You know he is. But that
ball got him flush.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley, who made 100 starts at first base for the Sox, was just
1-for-6 in the two games in New York but hit a team-high .476
against the Yankees this season, with three homers and eight RBIs
in seven games. With the injury to his throwing hand, it is
doubtful he could play first but could be the designated hitter
while Brian Daubach takes first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say it's the same exact spot where Nomar (Garciaparra)
got hit (by a pitch in the Division Series with Cleveland),''
Stanley said.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE'S JORGE
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect to see much of Yankees catcher Jorge Posada this
weekend. Joe Girardi will work Games 3 and 4 while Posada, who
started 98 games this season, will be reserved for handling Orlando
Hernandez if there is a Game 5 Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Posada was charged with 17 passed balls this season while
throwing out just 21 percent (20-for-95) of attempted steals.
Although Girardi played just one game against Boston in 1999, his
glove, game-calling skills and playoff experience are favored by
the Yankees staff. NUMB NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   Sign of the times: Yankees pitchers have begun taking batting
practice; Red Sox pitchers have not.
</P>
<P>
   Smugly or not, New York senses it's heading for a third World
Series in four years. But despite leading the series two games to
none, New York has led in just four of the 19 innings and has been
outhit .278 to .258. The difference has been runners left on base.
Boston has stranded 19 runners, 11 of those in scoring position.
The club is batting just .182 (4-for-22) in RBI situations. ETC.
</P>
<P>
   After Williams let Ramon Martinez throw 120 pitches in Game 2,
former Sox pitcher Dennis Eckersley, now a local broadcaster, said,
``The bullpen is supposed to be a team strength but this is beyond
me.'' ... Dom DiMaggio will throw out today's first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
