<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clemens ready to take on fans, duel Martinez
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They lined up like kids waiting to see the principal,
the New York Yankees starting rotation hanging outside Joe Torre's
office while inside, Roger Clemens mulled what would surely be one
of the grandest moments of his baseball life.
</P>
<P>
   Or one of the most harrowing.
</P>
<P>
   Torre was determining his assignments for the American League
Championship Series and as Clemens recalled it, ``He was hemming
and hawing back and forth. I told him, `Skip, whatever slot you
want me in, you put me in. Doesn't make any difference.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So he said, `All right, you got Saturday against Pedro.' I
said, `Beautiful,' got up and left. He was shaking his head at me
as I walked out the door. The rest of the guys are standing
outside, waiting, and I said, `I already got the long straw. You
guys are good, go on in there. You guys got nothing to lose.'''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does baseball today, when New York's Clemens pitches against
Boston's Pedro Martinez in Game 3 at Fenway Park. Somehow, the
defending world champions, winners of 12 consecutive postseason
games, ahead 2-0 in the series, are instant underdogs. Clemens,
adopted favorite son of New England for his 13 long seasons as a
Red Sox, returns a villain in pinstripes.
</P>
<P>
   This is rich.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Boston manager Jimy Williams poetically put it, ``I think
the circuit breakers for that electric company for the great pad in
the sky, they might be challenged.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes. New England always admired Clemens but it never loved him
as it has come to love Martinez, whose infectious personality
helped elevate a club that first assembled last February without
much hope. That, more than anything, will explain the harsh fan
treatment Clemens will receive today. Fenway was boorish to him
during the All-Star Game. This will be far worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely understand,'' said Red Sox infielder Lou Merloni,
who grew up in nearby Framingham, Mass., the same town Clemens
lived in while with Boston. ``I can understand the way it is around
here. Players leave, they come back and they get booed.''
</P>
<P>
   If emotion is meaningful to the Red Sox, it has often been an
obstruction for Clemens, who has faltered in past big games because
he admits adrenaline gets the better of him. He was able to handle
a Division Series start in his home state of Texas last weekend but
unlike Arlington, Boston awaits this game with a raw nerve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am just going to go out there and pitch the game, and I'm
sure he is going to do that,'' said Martinez, this season's
winningest pitcher at 23-4. ``I hope he puts a lot of pressure on
himself and I hope he gives it up soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Down two games, Martinez can quickly change the ALCS. By
winning, he'd give the Sox a chance to even the series Sunday
against the Yankees' Andy Pettitte, a left-hander who must work
with one eye on the left-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro in big games?'' Boston general manager Dan Duquette
asked. ``In Pedro's very first game as a Red Sox last year at
Fenway, he struck out 15. When Mo Vaughn returned this year to
Fenway with Anaheim, Pedro struck out 15. When the Atlanta Braves
came to town this year, he struck out 16. And, oh, that's right, he
had 17 against the Yankees (in New York) when we swept them in
September. Allowed only one hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just no-hit Cleveland for six innings the other day.''
</P>
<P>
   One man in 25 cannot win a series, but Martinez alone can steer
this one in another direction, especially with all New England
pushing along from behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happens with Roger and the fans out there, it is his
business,'' Martinez said. ``Let him deal with it. I don't have
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens was seated next to Torre in New York on Wednesday night
as the Red Sox were introduced for Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they introduced Pedro, they booed him a little bit,''
Torre said. ``I said to Roger, `You will do better than that.'''
</P>
<P>
   He will. Boston promises.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
