<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-VANDY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bulldogs taking Vandy seriously
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Psychological preparation has been as much a
priority as offensive and defensive game plans as Georgia and
Vanderbilt get set to play today at Vanderbilt Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The 14th-ranked Bulldogs (4-1, 2-1 SEC) are coming off an
embarrassing 37-20 loss to Tennessee last Saturday in Knoxville and
coach Jim Donnan is concerned about how his young team will respond
to such a dominating defeat in the face of great expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really concerned because we put so much into that game
and got beaten so thoroughly,'' Donnan said. ``You worry about
young players who have a tendency to get depressed. But we've come
back with a very good attitude and worked hard in practice. I feel
good now about where our team is mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Vanderbilt coach Woody Widenhofer is trying a
different approach this week for getting his team ready to play
against a Top 25 opponent. He hyped their game against 12th-ranked
Mississippi State two weeks ago as ``the biggest around here in a
long time'' and the Commodores (4-2, 1-2) came out on the short end
of a 42-14 final score.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we approached the Mississippi State game didn't
work,'' Widenhofer said. ``I put a lot of pressure on our players
and staff, and we fell flat on our face. Now we're playing another
very meaningful game, but we're going to approach it as just
another game. I think our players are better when they're loose and
free-spirited. Our approach to Georgia will be to hang loose.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs will need to be at their best against Vanderbilt,
which is fielding what many believe to be its best team of the
1990s. The Commodores have not won more than five games since 1994
and haven't had a winning record since 1982, and their fans are
anticipating both numbers falling this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big game, a chance for us to make some noise in the
SEC,'' Vanderbilt receiver Tavarus Hogans said. ``We need to play
loose and just have some fun. This is what you play big-time
football for.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs have dominated the 106-year-old series, winning 22
of the past 25 games for a 40-17-2 edge. But Vanderbilt has sneaked
up on them at the most inopportune times, such as its 43-30
homecoming upset in 1994, its 27-25 victory in Nashville in 1991
and a 13-13 tie in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's players promise they're not taking Vanderbilt lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're 4-2; it's not like they're 0-6 or something,'' tight
end Randy McMichael said. ``We know we've got to go up there and be
ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The lopsided loss to Tennessee aside, Georgia's preseason goals
remain. The Bulldogs, Vols, Florida and Kentucky, next week's
opponent, all have one conference loss. Any team that can make it
the rest of the way unscathed likely will represent the Eastern
Division in the SEC Championship Game at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tennessee game's not going to make or break our season,''
Georgia quarterback Quincy Carter said. ``We've got six more pretty
good teams to play, and Vanderbilt's the first of them. They're
real scrappy, play hard and they've got some talent. We know that,
but we'll be ready for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
