<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Team healthier but not Tuggle
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Falcons enter Sunday's game against the Rams
healthier than they have been in awhile.
</P>
<P>
   But middle linebacker Jessie Tuggle doesn't want to hear about
it. Tuggle will miss his second game in 12 seasons, spanning 182
games.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Chandler, who missed three of the past four games with a
strained right hamstring, will start at quarterback, and all four
starting defensive linemen are better off than they have been in
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuggle (strained left patella tendon) and weak-side
linebacker Keith Brooking (partially torn right medial collateral
knee ligament) are out.
</P>
<P>
   Brooking's streak of playing in regular-season games ends at 16;
Tuggle's ends at 115.
</P>
<P>
   As an undrafted rookie in 1987, Tuggle played in 12 of 15 games;
one game was canceled by a strike. Then he played in 65 consecutive
before missing one in '92 because of viral meningitis.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be smart about it,'' the 13-year veteran said.
``Although I want to go, you don't want to risk going out there and
getting hurt again, and then it's too late to activate another
player. And it could bother me all year if I don't let it heal.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to the Falcons' record and fact book, Tuggle did not
enter this season with 105 starts in a row; he missed one in '97
when the defense began in the nickel.
</P>
<P>
   That means former center Jeff Van Note's consecutive starts
record of 112 in 1970-84, is safe, at least until the last game.
Left tackle Bob Whitfield has started 101 consecutive games and
could tie the mark by the end of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Van Note holds the record for consecutive games played, 155,
ahead of Tuggle (115), Ken Reaves (112) and Whitfield and Buddy
Curry (107 each).
</P>
<P>
   ROSTER RUMBLINGS
</P>
<P>
   With Tuggle and Brooking out, the Falcons will have two
linebackers at each position: Ruffin Hamilton and rookie Lamont
Green on the weak side, Henri Crockett and Jeff Kelly in the middle
and Craig Sauer and Whit Marshall on the strong side.
</P>
<P>
   Other than Tuggle and Brooking, the early inactives are reserve
safety Johndale Carty (strained left hamstring) and rookie fullback
Jeff Paulk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably will hold (reserve defensive tackle Ed) Jasper out
another week,'' coach Dan Reeves said, ``and we'll have to make a
(game-day) decision on (wide receiver) Jammi German.''
</P>
<P>
   Jasper missed the past two games with a partially torn medial
collateral left knee ligament. German broke the little finger on
his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   For the Rams, left guard Tom Nutten (back) will be replaced by
Andy McCollum (6 feet 4, 295 pounds), a former Saints player.
</P>
<P>
   THE GAME PLAN
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons will try to play keep-away, even though they have
had the advantage in possession time in just one of its five games.
</P>
<P>
   To do it, they will need a play ratio more like the 33-20
run-pass balance they had last week against the Saints. In the
first four games, the run-pass ratio was 95-146.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Green, activated from the practice squad Wednesday,
will play a lot on special teams. ... With Carty out, reserve free
safety Omar Brown, who had the cast taken off his broken right
thumb, will be active for the first time in several weeks. ... If
German can't go, Tim Dwight becomes the primary No. 3 receiver,
although Terance Mathis remains most likely to work out of the
slot.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
