u a BC-N.Y.-TERRORIST-SENTEN     10-15 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-TERRORIST-SENTENCE-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMORSEFUL TERROR PLOTTER RECEIVES 11-YEAR SENTENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A convicted terrorist who cooperated with the
government's investigation of the plot to blow up the United
Nations and other landmarks in New York was sentenced to 11 years
in prison Friday after he made a tearful apology and strongly
denounced terrorism, saying it was ``evil and ungodly.''
</P>
<P>
   The defendant, Siddig Ibrahim Siddig Ali, had admitted to a
major role in the plot in which 10 people, including Sheik Omar
Abdel Rahman, were ultimately convicted in a trial in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Siddig Ali, who pleaded guilty shortly after the trial began,
announced at the time that he would cooperate, and admitted helping
select some of the plotters' targets, which also included the
Lincoln and Holland Tunnels, the George Washington Bridge and the
Federal Building in lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to reiterate that I renounce violence,'' Siddig
Ali said Friday in U.S. District Court in Manhattan, ``and condemn
those who fraudulently preserve the sacredness of Islam to
perpetrate their unholy war against the innocent and the
unsuspecting.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he wanted to apologize to the people of New York, the
American people, and to the Muslim community in the United States
and around the world, adding, ``I know now more than ever that only
through peaceful dialogue can we resolve our differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Siddig Ali faced a term of life plus 30 years for his plea to
seditious conspiracy and other charges. But Judge Michael B.
Mukasey was able to avoid the strict federal sentencing guidelines
after he got a letter from prosecutors in the office of the U.S.
attorney, Mary Jo White, describing Siddig Ali's extensive
assistance in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The details of that assistance are not known, because Siddig Ali
never testified at trial, and the government's letter was not made
public. But from his statements at the time of his plea, it seems
likely that he supplied the government with intimate details of the
conspiracy, which also included an assassination plot against the
Egyptian president, Hosni Mubarak, on an official trip to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The cooperation may have also gone beyond the bombing case to
include information about the Sudanese Mission in New York. For
example, a document introduced at trial quoted Siddig Ali, a
Sudanese immigrant, as telling an informant in 1993 that he had
friends in the mission who could provide him with diplomatic
plates. That would help him to get a car packed with explosives
into the U.N. garage.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, that information may have helped the government
expel a Sudanese diplomat accused of helping a terrorist, and to
bolster its case that Sudan was involved in supporting terrorism
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The only hint in court Friday about Siddig Ali's cooperation
came when Mukasey described him as having ``provided substantial
cooperation, most of which, in my own view, most of the valuable
material was in essence intelligence material, and his willingness
to provide it in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no further elaboration. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In court Friday, Siddig Ali's lawyer, Howard R. Leader, asked
the judge to sentence his client to time served, in this case, six
and a half years. Leader cited the cooperation and his client's
``genuine sense of remorse.''
</P>
<P>
   Mukasey refused, saying such a sentence would have ``trivialized
what happened here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Had your actions gone uninterrupted,'' he said, ``hundreds,
perhaps thousands of people would have died.''
</P>
<P>
   But the judge said that Siddig Ali's guilty plea and cooperation
had assisted both in the prosecution of the case and possibly to
``prevent further cases.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge said that 11 years was, in his view, a term that
``balances the enormity of what you did and intended to do against
the substantial cooperation you provided.''
</P>
<P>
   The sentence means that Siddig Ali is likely to serve roughly
four and a half more years, depending on time credited for good
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Leader said later that Siddig Ali's sentence showed that even
for terrorists, ``if they are genuinely remorseful, that their
actions can have a dramatic impact on how they would be spending
the rest of their lives'' because of the tremendous value placed
upon their assistance and the risks inherent in deciding to
cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   All defendants convicted in the trial did receive substantial
terms, including a life sentence for Abdel Rahman.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Ms. White had no comment Friday night. In court,
a federal prosecutor, Patrick J. Fitzgerald, told the judge that
the government was seeking a lower term than mandated because of
Siddig Ali's ``substantial assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   In what appeared to be a show of support for Siddig Ali,
Fitzgerald was joined in the courtroom by other senior prosecutors
and agents of the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Siddig Ali, 38, broke down in tears several times as he spoke to
the judge, contending that his actions did not reflect the
``peaceful spirit of Islam'' nor the views of most Muslims around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six and a half years ago, upon my arrest, I stood before you
here a man filled with hatred and contempt,'' Siddig Ali said. ``I
was arrogant, immature and foolish.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I cannot find enough words to express my deep sense
of shame and remorse for what I have done, because what I did was
unjustified and wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
