<HEADER>
A8632 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-MARTINEZ-N     10-15 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-MARTINEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL COLUMN: MARTINEZ HAS SEVERAL GHOSTS TO DEFEAT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The passions of a proud city, the hopes of a plucky team and the
future of a horrible eight-decade-old curse rest on the sloped
shoulders of a 170-pound pitcher with a squeaky voice, a confident
demeanor and a playful personality whenever he is not firing
fastballs. To succeed, this pitcher must beat the best pitcher who
has ever called Fenway Park home.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox and their rowdy fans speak reverentially about Pedro
Martinez, especially in this delicate part of their dwindling
season. We still have Pedro, the players and fans say evenly, so we
still have a chance. Pedro's presence and pitching makes this solid
team a special team and could make this series between the Yankees
and the Red Sox competitive very quickly, they vow.
</P>
<P>
   They are correct, and Game 3 of the American League Championship
Series is even more intriguing than normal because it features
Martinez, who happily came to Boston for $75 million, against Roger
Clemens, who left Boston after a mostly successful yet sometimes
aggravating 12 years and is now a pariah.
</P>
<P>
   To the fans who will crowd Fenway Park, this duel of the century
will be good against evil. Pedro is good; Roger is evil. Pedro is a
hero; Roger is a traitor. Obviously, this comparison deserves more
analysis, but it is not forthcoming in Boston. Pedro will be the
king and he is not worried about how Roger will be treated in the
place where he used to be the only Elvis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happens with Roger and the fans out there, that's his
business,'' said Martinez. ``Let him deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez spoke respectfully about what Clemens has accomplished
in a Hall of Fame career, but he stressed that he did not want to
be compared to the other great Boston pitcher, and did not want to
reveal much about spending two hours at an awards dinner together
during the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was Martinez's way of asserting his game face or not
praising an opposing pitcher 24 hours before the biggest game of
the season, but the chatty pitcher turned ornery when asked what he
and Clemens spoke about at the dinner. He gave a brief response,
mildly scolded the reporter for asking the question in a postseason
setting and then called him ``curious man.'' It was a funny
display, another sign that Martinez was loose and was uninterested
in bowing to Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just wants to be himself,'' said Ramon Martinez, Pedro's
older brother. ``Pedro is Pedro. Clemens is Clemens.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez resembled a college student who had finished
cramming all night for exams with droopy eyes behind black-framed
glasses and a white jacket that might as well have been a
letterman's cardigan. Pedro was cool, quite cool, as he spoke about
pitching in the biggest game of the season and the biggest game for
the Red Sox since 1986. Pick Game 6, Game 7 or both from that
dreary year.
</P>
<P>
   When Martinez was at Yankee Stadium earlier this week, the
pitcher said he planned to ``forget that Babe Ruth was traded'' and
that he did not even know that memorable story. Obviously, Martinez
knows the details, but, to him, the past is irrelevant. Martinez
claimed Boston's 2-0 deficit is irrelevant. Pedro also said the
muscle strain in his upper back is irrelevant, because he had
enough to tame the Indians and he should have enough to stifle the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to change my game because there is more
pressure or less pressure,'' said Pedro Martinez. ``My pressure is
just to get them out.''
</P>
<P>
   But, when there is more pressure, Martinez gets nastier.
Remember how he whiffed five of the six batters he faced in the
All-Star Game? Remember how he struck out 17 Yankees and uncorked
an amazing one-hitter at Yankee Stadium last month? It might have
been the best game ever pitched at the Stadium, and it is a
performance the Yankees will definitely recall at about 4:30
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can do anything anytime,'' said Ramon Martinez. ``It
doesn't matter what kind of pressure there is.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement would have sounded boastful in 99 out of 100 other
settings, but it sounded appropriate for Pedro. He extended the Red
Sox' season by tossing six remarkable innings of no-hit relief
against the Indians in Game 5 of the division series. The Red Sox
were hoping Martinez could go two innings, but he experimented to
see what kind of repertory he had and slowly figured out how to
dominate, as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only he would know if he loves the spotlight,'' said catcher
Jason Varitek. ``But he knows how to handle throwing in the
spotlight.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro seemed relaxed Friday as he ran through the clubhouse,
tickled a reporter he did not know and sprinted to pick up his
ringing cellular phone the way a 5-year-old rushes to greet an ice
cream truck. Martinez was singing about finally going home and was
surely planning to rest up for facing Clemens and the Yankees.
Pedro could and should make this a memorable day at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win tomorrow,'' said John Valentin, a hint of a smile on
his face, ``this thing could get interesting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
