A8638 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-HAMILTON-WARRICK1     10-15 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HAMILTON-WARRICK16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heisman debate getting charged
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart and J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The arrest last week of Florida State wide receiver
Peter Warrick on a felony-theft charge has touched off a debate
about the Heisman Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Should character count when voters make their choice for college
football's best player? If so, do Warrick's problems open the door
for Georgia Tech quarterback Joe Hamilton?
</P>
<P>
   Judging from a sample of voters, the answer in not clear-cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now, it appeared (Warrick) was starting to take control
of the race,'' Steve Weiberg of USA Today said. ``This certainly
changes that. Now, it's a question of when he gets back, how he
plays and how many voters are willing to give him a second
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Warrick will miss his second game in a row when FSU plays
Wake Forest. He pleaded innocent to the theft charge, and his
attorney is attempting to get the charge reduced to a misdemeanor.
If the lawyer succeeds, Warrick could be in uniform Oct. 23 against
Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   Some voters said missing too many games could make the other
issue moot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The so-called character issue won't affect my vote. Missing
games will affect my vote,'' Ivan Maisel of Sports Illustrated
said. ``If a player misses two games out of an 11-game season,
that's a pretty good chunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Voters did agree on this: If Warrick doesn't get back into the
race, Hamilton becomes one of the favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite losing to Florida State, Hamilton played his heart
out, and a lot of people saw that,'' said Steve Richardson of the
Dallas Morning News. ``He is a bona fide candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton says he's less concerned about the Heisman race than
today's game. Eighth-ranked Tech (4-1, 2-1 ACC) plays Duke (1-4,
1-1) in Durham, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to put the Heisman stuff on the back burner,'' he
said. ``We're in the middle of a season where we can really do
something special, and we control our own desitiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton has the nation's top passer-efficiency rating. He has
passed for 1,347 yards and 12 touchdowns and run for 321 yards and
six scores.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he was getting plenty of media attention even
before Warrick's arrest and suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so good, he's in Sports Illustrated all the time,'' Duke
coach Carl Franks said.
</P>
<P>
   If Hamilton continues to play well _ and Tech continues to win _
voters will take note, no matter what happens with Warrick.
</P>
<P>
   Eligible to vote for the Heisman are 921 people _ former
winners, selected media members and administrative people
throughout college football. Many of them say that they think
Warrick needs to be more contrite.
</P>
<P>
   He apologized on national television last week, but days before
he was charged he sounded smug when he said he shouldn't be
suspended: ``It's not like I killed the president,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like Warrick's toast, but he might be a warm bagel,''
said Tom Shatel of the Omaha World-Herald. ``I need to see him eat
a little more humble pie. I need to hear him say he's an idiot, he
made a mistake and he'll never do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Other voters see no way that enough voters, many of whom are
older, conservative men, will cut Warrick any slack.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a Heisman voter, I would have a hard time voting for
Warrick in his current situation,'' said Richardson, the Dallas
writer who also is the executive director of the Football Writers
Association of America. ``If there is some futher development which
could prove him less involved or innocent, then I might
reconsider.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
