<SLUG> BC-STARR-SUCCESSOR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-635&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR IS LEAVING, BUT HIS OFFICE IS SAID TO INTENSIFY INQUIRIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to insert new graf after 5th graf to discuss background on
travel probe)   (bl)  
 By DAVID JOHNSTON and DON VAN NATTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At a time Clinton administration officials had
hoped that the Whitewater independent counsel office would soon
shut down, lawyers involved with the inquiry said Friday that the
office has intensified its investigation into matters that could
still prove difficult for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The surge of activity in recent weeks has been accompanied by a
change in leadership at the independent counsel's office. The
federal judicial panel that supervises independent counsel issues
has appointed Robert Ray, an aggressive racketeering and gang
prosecutor who joined the office five months ago, to succeed
Kenneth Starr, who plans to step down, possibly as soon as next
week, after holding the job for five years and two months.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with Starr, Ray, 39, is relatively obscure in
Washington's political and legal circles. But his appointment
suggested that prosecutors may hope to accomplish more than simply
writing a final report and closing down.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation has recently racheted up, the lawyers said
Friday, as prosecutors have centered renewed attention on trying to
determine whether White House aides played any role in what a
former White House volunteer, Kathleen Willey, has said was an
effort to persuade her to deny that the president made a sexual
advance to her in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the lawyers said prosecutors are continuing to
pursue what they see as their still-open inquiry into the
dismissals of White House travel office employees in the early
months of the Clinton presidency. They are also investigating
whether anyone involved in the matter at the White House misled
investigators about who had ordered the ouster of the employees.
</P>
<P>
   The furor over the travel office erupted in 1993 when Clinton
aides abruptly dimissed all seven employees at the White House
travel operation and replaced them with a group led by Clinton
associates from Arkansas. A White House review found that mid-level
aides were responsible for the firings, although a congressional
investigation later unearthed memorandums that suggested first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton played a central role in the dismissals. She
has said she never urged that the employees be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential aides have long denied any wrongdoing in either the
Willey or the travel office matter.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have seemed particularly active in their inquiry
into Ms. Willey's accusations. Specifically, prosecutors are
examining her accusation that Nathan Landow, a high-profile
Democratic fund-raiser and Maryland real estate developer, tried to
influence her testimony in a deposition she was preparing to give
in Paula Jones' sexual misconduct lawsuit against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors from the independent counsel's office have
subpoenaed several associates of Landow to testify before a federal
grand jury in Alexandria, Va., away from the media glare of the
District of Columbia federal courthouse, said one lawyer with
knowledge of the activity.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, agents from the FBI assigned to the independent
counsel's office have recently subpoenaed Landow's telephone logs
and business records in what appears to be an effort to find a
connection between him and White House aides, the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Landow has repeatedly denied Ms. Willey's accusation; he would
not comment on the matter Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this renewed activity, it remains uncertain what the
prosecutors hope to achieve in their continuing inquiry and whether
they might plan still more indictments. The lawyers said they
suspected that some prosecutors have never abandoned their goal of
somehow implicating senior White House officials in a crime, even
Clinton or his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton. But others said that
there was scant concrete evidence and little legal basis to support
such an effort.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Starr, who is expected to resume his law partnership
in the Washington office of Kirkland &AMP; Ellis, seems to be drifting
out of public view after a tumultuous tenure in which the
independent counsel's office presided over the investigation of
Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky. Starr's inquiry
culminated with Clinton's impeachment by the House of
Representatives in December and the president's trial and acquittal
in the Senate in February.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House on Friday, the residue of bitterness over
Starr's investigation was apparent even as the prosecutor was
stepping aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as Starr goes, I think Americans will be glad that from
now on, he'll be taking his garbage out each morning in private,''
said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   In some instances, independent counsels nearing the end of their
inquiries have turned their cases over to deputies who operated as
legal caretakers with the primary jobs of handling appellate issues
and shutting down the office. But Ray is a courtroom-hardened
veteran of criminal trials, and his credentials do not suggest that
he will be a passive legal administrator.
</P>
<P>
   He was an assistant U.S. attorney in New York, where he helped
prosecute a gang known as the ``142nd Street Lynchmob'' under
federal racketeering statutes. He also helped prosecute a
49-defendant organized crime and narcotics case and supervised
``kingpin'' wiretap investigations of large scale drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   His biography, furnished by the independent counsel's office,
said he had conducted ``multi-defendant prosecutions involving
public corruption, organized crime, violent crime and narcotics
trafficking at all levels and stages of federal courts.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Ray moved to Washington to work as a deputy in Donald
Smaltz's independent counsel investigation into whether former
Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy had accepted improper gifts from
companies with a financial stake in decisions of the Agriculture
Department. Espy was indicted, but after a lengthy and expensive
investigation and trial, he was acquitted of all charges.
</P>
<P>
   But Ray was the lead prosecutor in the case against Archie
Schaffer, a senior employee at Tyson Foods, the huge Arkansas-based
poultry producer. Schaffer was convicted of two counts of providing
illegal gifts to Espy. The trial judge threw out both convictions,
but an appeals court reinstated one of the counts. A sentencing
hearing is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Just five months ago, Starr named Ray the office's ``senior
litigation counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Lockhart questioned whether experience in the Espy and
Schaffer cases qualified a prosecutor to take over as independent
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's somewhat of a dubious proposition that someone involved
both in the Espy investigation and the Starr operation'' is
``getting a promotion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Lockhart said he had no ``particular concern'' about Ray,
but said there was a broader concern ``that we're continuing to
keep going and keep going and people are moving up.'' He added,
``We think they ought to find a way to wrap this up.''
</P>
<P>
   But another prosecutor in the Schaffer trial, Barry Coburn, said
Ray was a professional, apolitical prosecutor who handles complex
cases like the Espy case with aplomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were moments during the course of the investigation that
were extremely stressful,'' he said. ``The level of tension was
unlike anything I have experienced. He handled it with calmness,
poise and tact.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
