<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: HITLER'S BUNKER UNEARTHED
</P>
<P>
   Construction workers near the Brandenburg Gate in Berlin have
found remnants of Hitler's bunker, Berlin city officials said.
Though the site has been known for years, it was sealed off by the
Russian army and the former East German government throughout the
Cold War. City officials now have to decide what they will do, but
said they hope to avoid interrupting the construction of new
government buildings and a street nearby.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PLEA FOR PINOCHET REJECTED
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the first anniversary of the arrest in London of
Gen. Augusto Pinochet, 83, Britain said it could not grant a new
formal request from Chile to release him on grounds of his age and
failing health. A spokeswoman for Home Secretary Jack Straw said he
could not take any action at all until legal proceedings were
finished. A London court ruled last week that the former Chilean
dictator can be extradited to Spain to stand trial on torture
charges.
</P>
<P>
   BELGIUM: MONTENEGRIN VISITS NATO
</P>
<P>
   Milo Djukanovic, the president of Montenegro, increasingly at
odds with Serbia in what is left of the Republic of Yugoslavia, met
NATO's new secretary general, Lord Robertson, in the alliance's
headquarters in Brussels. Montenegro, which was opposed to
President Slobodan Milosevic's attempt last winter to expel the
ethnic Albanian population from Kosovo, got assurances of allied
support for its elected government.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: PROSECUTOR UPHELD
</P>
<P>
   President Boris N. Yeltsin's repeated efforts to dismiss
Prosecutor General Yuri I. Skuratov, who began a corruption
investigation that has led into the Kremlin itself, were set back
again by a Moscow court. It upheld a lower court ruling ordering
that a criminal investigation of Skuratov be brought to a close.
Now that the grounds for his suspension have been removed, Skuratov
said he intends to return to work soon. Parliament's upper house
this week rejected Yeltsin's third bid to fire Skuratov.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: RIOT POLICEMEN HELD
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rosario Robles of Mexico City announced that two riot
police agents were arrested for beating student strikers from the
National Autonomous University during a protest. The clash came
after the police removed students blocking traffic on the most
important highway around the capital. Police Chief Alejandro Gertz
said the police will act again if the students, who have maintained
the strike since April, try to disrupt major roads.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: LEFTIST BREAKS WITH PARTY
</P>
<P>
   Porfirio Munoz Ledo, a veteran opposition leader, has announced
his ``irreversible'' break with the leaders of the Party of the
Democratic Revolution, the major leftist party. Munoz Ledo started
a movement to reform the party, but his faction lost in recent
internal elections to supporters of Cuauhtemoc Cardenas Solorza,
the party's best-known leader.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   BOTSWANA: ELECTION DUE SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   Voters go to the polls here Saturday in presidential elections,
and President Festus Mogae is expected by most political analysts
to lead the ruling Botswana Democratic Party to its eighth election
victory since the country won independence from Britain in 1966. He
took office last year after President Ketumile Masire stepped down.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANISTAN: TALIBAN SANCTIONS
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Security Council voted to impose sanctions on the
Islamic Taliban movement, which controls most of Afghanistan, in 30
days unless it turns over Osama bin Laden, the Saudi-born militant
wanted in the United States for bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya
and Tanzania last year. The sanctions, proposed by the United
States, will freeze Taliban assets abroad and curtail international
flights of Afghan planes except for relief flights and the annual
Haj pilgrimages to Mecca.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: SECOND SUICIDE
</P>
<P>
   A second suicide has occurred among suspects in a Tehran jail in
connection with a series of political murders, the Tehran newspaper
Azad said. He was named as Akbar Khosh-Kush, one of 27 people
arrested after the Intelligence Ministry admitted that a ``rogue''
group within its ranks had killed five people last year. In June,
officials said, the accused mastermind of the slayings, Said Emami,
killed himself by drinking poison.
</P>
</TEXT>
