<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0351 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8657 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-GAF-ASBESTOS-$ADV17-A     10-15 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAF-ASBESTOS-$ADV17-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW A COMPANY LETS ITS CASH TALK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.Y., Mich., Conn.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic of
influencing the progressd of a bill on Capitol Hill is being sent
to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17) 
(af) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``It was a good day,'' Ronnie Heyman was overheard
telling a friend on Oct. 5, at the end of a Senate subcommittee
hearing on legislation championed by her husband, Samuel J. Heyman,
the chairman of the GAF Corp.
</P>
<P>
   And so it was. Embraced warmly by the subcommittee, the bill and
a similar one moving rapidly through the House of Representatives
would limit sharply the crushing legal liability of former asbestos
producers like GAF, which have been locked in a decades-long battle
with hundreds of thousands of people who say they have been made
ill by exposure to asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   With powerful opponents like labor unions and the Association of
Trial Lawyers, the GAF legislation was considered a dead letter at
the beginning of the year. Now it is gaining stunning momentum, all
because of a remarkable multimillion-dollar lobbying effort
engineered by the Heymans.
</P>
<P>
   For the Heymans, the benefits of limiting GAF's liability to the
most serious cases of asbestos poisoning are clear. Heyman owns
most of GAF; his investment in the company constitutes the bulk of
the family's estimated $1 billion in wealth.
</P>
<P>
   For other supporters, the legislation would limit runaway
liability and speed money to victims.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the bills would shrink many settlements and cut
many victims out of the process.
</P>
<P>
   With stakes this high, the Heymans are proceeding with the same
determination they used as dissident shareholders nearly 17 years
ago, when they won a bitter proxy fight and wrested control of GAF
from its old management.
</P>
<P>
   The Heymans and GAF have retained a battery of lobbyists,
including a former United States senator, Dennis DeConcini, and the
son of Sen.r Orrin G. Hatch, a co-sponsor of the GAF measure. They
have used the same advertising firm that created the famous ``Harry
and Louise'' ads that helped crush President Clinton's health care
package five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And they have given generously to scores of lawmakers, most
notably to a handful of Democrats like Sens. Charles E. Schumer of
New York and Robert G. Toricelli of New Jersey who have
longstanding alliances to unions and the trial lawyers but who have
begun to come around to GAF's position.
</P>
<P>
   GAF has also hired two law professors as consultants. One,
Christopher Edley Jr., a professor at Harvard Law School and a
former top aide to President Clinton, wrote the legislation for
Congress. He is being paid by the Coalition for Asbestos
Resolution, an ad hoc group of businesses organized and financed
largely by GAF.
</P>
<P>
   The other, who testified on behalf of the measures, is Paul R.
Vurkeil, the dean of the Benjamin N. Cardozo School of Law at
Yeshiva University in Manhattan, which named a research center on
corporate governance after the Heymans when they donated $1 million
to the school.
</P>
<P>
   The trial lawyers and the unions, traditionally among the most
powerful interest groups in Washington, have been caught
flat-footed, largely distracted by other legislative matters. They
have salted Congress with significantly more money in campaign
contributions than GAF has, but they have many more causes to
advocate. And while they have apparently used only one outside
lobbying firm, GAF has outgunned them with at least six.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some sense, it's an advantage to be an outsider because you
come with no preconceived notions of what can and cannot be
achieved within the system,'' Heyman said in an interview last
week. ``We've run a focused legislative campaign, emphasizing the
merits of the legislation, and we have a high conviction that we're
right.''
</P>
<P>
   That determination has already led to much bipartisan support,
with 18 senators and 57 representatives sponsoring the measures _
giving the legislation a bright prospect of passing this session or
next.
</P>
<P>
   So it was hardly surprising that the five senators at the Oct. 5
hearing _ some with longstanding ties to labor and the trial
lawyers _ praised the legislation. While witnesses supporting the
GAF bill were treated to a series of softball questions, the two
lawyers representing labor and the trial lawyers' group had to
contend with sliders and curves.
</P>
<P>
   GAF's measure would eliminate crushing punitive damages, which
can be high multiples of actual damages. It would supersede state
laws and mandate more restrictive medical proof for many claims.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say it would slash GAF's potential liability, now in the
billions of dollars. And they say it would eliminate up to 70
percent of the 100,000 cases pending against GAF, as well as many
times that number in those that may ultimately be filed,
particularly cases that involve some exposure but, as yet, no
serious disease.
</P>
<P>
   It does offer benefits for plaintiffs. It would, for instance,
eliminate state statutes of limitation that defendants often use to
knock plaintiffs out of court. It would place a 25 percent cap on
fees paid to plaintiffs' lawyers, who now often get more than a
third of an award, and set up a new office to ease out-of-court
settlements. That, proponents say, would save plaintiffs money.
</P>
<P>
   But critics see a wolf in sheep's clothing. The bill's backers
``purport to want to fix the liability system so that people can
get quickly compensated,'' said Frank Clemente, director of Public
Citizen's Congress Watch, an organization founded by Ralph Nader
that has campaigned against the measure. ``Their proposal could
actually do nothing of the sort. If anything, it would cut off more
than half of the population injured by asbestos from pursuing their
legal rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Later this month, the House Judiciary Committee is expected to
approve a version of the legislation, moved in part by a Supreme
Court decision in June. In it, the exasperated justices implored
Congress to find a solution to ``the elephantine mass of asbestos
cases.'' As of now, GAF's in-house legal team, with little
experience in the ways of Washington, is outmaneuvering the more
seasoned trial lawyers and labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started this thing, people told us that there was no
way we could win because of the control over Congress by the trial
lawyers,'' said Richard A. Weinberg, GAF's general counsel and
Heyman's field general in the campaign. ``It's nice to finally see
that policy is finally prevailing.''
</P>
<P>
   But not policy alone.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
