<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8660 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-GAF-ASBESTOS-$ADV17-A     10-15 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAF-ASBESTOS-$ADV17-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: policy alone.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earlier this year, a group of other asbestos makers abandoned
GAF, apparently after being threatened with more personal-injury
lawsuits from aggressive plaintiffs' lawyers. For GAF, the
short-term loss proved to have a longer-term benefit: On its own,
the company did not need to strike any industry compromises or
freight the legislation with other companies' pet causes.
</P>
<P>
   The company then turned to Edley, who first wrote about asbestos
issues earlier this decade, to draft the legislation. He said that
he does not have a normal lawyer-client relationship with GAF and
that he regarded himself as working somewhat independently _ he
occasionally disagrees with Heyman and Weinberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked into this with a very strong expectation that in
pursuing the right public policy, I would at the same time be
satisfying the client, if not perfectly, at least adequately,''
Edley said.
</P>
<P>
   Heyman said that even though Edley was being paid by the
coalition financed by GAF, ``We don't regard him as our lawyer in
the normal sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Heyman also said that despite his own strong ties to Harvard Law
School _ he is an alumnus, a major donor and a member of the dean's
advisory board _ it would be unfair to make any links between those
ties and Edley.
</P>
<P>
   Controlled and financed by GAF, the Coalition for Asbestos
Resolution is led by Conrad L. Mallet Jr., a former chief justice
of the Michigan Supreme Court. Mallet has testified repeatedly
about the legislation's virtues.
</P>
<P>
   A third witness who testified about the constitutional and
administrative law aspects of the legislation was Verkuil, the dean
of Cardozo, the home of the Samuel and Ronnie Heyman Center on
Corporate Governance. Mrs. Heyman, a lawyer and director of GAF, is
also on that school's board, and is a 1996 Clinton appointee to the
National Council on the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Verkuil said that, while he had a long friendship with the
Heymans, his views on the law had not been colored by those ties or
by the family's association with the school. ``The fact that the
Heyman Center and Sam and his wife have been supportive of the
school is more coincidence than anything else,'' he said. ``My
views have developed over the greater part of 30 years of thinking
about these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The connections forged by the Heymans are deeper than academic.
</P>
<P>
   At the current rate of spending, GAF's registered lobbyists
could wind up being paid more than $3 million this year, probably
more than lobbyists for any other company in its industry will be
paid. The lobbyists include Scott Hatch, whose father, a Utah
Republican, heads the Senate Judiciary Committee and was a
co-sponsor of the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Parry, Romani &AMP; DeConcini, the firm where Scott Hatch works, is
headed by Thomas Parry, a close friend and former chief of staff to
Hatch. Its other partners include Dennis DeConcini, the former
democratic senator from Arizona, a former member of the judiciary
committee who has helped persuade current senators like Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., to support the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The firm has received $360,000 from GAF for its services,
according to records filed by the lobbying firm at the Senate
clerk's office.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hatch did not return several telephone calls seeking
comment. The firm's president, Romano Romani, said Hatch's primary
job is to perform research and that he was listed on the lobbying
forms to meet the technical requirements of the disclosure law.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has never lobbied his father on anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Smith, a spokesman for Senator Hatch, also said that Scott
Hatch had not lobbied his father.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Hatch has received at least $10,000 in campaign
contributions from the Heyman family, far from the lion's share of
the company's and family's contributions. Since last year, the
family and GAF's political action committee have given more than
$250,000 to both Democrats and Republicans, according to records at
the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In the last four years, the company and the family have made
donations to more than 100 current and former lawmakers. Not
surprisingly, the bulk of the more recent contributions has gone to
members of the House and Senate Judiciary Committees, which would
have to approve any measures.
</P>
<P>
   While Republicans have long supported GAF's cause as part of
their efforts toward so-called tort reform, the donations and
lobbying appear focused on dislodging enough Democrats to win final
approval. Many Democrats have long been allied with the unions and
trial lawyers, but after donations and heavy lobbying, a number of
them have joined the GAF cause.
</P>
<P>
   When he served on the House Judiciary Committee, Schumer,
outspoken on many issues, never sponsored any asbestos legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer has also been a significant recipient of campaign
contributions. The Heyman family gave $77,500 to his Senate
campaign, including $62,500 to a ``Victory in New York'' fund in
the final week of the race.
</P>
<P>
   He said during the hearing two weeks ago that it was crucial for
Congress to come up with a way to resolve the problems in the
courts and quickly compensate the injured.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli said at the same hearing that he rarely disagrees
with the unions and the trial lawyers. But he also backs the
legislation. As chairman of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee, Torricelli is his party's top fund-raiser in the Senate,
and his campaign and the committee have received at least $41,000
from the Heymans and GAF so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   But GAF's approach to fund-raising has been bipartisan, with its
political action committee giving at least $32,000 to Republicans
on the Senate Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the donations came after GAF suffered a stunning setback
in the Supreme Court in 1997. The court suggested that only
Congress was in a position to clamp down on GAF's mounting asbestos
liability. After that decision, more than 93,000 asbestos claims
were filed against GAF and its affiliated companies, and by the end
of last year, the company faced 113,800 cases.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the members of the Senate Judiciary subcommittee that has
initial jurisdiction over the legislation, only one, Russell D.
Feingold, D.- Wis., has not signed on to the bill. Irking many
corporate lobbyists, Feingold, who is the main proponent of
campaign finance reform, has a singular reputation in the Senate
for spurning big financial contributions and donations from
political action committees.
</P>
<P>
   Heyman, a real estate developer from Connecticut and former
Justice Department prosecutor, inherited GAF's asbestos problems
when he won control of GAF in 1983. Holding only 6 percent of the
company's stock, he and nine others ran against GAF executives and,
against long odds, were elected to its board. In 1989, he took the
company private in a leveraged buyout.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
