<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8661 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-GAF-ASBESTOS-$ADV17-A     10-15 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAF-ASBESTOS-$ADV17-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: leveraged buyout.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAF, founded in 1868, got into the asbestos business a century
later, when it acquired the Ruberoid Co. of New York. In 1928,
Ruberoid bought the H.F. Watson Co., which made thermal insulation
that contained asbestos. The company later acquired an asbestos
mine in Vermont. Ruberoid made significant use of asbestos as an
insulation known as Calcilite, used primarily in roofing products.
</P>
<P>
   GAF never made much money from asbestos and stopped making
asbestos products years before the Heymans arrived.
</P>
<P>
   A white, flaky mineral known for its fire-retardant properties,
asbestos gets its name from a Greek adjective that means
inextinguishable, which history has proved was an apt choice.
</P>
<P>
   The substance was widely used by the turn of the century as
insulation in construction, at shipyards and in household
appliances. Between 1940 and 1980 alone, an estimated 21 million
Americans were exposed to it at work, and countless millions more
are believed to have inhaled loose fibers.
</P>
<P>
   It was only after World War II that scientists, led by the late
Dr. Irving J. Selikoff, discovered that the fibers cause lung
cancer, asbestosis, mesothelioma and other debilitating and fatal
diseases _ but often not until decades after exposure.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, as the research translated into litigation,
companies began to face staggering liability claims, which have
multiplied as relentlessly as the broom in ``The Sorcerer's
Apprentice.''
</P>
<P>
   But huge verdicts, punitive damages and large fees for both
plaintiff and defense lawyers can deplete the money necessary to
help victims.
</P>
<P>
   GAF is one of the most frequent defendants. ``Since the late
1970s, when asbestos litigation as we know it today began,'' Heyman
testified before the Senate subcommittee, GAF has paid out ``more
than $1.2 billion in claims and expenses, a substantial portion of
which has gone to people who are not sick.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite both GAF and the industry having settled almost
300,000 cases,'' he added, ``more than 200,000 asbestos cases
remain pending nationwide, 100,000 of which involve claims against
GAF, with new claims being filed now at the rate of 50,000 per
annum _ with more to come and no end in sight.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of possible claimants is indeed staggering, and many
experts say they are already overwhelming the legal system. The
AFL-CIO estimates that up to a million current or retired members
were exposed to asbestos and that many will suffer from serious
ailments. A widely cited study by the Judicial Conference, the
policy arm of the federal court system, predicts up to 265,000
asbestos-related deaths by 2015.
</P>
<P>
   All this has made it difficult for those who made or used
asbestos to control their expenses. More than 15 companies have
gone bankrupt, and in many cases, the injured have had to wait
years for compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts at consolidating the cases to try to put some cap on
liability have met with mixed success. Twice in the last two years,
the Supreme Court has struck down large class action settlements,
saying they simply cannot accommodate the diverse interests of all
current and future plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   The first of those cases, Amchem Products vs. Windsor, involved
a settlement that set up a special center that claimants could use
to resolve their cases against the 20 large asbestos makers,
including GAF.
</P>
<P>
   Heyman's interest in the legislation is in no small part a
personal one because of his stake in GAF.
</P>
<P>
   But some other large asbestos defendants, like the Manville
Trust, have declined to join GAF's legislative campaign. GAF
executives say this is in part because trial lawyers have
threatened to increase the number of cases they file against them.
</P>
<P>
   One large former asbestos manufacturer, Owens Corning, has
actually testified against the legislation, suggesting that in its
present form it may upset a delicate settlement program the company
has devised with the law firms of more than 100 plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   The program involves giving modest sums to the least injured and
opportunities for victims to reapply for more later, if their
exposure creates more serious problems. Over the next few years, it
will make payments of nearly $3 billion, excluding insurance
contributions and any tax benefits, in the hope of keeping the
company solvent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to discharge our obligation in a way that also works
for us financially,'' said Maura J. Abeln, the general counsel of
Owens Corning and architect of the company's national settlement
program.
</P>
<P>
   Heyman remains dubious, suggesting that the program is destined
to fail because it relies too much on the promises of plaintiffs'
lawyers that they will not sue _ lawyers who in his mind are
needlessly bleeding his and other companies dry, and raking in huge
fees in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``There just is not enough money in the world to buy off all the
asbestos lawyers,'' Heyman told the Senate subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Abeln disagreed, and has a far kinder assessment of
those lawyers. ``Over all, the plaintiffs' bar some 15 years ago
represented people who were exposed and did become ill,'' she said.
``Had they not had access to the court system, they probably would
never have gotten paid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
