<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8668 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-DELAY-REPUBLICANS-1ST     10-15 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELAY-REPUBLICANS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (EDS: Subs 35th graf to change `ARMPAC' to `his federal PAC'. No
other change.)  
 HOUSE GOP WHIP TOM DeLAY EXPANDS HIS POWER, AND RELISHES IT  
(Eds.: sidebar at end of article) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)
(bl) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL and MARC LACEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Majority Whip Tom DeLay has never been called
shy about displaying his power.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon, the 52-year-old Texas Republican
mischievously showed that he really does know how to use the long
whips that he keeps coiled in his office as symbols of his job as
the House's chief head-counter and vote wrangler.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay slipped out the back door of his suite, holding a red,
white and black, braided Hungarian whip. He marched out to the East
Front of the Capitol, instructing his bodyguard to warn police that
the loud bangs that would soon ring out were not gunshots.
</P>
<P>
   Then, standing as poised as a ballet dancer, he swung the
eight-foot coil over his head and sent its end cracking, again and
again. Bill Paxon, a former congressman turned lobbyist, who had
been nearby, whispering into his cellular phone, cowered and called
out playfully, ``I didn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, no one questions that the whip-cracking DeLay is the
House's most powerful member. Though technically just the
third-ranking member of the Republican leadership, he wields more
influence than Speaker Dennis Hastert, whose election he largely
orchestrated. Although he enjoys moments of showmanship, he has
acquired this power more quietly, building a political machine that
many experts call the most formidable organization of any member of
Congress today. The confederation, knitted over the last five
years, includes House loyalists, DeLay proteges, political
committees and corporate lobbyists all deployed to expand and
protect the thin Republican majority.
</P>
<P>
   The machine is fueled by money and some of his fund raising has
been criticized because, even though he is a federal official, he
seeks contributions that fall outside the purview of federal
election law. He has raised millions of dollars for other
Republicans, including state officials, sometimes by using legal
loopholes in the campaign finance laws. DeLay is currently raising
funds for a controversial $25 million drive to counter labor union
efforts for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In his brashness, DeLay has sometimes skated close to the
ethical edge. Reports that he has demanded declarations of loyalty
from lobbyists have led the House Committee on Standards of
Official Conduct on two occasions to remind him of the rules
against linking official actions to partisan considerations. But
ethics complaints against him were dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay is a powerful force in the conservative wing of his party
and led the charge for the impeachment of President Clinton. But
Republican moderates turn to him, too, and several say they like
the way he is masterminding the Republicans' budget showdown with
the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to turn over to my kids a country that I had a part
to play in changing from the failed welfare state that I lived
in,'' DeLay said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of DeLay's strength that he was the only House
leader to go unchallenged when the loss of House seats by
Republicans last November forced the resignation of Speaker Newt
Gingrich and set off a struggle for every other post in the House
Republican hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's never been more influential than he is right
now,'' said Rep. John Doolittle, R-Calif., who is part of DeLay's
whip organization. Marshall Wittmann, a congressional analyst at
the conservative Heritage Foundation, said: ``He is the most
powerful majority whip in the history of the House of
Representatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every member of the current House Republican
leadership is somehow indebted to DeLay _ either because of favors
he has performed or campaign funds he has shared. And his kitchen
cabinet of plugged-in players in the lobbying world meets regularly
in DeLay's inner sanctum.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay wins praise from Republicans for his skill, his energy and
his willingness to help colleagues. But much of his power is rooted
in his unabashed devotion to political money.
</P>
<P>
   In Gingrich's absence, Delay has emerged as the chief
fund-raiser for the National Republican Congressional Committee,
the campaign arm of House Republicans. Republican strategists
estimate that DeLay, through telemarketing, direct mail and
personal appearances, has helped raise at least $11 million in the
first half of this year _ or nearly half the organization's money.
</P>
<P>
   ``My infrastructure expands,'' he said in an interview. ``The
number of people I know, the networking and everything, just grows.
It doesn't happen overnight. It's a lot of work. Years of work.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Now DeLay is helping his conservative allies raise money for an
ambitious new enterprise, a $25 million campaign to counter
organized labor's plan to help Democrats in the coming
congressional elections. The effort is being directed through a
non-profit corporation that can raise money in unlimited sums
without disclosing its donors.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., a sponsor of legislation to
overhaul campaign finance, has called the secrecy of the group
``unbelievably sick.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay argued that the group was necessary to return Republicans
to their grass roots. ``There's no other organization that can
fight with the unions toe to toe, in the streets, in the
communities,'' DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   Partisan battle is what DeLay is all about. He is proud of
running the whip's office not just as a vote-counting operation but
as part catering hall, part campaign headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   He will help a fellow House member find a private plane if the
Republican needs to get to an event quickly. He will travel to a
far-flung congressional district to headline a fund-raising event.
He routinely offers buffet dinners in his office during the House's
late-night sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's barbecue,'' said Doolittle. ``Sometimes it's
fried chicken. Sometimes it's pizza. Frequently it's more than one
of those things.
</P>
<P>
   Even though that doesn't have anything to do with the
legislative process, it develops closer relationships,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
