<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rocker `pushes their buttons'
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The pack of starving Mets fans got what they wanted
on Friday and it was long before the game started. They got a piece
of the newly anointed king of trash talk John Rocker upon his
arrival for batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker was interviewed by NBC in the dugout, then surrounded by
a pack of reporters where he was asked to explain his sentiments
behind ``to hell with Mets fans'' comments among others. But to the
jeers of the Mets fans above the Braves dugout, Rocker finally
walked up the steps, turned and tipped his cap to the fans.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker even stopped to sign autographs down the left field line
on his way to the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's funny I can push their buttons that bad,'' Rocker
said. ``One comment can make them expend this much energy.''
</P>
<P>
   But did he expect it to be much worse?
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be just as irate and derogatory toward me,'' Rocker
said. ``Are they going to tell me I really (stink) this time?''
</P>
<P>
   When asked to gauge his competitive juices, Rocker smiled and
said: ``They're about as high as they've ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves manager Bobby Cox spoke up Friday about his displeasure
when he was asked about Rocker's comments, saying it was something
he would address with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it irritates me,'' Cox said. ``I don't like it. I don't
condone it. He was roughed up by the fans, I think, our first
series here out in the outfield. And he's the type of guy that's
going to give it right back. He's got to work on that. He's a great
pitcher, a great competitor, but he needs to work on his player/fan
relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   That was met with laughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe if you feel something is wrong, maybe you ought to
speak up,'' Rocker said.
</P>
<P>
   BAYLOR UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's news that Phil Garner had been hired to manage the
Detroit Tigers just underscored that Braves hitting coach Don
Baylor is the leading candidate for the Cubs managing position and
will probably have the job offered to him once the Braves season is
over.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs general manager Ed Lynch called Baylor at 9 a.m. in his New
York hotel room on Friday. Baylor said Lynch did not offer him the
job, just told him he was still evaluating other candidates and
would be back in touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't talked length of contract or of dollar figures,''
Baylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor has also been pursued by the Milwaukee Brewers, and has
talked with former Braves assistant general manager and current
Brewers GM Dean Taylor six or seven times already. But the Anaheim
Angels and the Cubs would appear to have most of Baylor's interest.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor has interviewed with the Angels but is waiting for the
hiring of a new general manager, something that is expected as
early as Monday. Also with Friday's news that Cleveland manager
Mike Hargrove was fired, his name could enter the mix in several of
those cities.
</P>
<P>
   LINEUP SHAKEUP
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to get out of an Atlanta pitching-induced slump,
Mets manager Bobby Valentine juggled the top of his lineup for Game
3, moving the struggling John Olerud up to No. 2 and putting the
hot hitting Edgardo Alfonzo at No. 3. He also dropped a cold Robin
Ventura from fifth to sixth and put power-hitting Benny Agbayani in
Ventura's usual fifth spot behind Mike Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitting Mike where he might get a pitch or two more to hit,
gives Fonzie a little more prominence in our lineup and it spaces
our left-handers,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
