u w BC-DELAY-REPUBLICANS-1ST     10-15 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELAY-REPUBLICANS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
WASHINGTON: he said.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Building DeLay Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Delay was never expected to become whip. When Republicans won
the majority in 1994, Gingrich had endorsed his friend, Rep. Bob
Walker, R-Pa. Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., also made a spirited and
well-financed run. But DeLay defeated them both, benefiting from
nine months of helping Republican congressional candidates around
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   He formed a leadership political action committee, known as
Americans for a Republican Majority, that poured $2 million into
the campaigns of incumbents and challengers. The group has received
large donations from an array of corporations, including tobacco
and telecommunications companies. He has traveled to 25 states to
help get Republicans elected, offering campaign advice,
fund-raising help, anything that a candidate asked for. His toiling
translated into votes.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, now a lobbyist, still seems somewhat jarred that DeLay
defeated him. ``Tom is someone who enjoys raising money,'' Walker
said. ``It is one of his strengths. Even though I didn't want to
campaign that way, I admired in the end that it was successful for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mildred Webber, a DeLay loyalist who managed his campaign
for whip says that it was more than contributions that led to
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom knew that it wasn't just going to be money that got us the
majority _or that won him the whip race,'' she said. ``It was going
to be a full-service operation and that's what we became.''
</P>
<P>
   He even sent out tapes to candidates providing such practical
tutoring as how to use lawn signs.
</P>
<P>
   After securing the whip's job, DeLay continued using money to
enhance his power, much like other aspiring House leaders. Because
he rarely faces a serious challenger for re-election he
traditionally gives away as much as 90 percent of his campaign
funds. And, with Gingrich gone, DeLay has become the linchpin
between Republicans in the House and their conservative donors. His
popularity with these donors was enhanced by his role in the
impeachment of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't waste Tom on small donors,'' said one of DeLay's
advisers. ``We don't ask him to make $1,000 calls. He makes
six-figure calls.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay has expanded his organization from a vote-counting
operation into a kind of political machine.
</P>
<P>
   This year, through a program called Romp, or Retain Our Majority
Program, DeLay nudged his deputy and assistant whips to contribute
to the campaigns of 10 Republican incumbents who were in danger of
losing their re-election races. The money was supplemented by
lobbyists, political action committees and other House leaders,
altogether netting more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay's edge was apparent in an early draft of the program's
organization plan, written by an aide. It opened with a quote from
Winston Churchill that seemed to capture the spirit of the office:
``Victory at all costs, victory in spite of all terror, victory
however long and hard the road may be. For without victory there is
no survival.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay also opened an offshoot of his federal PAC in Virginia,
where he gave donations to candidates for the state legislature. He
called the focus on state politics essential to ``grow the majority
party,'' saying it was designed to help create a farm team for
Congress and wrest control of state legislatures before crucial
decisions on redistricting that could affect control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Operating in Virginia allowed him to take advantage _ as other
lawmakers have done _ of that state's lack of contribution limits
for PACs. In 1996, the Virginia operation directed $12,000 back
into DeLay's federal PAC, drawing a warning letter from the Federal
Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Although DeLay eventually closed his Virginia group, his federal
PAC has continued to maintain a state fund that accepts corporate
donations and keeps its records to itself. The organization is in
the process of registering again in Virginia and Mississippi,
associates said, and plans to focus on the 22 states that allow
corporate contributions to candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Another organization that benefits from DeLay's fund raising is
the Republican Majority Issues Committee, which Democrats have
challenged before the Federal Election Commission because of its
decision not to report donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the worst thing in politics is anonymous, under the
bedclothes money,'' said Rep. David Obey, D-Wis.
</P>
<P>
   The group is led by Karl Gallant, who previously ran the federal
PAC for DeLay. For years, Gallant fought organized labor as vice
president of the National Right to Work Committee. He described the
group as a ``mirror image of the AFL-CIO'' because it would devote
its efforts to identifying and turning out conservative voters in
key congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the organization unusual is that it is registering
under the IRS code as a nonprofit corporation involved in politics.
That designation means that it does not have to make its tax
returns public or report its contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal election law, such a group is banned from
coordination with candidates and Gallant carefully says that
although DeLay is a major fund-raiser, the organization is
independent from him. ``We are separate from the DeLay operation,''
he said. ``I have had to leave the nest to get this started.''
</P>
<P>
   But many Republican-leaning lobbyists say they consider the
group another surrogate DeLay organization, and DeLay has been
unabashedly helping it raise money. He says he does not run the
group, but he does not distance himself from it either. And he
staunchly defends the lack of disclosure because ``the law doesn't
require it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be glad to disclose it if I can get disclosure of Ralph
Nader's groups, disclosure of the ACLU, disclosure of the leftist
organizations,'' DeLay said. ``If they'll disclose, I'll
disclose.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee made its initial pitch for funds earlier this year
on the private yacht of Amway president Richard DeVos and his wife,
Betsy, the chairwoman of the Michigan Republican Party, both of
whom are among the Republican Party's biggest donors.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay and the other Republican leaders in the Hose were all on
hand. The first to step forward with a pledge was lobbyist and
fund-raiser Jack Abramoff, who is close to DeLay. He says he will
raise ``plenty'' for the effort.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
