<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8680 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-NY-YANKS-HISPANICS-NY     10-15 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-YANKS-HISPANICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIXING HISPANIC AND YANKEE PRIDE NEAR THE BALL PARK 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By AMY WALDMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Maria Infante is Dominican by parentage, but she has
little affinity for the baseball heroes with whom she shares a
heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate Pedro,'' Ms. Infante said with a 16-year-old's ruthless
absolutism, referring to the Boston Red Sox pitcher, who is
scheduled to start Saturday's playoff game against the Yankees in
Boston. ``I hate Sosa. I hate all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter, however, is a different story. ``I luuuuuuv him,''
she said, lingering on the word as if it were Jeter himself.
</P>
<P>
   On her block in the Highbridge section of the Bronx, where
perhaps one in five residents is Dominican, only one kid likes
Pedro Martinez and the Red Sox, Ms. Infante said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks just because he's Dominican and they're Dominican
they're the best,'' she snorted.
</P>
<P>
   And so this week, at least, in this corner of the Bronx, just a
few blocks from the Yankees' ball park, neighborhood is apparently
trumping nationality. Not only is the Yankee logo everywhere _ on
hats, T-shirts, jackets _ but a new version featuring Chinese
letters is in vogue, too.
</P>
<P>
   But for Hispanic baseball fans across the city, allegiances are
less automatic, for the success of Hispanic players, from Sammy
Sosa to Manny Ramirez to El Duque, has given rise to all sorts of
divided loyalties. And the sorting out of those interests has only
become more intricate this October.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is arguably the finest Dominican pitcher since Juan
Marichal, and many Dominicans this season turned out to cheer him
loudly at Yankee Stadium. The Mets, meanwhile, have more Dominican
stars _ Armando Benitez and Octavio Dotel _ than the Yankees. Oh,
and then there was the problem of how to feel about Ramirez, the
Washington Heights prodigy who drove in more runs for the Cleveland
Indians than anyone in baseball this year. Sadly _ or mercifully,
perhaps _ for Ramirez fans, the Indians were eliminated last Monday
by the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, then, Miguel Rodriguez's anguish was real this
week in Highbridge. ``I want Ramon Martinez to get a victory,''
Rodriguez, a 40-year-old train operator for New York City Transit,
said before Thursday night's game, referring to Pedro's brother,
who also pitches for the Boston. ``I would like my Dominican
brothers to win. But not against the Yankees.'' Ramon, it turned
out, took the loss.
</P>
<P>
   Rady Torres, who owns the Palacio social club at Woodycrest
Avenue and West 165th Street, said he is a Mets fan, and has been
since he arrived from Puerto Rico in 1969 and spent a summer with
his aunt and uncle watching the Mets on television. But Torres is
not a stupid man: his club, where the two televisions have gotten a
workout this week, has Yankees pictures on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' latest ascent to dominance seems all the more sweet
here because it mirrors the arc of the neighborhood, where gunfire
once underlay drug dealers' transactions like a bass line. Fortunes
have not changed so much that anyone around here has the cash for a
ticket to a playoff game, but now, children of all ages can at
least play in the streets _ throwing a baseball, teasing each other
_ without fear.
</P>
<P>
   There are just-built multifamily homes and a few new businesses.
Optimism is in the air, and its soundtrack is the cheering from the
stadium down the street.
</P>
<P>
   Proximity also creates a certain willingness to forgive. Yes,
Carlos Melo, 32, who works at the bodega at the corner of
Woodycrest and West 165th, conceded, the Yankees have few Hispanics
on their team. Yes, he said, he likes Pedro Martinez. But, he said,
``Boston does not play among us.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, most Hispanics here seem to separate the players
from the teams. ``I luuuuuv Pedro and Ramon,'' Glauco Vidal said,
sounding like a certain neighborhood girl. ``But I do not like
Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does he like the Yankees, however. Vidal, a Mets fan, is
careful not to display that fact in his new travel agency and phone
center, which is down West 165th Street from the social club. His
opinions, he said, were formed in the 1980s, when the Yankees, it
seemed to him, did not value the neighborhood's legions of baseball
fans and were always talking of relocating. Now, with attendance
soaring, the question of the Yankees leaving the Bronx has all but
evaporated. Still, Vidal has not forgiven them.
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone around here, Vidal lives so close to the stadium
that, if he cannot hear the crack of the bat, he can hear the crowd
responding to it. On Wednesday night, watching sheets of rain fall,
he turned off his television set, certain the game was being
suspended. A few minutes later, he heard a great roar a few blocks
away, and turned on the television to see Bernie Williams circling
the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Caban, 16, predicted Wednesday that Williams would win
the game, and Thursday he was back on the street to gloat. He is
Puerto Rican, he said, and has little interest in the Dominican
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shut up with Pedro Martinez,'' he said when a brave
13-year-old piped up that the pitcher would lead Boston to victory.
</P>
<P>
   Most, but certainly not all, Puerto Ricans in the neighborhood
expressed similar sentiments: disinterest in Dominican players and
passion for the Yankees. If anything, Boston's defeat of Cleveland,
where Sandy Alomar, a Puerto Rican, plays, made the team even more
unpopular here.
</P>
<P>
   In this neighborhood, Dominicans, Puerto Ricans and Cubans and
other Hispanic immigrants live together, which further complicates
_ and sometimes confuses _ the question of loyalties. Consider
12-year-old Junior Gamoneda, who is half-Dominican, with the rest a
mix of Honduran, North American and Puerto Rican _ and a 100
percent Yankees fan.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa Rosario, 29 and Puerto Rican, also loves the Yankees; her
husband, who is Dominican, ``likes Pedro,'' she said distastefully,
adding, ``Everybody Dominican likes Pedro.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Angel Diaz, who on Thursday was wearing a hat
that said Puerto Rico and a sweatshirt that championed the Mets. As
it turns out, he is Cuban and a Yankees fan. He makes and sells the
hats in a tiny workshop on West 165th Street, and he had grabbed
the sweatshirt to combat the cold.
</P>
<P>
   Big mistake: he might as well have worn red in a Crips
neighborhood. After more than a few ominous-sounding ``hey, are you
crazy?'' remarks from passers-by, he said, he was going home to
change. A few minutes later, he re-emerged, a plain gray sweatshirt
on his back and a Yankees ski cap on his head.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
