<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8691 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-15 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BISHOPS AND EDUCATORS NEAR ANOTHER ROUND ON RELIGIOUS LOYALTY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Italy)   By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the first three months of this year, newspapers in
Boston, Chicago, New York, San Francisco, Seattle, Washington and
other major cities ran prominent articles with headlines like
``Catholic Colleges See Peril in Vatican Push for Control'' or
``Catholic Campuses Face Showdown on Ties to Church.''
</P>
<P>
   As so often happens, the story then sank from sight. Now it is
back. And it is part of a larger story that stretches far beyond
the 200-plus Roman Catholic campuses to many other religiously
affiliated colleges and universities in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The steady secularization of American higher education over the
last hundred years has often been viewed as a virtually
irresistible trend. Catholic leaders, both educators and bishops,
have nonetheless declared themselves determined to resist
secularization, but they are divided about how to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Among many colleges with ties to Protestant denominations or
other religious groups, there is also a renewed desire to retain
some distinctive religious character, either in the name of a
religious form of multiculturalism or as a crucial resource for the
survival of particular traditions. But here, too, opinions clash
about how to do it.
</P>
<P>
   What caused the spate of news articles last spring was a draft
document spelling out how Pope John Paul II's 1990 statement on
Catholic higher education, ``Ex Corde Ecclesiae'' (``From the Heart
of the Church''), should be applied in the United States. The
draft, in turn, was a revision of a 1996 document in which American
Catholic bishops emphasized communication and trust between
educators and church leaders as the chief way to maintain a
distinctive Catholic character in the education, research efforts
and campus life at Catholic colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 approach won overwhelming support among the bishops.
But Rome found it, well, whatever would be the polite Latin
equivalent of mealy-mouthed. The Vatican wanted some hard-and-fast
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   So last year's draft insisted, among other things, that a
majority of faculty members and trustees at Catholic colleges and
universities should be ``faithful Catholics,'' that the presidents
of these institutions take a special oath of fidelity and that
Catholics teaching theology obtain a ``mandate'' from the local
bishop indicating they are Catholics in good standing and are
presenting church doctrines as authoritatively interpreted.
</P>
<P>
   Would such requirements threaten academic freedom, undermine the
credibility of Catholic scholarship, hobble the drive toward
academic excellence that has marked many Catholic campuses over the
last decades, run afoul anti-discrimination laws and perhaps
endanger federal and state financial aid?
</P>
<P>
   Many Catholic educators, whose institutions are generally not
under the direct control of the bishops but of independent boards
of directors, said yes. A minority said no, arguing in particular
that fears of legal entanglements or the loss of government aid
were hypothetical problems never tested in the courts. A few simply
pointed to the loophole phrases in the draft, like ``as much as
possible'' and ``to the extent possible,'' as clues that once these
requirements were on the books, no one would take them too
literally.
</P>
<P>
   The bishops themselves said almost nothing, waiting for a
further revision of the draft. Now they have it. In September, the
administrative board of the National Conference of Catholic Bishops
decided that when the conference meets in November, a major item on
its agenda will be a revised version of last year's draft.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a year of discussions with worried educators, most of
the revisions appear cosmetic, saying the same thing but in what
the drafters term ``a clearly pastoral tone.''
</P>
<P>
   The revised draft insists, for example, that the requirement
that faculty members respect Catholic doctrine does not mean that
``a Catholic university's task is to indoctrinate or proselytize
its students.''
</P>
<P>
   In a commentary accompanying the new version, the drafters point
to language about ``academic freedom and integrity'' and ``respect
for religious liberty and freedom of conscience'' and ``observance
of federal and state law, regulations and procedures in hiring.''
</P>
<P>
   These references, they say, are ``specifically aimed at
protecting not only governmental assistance to students but also
the federal and state entitlements and benefits that Catholic
colleges and universities enjoy as significant participants in U.S.
higher education.''
</P>
<P>
   Other changes may make the new version more palatable to a wider
academic audience and to a public that sometimes equates any
religious language with blind fervor. Instead of calling for
``faithful'' Catholics on the faculties and boards of trustees, an
adjective that appeared to invite subjective judgments, the
document now speaks of Catholics ``committed to the church.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of calling on Catholic institutions to be instruments of
``evangelization,'' which, for many people, has overtones of
proselytizing, the new version speaks of contributing to ``the
mission of communicating Gospel values.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of calling on presidents of Catholic colleges and
universities to take an ``oath of fidelity,'' a phrase with unhappy
echoes of loyalty oaths, the new version requires each new
president to ``express his or her commitment to the university's
Catholic identity and to the Catholic faith in accordance with
canon 833'' (which in fact specifies the oath of fidelity).
</P>
<P>
   Instead of using the English ``mandate,'' with its suggestion of
command or injunction, the new version uses the original Latin
``mandatum'' as technical and not so ``easily misconstrued.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems doubtful that these minor revisions will relieve the
anxieties provoked by the draft discussed last year. Some bishops
have gone on record against taking any action in November, although
they are under pressure from the Vatican to do so. They fear that a
confrontation with Catholic educators will initiate an extended
period of squabbling, even litigation, and will undercut the many
efforts to reassert the religious identity of Catholic colleges and
universities that the pope's letter has already encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   Other bishops believe that nothing but a set of unambiguous
stipulations will hold back the tide of secularization. Who is
right?
</P>
<P>
   In the history of American higher education, secularization has
sometimes been abetted by an abdication or failure of nerve by the
religious authorities. At other times, strong efforts to assert
church control have actually reinforced the drive toward
secularization.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever the outcome at the bishops' meeting in November, it
will have an impact well beyond the campuses of Catholic colleges
and universities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
