u s BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-15 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FOR THE LONG HAUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A man who sort of looks like me predicted the Red Sox would
sweep the Yankees in the American League Championship Series. What
nerve. If this weren't such a compelling series, I would use this
space to talk a little trash about the man. But for now, let's just
say he was joking.
</P>
<P>
   Really, the last thing anyone should be thinking about Saturday
morning is a sweep or short series. The Yankees are not going to
sweep the Sox. And they won't win in five games. All I can tell you
is that you should keep Thursday night open because that's when the
final Sox-Yankees game of the 20th century will take place in
Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Please do not take that as a prediction. It's obvious, isn't it?
These teams have played two one-run games, with the Yankees winning
both. The New Yorkers received breaks and bounces that can't
possibly continue for the next couple games. The Sox will win three
of the next four to force a seventh game in the Bronx. I didn't
even have to consult with my insightful alter ego, the Holley Lama,
to come to that conclusion. All I had to do was watch the first 19
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, most Sox fans have missed the beauty of these
games. The first one was tainted by umpire Rick Reed, who watched
Chuck Knoblauch drop a ball in the 10th inning and determined,
strangely, that it wasn't a dropped ball. (Yo, Rick. Have you been
following Knoblauch's woes this year? The second baseman handles
the ball as if he were at war with the thing. Of course he dropped
it.) In the second game, 13 stranded runners and two balls that
just missed leaving the park had fans complaining about managerial
strategy and players who do not know how to move runners over so
they can come home.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is that if baseball had more games like these,
baseball would have no problems. You want to know how good these
games have been? So good that I wouldn't be surprised if Reggie
Jefferson called Mo Vaughn Friday night and said, ``Have you been
watching this Sox-Yankees series? This is how the game is supposed
to be played, man. You gonna watch today?''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday afternoon at Fenway Park, Pedro Martinez and Roger
Clemens will oppose each other. Arguments have gone deep into the
night over matchups like this, mostly because they rarely happen.
Boxing fans would have loved to have seen Rocky Marciano face Larry
Holmes. Fans of irreverent comics dream of Chris Rock matching
monologues with Lenny Bruce. Jazz fans would pay thousands to see a
Billie Holliday-Cassandra Wilson marquee. But those performers are
eras and generations apart.
</P>
<P>
   That is not the case with the 27-year-old Martinez and
37-year-old Clemens. The hype of their Game 3 paceoff is justified.
But the two men already have tough acts to follow. That's how good
the series has been. Even those involved have a difficult time
explaining the intensity that will be splayed over the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the regular season you play a close game and people
say, `That game had a playoff atmosphere,' '' Sox first baseman
Mike Stanley said Friday. He shook his head. ``That's not true.
There is nothing you can compare this to.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time in Stanley's career that he has made it
to a championship series. He said he always wanted to make it here,
but he acknowledges he had no idea it would be like this. At this
level of the playoffs, you can walk by anyone in the afternoon _ a
manager, player, reporter, league official _ and they all look like
they have spent eight hours dancing at a club. Ask someone how they
are doing and they are likely to reply, ``Dehydrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, it would have been an acceptable answer from either Joe
Torre or Jimy Williams. The point-counterpoint the two managers
displayed in the eighth inning of Game 2 was even exhausting to
watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it is fun when it works to your benefit,'' Torre said.
``I mean, it is something that if I am in his dugout, I do the same
things he did. And if he is in my dugout, he probably does the same
things I do.''
</P>
<P>
   It's like Torre and Williams had a Jenga game going. You know,
when you put a piece of wood on top of another until your towering
creation finally topples.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have teams like we have, you don't pay much attention
to what is going on in the first six innings, because down toward
the end is where you have to save your moves and really see if, you
know, see if you can match up,'' Torre said. ``Matchups and knowing
what matchup you want . . . a lot of times it is just a matter of
who gets the first move, which dictates other things.''
</P>
<P>
   After the moves are complete and games finished, the natural
thing to do is review them all. That's when fans in most cities _
Atlanta being the exception _ raise their games to match the
passion of the playoffs. It's when everyone becomes an expert. It's
when there is a lot of questioning and doubt attached to every
move.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, that meant wondering why Butch Huskey pinch-hit for
Trot Nixon in the eighth inning of Game 2. In the ninth, that left
the overmatched Damon Buford trying to hit Mariano Rivera's cutter,
which sometimes reaches the high 90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good that people are that into it,'' Sox catcher Jason
Varitek said with a laugh, ``but we already get the second-guessing
in the regular season.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Sox were home, a final-day Ryder Cup-type of
crowd guided them through a 23-7 win over the Indians. Every strike
was cheered. There were boos on balls. There was cheering on foul
balls.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the Ryder Cup crowd will merge with the Big Event
crowd. They will see the best contemporary pitcher, a man who won
Cy Young Awards in both leagues, challenge a five-time Cy winner
who was the most dominant pitcher in the game for most of the 1980s
and two seasons in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is gonna be a hell of an experience,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   He's right. He could make the same statement about the series.
The seven-game series. So don't call me on Thursday, OK? I'll be in
the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   (Michael Holley is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
