<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8699 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BO     10-15 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS WILL GET A `SPECIAL' FENWAY WELCOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time _ when he was younger and thinner and we knew
so much less about him _ when Roger Clemens was the most popular
Red Sox player. He was all fire and fuzzy cheeks, and it seemed he
never lost. Young Roger was compared to young Larry Bird.
</P>
<P>
   That was before he came out of Game 6 in '86, before his spring
training walkout in '87, before the ``we've got to carry our own
bags'' interview. It was before Velvet Elvis, Possessed Rebel,
Terry Cooney, and the headphones incident in which he dissed Daddy
Butch Hobson. It was before his final four mediocre (by his
standards) Red Sox seasons and before he went to Toronto and
pitched with the rage of a man whose family had been terrorized.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens's local popularity waned steadily even as he was
establishing himself (side by side with Cy Young) as the winningest
pitcher in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   And then he committed the ultimate crime and took his game to
the New York Yankees. It was like having an ex-girlfriend move in
with your hated next door neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   This is why Clemens was booed when he was announced to the
Fenway crowd before the All-Star Game as one of the century's top
100 players. And this is why he's going to hear it again Saturday
after 4 p.m. when he tries to beat Pedro Martinez and the Red Sox
in the third game of the American League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever that is, whatever that does, I don't know,'' Clemens
said Friday. ``I've got plenty of people who appreciate what I was
able to do in my 13 years here, and that is never going to change.
You can't make people not boo you or like you if they don't and you
want them to come and get it out and let it out. That's what the
Boston-New York situation is supposed to be. I don't think as far
as hate and nasty towards one another is really there, like when
Zim (Yankees bench coach Don Zimmer) tells us some of the stories.
But they get better each year, too, as it goes by.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens was relaxed and uncommonly anecdotal when he met with
the media Friday. Sounding like a regular Roger Waldo Emerson, he
spoke lovingly of his old Mass. Pike commute from Framingham, and
the blazing colors of autumn in New England. He didn't disown the
obvious, as he had in other return trips to Fenway. He appeared to
be in the moment, just like everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's joust is the most wildly anticipated Fenway game
since the 1978 one-game playoff between the Red Sox and Yankees,
and Clemens acknowledged, ``This is not business as usual. I'll be
as excited as everyone else tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a stunning comment from a man who's constantly downplayed
what his presense in a Yankee uniform means to Red Sox fans.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is 3-1 against the Sox since Dan Duquette said he was in
the twilight of his career. Sox fans think they've got the goods on
the Rocket Saturday because Pedro is pitching and we all remember
his 17-strikeout, one-hitter in Yankee Stadium last month.
Moreover, Red Sox Nation thinks Roger will spit the bit because
it's postseason ball.
</P>
<P>
   When he wore a Red Sox uniform, Clemens started nine playoff
games and won only once. That stat is somewhat unfair because he
pitched well in many of those games and his bullpen blew leads. His
World Series ERA is 3.18, and his ALCS mark is 4.10. He won the
seventh game of the ALCS for Boston in 1986 (he also pitched seven
shutout innings in New York's Division Series clincher against
Texas). The Sox have lost 10 straight ALCS games since Clemens's
victory over the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   But image means a lot, and New Englanders see Clemens in the
playoffs and think of Bo Schembechler at the Rose Bowl or Shaquille
O'Neal at the foul line. Red Sox fans remember when Dave Stewart
played Bill Russell to Clemens's Wilt Chamberlain. The Rocket could
not beat Oakland's ace when it mattered, and there are those who
believe Clemens intentionally got himself tossed out of their final
playoff match at Oakland in 1990 _ just to avoid the embarrassment
of another futile effort against Mr. Death Stare.
</P>
<P>
   And of course there is the nasty spitting contest between
Clemens and ex-manager John McNamara, who told the world that the
Rocket asked to come out of Game 6 in '86 _ a statement Clemens
angrily denies. No Warren Commission could possibly unearth
everything that actually happened that fateful night at Shea
Stadium, but Mac's version of events was harmful to Clemens's local
repuation.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the history Roger lugs to the Fenway mound Saturday. He
can fool folks in Texas, Toronto, and New York, but he can't fool
Bostonians. He was here too long. These fans know him as a flawed
pitcher in October. They also know that he dislikes New York and
went there only for the money and the chance for a ring. We know
that Saturday's game could stand as the defining moment of a Hall
of Fame career that's already seen five Cy Young trophies and two
20-strikeout games.
</P>
<P>
   No excuse will work if things don't go Clemens's way Saturday.
Pedro can come out with an injury and nobody will peep, but the
Rocket exhausted the patience of Sox fans while he was here, and
thousands can't wait to see the Red Sox benefit from a continuation
of his playoff woes. There can be no excuses. Clemens has emptied
the auxiliary tanks of fan tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if Clemens sticks it to the home team, look
out below. Fragile New England sports fans are emotionally
incapable of coping with a series sweep set up on the strengh of a
Clemens Game 3 shutout. It would be Babe Ruth, Sparky Lyle, and
Wade Boggs all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody got an extra ticket?
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
