<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-N.Y.-PATAKI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PATAKI'S FRIENDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Oct. 16:
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki has become the perfect leader to reform New
York's cozy relationship between those who make policy and those
who donate money in order to influence policy. The reason is that
Pataki knows this coziness all too well. He has been nestling into
New York state's comfortable system for some time now, and although
he and his aides have insisted that he follows the letter of the
law, that letter all too often looks like a D- on fund-raising and
government ethics.
</P>
<P>
   A promising politician like Pataki who wants to make his mark in
the national arena needs to do better than conform to the loose
ethical standards imposed by New York state. Thus when he announced
the skeleton of a campaign finance plan in June, there was some
reason to hope that he would lead a new spirit of reform in Albany.
This hope survives despite the fact that the governor's proposal
came just a few hours before the end of the legislative session and
brought snickers from other legislators who presumed by its very
lateness that the governor wanted plenty of credit but little real
change in the system.
</P>
<P>
   The time for real change is while Pataki still serves in the
state Capitol. As it is now, the shadows on his administration's
fund-raising practices grow longer each season. Questions began
soon after he was elected and established an inauguration and
transition fund in 1994, a secret $2.5 million fund-raising
operation that was finally made public by a judge two years later.
Federal investigators are looking at whether the Pataki
administration has influenced the state parole board to go easier
on relatives of the governor's financial supporters. Those who give
thousands to campaign funds controlled by the governor can and do
expect to win state contracts. Silverite Construction Co., for
example, gave thousands of dollars to state Republican funds
controlled by Pataki and won a $97 million state contract for work
on the Queens-Midtown Tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the Pataki family's combined vacation and
business trips to Hungary in 1995 and 1996, which the governor's
aides say were approved by the state's Ethics Commission. The trips
were sponsored by the Hungarian-American Chamber of Commerce,
U.S.A., but appear to have been financed by corporations such as
Pepsico and Philip Morris, which have important business interests
before the governor. Pataki's spokesman says there was no way for
these corporations to have undue influence on Pataki and his staff
because they did not know about donations that went directly to the
Hungarian group.
</P>
<P>
   The Hungarian organization, after paying the governor's fare,
received a free office at the World Trade Center, which is owned by
the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey. Pataki appointed a
longtime friend as the authority's executive director. The
governor's spokesman said Pataki had played no role in his friend's
decision to provide the office. Such distinctions may get the
governor off the hook in Albany, but they leave the strong
impression that his administration is up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has proposed significant restrictions on ways that state
politicians raise and spend money. Now his own reputation depends
on using his formidable clout in Albany to follow through. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 2214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
