<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX THE FIRST TO FILL KOBE'S ROLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Lakers are staying home for the weekend, and
coach Phil Jackson said it's just as well. No makeup game in Little
Rock, Ark., means more practice time _ and more time to find a
replacement for injured Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Little Rock have discovered more cracks in the new
Alltel Arena, canceling plans to reschedule an exhibition game
there. Instead the Lakers will practice today and possibly twice
Sunday in preparation for Tuesday's game against Golden State in
San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   And who will start at shooting guard?
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't ask me that question,'' Jackson said. ``I won't answer
it.''
</P>
<P>
   With Ron Harper not yet in shape, Rick Fox is the likely
temporary replacement for Bryant, out six weeks because of a broken
hand. But Jackson has more general concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fortunate'' not to return to Little Rock, he said,
``because we're just not ready as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper, now a key component, practiced for just the second time
and was pulled off the court 20 minutes earlier than his teammates
because Jackson is concerned about his conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to be careful with him right now,'' he said. ``I
want to see Ron get in shape. If he gets in some kind of shape,
then we can cover our butts (at shooting guard) for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Awaiting the call: Fox, a starting small forward for most of his
pro career, welcomes the chance to start at off-guard Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think six years of starting in this league gave me enough
experience to step back in there and fill the void of Kobe,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``one of us, especially myself or Harp or the other guys who
have eight years and above are going to fill his youthful legs and
his explosiveness. I'd like to think that we can think the game as
well or even maybe better with the years of experience we have. You
fill the void by committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Trimming down: The loss of Bryant and Travis Knight (ankle, 3-4
weeks) might simplify the Lakers' roster reduction efforts.
</P>
<P>
   If both are placed on the injured list, Jackson will have to
waive just five players to get down to the maximum 12. The likely
five are free-agent pickups Andy Panko, Donald Williams, Gerald
Jordan and Stephen Smith, plus second-round draft choice John
Celestand.
</P>
<P>
   In that scenario, aging big men Benoit Benjamin and John Salley
both make the opening-day roster. Benjamin seems to have cemented a
position as Shaquille O'Neal's primary backup. Salley is needed to
provide depth at power forward, especially in Knight's absence.
</P>
<P>
   Psychology 101: Jackson had an interesting response when
addressing the challenge of getting his players to focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all autistic in some form or fashion _ I don't mean to
say that as a snide remark toward a certain population in our
society _ but they have a limitation of their attention span, a lot
of it probably due to too much rap music going in their ears and
coming out of their being. So they need to get a focal point that
lasts longer than a TV commercial or one short, 15-second span.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 2234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8716 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SOX-MARTINEZ-BOS &LR;      10-15 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SOX-MARTINEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ POISED FOR ULTIMATE TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   His team's season was down to a death rattle, his back was in
slightly worse shape, his vintage stuff was a dusty memory, and his
durability was a piece of Waterford crystal spinning on the edge of
a shelf.
</P>
<P>
   And he betrayed none of this, not the slightest awareness of
these mortal curses, not a clue that this madhouse of misery was
about to collapse on top of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not an ounce of pressure on his face,'' said Red Sox pitching
coach Joe Kerrigan. ``Not an ounce of pressure in his body. He was
just having fun out there.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why Pedro Martinez crossed the threshold Monday night,
leaving behind the realm of mere master and entering the rarefied
zone of mythic figure.
</P>
<P>
   With his playoff salvage mission in Cleveland _ in which he
eliminated the Indians and rescued the Red Sox with six implausible
innings of no-hit relief at a time when he more belonged in
traction than on the mound at hostile Jacobs Field _ Martinez
gained a place in the pantheon. It's one his opponent Saturday,
Roger Clemens, never achieved despite 13 years of statistical
marvels in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   That is what a postseason crucible can do for you. Or to you.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens's Boston legacy has a huge void. He is defined as much
by what he didn't do here as by what he did. Even his most fabled
season _ that 24-4 epic in 1986 _ became a textbook case of
heartbreak. True, he won Game 7 of the American League Championship
Series against the Angels, but the heroics of that enterprise
belonged to Dave Henderson. And he left the infamous Game 6 of the
World Series against the Mets _ under murky circumstances, no less:
was the decision his or manager John McNamara's? _ thus exposing
the Red Sox to the treachery of Bill Buckner's glove.
</P>
<P>
   In nine postseason starts for Boston, Clemens won once.
</P>
<P>
   In two postseason starts and one relief appearance for Boston,
Martinez has won twice.
</P>
<P>
   His playoff debut at the end of his first year here, 1998, was
an 11-3 rout of the Indians that ended a skid of 13 consecutive Red
Sox postseason losses, all of which Clemens was around for, if not
a party to.
</P>
<P>
   And in the deciding Division Series game Monday, four days after
he had been forced to leave his Game 1 start with a strained muscle
in the middle of his back that was supposed to render him useless
until the millennium, Martinez pushed the envelope of heroism. With
the Sox pitching in tatters, the Indians owning an 8-7 lead and
seeming as if they were just starting to flex their muscles,
Martinez was a one-man cavalry charge. He stifled Cleveland, giving
Boston breathing room for a 12-8 victory and a date in the ALCS
against the accursed Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it is a quirk of the rotation or destiny, Game 3
Saturday at Fenway Park brings us Clemens-Martinez,
point-counterpoint.
</P>
<P>
   It is a seemingly can't-lose situation for Martinez, whose
health remains questionable but whose credentials cannot be denied
after Monday's transcendent performance. As improbable as it may
seem, he took numbers that rivaled Clemens's best _ a 23-4 regular
season _ and dwarfed them with one October outing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't surprise myself, but I was more impressed with the
time I stayed out there,'' Martinez said Friday upon reflection.
``I stayed there for four innings and then I said, `Well, I feel a
little bit tight but I am going to keep going and see how long I
last.' Then all of a sudden, I was there for six innings, and that
impressed me more than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the closest he will come to self-congratulation, and
perhaps that is his greatest gift: utter unflappability in showcase
situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you look at his record,'' said manager Jimy
Williams, ``every time he pitches, it is a big moment. That is his
whole mindset: Be prepared to pitch that game and help his team
win.''
</P>
<P>
   So what if it's the All-Star Game on his home turf, a worldwide
television audience waiting to see what's so special about this
skinny Dominican righthander _ and watching him win the game MVP
award with five strikeouts in two innings?
</P>
<P>
   So what if it's a crucial September stretch-drive game at Yankee
Stadium, with a wild card in the balance and a clearly superior
team in the opposing dugout _ a team that flails for one hit and 17
strikeouts as the upstart Sox make an indelible statement of
credibility?
</P>
<P>
   So what if it's a survival game for which he was supposed to
have called in sick?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he ever lets a situation get bigger than he can
handle,'' said catcher Jason Varitek.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, that is the case Saturday. Let others ponder the
cosmic implications of this duel of the decade _ and oh, by the
way, the Red Sox' 2-0 deficit in this best-of-seven series.
Martinez is having none of it, at least not for public consumption.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't help what is going on out there,'' he said. ``I can
only control what I do with the ball on the mound. So I don't focus
on those things. I let that happen out there. I let the fans go
crazy in the stands and I do my thing. I am not going to change my
game because there is more pressure or less pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez won't acknowledge the ramifications, but Clemens will.
He volunteered to pitch the Yankees' potential Division Series
clincher in his home state, Texas _ and his seven shutout innings
there gave him as many wins in 10 postseason appearances as
Martinez has in three. After that, Clemens went to manager Joe
Torre and said he didn't care which ALCS assignment he drew.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right,'' said Torre. ``You got Saturday against Pedro.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful,'' Clemens responded. He got up and left, leaving
Torre to shake his head, undoubtedly questioning his veteran's
sanity.
</P>
<P>
   Spying his staff mates outside the manager's door, Clemens
informed them, ``I've already got the long straw. You guys are
good. Go in there, you've got nothing to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   That mentality is the secret weapon that has enabled Martinez to
surpass Clemens in Boston lore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
