<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICAL CROSSROADS FOR USC, NOTRE DAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ USC coach Paul Hackett and Notre Dame coach
Bob Davie could be expected to say the same things when discussing
what is billed as the greatest intersectional rivalry in college
football.
</P>
<P>
   But their remarks were almost indistinguishable on another topic
this week. See if you can match up these comments with the correct
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got enough pressure on me right now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have more criticism from myself than there is from the
outside. A fan from the outside is able to say whatever they want
to say.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, guess who said what? Give up? The first remark came from
Davie, and the second from Hackett. But either coach could have
said them, considering the Trojans are 3-2 and the Irish 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the teams' records make today's 11:30 a.m. game
almost more important, as a victory over your archrival can
sometimes turn a season around, or at least make the alumni less
lethal.
</P>
<P>
   Criticism aside, there is a sense of urgency from both teams
that today is a good launching point to reclaim their preseason
optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to get going now,'' USC wide receiver Kareem Kelly
said. ``This game separates the men from the children right here.''
</P>
<P>
   Davie was doing his fair share of re-analyzing the Irish's mixed
start this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of us realized there was a chance we could
struggle early in the season,'' he said. ``I'm not totally shocked
by what our record is. What's frustrating is how we had an
opportunity to win those games we didn't win. That's what haunts
you.''
</P>
<P>
   There's been some tinkering with the personnel for both teams.
</P>
<P>
   USC's offensive line _ long a source of derision _ will sport a
new look, thanks to injuries. Left tackle Trevor Roberts will start
ahead of Brent McCaffrey, who has a sore ankle but is expected to
play. Freshman Zach Wilson will start at right guard with Jason
Grain out a month with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Denmon, out two weeks with sore knees, will start, and
Faasea Mailo will start his third straight game at left guard,
although Donta Kendrick is nearly recovered from an ankle injury
and will play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just when I think we're making progress, we slide back because
we don't have the same people in there we had two days earlier,''
Hackett said. ``We worked hard at paring the running game now and
adjusting it to what we think will work best against Notre Dame.''
</P>
<P>
   Davie has decided to bench kicker Jim Sanson, who missed three
field goals against USC in 1997, and start sophomore David Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett has also done an about-face in another area. He decided
to hold a one hour walk-through in Notre Dame Stadium on Friday.
Last week, the Trojans abandoned the walk-through the day before
playing Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notre Dame Stadium creates an atmosphere that is what college
football is about,'' Hackett said. ``If that atmosphere intimidates
you or makes you nervous, then you're not ready to play yet. It's
part of the process of learning to be a champion. If you can't go
to Notre Dame and play well, you can't expect to be a contender.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
