<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S REESE MAKES THE MOST OF OPPORTUNITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA true freshman linebacker Marcus Reese thought
his playing time would disappear when the two-game disabled-parking
suspensions ended and the starting linebackers returned.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Reese is on the field more than ever, and he's rapidly
becoming one of UCLA's best players _ solid against the run and
indispensable against the pass, both as a blitzer and cover man.
</P>
<P>
   Last week against Oregon, for example, he played 66 percent of
the defensive snaps, he intercepted a pass, he recovered a fumble,
and he tied for the team lead with six tackles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought when the (suspended) players came back, I'd be out
of the picture,'' Reese said as he prepared for today's game
against Cal at the Rose Bowl. ``I'm pretty surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins aren't. Reese was one of the top linebackers in the
nation last year at San Jose's Oak Grove High School, which
produced former Bruins tight end Mike Grieb. Reese has superb
instincts, he's stronger than he looks at 215 pounds, and he's
better conditioned than most true freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very physical, and he'll hit you,'' Bruins coach Bob
Toledo said. ``We always said he'd play as a true freshman. He was
the No. 1 linebacker recruit in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   For his prep success, for his dedication, conditioning and
impact at UCLA, Reese credits former Oak Grove teammate Andre
Carter, who plays defensive end for Cal and leads the Pacific-10 in
sacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the reason I'm here,'' Reese said. ``When I was a
sophomore (and Carter was a senior), I was real small. Andre helped
get my lifting technique down. I trained with him and ran with him.
Andre was like my big brother. When I wanted to chase girls, he
told me no, I had to concentrate on football and school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andre always called me `Little Andre.' I was the next
All-American. My junior year, people called me the next Andre, the
next great defensive player from Oak Grove. But I just wanted to be
Marcus.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for Reese to carve a niche in Westwood. When
UCLA broke training camp, Reese was the second-string weakside
linebacker. He made four tackles in the opener against Boise State,
then led the Bruins with nine at Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   The suspensions ended, but Reese did not falter. Each week, he
got more comfortable with the system. Each game, he made something
happen. Now, halfway through the season, he's UCLA's fifth-leading
tackler despite playing fewer snaps than players ranked above him.
</P>
<P>
   And because of his speed, Reese is integral to the pass defense.
When UCLA uses its nickel (five defensive backs) and dime (six)
coverages, Reese plays and starter Ryan Nece sits.
</P>
<P>
   That could be a combustible situation _ rookie playing ahead of
veteran _ but Reese and Nece have become friends. In fact, during
training camp, Nece treated Reese to burgers at In-n-Out. Shy and
anxious, Reese wondered how he could play linebacker at 215 pounds.
Nece, all of 214, told him to play smart and fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people say, `You guys must compete,' but in person
there's no competition,'' Reese said. ``I'm still trying to learn
the stuff, and I always ask Ryan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 2237EDT &QL; 
