<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S PAUS WILL BE TARGET FOR CAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA has reason to fear for quarterback Cory Paus'
health this afternoon in the Rose Bowl, and he'll be wearing No.97
in white.
</P>
<P>
   Cal junior end Andre Carter is the closest thing the Pacific-10
has to a dominant defensive lineman _ stronger than his 250 pounds,
yet fast as a linebacker. He leads the league in sacks (seven) and
tackles-for-loss (13).
</P>
<P>
   But stopping Carter does not guarantee stopping the Bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the best defensive team we will have faced this
year,'' Bruins coach Bob Toledo said. ``They have an excellent
front seven.... They can devastate you with their pass rush.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bears, who held Nebraska's mighty running game to 114 yards,
have several NFL prospects. Linebacker Sekou Sanyika is a preseason
All-American. Cornerback Deltha O'Neal is one of the league's most
versatile players and leads the conference with four interceptions.
Jacob Waasdorp, of Quartz Hill, and Jeremiah Parker form the
Pac-10's best tackle tandem.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all good,'' UCLA offensive tackle Bryce Bohlander
said. ``They could be the best in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Countermeasures: Protecting Paus will be difficult, but the
Bruins have several options.
</P>
<P>
   They can deploy extra tight ends to protect the outside rushing
lanes. Or they can use a blocking technique known as chipping, in
which running backs hit the rushers before starting their pass
patterns.
</P>
<P>
   But the most effective countermeasure may be Paus' mobility.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (the quarterback) always lands in the same place, they'll
get you,'' Toledo said. ``Part of it is moving the pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   Which way did they go? One of Cal's most effective pass-rushing
techniques is the end-tackle exchange: The defensive tackle breaks
to the outside while the end moves inside, forming an X. The Bears'
speed makes blocking the exchanges difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've worked against it a lot in practice, and we've done
well,'' Bohlander said. ``But they do it a lot, and their personnel
is really good. So we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Under lock and key: Asked to name the key to victory, Toledo
pointed to the front lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be able to run the ball and protect our passer,
and our (defensive) people have to do a good job stopping the run
and putting pressure on (Cal quarterback Kyle) Boller.''
</P>
<P>
   Attack the quarterback: Asked if he would try to exploit
Boller's inexperience _ he's a true freshman making his fourth
start _ Toledo didn't hesitate: ``Absolutely, and you can write
it.''
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: The Bruins have won 13 consecutive
regular-season home games.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two games, UCLA receiver Danny Farmer has caught 13
passes for 344 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins kicker Chris Griffith has made 10 of 13 field goals.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA has scored 45 points following opponent turnovers, while
opponents have scored 36 points off UCLA mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Something has to give: Cal is last in the league in offense (236
yards per game), while UCLA is last in defense (451).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 2240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
