<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YANKEES-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE YANKEES CAN AFFORD A MOMENT OF LAUGHTER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Allen Watson entered Game 2 in the eighth inning to
face Lou Merloni and was promptly ordered to walk him
intentionally. It was the only batter Watson faced before manager
Joe Torre replaced him.
</P>
<P>
   As Torre reached for the ball with a look of disgust on his
face, he said to Watson: ``I got to get you out of here. You're too
wild. You've got to stop walking guys.''
</P>
<P>
   And Watson burst out laughing, in perhaps the only light-hearted
moment of that tense half-inning that was integral to the Yankees'
3-2 victory. Jimy Williams, the manager of the Red Sox, made five
personnel changes in the inning, while Torre made four.
</P>
<P>
   David Cone, the Yankee pitcher, said, ``I couldn't keep up.''
</P>
<P>
   After all the pinch-hitters and pinch-runners had been inserted,
after Torre had the pitcher he wanted on the mound, the Red Sox had
the bases loaded and one out, and Boston's Butch Huskey was facing
Ramiro Mendoza. It was Mendoza's first appearance in 13 days.
</P>
<P>
   Torre had the Yankees' infielders play back, looking for a
double play off Mendoza's hard-sinking fastball, which often
creates ground balls. But Mendoza had other intentions: the last
time he faced Huskey, in September, Huskey seemed to be
anticipating his fastball, so this time Mendoza threw him changeups
and struck him out. Then Jose Offerman flied out to center field to
end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Mendoza's teammates mentioned later how remarkable it
was that he had such great control despite his long layoff. They
weren't surprised at how calm he was, however; Cone surmised that
it might be the heritage Mendoza shares with Mariano Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's in the water in Panama,'' Cone said. ``He
and Mariano, they're both expressionless when they're out there,
unflappable.''
</P>
<P>
   Posada Waits His Turn
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada was saying all the right things after Joe Girardi
started ahead of him at catcher in Game 2. Posada said that he
could understand, that Cone is just more comfortable with Girardi,
and that he would have made the same decision if he were the
manager.
</P>
<P>
   But saying all the right things doesn't necessarily translate
into being happy with the decision. ``You want to play,'' said
Posada. ``You want to go out there and help the team win. I want to
be the guy. It doesn't get any better than this, playoff time.
We're playing for our lives, for the World Series, and you want to
be out there, there's no doubt. I get more nervous on the bench
than when I'm playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Posada's time as the full-time, front-line catcher will probably
come next year. Girardi is expected to depart as a free agent _
many executives in baseball believe he is headed to the Chicago
Cubs _ and Posada will get a chance to play every day for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   No More the Hero
</P>
<P>
   Lou Merloni is a native of Framingham, Mass., and he admitted
that he knows the culture of the Red Sox and their fans better than
his teammates do, because he has lived in both worlds. He tried to
explain why Roger Clemens will be booed so incessantly when he
opposes Pedro Martinez in Game 3 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though there were things that went on between him and
management, the bottom line to the fans is that he left,'' said
Merloni. ``When he first left and came back with Toronto, they
called him a traitor. You hardly see a great hero return to Boston
to cheers. Look at what they do to Wade Boggs with all that he did
in Boston. That's just the way it is around here.''
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old Merloni said that he was a big Clemens fan, but
when he got older, he studied Clemens more as a pitcher and not as
a hero. If it were up to Merloni, Clemens would not be berated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't boo him,'' said Clemens. ``Not after all he did
while he was in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fans definitely will. _ JACK CURRY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Through the Roof
</P>
<P>
   How much interest is there in the Martinez-Clemens matchup? The
Boston Herald reported that four tickets for Game 3 sold for
$12,100 on E-Bay, the auction Web site. When Boston manager Jimy
Williams was asked about this huge amount for an ALCS game, he
said: ``I think you probably you should comment on that yourself. I
just leave it at that.'' _ JACK CURRY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
