<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATCHUP FOR THE AGES: PEDRO AGAINST ROGER AT FENWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It has already given us two riveting nights of
Masterpiece Theater, though judging by the face of Red Sox Nation _
dark circles under sleep-deprived eyes, anxiety creasing every
forehead _ it has had a horror-movie feel, too. The Beast from the
Bronx having its way with the Olde Towne Team.
</P>
<P>
   And now the first postseason confrontation between those ancient
rivals, the Boston Red Sox and New York Yankees, which opened with
two exquisitely played games in the Bronx, each won by a single run
by the Yankees, switches to Fenway Park Saturday afternoon with
perhaps the most anticipated pitching matchup ever seen on Yawkey
Way.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens, returning in New York pinstripes in search of the
World Series ring that eluded him through 13 years in Boston in
which he won more games (192) than any Red Sox pitcher except
turn-of-the-century Cy Young, is facing Pedro Martinez, who in two
short years in Boston has won accolades here once reserved
exclusively for the Rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox manager Jimy Williams was asked to consider the
magnitude of this pitching pairing. He responded in his folksy
style that has come to be known as Jimywocky.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as tomorrow's game, I think the circuit-breaker for
that electric company, for the great pad in the sky, they might be
challenged,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The diminutive Martinez, the first Dominican-born star ever to
play for the Sox, may already have eclipsed Clemens, the
larger-than-life Texan, in the affection of Red Sox fans.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, at age 36 a lion in winter who only on occasion this
season has flashed the brilliance of a future Hall of Famer, always
was admired in when he was in Boston. But his clashes with the Red
Sox front office and stormy departure because of a contract dispute
three years ago left a sour taste.
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old Martinez, who in two Octobers already has won as
many postseason games (two) as Clemens has in a decade and a half,
is loved. No Never more so than Monday night, when he came out of
the bullpen in Cleveland with a sore back _ Everyman's affliction _
and pitched six hitless innings to win the deciding game of the
Division Series against the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Martinez is being asked to rescue the Red Sox yet again.
The Yankees, who have won 35 American League pennants and 24 World
Series titles, are two wins away from returning to the World Series
for the third time in the last four years. They have won 12
consecutive postseason games, matching the record set by their
illustrious predecessors 67 years ago, a team that included Babe
Ruth (another former Red Sox pitcher) and Lou Gehrig.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who won the first game of the series on Bernie
Williams's home run off Sox reliever Rod Beck in the 10th inning
Wednesday night, beat Martinez's older brother, Ramon, 3-2, in the
second game Thursday. Ramon the Elder pitched beautifully, allowing
just six hits in 6 2/3 innings, but the Sox bullpen faltered in the
seventh inning, when the Yankees scored twice to overcome Nomar
Garciaparra's two-run home run. Sox hitters, 1 for 13 with runners
in scoring position, left the bases loaded in the eighth inning and
runners on first and third in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Red Sox, who have taken leads into the late innings of
each of the first two games only to lose, are two defeats away from
winter, and a fin de siecle realization that they will enter the
new millennium with their streak intact of no World Series titles
since 1918.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure all falls on Pedro, who on Sept. 10 in Yankee
Stadium may have pitched the best game ever pitched against the
Yankees. He allowed just one hit, a second-inning home run by Chili
Davis, did not walk a batter, and struck out 17, the most whiffs
ever recorded against the Bombers. By the end of that night,
Yankees fans were on their feet, cheering for him.
</P>
<P>
   How will he respond to that pressure?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' he said, ``I just lay myself in God's hands and let it
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``My body might be beat, my arm might be beat, but my heart is
out there and my mind and my love for the game and respect for the
fans, it is out there.''
</P>
<P>
   But Martinez also stressed that this game isn't just Roger and
Me.
</P>
<P>
   ``As capable as I am of beating any team, I believe my team is
good to do it, too,'' he said. ``You guys got to start having some
respect for my teammates. They are good. They are really good, and
if you don't believe it, you can analyze where you are right now
and it wasn't just one single man, it wasn't me with my 23 (wins),
no. I did it because they were behind me, and I think you guys have
to give them some credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox CEO John Harrington said Friday that tickets for the
game may be the most sought-after ticket ever for a Red Sox game.
On eBay, an Internet auction site, one buyer reportedly paid
$12,100 for four box seats.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens said Friday that when Yankees manager Joe Torre was
trying to decide upon his postseason pitching assignments, he
called the Yankees pitchers into his office.
</P>
<P>
   ``They called us in one by one like drawing straws, I guess,''
Clemens said, ``and (Torre) was hemming and hawing back and forth.
I told him again, `Skip, whatever slot you want me in, you put me
in, doesn't make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``So he said, `All right, you got Saturday against Pedro.' I
said, `Beautiful.' I got up and left.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he was shaking his head at me as I walked out the door.
The rest of the guys are standing outside the door waiting. I said,
`I've already got the long straw. You guys are good. Go in there,
you've got nothing to lose.' ''
</P>
<P>
   When Clemens was introduced here at the All-Star Game in July as
one of the 100 best players of the century, he wore a Yankees cap
and was loudly booed. Even though he said he expects some Sox fans
to be cheering for him ``undercover,'' Torre knows better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when they introduced Pedro in Yankee Stadium they
booed him a little bit,'' Torre said. ``I said to Roger, who
happened to be sitting next to me, `You will do better than that.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think that is what the goosebumps are going to be about
tomorrow. It is going to be respect. There is going to be screaming
and yelling just like every time we play here, except magnified,
because of postseason and what it means. It is going to be a heck
of a show.''
</P>
</TEXT>
