<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOW JONES INDUSTRIALS DROP ON NEW FEARS OF INFLATION
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average and other stock market gauges
plunged after an inflation report showed the biggest monthly
increase in nine years in prices at the producer level and Alan
Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve, alarmed investors
by warning that the stock market might be more risky than many
people now believe.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 266.90 points, to
10,019.71. The Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks fared even
worse than the Dow, dropping 2.81 percent, to 1,247.41, The Nasdaq
composite index fell 2.67 percent, or 75 points, to 2,731.83.
Long-term interest rates have been rising lately, although the
yield on the 30-year Treasury bond declined to 6.26 percent Friday
as investors sought alternatives to stocks.
</P>
<P>
   PAYING A CALL ON THE WEST BANK
</P>
<P>
   Commerce Secretary William Daley, leading a delegation of
American executives in the first U.S. Department of Commerce
business mission to the Middle East to include the West Bank, sees
encouraging signs.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MORE PLANES ARE HEADING TO CANADA
</P>
<P>
   An open skies agreement signed in February 1995 has proved to be
a boon to travel between the United States and Canada. Canada now
matches Britain as the favored destination for Americans. Last
year, about 8.4 million Americans boarded planes for each country.
</P>
<P>
   VACCINE MAKER WITHDRAWS PRODUCT
</P>
<P>
   American Home Products, which makes the only licensed vaccine to
prevent the most common cause of severe diarrhea in infants and
children, is withdrawing the vaccine from the market because of
concerns over possible side effects.
</P>
<P>
   APPLE BACKS OFF PRICE INCREASE
</P>
<P>
   Apple Computer backed off from a decision to raise prices
retroactively on some computers that customers already had ordered
and paid for. It did so after receiving many customer complaints.
The turnaround came after the matter threatened to blemish an
otherwise positive public image for Apple, which has delivered a
string of popular new computers and strong financial results in the
last year.
</P>
<P>
   B SKY B WEIGHS KIRCH GROUP STAKE
</P>
<P>
   British Sky Broadcasting Group is in talks to buy a minority
stake in the Kirch Group media company of Germany and might
purchase part of Deutsche Telekom's cable business, according to
Rupert Murdoch. But he denied speculation that B Sky B, which is 40
percent owned by Murdoch's company, News Corp., might buy or merge
with Canal Plus, the big French pay-per-view company.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFITS DECLINE 35 PERCENT AT CATERPILLAR
</P>
<P>
   Caterpillar said a continued slump in heavy machinery sales
lowered its third-quarter earnings by 35 percent. The company
earned $219 million, or 61 cents a share, compared with $336
million, or 92 cents a share, in the corresponding quarter last
year. The results were a penny over the expectations of Wall Street
analysts.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MBNA TO BUY CREDIT CARD PORTFOLIO
</P>
<P>
   MBNA Corp. has agreed to buy the $1.5 billion credit card
portfolio of Suntrust Banks, extending a string of acquisitions of
credit card businesses that lack the size to compete. Atlanta-based
Suntrust has 1.4 million customer cards.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BRAZILIAN OIL GIANT GOES AMERICAN
</P>
<P>
   Petrobras, Brazil's big oil company, reduced shareholders'
equity by about $2.4 billion as it shifted its accounting practices
to U.S. standards in preparation for listing its shares in New
York.
</P>
</TEXT>
