<SLUG> BC-GORE-AD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AD CAMPAIGN: GORE ON TREATY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a new 60-second commercial made in the wee hours of Oct.
14 by Vice President Al Gore. Gore says he conceived the idea for
the commercial as he received word during a flight to Seattle that
the Senate had rejected the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty _ the
first major treaty the Senate has rejected since the Treaty of
Versailles setting up the League of Nations in 1920. This is the
first commercial of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: Century Media Group.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN: The commercial opens not with a picture of Gore
but with two famous black-and-white still pictures of President
John F. Kennedy. It then cuts to Gore, wearing a coat and tie and
speaking directly into the camera. As he talks about nuclear arms,
the Internet headlines about the Senate vote and a live shot of a
rocket lifting off are shown. Later, it shows Gore in his Senate
days during arms-control talks with Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev
and George Shultz, who was secretary of state under President
Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY: Gore is correct that the chairmen of the Joint Chiefs
of Staff have supported the test ban treaty, and they are the
senior responsible officers. Other defense experts have overtly
opposed it, including Dick Cheney, who was secretary of defense
under President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   SCORECARD: Gore wants to convey that he is well-versed in a
vital issue to which he has had a longtime commitment. After he was
first elected to Congress in 1976, he schooled himself in arms
control. The subliminal message is that his opponents have no
comparable experience.
</P>
<P>
   Still, polls have showed that voters believe Gore lacks the
elusive quality called leadership. The commercial is meant to
counter that impression. Gore's voice is soft, and the commercial
aims for restraint _ a rocket lifting off rather than a
mushroom-clouded screen of destruction. This restraint is meant to
convey leadership as well as contrast with what he has
characterized as the Republicans' recklessness.
</P>
<P>
   Because Gore made public the story of how he penned the ad
himself, he also wants voters to see him as passionate about a
subject _ they perceive him as too cautious in general _ and as
someone who is taking direct control of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether this is a topic that will resonate with
voters. While polls show voters support arms control, they do not
call it as urgent a priority as domestic issues like education.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
