<SLUG> BC-VIRUS-DISASTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TO SEEK DISASTER FUNDS IN VIRUS OUTBREAK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City plans to ask the federal government to
reimburse it for the cost of battling a viral outbreak, city
officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The city's Office of Emergency Management will request a
presidential disaster declaration from the Federal Emergency
Management Agency, seeking reimbursement for roughly $10 million
that it spent in recent weeks to contain an outbreak of the West
Nile-like virus, which began in August, said Jerome M. Hauer,
director of the emergency management unit. The request, which was
still being drafted Friday, is likely to be submitted Monday, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Hauer said costs to contain the virus, which has killed six
people and sickened 54 in the New York region since late July,
mostly centered around mosquito control. West Nile virus and St.
Louis encephalitis _ the original diagnosis by the Federal Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention in the outbreak _ are carried by
mosquitoes that bite infected birds and then go on to infect
humans.
</P>
<P>
   The city spent several days spraying the city with malathion and
other insecticides and handed out thousands of cans of bug spray,
cornering the country's supply at one point. Other costs included
large blocks of overtime for city workers, Hauer said.
</P>
<P>
   While it is not unusual for the city to make the request to FEMA
_ it has done so almost every time there has been a bad snow storm
or northeaster _ this will be the first time it has done so for a
public health threat, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The West Nile-like virus that has been found in the New York
City area has also been discovered in a dead bird 150 miles north
of Manhattan, State Health Department officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The virus was found in a dead crow collected earlier this month
in the Saratoga County village of Ballston Spa, officials said, and
in a cuckoo found at the United States Military Academy at West
Point, 40 miles north of Manhattan. No human encephalitis cases
have been reported in those areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 2254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
