<HEADLINE>
SATURN'S NEW WAGON A COOL RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Some really fine, midsize station wagons have crossed
my path recently. Quick, good-handling, luxurious cars with plenty
of room and lots of character, they all have had two things in
common:
</P>
<P>
   They are European and they cost plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Now, along comes Saturn to throw a monkey wrench into my neat
little world view. Here's the square-back version of its L-Series
cars, the first all-new products from the corporation since it
started up a decade ago and its first midsize cars ever.
</P>
<P>
   And guess what? The upscale wagon I drove, with the catchy name
LW2, is quick, good-handling and luxurious with plenty of room and,
well, a fair amount of character. Can't have everything. Especially
when a fully loaded, leather-lined, top-of-the-heap LW2 costs about
as much as the Euro wagons' base models.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, it's made in Tennessee, although with a bit of European
DNA thrown into the mix. The basic platform is from the Opel
Vectra, a European GM product, which was lengthened and then
transformed with Saturn's signature space-frame construction and
plastic lower-body panels.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about pleasant surprises. No offense intended, Saturn, but
I didn't really expect the LW2 to be such a cool ride. The compact
S-series cars are good machines, with proven reliability and
durability, but without much in the way of panache.
</P>
<P>
   When Saturn first hit the market, it was as a remarkable new
kind of automaker organized by General Motors as a clean-slate
attempt to beat the imports head on.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the original compacts were updated and improved,
but the marketplace was changing and the demand for little cars was
fading. Some of the original warts, such as noisy engines and
cramped interiors, were also taking their toll.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the L-Series arrives as Saturn's first foray into a new
line of cars. Too bad the corporation waited so long to expand, but
if the LW2 is a fair example of the breed, Saturn should regain its
luster.
</P>
<P>
   Saturn has a strong following of loyal customers, an automotive
Up With People! that recently gathered by the thousands at the
corporation's Spring Hill, Tenn., for group hugs and camp songs.
</P>
<P>
   The L-Series gives them somewhere to go once they outgrow their
compact Saturns.
</P>
<P>
   The uptown tester was equipped with a strong V-6, actually a
detuned version of the 200-horse engine found in the Cadillac
Catera. The engine is made in GM's engine factory at Ellesmere
Port, England.
</P>
<P>
   German chassis, British engine, yes it's true the new Saturn is
no longer a 100 percent U.S. product, as the compacts are.
</P>
<P>
   The engine is smooth and powerful, with a muscular feel and a
subtle growl under acceleration. Coupled with a good automatic
transmission, the engine performed with flexibility, tame around
town, aggressive on the open road.
</P>
<P>
   Base engine for the wagon is a 2.2-liter twin-cam four, a newly
minted engine that's expected to be used in other GM cars. I didn't
drive this version _ which has the equally catchy name LW1 _ but
from what I've read and heard, the new four is a step up from the
one in the S-series cars.
</P>
<P>
   Stick shift is available only with the four and only in the
sedan.
</P>
<P>
   The four-wheel disc brakes work well, but anti-lock is optional.
It should be standard, just like most other GM cars.
</P>
<P>
   The styling of the wagon is simple and purposeful, with clean
lines and a front end that carries over the Saturn theme. I favor
the look of the wagon over the sedan, which has a fussy rear-end
treatment. The wagon's rear end looks simple and uncluttered.
</P>
<P>
   The interior on the tester included optional leather seating at
$1,095, an upgraded stereo for $220 and six-way power driver's seat
at $325, the only extras added on to the price of the V-6 model. I
found the interior roomy, even for an extra-tall driver and his
extra-tall back-seat offspring. The ride was quiet and rattle-free.
</P>
<P>
   The dashboard, console and doors are very straightforward, even
spare, which might be a fault to those used to lavish appoints.
However, I thought it was clean, functional and unpretentious.
</P>
<P>
   The new Saturns are as aggressively priced as the compacts, with
the base sedan starting at $15,000 and the base wagon at $18,835.
The wagon model driven here was about as expensive as they get.
</P>
<P>
   I've heard some reports that Saturn has plenty of advance orders
for L-series cars, and with good reason. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Vehicle type: Five passenger, four-door station wagon, front-wheel
drive. &QL; 
Base price: $21,360. &QL; 
Price as tested: $23,440. &QL; 
Engine: 3-liter V-6, 182 hp at 5,600 rpm, 190 lb-ft of torque at
3,600 rpm. &QL; 
Transmission: &QL; 
4-speed automatic. &QL; 
Curb weight: &QL; 
3,230 pounds. &QL; 
Wheelbase:  &QL; 
270.5 inches. &QL; 
EPA mileage: &QL; 
20 city, 26 highway. &QL; 
_Good performance. &QL; 
_Quality feel. &QL; 
_Roomy interior. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
_Anti-lock brakes optional. &QL; 
Generic dashboard. &QL; 
_Boring name. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 2257EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991015.0392 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8827 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-IRENE16-COX     10-15 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRENE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Irene unloads flooding in Florida
 &HT;    By Pat Moore, Sally Swartz
 &HT;    and Thomas R. Collins
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ As Hurricane Irene plowed across South
Florida with 80 mph wind gusts and up to 10 inches of rain Friday,
Treasure Coast officials expected to find flooded roads and perhaps
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be quite a rainfall producer,'' said Randy
Lascody, senior forecaster at the National Weather Service in
Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
   But the South Florida Water Management District late Friday
forecast lower amounts of rain than meteorologists originally
predicted. They expected the Treasure Coast to get about 2 inches
of rain and most of Palm Beach County, 4 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Irene, a Category 1 hurricane, was expected to weaken to a
tropical storm as it moved slowly north overnight, bringing wind
gusts of 50 to 60 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the center gets to the north during the day Saturday, winds
will switch to the west and southwest and will diminish,'' Lascody
said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin County Red Cross officials opened one shelter at the
First United Methodist Church. St. Lucie County officials opened
shelters at Westwood High School in Fort Pierce and Port St. Lucie
Community Center. The Community Center, usually designated for
people with medical problems or other special needs, will serve any
resident who needs shelter, St. Lucie County Public Safety Director
Jack Southard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're opening them for anyone who has special needs or needs
to evacuate their houses because of localized flooding or other
problems,'' Southard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing we're concerned about is flooding,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   MARTIN ROAD CREWS GET JUMP
</P>
<P>
   After the storm came ashore Friday afternoon, the three major
South Florida airports closed and power losses mounted.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Power &AMP; Light Co. reported more than 400,000 customers
lost electricity in Miami-Dade, Broward and Palm Beach counties by
nightfall.
</P>
<P>
   Even the National Hurricane Center had to switch to backup
generators when the power went off, blacking out many computer
screens.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeb Bush asked President Clinton to declare a state of
emergency in Florida, hoping to unleash federal dollars and
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance Commissioner Bill Nelson said people with damaged
homes should contact their flood insurance agency, and said those
with no flood insurance may be eligible for federal aid; a hotline
number has been created: (800) 22-STORM.
</P>
<P>
   St. Lucie County law enforcement and Red Cross and hospital
officials gathered late Friday at the county's emergency operations
center preparing to respond to any emergency, Emergency Management
Director Keith Holman said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin County road crews got a jump on the storm Thursday by
placing pumps at strategic places that typically flood during wet
weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest threat is going to be the rain. The ground is
already saturated,'' the Weather Service's Lascordy said. ``If we
get as much rain as they're predicting in that short a period, some
roads will be impassable and some residences will experience
flooding.''
</P>
<P>
   William Larsson, who lives in the low-lying, frequently flooded
St. Lucie area in Martin County, said water in the St. Lucie River
behind his home rose about an inch every hour Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Port St. Lucie Public Works Director Larry Thacker said the city
can handle the 7 to 10 inches of rain forecasters are projecting
but said motorists should expect some intersections to be under
water temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   EROSION TAKES AWAY BEACH
</P>
<P>
   The city has lowered the level of its canals and waterways by
several inches in anticipation of Saturday's deluge. That water is
released to the St. Lucie River and ultimately makes its way to the
ocean, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Water managers continued to monitor conditions downstream of the
St. Lucie Lock late Friday to ensure waterfront residents aren't
flooded by Irene's rains.
</P>
<P>
   The lock gates were all open to release moderate amounts of
local runoff from area farms and residences into the St. Lucie
Canal and from the canal into the St. Lucie River, water district
spokesman Paul Millar said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers stood by its plan to stop
releasing fresh water from Lake Okeechobee until Irene passed. Then
lake water will be dumped into the St. Lucie River on Florida's
east coast and the Caloosahatchee River to the west.
</P>
<P>
   At Martin County beaches Friday, some waterfront residents
boarded up their homes and one who lives just north of the Bathtub
Beach built a makeshift seawall, lifeguard Mike Diapoules said. At
Stuart Beach, water washed under the boardwalks at high tide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a constant drizzle that stings when it hits you, and
the ocean is taking away the beach again,'' said lifeguard Dan
Naughton.
</P>
<P>
   85 MPH WIND GUSTS IN MIAMI
</P>
<P>
   Hobe Sound Beach lifeguard Bob Dixon said tourists crowded into
the covered picnic shelter facing the beach and were out shooting
pictures despite 40 to 45 mph winds and 6-to-10 foot seas. Surfers
were out of the water by early afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``One surfer did try it after the seas got rough,'' Dixon said.
``He got slam-dunked, ate the sand and got out.''
</P>
<P>
   Lifeguards are looking for today's tides to be even higher than
Friday's surge of about a foot above normal.
</P>
<P>
   Cattle ranchers and citrus farmers around St. Lucie and
Okeechobee counties were busy Friday pumping existing water from
their pastures and fields to try to lessen the effect Irene's rain
may have. But generally, their feeling was that the area would
avoid a severe drenching and their cows and crops would fare well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can handle this,'' said Doug Bournique, the executive vice
president of the Indian River Citrus League, which represents 1,600
growers from Daytona Beach to Palm Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem for citrus growers is that the industry is
on the cusp of what is predicted to be a productive year for them
and this will delay harvesting for two or three days, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just brings to a screeching halt a very successful start to
a season,'' he said. ``You want to get going. You want to employ
people and this puts you on hold.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Jim Reeder, Dani Davies, Molly Hennessy-Fiske,
Teresa Lane and Mary McLachlin contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
