<SLUG> BC-NJ-MAYOR-INTIMIDATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOTS FIRED AT IRVINGTON MAYOR'S HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINGTON, N.J. _ With a fresh bullet hole in her front door,
Mayor Sara Bost said Friday that someone had fired several shots
into her house Thursday morning in what she believed was an effort
by a vandal to intimidate her following a confrontation last month.
</P>
<P>
   Bost said she and her husband, Fred, an administrator in the
Essex County Sheriff's Department, were home when the shooting
occurred at 2 a.m. on Thursday. Neither of them was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Bost said she was asleep in a second-floor bedroom and her
husband was asleep in front of the television downstairs when they
were awakened by a rapid succession of loud bangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a drive-by. It started at the garage and went to the
front of the house,'' Bost, 51, said at a news conference on the
steps of City Hall Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Steven Palamara of the Irvington Police said nine shots
were fired from a .45 caliber automatic weapon. He said a witness
saw shots fired from a car that drove past the house.
</P>
<P>
   Police Director Robert Rankin said that there were ``some
leads'' in the case, but declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Three Sundays ago, Bost said, she and members of the Oak Avenue
Block Association spent the day removing graffiti from a building
and signs about a block away from her home, a green-and-white Cape
Cod-style house in a neighborhood of two-family houses that are in
varying states of repair. Two houses on her block are boarded up.
</P>
<P>
   Bost said she was driving by the site several days later when
she encountered a young man, age 19 or 20, spray-painting graffiti
on a stop sign that the group had painted over. The mayor said she
got out of her car and told the man to stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wouldn't look at me. He turned his back on me and he spit
at me down by my feet,'' the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   Since being elected in 1994, Bost said she has often spoken out
against the violence, drug dealing and vandalism that have plagued
Irvington, a 2.8-square-mile city of 61,000 people on Newark's
northern border. She theorized the offended graffiti writer may be
involved with or have friends or associates in the drug trade who
participated in the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Palamara said police are investigating whether there is a
connection between the shooting and the mayor's encounter with the
graffiti writer. He also said investigators are looking into an
incident about a month ago in which car thieves crashed a stolen
car into the front of the mayor's house.
</P>
</TEXT>
