<SLUG> BC-BAPTIST-DANCING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAPTIST COLLEGE BREAKS ITS NO-DANCING TRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN FRANEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIBERTY, Mo. _ Graduates of William Jewell College will return
to the Baptist college Saturday for the usual homecoming
festivities _ the parade, the football game, the crowning of the
homecoming queen.
</P>
<P>
   They'll also come for the unusual:
</P>
<P>
   Dancing. On the central quadrangle.
</P>
<P>
   Homecoming has never included a dance on campus before, a taboo
left over from the Baptist heritage that condemned dancing as a
sin.
</P>
<P>
   The college has had dances off campus, and student groups have
danced at other spots on campus, as well as at off-campus hotels.
</P>
<P>
   But having a celebratory dance for alumni, benefactors,
administrators, professors and students in the heart of campus?
</P>
<P>
   Never even considered.
</P>
<P>
   Until now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has come that the prohibition, whether official or
unofficial, ends,'' said Barry Morris, an independent television
producer who graduated from Jewell in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks it will be spectacular to see people dancing in the
center of this school that opened 150 years ago. And even though he
considers himself a ``klutz,'' he probably will try to groove along
with the Swing 39 band, ``just for the entertainment value.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris, who is a co-chairman of the sesquicentennial homecoming
festivities, said more than 1,000 people had reserved spots for
tonight's dinner and dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the real world, having a dance on campus is not a big deal
at all, but at a Baptist campus, it is an event. It's not
controversial, but it is the first of a kind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Jones, a college spokesman, said some conservative Baptists
might see the dance as a sign that the college was becoming too
liberal. He said a couple of persons had questioned the college's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   But many people on campus are not against dancing and are
definitely in favor of having fun to celebrate the college's 150th
anniversary, Jones added.
</P>
<P>
   The homecoming booklet tells alumni: ``A large dance floor will
offer plenty of room for all those wanting to kick up their heels
and make a little history. This will not be a foot function.''
</P>
<P>
   Decades ago, students avoided the word ``dance'' by labeling any
event that included dancing a ``foot function,'' said Jewell
graduate John Philpot, a physics professor on campus for 38 years.
</P>
<P>
   Philpot sent a notice to the faculty about the upcoming dance
saying that even though this one was not a ``foot function,'' his
feet would function tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some alumni coming back because they can't believe
it, and they want to see it for themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   David Fulk, director of alumni programs, told a story about Will
Adams, a former professor, who taught ballroom dancing classes on
campus.
</P>
<P>
   In a fund-raising campaign in the 1970s, Adams pledged $500. He
gave the college $5 and said: ``You'll get the rest of this when
there's dancing on the quad.''
</P>
<P>
   That time has come. At the end of the dance tonight, Adams plans
to hand over the rest of the money.
</P>
<P>
   Fulk said alumni wanted to be part of officially changing the
campus tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had so many people calling us and saying, `Is this
really true? I read it in the brochure, but is it really going to
happen?' The consistent response is, `I'm not going to miss being
there to see it and participate in it.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
