<SLUG> BC-BBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALENTINE TRIES SHIFTING THE BATTING ORDER  
 ROUGH RECEPTION FOR ROCKER   
 SAFE ON THE STREETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Edgardo Alfonzo wondered how long it had been since
he had last hit third in a lineup. It was May 3, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday night, Alfonzo, essentially the only hot hitter for
the Mets in the National League Championship Series (4 for 8 with
one run batted in and one run scored), arrived at the clubhouse to
find himself in that unfamiliar spot. The move came after the heart
of the Mets' lineup _ John Olerud, Mike Piazza and Robin Ventura _
had gone 1 for 21 in the first two games of the series.
</P>
<P>
   The last time that manager Bobby Valentine changed the lineup
was during the Mets' seven-game losing streak in September, but
this move, Valentine said, was intended less to wake up his dormant
offense than as a move to put some batters between the Mets' two
left-handers _ Olerud and Ventura _ so that it would be more
difficult for Atlanta to use one of its left-handed relievers to
face both of them in the same inning.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said that in the last few days, several players had
made suggestions to him about what the Mets could try to break out
of their funk against Atlanta. So Friday night Olerud batted second
and Ventura sixth. Piazza remained fourth and Benny Agbayani, who
played right field, was fifth. Olerud batted second six times last
season, the last time on July 14, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there is some spacing that we needed when we played
Houston, because of their dominant left-handed reliever,''
Valentine said of Billy Wagner and the Mets' games against the
Astros during September. ``And Fonzie went to fifth. I think the
same kind of spacing, with Fonzie being hot, hitting in front of
Mike where he might get a pitch or two more to hit, gives Fonzie a
little more prominence in our lineup and it spaces our
left-handers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be real difficult in one inning to pitch to John and
Robin with the same left-hander. I know they have another good
left-hander out there, and I know they can use Maddux to go after
my right-handers, and probably will if the situation calls for it.
But I think it will make it a little more challenging for them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Alfonzo, who usually bats second, had expressed
unhappiness with being shifted in the lineup, although he is the
one who suggested it during the losing streak. Friday night,
Alfonzo said, he was not surprised by the move and did not feel any
increased pressure being in a position typically reserved for the
hot hitter on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever it takes,'' he said. ``I've got to go up and try to
do the same things. I'll do the same things and see if things
change. You see the numbers we have against Atlanta, especially in
the playoffs, and we have to try to find out what's happening.
Hopefully, it works.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo had batted third in just 10 games in his career, going
12 for 29, a .414 average. Olerud had batted in the second spot 17
times, going 22 for 63, a .349 average.
</P>
<P>
   In another switch, Valentine put Melvin Mora _ who was called up
from Triple-A when the rosters expanded and has been involved in
some of the biggest plays of the last few weeks _ in center field
instead of Shawon Dunston. Mora, playing in place of the ill Rickey
Henderson on Wednesday, belted a home run. He scored the winning
run on a wild pitch in the Mets' dramatic victory over Pittsburgh
in the final regular-season game. Friday night was Mora's third
start of the season, his first of the post-season, but he was as
cool as the veterans he joined in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not nervous,'' he said. ``I was nervous my first at-bat.
It's the same game. I know there's more pressure in New York, a lot
of people are waiting for you to do something. I've been in the
playoffs for 10 years in Venezuela. In Venezuela, there's more
pressure. They throw glasses if you don't do well. Here they just
scream.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Mora is capable of playing almost any position on the
field, he said he is most comfortable in center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my best position,'' he said. ``I've been playing it all
my life. I can make diving catches. I can control the outfield. I
can help a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   His recent success _ particularly the home run in Atlanta _ has
given a jolt to Mora's already substantial confidence. He was
thrilled when Valentine called on him to replace Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was looking at me and he wanted to put some defense in,''
Mora said. ``I respect Rickey. He was my favorite player. I think I
can help the team. I think I can do more than that. I showed
everybody here I can play. I know it's impossible to play in this
lineup. The only thing I can do is prepare myself physically and
mentally. My cousin from Miami told me when I got in the game, the
people started to talk on television and say, `I don't think this
is a good situation to put him in, he has no experience.' When they
were saying `they better put in Benny,' I hit the home run.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Masato Yoshii's sprained ankle was taped Friday, and
Valentine said it was ``wait and see'' whether Yoshii would be able
to pitch Game 5. If he cannot go, Orel Hershiser, who pitched one
inning of relief Oct. 8 against Arizona and has not started since
the final game of the regular season against Pittsburgh, would be
the most likely starter.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the medical report was more positive. Henderson, who
had flu symptoms that forced him to leave Game 2, was much better
and started in left field Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Rough Reception for Rocker
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker emerged from the Braves' dugout before the start of
the game and met the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   After taunting Mets fans through the news media, Rocker was
expected to draw a vicious response from the fans. He stepped from
the dugout to begin the pregame warm-ups, and while enduring the
first taunts, he turned to the fans, smiled wide, tipped his hat
and said, ``Hey, boys.'' He then started toward the outfield,
stopped to sign autographs for a pair of young children wearing
Mets hats, and then continued on.
</P>
<P>
   When Rocker's name was called during player introductions, he
drew the loudest boos from the fans. He tipped his cap again in an
exaggerated gesture.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium was littered with signs challenging him, and that
was enough to draw the ire of his manager, Bobby Cox.
</P>
<P>
   ``It irritates me,'' Cox said of Rocker's comments in the news
media. ``I don't like it. I don't condone it. He was roughed up by
the fans, I think, in our first series here, and he's the type of
guy that's going to give it right back. He's got to work on that.
He's a great pitcher, a great competitor, but he needs to work on
his player-fan relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell all our guys to watch what they say, that's it still
the game of baseball, not a game of words.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One thing that Cox did not worry about was that the angry crowd
would fluster Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He certainly is not going to scare,'' Cox said. ``They can
yell all they want and curse him all they want. If he's on, he's
on, but if he's off, he's off. If he has a bad a game it's not
going to be because somebody yelled at him.''
</P>
<P>
   Safe on the Streets
</P>
<P>
   Cox spoke glowingly of New York City, stating that his opinion
has changed in recent years. He described New York as ``one of the
safest cities, walking around.'' But when asked whether that
applied to Rocker and Chipper Jones, he said, ``I don't know about
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 2346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
