r s BC-BBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     10-15 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALENTINE TAKES HITS, BUT HE'S RIGHT FOR NEW YORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bobby Valentine, as usual, is smiling the most hated
smile in baseball. It's his badge of honor, that cocky Frankie
Avalon smile. Wipe it off if you dare.
</P>
<P>
   I say it can't be done.
</P>
<P>
   We're standing near the batting cage before Game 3 of the
National League Championship Series last night and his team is
about to lose its third straight to the Braves, but Valentine is
somehow relaxed and laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can take the heat better than anyone,'' he corrects, ``but
that doesn't mean I like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days earlier, after the Mets had blown a 3-0 lead and lost,
4-3, to the Braves, Valentine had quickly stepped forward to take
the blame, saying he'd left starting pitcher Kenny Rogers in too
long.
</P>
<P>
   His critics welcomed the confession and tabloid headlines
screamed that ``Bobby Blew It!'' but Valentine's ``mea culpa'' had
accomplished two things: He had defused the second-guessers by
admitting the mistake and at the same time took the heat off Rogers
and the heart of his batting order, which was a pitiful 1-for-21
with one RBI in the first two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know what they \Rthe New York media\S would have done
to Kenny?'' he asks, his eyebrows climbing up his forehead with
every word.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the New York sharks might have done to Rogers can't
compare with what they've already done to Valentine. When the Mets
were losing five in a row in the final week of the season,
Valentine said for the second time this season that if the Mets
didn't make the playoffs he should be fired.
</P>
<P>
   In both instances, he again became the lightning rod for all the
negative emotions and tension surrounding his team. After the
second time, he woke the next day to this ``New York Post''
headline: ``Why Wait? Can the Phony Now.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that yesterday the same newspaper ran a column
headlined: ``Bobby V Perfect Man for This Town and This Team.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, the same writer who had vilified Valentine in the first
column, later wrote a glowing tribute after the Mets had won the
wild-card spot with a clutch sweep of the Pirates and a one-game
playoff win over Cincinnati.
   But that's Valentine: There are few emotions that aren't touched
where he's involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media in New York is pretty much split down the middle on
Bobby,'' says a longtime New York baseball writer. ``He reads
everything very closely and believes you're either for him or
against him. If you're against him, he doesn't have much use for
you. If he thinks you're giving him a fair shake, there's nothing
he won't do for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine is, according to longtime Mets' media relations
director Jay Horwitz, the best he's ever worked with.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 20 years in this business, I've never seen anyone more
accommodating to the media,'' Horwitz declares. ``But it doesn't
matter what he does, they still crucify him.''
</P>
<P>
   The TV camera loves his handsome, expressive face, his
unconcealed passion, his recklessness. He is brash, cocky,
paranoid, arrogant, controversial and amazingly candid, all the
things old-line baseball men detest.
</P>
<P>
   Is there another manager in baseball who would have had the
audacity to don a fake mustache and sunglasses and sneak back into
the dugout after an ejection during the team's earlier travails? Or
brashly predict that his team would go 40-15 over the next 55
games, and hit it right on the nose?
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give me credit for that one,'' Valentine says,
chuckling.
</P>
<P>
   A recent revealing ``Sports Illustrated'' article on the
``inside'' Valentine brought gasps of disapproval from around
baseball. Valentine just shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a good article,'' he says. ``The guy was
following me for three weeks. There were some times when I said,
`Now, you're not going to write this are you?' and he'd say, `No.
No,' but it was all in there.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what?''
</P>
<P>
   His one real regret, he says, is the section in which he said of
his players, ``You're not dealing with real intelligent guys, for
the most part,'' and ``there's about five guys in there right now
who basically are losers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I hadn't said that, but it's true,'' Valentine says.
``I called a team meeting and said, `Hey, if the shoe fits and
you've got a problem with it, let's go into my office and talk
about it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And if the shoe fits, they need a shoeshine.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics say Atlanta's Bobby Cox has managed rings around
Valentine in this playoff series. Based on postseason experience
alone, he should. I know this, it's a lot easier to manage when
you've got players like Maddux, Smoltz, Millwood, Glavine and
Rocker on your side. The Mets simply have not hit.
</P>
<P>
   But then, you can put me down on that shrinking list of
Valentine defenders. I like him both as a person and as a manager.
He came to the Rangers at one of the low points of the franchise's
existence, having been dragged into the gutter during the sordid
Doug Rader era, and no one worked harder to promote the team and
build it back to respectability than Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   The media here may have a love-hate affair with him, and the
Mets may yet can him _ two managers who finished behind him,
Philadelphia's Terry Francona and St. Louis' Tony La Russa, have
received extensions; Bobby V hasn't _ but the headline in
yesterday's ``Post'' was right: Valentine is perfect for New York.
</P>
<P>
   The day they fire him, he'll still be smiling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-15-99 2354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
