<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8838 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-ALCSPREVIEW-TEX     10-15 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCSPREVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS VS. MARTINEZ IS A HIGH-STAKES SHOWDOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ So far it has been a terrific series, potentially one
for the ages that people will be talking about for many years to
come.
</P>
<P>
   It has been two terrific teams in a historic rivalry and two
great games filled with tension, suspense, great plays and
controversial calls. The American League Championship Series
between the Boston Red Sox and the New York Yankees has been what
everybody expected.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the preliminaries. It's time for the main event.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens vs. Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The five-time Cy Young Award winner against the best pitcher in
baseball, going at it today on a late October afternoon at a
sold-out Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what baseball is all about,'' Yankees shortstop Derek
Jeter, echoing the thoughts of many. The anticipation has been
building since Yankees manager Joe Torre and Boston's Jimy Williams
announced their rotations Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be fun,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   The game means much more to the Red Sox, who trail two games to
none in the series after losing two one-run games at Yankee
Stadium. If they lose Game 3 today, the series is almost assuredly
over. No team in baseball history has ever rallied from three games
down to win a best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   If they win, Red Sox fans will once again have hope of another
sensational comeback, perhaps one even better than coming back from
two games down to beat the Cleveland Indians in the Division
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never easy being down 0-2,'' Williams said. ``We just
have to go out there and do the best we can.''
</P>
<P>
   But the implications for the Red Sox seem to run almost
secondary to the eagerly anticipated pitching match. The subplots
alone are delicious.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is returning to Fenway Park, his home with the Red Sox
for 13 years. He won the Cy Young Award three times while wearing
the Red Sox uniform before leaving in 1997 to pitch for the Toronto
Blue Jays. Now he's coming back as a member of the hated Yankees,
which should only enhance the booing he has had to endure from his
former fans for the past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been back to Fenway many times,'' Clemens said. ``Going
to Texas for me is just as difficult. As much action as there's
going to be on the field, there's going to be in the stands. I just
hope it's as exciting as it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens has not had a great year. After winning the Cy Young
Award twice with the Blue Jays, he went 14-10 with a 4.60
earned-run average for the Yankees. Those are hardly the numbers
they expected in spring training when he was acquired from the Blue
Jays for pitchers David Wells and Graeme Lloyd and second baseman
Homer Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But the road to redemption started in Arlington, when he wrapped
up the Division Series against the Rangers with seven scoreless
innings in the Yankees' 3-0 victory a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   He also knows that with a victory today, he will be on the verge
of going back to the World Series for the first time since 1986
with the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get in these kind of games, you have to elevate your
focus,'' Clemens said. ``I know \Rtoday\S that will definitely have
to be the situation. I don't think I'm going to be afforded too
many mistakes against Pedro.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's record suggests that. No pitcher in baseball
performed better this year than the Red Sox ace. He was 23-4 with a
2.40 ERA, 313 strikeouts and won the Most Valuable Player Award in
the All-Star Game. He also strained a muscle in the back of his
shoulder in Game 1 of the Division Series against the Indians, an
injury that seemed to doom the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   But he came back with six scoreless innings in relief in Game 5,
allowing the Red Sox to complete their improbable comeback and
advance to the ALCS.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he has done this year is just tremendous,'' Clemens said.
``Everybody backs the truck up to him and he has to come out and do
it. It's been great for him, what he's been able to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's shoulder is a concern but he said, ``I feel good. I
am sure I can work through it. And now I have more days to rest. I
should be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, well aware of his team's plight, has downplayed the
confrontation and the pressure that both pitchers will be under.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Roger is very professional, and he has been through
everything,'' Martinez said. ``He knows how to handle the situation
just like I will. I'm just going to go out and pitch the game, and
I'm sure he will too. I hope he puts a lot of pressure on himself,
and I hope he gives it up soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez blew away the Yankees on Sept. 10 at Yankee Stadium,
throwing a one-hitter while striking out 17.
</P>
<P>
   If Martinez wins, and the Red Sox stay alive, the 1999 ALCS has
a chance to reach epic proportions. It could also lead to another
epic matchup, given the way both rotations are set up.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez vs. Clemens in Game 7 at Yankee Stadium on Thursday
with a trip to the World Series on the line.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
