<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR THE METS, A DREAM DEFERRED? 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shea Stadium was alive and crackling with the spirit
of playoff baseball Friday night. Fans came and unleashed the fury
of a decade worth of pent up emotions: everything from frustration
and anxiety to unbridled joy that the New York Mets had climbed so
many steep mountains to reach the National League Championship
Series.
</P>
<P>
   They came by elevated train, by car, by bus, to witness their
beloved Mets take the field in a home playoff game. As if they need
any more reason to be excited, Mets fans had been egged on by two
Atlanta Braves players.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones had suggested near the end of the season that the
Mets' fans go home and put on their ``Yankees stuff,'' and John
Rocker, the young, tough relief pitcher, had expressed disdain for
the Mets and even deeper dislike for their fans. So fans showed up
with signs and plenty of taunts in hopes of unnerving Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Some unnerving. Like so many strategies the Mets try against
Atlanta, it didn't work, as the Mets lost by 1-0 Friday night.
Within the first inning, Atlanta had scored a run, knocked Mike
Piazza dizzy and forced the normally infallible Mets' infield to
commit two errors. Atlanta is the team that has waited at the top
of the mountain each time the Mets got close, then pushed them back
down. The Mets were not so much decimated as demoralized.
</P>
<P>
   In the first two games of this series, the Mets would score a
run and Atlanta answered with two; the Mets would score two runs
and Atlanta answered with three or four. It began to seem that if
the Mets scored 100 runs, Atlanta would score 101.
</P>
<P>
   And not just Tuesday and Wednesday nights, but for two full
seasons. Anything the Mets have done, the Braves have done better,
and with maddening precision. They not only took Games 1 and 2 of
this series, but also seemed on the verge of snatching one of the
Mets' best assets: their resilient spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Al Leiter held Atlanta to one run, but Tom Glavine kept
the Mets scoreless. The Mets had just one poor inning _ the first.
Leiter and Piazza made throwing errors and the Braves had the only
run they needed. Except for those two plays in the first inning,
the Mets played brilliantly in the field. Mora threw out Bret Boone
at the plate and Rickey Henderson threw out two runners at second.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Valentine had changed the batting order before the game,
moved John Olerud to the No. 2 spot, Edgardo Alfonzo to No. 3 and
Melvin Mora started in center field. The only way to defeat the
Braves and their closer John Rocker is to have the lead going into
the final innings, but Friday night the Mets trailed by a run.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets co-owner, Fred Wilpon, had tried to raise the Mets'
spirits on Thursday. At the Mets' workout at Shea, he walked out of
the dugout with his manager as if on parade as a wave of
journalists followed. Wilpon made a point of speaking to each of
the potential goats of this series. He walked out to visit Rickey
Henderson. He had an animated conversation with Bobby Bonilla.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Wilpon walked back to the dugout and held court. ``Our
team is loose,'' he said. ``They're ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   This has been a dream ride for the Mets. Two weeks ago Friday
the Mets opened a series in this stadium against Pittsburgh,
desperately needing a miracle just to qualify for the chance to get
into post-season play. The Mets got their miracle with Cincinnati
losing twice to Milwaukee, and the Mets swept Pittsburgh. The Mets
and their fans jumped sky high and never came back to earth as the
Mets won the playoff game against Cincinnati, then managed three
victories out of four games against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have been yanked back to earth, once again, by Atlanta.
But when someone asked Wilpon if he was ready to cash in the chips
and begin thinking of what a great season this had been, he cut in.
``No way, I'm not even going to let you finish. We're in it for
this series. We're going to win some games here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets will win one battle: There were 6,000 empty seats at
Turner Field for Games 1 and 2. Shea Stadium was packed and rocking
Friday night. Even the lack of a sellout is the signature of how
comfortable Atlanta fans have become with their team's success.
That lack of passion is precisely the reason Atlanta has won just
one World Series championship in a decade the franchise has
otherwise dominated. This sets up a classic confrontation with the
Yankees: Atlanta is the team of the decade, but the Yankees are the
franchise of the century.
</P>
<P>
   But all this is at an entirely different level from where the
Mets and their fans find themselves this weekend, hungry after 11
seasons without a championship, chasing a dream that stays just
beyond their grasp.
</P>
</TEXT>
